<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOS NOT HIP TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ L.A.'s the place for David Wheaton, sort of. But
it's definitely not for Marcelo Rios.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lost to Canada's Sebastian Lareau 6-4, 6-2 Monday,
Wheaton, an All-American at Stanford, was the happiest of
first-round losers. That's because this was the first time this
season he qualified for the main draw.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, the fourth seed and former world's No. 1-ranked player,
pulled out of the Mercedes-Benz Cup at UCLA on Monday with
tendinitis in both hips, a day before his scheduled first-round
match with qualifier Magnus Larsson of Sweden. Larsson today will
play another qualifier, Paradorn Srichaphan of Thailand, his
country's top player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst (year) of my career,'' Rios said. ``It's the
first time I've been so injured in my four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios also has had back and elbow problems. But his hips started
hurting last week, although he played in the Mercedes Cup in
Stuttgart, Germany. He didn't expect this. Not after flying in
following his third-round exit from the Mercedes Cup. Rios arrived
here Saturday feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   The pain flared, so on Monday Rios visited Dr. George Fareed,
who suggested rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like a 100-percent player,'' Rios said. ``I'll
have treatment tomorrow and see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although clearly frustrated, Rios, who reached No. 1 in March
1998 without ever having won a Grand Slam, found the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can win the top ones, you can do it again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton would like to prove that true. He once was a top-20
player, having reached the Australian and U.S. Open quarterfinals
in 1990 and the Wimbledon semis in '91.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's fighting age and injuries. He's 30 and has struggled
since having a bone spur in his foot removed two years ago and
elbow surgery in January 1998. His ranking has gone from a high of
12 in 1991 to 300-something now.
</P>
<P>
   `Once you've been hurt, it's a hard climb back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This season serves as proof. Wheaton has played in at least
eight qualifying and challenger tournaments with little success.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, he reached the final of qualifying in doubles.
Playing singles, he lost in the final round at Delray Beach (Fla.),
7-5 in the third and final set. At Newport, R.I., he reached the
final but suffered heat exhaustion. In Birmingham, Ala., he served
for the match in the second round and lost. At Aptos last week, he
had match point in the first round and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I'm winning,'' he said. ``I'm like 15-11 on the
year. I shouldn't get discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has had his moments when he thought about finding a
new career, only to decide he isn't ready yet. Then came Los
Angeles, which he sees as his latest proof he can again find
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm close,'' he said. ``It's funny, but I'm 30
years old, and I need to get some exposure playing the good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Lareau, who once won junior doubles titles at Roland Garros and
Wimbledon, is better than anyone Wheaton has played lately in
qualifying. Wheaton also hurt himself with several double faults
and by failing to hold serve four times.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he reached the main draw. He hoopes to continue a
comeback next week in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's as long as I feel like I'm still contending in
matches and not just getting beat in the first round all the time.
. . . If I did it once, I must have it in me to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In other first-round matches Monday, Frenchmen Anthony Dupuis
handed Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden his seventh first-round exit of the
year 6-4, 6-4. Qualifier James Sekulov of Australia beat Martin
Damm of the Czech Republic, setting up a second-round match with
fifth-seeded Thomas Enqvist, who swept Australian Mark Woodforde.
</P>
</TEXT>
