<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-ARREST-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CONFESSES TO 4 KILLINGS AT YOSEMITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A motel handyman who was dismissed as a suspect
in the deaths of three sightseers last February at Yosemite
National Park has confessed to the decapitation of a park
naturalist last week and to the other three killings, according to
an FBI affidavit and to an official involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Stayner, 37, confessed to the killing of Joie Ruth
Armstrong, 26, and has provided details about the crime that only
the killer could have known, according to the FBI affidavit filed
on Monday in Federal District Court in Fresno, Calif. He has also
confessed to the other slayings, a law enforcement official
confirmed, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner worked as a janitor at the Cedar Lodge in El Portal at
the western edge of Yosemite, where the three sightseers were last
seen alive.
</P>
<P>
   His confession _ or confessions _ mark another turn in a case
that has FBI officials wondering whether the latest killing could
have been prevented. The FBI had said on Sunday that evidence
obtained after Ms. Armstrong's death linked Stayner to the slayings
of the three sightseers and that it was pursuing an investigation
of those killings. The official said the bureau was looking for
evidence to corroborate the confession.
</P>
<P>
   The sightseers' disappearance from the Cedar Lodge in February
set off an extensive search, national headlines and numerous
arrests of ex-convicts whom the FBI has called unofficial suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner was arrested Saturday at a nudist resort near
Sacramento, Calif., and charged with one count of murder in the
death of Ms. Armstrong on Monday afternoon in federal court in
Sacramento. At his brief court appearance, Stayner, a muscular,
clean-cut man dressed in an orange prison uniform, said nothing but
nodded repeatedly as the federal magistrate, Judge Peter A.
Nowinski, asked him if he understood the charge and read him his
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Like all other residents living near the Cedar Lodge, Stayner,
who had rented a room above the restaurant adjacent to the motel
for two years, was questioned at the time of the sightseers'
disappearance. The law-enforcement official who would speak only on
the condition of not being identified said Stayner was probaby
dismissed as a suspect, at least in part, because the authorities
believed the slayings could not have been committed by only one
person.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stayner has not yet been charged with the deaths of
Carole Sund, 42, her daughter Juli Sund, 15, and their friend
Silvina Pelosso, 16, the FBI believes he is the only person
responsible, said James M. Maddock, the agency's special agent in
charge of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has refused to discuss details regarding the links among
the slayings. But The Modesto Bee, quoting unidentified sources,
reported that such evidence was found in Stayner's room and that
Juli Sund's throat was slashed almost to the point of beheading,
like Ms. Armstrong's.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Carole Sund and Miss Pelosso were found in the
trunk of their charred rental car more than a month after they
disappeared. Juli Sund's body was found a few days later, off a
little-traveled road.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Armstrong's body was found on Thursday, one day after she
was last seen near the cabin where she lived with her boyfriend and
another roommate, both of whom were away. Until then, the FBI had
maintained that it believed all the people responsible for the
Sund-Pelosso deaths were in custody, though on unrelated charges.
Numerous ex-convicts with either ties to El Portal or Modesto,
where Carole Sund's wallet was found three days after the trio
disappeared, have been held for months for various offenses while
officials have tried to gather enough evidence to charge them with
the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner was questioned about Ms. Armstrong twice on Thursday, a
day after his sport utility vehicle was spotted near her cabin
about an hour after she was last seen.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing in the Armstrong case was scheduled for Aug. 6 in
federal court in Fresno, where the case is being moved, but John P.
Balasz, the assistant federal defender who represented Stayner,
said the hearing will probably be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner's arrest has prompted sheriff's detectives in Merced
County, where Stayner lived until moving to El Portal in 1997, to
announce that they were re-examining the unsolved 1990 death of his
uncle, Jerry Stayner, who was shot to death in what authorities had
considered a botched burglary.
</P>
</TEXT>
