<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys send urgent message to draft choices
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones has a message for his
1999 draft picks:
</P>
<P>
   Get signed and get to camp, or suffer the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an individual or his representative can't see how important
it is to get him in here, we mark that down someplace for the
future,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only three have heeded the warning. Seventh-round pick
Mike Lucky signed a three-year contract last week. Former Texas A&AMP;M
linebacker Dat Nguyen and Texas receiver Wane McGarity signed on
the eve of reporting day.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies and select veterans were due to report to Midwestern
State University on Monday. The first practice is this morning. All
others are due on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, the Cowboys' third-round pick, signed a three-year deal
worth a reported $1.2 million, which included a $350,000 signing
bonus. He will receive $175,000 this year, $250,000 next year and
$325,000 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of McGarity's deal were not released. He was one of the
club's two fourth-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves five draftees unsigned, most notably defensive end
Ebenezer Ekuban and offensive tackle Solomon Page, the top two
picks. The Cowboys hope Ekuban can contribute immediately in
pass-rushing situations. Page is to be groomed to replace nine-year
veteran Erik Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a rookie not to be in training camp for the very
first practice, the very first meeting,'' Jones said. ``Does it
hurt the team? Yes, it does, but not as much as if we gave him what
the agents for the rookie want us to give him that's keeping him
out of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys began negotiating with their draft picks only about
a week ago, a date that was strategically picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to drive this process; we don't want to be driven,''
Jones said. ``The more compact you can get the negotiating period
to make a decision, the better it is for our football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've negotiated on the clock during the draft. We've had
contracts signed within hours of the draft being over. I've spent
some money that I shouldn't have spent negotiating during the
draft. I'd have been better off negotiating just before we reported
(to camp), and we would have gotten a better deal, which ultimately
would have made us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Any or all of the remaining rookies could be signed before the
team takes the field this morning, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very involved with the ones who haven't agreed,'' he
said. ``Don't use the word close for any reason. But the issues
involved should not, in my opinion, prevent a rookie from being
here tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In other news, the Cowboys are awaiting word on the length of
Leon Lett's suspension. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue has not ruled
on how much time the defensive tackle must miss after another
violation of the league's substance abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's on the commissioner's timetable,'' Jones said. ``We had
thought we might have a word early in our training camp. It may
still be, but it's his time frame, and I don't know that he's made
any decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The other mystery time frame concerns the return of cornerback
Deion Sanders, who is rehabilitating after offseason surgery on his
big toe. At this point, Sanders is questionable for the Sept. 12
opener at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running hard on machines,'' Jones said. ``Beginning right
now, he'll begin running without machines, doing a lot of
straight-ahead running. He's progressing, but I'm told we won't
know anything really until he starts pushing off, starts cutting
and gets into football situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also announced they are resurrecting their tradition
of a blue-white scrimmage. It will take place at 8 p.m. Aug. 5 at
Memorial Stadium in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won't scrimmage another NFL team, as they have in
previous seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
