<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-IRL-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CART, IRL close to reconciliation
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Officials for CART and the Indy Racing League
have been quiet lately about the prospects of a reconciliation.
Maybe too quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations say talks between leaders of
the rival circuits have made ``significant progress'' in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And two officials for the CART engine manufacturers say a
compromise proposal might make it possible for the leagues to race
together next year at the Indianapolis 500 before racing as one
league in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   CART president Andrew Craig talked with reporters for more than
45 minutes after Sunday's U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway. Although
he didn't reveal much concrete information, it was a rare post-race
appearance for Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having one series probably is critical to not confusing the
public,'' Craig said. ``I don't want to comment on any rumors, but
I will say that a lot of elements must be worked out before
anything can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying a lot on the record, but merger rumors were
rampant in every team's garage at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   One source said the reason talks have become more fruitful
recently is the fact CART team owners Bobby Rahal and Barry Green
have taken lead roles in the negotiations. CART team owner Roger
Penske admitted he has stepped away from the negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal and Green are considered to be a little less
confrontational and more receptive to new ideas. Rahal has been a
hard-liner at times, but he also is a former golfing buddy of IRL
founder Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario being discussed is for Craig to step down and Greg
Penske, Roger's son, to take over as the president of CART. Greg
Penske is the president of the California Speedway, but Roger
Penske recently sold his tracks in Michigan, California and
Nazareth, Pa., to NASCAR's International Speedway Corp.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications something may be in the works for next
year. CART has tabled discussions of new rules and testing dates
for 2000, something that usually is already being decided. CART
also has yet to name a replacement for retiring chief steward Wally
Dallenbach.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, engine manufacturers say it's too late for the
open-wheel leagues to come together as one league for the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about 2001 now, and we're very close to being
out of time for that,'' said Lee White, general manager for Toyota
Racing Development. ``We will have to know by Labor Day if we are
going to go to a completely different (engine) formula. If
discussions drag on until the end of the year, it would be very
difficult for all of us to get ready by 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The drastic differences between the types of engines the cars
use and how they are distributed has been the biggest obstacle to a
resolution between the two circuits. But Ford Racing executive Greg
Specht said some type of engine equivalency formula might allow the
two leagues to race together at Indianapolis next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we would want to do over the long haul, but
it could work for this one situation,'' Specht said. ``It might be
fun. We could look at it as the final showdown between the two
leagues while they're still apart.''
</P>
<P>
   CART uses turbo-charged, 2.65-liter motors, while the IRL uses
normally aspirated 4.0-liter engines. But the IRL is switching to
3.5-liter engines next season.
</P>
<P>
   CART has Mercedes, Honda, Ford and Toyota as its engine
suppliers through a leasing program from the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL uses Oldsmobile and Nissan and gets its engines at a
much lower cost per season than the CART system. The CART
manufacturers build and maintain the engines, but the IRL teams are
able to make changes to their motors.
</P>
<P>
   The engine leasing program in CART can cost more than $1 million
a season with the top teams, something the IRL teams say they
cannot afford. But Specht believes that problem can be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the lease situation is a deal-breaker,'' Specht
said. ``That can be worked out. Ford is willing to do whatever is
reasonable. It's high on our agenda because there is a sense of
urgency to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   For the two leagues to race together at Indy next year, some
sort of limit would need to be placed on the CART engines. CART
engines run at 15,000 RPMs while the IRL recently lowered its RPM
limit to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some type of rev-limiter on the CART engines might enable the
cars to compete equally next year at Indy until new engines could
be built.
</P>
<P>
   White said Toyota is receptive to design changes if it will
bring the leagues together, which might mean some type of normally
aspirated engine for all the cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very willing to consider almost any option in rules as
long as it's within reason,'' White said. ``It's paramount for the
future to have all the open-wheel cars at the Indianapolis 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's U.S. 500 was another indication that the four-year
split between the two leagues is hurting the sport. The inaugural
U.S. 500 in 1996 drew more than 110,000 fans to the two-mile oval,
but fewer than 50,000 were in attendance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive year that attendance has declined
for the event. The NASCAR Winston Cup race at Michigan one month
ago drew a sellout crowd of more than 160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Said one CART driver Sunday: ``If this doesn't tell (CART and
IRL officials) they have a problem, they'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL event at Atlanta Motor Speedway earlier this month drew
fewer than 30,000, a decrease of more than 20,000 from the Atlanta
race in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It has become clear to everyone in Indy-car racing that
something has to change. For the first time, it appears both
leagues are serious about making those changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
