<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-FOUNDAT     07-27 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-FOUNDATION-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Armstrong's win draws attention to foundation
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NEIL HOHLFELD
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Even after the initial rush of publicity over Lance Armstrong's
stunning victory in the Tour de France begins to ebb, Karl
Haussmann hopes he's still working 18-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   Haussmann is the executive director of the Lance Armstrong
Foundation, a nonprofit organization established by Armstrong after
he was diagnosed with testicular cancer less than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Haussmann, his one full-time staffer, a couple of interns and a
number of volunteers at the Austin-based foundation were riding the
draft Monday of Armstrong's victory in the world's most prestigious
cycling race. The foundation no doubt will benefit from the
attention Armstrong has received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, we expect an increase in interest after what Lance
accomplished,'' Haussmann said. ``I mean, we haven't had any calls
from people saying, `Now I know you're there, so here's $1
million.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But there will be a long-term lasting effect. More
corporations will be willing to talk to us. There will be more
sponsorship, which ultimately will lead to more research. More
people will know what we're about. We'll be a little bit more
mainstream, and we want that growth. The more (funds) we generate,
the more we can help.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's mission is to help people manage and survive
cancer through research, education and awareness. It raises money
through an annual cycling event in Austin over Memorial Day weekend
and through other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the foundation awarded more than $250,000 in
research grants to study testicular cancer and urologic cancer.
According to the foundation's Web site (www.laf.org), Dr. Ellen
Gritz of the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston received one
grant to lead a study that focuses on the effects of chemotherapy
for the treatment of testicular cancer on neurocognitive function.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the foundation is patient-focused. This is of
particular concern to Armstrong, who wants all those diagnosed with
testicular cancer to have access to the latest advances in
screening, diagnosis and treatment. Armstrong's experience after he
learned he had cancer was the genesis for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a pretty miserable experience in his post-diagnosis
stage,'' Haussmann said. ``He felt there was a severe lack of
information, and he found himself surfing the Net, trying to get
any kind of information about what he was going though.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty scared, and with nowhere to turn for help, it
made it worse. Lance has said he doesn't want anyone to go through
the same experience he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 27, grew up in Plano before moving to Austin. He was
a world-class cyclist when, at the age of 25 in 1996, he was told
he had a lethal variety of testicular cancer that had spread to his
lungs, abdomen and brain.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent surgery twice, once to remove his right testicle
and again to have two brain lesions removed. Armstrong also
underwent four rounds of intense chemotherapy. Doctors gave him
less than a 50 percent chance to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeries and chemotherapy eliminated the cancer, and
Armstrong began his cycling comeback. He sat out all of 1997, raced
briefly in 1998 and set his sights on competing in the Tour de
France this year.
</P>
<P>
   During one of Armstrong's last visits with friends and
supporters in Austin this summer, Haussmann admitted talking with
people about how it might be too much to ask of Armstrong to win
the Tour de France. They believed in their man, but they also knew
how difficult it would be to overcome the ravages of chemotherapy
in a sport as demanding as cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talked to Lance about the possibility of winning the
Tour, there was always the feeling that it might be too soon,''
Haussmann said. ``We believed he could do it _ but maybe not right
now, not so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he'd have a great Tour, possibly lead a little, win
some stages, maybe finish in the top three. I'd love to say we were
right there with him from the start. Don't get me wrong, we're huge
believers in what he does when he puts his mind to it. But toxic
drugs from chemotherapy can do irreparable damage to the body. You
don't know what kind of effect it will have on the body. We were
unsure of that, not of Lance's desire to win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Armstrong came through in France, the ripple effect was
felt in Austin. Haussmann said Monday it was all he could do to
return the hundreds of phone calls the foundation has received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could ever imagine the kind of exposure this
has generated,'' Haussmann said. ``We've got calls from all manner
of media outlets, wanting to know what the foundation does, how
people can find out more about it. We're getting calls from
companies looking to sponsor events rather than having to hunt them
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our Web site, we've already sold out of most of the gear _
hats, T-shirts and cycling jerseys. We've reordered three times,
and we'll reorder as long as we have to. It's the kind of thing
that people all over the world feel good about.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the corporate end of the foundation, Haussmann said
Armstrong's success after his illness has helped lift the spirits
of others undergoing what he went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the hundreds of e-mails that have been sent to Lance in the
last month, the word inspiration shows up nearly every time,''
Haussmann said. ``What Lance has accomplished gives people hope,
which is something they might not have had yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance will tell you that this entire experience is one of the
best things that ever happened to him. It helped get a better
perspective on his life. No longer is cycling the most important
thing in his life, and it shouldn't be to anyone else. Your life
and health and family all come first. He's been humbled by the
cancer, but his determination never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he wanted to do with the foundation was to fund research,
but also to give people with cancer the information he didn't get.
With research and information and Lance's determination and
accomplishments, maybe we can give people hope.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Lance Armstrong Foundation, call
512-236-8820.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
