A4955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS     07-27 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Injury won't keep Biggio from playing on
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Astros filled in the blanks Monday regarding the
pain that has lingered in second baseman Craig Biggio's left
shoulder for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, who disclosed Sunday he has been playing with pain since
early June, has a slight tear of the labrum in his left shoulder, a
condition he can play through for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The injury likely will require arthroscopic surgery in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI on Biggio's left shoulder following the All-Star break
revealed a tear in the cartilage surrounding the rotator cuff,
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to have an MRI just to find out exactly what was
wrong in there,'' Hunsicker said. ``The MRI disclosed a slight tear
of the labrum. It's something he will continue to play with. We
don't anticipate it getting any worse than it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all probability, we will have to surgically repair it when
the season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, 33, spoke publicly of his injury Sunday but gave few
details, saying only that he would ``probably have it fixed in the
offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said based on the fact Biggio has played with the
injury for two months, there is little reason to believe the
seven-time All-Star won't be able to continue to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to come out of the lineup unless there is
something really significantly wrong,'' Hunsicker said. ``I'm not
minimizing the fact it's painful. This is something he has a
reasonable chance to play with for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio has hit safely in 22 of his last 25 games, posting a .369
batting average during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said former Astros third baseman Sean Berry played
with a torn rotator cuff in his right (throwing) arm during the
entire 1997 season, and Cincinnati righthander Pete Harnisch, also
a former Astro, is currently playing with a torn labrum in his
pitching shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that unusual,'' Hunsicker said. ``(But) any time one
of your star players has a physical problem, it's a concern. I know
he has good days and bad days, some days where it's a significant
factor for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take consolation in the fact he has been able to play with
it and been pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio said he first remembers experiencing pain while
stretching during the Astros' series in Milwaukee June 1-3. The
pain is most evident when he bats _ his left shoulder is his lead
shoulder _ and on certain defensive moves.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the MRI was performed to ``satisfy Biggio's
curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to know what was wrong,'' Hunsicker said. ``He said
before he had it, `I don't care what it says. I'm still playing
with it.' That's why we didn't say much about it, because he is
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio has never been on the disabled list in his 10-plus
major-league seasons and has missed only three games since 1996. He
played in a club-record 494 consecutive games between 1995-98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
