<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-REPAIR-II-1STLD-WRITETHRU-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BID TO RESCUE CITY'S SCHOOL BUILDINGS WAS HARD-WIRED TO FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change `last March' to `last year' in lede graf. No other
changes.)  (mk) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN, JACQUES STEINBERG and CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fire that was touched off by a welder working in a
Brooklyn vocational school briefly trapped 150 students last year.
The construction work was not supposed to begin until school was
done for the day, but school administrators and construction
officials could not agree on when classes were actually over.
</P>
<P>
   A new elementary school opened in upper Manhattan in 1995 with
problems ranging from loose floor tiles to a broken elevator. It
took three years to fix all the problems, while officials at the
New York City Board of Education and the School Construction
Authority argued about whose job it was to make the repairs.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the state Legislature created the construction
authority and joined it in a shotgun marriage with the city's
school board, the breakdown in their relationship has been a major
obstacle to reaching the goal that was set for them: mending and
expanding the nation's largest school system by century's end.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators were hoping to rescue a school system whose building
division was taking 10 years, and often a few bribes, to build a
single school, but in their haste to solve the problem they
effectively hard-wired the new arrangement for failure. They made
the board the client and the new authority its builder, but they
never specified where one agency's job ends and the other's begins.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as city and state officials are beginning to pour $7
billion into school construction and repairs over the next five
years, they have done little to fix the broken partnership. The
board is slow to plan, and the authority is lax in policing
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   An almost unfathomable amount of work must be done. An analysis
of the city's most recent school-by-school engineering survey by
The New York Times shows that at least 40 percent of the 1,100
schools are plagued by porous roofs, disintegrating facades or
windows that do not open or shut.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the board and the authority were overwhelmed by
the job of rebuilding a deteriorating system in which half the
school buildings were built before 1940.
</P>
<P>
   And the construction process became infected by the very
politics that had eaten at the schools for generations. The
construction apparatus is overseen by one appointee each of the
governor, the mayor and the city schools chancellor. Any top
official can take credit for successes, but no one is directly
responsible for failures.
</P>
<P>
   Since the construction budget ultimately has to be approved by
the mayor and the City Council, horse-trading is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report on the five-year plan that just expired included
hundreds of projects on 43 single-spaced pages _ many for critical
wall, window and roof work _ that had been promised, only to be
deferred. They were replaced by 35 pages of other projects, most
picked by the mayor and the Council.
</P>
<P>
   The changes make for dashed hopes at schools like John Bowne
High School in Queens. In the fall of 1997, the board informed
Bowne administrators that its laboratories would be renovated,
welcome news since three of its labs are 35 years old and the
fourth is a home economics classroom.
</P>
<P>
   But in March 1998, after the new labs were already designed, the
board suspended the project indefinitely, deciding instead to
repair the exteriors of other schools.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the project died matters little at a school where the
advanced placement environmental sciences class is held in an old
kitchen. There, 22 students share two sinks and cannot light Bunsen
burners on the counter tops for fear of setting the wooden cabinets
on fire. Instead, they hold the burners in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the authority and board are quick to point
out that whatever the shortcomings of the last decade, they have
produced classroom space for 115,000 students, 76,000 within the
last five years. Schools are now erected in as little as three
years, much quicker than the average of 10 years it took in the
1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fewer than half of the new classroom seats, about 53,500,
are in new, permanent buildings. More than a third, about 42,000,
sit in leased commercial spaces, in makeshift classrooms
partitioned from existing classes and locker rooms, or in factories
and other buildings that the board now owns. The remainder, about
20,000, are in trailers and other portable buildings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A recent survey by the board found that almost a third of the
city's schools had their windows or roofs replaced, their exterior
masonry shored up or some combination over the last five years. But
that yearlong survey also found that one out of four city schools
had seriously deteriorated roofs or exterior walls, and two out of
five had deteriorated windows.
</P>
<P>
   In a more disturbing finding, the survey highlighted significant
problems in a number of schools that were either built or repaired
by the authority within the last five years. Those deficiencies,
often in the very roofs or set of windows that were to have been
fixed, point to any number of shortcomings in the system, from
sluggish contractors to a maintenance budget so paltry that it
allows for little maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this leaves teachers and students waiting, people
like Karina Constantino, the principal of P.S. 22 on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   The authority spent $2 million putting a new roof on the school
and sealing its brickwork from 1995 through 1997. But almost two
years later, the roof leaks in seven places, she said, pointing out
the wide, wet blotches on the ceilings of a number of classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Constantino is hardly surprised, since she said it was often
up to her to bound up to the roof to scrape her fingernails against
freshly set mortar to determine its consistency or to check whether
the chimney was in danger of falling _ tasks, she says, the
authority should have been doing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
