<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4966 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-KC-KAN &LR;      07-27 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITIES ISSUE CAUTIONS ABOUT ELECTRICITY USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY and LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Unrelenting heat pushed electricity
consumption to an all-time high for Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.
on Monday, and the utility asked customers to reduce their usage
for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   For the ninth-straight day, the high temperature in Kansas City
registered in the 90s, and even hit 100 for the first time since
1991 at Kansas City International Airport. Even though the rain
forecast for today could break that streak, hotter weather is
expected later this week _ a threat that officials at KCP&AMP;L are
taking seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Levetzow, a spokeswoman for the utility, said the record
demand was met without brownouts. Nonetheless, predictions of more
hot weather and tighter supplies of wholesale electricity in the
region spurred the utility to request conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a potential for greater concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The demand by KCP&AMP;L customers on Monday reached 3,227 megawatts
between 3 and 4 p.m. The previous hourly record was 3,175 megawatts
last Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Kansas City said they think that heat advisories,
issued daily in the area since the July 4 weekend, are saving
lives. No heat-related deaths have been reported since the latest
wave began, but a 65-year-old Kansas City man died July 8 and an
81-year-old Lee's Summit woman died a day later from heat exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger immediate concern, said state utility regulators, is
the soaring demand for electricity. Consumption has put constraints
on the wholesale electric market, where utilities routinely sell
excess power to one another to help meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   So far demand is being met, but ``everything is tight,'' said
Bill Washburn, manager of the electric department at the Missouri
Public Service Commission in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L is asking customers to cut consumption between 2 and 8
p.m. by setting air conditioners at 82 degrees, not running large
appliances such as dishwashers and clothes dryers during the heat
of the day, and turning off unnecessary lighting and electrical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Public Service, the Raytown utility with about 200,000
customers in western Missouri, said it was meeting demand. But it
reminded customers of ways to reduce usage, such as taking showers,
cooking only during the early morning and late evening, and raising
the thermostat.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L's large commercial and industrial customers with
interruptible contracts already have reduced consumption. Those
contracts give utility customers cheaper rates when they agree to
reduce use at the utility's request.
</P>
<P>
   All of KCP&AMP;L's plants are running except Hawthorn 5, which was
put out of commission earlier this year by an explosion. The
utility is buying electricity on the wholesale market to help
replace the power that would have been provided by Hawthorn 5.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Kan., the Board of Public Utilities said it was
able to meet Monday's demand, despite a fire last week at its
largest power plant, which had prompted appeals for conservation.
The request remains in effect, said Don Denney, a BPU spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU also got some good news when it was told that a
temporary elevator would be in place by Aug. 16 that would deliver
enough coal to bring the fire-damaged Nearman plant up to 25
percent of its capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources, which operates KPL and KGE in Kansas, said
Monday that all of its plants were running and that it was able to
meet demand; neither utility set a record for electricity use
Monday. Spokesman George Norton said Western always encourages
customers to conserve and was not yet calling for voluntary cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Such appeals by utilities must be issued with a caveat, said a
health official in Cincinnati, where seven persons died of
heat-related illnesses over the weekend _ including a woman who had
turned off her air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The utility companies always stress power conservation, but we
need to be more careful about issuing that to the public,'' said
Malcom Adcock, commissioner of the Cincinnati Department of Health.
The woman who turned off her air conditioning, Adcock said, was
either trying to save power or save on her utility bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't turn off your air conditioning if you are elderly or
have a health problem,'' Adcock said. ``Most of us don't think of
the heat as being life-threatening. It can very well be.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the temperatures in Kansas City, the Metropolitan
Ambulance Services Trust reports no unusual upswing in runs. In
addition, area hospitals have not reported increases in
heat-related illnesses. And none of the area's eight heat shelters
has opened yet because, even though it has been hot, it hasn't been
hot enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know why we've been so lucky, except maybe we've
learned,'' said Dan Lindholm, chairman of the Kansas City Area Heat
Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 weather was blamed in the deaths of 148 Kansas Citians
when ovenlike heat blanketed the city with 100-degree temperatures
for more than two weeks. That same year, a study of heat-related
deaths was released by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC encouraged cities to coordinate agencies and approach
the heat the same way as any other disaster. The study also
determined that fans alone in 100-degree heat might actually
increase body heat.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioned shelters were needed for those who didn't have
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City created a plan that same year, Lindholm said. Today
the Heat Task Force is made up of 16 area agencies, including the
Red Cross, police and fire departments and public utilities. The
group has met once this year to talk about preparations, Lindholm
said. ``But we're watching the forecasts this week closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight cooling shelters are ready to be opened if a heat alert is
issued, he said. So far this summer Kansas City has not issued any
heat alerts.
</P>
<P>
   Heat alerts are issued when the heat index reaches 105 degrees
or hotter by 11 a.m. The heat index is a measure combining heat and
humidity, gauging more accurately what the weather actually feels
like.
</P>
<P>
   The task force wants people to know that public libraries are
available for people to escape the heat during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have four homeless shelters where people can go during
the hottest parts of the day to get some relief from the heat,''
Lindholm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
