<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-NOSMOKE-2Takes-LAD     07-27 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NOSMOKE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF TICKETING HAS ANTI-SMOKERS FUMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles fire inspectors, recently assigned to
enforce the 18-month-old statewide ban on workplace smoking, have
visited more than 80 bars in the past three weeks and found several
smokers _ but issued no tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors said they are trying a more educational approach
to their job, rather than busting violators and slapping them with
$81 fines, especially since the enforcement program has just
started.
</P>
<P>
   That soft approach has Mayor Richard Riordan's support, but it
is not what the City Council had in mind when it approved the
$250,000 enforcement program, said Councilwoman Laura Chick, Public
Safety Committee chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pleased with what I'm hearing,'' Chick said. ``The
Fire Department presented, along with the city attorney, to the
City Council an enforcement program, not an education program.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Capt. Mark Gozawa, who supervises the program, said the
inspectors were not instructed to refrain from issuing tickets but
rather to judge each case on its merits. If someone is defiant or a
repeat offender, they should get a ticket, he said, but in other
cases the inspectors should use their discretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to meet the spirit of the law _ which is trying
to get a smoke-free workplace, not to see how many tickets we can
write,'' Gozawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said such direction is at odds with the council's intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not what they have been directed to do,'' replied
Chick. ``This is about enforcing the law. They are supposed to be
going out and enforcing the law. Those are the instructions they
received from the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick's office called the Fire Department recently to register a
complaint, but she has not yet received a response.
</P>
<P>
   Gozawa said there are no changes planned in how the department
conducts its inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he agrees with the inspectors' approach because the
city is just starting to enforce the smoking law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you have quality-of-life crimes, sometimes you're
better off to first educate the public on it and warn them you're
going to be ticketing them after a certain period of time, but to
jump right in I think is not good government,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide ban on smoking in bars and restaurants took effect
18 months ago, although the city's enforcement had been spotty
because it lacked a formal enforcement program and policy. To
address that problem, the City Council recently authorized the Fire
Department to assign two full-time inspectors and a clerk to
smoking enforcement starting July1, saying it was long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors can levy fines of $81 to a smoker on a first time
offense, which doubles on the second offense and doubles again on
the third. Businesses can be fined $100 at first, and then as high
as $7,000 for numerous offenses, at which time the California
Occupational Safety and Health Administration can get involved
because the ban is considered a workplace health issue.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening, uniformed fire inspector Brian Jones and
his temporary partner, Luis Jaramillo, visited at least four bars
and restaurants in the San Fernando Valley. Each bar was chosen
because of past complaints received from customers before the city
had a formal enforcement program.
</P>
<P>
   A boisterous customer greeted them warmly as soon as they walked
in _ at first joking, ``Hey, you got a light?'' and then
high-fiving them as he declared, ``These guys are my heroes!''
</P>
<P>
   The customer, Chris Vandoli of Palmdale and his wife, Sherri,
said they are happy to see the inspectors and choose to come to
this particular bar in North Hollywood because it usually enforces
the smoking ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't smoke, so we're glad it's illegal,'' Sherri Vandoli
said. ``That's why we come here.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a bar in suburban Sherman Oaks, Jones caught a woman
smoking at the bar near the front door. And at a Woodland Hills
restaurant, he saw a trio of smokers sitting at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, he let off the smokers and the bartenders with
just a warning, even though they acknowledged they knew smoking
there was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to go to the places and educate the general public and
the owners as to what has to be done to avoid them getting cited,''
Jones said. ``We're not looking, like the CHP, to have 50 tickets
written in an eight-hour day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and his partner visit Los Angeles bars and restaurants two
nights a week, and visit offices and warehouses two days a week.
With some 3,000 bars and restaurants, they know they can't possibly
visit them all _ especially since they always travel together _ so
they only respond to complaints, some more than 6 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, Jones' approach to smokers and bartenders is fairly
affable and straightforward. When he saw the three smokers in
Woodland Hills, he told them, ``Are you guys from California? You
should know better. You have to put those out _ otherwise we have
to write you a ticket right now.''
</P>
<P>
   They snuff out the butts and then listen to the polite lecture
that Johnson finds himself giving several times a night. He informs
them about the hefty fines they could be subject to, but this time
he is letting them go with a warning.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Although they aren't happy, by the end of the talk they thank
him for not issuing fines and move to the restaurant's outside
terrace to continue smoking where it is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The three smokers complied with the inspectors but said they
think the state's smoking law goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this Big Brother thing,'' said Jackie Ketcham, a
hotel supervisor from Hermosa Beach. ``They're telling you you
can't do this, you can't do that. It's getting out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have stronger words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely disgusting,'' said Pat Clark, the
woman who was caught smoking in Sherman Oaks. A Beverly Hills
Realtor, Clark put out her cigarette at Jones' request but argued
with him for some time instead of listening to his lecture quietly.
</P>
<P>
   She told him it didn't seem fair that California has such strong
restrictions when no other state does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go stand outside and have a cigarette,'' she
told Jones. ``Why don't we do it nationwide?''
</P>
<P>
   To which Jones had a quick reply: ``You know what? New York is
coming out here next week. They want to see how the program
works.''
</P>
<P>
   The smoking ban, in effect for the workplace since 1995 but
expanded to bars and restaurants in January 1998, has been enforced
to varying levels in different cities throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   While Los Angeles and San Francisco have been slower to dedicate
resources to the ban, San Diego has been more aggressive, sending
undercover police into bars to ticket smokers and bar owners, and
referring cases to the City Attorney's Office for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the San Diego police issued 134 citations to smokers,
according to the City Attorney's Office. Of those, 101 either
pleaded guilty or were found guilty, while 28 people failed to
appear in court and therefore have warrants outstanding for their
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the San Diego police have issued more than 70 smoking
citations, according to Detective James Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   He said they try to take a discreet approach: They'll hang out
in plainclothes in a bar for a little while, and when they see
someone smoking they will approach them and quietly show their
badges and ask the person to step outside. They always travel in
teams, just in case a drunken patron decides to get rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett said it is rare for the vice detectives to let people
off with a warning if they catch them smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law went into effect in January of 1998, so it's been over
a year and a half,'' Jarrett said. ``It's been a very publicized
law, so we pretty much allowed a 30-day grace period and then
started enforcing back in February of 1998. There were no warnings
at that time _ we just basically began citing folks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
