Europe into wireless data services is keeping the Continent well
ahead of the slower-moving United States. Teen-agers in Italy
already use their cell phones to tap out millions of short messages
every day. Germany's top-selling tabloid offers scores of news and
sports bulletins through short messages. In Finland, it is possible
to order taxis and take-out pizzas. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ One of the nicest things the United
States ever did for Japan, it seems, was to force it, screaming and
kicking, to open its market for cellular phones. That was five
years ago. Now Japan has a higher concentration of cellular
telephones than the United States. More astonishing, Japan has
caught up with Europe, the early pace-setter, and has plans to move
ahead. By Sheryl WuDunn.
