<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-WOMEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN PLAYING SOCCER FOR THE LOVE OF A GAME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 16th graf to correct spelling of Dyckman Park)  (ms) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were career professionals who were also soccer
moms, sideline boosters content to watch smaller versions of
themselves scurrying about soccer fields. They did not fit the
profile of the typical frustrated jock.
</P>
<P>
   Yet every time they helped their children don their jerseys and
strap on shinguards or watched them score a goal and beam in joyous
celebration, the more consumed they were with a desire to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always proud to watch my two sons play soccer,'' said
Joan Madden-Peister, a state Supreme Court judge whose sons, Evan,
18, and Kyle, 14, play in a youth league in the city. ``One day, I
realized I wanted to get a soccer ball and I wanted to have a
uniform and I wanted to score goals. I never had that opportunity
when I was growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, she was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Madden-Peister and her teammates on the Parlour Moms,
a recreational women's team she helped found three years ago, will
travel to Ireland to play four amateur women's teams in Dublin and
Galway. Their first match is Saturday against the Irish Allied Bank
team. Three more games will be played next week against opponents
they know little about, except that the team in Galway is known as
Castle Celtic.
</P>
<P>
   And after the tournament, there will be no news-media frenzy or
promotional trips to Disneyland for the Americans, as there were
for the U.S. women's team that won the World Cup two weeks ago.
There's nothing more at stake than bragging rights over beer and,
perhaps, a shared sense of personal satisfaction for a group of
women who have come to discover that it is never to late to score a
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little scared, but this will be fun,'' said Jane
Kenney, a magazine editor who is leaving the children behind with
her husband, John.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was arranged by Maggie Bradley-Cook, a physical
therapist and mother of two soccer-playing teen-agers, after she
was feeling a bit jealous last summer that her 13-year-old daughter
got to play soccer in Sweden and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself: `What's this? Our kids get these
opportunities and we sacrifice,''' Bradley-Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The Parlour Moms were formed after a youth soccer dinner, when
Madden-Peister had a sign-up sheet asking if there might be other
women interested in playing. More than 100 women signed up.
</P>
<P>
   That was in the days before the U.S. women's national team,
mostly pony-tailed and unified in team spirit, put the sport into
the national spotlight. Through attrition _ injuries, frustration,
other responsibilities _ nearly 60 dropped out. What was left was a
ragtag team that became known as the Parlour Moms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly invigorating,'' said Wendy Hollender, 44, a
home-furnishing designer who continued to play during recent
chemotherapy treatments for breast cancer. ``I see some of my
neighbors walking around half asleep, and I'm coming in after
playing two hours and my adrenaline is pumping.''
</P>
<P>
   The team plays under the auspices of the Bronx Irish League.
Started 10 years ago by newly arrived Irish immigrants, the adult
recreational league sponsors interleague play between teams from
Queens, the Bronx and the only Manhattan-based team, the Parlour
Moms. The name was taken from The Parlour, the Irish pub and
restaurant on the Upper West Side, where members of the team
gathered on Monday and Thursday evenings after practice at Turf
Soccer Field in Riverside Park.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine of the Parlour Moms will be making the trip to
Ireland. Among the missing will be the team's three goalies. To
bolster their roster and their chances of winning, the team
recruited players from a rival team, the Harps, this season's Bronx
Irish league champions. They are younger and more skilled players.
</P>
<P>
   Katie McNeil, an architect, who plays defense for the Harps,
learned that the Parlour Moms were looking for volunteers to make
the trip to Ireland. She changed her vacation plans and persuaded
Karen Rice, a forward, Allison Kaye, who played for Dartmouth
College, and Hillary Potkewitz, a central midfielder, to put aside
interleague rivalry and become a Parlour Mom, even though all four
are single and childless.
</P>
<P>
   The Parlour Moms know they will have to play their best to wrest
a victory from their Irish opponents. For one thing, the teams in
Ireland play regulation 90-minute games, as opposed to the
70-minute games in the Bronx Irish League. In addition, the fields
are expected to be bigger than the ones at Van Cortlandt and
Dyckman Parks and those on Randalls Island where the Parlour Moms
play on Saturday afternoons. And, the amateur leagues in Ireland
are said to be highly organized and the players far more
experienced than their American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday evening, John Kelly, co-owner of the Parlour, was
standing on the sideline of Turf Field watching the team practice
and reminiscing about the women in the knee-high socks, T-shirts
and shorts, who dragged themselves into his bar one evening two
years ago shortly after it opened and commiserated about how
terrible they were as players. One year later, with Kelly as their
sponsor, the team won the league's championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude has completely changed,'' Kelly said. Asked in
what way, he replied, ``Oh, they're cutthroat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley-Cook, a tall, athletic-type who played basketball in
high school and finished the 1979 New York City marathon in 4 hours
4 minutes, said that she and the other women on the team _ which
has an average age of 45 _ have no illusions about the level of
their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we felt eager to ingratiate whatever experience we could
create for ourselves,'' she said. ``I'm 50 years old. It doesn't
seem like a valid thing to seem so important to me because it seems
very selfish and separate from my family and my work. But it's
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The players say that soccer has become their saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   Hollender said she might have let cancer get the better of her.
As a soccer player, however, she is used ``to taking blows and the
aches and pains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After I had my surgery, once the anesthesia wore off, I
climbed off the table and was ready to go,'' said Hollender, the
speedy striker who credits her teammates with helping her maintain
her psyche throughout her chemotherapy treatments. ``Heck, I was
bruised up more on the soccer field. Instead of focusing on the
cancer and living in fear, my question to my doctor was when could
I play soccer again.''
</P>
<P>
   By their own admission, they will never play as well as their
children. But at least they will know what it feels like to use
your head to block a shot or to catch a pass on the inside of your
foot, then kick it to another woman streaking down the field, who
steadies it for a moment and sends it sailing toward the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now all we need are ponytails,'' Bradley-Cook said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
