<HEADLINE>
KING TO FACE TENNIS ROYALTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Phillip King discovered he had a solid chance
of earning a wild-card entry into the Mercedes-Benz Cup at UCLA, he
was excited. Then he discovered the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called (an event official) and asked, `Who do I play?' ''
said King, a 17-year-old Long Beach resident and top junior player
in the country. ``He said, `Sampras.' I said, `Ha ha ha.' He said,
`No, you really do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Can I give the wild card back?' '' said King's
coach, Eliot Teltscher.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. King plays in the first round tonight at 7:30 against
second-seeded Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   King, who won the prestigious Easter Bowl tournament this
spring, earned the opportunity by being the last name to come out
of the draw on Friday. Instead of being intimidated, King has been
relaxed about his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just trying to be myself,'' the baseliner said. ``Hopefully,
I'll just go out and play my best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   He has two things going for him. King has hit with Sampras at
Riviera. Plus, the last time Sampras played a 17-year-old, Xavier
Malaisse took him to 7-5 in the third set in Philadelphia last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also remembers what it's like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember playing (Ivan) Lendl and (John) McEnroe the first
time,'' he said. ``It's intimidating. You grow up watching these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Paying homage: The tournament is honoring Rod Laver, who won
titles here in 1968 and '70. Sampras and Agassi spoke reverently
about the Australian legend who is one of the few to win two of the
four Grand Slam tournaments in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a player who was complete,'' Sampras said. ``He played
well in all surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi added: ``Most players feel the same way Pete does. Rod
has impacted the game like no other. To me, his record is
phenomenal. He's the man in the game of tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Back home: Justin Gimelstob loves UCLA. As a Bruin, he led
UCLA to the NCAA team final against Stanford in 1996. Last year as
a pro, he reached the semifinal here.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he started with a 6-2, 6-2 victory over 18-year-old
Taylor Dent, a wild-card qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being in L.A.,'' Gimelstob said. ``I love that court. I
get my friends to support me.'' One such friend was his former UCLA
teammate, Jean-Noel Grinda. The native of France is taking
summer-school classes, so he figured watching the matches would be
fun, especially considering Grinda has faced several of the
participants in junior tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   One such player is Australian James Sekulov, a qualifier who
beat Martin Damm of the Czech Republic on Monday. Sekulov was the
second seed at the U.S. Open juniors and Grinda beat him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Night at the Net: Agassi and Sampras participated with Robin
Williams and Billy Crystal in a fund-raiser for MusiCares, the
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences' charity.
</P>
<P>
   The quips flew faster than the balls Sampras and Agassi hit. A
sampling:
</P>
<P>
   After Williams shows his leg, Crystal said, ``Did you wax?''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, frustrated that his partner, Crystal, kept hitting the
ball at Sampras: ``Six Wimbledons! Hit it to Robin!''
</P>
<P>
   Country singer Clint Black, who sang two songs: ``I've never
opened up for a tennis match. I've got to give credit to my
manager. In the past, I've opened up for Ping-Pong matches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
