<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-27 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY, RODRIGUEZ AWAIT CLUES FROM M'S OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Butch Huskey was on his way to Boston Monday. The
Mariners traded the outfielder for a minor-league pitcher, helping
add to the deal-making fodder of this so-called important week in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   (As if any team other than the Yankees, Mets, Cleveland or
Atlanta is going to win the World Series.)
</P>
<P>
   Trading deadlines are when clubs splurge or purge to set a tone
for what happens next, and the M's, now 11 games out in the AL
West, certainly have reason to start looking to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The M's need pitching. They don't need any more slow-footed,
big-bat outfielders. So Huskey was a logical place to start with
the Safeco Field-necessitated re-tooling.
</P>
<P>
   But more than Huskey's trip to Beantown, one should look at Ken
Griffey Jr.'s solo trip home to Florida Monday for a visit with his
family to get a truer sense of what the future holds for the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey used the Mariners' off day to charter a flight home
between games in Minneapolis and Kansas City. Now that his son Trey
is starting school in Orlando, Griffey has said getting back home
on off days is a priority.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the 2,700 miles that separate Seattle from
Orlando, that is a pretty tall order, should the superstar center
fielder wish to remain in a Mariner uniform, as most everyone
wishes he would and as he, deep down in his loyal baseball heart,
knows would be a good thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   What could convince Griffey to sign on the dotted line?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners know the answer _ or at least a big part of it _
and it's pitching. They have had the answer all year, ever since
Randy Johnson was traded away and the Mariners of 1995 started to
become a distant memory and the M's found no free agent pitcher
they felt was worth the investment.
</P>
<P>
   (They'll say hindsight is treating them favorably. Tim Belcher
is hurt and the Angels were toast. Kevin Brown and his $105 million
haven't done anything for the Dodgers. Johnson did not want to be
here, they say.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mariners' task of convincing their superstars they
are committed to winning is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to sign Ken Griffey Jr. We want to sign Alex
Rodriguez. But they have to want to sign,'' club president Chuck
Armstrong said Monday after another discussion about Griffey's deal
failed to produce an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mariners are willing to pay Griffey and Rodriguez top
dollar, money and length of service are again not the issues _ at
least with Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Griffey and Rodriguez have been adamant
about what it will take to get them to consider sticking around. In
fact, at so many points this season when the Mariners' minor-league
call-ups have been battered, Rodriguez has wondered out loud:
</P>
<P>
   How long can this go on? Can't the Mariners fix this leaking
ship?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, meanwhile, has scoffed at reports that said he gave
Armstrong a list of teams to which he would accept a trade.
Instead, Griffey tendered a few suggestions about how to improve
the Mariners' travel schedule along with other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But certainly Griffey, like anyone else who has tried to
understand the motives and mechanics of this Mariner franchise, is
frustrated by an ownership that has been so distracted by the new
ballpark financing and politics that the team has been left without
a credible flight plan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, news broke about how Mariners part owner Howard
Lincoln was going to step down as Nintendo of America chairman
early next year. With Mariners CEO John Ellis hinting about
retirement, speculation is that Lincoln, perhaps along with his
chief confidente confidante and fellow Nintendo executive John
Bauer, will take over running the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to see how this will make much difference in the
way the M's pursue free agents or commit to a championship-caliber
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of asking Woody Woodward, the team's vice president of
baseball operations, or Armstrong or Ellis to go out and take a hit
for the team, the job of breaking unpopular news or changing
direction would fall squarely on the shoulders of the men whose
deep pockets own this club.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Lincoln and his cohorts are tough businessmen. They can
hack it, if they want the job.
</P>
<P>
   But if any of the Mariner owners has the notion that just by
stepping into the day-to-day fray makes the organization more
credible and in better control of its destiny, there could be some
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the same owners. They'll just have different
titles. It doesn't make a difference,'' Rodriguez said Monday. ``I
just have to keep playing hard, play out the year and make my
decision after 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, it doesn't matter who from this current ownership
is running the Mariners. It doesn't matter how many Butch Huskeys
are traded for minor-league pitching help.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the Mariners' future depends on what kind of rather
grand and perhaps impractical reassurances the club can give to two
of baseball's best players. And up until now, those guys are
putting out vibes that they've been given few reasons to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
