<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-YOSEMITE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-27 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-YOSEMITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FBI PROBE OF YOSEMITE SLAYINGS SCRUTINIZED  &HT;     By SUSAN SWARD and STACY FINZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With an anguished expression on his face, FBI
Special Agent James Maddock posed the question about the Yosemite
killings as clearly as anyone could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask myself if we could have done anything differently that
would have prevented the death of Joie Armstrong,'' said Maddock,
standing before a battery of cameras and reporters in Sacramento on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've struggled with that over the last 24 hours, and I
continue to do so, (but) I'm confident that we've done everything
that reasonably could have been done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddock's remarks underscored what is already obvious _ that the
FBI's investigation of the Yosemite case is now certain to come
under intense scrutiny by the public and by the FBI itself.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the agency has been reassuring the public that it had
the killers in the Yosemite tourists' slayings behind bars. The FBI
identified the alleged killers as members of a loose-knit band of
Modesto drug users with long criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   Then Monday, Cary Stayner, a 37-year-old maintenance worker, was
formally charged with last week's killing of Armstrong, and
sources, including a San Francisco TV station, say he has also
confessed killing three women touring Yosemite five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The basic facts of the case are well-known: On February 15,
Carole Sund, her daughter Julie and a family friend, Silvina
Pelosso, vanished after last being seen at the Cedar Lodge just
west of Yosemite National Park. In the ensuing days, Stayner _ who
had worked as a maintenance man at the lodge _ was interviewed by
FBI agents, as were dozens of other people living and working near
the park. But Stayner was quickly let go _ and now the public wants
to know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public's concern is that the FBI interviewed a guy, let
him go and he commits another crime,'' said Rick Smith, a former
FBI agent who now heads Cannon Street Inc. detective agency in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can feel good about that, but at the time they
interviewed Stayner regarding the Sund murders, in my opinion, they
must not have had probable cause to charge him,'' Smith said. ``I
don't think the public wants to change the Constitution to lean
toward charging someone where the FBI doesn't have enough proof to
charge him.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the FBI in Washington moved to put the handling of the
Yosemite killings in the best possible light. Tron Brekke, deputy
assistant director of the FBI, told The Chronicle that the media
would be overreaching to infer that Maddock's statement indicated
that something was done wrong in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for him (Maddock), but I think he felt anguish
about putting out something that may have misled people between
Saturday and Sunday (when Maddock initially discounted any link
between Armstrong's killing and the three other slayings),'' Brekke
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his statement that he read and put out Sunday, he (Maddock)
very clearly articulated that he feels and the others on the task
force feel they did everything in their power to investigate the
Sund-Pelosso case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is something to indicate that a person is
involved in a crime, there is very little we can do to prevent that
person from being involved in a future crime,'' Brekke said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major unanswered questions in the case is how the FBI
came to seize on a group of Modesto ``cranksters'' as the killers
of the Sunds and Pelosso.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when the bodies of the three sightseers were found,
the investigation began to focus on a group of parolees in the
Central Valley. They concentrated primarily on half-brothers
Michael Larwick and Eugene Dykes, both convicted sex offenders with
histories of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The men, both arrested on unrelated charges, remain in jail.
While in custody, Dykes allegedly acknowledged playing a role in
the Sund-Pelosso murders, sources said. But his stories changed
each time he was interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a federal grand jury began hearing testimony in the
case and witnesses confirmed that agents were taking a hard look at
the men and an assortment of their associates.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddock later told reporters that they were having a
difficult time making a case _ in large part because their
witnesses were ``cranksters,'' who used methamphetamine and were
regarded as unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   But he attempted to soothe the public by publicly announcing
that all the key participants in the killings were safely behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel we have all the main players in jail,'' Maddock said
last month. ``But we are in no rush to charge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some federal insiders now believe that the stream of oddball
witnesses, who ranged from jail inmates to known drug dealers, were
just leading investigators on.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, an 18-year-old member of the group, agreed to let
agents set up a recording device on his phone to tape a telephone
conversation between him and a woman who said she had a lot of
information on the case. But instead of giving the tape only to
investigators, the man sold it to a television tabloid show _
tainting its potential use as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's focus on the Modesto group as the only suspects in the
Sund-Pelosso case troubled even some who have worked closely with
law enforcement in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this: If the FBI didn't have a rock solid case
against all the participants (in the Sund-Pelosso killings), they
shouldn't have put out the information that the killers were behind
bars,'' said one former homicide prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But the ex-prosecutor, who has worked on numerous homicide cases
over the years, added that he believed the FBI's assurances that
the Sund-Pelosso killers were in custody might not have contributed
to Armstrong's decapitation death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure that made a difference in her killing,'' the
former prosecutor said. ``She more than likely would not have been
suspicious of Stayner in any event _ because of his normal
demeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brekke stressed that ``no one is here to fix blame at this
point,'' others familiar with the FBI say such a high-profile case
is certain to prompt much finger-pointing within the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of case causes nothing but absolute havoc for the
FBI,'' said one source knowledgeable about the FBI's inner
workings. ``From the standpoint of the FBI's Washington management,
it's always hindsight and Monday morning quarterbacking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
