<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 03:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5052 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-SLAYINGS-SFC     07-27 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-SLAYINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDYMAN ADMITS 4 KILLINGS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By STACY FINZ and JAXON VAN DERBEKEN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
(Ed. note: This story is accompanied by a sidebar, slugged
FBI-YOSEMITE)
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The handyman charged Monday with decapitating a
Yosemite naturalist has confessed that slaying as well as the
February killings of three park sightseers, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Stayner _ a 37-year-old maintenance man at the Cedar Lodge,
the motel just outside the park where the three tourists were last
seen _ knew details about the four slayings that only the killer
might know, said one source close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a jailhouse interview Monday with a San Francisco television
station, Stayner said he had dreamed about killing women for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner told KBWB Television in detail how he killed sightseers
Carole Sund, her daughter Julie and family friend Silvina Pelosso
in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   He said he strangled Silvina Pelosso and Carole Sund in their
rented cabin at the Cedar Lodge in mid-February, then took Julie
Sund to a lake, where he killed her early the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   He said he abandoned the group's car with the bodies of Silvina
Pelosso and Carole Sund in it, returning two days later to burn
evidence and retrieve Carole Sund's wallet, which he dumped in
Modesto to confuse authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner told KBWB he was the person who tipped the FBI to the
whereabouts of Julie Sund's body by sending an anonymous letter.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought he had gotten away with the crimes and did
not leave the area for fear of drawing attention to himself. That
changed when he met Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, last week and struck
up a chance conversation with her. He said he could not resist the
urge to kill her when he realized she was alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am guilty,'' said Stayner, who was not interviewed on
camera. ``I did murder Carole Sund, Julie Sund, Silvina Pelosso and
Joie Armstrong. ... None of the women were sexually abused in any
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have controlled myself and not done what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Nick Rossi said he could not say whether Stayner's
statements were consistent with what he has told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Stayner stood silently in U.S. District Court in
Sacramento as he was being charged with a single count of murder in
last week's slaying of Armstrong. The tanned, clean-cut defendant
nodded his head when a judge asked whether he understood the
allegation. If convicted, Stayner could be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   John Balazs, an assistant public defender with the U.S.
attorney's office, represented Stayner in court and said his mood
seemed ``fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner was arrested Saturday morning at a nudist colony near
Sacramento and questioned for hours about the slaying of Armstrong,
an environmental educator whose beheaded body was found Thursday in
a densely forested area of the national park, just a few hundred
feet from her home and about four miles from the Cedar Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   During the FBI interrogation, Stayner admitted killing Armstrong
as well as Carole Sund, Julie Sund, 15, and Silvina Pelosso, 16,
said the source close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunds and Pelosso visited the park in February and
disappeared from the Cedar Lodge, where they were staying. More
than a month later, Carole Sund's and Pelosso's charred bodies were
found in the trunk of their rental car about 50 miles away in the
hamlet of Long Barn. Julie Sund was discovered on the banks of Lake
Don Pedro a few days later _ and authorities said her head was
nearly severed from her body.
</P>
<P>
   Agents are trying to corroborate Stayner's statements that he
killed the tourists, said a federal official who asked not to be
named. Stayner has not been charged in the three sightseers'
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four months, investigators working on the Sund and
Pelosso killings have focused on a loose-knit group of violent
methamphetamine users living in Modesto. Many in the group,
including two half-brothers, were rounded up and jailed on
unrelated charges.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were hoping that an investigative grand jury in
Fresno would help them gather enough evidence to charge members of
the group with the three slayings. But now they are questioning
whether the men were involved at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not off the hook yet,'' said the source. `'It's very
difficult to believe he (Stayner) did this on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators looking into Armstrong's killing became suspicious
of Stayner when someone reported seeing his blue and white
International Scout near Armstrong's cabin on Foresta Road on
Wednesday about 7:30 p.m. _ an hour after Armstrong was last known
to be alive _ according to a criminal complaint filed Monday in
U.S. District Court in Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was scheduled to visit a friend that night in
Sausalito, but she never showed up. The friend called police early
the next morning to report Armstrong missing, and at 1 p.m. park
rangers and FBI agents found her body. More than three hours later,
a park ranger and a Mariposa County sheriff's detective interviewed
Stayner about the killing.
</P>
<P>
   He denied being anywhere near Foresta Road the evening of
Armstrong's death and let investigators search his truck, according
to court papers. When Stayner refused to let them look in his
backpack, they seized it, fearing that Armstrong's head _ missing
at the time _ might be hidden inside, according to the documents.
The head was later found near her body.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Stayner did not show up for work, which Cedar
Lodge employees said was unusual. Authorities put out an all-points
bulletin, and a woman at the nudist camp who recognized his name
from news reports turned him in the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his statement to the interviewing agents, Stayner provided
details about the (Armstrong) crime that are not generally known
outside law enforcement, and which corroborate his confession,''
court records say.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner is the older brother of Steven Stayner, who was abducted
from a Merced street in December 1972 and sexually abused by his
kidnapper for more than seven years. He escaped in March 1980 and
was reunited with his family, only to be killed nine years later in
a motorcycle crash at age 24.
</P>
<P>
   Merced County authorities say that in addition to the killings
of Armstrong, Pelosso and the Sunds, they want to question Cary
Stayner about the Dec. 26, 1990, shooting death of his 42-year-old
uncle, Jesse ``Jerry'' Stayner.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Sheriff Henry Strength of Merced County said Cary
Stayner had been living with his uncle at the time but had not been
considered a suspect. ``He was somewhere else (when the uncle was
killed),'' Strength said. ``Nothing tied him to the homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Stayner had come home for lunch from his job as a
dispatcher for a hay-chopping operation when he was shot with his
own gun.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner has no criminal record. He was arrested March 28, 1997,
in a drug raid on the home of a friend in Atwater, near Merced, but
was released without being charged.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said little Monday about the killing of Armstrong or the
Sund-Pelosso case. During a press conference Sunday, Special Agent
James Maddock said agents had been unable to make a link between
Stayner and the original suspects in the Sund-Pelosso killings.
</P>
<P>
   But Carole and Francis Carrington, the parents of Carole Sund
and grandparents of Julie Sund, seemed confident that their long
wait for justice may be coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Armstrong's family said they were not ready to
comment. An uncle, who asked to be identified only as Jim, said,
``We're exhausted. We're just drained.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Charlie Goodyear, Lynda Gledhill,
Meredith May, Torri Minton, Pamela Podger and Kevin Fagan
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
