r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUNWAY-SAFETY-SFCHRON     07-27 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNWAY-SAFETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY PLAN FOR RUNWAYS CALLED A FLOP
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID DIETZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A Federal Aviation Administration program to avoid accidents
and close calls on runways has flopped, a government oversight
report said Monday.
<P>
   The report, by the Department of Transportation's inspector
general, said the number of ``runway incursions'' remains at a high
level because the FAA has been too slow to fight the hazard.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second major analysis this year to criticize the
FAA's handling of a problem that a White House report identified in
1998 as one of the most pressing aviation dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Incursions are occasions in which aircraft get too close to each
other or to vehicles, people or objects at airports.
</P>
<P>
   The number of close encounters rose from 186 in 1993 to 325 in
1998, a 75 percent increase. Through the first six months of this
year, 149 incursions were recorded, one fewer than the comparable
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runway incursions continue to be a serious problem in 1999,''
the inspector general said.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes in the aftermath of two harrowing near-misses
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, a fully loaded Korean Air jumbo jet missed a cargo
plane by 50 feet while taking off at Chicago's O'Hare International
Airport. Last month, an Icelandair 757 passenger jet narrowly
averted an Air France 747 freighter in another takeoff near-miss.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector General Kenneth Mead said the FAA's 1998 plan to
reduce incursions has been ineffective because 15 of 23 proposed
actions still await implementation.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the FAA is between five and 13 months behind in
finishing such projects as installing collision-warning systems in
traffic control towers and developing individual incident reduction
plans at airports.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that unless the FAA oversees the program more
aggressively, it is unlikely to achieve its goal of reducing annual
incursions to 248, a 15 percent cut from the 1997 level, by the end
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman Fraser Jones said the agency agrees with the
report's conclusions and has ``already taken actions to implement
the recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   To see to it that the 1998 plan gets implemented as quickly as
possible, FAA Administrator Jane Garvey has gotten directly
involved through monthly briefings, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, an FAA consultant also accused the agency of
foot-dragging on incursions. Mitre Corp. of Virginia said the FAA
was relying on primitive technology for guiding runway traffic,
despite a surge in air travel.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional committee looked into FAA handling of runway
incidents in 1997, the result of a series of Chronicle articles on
incursions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
