<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OLD 49ERS COULD EVEN SPELL FINESSE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's official: The 49ers have become the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Al Davis' Raiders were once a refuge for outcasts and misfits,
while the 49ers rejected players who ate their salad with the wrong
fork.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders' bad-guy thing played itself out, and they now seek
men of character. While the 49ers seek ... whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walsh, new 49ers' GM who coached the team back in the days
of high moral fiber, has signed defensive end Charles Haley and
Monday added running back Lawrence Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers shipped Haley out years ago for very, very unsociable
conduct. Phillips betrayed every American team he ever played for,
college and pro. And then there are his convictions, including a
brutal attack on a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Is Walsh channeling the spirit of Jerry Tarkanian, world's
foremost Outlaws-R-Us college basketball coach? No, on a
technicality: Tark's still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers swear that Haley and Phillips have cleaned up their
acts, and maybe so, especially Haley. But Walsh is doing his best
to dump the team's Boy Scout image.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY ON Creepy Theater, we present: ``Cold Chills in the Hot
Tub.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Geist, ace reporter for KGO radio, checked into the
Cedar Lodge in Yosemite last March to file reports on the search
for three female tourists who would later turn up murdered.
</P>
<P>
   In our opening scene, Mary Ellen works hard and files her
reports, then about 10:30 p.m. decides to take a swim in the lodge
pool and a soak in the hot tub. There's no one around as she swims
her laps, until she senses something, sees a man in a black bikini
suit walk by and sink into the hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let him ruin my plans,'' Geist says to
herself, and she joins the man in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' he says to her, ``my name is Cary Stayner.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next half hour he tells her the tragic story of his
brother, who spent seven years as captive of a kidnapper-molester,
then died in a motorcycle accident.
</P>
<P>
   Geist now says of her tubmate, ``He was handsome, and very nice,
very polite. But he was looking at me in a way that made me
uncomfortable, so I just got up suddenly and left. I ran up the
steps, double-bolted my door and pushed a table and chair against
it. That's very unlike me, but I got the creeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner has been charged with murdering and decapitating a woman
who worked at Yosemite, and is the prime suspect in the killing of
the three tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still creeped out,'' says Mary Ellen.
</P>
<P>
   FILE THIS under Stories That Come Back to Bite You in the End.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Patrick Ziemann of Santa Rosa, who resigned last week and
admitted having a sexual affair with a priest, was the subject of a
glowing article in the Santa Rosa Press-Democrat last October. The
priest now claims he was forced into the three-year relationship by
Ziemann's threats to report the priest for stealing church money.
</P>
<P>
   From the P-D story: ``(Ziemann's) direct, personal style may
help explain his popularity in the face of the biggest
(molestation) scandal ever confronted by the region's Catholics ...
''
</P>
<P>
   What made Bishop Ziemann so popular? One parishioner told the
P-D, ``He's the most accessible, hands-on bishop that I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUING today's theme of borderline bad taste: Country Joe
McDonald, the Berkeley music legend who rocked the original
Woodstock with his ``Vietnam Rag'' (``Whoopie, we're all going to
die!''), got bad news Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness Book of World Records rejected Country Joe's formal
bid to be recognized as the person who has made the most people
yell the F-word in public. Country Joe and the Fish used to open
their act with a spell-out, Joe saying, ``Gimme a big F,'' and so
on, then, ``What's that spell?''
</P>
<P>
   He led half a million people in screaming the word at Woodstock.
It had to do with Vietnam, kids, and you had to be there, but many
found the spell-out daring and inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Guinness says its officials have no way of knowing if
anyone might have topped Joe.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's not giving up on his quest, and you have to admire
his ... Gimme a big P ... L ... U ... C ... K.
</P>
<P>
   ``STAY TUNED, folks. Immediately following the figure skating,
we'll have the finals of the drive-by shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun enthusiasts are fighting to have ``combat shooting''
declared an Olympic event. Only they've changed the name to
``practical shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors armed with assault rifles, semiautomatic handguns
and shotguns blast away at targets shaped like people _ enemy
soldiers, pizza delivery boys, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get behind this movement, a guaranteed gold medal for
America. We'll blow away the competition.
</P>
<P>
   YES, SAN FRANCISCO, you've got the most expensive gasoline in
the country. But stop complaining. It's God's way of evening out
the blessings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
