<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GETTING AROUND IRA TAX  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I know that if I withdraw money from my traditional
Individual Retirement Account, I will have to pay taxes on the
money. But what if I donate the entire account to a charitable
organization? Can I avoid taxes and claim the donation as a
deduction?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not that simple. In fact, when it comes to tax matters,
practically nothing is simple.
</P>
<P>
   You can't simply pick up your IRA and hand it over to a charity
tax free. Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says that
under tax law you would be viewed as withdrawing all your funds
from the IRA, and that is ``a taxable event.''
</P>
<P>
   You can, however, do essentially what you want to do if you wait
until you die. If you name the charity as a beneficiary in your
will, you can leave it the entire IRA, and the amount of the IRA
will be exempt from estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to give the money to charity before you die, you are
free to do that, too _ after paying taxes on the IRA withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   You don't indicate how much money is in the account, but bear in
mind that when you claim a deduction for the donation, you are
limited to a maximum of 50 percent of your adjusted gross income
for the year. For example, if you give away $100,000 and your
income is $50,000, you can claim only $25,000 as a deduction on
that year's income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you are allowed to carry over the excess amount for
as long as five years. In the example above, you can deduct $25,000
more the next year _ assuming that your income remains at $50,000.
You can do the same thing the next year and the year after that, at
which point the full $100,000 deduction will be used up.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing an IRA
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to open two Individual Retirement Accounts, one for me
and one for my husband. Should I open two Roth IRAs, or one Roth
and one traditional?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are opening a new IRA, I can't think of any reason to
open anything but a Roth. Roths are vastly superior to traditional
IRAs in almost every respect.
</P>
<P>
   However, because you don't mention your income, I don't know
whether you actually qualify for a Roth. Individuals can't open one
if they have income greater than $110,000, while there is a
$160,000 maximum for married couples who file a joint tax return.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest thing about a Roth is that your investment gains
accumulate tax-free. That isn't true of traditional IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Another big advantage: You don't have to withdraw your funds
when you reach age 701/2, as you must with traditional IRAs. In
fact, you can keep making contributions to the IRA beyond that age,
and you never have to withdraw the funds. You can leave the Roth
account to your heirs, and they won't have to pay estate taxes on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Gains Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I realize that one needs to pay capital gains taxes on
profits one makes trading stocks. But can you tell me whether
capital gains could push me into a higher income tax bracket?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it conceivably could happen _ but only with short-term
capital gains. If you don't sell a stock until at least a year and
a day after you buy it, any profit becomes a long-term capital
gain, and there is no bracket creep. (I'm not calling you names;
that's jargon for moving into a higher tax bracket.)
</P>
<P>
   For example, if your ordinary income places you in the 28
percent tax bracket, any additional income from long-term capital
gains will be taxed at a maximum rate of only 20 percent. If you
are in the 15 percent bracket, your long-term capital gains would
be taxed at 10 percent. Obviously, your long-term capital gains
wouldn't be pushing you into a higher bracket.
</P>
<P>
   But it can happen with short-term gains, which are taxed as
ordinary income. If they are big enough _ or if you already are
close to the next highest bracket _ they could push you over.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, a married couple filing a joint return would move from
the 15 percent bracket to the 28 percent bracket if their taxable
income were to rise above $43,050. A move from the 28 percent
bracket into the 31 percent bracket occurs when income exceeds
$104,050. The 36 percent bracket is reached when income exceeds
$158,550, and you get into the top bracket _ 39.6 percent _ when
your income goes above $283,150.
</P>
<P>
   We should all have such problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
