<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SHAREHOLDERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SOME EX-GENENTECH SHAREHOLDERS FUMING  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Several former Genentech shareholders complained
Monday that they got the runaround when they tried to act on an
offer to give small investors like them first crack at some of
Genentech's reissued shares.
<P>
   Genentech stock temporarily ceased public trading in June, when
the Swiss firm Roche Holdings acquired Genentech in a deal that
required shareholders to sell their holdings at $4 below market
price.
</P>
<P>
   When Genentech prepared to go public again in July, the South
San Francisco, Calif., company publicized a special deal: It would
set aside some shares in the new offering so small investors who
had sold at a loss could get in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech, which returned to the stock market July 20 at $97 per
share, closed at $128.38 Monday _ a 32-percent profit for those who
got in.
</P>
<P>
   But after a Chronicle column Monday questioned whether small
investors had a fair chance at any shares, half a dozen readers
called or e-mailed to say they'd tried to follow the procedures
Genentech had laid out, only to get rebuffed in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Kochenderfer of Belmont, Calif., has asked the Securities
and Exchange Commission to investigate her complaint. Kochenderfer,
who had held 200 shares, furnished a copy of the fax she sent to
Genentech before the deadline for getting in on the special
program.
</P>
<P>
   She says Genentech ignored her fax, and when she called the
firm's investor relations department to complain, she was hung up
on.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Malinowski, a San Francisco retiree with 200 shares, didn't
keep as detailed a record of her attempts to get in on the offer.
But she's certain she phoned Genentech investor relations three
times and never got called back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 200 shares aren't going to make me or break me,'' she
said. ``It's the idea it was really a public relations act and was
not sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other former Genentech shareholders contacted The Chronicle
with similar tales.
</P>
<P>
   This follows complaints last week by small shareholders that
Genentech didn't inform them of the offer but relied on the media
to disseminate it.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech spokeswoman Laura Leber repeated that the company had
worked hard to create a special program for former shareholders _ a
rarity in public offerings _ and said any shortcomings owed to the
fact that many people wanted in on the offer, and everything
happened so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the best job we could,'' she said. ``If the stock were
flat, nobody would care.''
</P>
<P>
   Leber repeated that Genentech's underwriters, led by J.P.
Morgan, had set aside a generous 20 percent of the offering _ 4
million shares in all _ for three classes of small investors:
employees, former shareholders and private investors who have
relationships with institutions and brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
   But Leber declined to say how many shares were purchased by each
of the three classes. ``It is not customary to break the figure
down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gable, a spokesman for Charles Schwab, which handled the
sales to employees and former shareholders, said his company could
put its finger on that number but would not reveal it unless
authorized by Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taulli, an analyst with the IPO Monitor newsletter, said in
a typical IPO, anywhere from 1 to 10 percent of the shares are set
aside for a ``friends and family program.'' Companies decide who
makes the list. Taulli said underwriters also allot shares to
brokerage houses close to them. Those brokers typically give their
biggest customers a crack at hot IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might happen is you have a lot of rich private
individuals who had connections to the underwriters'' getting in on
the 20 percent of the shares Genentech dedicated to all three
classes of investors, Taulli said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
