 MATTEL TO SELL FURNITURE ONLINE VIA GOODHOME.COM  &HT;     By DAN FOST  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ A new venture spinning out of Mattel Inc.'s Marin
County, Calif., divisions has $50 million in backing and an
audacious goal: to use sophisticated technology to sell home
furnishings over the Internet.
<P>
   The new company, GoodHome.com, will announce its formation
Tuesday, and it plans to launch its Web site by October. In
addition to toy giant Mattel, GoodHome has investments from Hearst
Corp. and leading venture capital firms Thomas H. Lee Co. and
Weston Presidio Capital.
</P>
<P>
   GoodHome will use technology from Broderbund Software's home
design CD-ROMs to allow Web surfers to design a kitchen, a living
room or a bathroom _ and then purchase the items online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the opportunities for e-commerce retailers in home
furnishings are pretty plentiful going forward,'' said analyst Alan
Rifkin, a partner at Thomas Weisel Partners in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of home goods online should hit $319 million this year,
according to Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., and could top
$3 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the challenges is definitely going to be presenting the
product itself, which is going to make or break some of these
companies,'' said Forrester analyst Seema Williams. The company
will have to present good enough pictures online, Williams said,
``for a consumer to be able to make a purchase decision without
actually making a visit to the furniture store.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Mack, the chief executive of GoodHome, said ``it's a little
bit of a fallacy'' that people need to sit on a sofa before they
buy it. Consumers often order from catalogs, particularly if the
store they're visiting doesn't have the exact item they want, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pottery Barn and Crate &AMP; Barrel are a $7 billion industry,''
Mack said. ``People are already doing it. We got over that concern
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack, 30, was a vice president at Broderbund when the company
was acquired last year by the Learning Co., which in turn was
bought by toy giant Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   In the new venture, he'll oversee 70 people, with 30 based in
the San Rafael, Calif., headquarters; another 30 in Brea, Calif.;
and 10 in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   While Mattel has provided most of the employees and technology,
GoodHome has plenty of expertise from its other investors. Hearst
is the publisher of such magazines as Good Housekeeping, House
Beautiful and Country Living. Hearst New Media and Technology, the
corporate division leading the GoodHome investment, owns half of
online women's portal Women.com, among other startups.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Lee Co. manages more than $6 billion and helped build
the Learning Co. San Francisco's Weston Presidio Capital is a $900
million fund that helped build Restoration Hardware, Staples and
DigitalChef.
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million is a large amount for a first round of venture
funding, but GoodHome will need it: The company is not only
building a brand from scratch, but it also will have to build a
warehouse for the furniture it plans to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that to offer top customer service, we have to have
direct control,'' said Mack, the CEO. The warehouse will be ``key,
key, key to the success. I can't tell you the number of people who
are disappointed as they redecorate and things are delivered late.
We will spare no expense to make this the best possible consumer
experience in this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   GoodHome will also face competition from companies like
Massachusetts' Furniture.com, which launched this year and is
already racking up impressive sales, according to analyst Rifkin.
But the growing market and a brick-and-mortar industry slow to
change present a great opportunity, Rifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furniture in and of itself is a very nonprogressive
industry,'' he said. ``Many manufacturers and some retailers want
to protect their dealer network. It hasn't evolved with the
times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
