<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBRECHT-IPOS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DUTCH AUCTIONS GIVE EVERYONE ACCESS TO STOCK IPOS  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Although he recently underwrote two dull initial
public offerings, famed San Francisco investment banker Bill
Hambrecht makes no apologies _ and promises that a half-dozen more
dull IPOs will follow soon.
<P>
   Last month, his new firm, W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., used a Dutch
auction via the Internet _ what he calls an ``Open IPO'' _ to sell
shares of Salon.com, an online magazine based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the wild IPO market of the past year, dozens of newly issued
stocks have doubled, tripled or more on the first trading day. That
has been particularly true of companies with an Internet identity.
</P>
<P>
   Not Salon.com. Its stock finished the first trading day 50 cents
below its $10.50 offering price.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it might seem that the IPO was a failure _ and
it was branded as such by much of the media. But it succeeded on
its own terms, insists Hambrecht, who co-founded the Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist investment banking firm three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht explains that the Dutch auction system automatically
causes a stock to be issued at a price near its intrinsic market
value. So it lets a company get full value for its shares, rather
than ``leaving money on the table'' to satisfy the greed of IPO
speculators.
</P>
<P>
   In a Dutch auction, investors specify how many shares they are
willing to buy and at what price.
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Hambrecht's brokerage customers, along with customers of a
few affiliated brokerage firms _ most notably, Fidelity Investments
_ can post their bids online directly.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of other brokerage firms can get in on the auctions as
well, but not directly. They can place bids only if their brokers
agree to submit them through the W.R. Hambrecht Web site at
www.openipo.com.
</P>
<P>
   A computer sorts the bids to determine the highest price at
which the investment banker can sell all the shares offered, and
they are then sold at that price to everyone who bid that much or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch auctions have been used for years to raise money for
companies in the United States and abroad. Hambrecht's special
contribution is to make the Dutch auction available to everyone
interested in an IPO and to conduct it over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Most traditional IPOs are grossly underpriced at the offering,
Hambrecht observes, to provide windfall profits for a small, elite
group of favored investors _ institutions and individuals who have
given the underwriter large amounts of brokerage business. Ordinary
investors have virtually no chance of getting in at the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Once the IPO is completed, many of the initial investors _ with
no desire to own a stake in the company _ quickly sell their shares
in the market as other investors bid the price up.
</P>
<P>
   But with Hambrecht's Open IPO, investors who really want the
stock can get in at the start. In fact, there is scant incentive
for anyone else to buy.
</P>
<P>
   There is a temptation for managers with large stakes in their
own companies to use the old-fashioned, restricted type of IPO. If
the IPO attracts wild speculation and the stock price spikes, it
can make them fabulously rich.
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Hagen, chief financial officer of Salon.com, says his
company was ``very pleased'' with the results of its Open IPO. ``We
maximized the amount of cash that came into the company and placed
the stock in the hands of long-term shareholders,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Grundfest, a Stanford law professor and former commissioner
with the Securities and Exchange Commission, calls Hambrecht's Open
IPO ``a very exciting, bold, creative idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open IPO is designed to attract what Hambrecht calls
``affinity groups'' _ people with a strong interest in a company,
such as customers and suppliers, who are likely to become long-term
holders. That kind of holder keeps the stock from becoming too
volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Low volatility is a good thing for companies, Hambrecht argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volatility is very destructive to a company,'' he remarks.
``It creates a crisis with the employees and their options. Also,
when the price shoots way up, many investors pay too much for their
shares, and when the stock goes down again they think they have
bought a loser _ so you have a lot of discontented shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht says he began developing the Open IPO concept after
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist co-managed the IPO of Boston Beer Co. in 1995.
The company wanted to issue $30 million worth of stock, and the
chief executive insisted that $10 million worth be sold to people
who actually drank his beer, which includes the Samuel Adams brand.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Beer accomplished this by hanging tombstone ads for the
IPO around the necks of the beer bottles before they were shipped
for distribution. The response was tremendous, with customers
placing orders for four times as many shares as were available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the customers who bought are still shareholders four
years later,'' Hambrecht says.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht, who was then serving as chairman of H&AMP;Q but not as
chief executive, broached the Open IPO idea to Dan Case, the firm's
CEO. Case didn't want to go that route, so Hambrecht quit and
started W.R. Hambrecht in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an organization is very successful the old way, it is
hard to change,'' Hambrecht remarks. He also notes that Case made
``a strategic decision'' to offer IPO shares over the Charles
Schwab Web site, rather than launching a do-it-yourself online
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Newman, a spokeswoman for H&AMP;Q, said that neither Case nor
anyone else at the firm wants to comment on Bill Hambrecht's new
venture.
</P>
<P>
   With a Dutch auction, companies don't see the kind of
after-market enthusiasm that spikes the share prices of ordinary
IPOs. Most of the enthusiasm already has been discounted by the
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com stock, after the IPO at $10.50, has moved as high as
$15.13 and as low as $9 _ not particularly volatile, compared with
most other Internet IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Even less volatile was W.R. Hambrecht's first IPO, Sonoma's
Ravenswood Winery, which went public in April at $10.50 per share.
In nearly four months of trading, it has never moved higher than
$11.13 or lower than $10.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone transposed our stock chart to a hospital monitor,
they'd say `The patient is dead, tie a tag to his toe and get him
out of here,' '' quips W. Reed Foster, Ravenswood's chairman and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   However, Foster says he is grateful to W.R. Hambrecht for
underwriting the issue, because he was turned down by larger
investment bankers who considered Ravenswood _ with annual revenues
in the $20 million range _ too small to bother with.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their low-key debuts, Hambrecht's Dutch auctions pose a
potentially serious competitive threat to the rest of the
investment banking community.
</P>
<P>
   He says some ``very large'' publicly held companies _ which he
declines to identify _ are considering forsaking their usual
investment bankers and making secondary offerings through W.R.
Hambrecht.
</P>
<P>
   They are attracted not only by the prospect of getting full
value for their shares, but also by W.R. Hambrecht's relatively low
underwriting fee. The firm charges its clients 3 to 5 percent of
the proceeds from a securities sale, compared with the industry
standard of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht says he can scrape by with a lower fee because
Internet-based IPOs entail less labor and other overhead costs than
standard IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts argue that IPOs with scrupulously fair prices might
look good in theory, but that they won't catch on because they are
out of tune with the psychology of today's markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wild swings in the market price are exactly what IPO investors
want these days, says David Menlow, president of IPO Financial
Network, a New Jersey research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago, Menlow says, stocks that rose a
half-point from their IPO prices on the first trading day were
considered hot. In today's market, he says, ``That would be a major
disappointment. The investors today are spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only investors, but many companies as well, want their
stocks to surge, because that attracts publicity for the company
and more buyers for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   That is false reasoning, contends Jay Ritter, a professor at the
University of Florida, who is widely considered the top academic
expert on IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly does attract attention when a company doubles on
the first day, but it's incredibly expensive advertising,'' he
observes.
</P>
<P>
   He points to Gadzoox Networks, a San Jose, Calif., networking
company that went public last week at $21 per share and finished
the day at $74.81.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left $188 million on the table _ which is defined as the
number of shares sold times the price jump on the first day,''
Ritter says. ``For $188 million, Gadzoox could have bought every
advertisement on next year's Super Bowl broadcast and it would have
gotten a lot more visibility that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
