<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5200 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX     07-27 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wedding preparations won't wear me down yet
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ I have just hung up from having a casual chat
with my son. He lives in Philadelphia now. Come Aug. 14, he'll be
married. Casually, he wondered aloud if I'd found a dress for the
wedding. I offered a description that apparently rendered him
speechless _ momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purple and green with a long purple, ruffled slip that
hangs out in the front.'' Being a little concerned that my
description had fallen short of his expectations (or possibly (SET
ITAL)far(END ITAL) exceeded them), I hurriedly explained that I had
shoes and a hat to match. Silence.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor is my one and only kid, so I've never married anybody
off before. His father and I (both airline folks) were married in a
minister's study between flights. We had five witnesses _ his
roommate, mine, and a couple of friends, three of whom gave us
coffee pots. My point is, I don't know about wedding stuff.
</P>
<P>
   When friends ask if I'm ready for the big day, I ask them what's
to get ready? His father is handling the rehearsal supper from
Georgia, and if I have a dress and directions to DuBois, Penn., the
bride-to-be's hometown, what else do I need? I'm just the mother of
the groom and I'm quite familiar with my job specifications: Wear
beige and keep my mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Although I've apparently blown it in the dress department, I'm
doing fine in the ``mouth shut'' area because I'm here and they're
somewhere else. Out of range, so to speak. And the more I think
about it, the more thankful I am for having been clever enough to
have a son instead of a daughter. That way I don't have to toss in
my sleep worrying about tables, cakes, and string quartets.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the kids faxed a copy of their gift registry to me.
I'd never seen one before because when my friends were getting
married back in the '50s, the only registering anyone did was for
crystal, china, and silver. Of course they all ended up with the
usual three sugar shells and a nut spoon nobody knew what in the
hell to do with.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I wasn't too thrilled with the idea of the kids
wandering into Bloomingdale's or wherever, and living out their
fantasies. ``Umm,'' they'd muse, pointing, ``we'd like two of
these, six of those, and could the Steinway be delivered to a
third-floor walkup?'' Kind of like polite blackmail _ fork over or
you're out of the loop. Giving should be spontaneous. And what's
wrong with three coffee pots? They all break anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, a fax of their wish list arrived. I was
curious. This was a license to snoop _ just about as nosy as an
almost-mother-in-law can get. ``Macy's West celebrates the wedding
of Amy J. Barley and Kristofor C. Schuett on Saturday, August 14,
1999. Amy and Kristofor registered at the Lazarus Tuttle Crossing
store.'' I thought that was kind of nice and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets and towels, and some slotted things (spoons and spatulas)
headed the list. Candlesticks and vases followed. Now I'm thinking,
Isn't that romantic? Visions of these beautiful, starry-eyed
children bringing each other flowers and dining by candlelight fill
my head.
</P>
<P>
   On a more practical note, there's a registry from the local
hardware store in DuBois. Need: muffin tins, cookie sheets, a
vacuum cleaner, a can crusher, and a dual-temp glue gun. I'm not
sure what glue guns and can crushers do, but they sound modest
enough. One item stopped me dead in my tracks _ a circular saw.
Those things cut off fingers! I blew my cool and called the kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``NO ELECTRIC SAWS.'' His reaction was pretty much the same as
with the dress. Then he reminded me he would be celebrating his
32nd birthday three days after the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' I barked, ``and you'll do it with all of your fingers.
You may be old enough to be married but not to have power tools.''
Silence. Stupid! I'm talking to myself now. You're turning into a
goofy old broad in a funny dress (and hat to match). I apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it Mum, I love you and you're going to make one great
mother-in-law. Now about the green and purple. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't life grand?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
