<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN28-CO     07-27 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preferred stocks can be attractive
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market is so high now that rational
investors should be at least a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true that large-company stocks have averaged a
pleasing 11.22 percent total return over the long term. But it's
also true that when things go wrong, they can stay wrong for a very
long time.
</P>
<P>
   Large-company stocks hit a peak in August 1929. Then came the
Depression. The S&AMP;P 500 index fell 86 percent, and it took 25 years
for it to get back to its 1929 level.
</P>
<P>
   That's a long time indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The market is giving many people the willies, which explains why
more conservative alternatives _ such as preferred stocks _ are
getting more attention.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred stocks, a cousin of the common stocks most of us
usually invest in, are an intriguing possibility. Preferred shares
are bought and sold just like common shares of the same company.
They're listed side by side in the stock tables.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred shares are usually issued by large, mature companies,
such as utilities and auto manufacturers. About a third of the
companies in the S&AMP;P 500 issue preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred stock gets its value mainly from the relatively large
dividend it pays. For example, IBM's preferred stock pays an annual
dividend of $1.88 per share, compared with 48 cents for common
stock. The price of the common stock depends not so much on the
dividend as on the performance of the company itself. As sales and
earnings go up, the price of the common stock will usually follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preferred stock can be thought of as a cross between a bond
and a common share of stock,'' said Tish Jackson, chief investment
officer of the Bank of America Private Bank in Georgia. It manages
about $4 billion in assets of affluent customers.
</P>
<P>
   The shares are called preferred because their dividends are paid
before those owed on common shares.
</P>
<P>
   The main advantages of preferred shares are the relatively high
dividends and the more stable price of the stock. The chart
illustrates how much IBM's common and preferred shares differ.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorable element is that preferred shareholders will
get their money back before common shareholders should the company
go bankrupt. That offers a degree of protection, even though
preferred shares stand in line behind bond holders.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the stable price means preferred shareholders
will benefit very little if the company's performance _ and common
stock price _ shoot up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all remember 10 years ago, when everybody thought IBM was
about to go out of business,'' said Jackson. ``Now it's done a
fabulous turnaround. Those who own the preferred shares would not
have participated in that recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Another disadvantage is that preferred shares usually do not
have voting rights. You own a piece of the company, but you have no
say in how it is managed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another potential drawback with most preferred stocks is
that the dividend is fixed. If interest rates go up, the price of
the stock will go down, much like the price of a bond. If inflation
goes up, the purchasing power of the fixed dividend will go down.
One other factor to consider: Your reward is in dividends, which
are taxed as ordinary income. With common shares, you hope to make
money by selling the stock at a higher price than you paid. That
incurs capital gains taxes, which are lower than ordinary
income-tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least four mutual funds that specialize in
preferred stocks. I don't think they are an attractive alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them are closed-end funds with returns from OK to very
attractive. They also have high expenses _ 1.32 percent for the
Preferred Income fund and 1.46 percent for the Putnam Dividend
Income fund. That's too expensive for me, especially when I see
that total returns are between 7 percent and 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other two funds are structured to appeal to institutional or
corporate investors. Vanguard _ a reliable and customer-friendly
outfit _ offers one of those two. Morningstar, the Chicago-based
mutual fund tracker, gives the Vanguard fund a blunt assessment:
``It is not appropriate for individual investors.'' With all those
variables, the final question is the usual, straightforward one: Is
this a good idea for me? The answer is the usual, complicated one:
It depends on your circumstances and your goals. Experts can
explain the facts, but the selection is up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
