r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JASONTERRY28-COX     07-27 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JASONTERRY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA: Rookie Terry's world a whirl
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since Arizona was eliminated from the NCAA Tournament
in March, Jason Terry's life has been a dizzying experience. Not
until the point guard landed with the Atlanta Hawks last month as
their first-round draft choice did he manage to find any calm.
</P>
<P>
   To get to that point, however, Terry experienced anxiety,
fulfillment, anger, disappointment, confusion and, finally,
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can only get some rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person would have to walk in my shoes to understand what
I've been through,'' Terry said. ``It's hard to really explain it.
You have to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time in his life one would think would bring only joy,
Terry, 21, made difficult decisions that brought a lot of pain and,
for a time, damaged his most coveted relationship _ the one with
his mother, Andrea Cheatham. He withdrew from college six weeks
before graduating, a decision Cheatham did not like. He was advised
to do so by his former agent, Larry Fox, who would not have been
Cheatham's choice to represent her son. She expressed her concerns
about Fox in a well-crafted letter she sent to the NCAA, the NBA
Players Association, the Pacific 10 and the Arizona coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Cheatham accused Fox of spending ``considerable
time, money and favors (on Terry) laying the groundwork for an
indebted relationship.'' She cited cash gifts and a Caribbean trip
Terry took with two friends at Fox's expense as an attempt to
``enslave them to the point they feel obligated to sign with him. .
. . Two weeks later, my son signs. Surprise, surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry was extremely upset about the letter and told his mother
so. Their relationship, which while he was growing up in Seattle
had been as close as mother and son could be, suffered. ``You have
to understand that his mother has never been through this before,''
Fox said. ``She's very opinionated and has a bad temper. She tried
to blame everything on me. She bad-mouthed me. She got very close
to a woman in San Francisco, and she wanted her to represent Jason.
When he signed with me, she started bad-mouthing me _ even though
that woman had no experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The other agent, Ndidi Opia, countered, ``It serves no purpose
for me to dignify that kind of propaganda. I did not know Larry Fox
is so well-versed in my background. I've been negotiating sports
contracts for the past six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox contends that Cheatham ``regrets writing the letter,'' and
he added, ``All I could do was laugh about it.'' Apparently, he's
the only one laughing. Based on the letter, the Pac-10 is
investigating Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Terry said, he and his mother ``fell out'' after she
distributed the letter but they later reunited. She was among 21
family members in Washington at the June 30 draft, and she visited
Terry here during the rookie and free-agent camp last week.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal ``has made us stronger,'' Terry said. ``There were a
couple of misunderstandings. We hadn't communicated. She wrote some
stuff that wasn't true. Most importantly, we're all right now. Time
heals all wounds. It was difficult for both of us. But you've only
got one mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock said he was unaware of
Cheatham's letter. But ``all the research we did was all positive
about Jason,'' Babcock said. ``He was great in the three days
together (for the camp). His college coach, Lute Olson, told me
that when Mike Bibby was a freshman, Jason volunteered to come off
the bench, because he could handle it. That tells you about his
unselfishness right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham admires her son's unselfishness, too, but his
withdrawal from school really angered her. Terry was on course to
graduate with his class with a degree in family services. But Fox
said Terry had countless out-of-town obligations that made it
impossible for him to attend classes. He cited appearances around
the country as the CBS and Sports Illustrated National Player of
the Year and pre-draft individual workouts and camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry leaving school is blown way out of proportion,'' Fox
said. ``It's very easy to jump to conclusions. He was very close to
graduating, yes. But he was being flown all over the country
accepting awards. He was being pulled in so many directions. Three
or four times a week he would leave Tucson for a different city.
There were the camps and then the individual workouts. It was
something that he had to put a lot of concentration on, because it
was very important to his basketball future. But he wrote a letter
to withdraw instead of receiving incompletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said, ``I knew after my last game that I was going to
withdraw. School is going to be there. My family's OK with it. I'm
going to go back in the summer to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   But not this summer. Too much to do. This weekend, his first
basketball camp as an NBA player opens in Seattle. As much as
playing in the country's famous arenas and against the world's best
talent was a dream for Terry, so was having his own camps. Among
the first deeds Terry had Fox do was establish three of them: one
in Seattle, one in Tacoma and another in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to give back, and to do it now,'' Terry
said. ``There's no need to wait. The opportunity is there. Seattle
has been good to me. So (have) Tacoma and Tucson. It was very
important to me to get started on giving back now.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago, Terry, whose camps had been set up by Fox,
fired his agent and signed a deal with No Limit Management, the
fledging sports agency owned by Percy Miller, the rapper, producer
and record mogul known as Master P.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was livid. ``It's a very exciting time in Jason's life, but
he's confused about some things,'' he said. ``He's made some tough
decisions on his life. . .. It's bad he's caught up in this
lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said, ``It's not lunacy. The agent (Fox) did his job for
two months. He was good for then. It was time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   No Limit executive Tevester Scott said the company had an
interest in Terry because ``he's a good kid, a great athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said, ``He's clean-cut and about being a role model. Our
first concern is for Jason to get his career together. I don't know
anything about that other agent stuff, and I don't want to know.
He's with us now, and the emphasis is on helping him flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry showed in the three-day series of games at Life College
that he can be a major factor; he scored 30 points in his first
game against No. 3 pick Baron Davis of Charlotte and generally
displayed flashes of brilliance at both ends of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his life has begun to settle. Terry and his fiancee and
21-month-old daughter Jasionna have found a home in the Atlanta
area. He has a three-year sneaker contract with Converse with six
figures and a three-year, $4.73 million deal with the Hawks. He has
representation with No Limit that he's happy with and a
relationship with his mother that he says is stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basketball is the easy part,'' Terry said. ``People can
never understand all that comes with being someone ready to get
drafted, what I had to go through. It was difficult. The agent
situation is difficult for anybody. The family situation is
something to deal with, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm here now, in a city I want to be in and with a team
that I'm happy with. So, finally, I can get on with my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
