<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-SALARIES28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC salaries: Where does it pay to coach football?By Chip Towers
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The University of Georgia long has been said to be
a a good place to coach football. The Bulldogs coaches now are
taking that notion to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's coaching staff is the second-best paid in the
Southeastern Conference, according to a league-wide salary survey
conducted by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Only Tennessee,
which has won the past two SEC championships, pays its coaching
staff better than the Bulldogs, and then by a total of just $31,000
a year. Georgia coaches will make nearly $68,000 more than those at
Florida, the league's winningest team this decade, and almost
$150,000 more than Mississippi State, which played Tennessee in the
conference championship game last season. In fact, Georgia football
coaches will make nearly $101,000 more this year than they did last
year _ an increase of 13.4 percent _ even though the Bulldogs did
not win a championship or play in a major bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The average pay raise for faculty and non-faculty employees at
UGA for the current fiscal year was 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Including head coach Jim Donnan, who will make $160,000 in base
salary this year, the Bulldogs have six coaches earning more than
$100,000 each. Only Tennessee, with six $100,000 coaches, plus a
seventh making $99,662, can match that number.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is anything but apologetic for paying its coaches well.
Acknowledging that such salaries usually follow huge success on the
field, athletics director Vince Dooley said the Bulldogs are doing
what it takes to keep their staff together in anticipation of
championships to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably a little ahead of the game on the salaries,
because we haven't had the production yet. But we think that
production is going to come as a result of the coaches that we
have,'' Dooley said. ``You normally reward production. We are
investing in the anticipation of production, and we believe it's a
good investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan has been the driving force behind the higher salaries. He
has worked hard to assemble the current staff and, perhaps just as
important, keep it in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to try to pay our coaches as much as we
can,'' Donnan said. ``I'm not too concerned with what others make.
We just do whatever we can to have the best coaching staff we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the raises can be attributed to ``market-driven''
situations. Coaching can be a transient business, and the best in
the business are constantly tempted by bigger and better deals.
That situation has contributed to Georgia's spiraling payroll
recently.
</P>
<P>
   In order to lure Kevin Ramsey away from Tennessee, which had
just won a national championship, Donnan had to offer the secondary
coach a coordinator's position and a hefty pay increase. Ramsey is
Georgia's defensive coordinator and, with a $130,000 salary, its
highest-paid assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey will make $38,000 more this year with the Bulldogs than
he did last year at Tennessee, an increase of 41 percent. He and
Tennessee defensive coordinator Johnny Chavis are the SEC's
highest-paid assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Three Georgia coaches received raises of more than 20 percent.
Linebackers coach Brad Lambert got a 26.5 percent bump to $93,600,
a ``market-driven'' increase resulting from overtures from Tulane.
Former Georgia coach and longtime Donnan assistant Chris Scelfo,
who was hired as head coach at Tulane in December, wanted to make
Lambert the Green Waves' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line coach Rodney Garner saw his pay increase from
$95,000 a year to $114,400. Donnan denies that the raise was a
direct result of Auburn's interest in Garner, but the Tigers
approached Garner to return to his alma mater as defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Five coaches have left Georgia since Donnan became coach in
1996, and all but one of them did so to become a head coach or a
coordinator at another program: Daryl Drake to Baylor as offensive
coordinator; Greg Briner to SMU as offensive coordinator; Mickey
Mathews to James Madison University as head coach, and Scelfo to
Tulane as head coach. The exception was former defensive line coach
George Edwards, who took an NFL job with the Dallas Cowboys after
the '97 season and doubled his salary in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that shows the quality of coaches we like to hire,''
Donnan said, ``and I think that's the kind of coaches we have to
have to be competitive in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   SALARIES OF GEORGIA'S FOOTBALL COACHES
</P>
