<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-LAWNS _ May was drier than normal, according to National
Weather Service records, but June and July have been right on
target as far as precipitation goes. Even with normal rainfall,
though, lawns tend to go dormant through the hottest part of the
summer, so your yard is probably showing lots of brown spots unless
you have been regularly watering. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News).
(Nuts &AMP; Bolts column, with tips on watering). 28.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING LIFE _ Everything's popping up mushrooms _ at least in
Lee May's backyard it is. Those thunderstorms from a week ago, set
off a growth in fungi that's yielded big ones the color of brown
leather and tiny red ones covered with spots, Most seductive was a
grouping that looked very much like the delicious morel. Lee says
he could almost swear they were morels, but instead swore off his
desire to eat them. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-FRENCH _ Furniture trend forcasters say the casual French
look is among several that consumers can expect to see in stores
beginning this fall. An earmark of the French look is hand painted
furniture. Interest in painted furniture has been soaring for years
and is fueled by the influences of European decors and Americans'
penchant for second homes. Atlanta's Mary Bairstow has been a
leader in the new French look and tells how to get that look at
home.( Flanders, Atlanta Jounral-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
</P>
<P>
   WORKSHOP-VERDIGRIS _ Some people long for a home full of new
furniture and accessories. Others want their furnishings to have
that weathered or rustic look, without the benefit of time taking
its toll. The process of aging metal and some wood products is
called verdigris.(A.Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
