Weather Service records, but June and July have been right on
target as far as precipitation goes. Even with normal rainfall,
though, lawns tend to go dormant through the hottest part of the
summer, so your yard is probably showing lots of brown spots unless
you have been regularly watering. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News).
(Nuts &AMP; Bolts column, with tips on watering). 28.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING LIFE _ Everything's popping up mushrooms _ at least in
Lee May's backyard it is. Those thunderstorms from a week ago, set
off a growth in fungi that's yielded big ones the color of brown
leather and tiny red ones covered with spots, Most seductive was a
grouping that looked very much like the delicious morel. Lee says
he could almost swear they were morels, but instead swore off his
desire to eat them. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
