<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     07-27 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES ITS OWN ABOMINABLE JUVENILE CRIME BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, the U.S. House passed H.R. 1501, the Juvenile
Justice Reform Act of 1999. The bill contains an amendment authored
by Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, that strips children in jails of
protections against physical or sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time that Congress has shown its nasty side
in regard to children. Last year the Senate passed a bill that
would have allowed young teenagers to be jailed with adults _
despite the overwhelming evidence that when young people are
confined in the same facility with adults, they are beaten and
raped, sometimes killed, and too often commit suicide under such
conditions. Fortunately, the Violent and Repeat Juvenile Offender
Act, S.10, never became law.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest abomination called a reform, section 110
eliminates any consent decree ``that provides for remedies relating
to prison conditions'' and was entered into before the Prison
Litigation Reform Act (PLRA) was passed in 1995. PLRA was passed to
make it difficult for inmates or relatives to sue a prison system
for violations of the U.S. Constitution and Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, in a consent decree involving incarcerated children,
parents sue a county or state in order to stop the jailing of teens
with adults or to end some mistreatment of imprisoned teens. The
county or state agrees to no longer jail children with adults or
agrees to end some ill-conceived method of dealing with children in
jails _ without admitting wrongdoing. A consent decree is like a
contract between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Center of Juvenile and Criminal Justice provides a striking
example of a consent decree that would be wiped out by H.R. 1501.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Horn's 15-year-old son Robbie was held in Oldham County
jail in LaGrange, Ky., for a minor infraction. He took off his
shirt, wrapped one sleeve around his neck and the other around the
bars of his cell and hanged himself. Rita Horn sued the county for
jailing juveniles with adults. Records show that nearly 1,400
children were held in the county jail in a four-year period _ most
for minor offenses. As a result of the lawsuit, in 1985, the Oldham
County officials signed a consent decree in which they agreed to
never again hold children in the jail.
</P>
<P>
   If DeLay has his way, Oldham County can start jailing juveniles
with adults once more. With the sad predictable results.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 20 news release, Mark Soler, president of the Youth
Law Center in Washington, D.C., commented: ``The DeLay provisions
would immediately wipe out protections in scores of counties around
America where children have been abused and mistreated in adult
jails and juvenile facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of abuses curtailed or ended by these consent decrees
stagger the imagination: Children in juvenile detention in
Philadelphia were regularly beaten with paddles and chains. Unruly
children in juvenile detention in Hannibal, Mo., were strapped to
boards and leaned against a wall _ sometimes upside down. Children
in state institutions in Arizona were stripped naked, hands and
feet tied to the four corners of bed frames and kept in solitary
confinement for days at a time. In Oklahoma, children in one state
juvenile correctional institution were handcuffed, hogtied and
beaten in the dungeon-like ``punishment unit.''
</P>
<P>
   If DeLay has his way, all these obscene practices can begin once
again.
</P>
<P>
   The DeLay amendment, however, raises a significant legal
question. Can a law passed by Congress override consent decrees or
agreements worked out between counties or states and those
individuals who sued? Can a federal law declare null and void a
state's agreement over how a state facility will be run? It's
doubtful. And if the DeLay amendment becomes part of the law, it
will lead to more litigation over this constitutional issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the GOP flies the banner of local control, yet
this amendment, authored by a Republican representative, would
completely destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   In response to DeLay's amendment to the House juvenile justice
bill, Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., offered an amendment to the
Senate's Commerce and Judiciary Appropriations bill that would
protect children from abuse in all the nation's jails and
correctional facilities.
</P>
<P>
   On July 22, the American Academy of Child and Adolescent
Psychiatry, the Children's Defense Fund and 13 other organizations
sent a letter to the U.S. Senate in support of Wellstone's
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The letter states, in part: ``The U.S. Department of Justice
issued a report earlier this year documenting widespread inhumane
and abusive conditions for children with mental illness in jails
and juvenile facilities. The report cited cases of extreme physical
abuse and neglect, including lengthy periods of isolation and the
use of tear gas as chemical restraints. ... The Wellstone amendment
would allow federal courts to protect children, especially those
with mental illness, from danger and mistreatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Wellstone amendment was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill now goes to a House-Senate conference committee
along with another version of a juvenile crime bill which the
Senate passed (S. 254).
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill dismantles the federal mandate to study and
attempt to correct the problem of disproportionate minority
confinement (DMC). In every state of the union, teens of color are
treated more severely by law enforcement and prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   Recent news stories in the Baltimore Sun document that in
Maryland mentally ill delinquents are treated differently,
depending upon race.
</P>
<P>
   White teens who are mentally ill and have committed crimes are
placed in residential centers that specialize in treating mental
illness. Teens of other races who have committed similar offenses
and have similar mental problems are locked up in juvenile jails or
state training schools and given tranquilizers or psychotropic
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun also reported that last year's crime figures show that
one out of every three white delinquents is sentenced to
confinement in a treatment center, while one of six black
delinquents goes to a treatment center. In Baltimore, only one out
of nine black delinquents was sentenced to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, according to the
Baltimore Sun, has ordered officials of the appropriate agencies to
find out why a much higher percentage of black mentally ill
juvenile delinquents than their white counterparts are sentenced to
jail instead of treatment. ``Race,'' she is quoted as saying,
``must never play a role in placement or providing treatment to
juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but unless the DMC mandate is kept alive, the racist
policies will continue _ blindly.
</P>
<P>
   A few members of the House and Senate in conference committee
will decide which provisions of the two juvenile crime bills will
be kept and which shucked in order to fashion the legislation that
will then be taken to a vote in both houses. They have only to
think ``equal before the law'' and feel compassion for children who
have taken the wrong path.
</P>
<P>
   And they will shuck right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
