<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-KILLINGS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Cary Stayner reportedly
admitted that he killed Yosemite naturalist Joie Ruth Armstrong and
three Yosemite tourists, saying in an interview that he had dreamed
about killing women for 30 years. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-IMPACT (Yosemite National Park, Calif.) _ The tragic
deaths in the Yosemite area have taken a heavy toll on park
employees, especially because the latest victim belonged to their
own tight-knit community. By ILENE LELCHUK and MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   ATT-CABLE (San Francisco) _ Caught in the middle of a
high-stakes cyberspace turf war, the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors granted AT&AMP;T a monopoly on high-speed Internet access
over its cable lines _ for now. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-STUDENTS (Mexico City) _ While members of Mexico's latest
generation of student revolutionaries are known to quote Karl Marx,
they also sport dreadlocks and are more likely than not to have
some parts of their bodies pierced. Among the thousands of
Generation Xers involved in one of the biggest university protests
since the late 1960s, many now believe that what started out as a
fight over an increase in tuition can be transformed into a
left-wing movement that will reach far beyond the confines of
campus politics. By MICHAEL RILEY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-FEEDING (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ For too many mothers, going
back to work marks the end of breast-feeding. In some cases, moms
give up the idea, citing frustrations over not having the time or
privacy to pump. But a federal initiative known as Healthy People
2000 wants to get 75 percent of all women in the United States
breast-feeding by the time they leave the hospital next year. By
SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   DIET-DRUG (Albany, N.Y.) _ The latest weight-loss drug, Xenical,
is no antidote to chronic laziness or a steady diet of
cheeseburgers. But health specialists say the newest anti-obesity
drug, approved by the Food and Drug Administration in April, may
help the seriously overweight stick with a diet long enough to
alter their lifestyle and behavior. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   VETS-BOOKS (Undated) _ Toshio Whelchel, a Marine veteran from
1977-81, has compiled an oral history of a dozen Japanese American
troops in Vietnam. Each man was either born in a Japanese
relocation camp during World War II or is the son of parents who
spent time in the camps. Each experienced prejudice and ignorance,
but the reactions are different. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-PRAYER (San Antonio) _ High school football has long
been considered sacred in Texas, but a recent court ruling says the
pitched battles over pigskin are not appropriate occasions for
government-endorsed prayer. The opinion by the 5th Circuit Court of
Appeals, which the U.S. Supreme Court has been asked to review,
will end ritual pre-game prayers in many communities when the
football season kicks off next month. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GORGEOUS-DIRECTOR (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Drop Dead Gorgeous''
might be Michael Patrick Jann's debut as a director of feature
films, but it isn't the first movie he ever made. For that, zoom
back to the mid-1980s and the hallowed halls of Albany Academy.
Jann, a sophomore, got ahold of a school videocamera and used it to
make a short film for biology class. The subject? Chicken embryos.
By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOX (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Fox, home to youthful dramas,
animated comedies and historically horrific live-action comedies,
is rolling out a pair of sitcoms that stand out among a thin field
of new network comedies. The first of the promising comedies is
``Action,'' the other is ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-NOTICE (Undated) _ ``Black Notice'' is Patricia
Cornwell's latest forensic thriller featuring Dr. Kay Scarpetta,
Virginia's chief medical examiner. It is the author's darkest and
perhaps best. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN-CHAMBERS (San Francisco) _ It isn't easy being Marilyn
Chambers. Child-rearing. Boyfriends. Career choices. These matters
weigh on a porn goddess's mind. But fun? Oh yes, says the star of
that landmark dirty movie, ``Behind the Green Door.'' Being Marilyn
Chambers is oodles of fun. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WATER-PARK (Sheridan, Texas) _ There were plenty of doomsayers
three years ago when a group of city boosters in the tiny town of
Sheridan decided to push for a locally run water park that could
boost the small-town economy, creating jobs and attracting a few
summer tourists between San Antonio and Houston. Now the park,
about 12 miles south of Interstate-10, has been in business for a
year, and it's making a big splash. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ In 1970, women comprised 1 percent of
all business travelers. At the turn of the millennium, that number
will be 50 percent. But has the travel industry _ and female
business travelers themselves _ fully adapted to this remarkable
trend? By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-METROPLEX (Dallas) _ Like a mismatched couple trapped in
a rocky marriage, Dallas and Fort Worth are constantly at odds.
Folks in Fort Worth often consider their Dallas counterparts
``uppity'' while many Dallasites have been known to look down upon
their Fort Worth brethren as unsophisticated rubes. Still, as
bookends in a sprawling mass known as the Metroplex, they are
joined at the hip by location and by a common desire to impress the
world. By CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DALLAS (Dallas) _ In typical Texas understatement,
tourism officials boast that Dallas offers ``more thrills than
Disneyland, more music than Nashville and more shopping than New
York.'' Strange that they don't mention ``wretched excess.''
Outside of Beverly Hills, probably no other city in the nation
exemplifies showy living and ostentatious displays of wealth. By
CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DALLAS-TREASURES (Dallas) _ Mention Dallas to almost any
adult in the world and two images come to mind: an assassinated
president and a television show.So it's not surprising that two of
the Metroplex's most popular tourist sites are a memorial to John
F. Kennedy and a homage to J.R. Ewing. By CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SUNDANCE (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Fort Worth's Sundance
Square doesn't rate real high on the ``hip quotient.'' But even
without the glitz, it's the liveliest downtown area in Texas _ and
maybe in the United States. By CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I had expected to hear from the
folks at the AARP this year _ just not so soon. It's several more
months before I hit their minimum age requirement of 50. But, sure
enough, a big white AARP envelope was sticking out of my mailbox:
``Membership Certificate and Temporary Membership Card Enclosed.''
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
