<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIEST-MOLEST-COX     07-27 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-MOLEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-priest admits 1980s sex abuse past sex abuses to
investigators
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla _ Two Nashville police detectives came to
the tidy pink bungalow in Flamingo Park in February bearing dark
burdens for Frank Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some horror stories,'' they told him.
</P>
<P>
   With those words, the life Richards left in Tennessee was
resurrected in his West Palm Beach living room.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, he was known as Father Frank Richards, a Catholic
priest in Nashville who rose in the church to become principal at a
Knoxville high school.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-hour interview, Richards told the horrible
stories the detectives had heard from many of his former altar boys
and students.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, Richards sexually molested dozens of teenage boys
entrusted to his care. He was a pedophile priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I was doing was wrong,'' he told detectives. ``It
was a constant struggle _ just like an alcoholic who knows that he
can't drink but does.''
</P>
<P>
   The police took Richards' taped statement back to Nashville but
likely will be able to do nothing with it. All the known offenses
occurred well before he left the priesthood in 1989, and in
Tennessee, the statute of limitation is eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, 52, declined repeated requests to be interviewed for
this story. Last week, he continued to work at the new life he has
forged here in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He is employed by the state as an administrative assistant with
the Palm Beach County Health Department's division of environmental
health and engineering. He is paid $25,081.94 per year to do
computer work _ budgets, accounting and license recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is strictly a numbers-cruncher,'' a Health Department
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Richards does no field work and is not involved in the
regulation of day-care centers, which his division oversees, she
said. His computer is linked, however, to databases that hold basic
information _ addresses, staff sizes, class sizes _ on day-care
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Background checked out
</P>
<P>
   Health Department administrators were unaware of Richards' past
when they hired him in November 1996. They had no way of knowing
it.
</P>
<P>
   He has never been convicted of a crime, or even charged. He
apparently has never lost a civil case, or even been sued.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and FDLE background checks the Health Department made on
him came back clean, and Richards answered all questions on his
employment application truthfully: No, he has never been convicted
of a felony or first-degree misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, by his own admissions, by the referrals made by the
Catholic Diocese of Nashville, by the testimony of victims, and by
the evidence uncovered by prosecutors and police, Richards was once
an active and aggressive pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   The police statements given by Edward Joseph McKeown also
confirm this.
</P>
<P>
   Richards' longtime friend and colleague in the priesthood,
McKeown was sentenced to a 25-year prison term last month after
pleading guilty to molesting and raping a Nashville boy, part of
what prosecutors termed a pattern of abuse that involved some 30
victims over more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Both Richards and McKeown resigned from the priesthood the same
day: March 1, 1989. Prosecutors were able to convict McKeown, 54,
because he continued to claim victims in the '90s, within the
eight-year window for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Besieged with calls
</P>
<P>
   When press reports of McKeown's arrest came in February,
investigators were besieged with calls from adult men who claimed
to have been victimized as teens by him and Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had more phone calls than we can count,'' Nashville
police Detective David Zaccola told Richards during the interview
in his home. ``From as far away as Maryland _ just all over the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '80s, Richards and McKeown regularly took students
and altar boys on outings that ended in episodes of sexual abuse,
according to the police statements. Many times the molestation
occurred at a farm outside Nashville that was owned by Richards'
family.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Zaccola, Richards admitted sexually abusing
``about 25'' boys whose names he could remember. Richards said an
alcohol problem contributed to his abusive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also did a lot of drinking, and that doesn't help because I
don't always remember the things that I had done,'' he told police.
</P>
<P>
   He said he chose only boys that had reached ``physical maturity
... 14, 15, somewhere in there.'' Richards said he wouldn't ``take
kids in grade school out.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when he was principal of Knoxville Catholic High
School, Richards was confronted by the parents of three of his
victims who complained to the diocese. Gino Marchetti, the diocese
attorney, said Richards was then confronted and admitted the abuse.
Marchetti said the church reported the charges to the state's
Department of Human Services, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public records are clear that the case was referred,''
Marchetti said. ``There's no dispute on that.''
</P>
<P>
   What is disputed, however, is why state agencies never took the
allegations to police. The state's Human Services officials say
they aren't sure what happened and that some documents about
Richards have since been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement not involved
</P>
<P>
   ``What gives me a lot of concern is that law enforcement never
got involved,'' Zaccola told Richards. ``We never knew.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid possible civil action, Richards and the diocese paid a
settlement to the three victims. He told police he put up $5,000,
the diocese lent him another $5,000, and the diocese paid $30,000
more to satisfy the families.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the charges surfaced, Richards was transferred to
Nashville and named an associate pastor at Christ the King Church.
He was told not to have contact with children and to keep his
office door open at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Richards said he was undergoing psychiatric treatment for
pedophilia during this period and did so for ``three or four
years.'' He told police he no longer has the desire to have sexual
relations with boys because he is now able to live a gay lifestyle
outside the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I wouldn't even come close to touching a kid,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Richards told investigators he moved to Florida because he had
relatives here. He worked as an administrative assistant for AIDS
nonprofit groups in Orlando and Key West before moving to West Palm
Beach in 1994 and taking a job as an admission coordinator for the
Palm Beach Kennel Club.
</P>
<P>
   Richards has received positive evaluations in his 2 1/2 years
with the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous asset,'' wrote one supervisor. ``Mr. Richards
speaks, writes and expresses himself well,'' wrote another.
</P>
<P>
   A Health Department spokeswoman said no decision has been made
about Richards' future.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time,'' she said, ``we do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards told the detectives he is certain he is no longer
capable of sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't allow myself to be in that kind of situation,'' he
said. ``There's no way I want anything like that to ever happen
again _ for my sake and for everybody else's. It's been 15 years.
I'm very confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
