<HEADLINE>
SPECIALISTS STEP UP EFFORTS TO ENCOURAGE BREAST FEEDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ For too many mothers, going back to work
marks the end of breast-feeding. In some cases, moms give up the
idea, citing frustrations over not having the time or privacy to
pump.
</P>
<P>
   Others never get that far, weaning their babies before they
return to work or never bothering to nurse at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some women think they just can't work and breast-feed,'' said
Patty Lane, director of the Delmar, N.Y., chapter of the La Leche
League, an international breast-feeding support and advocacy group.
``It's important for them to know that it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   As research continues to show the benefits of breast-feeding for
both mother and baby, health specialists are stepping up a campaign
to encourage nursing, not only when babies leave the hospital but
when moms return to work.
</P>
<P>
   A federal initiative known as Healthy People 2000 wants to get
75 percent of all women in the United States breast-feeding by the
time they leave the hospital next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a woman knows that in four or six weeks, she's going to
have to go back to work and her employer won't make any
accommodations, she may have the feeling that it's not worth it to
even start breast-feeding,'' said Dr. Mary Applegate, director of
the Bureau of Women's Health at the New York Health Department,
which is planning to survey companies on their breast-feeding
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also getting national attention. Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, D-N.Y., recently introduced a bill to Congress that would
support breast-feeding in the workplace. And last year, the
American Academy of Pediatrics issued a statement that
breast-feeding should ideally begin within one hour of birth and
continue for at least 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if your employer doesn't offer a special place to pump
or a designated refrigerator to store milk, both lactation
consultants and working moms say it's still possible to keep
nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the newest electric pumps are small enough to carry in a
handbag and can operate on a battery or plugged into a car lighter,
good for women who are on the road a lot. Many pumps are also
discreet enough that women may have enough privacy at their cubicle
to use them. As for storing milk, an insulated lunch bag with ice
packs will keep the milk fresh until you get home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it's just thinking ahead and having some
knowledge,'' said Margaret Wilkinson, a lactation consultant at St.
Peter's Hospital in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast milk and breast-feeding promote good health in babies,
which means their mothers won't have to call in sick as often,''
said Wilkinson, citing one reason companies should be amenable to
the idea. ``It's really a win-win for the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   The health benefits of breast milk are well-documented and
growing.
</P>
<P>
   A study published earlier this month by the British Medical
Journal found that babies are less likely to become overweight
children if they are fed breast milk exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Other research has shown that breast milk helps protect babies
against illnesses, including ear infections, allergies, vomiting,
diarrhea, pneumonia and meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Breast-feeding has also been linked to a lower incidence of
sudden infant death syndrome. And since suckling at the breast is
more challenging for a baby, nursing helps develop the jaw muscles
needed to promote healthy tooth and speech development, Wilkinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those physical benefits, early childhood experts say
breast-feeding also provides the physical contact, warmth and
closeness that help create a strong bond between mother and baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really special,'' said Dr. Marla Eglowstein, an
obstetrician and gynecologist with St. Peter's Hospital, who has
continued to nurse her 9-month-old daughter, Sophie, since
returning to work earlier this year. ``She looks at me when she's
all done and has a big smile on her face.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eglowstein often uses her own experience to explain how mothers
can both nurse and work at the same time. In her case, she
breast-feeds her baby before leaving her with the nanny in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Eglowstein then pumps at least once during the day in a special
lactation room established by St. Peter's exclusively for nursing
employees.
</P>
<P>
   When she returns in the evening, she nurses again. After putting
Sophie to bed, she'll try to squeeze in another 20 minutes with her
pump.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a private place to pump in the hospital, Eglowstein
said it's not always easy to find time in between patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a juggle,'' she said. ``We're usually just a few bottles
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The key is figuring out a routine and finding a pump that works
well, Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some women may choose to pump less frequently, using formula to
supplement regular nursing at home. Others may want to pump two or
three times a day so their babies are fed only breast milk.
</P>
<P>
   While using a pump may seem inconvenient, she encourages mothers
to think about how breast-feeding can make their lives easier.
``You don't have to heat up a bottle or worry about sterility,''
she said. ``A lot of times it's much cheaper to breast-feed as well
as better nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
