<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-DRUG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIET DRUG IS NO CURE FOR OBESITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The latest weight-loss drug, Xenical, is no
antidote to chronic laziness or a steady diet of cheeseburgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that's going to take off 100 pounds and
keep it off over the long term,'' said Dr. Sharon Alger, a
professor of medicine and clinical nutrition at the Albany Medical
Center. ``It will help you lose five to 10 percent of your starting
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   But health specialists say the newest anti-obesity drug,
approved by the Food and Drug Administration in April, may help the
seriously overweight stick with a diet long enough to alter their
lifestyle and behavior. The drug can be taken for a maximum of two
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about helping someone go through a period of making
changes,'' said Margaret Malone, a professor in the department of
pharmacology practice at the Albany Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike anti-obesity medications that suppress appetite, Xenical
works by blocking the absorption of fat in the intestines.
</P>
<P>
   For someone eating a 1,200 calorie diet, with no more than 30
percent of calories from fat, the number of unabsorbed calories
equals about 300 daily, Malone said. Over a year, studies have
shown that patients treated with Xenical and a reduced-calorie diet
lost an average of 13.4 pounds, while those on a reduced-calorie
diet alone lost 5.8 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Xenical isn't for everyone, and certainly not for people who
need to lose only 10 or 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is approved for those people who meet the federal
government's definition of obese, those who are 30 percent
overweight, or are 20 percent overweight with high blood pressure,
high cholesterol or diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, health specialists say that Xenical shouldn't be
prescribed as a first-line treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to diet and exercise first and if they are
struggling with that and are unable to lose a pound or two a week,
they may be a candidate,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical works, in part, by reinforcing the need for someone to
eat low-fat foods because of potentially uncomfortable and
embarrassing gastrointestinal side-effects, including loose, oily
or accidental stools.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, also known by its chemical name, orlistat, prevents
the body from producing lipase, an enzyme necessary for the
breakdown of fats. For people on a low-fat diet, digestion under
those circumstances doesn't present a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But if you take Xenical and then splurge on cheeseburgers,
pizza, ice cream or other high-fat foods, you're more likely to
regret your decision. ``One-third of the fat you eat doesn't get
digested, so it's got to go somewhere,'' Alger said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the potential side effects, Alger said she's hearing
interest from patients who want to try Xenical, manufactured by
Hoffman-La Roche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a number of people asking for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, however, may still be skeptical over any diet drug
since the Food and Drug Administration's 1997 recall of Redux and
fenfluramine _ half of the popular ``fen-phen'' diet combination.
The drugs were linked to potentially fatal heart valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   But new pharmacological approaches to treating obesity are
increasingly popular as a tool to help people who can't seem to
lose weight on diet and exercise alone.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists caution, however, that no drug will offer a quick or
easy solution to weight loss. And the age-old remedy of eating less
and exercising more is still the best prescription.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic bullet,'' Alger said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
