<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-NOTICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNWELL'S `BLACK NOTICE' IS DARK, COMPELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Black Notice,'' Patricia Cornwell's latest forensic thriller
featuring Dr. Kay Scarpetta, Virginia's chief medical examiner
(G.P. Putnam's Sons, $25.95, 415 pages), is the author's darkest
and perhaps best.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a year since Scarpetta's lover, FBI profiler Benton
Wesley, was tortured and murdered. Barely coping with her grief,
Scarpetta gets a visit from Sen. Frank Lord, who takes her a letter
that Benton had written to her before his death and had asked the
senator to deliver a year after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loving you was when life began,'' the letter reads. ``Now that
it has ended, your gift to me is to go on. Of course you haven't
dealt with a damn thing, Kay. ... It's time to stop dodging your
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubborn, intensely private, Scarpetta finds it hard to reach
out to either her niece Lucy, an ATF agent, or her good friend and
colleague, Homicide Det. Pete Marino, who has recently been demoted
to street patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Called to a crime scene at the Richmond, Va., docks, Scarpetta
discovers that the only detective there has not secured the crime
scene. Unsealing a cargo container on a newly arrived ship from
Brussels, Scarpetta and Marino find a badly decomposed male body.
</P>
<P>
   Scrawled nearby are the French words for werewolf. The only
other clues are strands of very fine hair and a strange tattoo.
After the body is removed, Scarpetta confronts the newly appointed
deputy police chief, Diane Bray, for the lack of professionalism by
the police department.
</P>
<P>
   Because the body likely began its journey in Brussels, Scarpetta
alerts Interpol of her findings. Then another body turns up _ this
one badly disfigured.
</P>
<P>
   Things begin disappearing from the coroner's office. Scarpetta's
e-mail is being intercepted, and someone has started a Dr. Kay chat
room.
</P>
<P>
   But worst of all, Lucy and her lover, Jo, a DEA agent, are
involved in an undercover operation that goes bad. Lucy kills two
drug dealers and Jo is shot. Then Interpol requests that Scarpetta
and Marino travel to Paris to assist in a murder investigation
there.
</P>
<P>
   The more descriptive forensic examination scenes may be too much
for some readers. I had to put the book down during lunch, and the
anger and pain throughout the book is so intense that I often had
to take a break. But this is a fast-paced, first-rate thriller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lehane's latest psychological thriller, ``Prayers for
Rain'' (William Morrow and Co., $25, 337 pages), is a taut and
enticing look at pure evil.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent Karen Nichols hires Boston private investigator Patrick
Kenzie to stop a man from harassing her. Months later, he gets a
voice mail message asking that he call her. When a naked Karen
commits suicide by jumping off a building, Kenzie feels guilty
about not returning the call and decides to find out what led her
to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   As he looks into the last six months of her life, Kenzie
discovers that her fiance was hit by a car and remains in the
hospital in a coma. Trying to pay his medical bills, Karen
eventually lost her car, her apartment, her job and eventually her
sense of self. Believing that someone orchestrated the tragedies,
Kenzie enlists the aid of his former partner and lover, Angela
Gennaro, and his best friend, Bubba Rogowski _ big, mean and
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Their investigation leads to a super-intelligent sociopath who
doesn't kill his victims, but drives them to the brink of oblivion.
He intercepts their mail, both incoming and outgoing; he bugs their
phones and homes. He knows their every move. But Kenzie, Angela and
Bubba begin to wage counter warfare leading to a terrifying
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides play a cat-and-mouse game in this satisfying
thriller, full of intriguing characters and sharp dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heroin Factor,'' James McEachin's police procedural (Rharl
Publishing Group, $25, 340 pages), is a very dark, very tense look
at the life of a Los Angeles police lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt W. McKnight has been on the Los Angeles police force for
28 years and has only 13 days to go before he retires. McKnight
``was not a well-liked policeman. He was not known for keeping his
views to himself. Most of the whites in his division considered him
a racist. Most of the blacks thought he was aloof. He was neither.
He was a veteran of the dark streets of Los Angeles, and he was
therefore angry.''
</P>
<P>
   The last eight years McKnight has worked narcotics. He
especially gets angry when racist Capt. Ault pulls him off his
current investigation to check into the murder of vacationing Det.
Sgt. Verneau LeCoultre, one of the department's lowlifes _ a drunk,
a junkie and probably on the take.
</P>
<P>
   LeCoultre first had been attacked by a dog, escaped in his car,
been shot and then crashed the car. Now McKnight must trace
LeCoultre's final days. Eventually, an Englishwoman starts calling
and leaving messages. McKnight learns the Englishwoman is named
Leslie Van Horn. He tracks her down, but before he can arrest her,
she shoots him up with pure heroin from California-grown poppies.
By the time he is found, his mind is practically gone, and for a
year he stumbles in and out of hospitals and drug rehab. Then, he
heads for England to find Leslie and his future, and the past he
barely remembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heroin Factor'' is a very original tale, full of anger and
yet full of hope. It is not an easy read because much of the
plot-line is very disturbing. The descriptions of heroin addiction
are gut-wrenching and vivid.
</P>
<P>
   An actor who starred in the 1970s detective series ``Tenafly,''
McEachin has successfully changed career directions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
