<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FOX-HNS &LR;      07-27 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX IS ON THE LAUGH TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Forget ``Costello'' and ``Holding the Baby''
for a moment, if you can remember them to start with. The folks at
Fox, home to youthful dramas, as well as animated comedies and
historically horrific live-action comedies, may have finally
figured out how to give us a funny sitcom with real people.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there was a hint of what was to come with ``That '70s
Show,'' a smart and unique take on the days of Peter Frampton and
disco.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fox is rolling out a pair of sitcoms that stand out among a
thin field of new network comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first priority for Fox was to come up with a half hour
that was funny, which is something we haven't done in a long
time,'' said entertainment President Doug Herzog, who came to Fox
at the beginning of the year from Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning the ropes but I'm really, really excited
and very comfortable with the kinds of shows we put on the air.''
Comfortable and lucky, because the two solid rookie comedies were
developed for other networks: ``Action'' for HBO, and ``Malcolm in
the Middle'' for UPN (what were they thinking?).
</P>
<P>
   (It should be noted that Fox is the network that passed on ``The
Sopranos,'' which just had a legendary first season on HBO, and
could not find a place this fall when offered ``Roswell,'' whose
pilot was the strongest among the new dramas to air this fall on
the WB.)
</P>
<P>
   The first of the promising Fox comedies is ``Action,'' a coarse
but dead-on satire of the world of Hollywood, where Jay Mohr plays
an almost amoral movie producer, and the noble conscience of the
cast is a prostitute (played deftly by Illeana Douglas).
</P>
<P>
   The other is ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' which will not premiere
until after the football season. It is the story of a regular kid
from a harried family who is unexpectedly discovered to be a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   Among Fox's other offerings: ``Ally,'' a re-cut, half-hour
version of ``Ally McBeal'' (critics have yet to see a finished
version, which will at times include new footage).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is ``Get Real,'' a promising one-hour
drama/comedy.
</P>
<P>
   For years Fox has portrayed itself as the irreverent network.
Now it might be a funny one, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
