<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-27 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARATOGA SUCCESS BY THE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saratoga opens Wednesday for a 36-day meeting, which runs
through Labor Day. New England horse players, noted for their love
of The Spa, might want to heed a few tips from Jim Mazur, author of
The Saratoga Handicapper 1999, before making their annual
pilgrimage to upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to accomplish is to provide handicappers
with information that's not out there for the general public,''
said Mazur, who has been collaborating with originater John Angelo
on the guide since 1995. ``I'm a player myself, and I was asking
questions I couldn't get answers to. Who's good with firsters? Who
are the best sires? Who's good on turf? Who's good off a layoff?
Who is this guy from Kentucky I've never heard of?
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through three years, and created a data base. Each
book is based on the last three seasons. If you go past three
years, you lose currency. We want to stay on top of it. Over the
course of three years, some barns go sour, while others get hot. We
cover a lot of ground. Some things we did last year worked, and
some didn't. But we had one of our best meetings, and that was
reflected in our sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that we're missing 90 percent to 95 percent of the
handicappers because they want a quick out. This guide is for
people who want to get into it, who want to look things up and get
a little bit of an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazur is the author of several handicapping books, including the
Triple Crown Handicapper and Crushing The Cup. He is a frequent
analyst at Gulfstream, Woodbine, Monmouth, and the Meadowlands.
John Angelo, who began The Saratoga Handicapper as Saratoga
Scorecard in 1989, is the turf writer for the Glenn Falls Post-Star
and has been attending the races at Saratoga for more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``John started it,'' said Mazur. ``It was a fun thing for him.
He wanted to track what was going on at Saratoga. I had been doing
a similar thing at Gulfstream, when John called me and asked me to
take the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzur recalls a particular score that the publication pointed
out late last season. ``Jonathan Sheppard had a horse going against
Parade Ground (considered the top young turfer at the time) in the
Saranac,'' he said. ``The horse's name was Crowd Pleaser, and he
looked overmatched on the speed figures. But we've learned that
Sheppard's horses always do well at Saratoga, regardless of the
figures, and Crowd Pleaser paid 15-1. Day in, and day out, there
are a lot of little angles you can follow when you're betting. For
example, trainer John Hertler has ridden Jean-Luc Samyn seven times
in New York state-bred races, and they've won three, with three
thirds, with an average payoff of 21-1. Everybody knows about
(trainer Bill) Mott and (jockey Jerry) Bailey, but who knows about
Hertler and Samyn?''
</P>
<P>
   The Saratoga Handicapper has sections dealing with `Spa Hares,'
and `Spa Tortoises,' which divides trainers who start out well at
the Saratoga stand, from those who finish well. Since Wednesday is
Opening Day, Mazur took a look at the hares, and peeked at some
other interesting factors, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious fast starter is John Kimmel,'' said Mazur. ``But I
like to follow Barclay Tagg (who is based in Maryland), as well.
Twenty-four percent of the horses Kimmel sends out win the first
time over the Saratoga track. Michael Hushion is at 21 percent.
Rich Violette is at 25 percent. For a New England angle, Mike Aro
is at 50 percent, three winners from six starters. How's this one
in steeplechase racing? Over the last four years, five trainers
have won 91 percent of the jump races. They are Janet Elliot, Bruce
Miller, Sheppard, Richard Hendricks, and Tom Voss. Sure, they all
battle each other, and you still have to pick the winner. But why
bother with anyone else?''
</P>
<P>
   Mazur follows not only the stats of the jockeys but also their
riding styles. ``Jorge Chavez's best strength is when he's hooked
up with horses that close on the turf,'' he said. ``On dirt, he
senses the usual speed bias, and his winners are on or near the
pace. Robbie Davis is a very patient rider, and he's very good on a
stalker. Unfortunately, the best speed rider, Richard Migliore, is
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a `Bomb Squad' of riders, who average high payoffs.
Samyn averages $17. Chavez $15, which is pretty good for one of the
leading riders, and Aaron Gryder averages $14. As for
jockey-trainer combinations, how's this one? Frank Lovato and
Hushion were 3 for 5 in '98. Samyn and Hertler were 3 for 8, and
Shane Sellers and Dallas Stewart (a Kentucky connection) were 3 for
10.''
</P>
<P>
   Track bias is always a consideration, especially at a short
meet. ``At Saratoga, a lot depends on the temperature,'' said
Mazur. ``If it's hot and humid, the winners in sprints seem to all
come from the front end, with nothing coming from behind. There is
a definite bias against deep closers, especially at 7 furlongs. The
route races can still play pretty fair, because, I think, at a mile
and one-eighth (once around the Saratoga oval), they are so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both turf courses, it seems to me, play the same. Very seldom
do horses carry their speed gate to wire. You'd think speed would
be better on the inner course, because of tighter turns, but over
the last six years, only 20 percent of the winners on the inner
turf have been front-runners. The best chance to catch some
wire-to-wire winners is early in the meet because the courses
aren't chewed up yet. As for post position, going a mile and
one-eighth on the inner, where up to 12 can start, posts outside
No. 8 are 4-157 in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``On an off-track, you have to differentiate between sloppy and
muddy. Slop favors speed, mud favors stalkers. That goes for both 7
furlongs, and a mile and one-eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a few of the things we point out. At least we can
help people eliminate horses, and then they can look at the other
things that might produce a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saratoga Handicapper, which also contains sire angles for
the ever popular 2-year-old racing, is available at the bookstore
at The Spa. If you'd like a copy before you go, call
1-800-272-8039. The guide costs $21.95, plus $4 for handling, and
will be shipped via two-day mail. If you've just got to have it
now, arrangements can be made for overnight delivery.
</P>
<P>
   For a lighter look, the Daily Racing Form has introduced The
Saratoga Players' Guide. The guide, which sells for $4, the same
price as a regular Form, offers handicapping columns, analysis of
key track angles, and the charts of every race run at The Spa in
1998. For serious simulcast players, the Form also offers a likely
guide for the 42-day Del Mar meeting, which opened Thursday. Both
guides are available wherever Forms are sold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Information from The Saratoga Handicapper 1999 and the Daily
Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
