<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMAL-TROUBLE-BOS &LR;      07-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-TROUBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'RE BRINGING OUT THE BEAST IN THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decade of wars and genocide, these may be the headlines
that may shock us most:``Evidence Puts Dolphins in New Light, As
Killers,'' trumpeted The New York Times this month. ``Why Your Dog
Pretends to Like You'' snarled at us from the cover of this month's
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Study Exposes Craven Motive of the Brave Meerkat Sentry'' the
paper of record blared last month, picking up a report published in
the journal Science and illustrating it with an adorable picture of
the discredited creature, who looked, quite simply, stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Even discounting humans for a moment, it has been a bad summer
for mammals.
</P>
<P>
   These stories, in all fairness, are complicated reappraisals
that set new science against old misconceptions. All that we are
really learning this summer is that cute little critters can be
nasty, scheming beasts _ rather like their human counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the meerkat, a Kalahari Desert resident that
resembles nothing so much as a Disneyfied land otter, big eyes all
aglow as if awaiting its musical cue. Nothing in that round furry
face ever promised altruism, at least not to the mice and bugs it
feeds on.
</P>
<P>
   But now the meerkat is big news because it has been shown that
he and his fellows do not stand guard for their peers out of any
community spirit, but because those on sentinel duty have the best
chance to spot and escape from predators.
</P>
<P>
   True, the story concludes _ 80 lines in _ that the meerkat shows
some generosity of spirit by whistling a warning to his fellows,
rather than increasing his own chances by allowing the predator to
sate his hunger (take my den mate, please). But this meerkat
warning is dismissed as mere afterthought; ``I'm heading for the
hills, guys, and, by the way, there's a hawk behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   O tempora! O mores! But, worse than this disappointment from a
desert rat with a handsome face, is the apparent betrayal of our
companionate nonhumans, the animals we thought we knew, and that we
thought loved us.
</P>
<P>
   There is Fido, snarling up at us the moment we cease to hold the
alpha position in our home pack. And there is Flipper, not saving
hapless shipwrecked sailors, but, in the words of the gleefully
nasty chart, ``simply . . . playing with the sailors as they would
a piece of debris.'' Debris! We feed and shelter these animals (or
at least train them to carry bombs and set off depth charges), and
this is how we are repaid? It is enough to make some of us eat tuna
again, or at least get a cat, which you know will be straight with
you.
</P>
<P>
   The writers of such stories _ perhaps echoing what many of us
feel _ affect a wounded innocence. The Atlantic's Stephen Budiansky
gasps at the inherently wolfish traits in dogs, as if enlightened
self-interest were not at the core of international relations (and
most marriages) as well. He then describes breeding practices (by
humans, on dogs) dangerous enough to make any purebred petulant.
Readers can draw their own conclusions about what is behind the
sour look on the face of the retriever who graces the magazine's
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists, pet owners obviously, claim the news is not
entirely bad. They point out that we have known for years that our
warm, fuzzy neighbors were not necessarily either of those things _
emotionally speaking, that is _ to us or to themselves.
Chimpanzees, for example, have been found to war among themselves,
and even to practice cannibalism. Certain birds, long thought to be
faithful throughout life, have been caught feathering others'
nests.
</P>
<P>
   They are not noble savages; they are animals. That's their job.
As Trevor R. Spradlin, who was intriguingly identified as a federal
dolphin expert, told the Times with a firm grasp of the obvious:
``Wildlife can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some would argue that the point in these news stories
is not that familiar creatures are newly nasty, but that we are
finally willing to accept their, well, wild natures and rise above
our innate anthropomorphism. And perhaps we are ready to leave
behind the web-footed nursery tales of Mr. Jeremy Fisher and take
him as he is, warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a darker context, one that doesn't make us _
for once _ the mature adults who have learned to accept that
sometimes Santa Claus smells of whiskey and the Tooth Fairy
forgets. No, behind this current string of ``bad animal'' stories,
some savvy analysts have begun to detect a subtle strain of
speciesism.
</P>
<P>
   We are living in a time when ethnic cleansing has reentered our
vocabulary. When war crime tribunals have once again convened, and
something called ``compassionate conservatism'' is gaining
throughout the land. We are at a humanitarian low, and so we are
striking back _ as present-day defendants so often do _ by blaming
our family. Our mammalian family.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the ``Flipper kills baby porpoises, so what do you
expect from me?'' defense; it seems to be working. The grinning
mouth, now so clearly full of razor-edged teeth, looks up at us
from the page just as it once did from our favorite TV show and
seems to say, ``We are all in this together.'' And by imagining an
evil glint in its small and beady eye, we find the perfect
evolutionary excuse for our own beastly behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
