<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-27 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS MUST OPEN WALLET TO DRAW NAMES, TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The saga of the Revolution's acquisition of striker Ariel
Graziani highlights some of the deficiencies of Major League
Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The league is centrally controlled from New York, so player
scouting and signing is handled by the personnel department headed
by Ivan Gazidis. The bulk of the signings were accomplished in the
first two years of the league under former deputy commissioner
Sunil Gulati, but since then MLS has become less ambitious in its
pursuit of players.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attracting names on the level of Jorge Campos, Marco
Etcheverry, and Carlos Valderrama, MLS appears to be going after
lower-profile types who might exceed expectations and establish
their reputations in the United States. A Mauricio Cienfuegos or
Mauricio Wright would be a good example of this type of performer.
</P>
<P>
   The league is apparently not interested in delving too deeply
into the international marketplace but would prefer to arrange
liasons in Latin America and the Caribbean for reasons of
accessibility and cost-effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the Revolution brought in players from England, Ghana,
Ireland, and Portugal for recent tryouts, the team might have been
wasting its time. About the same time, Gazidis was working on
connections in Mexico, and in recent days it became apparent he
could sign Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, the only MLS team with a foreign player opening,
became the prime candidate for Graziani _ though striker was not
the position they needed filled.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion set in when the Revolution appeared interested in
Joseph Addo, who could not only solve their immediate problems but
could become the best defender in MLS. After flirting with Addo for
several days, however, the Revolution announced Monday that
Graziani would be joining them.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani will likely become one of the best forwards in the
league and may be cost-effective _ if the league actually paid
substantially less than the $2 million that has been published.
Gazidis denied the league paid $2 million for Graziani but would
not confirm a fee.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, questions are raised about priorities. If the league
is interested in cost-effectiveness, it is almost obligated to
acquire Addo, since no transfer fee is required.
</P>
<P>
   The league simply will not improve if it misses out on such
bargains. There are too many weak links on MLS teams for them to be
treated seriously over an eight-month season. While MLS executives
are congratulating themselves for holding the line on costs,
attendance is not improving and will not unless the quality
improves drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Revolution are not a credible team. They are in
third place in the Eastern Conference, but they have earned only 18
points in 18 matches. And they are one injury away from disaster.
They should have realized early on that the defense needs more
athleticism and variety, both in central defenders and defensive
midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are now in position to make a trade to bolster
the defense. But they will not be able to find anyone of the
caliber of Addo. In fact, Tampa Bay is interested in Addo and could
rejuvenate itself by signing him.
</P>
<P>
   This is no way to build a soccer team. In fact, just when the
Revolution appear about to fit enough of the right pieces together,
the entire project is diverted. The philosophy _ solid, all-out
defending combined with esprit de corps _ is not being followed.
The team now has five strikers but only two central defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Again, a question is raised: How often does something like this
happen in MLS? Well, in 1996 and '97, D.C. United tried to acquire
Addo. But the league's offer was unrealistically low, no room was
left for compromise, and Addo moved to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kaviedes strikes it rich
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The going rate for top-level Ecuadorian strikers is $5.5
million. At least, that is what Celta paid for Ivan Kaviedes,
another former Emelec player who has been with Perugia in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Kaviedes scored 43 goals in 1998, the best total for any club
player. He is bigger than Graziani, mobile, and has excellent
offensive instincts. Probably no other Ecuadoran player has been
regarded as seriously as Kaviedes since Alberto Spencer in the
1960s. Even if Kaviedes is being overvalued, the trend now is for
clubs to pay for potential, and that means young players. Kaviedes
is 20 years old but mature enough to have survived in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Celta also signed South African Benedict McCarthy, 20, who
played for Ajax last year.
</P>
<P>
   The best bargains, though, are still to be found in Uruguay. The
Uruguayans presented a group of local players, average age 23, in
Copa America and finished second to Brazil last week.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a small country _ 3 million population _ and nearly
every viable player is controlled by Francisco (Paco) Casal, one of
the world's most powerful agents.
</P>
<P>
   Casal, who represents Daniel Fonseca, Fabian O'Neill, Alvaro
Recoba, and dozens of others, has become even more ambitious. He
acquired the passes of five players by paying the club Bella Vista
$4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Adrian Berbia, midfielder Guillermo Giacomazzi, and
Copa America stars Diego Alonso, Alejandro Lembo, and Leonel
Pilipauskas will continue to perform for Bella Vista but will
answer to Casal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
