<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA TOPS THE WISH LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If cost were not an issue, where would you like to go?
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row Australia tops the list of a Harris
Poll taken in June. Great Britain (England, Scotland, and Wales)
took second place, followed by Germany, which moved up from fifth
place a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries in the top 15 in order of popularity were Italy,
France, Canada, Ireland, Jamaica, Switzerland, Mexico, Greece,
Spain, Japan, New Zealand, and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Harris pollsters say, money is an issue, and
getting to Australia is generally more expensive _ and a longer
journey _ than going to Europe, Canada, or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you plan an Australian trip right, it can be a
great value. For example, Qantas Vacations is offering specials to
Australia from Oct. 31 to Dec. 8 that include five nights' free
accommodations at $1,248 a person from Los Angles to Melbourne, and
from New York, a $1,648 round-trip package that includes a free
four-day, three-night self-drive Victorian Highlights tour and two
free nights at the five-star Melbourne Hotel. From April 19-May 30,
Qantas Vacations offers a $1,398 package to either Sydney or
Melbourne. For information, call 800-252-6286.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Old home days
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old home days were a tradition in Vermont and New Hampshire in
the early 20th century. Now many communities have revived the
tradition with special events, exhibits, culinary treats, and more.
In New Hampshire, these days were also for luring back former
residents to help revitalize the state's economy. New Hampshire
Preservation Alliance offers a history of old home days. For a
copy, call 603-224-2281.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, Calvin Coolidge's birthplace, Plymouth Notch, will
celebrate Old Home Day July 31 with reenactments, music, a kite
parade, a barbecue, and even free Moxie (you haven't lived until
you try this once popular New England ``tonic,'' otherwise known as
soda). Admission is free but evening events and house tours have a
reasonable admission.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Hampstead celebrates 250 years July 30-Aug. 8
(call 603-329-5789); Bethlehem celebrates its bicentennial Aug.
6-Aug. 8 (call 503-869-3386); Washington Old Home Days are Aug. 6-8
(call 603-495-3262); and from July 28-Aug. 1, history comes alive
in Portsmouth as actors playing Daniel Webster, Mary Baker Eddy,
and others perform under the Chautauqua tent at Strawbery Banke.
For information, call 603-224-4071.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first annual Best of the Cape &AMP; Islands will be held Aug. 1
from 2 to 6 p.m. at the Cape Cod Mall on Route 132 in Hyannis.
Restaurants and attractions throughout the Cape and Martha's
Vineyard and Nantucket will participate, including Cobie's in
Brewster, Cape Cod Baseball, Heritage Plantation, and the Lobster
Pot in Provincetown. Admission is $5, with proceeds benefiting the
Cape and Islands Children's Charities. For information, call
508-771-0200.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohonk Mountain House will celebrate its 64th Annual Garden
Holiday program Aug. 29-Sept. 1. Mohonk's gardens are in their
111th year and are the focal point of the weekend. There will be
guided walks, plant talks, classes in drawing, and workshops by
specialists. For information on the program and resort packages,
call 800-772-6646.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest Irish festival takes place in Milwaukee Aug.
19-22. More than 50 performers will be featured including Tommy
Makem, the Trinity Irish Dancers, and Gaelic Storm, the group that
performed in the festive steerage class scene in the movie
``Titanic.'' In addition there will be plays, a tug of war, and
children's area. For information, call 414-229-5879.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smart card
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Museum of Fine Arts now offers a Smart Card good
for admission to exhibitions, and purchases in the museum shop or
its cafe. And, the card has become a collector's item. Each card is
produced in limited quantity and illustrated with a work from the
current exhibition, ``Cosmos: From Romanticism to the
Avant-garde,'' which celebrates the discovery and search for new
horizons through art. Another card, illustrated with the ``Crown of
Flowers'' by Cilliam Bouguereau, has replaced the museum's gift
certificate. In Europe, Smart Cards rank second after stamps among
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda dreams
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever wanted to visit Bermuda? Better still, with your
company paying all the bills? That's what happened recently for the
people who work for Jordan's Furniture stores in the Boston area.
All 1,300 employees were flown to the island for a day of fun and
sun. It's a great idea, and now Steve Belkin, president of TNT
Vacations, which arranged the outing, is out to market it to other
companies in the New England area. Belkin, needless to say, thinks
it's a great idea. And to back this up, he's been closing up shop
and taking his employees to Bermuda every five years for the last
20. In case your employer needs a reason to do a similar outing,
Belkin notes that a trip like this helps team building, is a morale
booster, reduces turnover, helps in hiring, and offers great
publicity. Add to this that it's a great value for companies.
Belkin notes it costs about 1 percent of the payroll, about $400 a
person for Bermuda. ``Do something good, and it comes back,'' said
Belkin. Employees like working for a company that does such things.
Bermuda likes the idea, too. Tourism people there feel if people
come for one day, they'll come back. Interestingly, TNT discovered
that 70 percent of Jordan's employees had never been out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stay cool
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first exhibition to explore the transformative power of air
conditioning, ``Stay Cool! Air Conditioning in America,'' is on
view through Jan. 2 at the National Building Museum in Washington.
Through photos, artifacts, television commercials, and interactive
displays, the exhibit will explore the history of ``air
conditioning,'' beginning with pioneering experiments in the late
1800s. Manufacturers at the turn of the century were learning that
by filtering air and stabilizing temperature, mechanical systems
improved the environment for products . . . and people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
World peace
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A conference, ``Building Bridges of Peace, Culture, and
Prosperity through Sustainable Tourism,'' will be held in Glasgow
in October. An estimated 800 participants from more than 70
countries are expected for the conference, which will include
real-life case studies on the theme. The event is being organized
by the International Institute for Peace Through Tourism, founded
in 1986 in Montreal to harness the power of the tourism industry as
the world's first global peace industry. IIPT is now headquartered
in Stowe, Vt. For information, call 802-253-2658 or visit
www.iipt.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
