<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; sci-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SATELLITE-OF-HUMANITY     07-27 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-OF-HUMANITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARK DE TRIOMPHE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT KUNZIG  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   If there are human beings on Earth in the year 52,001, and they
happen to look up to the sky one evening and find it filled with a
shimmering aurora, they can thank Jean-Marc Philippe for the light
show.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe, an artist in Paris, is the creator of KEO, a satellite
designed to stay in orbit for 50,000 years. When KEO finally
plunges back into the atmosphere, its disintegrating heat shield
will generate spectacular streamers of light. As the northern
lights fade, KEO's core, a small titanium sphere, will fall to
Earth somewhere, intact. Inside will be letters from us.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe hopes to collect billions of letters, store them on
compact disks in that titanium sphere and launch them in 2001.
Because KEO is meant to be a work of art, it will have giant wings
that will flap for a few years after its launch. Their sole
purpose? To be beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Why send messages to people we're not even sure will exist?
Philippe wants to make us _ the people of the dawning third
millennium _ think. Think about what kind of future we want to
create for our world.
</P>
<P>
   ``An artist has to say what he feels strongly,'' he says, ``and
what I feel strongly is the contradiction between a supremely
gifted species, man, which is able to measure distances in
light-years, manipulate genes, produce a Mozart, and at the same
time is able to behave, on a day-to-day basis, in a way that makes
me ashamed. To raise kids, for example, in our rich society, who
are sorry to be alive. There's a profound incoherence to our
culture. As an artist, what I want to do is stimulate the beauty of
the species, the grandeur of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising thing about Philippe's idea is that
it may actually fly. He has the support of the French aerospace
industry. Dozens of engineers in France are working on his project
for free in their spare time. He does not have billions of letters
yet, but thousands have already poured into his Paris apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe says he has room for every human to send up to four
typewritten pages, or 6,000 characters. The messages, written in
any language, will not be censored.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe is a slight man with graying hair and beard and a warm,
open, focused expression. Thirty years ago he got a Ph.D. in space
physics at the University of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``After graduation I chose to favor intuition over
rationality,'' he says. ``So I became a painter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lying outdoors on his back one summer night, watching the trace
of light left by a satellite, it came to him: Why not use space as
his canvas?
</P>
<P>
   Philippe has conceived several works of space art. In the 1980s
Philippe secured time on a radio telescope near the Loire Valley.
He offered people the chance to send personal messages to
extraterrestrial civilizations. Some 10,500 people sent letters via
MINITEL, the French data-phone network. Philippe converted the
letters to radio signals and beamed them toward the center of the
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe has been working on KEO for nearly five years now,
without pay. Three years ago his wife, Karin Jestin, quit her job
to help him organize the project.
</P>
<P>
   To make KEO real, Philippe needed the help of engineers. The
first door he knocked on was Aerospatiale, the huge French company
that is a major contractor for the Ariane rocket and Airbus jet.
Philippe met the human resources director there, an engineer named
Patrick Tejedor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him right away that I thought it was an excellent
idea,'' Tejedor says. ``I could see it was a project that was one
part dream, one part passion and one part wonderful _ and that all
those parts might be a little difficult to realize, but that it
could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The point in launching a time capsule into space, instead of
burying it, was to capture people's imaginations. And that is why
Philippe wants the sphere to have wings. Engineers at Aerospatiale
have helped him figure a way to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Made of a carbon composite and tightly folded to fit into a
rocket's payload bay, the wings will unfold to their full span of
33 feet once the satellite reaches its orbit 1,125 miles above
Earth. The wings will fold each time KEO passes into Earths' shadow
and spread each time the satellite returns to sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Every satellite that flies lower than geostationary orbit
(22,500 miles) is destined to fall back to Earth. And in KEO's
case, according to calculations by Marc Montagne of Aerospatiale,
it should take approximately 50,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   What actually plops to Earth will be the titanium core of the
satellite, a sphere about 18 inches across. Chances are it will
plop in the ocean, float and eventually land on some beach.
Engraved on its surface will be a map of the present position of
the continents. The organism that finds the sphere, Philippe hopes,
may be intrigued enough to crack it open and look inside.
</P>
<P>
   Inside he will find gifts. A glass plaque will show a group
portrait of humanity today. Embedded in an artificial diamond will
be four hollow gold pellets, the size of BBs, containing samples of
air, seawater, soil and human blood. A human DNA sequence will be
engraved on the diamond's surface as a kind of universal signature.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there will be stacks of compact disks, made of special
plated glass to help preserve their digital contents from cosmic
rays. Some of the disks will contain a contemporary ``Library of
Alexandria'' _ a synopsis of current human knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But in Philippe's view the greatest gift to our descendants will
be our own personal letters. But how likely is it that KEO and its
message will be received? It may get obliterated in space by a
meteor. It may return to Earth but never be found. It may be found
but never understood _ people still argue, after all, about what
Stonehenge means, and Stonehenge is only around 4,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But communicating with our descendants is only half the point.
The other half is communicating with ourselves. As soon as KEO is
launched, Philippe and Jestin intend to publish all the messages.
People will learn what other people, of radically different
origins, think is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the most important moment in all this is that moment of
personal reflection,'' Jestin says. ``You may be a little bit
changed just by having taken the time to question yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert Kunzig is the European Editor at Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
