<HEADER>
A5353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      07-27 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR TAKES TOLL ON COLOMBIA'S PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA _ Last July, only two weeks before his inauguration as
Colombia's president, Andres Pastrana shook off his security detail
and sneaked into the Andean jungles for a secret meeting with
leftist guerrilla leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The move instantly sparked hope for an end to the hemisphere's
oldest civil war, and it immediately gave the
journalist-turned-politician an image of a bold and decisive
leader.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, however, it's hard to find a Colombian who still
feels that way about the prospects for peace, or has a good word to
say about Pastrana. In the aftermath of a surge of new violence
between rebels and the army, stalled negotiations and now a failing
economy, last year's optimism has given way to this year's dread.
And Pastrana is getting much of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too soft, that's his main problem,'' said Jose Marcos
Grijalva, 33, a furniture salesman who sat outside a downtown store
that drew just two customers all last week. ``He's been too soft
with the guerrillas, and now he's being too soft with the economy.
Sometimes I wish he would just stand up and say, `Look. I'm
president and this is how things are going to be done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks to end the conflict have been postponed twice this
year _ once in February when the rebels failed to show up, and
again last week because of disagreements over the role that
international observers will play and for a clearer definition of a
``demilitarized zone'' controlled by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting, meanwhile, has continued at an alarming pace. In a
major offensive last fall, the 15,000-member Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, a guerrilla group known as the FARC that
controls large areas of rural land, blew up one of the country's
main oil pilelines. Then, for a brief moment two weeks ago, another
FARC push came perilously close to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Its smaller counterpart, the National Liberation Army, known as
the ELN and thought to have 5,000 armed fighters, has resorted to
hijacking airplanes and regularly kidnapping prominent and ordinary
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Colombians' fears about the ongoing violence are second only to
their growing anxieties over the worsening economic situation.
Stung by years of mounting government debt, growing investor fears
over the conflict and record-high unemployment, experts say
Colombia is now in the midst of its worst recession since the Great
Depression of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   As he begins the second year of his term, Pastrana's government
is trying to tackle both the conflict and the economy, but it's
confronting a pessimism as thick as the summer clouds that daily
shroud much of this country.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia has rarely been an easy place to live. For most of the
last three decades, residents have tolerated the guerrillas, the
right-wing paramilitary groups who oppose them, and have lived
cautiously to avoid the bullets, bombs or fast-striking kidnappers
commanded by the world's deadliest drug lords.
</P>
<P>
   But this remarkably resilient population is losing patience, and
more residents are choosing to leave Colombia rather than endure
more instability.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say that demand for visa applications at the
US Embassy in Bogota has reached 50,000 a month, more than double
the number last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the number of tourist visas that we issue,'' one
American official here said last week. ``What we don't know is how
many of them are coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many residents say Pastrana is too lenient on the
rebels _ especially because he gave them control of a demilitarized
area equal to 1 percent of the country's total area _ they also
blame the guerrillas, who launched their Marxist-based revolution
35 years ago but now terrorize farmers and receive most of their
funds for weapons and equipment from drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the country's mounting problems, Pastrana's
administration is still firmly supported by Washington. Unlike his
predecessor, Ernesto Samper, who was publicly linked to drug money
and corruption and roundly criticized by US officials, Pastrana has
bolstered ties to the White House and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, President Clinton hosted a state dinner for the
Colombian leader, and Congress approved $285 million in emergency
funds, more than double the previous appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce its commitment, Washington has dispatched US drug
policy chief Barry McCaffrey on a three-day visit to Colombia this
week to review joint anti-narcotic operations. In the past,
McCaffrey has urged Washington to triple its military aid here to
slow the drug flow from Colombia, the world's top source of cocaine
and a growing supplier of heroin.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how fierce the bloodshed has been between the army and
rebels or drug rings, previous Colombian presidents could always
count on steady growth from an economy long considered a model in
Latin America for its relatively strong middle class and productive
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
   But experts now say that the conflict and the economy have
become intertwined as more businesses close and investors pull
their money out because of concerns over the political climate,
putting unprecendented pressure on Pastrana while strengthening the
rebels' hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless it solves the economic problems, this government won't
have the political capital to negotiate a peace agreement,'' said
Maria Angelica Arbelaez, an economist at Fedesarollo, a leading
think tank. ``The technical capacity is there, but it needs to make
tough decisions and explain them.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the past year, Pastrana has devalued the Colombian
peso, the national currency. Earlier this month _ for the first
time in its history _ the government received a $3 billion line of
credit from the International Monetary Fund by agreeing to reform
its constitution and cut spending.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before the Colombian congress last week, Pastrana
proposed a new labor law that would reduce time off and other
benefits for workers in an effort to bring down Colombia's 20
percent unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's headaches have recently extended beyond the country's
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Fujimori, the Peruvian president known for authoritarian
methods that helped wipe out that country's Maoist rebel group, the
Shining Path, has publicly criticized his Colombian counterpart for
not using a ``mano dura'' _ a strong hand. And President Hugo
Chavez of Venezuela, who led an unsuccessful coup seven years ago,
has banned Colombian truck drivers from crossing the border in
retaliation for the terror and assaults that Venezuelan drivers
encounter on Colombian roads.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana's most important critics, perhaps, are those who
belong to Colombia's once-thriving middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard a flight on Sunday from Bogota to Caracas, the Venezuelan
capital, one American-educated owner of a fishing company said that
after two failed kidnapping attempts and countless shakedowns by
rebel troops over the last year, he has decided to leave his native
country to invest in a similar business in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's people like me in the middle class who have kept Colombia
stable even through years of civil war and drugs,'' said the man,
who requested anonymity. ``But we can't wait anymore. I have other
friends who have left. I know I won't be the last one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
