<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$8 FOR MEMBERSHIP IN OLD AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I expected to hear from the folks at the AARP
this year _ just not so soon. It's several more months before I hit
their minimum age requirement of 50.
</P>
<P>
   But, sure enough, a big white AARP envelope was sticking out of
my mailbox: ``Membership Certificate and Temporary Membership Card
Enclosed.'' Inside: ``WELCOME TO AARP!''
</P>
<P>
   Countless friends had told me that part of marking one's big
Five-O in the USA is receiving an invitation to join the nation's
largest senior citizens lobby. Few of these friends were thrilled
to be included, and even fewer chose to become actual card-carrying
members of the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   (``You must be 50 or over. You need not be retired.'')
</P>
<P>
   I, however, have been looking forward to signing up. Among other
benefits, AARP membership gets you all kinds of discounts on hotel
rooms, tours, bed and breakfasts, restaurants, rental cars and
cruises. For example, some 3,500 Choice hotels, which include
Comfort Inns and Clarion hotels, knock 30 percent off room rates
for guests of the AARP persuasion. Sheraton shaves 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't want a discount? More attractively (for me), the
AARP has 33 million members, making it one of the few little-guy's
special interest groups that can kick butt in Washington. Every
other organization I pay dues to is liberal, left-wing or
tree-hugging _ and about as powerful a lobby as my high school
graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe best of all, AARP dues are only $8 a year. That's about
two pennies a day, which you can find on the sidewalk if you live
in a city and keep your eyes half-open.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else I know of in life costs 2 cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as I said, I wasn't looking for my invite for another
four months. If I returned my ``Certificate of Admission to
Membership'' by Sept. 1, as instructed, I'd be a cheating
49-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   I called AARP in Washington, D.C. The press office was closed
for the day _ hey, why do you think it's called an association of
RETIRED persons? _ so I asked the operator who answered the phone
what the deal was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You received a membership offer and you're not eligible?'' she
said. ``That happens. Sometimes, when you get on a mailing list, we
buy it. Like, maybe some magazine that you subscribe to.''
</P>
<P>
   I ran through the eclectic list. Who sold my name to AARP? Opera
News? Tricycle, the American Buddhist Quarterly? The Nation?
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet it was Newsweek. The only reason I get Newsweek is
because it was part of a gifts package for joining KQED, the local
PBS television station. (All I'd wanted was the ``Roy Orbison and
Friends'' videotape.)
</P>
<P>
   KQED recently admitted that it twice leased its mailing list to
the Democratic National Committee and twice to Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif. How big a leap is it to suspect Newsweek would hand KQED's
members over to AARP?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing department buys the mailing lists,'' the
operator continued. ``Anything anybody signs for can end up on one.
Like, students sometimes get our offers because they signed for
something for their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   I told the woman that I'd just figured the AARP knew my 50th
birthday was coming and jumped the gun. She laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean like we'd know? It was just a coincidence,'' she
said. ``We have mailing lists but we don't have any mechanism to
determine when you turn 50.''
</P>
<P>
   And all this time I'd pictured a vast computer in the basement
of 601 E Street in Washington, D.C., that is wired into Social
Security or Birth Certificates, Inc., or whatever, and would
automatically spit out the names of the Americans who hit their
official ``You Are Now Entering Geezerhood'' birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Ask again in a few months, AARP. If you'll kick
congressional butt for me, I'll give you eight bucks a year until I
die.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
