<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZKIT TAKES LEAD IN RAP-METAL REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget all that hoopla about Latin pop, which is far more pop
than Latin, which will fade long before Ricky Martin stops shaking
his bonbon. What's making the biggest racket these days is
take-no-prisoners, make-your-ears-bleed hardcore rap and heavy
metal, which Limp Bizkit is elevating to new levels.
</P>
<P>
   In the August issue of Spin magazine, the one that has cover
boys Limp Bizkit in an almighty twist, Zev Borow writes of the
band: ``Dredging up youthful anger and rebellion is one thing,
taking it somewhere is another. Simply put, Limp Bizkit have yet to
write a truly good song.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so knuckleheaded charmers like ``Nookie'' and ``Break
Stuff'' aren't exactly ``Stardust'' or ``Hey Jude.'' But Spin's
observations _ however piquant, and perhaps even true _ really miss
the fact that Limp Bizkit is crafting a likely blueprint for
popular music as we careen into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, Limp Bizkit is the Jacksonville, Fla.-based
quintet that made industry types sit up and pay attention when the
band's sophomore effort, ``Significant Other,'' entered the
Billboard Album Chart at No. 1, drop-kicking the insipid Backstreet
Boys out of the penthouse for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Led by gleefully bombastic Fred Durst, the band makes music
that's all battering-ram rhythms, rhymes, and badass attitude,
equal parts Metallica and Tupac.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly other bands, most notably Red Hot Chili Peppers, Korn,
Rage Against the Machine, Kottonmouth Kings, and Biohazard, have
splashed about in these waters before, injecting their metal and
rock with healthy doses of funk and/or hip-hop. Rapper Ice-T
cranked up the volume, and ticked off just about everyone with his
thrash-metal outfit, Body Count, and the Beastie Boys have never
shied from the potent scream of guitars to bulk up their rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   And recently, there have been such
``Hey-you-got-peanut-butter-in-my-chocolate'' collaborations as
Busta Rhymes and Ozzy Osbourne on Busta's ``This Means War,'' which
samples Black Sabbath's ``Iron Man''; Puff Daddy and Jimmy Page's
``Come With Me,'' an unforgivable bastardization of Led Zeppelin's
great ``Kashmir''; and hard-to-find, wickedly slinky ``Bounce,''
which joined Rage Against the Machine and Snoop Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   But more than any other current band, Limp Bizkit, which
performed at last weekend's three-day love, music, and rioting
festival, Woodstock '99, has brought to fruition the delicious
possibilities Run-DMC hinted at more than a decade ago on such
classic tracks as ``Rock Box,'' ``King of Rock,'' and, of course,
their tag team with Aerosmith on the latter's ``Walk This Way.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that background-beat science, the boys of Bizkit _
Durst, along with guitarist Wes Borland, bassist Sam Rivers,
drummer John Otto, and DJ Lethal, who worked the wheels of steel
for House of Pain _ have created a metal album you can mosh and
dance to. It's a recognition of the groove underlying Metallica's
``Enter Sandman'' and Nirvana's ``Smells Like Teen Spirit,'' and a
shout-out to the metal-toothed snarl of N.W.A's ``Straight Outta
Compton'' and DMX's ``Get at Me, Dog.'' They're making records both
derivative and quite unlike anything else.
</P>
<P>
   With his old-school, shell-toe Adidas (bet he knows all the
words to Run-DMC's ``My Adidas'') and backward baseball cap, Durst,
who considers himself more a rapper than singer, has all the
pretty-fly-for-a-white-guy moves down. And unlike the grunge
crybabies of yore who were all bollixed up about the horrors of
fame, Durst, bless his megalomaniacal heart, revels in it, crowing
about his desire to blow up as a rap-metal mogul, comparable to
rapper-entrepreneur Master P. (He may be on his way; his label,
Interscope, recently named Durst a senior vice president, to
oversee producing, remixing, signing new acts, and directing
videos.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just Puffed-up posturing. Durst knows he and the
Bizkit boys are onto something with ``Significant Other,'' a
sizable stylistic leap from their debut, ``Three Dollar Bill,
Y'all$,'' and its chainsaw cover of George Michael's ``Faith.''
Durst is serious enough to trade lines with rap luminary Method Man
on ``N 2 Gether Now,'' and while he doesn't embarrass himself, no
one is going to confuse Fred D with Chuck D when it comes to his
flow on the mike.
</P>
<P>
   But that, like Spin's lament, is also beside the point. Limp
Bizkit's influence should not be denied, and while the band is not
the first shot in the rap-metal revolution, it is the most
successful. Other artists such as Kid Rock and Sevendust, both of
whom also played Woodstock '99, are also finding acclaim and
listeners. Perhaps few realize it now, but ``Significant Other''
may come to be regarded as important a musical touchstone as Dr.
Dre's ``The Chronic'' or Nirvana's ``Nevermind.'' And that's not
too bad for a bunch of guys who did it all for the nookie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
