<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUCK IN DENIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm an honest man, a God-fearing man with a wife and kids. I try
to see things as clear as I can, and I don't mean anybody any harm.
I'm about like any man who goes into the office every day and tries
his darnedest to do the best job he knows how. As a loan officer at
this fine institution, I try day-in and day-out to make the right
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   I've been in this spot before. I've seen men like this wanting a
helping hand from us, and I know full well what I'm thinking, I
know which way I'm leaning. But I'll be as thorough as a man can
be. I'll take my time, step-by-step, so Mr. Childs will know we are
fair, and friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Childs, I see here you had a little trouble with credit at
another institution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir. We missed one payment. But that was five years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On account of an illness in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is when you run a small business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then we've never missed another single payment. And the
business is growing every year. We'd like to grow some more now
with your help in the way of this small loan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Childs is enthusiastic, charming even. He is probably a good
businessman. But looking into his face, I don't know. I just see
something that scares me. As a loan officer, I have to be sensitive
to my instincts. And there's something there _ something in that
face screaming the one word we in this business can't tolerate:
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, it has nothing to do with the obvious. I am not a
biased man. I am aware of the latest studies, and I give them no
heed. There's that one by a Dartmouth professor who analyzed
Federal Reserve Board data on more than 4,600 small businesses. It
found that 66 percent of blacks were denied loans for their small
businesses, while 27 percent of whites were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alan Greenspan, our superhuman Fed chairman, worries about
the studies. He has said, ``To the extent that market participants
discriminate _ consciously or, more likely, unconsciously _ credit
does not flow to its most profitable uses.''
</P>
<P>
   My response is identical to that of the chief economist of the
American Bankers Association, James Chessen, who calls the studies
inadequate. ``They cannot capture the decision-making of loan
officers,'' he rightly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   And so I look into Mr. Childs face and, try as I might, I still
cannot get over my fears. ``You have been denied loans on two
occasions, is that right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystery to me. All I know is I got the one loan and was
denied two others.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous denial _ that worries me. What might I be missing, if I
approve this loan, that others saw. I'm looking into his face
again, and I see what I need to see. I'm convinced now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Childs, you keep your business account at this bank, don't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir. I thought it might work in my favor if I came to you
for the loan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted to have your business account. But, Mr.
Childs, I'm afraid we have to deny your application for a loan.
It's really nothing personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir. I've heard it before. Please don't mind my asking:
If it's not personal, then what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Mr. Childs, it's like this: I'm just not comfortable
with what I see _ on paper, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
