<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION ADD GRAZIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it has become obvious the Revolution need high-level
help in central defense, they have acquired a high-scoring striker.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Jose Graziani, who has scored 34 goals in the last two
years in Mexico, was officially assigned to the Revolution by Major
League Soccer Monday and could be available for their visit to
Tampa Bay Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, 28, is expected to become one of the top offensive
players in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution should probably be concentrating more on
defensive improvement, both on the back line and midfield,
following home losses to Los Angeles (5-2) and D.C. United (2-0).
They surrendered midfield possession for much of the first half in
Sunday's game, and United capitalized by scoring twice in the first
33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution were apparently moving toward adding
defender Joseph Addo last week, but changed direction after the
league signed Graziani. This leaves the Revolution with five
strikers and two central defenders, and will likely lead to other
moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ariel Graziani is a player we have had our eye on for some
time,'' MLS deputy commissioner Ivan Gazidis said. ``There are a
number of teams interested in him. He is one of the most elegant
strikers in Central and South America and one of the most prolific.
He is great to watch and he will score goals in the MLS.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the assignation seems strange, since Joe-Max Moore
has been on a scoring streak and the Revolution's vulnerabilities
are elsewhere. But Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga can be
faulted for not recognizing the team's need for more athleticism,
experience, and variety in central defense sooner. Yet, there were
no guarantees MLS would have been able to procure the type of
player Zenga requested.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Zenga had hoped to acquire an outside right midfielder
until recently. But after the Revolution were crushed by Los
Angeles, and central defender Dan Calichman suffered a hip injury
against D.C. United, the team's defensive needs have become more
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Revolution's choice,'' Gazidis said. ``If they
had preferred a defender, we could have helped them. They could
have passed on Graziani. I would have no problem negotiating with
Joe Addo, or whoever they want. It's not an easy choice for them,
because they are hurting for numbers defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, a native of Villa Empalme, Villa Constitucion,
Argentina, began his professional career in 1993 with Newell's Old
Boys in Rosario. The next year, he moved to Sport Boys of Peru,
then to Aucas and Emelec in Ecuador. Graziani scored 52 goals in 69
games with Emelec, became a naturalized Ecuadoran citizen, played
for the national team in World Cup qualifying and Copa America, and
has scored 12 goals in 21 international appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Graziani scored 20 goals for Veracruz in Mexico, then
produced 14 goals for Morelia this year. His teammates have
included Diego Maradona in Argentina and Alexi Lalas and Revolution
striker Joe-Max Moore in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no doubt in our minds as an organization
that we want Ariel Graziani on this team,'' Revolution general
manager Brian O'Donovan said. ``We believe that he is a very
big-time player who will have a major impact on whatever team he
goes to. We are celebrating the addition of a high-impact player,
in spite of our defensive weaknesses, which we can correct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
