<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAKE-BOARDING-ART-BOS     07-27 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAKE-BOARDING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD TO BE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER BONFANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTERVILLE, Mass. _ Lance Richardson is describing what it's
like to fly on water _ flipping, twisting, and soaring across the
wake of a towboat, pulling off gravity-defying stunts with offbeat
names like ``Bel Air,'' ``Tantrum,'' and ``Air Raley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my body totally extended,'' said Richardson. ``It's
quiet. I feel weightless looking down at the water . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   His tricks have onlookers gaping as he rides his wakeboard, the
offspring of the surfboard and the water version of the snowboard.
</P>
<P>
   Around large lakes and on rivers where speedboats chalk the
water, wakeboarding is growing quickly, said Michael Reardon, head
of the new wakeboarding department at Sea Sports in Hyannis. ``More
and more people have come in asking for bindings and boards.'' From
winter snowboarders, twitching for a summertime alternative, to
first-timers, wakeboarding is establishing itself as a summer
pastime and a competitive activity.
</P>
<P>
   As in waterskiing, a wakeboarder is towed behind a boat while
holding a length of rope, but the similarity pretty much ends
there. The boarder is towed at 20 to 25 miles an hour (slower than
waterskiing because wakeboards hydroplane easier) about 60 feet
behind the boat. The boarder's feet are in loose toeless boots _ so
he can slip out when he must _ in a skateboard, surfboard, or
snowboard position.
</P>
<P>
   A standard board is 4 feet long and is made of fiberglass,
plastics, and carbons. Because it has neither a front nor a back,
and has fins at both ends, it can be ridden in both directions,
giving rise to dozens of complicated and dynamic tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wakeboards are so much more versatile than water skis,'' said
Reardon. There are front flips, back flips, twists, and spins, and
creative variations on those moves. Many tricks bear the same names
as snowboarding. But instead of half pipes or jumps of
snowboarding, this sport uses the water wake to elevate.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 24, from Exeter, N.H., even has a sponsor, Hyperlite
wakeboards, an industry leader. He was a gymnast and a snowboarder
when he first tested the waters four summers ago. By his second day
on a wakeboard, he said, he was landing flips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wakeboarding is a totally different feeling than
skateboarding, but it's a lot like snowboarding. The biggest
difference is that you're out in the sun in warm water,'' said
Richardson. He said there are fewer injuries, since the water's a
cushion, ``and you don't have to pay $50 each time you go,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, wakeboarders, like downhill and water skiiers, need to be
cautious, particularly as novices. The combinations of wind, water,
and speed can prove tricky. Instruction can help smooth the
learning process.
</P>
<P>
   A recently established water sports school, Above The Glass, in
Centerville, offers wakeboarding lessons. ``There are so many
people who want to do it . . . even adults are trying it, because
waterskiing can get boring,'' said Marc Morin, shop cofounder and
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I'm trying to get my footing on a piece of ice,''
said first-timer Kevin Connolly, 28, on vacation from Chicago,
``but it's more fun than waterskiing.'' Connolly, who was up on the
water after the first pull of the boat, said he intends to switch
over from waterskiing.
</P>
<P>
   The school uses a Mastercraft X-Star, the boat used for the ESPN
X-Games competition that awards the biggest purses and is the most
publicized of wakeboarding tournaments. The boat has a special
wakeboarding pylon, an arched tower that cradles the middle of the
boat and sits 10 feet high, allowing the boarder to snare even more
air. Depending on how much weight's on the boat, there are four
sacks that can be filled to add 1,000 pounds to augment the wake.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's the snowboarding of watersports, wakeboarding so
far has avoided the hog-the-slope image of some hot-shot
snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's appearance may be on the edge _ right eyebrow
pierced, hair dyed red and black, an earring, a tongue ring, a
tattoo of a harlequin on his right shoulder and a personal design
on his left _ but he's a strong athlete with a commitment to his
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance will try anything. He has no fear,'' said Morin,
describing how Richardson goes to great pains, figuratively and
literally, to learn new stunts. Two years ago, Richardson knocked
himself out when he slammed into the water on his back, trying an
Air Raley _ a trick in which his body is fully extended at least 10
feet over the wake in a Superman pose.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is an amateur but would like to become a
professional. Representing New England, he placed sixth last summer
in the advanced division of the International Novice Tournament in
Austin, Texas. He hopes to compete in pro competitions this season.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of wakeboarding, about a dozen years ago, was
essentially a transition beyond ``skurfing,'' which used a short
one-directional surfboard with bindings, towed behind a boat. The
sports's equipment is being improved all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology of the boards has come up to speed, and it's
just a matter of time before people start investing in the sport,''
said Richardson. Wakeboards with bindings range from $300-$1,000.
Lighter boards are deemed superior because they allow for higher
jumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make it an aggressive sport, or a relaxing sport,''
said Richardson. Either way, wakeboarding is carving a niche.
``Hey,'' Morin said, ``it's the 90s at the brink of the millennium.
Wakeboarding is the new wave of style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
