<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SUMMER JOB FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You had to keep reminding yourself that this was not the real
NBA. Coach Larry Bird was wearing shorts and had his bare feet
slipped into loafers. He signed autographs at halftime. Red
Auerbach spent most of the afternoon sitting at the scorer's table.
Players wore uniforms that appeared to be straight off the discount
racks of a local sporting goods store. Rick Pitino sat in the
bleachers and, during one bizarre moment, was approached by an
extremely tall fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me what leagues I should be playing in?'' the
young man asked Pitino. The coach said he didn't know. ``Well,''
the man followed up, ``can you point out some agents in the
crowd?''
</P>
<P>
   That was just the beginning. There was also a German Select Team
forward named Boniface Ndong, a 6-foot-11-inch, 180-pounder who can
pass for a reed stalk anytime he wants. Not to be overshadowed, the
Nets brought 5-4 Shawnta Rogers to the court. If you can believe
this, Rogers actually looks smaller than 5-4 when he's on the
floor. In fact, if I were a coach, I would put 5-3 Muggsy Bogues on
my team _ I say Muggsy towers over Shawnta _ and have him post up
Rogers on each possession.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the opener of the Celtics' eight-team Pro Summer
League at UMass-Boston. This was the place to come if you wanted to
forget about the limiting boundaries of reality. Unless, of course,
you happen to draw your paychecks from the Boston Celtics. People
associated with the Celtics were the only ones who were constantly
reminded of the outside world, even when everything inside was
clearly artificial.
</P>
<P>
   I have many reasons for saying that. Here's one: Pervis Ellison
_ who has played in 39 games since Bill Clinton was reelected in
1996 _ was expected to play. He didn't. He told Pitino that he
wanted to play, but the Coach thought it would be best to rest him.
There were several people in the building who clearly got caught up
in the Fantasy NBA atmosphere at UMass, because many of them
acknowledged aloud that they were here to see Ellison. They also
acknowledged that they were disappointed when the center did not
appear with Wayne Turner, Tony Battie, Walter McCarty, and the rest
of the Celtics against the summer-vacation Wizards. (The Celtics
pounded the makeshift team, 98-77.) Maybe they all know the truth,
which is that if Ellison doesn't play in any of this week's games,
he probably won't play with the Celtics again.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison was not the only reminder that this Summer League world
was false. You want to know the best player of the day? Austin
Croshere. He dropped 30 points and had 11 rebounds against the
German team which, by the way, isn't loaded with a lot of Germans.
The only Pacer who looked nearly as impressive was Al Harrington.
Keep in mind that Harrington did not make the Pacers' playoff
roster and that Croshere played only a few more minutes than you
did throughout the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrington made some moves Monday that were breathtaking.
You wanted to lean back on the wooden bleachers here, gaze at the
quaint overhead banners that read ``Little East,'' and smile about
the artistry of basketball. But if you were Pitino and tried that,
there was always a question that brought everything back to real
time.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Ron Mercer situation. ``Based on his comments,'' Pitino
said with a laugh, ``we're not close (to signing him).'' Mercer
said the Celtics' offer to him was drastically below what he
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget about the Greg Minor story. There are those in the
organization who fear that the guard's career is over. He suffered
a severe hip injury late in the season in Miami. He is walking with
a cane now. Pitino said you usually don't see injuries like Minor's
unless you are looking at a car wreck or a pileup on a football
field.
</P>
<P>
   And, before we go back to that quirky, unrealistic NBA, there is
also the Dwayne Schintzius story. Supposedly, the team can't find
the 7-2 center. The Celtics wanted him to participate in the Summer
League. His contract is guaranteed until Dec. 31, so one team
official cracked, ``I hope he gets his money protected from Y2K
before he leaves town.''
</P>
<P>
   The fake NBA seemed to be much more fun than the real one. There
are always complaints about fans not being into the game, but
anyone who watched Turner couldn't say that. Turner is from Mission
Hill, so he had several of his friends and admirers behind the
Celtics bench. They cheered when he dribbled. They cheered when he
passed. He made a nice floater near the end of the first half and
they high-fived each other. Once, Frank King threw a low pass to
Turner that went off his leg and out of bounds. Wayne's World
wanted it to be known that their man was not responsible for the
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   There were other refreshing stories. If you don't like the
Knicks, you can be assured that they did not make a good decision
by drafting French center Frederic Weis (he can't play). If you
like underdogs, you will enjoy hearing that Celtic camper Adrian
Griffin most likely will be signed by the team in early August. If
you like to see coaches laugh, you would have loved to see Bird
giggling at Jason Miskiri when the guard asked out of the game.
Miskiri had been hot when he raised his hand toward the bench. Bird
looked at him, laughing, and said, ``You want to come out NOW?''
</P>
<P>
   No way this was the NBA of tough injuries, base-year
compensation, trading deadlines, and free agent signing periods. It
was light. It was loose. It was fun. But, as the Celtics know, this
camp lasts only a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-US-ARENA-BOS &LR;      07-27 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-ARENA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MEN PLAY ARENA FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ The Mexican with the microphone wants to
know what the US men's soccer team learned from watching the US
women win the World Cup. Bruce Arena gives him the amused stare he
uses with people who ask him silly questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You actually think we learned something from watching the US
women?'' the US men's coach says. ``We didn't learn anything. Their
accomplishment was tremendous, but it doesn't apply to our sport.
In our country, we have an expression: It's like comparing apples
and oranges.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Babes of Summer beat the Chinese and put
themselves on magazine covers, Arena has been talking to people who
don't know one orchard from another. ``There are American
journalists who think Mia Hamm could play for our team,'' Arena
says, shaking his head. ``Our women couldn't beat our under-16 boys
team. If you have to explain that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   That's a typical Arena assessment _ blunt and realistic. His men
may be 5-1-1 this year with shutouts over Germany and Argentina but
it'll be a year, he says, before they're a good national team. The
US federation's Project 2010 is a great idea, he says, but anyone
who thinks the Americans can win the World Cup by then is dreaming.
And winning the FIFA Confederations Cup here against the likes of
Brazil and Mexico would be nice, he says, but it doesn't mean the
Yanks will qualify for the next Mondial in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Arena watched them go three-and-out (with the worst goal
differential in the 32-team field) at last summer's World Cup in
France. He knows exactly what's in his talent pool because most of
the players competed for or against him in Major League Soccer or
on the 1996 Olympic team that he coached. And he knows what's a
realistic goal _ to create a team that's competitive with the
Mexicans and that doesn't have to go down to the wire to make it to
the Mondial.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to happen overnight and Arena knows it. That's
why he insisted on a contract that takes him all the way through
the 2002 Cup (unlike predecessor Steve Sampson's, which only went
until the end of qualifying). ``I made that clear from Day 1,''
Arena says.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be rebuilding from Ground Zero, but his roster is
decidedly imbalanced between gray and green. The team Arena put on
the field against New Zealand Saturday had Cobi Jones (116
international caps), Jeff Agoos (93), and John Harkes (87) at one
end and Eddie Lewis (9), Carlos Llamosa (4), and Richie Williams
(4) at the other.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it's going to be for the next year and more, as
Arena tries to win and build at the same time. Nothing unusual
there, he shrugs. It's the same for the Brazilians, the Germans,
and everyone else in the post-Cup year.
</P>
<P>
   So far Arena has managed to do both, while moving past the
bitterness and finger-pointing that marked the Yanks' abrupt and
sour seance in France. ``It's night and day here right now,'' says
former captain John Harkes, whom Sampson dropped from the squad
before the Cup but whom Arena asked back for this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   An atmospheric change was inevitable once Sampson resigned. And
the unhappiest people on the Cup squad _ Tab Ramos, Alexi Lalas,
Eric Wynalda, Preki Radosavljevic _ haven't played this year and
may not again. But much of the change, players say, is due to Arena
and his simple, straightforward approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just his common sense with things,'' says Harkes, who
played for Arena at both the University of Virginia and D.C.
United. ``He understands. He knows what players are like.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena was a player himself, a keeper at Cornell (he blanked
Harvard in the 1972 NCAA quarterfinals) who earned one cap (against
Israel) for the US team and played professionally in the American
Soccer League. As coach, he won five NCAA titles in 18 years at
Virginia, won two MLS crowns in his first two years with D.C.
United, and directed the 1996 Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   While Arena's credentials are beyond reproach, what's won over
his players is his no-nonsense style. No Mickey Mouse, no mind
games. ``He tells you exactly where you stand,'' says Agoos, who
also played for Arena at both Virginia and D.C. United. ``If you're
the No. 1 star or a guy on the bench, he'll tell you the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena is direct and demanding, but he's also approachable and
flexible. ``He doesn't micromanage things the way a lot of coaches
do,'' says Agoos. ``He allows you to express yourself freely within
a system. He allows you to be the player you are _ as long as you
get the results.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Arena was at Virginia, where he was hired as head
soccer and assistant lacrosse coach (he'd been an All-American at
Cornell) in 1978. Lacrosse was the bigger sport at Charlottesville
then, but soccer offered the better career opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious that my wait for the head lacrosse job
would be longer,'' Arena says. ``Jim Adams wasn't going to retire
anytime soon and the soccer program was growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena brought it to full flower, making the NCAA tournament 15
straight times, winning four straight titles in the '90s and
posting a better winning percentage (.808) than UCLA basketball
coach John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought he was a professional coaching college
ball,'' says Agoos, who served as Arena's assistant for a year at
Virginia. ``He always demanded the best from us. He put us in an
environment, especially in practice, where it was competitive,
where we challenged each other every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena could have stayed at Virginia forever. ``I could have been
comfortable there,'' he says. ``But once the pro league began . . .
'' His players knew he would leave. ``He just had to wait for his
time to come,'' says Harkes.
</P>
<P>
   Though MLS was far from a sure thing (``That was an issue.''),
Arena relished the challenge, and coaching D.C. United allowed him
to keep living in Virginia with his wife and teenage son. And
coaching pros, Arena realized over time, was no different than
coaching amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I probably didn't have the confidence to be
as demanding of them as I should have been,'' he concedes. ``But
the expectations of what they need to do have to be there. Maybe I
gave them too much credit because they were professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Players are players, Arena concluded. In 1996, he coached both
pros and amateurs, directing both D.C. United and the Olympic team.
That combination of credentials is what put Arena at the top of the
domestic candidate list when Sampson resigned at the end of the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Arena didn't figure he'd get the job. ``I thought they
would hire a foreigner,'' he says. But the top foreigners said no
and the landscape changed when federation president Alan
Rothenberg's term expired last August and Dr. S. Robert ``Doctor
Bob'' Contiguglia took over. ``If the decision wasn't left entirely
to Dr. Contiguglia,'' Arena says, ``I wouldn't have been hired.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena had no illusions about what he was inheriting. He knew the
Americans weren't the worst team at the World Cup, but he won't
argue that three-and-out wasn't a huge comedown. ``Not to walk out
of there without a point was disappointing,'' Arena says. ``And
they probably should have had three.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that advancing from a group that included Germany and
Yugoslavia was any gimme. And better teams than the US went
three-and-out, too. ``Spain didn't get out of the first round,''
Arena observes. ``They have the second-toughest pro league behind
Italy, they have incredible talent and organization. But they went
home and we went home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish can't tell you they'll win the Cup in 2010 and
neither can the Americans. ``I don't think that's realistic,'' says
Arena. ``That's typical of the way people who have had authority
with US Soccer think. It's a great marketing concept, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans struggled to even qualify for the Cup in both 1990
and 1998. They have an international player pool of 50, tops. They
have beaten Brazil once in nearly 70 years (they get another chance
here Wednesday night) and have never won in Mexico. 2010 is a
million years from now. Arena is more concerned with 2000, when
regional qualifying begins for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   He'll learn something useful here this week, he says, but there
was nothing _ as in nada _ to learn from watching the Babes of
Summer. They play in an orange grove. Bruce Arena only deals in
apples.
</P>
</TEXT>
