<HEADLINE>
A SERENE SPOT ON A BUSY BOSTON STREET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the hustle and bustle of trendy Newbury Street stands a
tranquil and timeless place, the Jewel of Newbury Boutique Hotel &AMP;
Restaurant, filled with both antiques and Old World charm.
</P>
<P>
   The new-yet-old Boston hotel consists of eight rooms/suites on
three floors of a circa 1882 brownstone at 254 Newbury St. As we
learned during a tour, each room has its own distinctive look,
thanks to antiques, artifacts, and crafts from Europe and North
Africa. All baths have been modernized, and most have marble or
brass fittings. And despite the aura of times past, all rooms have
telephones and cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Two public rooms on the first floor are for lounging and dining.
They are replete with period furnishings, mainly French Empire, and
are complemented by clocks, cut glass, porcelain, gilded mirrors,
antique oils, and Oriental rugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewel of Newbury Restaurant, meanwhile, is on the garden
level and can accommodate up to 44 diners. Those guests find
themselves surrounded by stained glass, tiled pictures,
brass-covered sconces, and fine china and crystal. The constantly
changing cuisine, served at small marble tables, is North
African-inspired and gently flavored with imported spices. Lamb and
couscous are popular, as are an exotic variety of soups, salads,
breads, and desserts. American and European wines are served; so
are regional coffees and teas, including hot mint tea.
</P>
<P>
   Proprietor and owner is the refreshingly candid Mouldi Sayeh,
who spent five years and a lot of money restoring the building and
creating the restaurant and hotel. Both reflect his total
involvement and philosophy that guests are family. Prices range
from $225 for a room with a bath to $2,000 for a four-bedroom
suite. Most restaurant entrees are $15-$28. For more information,
call 617-536-5523, fax 617-424-8798, or visit www.jewelboston.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: France is the world's top tourist destination, with
70 million international arrivals in 1998. But which country came
in second last year? And third? (Answers at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The JAL Newsletter reports that a hot new fast-food
chain in China is called Baked Pig Face. The specialty is whole
pig's head. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Baltimore forbids tossing bales of hay from a
second-story window within the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``Grace . . . graceful . . . graciousness'' _
frequently used words in messages accompanying flowers left at the
Kennedy Library in Dorchester in memory of John F. Kennedy Jr. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Helping handful: First, there was an honor: The Connecticut-based
National Theatre of the Deaf was chosen to represent the United
States at the 13th World Congress of the World Federation of the
Deaf in Brisbane, Australia. But then there was a problem: How were
they going to pay for the trip? And now there is a solution: with
travelers' gifts of leftover foreign currency. If you have any
zloty, lira, yen, pesos, drachmas, etc., send your notes and coins
to The National Theatre of the Deaf, 5 West Main St., Chester,
Conn. 06412. A total of $10,000 is needed for the five actors (both
deaf and hearing) and one interpreter. And although the Congress is
July 25-31, any money collected will be used after the trip to pay
the bills for plane tickets and other expenses. (We've sent along
some Irish punts, Spanish pesetas, and Korean won ourselves.) For
more information, call 800-300-5179, 860-526-4971 (both voice) or
860-526-4974 (tty), or e-mail bookNTD(at)aol.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bad idea: Belgium once tried to use cats to deliver mail, but
discovered something all feline owners know: You can't tell a cat
what to do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Update: The two newest exhibits at Mystic Aquarium in Mystic,
Conn., are up and running . . . or, in one case, swimming. ``The
Alaskan Coast'' is a one-acre outdoor beluga whale exhibit, and the
Institute for Explorations's Challenge of the Deep is a journey
into the world of deep-ocean science and exploration. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rooms galore: Las Vegas, which keeps adding hotels and casinos, now
has more than 113,000 guest rooms. By New Year's Eve, there will be
122,000 rooms. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: Here's one way to keep the kids quiet during your
flight: Tell them that the quietest one gets to land the plane!
(With thanks to www.flycontinental.com/travel/children.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Walt Gately of Medfield adds this coda to our recent
discussion of the song ``Route 66'': ``Now it's Interstate 44 and
doesn't rhyme with much of anything.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
It ain't cheap: A pound of Puerto Rico's coffee costs $55 in
Japan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? According to the World Tourism Organization,
Spain had the second-highest number of visitors (47.7 million) in
1998, and the United States was a close third (47.1 million). &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
