<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-SHOPS-ART-BOS &LR;      07-27 1823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-SHOPS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING OF GUNS USED FOR CRIME GIVES HOPE OF A CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Marcus Hawkins armed himself with a .44 caliber
handgun and went looking for money and trouble.
</P>
<P>
   First he broke into a north side apartment and abducted a woman
and her 17-month-old son. He raped the woman, then drove off with
the boy. But he soon ran out of gas, so he abandoned the crying
toddler and tried to rob a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   A clerk finally stopped Hawkins by shooting him in the leg.
Hawkins is now serving a 124-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins's 1996 case would be just an ugly criminal footnote if
not for one key detail: The way Hawkins obtained his gun fits an
emerging pattern that challenges conventional wisdom about the
source of guns used in crimes. And that, in turn, has raised hopes
among criminal justice specialists that cracking down on criminal
gun play is a realistic goal.
</P>
<P>
   The .44 caliber handgun Hawkins used wasn't stolen; it was sold
to Hawkins by a small-time trafficker named Lawrence Shikes, who
had bought it legally from a neighborhood gun store.
</P>
<P>
   And not just any gun store. It was Badger Guns and Ammo Inc, a
squat, fortress-like building on the edge of a West Milwaukee that
is, several studies reveal, the nation's leading source of guns
traced to crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, 495 crime guns were traced to Badger, or an
average of more than one per day. The next highest was 349 from an
Ohio gun store, according to data compiled by the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. The ATF data did not name the
stores, but law enforcement authorities, researchers and others
familiar with the data confirmed Badger was No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Badger was hardly alone. Rather, it was tops among a
relatively small number of federally licensed firearms dealers that
are the source of a disproportionate number of guns traced to
crimes, according to several yet-to-be released studies.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, just 1 percent of the nation's federally licensed
firearms dealers were responsible for 45 percent of the guns traced
to crimes last year, according to an analysis of ATF data performed
by the staff of Senator Charles E. Schumer, a New York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   A separate study by Northeastern University researcher Glenn
Pierce, working under contract to ATF, found that half the guns
used in crimes in 1996 and 1997 came from just 389 federally
licensed firearms dealers, or less than one-half of 1 percent of
the 104,855 dealers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the studies also found that almost half of all
crime guns were used for an illegal act within 50 miles, and within
three years, of their original sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think crime guns were all stolen. They're not. We
used to think there was basically no firearms trafficking. In fact
there's a lot of firearms trafficking. We used to think that to the
extent there was firearms trafficking it was all interstate gun
running. In fact, most of it seems to be local and close to home,''
said David Kennedy, a senior researcher at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government who directs the Boston Gun Project.
</P>
<P>
   This shifting view of the sources of weapons used in crimes is
also forcing reconsideration of the strategies now used to
interrupt the illicit trade that provides firearms to criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think there was such an ocean of guns out there
that there wasn't anything powerful that could be done to try to
limit criminal access,'' Kennedy said. ``In fact, the traced
studies and a number of other sources of information have been
showing that there are major gun sources and big traffickers, and
you can find them and shut them down.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the biggest problem is rogue dealers
or middlemen who act as traffickers. Regardless, the studies'
conclusions are prompting new thinking on firearms regulations
regarding gun dealers and ``straw purchasers,'' legal buyers who
sell weapons to people barred from owning guns. It also is
prompting an increasing number of cities, including Badger's home
city of Milwaukee, to follow an example set by Boston and trace all
firearms that police come across, regardless of whether the guns
were used in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer recently introduced legislation to push the issue a step
further. His bill would would allow ATF agents unlimited visits to
any gun store with more than 25 guns traced to crimes in the
previous year. Currently, ATF agents not investigating specific
criminal activity can make just one such visit per year without a
warrant. The change proposed by Schumer would have affected 399 gun
dealers nationwide last year, said Jim Kessler, Schumer's policy
director.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's bill also would give ATF authority to suspend the
licenses of gun dealers. ``Now they can pretty much only revoke a
license, which they rarely do,'' said Kessler. ``With suspensions,
they could take quick action against a rogue dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would specifically outlaw straw purchases of guns,
in part by requiring that any private resale of a firearm within
six months of its original purchase be preceded by a background
check of the new buyer. The law, which would allow prosecutors to
go after anyone who made such a sale without the background checks,
is much less cumbersome than current law. As it now stands,
prosecutors must prove a gun buyer intended to resell the gun
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby has firmly opposed Schumer's bill, arguing that
existing laws are sufficient to punish straw purchasers, gun
traffickers, and lax gun dealers. Proponents of gun owners' rights
said the problem is that federal prosecutions of gun crimes have
dropped sharply in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they started prosecuting those cases fully and
unflinchingly, the word would get out in the criminal community
that providing a firearm to a prohibited person isn't worth the
trouble,'' said Bill Powers, director of public affairs for the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   A clearer sense of how the system works, and the difficulty of
intercepting illegal sales, begins to emerge from a visit to
Badger, which proudly bills itself as Wisconsin's largest handgun
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Located next to an auto salvage business and across the street
from a huge grain elevator, the store still looks appropriate for
its previous use as an aluminum can-recycling center. The only
outward signs that something has changed are the barred windows and
the huge concrete blocks designed to stop thieves from driving a
truck through a wall to get at the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Inside is a huge assortment of weaponry, ammunition, and
paraphernalia, from cleaning fluids to holsters to knives and
pepper spray. High on the walls are long guns, mostly hunting
rifles and military-style weapons, alongside several stuffed animal
heads and an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   A sign near the door warns, ``No loaded guns in this store!''
But on another wall is a wooden plaque, carved with a large
revolver and the words: ``We don't dial 911.''
</P>
<P>
   Handguns are kept in glass cases at the front counter, with
prices as low as $149.99 for a .22 caliber handgun. Until recently,
the store sold several models of $99.99 handguns, but pulled them
from the shelves in the wake of criticism from antigun activists.
Still, a dozen different handguns have price tags of under $200,
though others cost upwards of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old store is owned by brothers Mick and Curt
Beatovic, 53 and 44 years old respectively, and their childhood
friend Wally Allan, 45, all lifelong gun enthusiasts who Allen says
consider themselves ``The three banditos.'' Mick Beatovic
interrupts him to ask of a reporter: ``Make that the three amigos,
OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Since opening for business they have sold more than 40,000 guns,
according to records they provided.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the owners tell it, they are deeply disturbed by, but
ultimately not responsible for, their No. 1 ranking on traced crime
guns. They blamed it on several factors, including their location
as the closest gun shop to Milwaukee's central city; a relative
absence of competition; and ``easy access'' from the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Mick Beatovic said they also are being unfairly singled out
because they keep such good records and cooperate so fully with
authorities that it makes it easier to trace guns to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Allan said there are other factors, as well. He pointed to four
young black men looking at handguns. ``The whole shop is full of
black people. What happens when these guys and these guns leave the
store we can't control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mick Beatovic said the store does all it can to prevent straw
purchasers, turning away three to five potential buyers a day.
While a reporter was in the store, he turned away Lavonda Taylor
and her 18-year-old son, Lee Andrew Jones, when an employee
suspected the gun was for Jones. She complained that she was
seeking a gun for protection, but acknowledged her son knew much
more about firearms than she did.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mick Beatovic said, he suspects one or two straw buyers
``slip through'' every day.
</P>
<P>
   Local ATF agents confirmed that they have a good relationship
with Badger's owners and do not believe they purposely sell guns to
criminals. ``They are as responsible as they can possibly be in the
business they are in,'' said Mark Murray, the agent in charge of
the ATF office in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Murray agreed with NRA officials and Badger's owners that a
major problem is too few prosecutions of straw buyers. ``They're
putting firearms in the community and causing death and destruction
the same way a dope dealer is, and in many cases they're not being
looked at that way,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   But Milwaukee's mayor, John O. Norquist, said it is wrong to
absolve Badger's owners of responsibility. The city's murder rate
is up this year, with 69 so far this year, versus 53 at the same
point in 1998. Most involved firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they sell to criminals, it's creating a greater likelihood
of murder, robbery, rape, and they shouldn't be able to do that
with impunity.'' Norquist said. He said he is powerless to act,
however, because the Wisconsin Legislature has barred local
communities from regulating gun shops.
</P>
<P>
   Badger's owners said they are troubled by stories about guns
sold by their store being used by criminals such as Hawkins. But
they make no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I think about that, but I also think of the times I sold
guns to people and they used them to protect their families,'' Mick
Beatovic said. ``I can't tell what's in people's hearts, but I know
for a fact that a gun will be used more times for good than it will
be to hurt someone. The way I see it, an honest person ought to be
able to have a gun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
