<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREEN-BULLET-BOS &LR;      07-27 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-BULLET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY TESTING A SAFER AMMUNITION FOR ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Human armies have been mowing each other down with lead bullets
for 600 years _ and the mayhem goes beyond the dead and maimed.
</P>
<P>
   After all, lead is harmful to the environment. It contaminates
soil and water. It makes birds and fish sick.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the US Army with a planet-friendly projectile for the
next millennium _ the ``green bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ammunition, just starting to go into experimental
production, rips flesh and bone as efficiently as old-fashioned
rounds. But the slugs are made of a tungsten alloy, not lead, and
pose little ecological hazard.
</P>
<P>
   There's irony here, lots, as munitions scientists redefine the
notion of a ``clean kill.'' But experts say creating a bullet that
is both harmless and deadly represents a vital military mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lead pollution is just a major, major problem on the firing
range,'' said Charles Cutshaw, small arms specialist and editor of
Jane's Ammunition Handbook. ``Lead dust is as bad for humans as it
is for wildlife. So coming up with `nontoxic' ammunition is an
urgent matter, odd as it may sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon already faces a $9 billion cleanup bill for
training sites dangerously polluted by lead. So the $12 million
committed to the green ammo project is a small price _ and success
appears at hand.
</P>
<P>
   According to Myra Hess, spokeswoman for the Army's Armament
Research, Development and Engineering Center at the Picatinny
Arsenal in New Jersey, the new projectile is ``an environmentally
friendly and safer bullet with the same performance, more accuracy,
and same lethality as its lead counterpart.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the slugs should still wreak bloody havoc on the
battlefield. But when the fighting stops, the killing grounds will
be safe for birds, bunnies, and butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   But making war less dirty is just part of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Most military bullets are fired in training, not combat. The US
Army pops off 300 million to 400 million rounds a year; ``live
fire'' practice keeps troops ready for combat.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, inspectors from the Environmental
Protection Agency pack at least as much punch on the home front as
the Pentagon's brass. Under fire from regulators, the military has
been forced to shut down hundreds of firing ranges at bases across
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, for example, the EPA halted all live fire
training at the Massachusetts Military Reservation amid warnings
that lead from rifle and artillery ranges was leaching into Cape
Cod's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that Army commanders are putting a new twist
on an age-old marching order: ``Get the lead out!''
</P>
<P>
   Get the xylene, barium nitrate, methyl chloroform, and other
earth-harming substances out, too. A single military small arms
cartridge contains 16 toxins in the bullet, primer, and gunpowder
propellant, according to military scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to have a completely lead-free cartridge,
including primer, by 2003 that will out-perform the standard
round,'' Wade Bunting, technical executive for the green ammo
project, told the Picatinny Arsenal newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Said Arthur Pizza, senior project engineer: ``We're making
history. Soldiers have been using lead bullets since the 1400s _
this is a significant change.''
</P>
<P>
   The changeover echoes a trend in shooting sports. Waterfowl
hunters have already converted from lead shotgun pellets to
ammunition made of steel, bismuth, or tungsten polymer, according
to Lawrence Ference, director of research for the Connecticut-based
National Shooting Sports Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   That followed the discovery that the billions of lead pellets _
fired by generations of hunters _ embedded in the mud of wintering
grounds from the Gulf of Mexico to New England were poisoning ducks
and geese. Swallowed lead is absorbed by animal tissue, and can
gradually build to lethal levels.
</P>
<P>
   On the military front, the first million green bullets are
already rattling off production lines after shooting tests at an
unsullied tundra test range 100 miles from Nome, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year or two, production should shoot to 200 million
bullets a year, and eventually the cleaner 5.56 mm rounds _ a
tungsten-tin core under a thin coating of copper _ will be the only
ammunition issued for the M-16 rifle, at least for training.
</P>
<P>
   The M-16 is the basic infantry weapon for US soldiers and is
standard issue for the ground forces of about 30 other countries,
including Canada, Israel, and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Other Western nations are expected to follow the United States
in converting their weapons to green ammo. Some, including Germany,
are already developing their own non-polluting rounds.
</P>
<P>
   For tungsten producers, the switch to the dense, white metal
represents a potential bonanza. If all goes as planned, demand from
the US military alone could give a 10 percent boost to worldwide
tungsten sales and production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that results in increased use of tungsten is
obviously going to be rather heartening for us,'' says Michael
Maby, general secretary of the London-based International Tungsten
Industry Association. ``It's good news.''
</P>
<P>
   It also may prove a last laugh for the hard-pressed industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the US military abandoned plans to use tungsten to
create a new generation of armor-piercing shells, mainly because
the metal was too expensive. Instead, weapons makers turned to
``depleted uranium,'' dealing a serious blow to tungsten producers.
</P>
<P>
   But uranium shells turn out to be hazardous not just to the
enemy but to the earth. According to environmental groups, the
shells released contaminants into air and soil during the Persian
Gulf War and, most recently, in the air campaign against Serbia,
where depleted-uranium shells were fired by A-10 Warthog jets and
other NATO aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of tungsten say the metal makes for a projectile that
does a dandy job of killing people but causes no ecological harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swans or geese that ingest lead shot often sicken and die,''
said Maby. ``But if they swallow tungsten, it just goes in one end
and out the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
