<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-WINDFALL-ART-     07-27 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-WINDFALL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC FOCUSES ON KOSOVARS, BUT DONATIONS AID OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RYAN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government in his home country wanted Charles Baadom dead
simply because of his ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Baadom's ethnic tribal group has been persecuted for years by
its government. Its land has been polluted, its leader hanged.
</P>
<P>
   So Baadom fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pack, I just ran,'' said Baadom, 27, who arrived in
Boston on June 10 with his wife, Blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly 75,000 others who arrived in the United States in
the last year, the Baadoms are refugees _ immigrants that the US
government has determined are fleeing persecution and cannot return
home safely.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the recent crisis in Kosovo and the stories of the
horrors committed there, the word ``refugee'' has evoked among many
Americans images of ethnic Albanians running from burning homes and
mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   But Baadom, an Ogoni tribesman from Nigeria, is not a Kosovar,
and neither are the overwhelming majority of refugees arriving in
the United States this year, most of whom are struggling to build
new lives with little government or private assistance.
</P>
<P>
   For these refugees, the Kosovo crisis, and the intense media
scrutiny that prompted the flood of donations to relief groups,
represents an unexpected windfall, paying for such necessities as
food, blankets, basic furniture, rental assistance and other
essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, for some refugees and their sponsors, the intense
focus on the Kosovars and the millions of dollars that have poured
into relief agencies helping them raise a fundamental question:
What pulls at America's heartstrings?
</P>
<P>
   One answer, refugee workers say, is a narrow view of the world
based on a lack of understanding of other cultures, especially
people coming from impoverished, developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the daily televised images of tired, frightened
Kosovars fleeing the onslaught of Serb forces was a heartbreaking
sight and made it clear that the world had to respond.
</P>
<P>
   But while there may be no parallel deluge of televised images,
terrified, weary refugees like Baadom have been streaming out of
several African and other nations for several years.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Institute of Boston, which has been
resettling refugees for 75 years, many of the former refugees who
work for the agency say they are happy for the Kosovars, but
perplexed by the intense attention they have received.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all scratching their heads bewildered,'' said Westy
Egmont, executive director of the International Institute. ``I
don't think there is an easy explanation for why we've become
riveted to one population and not to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Some refugee aid workers suggest it may be easier for white
Americans of European ancestry to identify with the white, European
Kosovars than with refugees from places such as rural Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for many middle-class Americans to relate to the
Kosovars who were forced out of their apartments and were dressed
well, had their televisions, and their computers,'' said Ralston H.
Deffenbaugh Jr., national president of Lutheran Immigration and
Refugee Services, one of the nine national agencies that resettles
refugees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The massive coverage of the war in Kosovo and the poignant
pictures of Kosovars arriving in refugee camps exposed Americans to
a stark and simple picture of the confict, refugee advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for the American public to see who the good guys are
and who the bad guys are,'' said Rita Kantarowski, director of the
International Rescue Committee in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Many conflicts in places such as Africa have not received nearly
the same attention, in part because they have not been as easy for
Americans to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare American who knows where Somalia is and who can
identify with the more rural developing nations,'' Egmont said.
``You have the unknown, race, and educational levels all working to
act as obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains, however, aid workers say, that refugees are
more similar than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing they all have in common is they've lost their place
in the world,'' said Claire Carroll, the director of refugee and
immigration services for Catholic Charities of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   According to many national and local directors of resettlement
agencies, refugees from Kosovo are receiving the most attention by
Americans since the boat people of southeast Asia, who started
arriving here in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, nearly 164,000 Southeast Asian refugees _ mostly
Vietnamese _ arrived in America. The number of Vietnamese refugees
to the United States remained above 10,000 through 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, about 10,500 Kosovars have arrived in the United
States; nearly 400 have settled in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of help for the Kosovars has been overwhelming,
aid agencies say.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Catholic Charities, the International Institute of
Boston, and the International Rescue Committee have been flooded
with money, furniture, and offers of housing for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, Catholic Charities of Boston has raised nearly
$200,000 in aid just for Kosovo refugees. It was the first time the
agency established a fund specifically for one refugee group.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the huge public response to the plight of the
Kosovars has generated unexpected windfalls for other refugees,
according to aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   For his first three weeks in the United States, Baadom and his
pregnant wife were able to share a Cambridge apartment with a
Kosovar refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have called local agencies wanting to help the
Kosovars, but after being told there was enough aid flowing to
those refugees, donors have ended up giving money, housing, and
furniture to aid other newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say, `And by the way there are other refugees' and they
say, `Oh, OK, we want to help all refugees,' '' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The extra largesse is indirectly helping refugees like Baadom,
who is unemployed and living in a rental apartment that Catholic
Charities helps pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Many agencies are trying to use the current fixation on the
Kosovars to educate the public about challenges all refugees face.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost their homes, their profession, and, for a large
part, their identities,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long-term story,'' Egmont added. ``It's not a flash in
the pan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCUMCISE-NOCUT-2ND &LR;      07-27 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUMCISE-NOCUT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... or doctors.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most controversial aspects of circumcision is that it
is often performed without the use of an analgesic to lessen the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only procedure done that involves a scalpel
cutting skin that is done routinely without analgesia,'' said Dr.
Lisa Stellwagen, a pediatrician at Massachusetts General Hospital
who said she always uses pain relief. ``For decades, nurses have
had to hold down these screaming babies, and it's a horrible
experience . . . There's really no excuse for not numbing up the
baby anymore. The technology has been around for 20 years and is
exceedingly safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some obstetricians argued that there is also pain
associated with giving a needle, most agreed that pain relief
should be a no-brainer. ``I was personally embarrassed,'' said
Acker, who began using analgesia after watching a demonstration
last year by Stellwagen. ``The difference is night and day.''
</P>
<P>
   Brigham and Women's Hospital now says that nine out of 10
circumcisions are performed with analgesia. But other hospitals are
slower to change. Last year at Newton-Wellesley Hospital, the
majority of circumcisions were performed without analgesia. Today,
that number has dropped to half, said Dr. Thomas Beatty, chief of
obstetrics and gynocology.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stellwagen has performed about 3,000 circumcisions, all
using analgesia, she is against the practice. ``I think it's not
necessary,'' she said. ``It's cosmetic. If parents ask me if I
think it's necessary, I often try to talk them out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, Stellwagen scheduled a circumcision for an
11-day-old boy. The father smiles broadly and tells her he wants
his son to look like him, a common reason for circumcision. ``It's
that Dad thing, that locker room thing,'' Stellwagen says after the
parents have left the room. The parents are not invited to the
procedure but can attend if they insist. Most don't.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Alexa Laurent places the baby on a plastic device called a
Circumstraint. He begins to cry when his legs are strapped down.
Laurent gives the baby a sugar-coated pacifier to calm him and
holds his arms. ``Babies don't like to be restrained,'' Stellwagen
says.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing gloves, Stellwagen gives the baby a series of four
injections around the base of the penis. The baby cries again and
there is a little blood. Stellwagen waits five minutes and begins
separating the foreskin. The whole procedure takes four minutes
during which the baby cries, but there is no blood-curdling scream.
``He feels a little of that,'' Stellwagen says. A little blood is
wiped away, the baby is hugged, wrapped, and returned to the
parents.
</P>
<P>
   At Massachusetts General, a group of doctors and nurses on break
who were polled about circumcision are overwhelmingly opposed to
it. The nurses charge that some doctors do not take the time to
discuss circumcision with parents. ``For the great majority of
Americans, circumcision is taken for granted,'' said Dr. Marvin
Wang, a pediatrician at the hospital. ``I don't know what this bond
is that parents feel the need for the son to look like his
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think circumcision rates would tumble if parents had to
pay for the procedure. ``It'll change when the insurance companies
don't cover it anymore,'' said one nurse. In Britain that is
exactly what happened. Once insurance stopped covering routine
circumcisions in 1948, rates fell to below 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Complication rates of circumcision are rare, but some procedures
have to be redone. ``I've heard circumcision redo rates as high as
10 pecent. Parents aren't aware of that,'' Stellwagen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly disagree with the procedure. I think it's totally
unnecessary,'' said Jane Burleson, a registered nurse at Mass.
General. ``It's a big decision to make for someone who has no say
in the matter. Would you make a choice to have it medically done
unless there was a real compelling medical reason to do it? Why is
it OK to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, some nurses have come together against circumcision.
``Why would you cut a healthy functional body part from somebody
when you haven't got their consent? It's genital mutilation,'' said
Mary Conat, a registered nurse and cofounder of Nurses for the
Rights of the Child, a Santa Fe advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights organizations do not see it as an issue.
``Amnesty International doesn't consider ordinary circumcision a
human rights issue,'' said Joshua Rubenstein, northeast regional
director of Amnesty International USA. ``There's no comparison to
female genital mutilation. It's not castration. Should I be
arrested for torture because I had a bris in my living room under
Jewish law using a topical anesthesia?''
</P>
<P>
   Jews and Muslims believe in circumcision, although Muslims
circumcise later in childhood. Jews believe it is part of the
sacred pact between Abraham and God to be performed by a specially
trained ``mohel'' on the eighth day after birth. Usually the mohel
uses a local analgesia cream or a wine-soaked cloth for the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Earliest records show that circumcision began in Egypt about
4,500 years ago. It became popular in the United States in the late
19th century when doctors thought it would discourage masturbation.
After World War II the procedure was sometimes automatically done
without a consent form after birth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition to what some call the barbarism of the practice
and its dubious medical benefit, many are questioning circumcision
on the grounds that it can make sex less enjoyable for the male.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a country of males who don't get to choose whether
they want their primary erogenous tissue,'' said Dr. Christopher
Cold, a clinical pathologist from Wisconsin. ``It's insane. You're
taking part of the sex organ and removing it. There's nerve endings
there. A man with a complete penis has more erogenous sensations.
The normal response is they would have a greater sex life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cold acknowledged that the debate on the sexual effects of
circumcision obscures the more fundamental issue of whether the
practice should be carried out at all. ``Do we automatically lump
off a little girl's breast as a protective measure because 47,000
women die each year of breast cancer? Do we pull out all the teeth
and say now you can never get a cavity?''
</P>
<P>
   Burleson said she now regrets that her son was circumcised. ``I
feel very badly about it,'' she said. ``I was clearly uninformed.
At 4 years old, my son announced from the back seat of the car that
he remembers when they cut his penis. I felt terrible. If I had the
choice to make again I wouldn't do that, even if my husband said
yes. He wouldn't have any say in the matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
