<SLUG> BC-TRAGIC-TWINS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS' SPECIAL BOND: DOUBLE TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. _ In his last days, before darkness and
disappointment would finally overpower him, Mark Fitzpatrick made a
mortal promise that he would not keep.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months out of the Army, Fitzpatrick was back home,
training to be an emergency medical technician, and feeling
melancholy about old friends who now seemed mere acquaintances. He
still deeply missed his identical twin brother, Daren, his best
friend and soul mate, who had shot himself to death at his boyhood
home two years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my twin were here, it wouldn't have been so hard because we
would have had each other,'' Mark Fitzpatrick wrote in a college
paper last fall. ``When you're a twin, you're not used to being
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daren was gone. And Mark, 22, was given to dark moods,
introspection that friends and family traced to Daren's suicide at
age 20 and, even further back, to a fatal car crash in 1993. Mark
had been driving, and three people _ two passengers and the driver
of another car _ were killed. Daren, who was a passenger in the
car, was left perilously close to death.
</P>
<P>
   During one of Mark's stormy moods last spring, Amy Fitzpatrick
grew concerned for her brother's well-being. ``I always thought
something could happen,'' said Amy, 24. ``So I told him, `You make
me nervous.' And he said: `You know that I love you and I know that
you love me. And I promise I won't put you through what Daren did.'
''
</P>
<P>
   But then he did.
</P>
<P>
   On a May evening, after returning from Bogie's, a local pub,
Mark Fitzpatrick approached his sister's third-floor bedroom and
softly asked to borrow Amy's cigarette lighter. ``I said, `Yes.
Just make sure you give it back to me in the morning.' He said, `I
will,' '' Amy recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mark Fitzpatrick walked downstairs, pointed his
grandfather's gun at himself, and fired. His body fell 4 feet from
the spot where Daren Fitzpatrick had died in January 1997. It was
the final chapter in the story of identical twins who lived
parallel lives and met identical, self-inflicted deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Now, friends and neighbors can only wonder about the unknowable
bonds between two brothers who, their family says, literally
couldn't live without each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identical twins have a stronger bond than most people can ever
imagine,'' said Nancy L. Segal, a psychology professor and director
of the Twin Studies Center at California State University at
Fullerton. ``They share all their genes in common. They are virtual
clones of one another. They have this enormous compatibility that
evolves from a very early age. Twins have said things like
`watching my twin die was like watching myself die.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Muller's third pregnancy seemed different. She was
bigger. Her breathing was more labored. She was having a difficult
time but all indications showed a single, strong baby. And on a
bright July morning, Daren Scott Fitzpatrick was born. It was 10:05
a.m. He weighed 6 pounds. The nurses unplugged the monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all of a sudden, out slipped Mark,'' Muller said. ``I was
literally shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes younger than Daren, Mark was fine. He weighed 5
pounds, 11 ounces and had a little strawberry mark below his
bellybutton, an early identifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's got the mark, thank goodness,'' their mother said.
</P>
<P>
   She dressed them alike and watched them grow. In a neighborhood
of tall trees and wide front porches, the Fitzpatrick twins were
newborn novelties.
</P>
<P>
   The next-door neighbor once called to gingerly report that the
toddlers had managed to open an upstairs window. ``Don't panic,''
she said, ``but the boys are leaning out.'' Once, when an aunt was
baby-sitting, they locked her out of the house. She watched from
the front porch as the twins clambered atop the counter and
gleefully tossed sugar around the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were always into something,'' Muller said. ``They were
mischievous. I always described them as one big brain with four
arms and legs.''
</P>
<P>
   They played Little League baseball together, served as altar
boys at the local Catholic church, and by the time they entered
Monument Mountain Regional High School, they shared a love for
wrestling and adolescent hijinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The twins were the most off-the-wall, crazy guys you ever
met,'' said Brock Foster, a lifelong friend, who rode bikes,
climbed trees, and sneaked into neighbors' pools with the
Fitzpatrick twins.
</P>
<P>
   They were ``all-American boys,'' their sister said. As
teenagers, they dreamed of military careers. They would join
separate branches of the service because, despite their close ties,
they considered serving together a little too ``geeky.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Drucker, 23, a neighborhood friend, said they once
seemed indomitable. ``They were tough Irish,'' Drucker said. ``It
seemed nothing could ever hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark was at the wheel of Barbara Muller's overloaded Ford Escort
station wagon on that wintry mid-March night in 1993. Daren rode
next to him in front. A high school dance had just broken up and
seven boys were heading south down a curving road that funnels
Route 7 from Monument Mountain into downtown Great Barrington. They
were heading for Friendly's.
</P>
<P>
   A mile south of the school, the car skidded out of control,
colliding with Irene M. Wheeler's Mercury sedan. Wheeler, a
30-year-old mother of two, was killed. So were two of Mark's
passengers, schoolmates Jed M. Blackwell, 15, and Richard L. Morey,
17.
</P>
<P>
   In the front seat, Daren lay critically injured, his legs
tangled, his head wedged under the dashboard. ``I remember him
making this horrible scream because I couldn't do anything for
him,'' Mark would write later in an essay for a community college
course. ``Right before the firemen got us out, Daren told me that
if it was his time to go, he wanted me to know that he loved me
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   As families buried the dead, doctors worked to repair damaged
organs, and police investigators sought to recreate the accident,
Daren fought for survival. The family kept a vigil by his bedside.
His liver was sliced. His spleen and part of a lung were removed.
Doctors put a plate in his sternum.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, treated and released from the hospital, was charged with
three counts of vehicular homicide, placed on pretrial probation
and ordered to surrender his license and perform 200 hours of
community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``That accident changed everybody,'' said Neal Barbieri, 24, a
next-door neighbor who was severely injured in the crash. ``When
you're teenagers, sometimes you think you're immortal. That
accident showed us that that wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark wore his guilt like a hair shirt, pouring himself into
court-ordered painting projects while his brother recuperated at
home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
