<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETS-BOOK-HNS &LR;      07-27 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK LOOKS INTO LIVES OF JAPANESE-AMERICAN VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Toshio Whelchel, who served in the Marine Corps
from 1977 to 1981, has compiled an oral history of a dozen
Japanese-American troops in Vietnam in his book ``From Pearl Harbor
to Saigon: Japanese-American Soldiers and the Vietnam War'' (Verso,
$25, 203 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Each man was either born in a Japanese relocation camp during
World War II or is the son of parents who spent time in the camps.
Each experienced prejudice and ignorance, but the reactions are
different.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yoshikawa remembers the summary executions of suspected
Viet Cong, ``just as it was common to run Vietnamese civilians off
the road, or to call them zips or gooks.'' But, he adds, ``Even
knowing these things took place, my reaction didn't rise to the
level of outrage. The one emotion I experienced most was absolute
boredom.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles Yakao said his mother argued in favor of him going into
the army, pointing to the heroism of the Japanese 442nd combat team
in World War II. ``She was basically saying that the
Japanese-American population has a unique history in this country
because the way we vindicated ourselves was through military
service. She said, `It's one thing if you're from any other
culture, but the way we got out of the internment camps and
established ourselves as fully participating citizens was through
the efforts of the 442nd.'''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of talk about drugs in ``From Pearl Harbor to
Saigon,'' starting with former Marine Marcus Miyatomo, who was born
at Manzanar in 1945. He joined the Marines out of juvenile court
and wound up in Da Nang, where ``we could get drugs as easily as we
could get liquor ... primarily grass and opium.''
</P>
<P>
   Artilleryman Tim Inakawa says ``a routine day in Vietnam was to
start the day loaded, either drinking or smoking pot.'' Melvin
Wadachi talks about cocaine, heroin and liquid opium, saying,
``We'd take two drops of opium, add water, cook it, and then shoot
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Yoshida goes so far as to describe his favorite opium
dens in Nha Trang: ``It cost five dollars per hit and we could stay
there as long as we wanted. The rooms were real dark, with pillows
all around, like in a bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know where Whelchel, who is working on a book on
homeless Vietnam veterans, is going with all this talk of drugs.
``From Pearl Harbor to Saigon'' is far more interesting when it
moves away from drugs and allows glimpses of what it was like to
grow up, as a Japanese-American, in the craziness that was Southern
California in the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Inakawa, born in a relocation camp at Tule Lake, Calif., admits
to being ashamed of his Japanese parents, saying, ``When I was
growing up I thought gardening was such a demeaning type of work. I
was always embarrassed that my dad was a gardener.'' He stayed
angry after being drafted, Inakawa says. ``My dad was willing to
have me die in war rather than disgrace the family. I think it
sounds like the old samurai code.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Imayama, who played varsity football, ran with gangs.
``Back then there were the Buddha Bandits from East Los Angeles and
other Asian gangs from the Gardena area. We never got along with
the Gardena people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Yoshida liked nothing better than surfing (``I listened
more to white surf music than the Motown my Japanese-American
friends were into.'').
</P>
<P>
   Wadachi was captain of his gymnastics team and hung around the
Gas House in Venice, listening to bongo music and the poetry of
Allen Ginsburg. He belonged to a car club called the Escorts,
cruising around in a '55 Chevy Bel Air _ ``a two-door, fire-engine
red, dual Carter AFB quads, Corvette cam 327, M&AMP;8 slicks, 4 x 11
rear, bucket seats, Tijuana upholstery, with black interior and a
stereo.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a counselor, Wadachi says, ``I haven't associated with
whites, except tangentially, since returning from Nam. ... I can't
say I hate whites but, even after making the adjustment back to the
world, I feel no need or desire to reintegrate myself with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAGIC-TWINS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     07-27 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAGIC-TWINS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass.: ... at home.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Segal said the emotional bond between twins yields a sense of
devotion and a sense of responsibility that is deeply stronger than
among mere siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identical twins are enormously altruistic about their twin,''
the psychologist said. ``They feel incredibly guilty if something
they do might have caused pain for their twin. They feel: I wish it
had been me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, Mark had a real tough time even though we assured
him that it wasn't his fault,'' Muller recalled. ``He kept saying:
`But I was the driver.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daren Fitzpatrick's view of his future was colored red, white,
and blue. The boy, who had clipped newspaper stories and taped TV
footage about the US triumph in the Persian Gulf War, proudly hung
the American flag in his upstairs room, which was festooned with
posters of the Marine Corps, the Few Good Men he intended to join
after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   But the accident ended that dream. His injuries, a Marine
recruiter told him, disqualified him for service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crushed,'' said Brian Mead, a longtime friend. ``He
took down his posters of the Marines. And for a couple of days he
didn't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Daren tried to regroup. He enrolled at Berkshire
Community College, majoring in criminal justice, worked part time
as a police officer in nearby Monterey, and talked of moving on to
a big-city force some day.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before Daren's suicide in January 1997, Monterey
Police Chief Gareth J. Backhaus received a call about a rollover
accident on Route 23. The car was on its side. The driver had
vanished. He called a wrecker and ran the plate, tracing the car to
Daren's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Daren had been driving. He walked away from the wreck his family
now believes may have been a suicide attempt, and was at home in
bed by the time the police called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went upstairs and I said, `Daren did you have an accident?'
And he said, `Yes, but I didn't get hurt.' '' It had been nearly
four years since that awful wreck on Route 7 and the events the
night before were crashing in on Daren Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   His mother told him the police were on their way over to talk to
him and urged him to get up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came downstairs to put the coffee on,'' Muller said. ``This
was about 5:30 or quarter to 6 and I came to the bottom of the
stairs and I said, `Darren, hurry. They're going to be coming soon.
And he said, `What do you think they're going to do to me?' And I
said, `Nothing. What do you think? They're not going to do anything
to you.' And I just walked 5 feet. Pop! And I just ran upstairs and
there he was.''
</P>
<P>
   He had fired the handgun he used during his police patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have thought that this situation might have something
to do with his career in law enforcement full time,'' Backhaus
said. ``Nobody really knows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say there is no such thing as a suicide gene. But in
a 1991 study, Segal studied 62 pairs of identical twins and 114
pairs of fraternal twins, of whom at least one had committed
suicide. She found that 13 percent of the surviving identical
twins, who share an exact genetic blueprint, ultimately followed
their twin in suicide, while just 1.8 percent of the fraternal
twins did.
</P>
<P>
   If Mark Fitzpatrick was a candidate to follow his brother's path
to the grave, no one saw it coming. He assured his friends and
family that he would never do that to himself _ or to them. He
studied suicide and wrote about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways suicide is one of the hardest forms of death to
mourn, and most likely will stay with you for the rest of your
life,'' Mark wrote in a college paper five months before he died.
``Following the suicide of someone you care about will cause you to
feel many different feelings, and one of those feelings is
betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Honorably discharged from the Army when his tour was up in June
1998, Mark was a volunteer for the Great Barrington Fire Department
and for the Southern Berkshire Volunteer Ambulance Squad, where he
was working toward certification as an emergency medical
technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very intense young man,'' said Victor M. Lucek Jr.,
president of Berkshire Emergency Training, who listed Fitzpatrick
among his top students.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before Mark's suicide, his class took part in a
simulated accident response drill in which casualties were made up
to appear to have genuine wounds. The instructors made the exercise
especially tough, throwing unexpected hurdles in the paths of the
would-be EMTs. The ``victims'' Mark's team was dispatched to help
did not survive.
</P>
<P>
   That Saturday night, Mark confessed to his mother that
everything had gone wrong _ perhaps triggering nightmarish memories
of the triple fatal accident on Route 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of bothered me,'' Muller said. ``I had this little
funny feeling in my stomach, thinking `is this a disappointment
like Daren had?' I mean it was just something but not enough to
say, `Let me get you help.' He didn't show those signs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the pub that night, friends said Fitzpatrick did not appear
distressed. But after handing over her cigarette lighter to her
brother at home later that night, Amy Fitzpatrick, still not quite
asleep, heard gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran downstairs in the hallway and there were pieces of wood
and dried flowers all over the place,'' she said. ``I peeked in the
door and I just saw the blood. So I ran downstairs and my
stepfather went up and just said: `He did it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the note left behind by Daren, who left his money to Mark
and his personal belongings to his mother, Mark's suicide note was
more personal. ``It was a way of letting us know that it was
something he had to do,'' Muller said. ``I think he knew we would
understand because we understood with Daren.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't live without each other,'' Amy explained. ``They
just weren't the same by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Goulston, a UCLA psychiatrist and an expert on suicide,
said the twins' suicides probably were rooted in a feeling of
aloneness that most people can't fathom.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men never really healed from the wounds of the trauma on
that icy night,'' Goulston said. ``When you're an identical twin,
one of the things you can always count on is a soul mate. And the
poignancy here is a sudden sense of aloneness. And one of the
common things that all suicidal people feel at the end is emotional
loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers, who had been united even in the womb, now lie
next to each other in St. Peter's Cemetery here, where they were
carried by the same hearse from the same funeral home; their
funeral Masses said by the same priest in the church they once
served together as altar boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
