<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Presient Clinton and Vice President
Gore meet with Prime Minister Stepashin of Russia. By John M.
Broder. (Eds, a 5 p.m. EDT news conference is planned.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Barak and
Palestinian leader Arafat hold their first working meeting. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ENVIRON (Belgrade) _ The U.N. Environmental Agency
reports on damage in Kosovo. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ASEAN-NKOREA (Singapore) _ As part of a full-blown diplomatic
effort to deter North Korea from going ahead with its anticipated
test of a long-range missile, Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright and her counterparts from South Korea and Japan appeal to
the isolated Communist government to accept engagement with the
world rather than risk ``serious negative consequences'' that they
said a test would entail. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Even as Republicans in Congress plan
to cut domestic programs by as much as 20 percent, the leadership
also wants to grant as much as $100 billion in tax breaks to
business special interests. Vice President Gore goes to the Hill to
meet with the Democratic leadership and to criticize the
Republicans' budget. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   INTERIOR-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to pass
an Interior spending bill rife with amendments and riders favoring
oil, gas, mining and timber interests _ a day after voting to ban
the practice of attaching legislative riders and policy amendments
on spending bills. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The prolonged delay of a final
vote on Richard Holbrooke's nomination to be the U.S. ambassador to
the U.N. has less to do with his qualifications than with the
Senate's low esteem for both the United Nations and President
Clinton. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEATWAVE (Chicago) _ Opressive heat continues in South and
Midwest. While there may be some respite in the northern Midwest
today, the heat and humidity is expected to continue later this
week. More than two dozen heat-related deaths have been reported so
far. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-DEATHS (San Francisco) _ A motel handyman described in
detail to the FBI and in a television interview how he killed a
naturalist and three Yosemite sightseers, saying he had dreamed of
such crimes since childhood. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-CAMPAIGN (Chicago) _ In an interview, Jesse Jackson says
he hopes he can still have influence in the presidential campaign
without being a candidate. He says he likes Gore and Bradley,
although he feels closer to Gore. Having both in the race could
lead to a debate over issues he's interested in _ workers rights,
health care, school financing. He's withholding his endorsement
until a date uncertain. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-ARK (Little Rock) _ New York City's mayor goes South
for a fundraising tour and a political poke at Hillary Clinton. By
Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (Washington) _ Meanwhile ... Hillary Clinton meets
with the leaders of various Jewish organizations to try to mend
fences over some of the political positions she has taken recently.
By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-REPO (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ As head of the asset
management division of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency,
Eko Budianto is his country's repo man. The agency is in charge of
an estimated $35 billion bailout of Indonesia's banks. Eko's job is
to get the corporate cronies who helped create the mess to cough up
roughly $23 billion they owe the banks. If they do not, he has
carte blanche to seize their assets, even if it means enlisting the
help of the army to do it. ``I see myself as a loan workout officer
with a big stick,'' Eko says. The work being done by Eko and his
colleagues represents the brass tacks of Indonesia's efforts to
reform itself. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   INSTINET-ARCHIPELAGO (New York) _ Reuters Group's Instinet has
bought a 16.4 percent stake in the Archipelago trading network.
Archipelago, a two-year-old trading network for Nasdaq Stock market
shares, also says it will apply to the Securities and Exchange
Commission to become a stock exchange, which would allow it to
trade New York Stock Exchange stocks. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-APPOINT (London) _ Barclays PLC, which has undergone
more than a year of turmoil in its executive ranks, names Matthew
Barrett, chairman of the Bank of Montreal, as chief executive. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-TALKS (Beijing) _ A senior U.S. official says after
a day of talks in Beijing that normal trade relations between the
United States and China are back on track, exclusive of the issue
of China's membership in the WTO. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is to vote on
China trade policy. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ARGENTINA (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil unilaterally suspends
trade talks with Argentina after the Argentine government announced
plans to impose import quotas against its partners in Mercosur. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
