<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAUREN-BESSETTE-FOOTN     07-27 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUREN-BESSETTE-FOOTNOTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUREN BESSETTE WAS NOBODY'S FOOTNOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   We were on the runway in Los Angeles, about to take off for
Chicago, when the guy sitting next to me gave me one of those
elbow-nudges that you just hate getting from guys next to you on
the plane, especially at the beginning of a flight. It's the kind
of move that tells you, ``Take out the Walkman now!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see who's in the first row?'' he said in a
conspiratorial tone.
</P>
<P>
   I leaned into the aisle. ``Sorry. All I can see are the backs of
their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Oprah and Stedman!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No last names necessary, of course. I know and you know he
wasn't talking about Oprah McGillicudy and Stedman Kramden _ he was
referring to Oprah Winfrey and her longtime companion, Stedman
Graham. (This was more than a few years ago, when Oprah was merely
rich and famous but had yet to take over the world. These days when
she needs to travel, she has her own personal space shuttle.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure hope this plane doesn't crash,'' said my new buddy.
``Because if it does, all the headlines are going to be about
Oprah. Nobody's going to care about you or me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well. I'd like to think that at least a few people would take
note of my demise _ family, friends, a few random strangers who
always preferred Phil Donahue in his prime to Oprah. Besides, I
think a better reason for hoping a plane doesn't crash is the fact
that it would probably KILL US ALL.
</P>
<P>
   But I knew what the guy meant. Of course Oprah would have been
the headline, then and now. Heck, she could be sharing a plane with
the pope, Sammy Sosa, Al Gore and every member of Limp Bizkit, and
she'd be the headline if (God forbid) something went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I can fault the Oprah-spotter for engaging in such
macabre speculation. Just about anybody who's ever been on an
airplane with a famous person engages in a little gallows humor
about being lost in the shuffle should the plane go down. I've even
heard celebrities telling anecdotes about flying with more
widely-known entertainers and lamenting that they would have been
reduced to a secondary story had disaster struck.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this very scenario played out last week when John
Kennedy Jr., Carolyn Bessette and the woman repeatedly referred to
as ``Carolyn's sister, Lauren,'' all perished in a plane crash.
While Kennedy was among the most famous faces in the world, and
Carolyn had achieved instant celebrity status by virtue of her
marriage to John, nobody outside of her own circle had ever heard
of Lauren until that plane disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen this before _ one or more non-celebrities dying in a
crash that took the life of a famous musician or actor or
politician. When that happens, the names of the un-famous appear in
sidebars or in stories that list the names of ``other victims,'' in
alphabetical order. In death as in life, there are leads and there
are supporting players.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever this occurs, I'm reminded of J.D. Tippit, whose name by
now has been forgotten by everyone save historians and conspiracy
buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Tippit was killed in a plane crash involving a
celebrity; he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   By Lee Harvey Oswald.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour after the assassination of John F. Kennedy, Oswald
gunned down Dallas police officer Tippit and then slipped into the
Texas Theatre, where he was apprehended by authorities. While
Tippit was hailed as a local hero and mourned by his fellow
officers, the very circumstances of his death turned him into an
instant footnote.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic and heartbreaking as it was, the death of John Kennedy
Jr. will not have anything approaching the historical impact of his
father's assassination; we all know that. Yet in some ways, Lauren
Bessette has a spiritual kinship with J.D. Tippit. Unknown to all
but their family, friends and associates in life, they were thrust
into the edge of the spotlight because their deaths were connected
to men named John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   There seemed to be an air of media guilt permeating the coverage
of the candlelight service for Lauren held Saturday night in
Greenwich, Conn. Nearly every story pounded home the point that she
was a person of grace and good character in her own right, and
should be mourned in that matter.
</P>
<P>
   But who was that message for? Anyone who knew the woman before
the nation saw pictures of her luggage washed up on the shore,
before the news channels started serving up her image in a
slow-motion home video _ anyone who knew her already understood
that Lauren Bessette was nobody's footnote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times, a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather'' and ``Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
