<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSMOLOGY-HUBBLE-NYTS     07-27 2632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMOLOGY-HUBBLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY THE SKY FELL DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD PANEK  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The group of graduate students had gathered, as groups of
graduate students do at such affairs, off to one side of the hall.
The occasion was a symposium at the Space Telescope Science
Institute at Johns Hopkins University, in Baltimore. The graduate
students were eyeing their elders and chatting nervously about the
many major figures in cosmology in the room.
 &HT;    One student made the inevitable joke about a bomb going off and
what that would do to their field of study. Everybody laughed.
 &HT;    ``But at least it would open up some jobs,'' said another. More
laughter.
 &HT;    ``And the first bomb can strike right there,'' said a third,
nodding toward a portly, elderly man standing not five yards away.
The group grew quiet.
 &HT;    In a way, they would get their wish.
 &HT;    This past May 25, NASA held a press conference in Washington to
announce that the search for the Holy Grail of cosmology was over.
A research team calling itself the Hubble Space Telescope Key
Project was claiming it had solved one of the original mysteries of
civilization, the age of the universe.
 &HT;    If correct, the result meant that Allan Sandage, the target of
the young cosmologist's imaginary bomb, was worse than wrong. It
threatened to render him irrelevant.
 &HT;    For nearly 50 years, Sandage had been laboring to complete the
effort of his mentor, Edwin Hubble, to find a figure that
astronomers now call the Hubble constant _ the rate of expansion of
the universe and, by implication, its age. Sandage himself long ago
came up with an answer.
 &HT;    Then he came up with it again, and then again, and again and
again. Now rival astronomers were claiming that they had divined
not an answer but the answer _ and it wasn't the same as Sandage's.
 &HT;    ``It's a disaster for me,'' Sandage said just after the
announcement. ``It's a psychological disaster. I mean, you just
can't imagine what the last two weeks have been like. But if you
permit it, the world will either break your heart or turn your
heart to stone.''
 &HT;    The Key Project had arrived at a constant of 70 plus or minus 10
percent (the expansion rate expressed in kilometers per second per
megaparsec), which put the age of the universe at 12 billion years,
while Sandage's most recent result was 58 plus or minus 10 percent,
or an age of 15 billion years.
 &HT;    To outsiders, a difference between 12 billion and 15 billion
years might seem cosmically (if not comically) insignificant _
indeed the error margins overlapped, if only just barely, somewhere
around a Hubble constant of 63 and an age of 13.5 billion years.
 &HT;    At long last, some Key Project astronomers suggested, the time
had come for the two sides in the ``Hubble wars'' to compromise.
 &HT;    For Sandage, however, science has never been about compromise;
it's about right and wrong _ the certainty of absolutes, not the
convenience of a politically expedient solution. For his rivals,
science isn't necessarily about compromise either. But neither is
it about what many have long thought they'd detected in Sandage:
obstinacy to the point of arrogance, arrogance to the point of
impeding progress.
 &HT;    As one graduate student at the Johns Hopkins symposium remarked,
glaring at Sandage in exasperation, ''Every time you see a graph of
results on the Hubble constant, there's everyone else, getting
closer together, and there's his 55, 55, 55.''
 &HT;    And that, for cosmology at the close of the century that
witnessed its birth as a science, was precisely the problem. There
was everybody else, and there was Sandage, and the universe wasn't
big enough for the both of them.
 &HT;    As it happens, Sandage is older than the universe, or at least
our current conception of it. An only child whose father was an
academic, Sandage was born in Iowa City, Iowa, in 1926. That was
three years before Hubble observed that the billions of galaxies
out there appear to be racing away from us, and the farther away
they are, the faster they're receding. In other words, that the
universe is expanding.
 &HT;    What Darwin had done for our species and Wegener had done for
our planet, Hubble had now done for the cosmos _ recast it as an
organism evolving over time. The universe had a story to tell, and
all you had to do was look.
 &HT;    So Hubble looked, and when he couldn't anymore, Sandage looked
for him.
 &HT;    Back in the early 1950s, Sandage might have figured it would
take 15 years or so to complete Hubble's program. Now, at 73, he's
still pursuing it. Which would be OK _ that's the way science goes
sometimes, after all _ if it weren't for these other astronomers
trying to overturn a substantial portion of his life's work.
 &HT;    Again and again during an afternoon in Pasadena three days after
the Key Project news conference, he insists he doesn't want to talk
about the Hubble constant; again and again he returns to it.
 &HT;    ``They're slowly educating themselves. They started at 115, then
went down to 100, then to 90, then 80, then 73, now 70. And when
will the thing be solved? When the other group gets our number and
claims it to be a new discovery.''
 &HT;    Then he makes a face of disgust. This isn't the way he wanted to
go out _ a figure of pity, with a controversy as his legacy.
 &HT;    Sandage is aware of his reputation among the younger generation.
 &HT;    ``'Allan is a grumpy old man,''' he offers, laughing. He won't
use voice or E-mail, and insists on driving a stick shift because
``it's just unbelievably boring to drive an automatic.''
 &HT;    When astronomers started looking to computer screens for data in
the late 1980s, Sandage knew it was time to quit. The era of the
lone observer, staring into the abyss, was gone.
 &HT;    ``The changeover to the modern world!'' he laments. ``If I were
15 years younger, I could have competed with these guys.''
 &HT;    He's standing in the attic of the legendary building on Santa
Barbara Street in Pasadena that has served as headquarters for the
Carnegie Institution's observatories since the 1920s.
 &HT;    Sandage has lost some sight in his right eye, the one he pressed
to an eyepiece for nearly half a century, and his sense of balance
is off, a hazard on an observing platform dozens of feet off a
concrete floor. Still, he works every day. He has years of
astronomical data to reduce, he says, decades of memories to put
down and a century's worth of archives that he would maybe like
``to get into some kind of shape.''
 &HT;    Then again, maybe not. He looks at the cabinets full of
photographic plates and daily logs and all the other data that
nowadays pass directly from the night sky into the digital ether.
 &HT;    ``Records like this no longer exist,'' he sighs, almost to
himself. ``I have no idea why we keep them.''
 &HT;    Sandage may be the last surviving link to Hubble. As a boy, he
read everything he could about the radically new vision of the
universe then emerging.
 &HT;    At 15, Sandage made a pilgrimage with his father to the Mount
Wilson Observatory, where Hubble was working his miracles. In 1948,
he returned, this time as a student at California Institute of
Technology in nearby Pasadena. Over the next four years Sandage
advanced from apprentice to assistant to Hubble's heir.
 &HT;    ``I came at exactly the right time,'' Sandage says. ``I was 26
years old, and all the monks and priests down here were ready to
retire. So I overlapped enough that I got to know them all.''
 &HT;    Up there, on the mountaintop, Sandage could dwell among his
gods, astronomers who knew they'd ``arrived,'' as Sandage puts it,
when they found their napkin not clipped to a clothespin but tucked
inside a wooden ring inscribed with their name. And down here, on
Santa Barbara Street, Sandage could inspect for himself ``the
plates of Moses'' _ the vast archives of photographic records, and
an apt metaphor in more ways than one.
 &HT;    Like Moses, Hubble had come down from the mountain bearing new
laws of nature. But also like Moses, Hubble had to wander the
proverbial desert for decades, only to die within sight of the
Promised Land.
 &HT;    Hubble suffered a major heart attack in the summer of 1949, at
the age of 60, just six months after making his initial
observations with the 200-inch-diameter mirror in the new telescope
on Mount Palomar outside San Diego _ an instrument that he'd been
eagerly awaiting since the late 1920s, the one that he hoped would
allow him to determine the age and structure of the universe.
 &HT;    In 1953, Hubble died. To his assistant fell the responsibility
for executing one of the most ambitious scientific programs in
history.
 &HT;    While finishing Hubble's work, Sandage also pursued his own
first love, how stars evolve. In 1960, he and a young radio
astronomer named Thomas Matthews identified something altogether
new and unforeseen and confounding, the first ``radio star.''
 &HT;    The discovery created quite a stir _ though not so great as the
finding three years later by other astronomers that the source of
the signal wasn't a star within our galaxy, as Sandage and Thomas
had assumed it to be, but something else 1.5 billion light-years
away, earning it the name quasi-stellar radio source, or
``quasar.''
 &HT;    The universe was getting curiouser and curiouser, but in their
rush to publish, Sandage's peers didn't always give credit where it
was due.
 &HT;    ``Tom Matthews and I were the discoverers of quasars,'' Sandage
says, the anger still evident. ``The quasars were stolen from both
of us.''
 &HT;    That episode altered forever the way he thought about his
profession. ``It's not
oh-we're-all-in-this-together-just-seeking-the-
secrets-of-nature,'' he says. ``The competition between colleagues
is really much stronger than anybody on the outside understands.''
 &HT;    As for Wendy Freedman, a Key Project leader, Sandage is blunt in
assessing a motive: ``fame.''
 &HT;    The first woman to join the permanent staff on Santa Barbara
Street, in 1987, Freedman belongs to a new generation of
astronomers. For them, a space telescope simply represented a
chance to take on one of the fundamental controversies in
cosmology.
 &HT;    ``There are some problems you work at and you work at, and you
can't really make progress,'' Freedman says, ''but this was an area
where there was an opportunity with Hubble to do something where
there was an impasse on the ground.''
 &HT;    The new generation, not surprisingly, isn't charmed by Sandage's
``Uncle Allan'' routine _ the hoots and howls, the chortles and
chuckles, the guffaws and wheezes and other explosions of seeming
enthusiasm that exhaust the thesaurus listing for ``laughs.''
 &HT;    He can be avuncular, all right _ with a vengeance. ``The answer
will come,'' he once announced about his rivals' efforts, ``when
responsible people go to the telescope.''
 &HT;    Over the years Sandage and Freedman have virtually stopped
speaking to each other. Freedman's summary of her differences with
Sandage is crisply professional: ''I have the utmost respect for
him. We just have a scientific disagreement. That's how science
proceeds.''
 &HT;    But that's not the only way science proceeds, Sandage says. For
him, his rivals' efforts resemble nothing so much as the Darwinian
struggle that he has observed in the stars and galaxies.
 &HT;    ``When I came in there were only 15 observational cosmologists
in the world,'' Sandage says. Astronomers in 1950 numbered maybe
2,000. Now, Sandage estimates, that total is as high as 15,000.
``The survival instinct is very, very crucial, especially now among
the young people. And the desire for media attention can be
overwhelming.''
 &HT;    It can raise the stakes; it can lower the error bar. It can push
programs, methodologies, results, even interpretations of
ostensibly objective data _ supposedly in the name of science, but
also for the sake of tenure, appointments, observing time,
financing. And in this habitat, what's one half-blind, off-balance,
retired astronomer more or less?
 &HT;    In the aftermath of the quasar controversy, in the late 1960s,
Sandage removed himself from public view. He continued working with
his longtime collaborator Gustav Tammann, continued publishing new
values for the Hubble constant (nearly always in the 50-to-55
range), but he stopped attending even astronomical conferences.
 &HT;    In 1983, he re-emerged suddenly at a meeting in Vancouver.
During his absence, according to ``Lonely Hearts of the Cosmos,''
by Dennis Overbye, he became a born-again Christian, a subject he
now won't discuss explicitly. But he will say that he struggled
with how to separate his needs from the needs of science.
 &HT;    To talk about the Hubble-constant controversy is to violate his
personal code; yet not to defend his research is to violate his
professional code. He is nearly keening with the conflict.
 &HT;    ``I really am very, very unhappy with this controversy getting
into the press,'' he says, his face falling. But in the end, it's
another, not entirely charitable, thought that seems to rally his
spirits: ``The very fact that every article I know of has indicated
that we do exist and have a different answer _ the opposition did
not expect that.''
 &HT;    Indeed, at a meeting in a Chicago hotel where members of the
Hubble Key Project team assembled to explain their results before
several hundred colleagues, it seems an astronomer from another
observatory arrived at a value of the Hubble constant using a new,
improved methodology. And guess what? It differs from the Key
Project's _ by 15 percent to 20 percent.
 &HT;    Which leaves Sandage precisely where he has been since he packed
up his eyepiece, pocketed his napkin ring and came down from the
mountain: as low as 50, as high as 58, call it 55. It's in the
literature that he'll endure, or not; either way, it's in the
literature that he lives.
 &HT;    ``The library is my telescope now,'' he says. ``If a day goes by
that I have not done something to prepare something for
publication, I believe that day is wasted.'' He is embarking on a
``proper history'' of the Mount Wilson Observatory _ after all, he
knows where the bodies are buried, literally.
 &HT;    Just outside the 100-inch, Sandage points out a plaque in the
grass that marks the final resting place for the ashes of an
astronomer. The summit would make a fitting end for Sandage, too:
blindingly white domes against achingly blue skies, sights so pure
they hurt. Has he considered such an arrangement for himself?
 &HT;    ``But I'm not going to die,'' he says. ``I'm going to live
forever!'' He's just going to have to get himself some of this
genetic engineering that prevents cells from growing old. ``My real
goal,'' he explains, lowering his voice to a conspiratorial growl,
``is to outlive my critics.''
 &HT;    And then he looses a shriek of glee into the thin mountain air.
More than ever, it is the sound of a man who fully intends the last
laugh to be his.
 &HT;     c.1999 Richard Panek  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Panek is the author of ``Seeing and Believing: How the
Telescope Opened Our Eyes and Minds to the Heavens.'') &LR;
