1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD PANEK  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The group of graduate students had gathered, as groups of
graduate students do at such affairs, off to one side of the hall.
The occasion was a symposium at the Space Telescope Science
Institute at Johns Hopkins University, in Baltimore. The graduate
students were eyeing their elders and chatting nervously about the
many major figures in cosmology in the room.
 &HT;    One student made the inevitable joke about a bomb going off and
what that would do to their field of study. Everybody laughed.
 &HT;    ``But at least it would open up some jobs,'' said another. More
laughter.
 &HT;    ``And the first bomb can strike right there,'' said a third,
nodding toward a portly, elderly man standing not five yards away.
The group grew quiet.
 &HT;    In a way, they would get their wish.
 &HT;    This past May 25, NASA held a press conference in Washington to
announce that the search for the Holy Grail of cosmology was over.
