<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-27 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE ALL TRIPS CREATED EQUAL? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable travel-related trends is this:
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, 1 percent of all business travelers were women. By the
turn of the century, that figure is expected to be 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a new book, ``The Smart Woman's Guide to Business
Travel'' (Career Press, $14.99), Laurie Borman, editor of Endless
Vacations magazine and a frequent traveler, writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often businesswomen miss out on priceless travel
experiences. After their workday is done, they hole up in their
rooms, reluctant to go out and see the sights. Perhaps they're
uncertain of the area or afraid to go out on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of embracing the opportunities that our work brings,
all too often we women suffer through them. But armed with a little
knowledge, a good strategy and a positive outlook, it's easy to
turn business travel tribulations into wonderful adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESPECT LACKING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle, Borman suggests, is that some elements of the
travel industry are slow in adapting to changing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many women traveling, it would seem that hotels, car
rental agencies, airlines and other travel providers would be
catering to our needs,'' she writes. ``Although some do, most do
not. And most travel books don't separate businesswomen's needs
from businessmen's needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing one recent survey, Borman says most female travelers
``simply want to be treated at least the same as men, but with some
regard to their particular needs, such as getting help with excess
luggage and offering safe waiting areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Members of the survey group thought that they were
often treated with less respect and received poor customer service
in comparison with men.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle travel writer Syd Kearney has journeyed to
many parts of the world and agrees that women's needs often aren't
properly addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At hotels, for instance, we need more towels than men do, if
only to put our hair up,'' Kearney says. ``Even budget
accommodations should provide skin lotion. Some women really want a
makeup mirror. And hair dryers should be in every room. I am
pleased that it's become standard for many hotels to include an
ironing board and iron among room amenities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAFETY FACTORS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More important, Kearney says, are safety concerns. Kearney's
first-floor room at one budget motel was burglarized last year, and
she says, ``I now pay closer attention to security measures. I'm
shocked at how easily some `locked' windows can be opened. And
deadbolt locks on doors should be required.''
</P>
<P>
   Peepholes placed high on doors are a pet peeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women are petite, and the peepholes are useless to
them,'' Kearney says. ``I was impressed that the new Portofino Bay
Hotel in Orlando (Fla.) has two peepholes in each door. One is at
child level. At least that's some help for adults who aren't
tall.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other hotels have adopted laudable policies. The Pan
Pacific San Francisco, a luxury lodging, offers a personal escort
to guest rooms upon request, and each room is equipped with an
easily accessed button that can be used to summon emergency
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Borman's book cites other factors that can affect women's
enjoyment of the travel experience:
</P>
<P>
   One chapter focuses on ``Keeping Your Home in Order,'' a
significant issue given that studies show that when men travel, 95
percent rely on their spouses to maintain the household, but that
20 percent of married women seek help elsewhere, such as a friend
or hired help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be more important than the peace of mind you'll
have knowing that everyone and everything is safe and under control
while you're away,'' writes Borman.
</P>
<P>
   Being apart from children is particularly difficult. Among
Borman's suggestions: ``If your child loves your nightly stories or
you have a favorite book you like to share, tape record a reading
of the book and let your child listen to that each night before
going to bed. You might also want to tape record or videotape a
daily message in case you can't talk to your child on the phone
each night.''
</P>
<P>
   Once on the road, though, Borman says it's essential that women
give some priority to themselves and seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for women to be intimidated by traveling
alone,'' she writes. ``Getting over the dread of being lonely or
bored is the first hurdle. Then it's time to figure out what can be
fun, yet safe, for a woman to do alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tend to use room service so they won't have to face
sitting alone at a table in a room full of couples and other
parties. Dining solo doesn't have to be intimidating, though. The
hotel concierge can offer ideas for small restaurants that have
just a few tables and cater to single diners. Restaurants often
define a city's culture _ why miss out on a chance to explore that
culture. Dining alone is also a great opportunity to exercise a
more adventurous palate.''
</P>
<P>
   Borman does provide valuable insight from a woman's perspective.
And some chapters _ especially one on etiquette issues _ are
clearly geared to female travelers.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't help thinking that many of the issues she and
Kearney raise also apply to men. Safety is our top priority, even
if we aren't always as quick to admit it. We, too, miss the family
when we're away. And I'll confess to spending many an evening
munching on room service.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to hear from other women travelers about their special
concerns. From men, too. How different are our travel priorities
and needs? Write me at 801 Texas, Houston, Texas 77002. Or e-mail
harry.shattuck(at)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Area bookstores stock or can order The Smart Women's Guide to
Business Travel. Or call 800-227-3371. Access www.careerpress.com
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
