<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTS BLOCK PRAYERS BEFORE TEXAS FOOTBALL GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ High school football has long been considered
sacred in Texas, but a recent court ruling says the pitched battles
over pigskin are not appropriate occasions for public-school
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans,
which the U.S. Supreme Court has been asked to review, will end
ritual pre-game prayers in many communities when the football
season kicks off next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly none of us, nor the community, agree with the
decision,'' said Marc Williamson, superintendent in Fredericksburg,
where traditional prayers for sportsmanship and safe play have
reluctantly been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericksburg School Board President Charlie Kiehne called it a
difficult decision. ``It's a situation again where I feel the
minority is telling the majority what to do,'' Kiehne said. But, he
said, ``It's not good fiscal management of taxpayers dollars to go
into court, knowing your going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Association of School Boards is urging its members to
abide by the court ruling. ``The odds of it being resolved before
the football season ends this year are almost zero,'' Shellie
Hoffman, a staff lawyer for the association, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute concerns the Sante Fe School District policy of
allowing student-led prayers to be broadcast over the public
address system at home football games. The unidentified parents of
two students in Santa Fe, a town of 10,000 people southeast of
Houston, filed a lawsuit in 1995 claiming that pre-game prayers
violated the constitutional separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The district policy allowed graduating students to choose by
secret ballot whether to have an invocation or benediction at
commencement ceremonies. A similar policy was used for prayers
preceding football games, which the district court struck down.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 ruling in February, the appeals court justices found
that while limited prayer may be suitable at once-in-a-lifetime
events like graduation, football games ``are hardly the sober type
of annual event that can be appropriately solemnized with prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court after the
5th Circuit Court refused to reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was ``a victory for the Bill of Rights'' said Jay
Jacobson, executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union
of Texas, which represented the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prayer is the ultimate religious observance. Clearly, it has
no secular purpose,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed to address a ``pervasively religious
atmosphere in the classroom,'' he said, ``including the practice of
leading the kids in prayer before lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Attorney General John Cornyn have
joined the fight to protect prayer at the games, and plan to file
friend-of-the-court briefs backing the school district next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush supports the rights of students to participate
in the free exercise of religion, a right that is guaranteed by the
Constitution,'' Linda Evans, a Bush spokeswoman, said Monday. ``He
believes government should not dictate or censor the content of
voluntary student-led prayer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
