<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-INTERNET-HNS &LR;      07-27 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST INVESTS IN HOME FURNISHINGS INTERNET SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology, The Learning Co.,
division of Mattel, Inc., the Thomas H. Lee Co. and Weston Presidio
Capital announced Tuesday that they have joined forces to back
GoodHome.com, a home furnishings Internet shopping venture.
</P>
<P>
   The new company received $50 million of backing, an all-time
record in its segment and one of the highest first-round totals of
any Internet venture to-date. The site will be launched later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``GoodHome.com is all about using the power of the Internet to
redefine the way consumers select and locate the entire spectrum of
home furnishings,'' said Al Sikes, president of Hearst New Media &AMP;
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The venture represents Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology's ninth
major investment in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to financial support, each backer brings a unique
element of expertise to GoodHome.com. Hearst, one of the world's
largest diversified communications companies, brings resources and
experience in publishing, broadcasting, and new media. The Learning
Co., a leader in family products and software publishing,
contributes technology from its line of home design software.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Lee Co., with four venture capital funds valued at
more than $6 billion, offers its highly regarded experience in
building market-leading brands such as Snapple, Rayovac, TRW Credit
Reports, and The Learning Co. And Weston Presidio Capital, a $900
million fund, brings its experience in building retail and Internet
companies including Restoration Hardware, Staples, Medscape,
DigitalChef, and MapQuest.
</P>
<P>
   GoodHome.com is headed by chief executive officer Douglas Mack,
formerly executive vice president of the Broderbund Software unit
of The Learning Co. Mack previously held senior management
positions at McKinsey &AMP; Co. and General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in San Rafael, Calif., GoodHome.com has 70
employees. The company is privately owned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
