<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5465 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGN-FRENCH29-COX     07-27 1610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-FRENCH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designer gives French furnishings new twist
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The dust rarely settles on Mary Bairstow's furniture.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that her Atlanta home serves as a showroom/photo
studio for many of the pieces she designs for her small Atlanta
home furnishings business.
</P>
<P>
   But even if her pieces didn't come and go, Bairstow believes in
constantly moving furniture around, trying new combinations, mixing
traditional with contemporary, formal with casual. Among her
collections are elegant hand-painted European reproductions that,
despite the gilded legs, black-lacquered finishes and straight
backs, invite visitors to prop up their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to take these pieces back to a patina that looks
old,'' she says. ``People think of painted furniture that's French
or Italian as very formal, but, to steal a phrase, this is more
`barefoot elegance.'''
</P>
<P>
   Furniture trend forecasters say the casual French look such as
Bairstow's _ more sophisticated than country French but less fussy
than formal antiques _ is among several that consumers can expect
to see in stores beginning this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in painted furniture in general has soared for several
years. What's fueling the trend, Bairstow says, are the influences
of European eclectic decors and Americans' penchant for second
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are becoming more sophisticated in their
decorating. They're seeing European publications, traveling more
and getting more comfortable with mixing pieces,'' she says.
``Americans traditionally have taken one style or look in
furnishings and carried it through the entire house, while
Europeans are known for taking a fancy gilded piece and mixing it
with cotton, which softens a room and adds a casualness to it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a growing number of middle-aged Atlantans are
buying weekend getaway homes where they're more comfortable with
casual furnishings such as painted pieces, housing experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hand-painted pieces give a softness to a room and are very
compatible with fabrics,'' says Paul Atwell of Ardley Hall, the
High Point, N.C., wholesale distributor for Bairstow Designs. ``A
lot of people think they can decorate with only one wood and one
pattern of fabric, like the old suites of furniture, but design has
shifted totally away from that. Painted pieces make a wonderful
accent.''
</P>
<P>
   The look is a high-end, sophisticated niche Bairstow decided to
target four years ago when she entered the design business. It's
also one that's earned her national recognition in the current
issue of Victoria magazine as one of 23 ``enterprising women.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine antiques to shabby chic. Bairstow _ who in past lives was
an advertising agency owner, stockbroker, photographer and real
estate agent _ caught the design bug while honeymooning five years
ago in the south of France. She was instantly intrigued by the many
hand-painted antiques housed in the Villa Rothschild, the
17th-century mansion museum. ``I thought to myself, people should
be able to have stuff like this without having to pay a fortune for
fine antiques,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she and a friend recruited a faux painter and
manufacturer to produce a small collection of hand-painted chairs
and other pieces, which they showed at the Atlanta International
Gift and Home Furnishings Market. ``After selling one piece, we
said, `This is not good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Their work was better received at the High Point furniture
market, but soon after the two decided to dissolve their
partnership. ``The next six months were horrible,'' Bairstow says.
``I had all this money invested.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ardley Hall noticed a national magazine ad for her
pieces and agreed to represent her, providing showroom exposure
around the country, including Brice Ltd. at the wholesale Atlanta
Decorative Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, demand has grown steadily, Atwell says, and the
small cottage industry now produces three lines _ one for Ardley
Hall and two sold exclusively on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Ardley Hall Collection consists of more than 75 pieces,
including beds, chairs and armoires, in finishes such as antique
black, gold, gold leaf and walnut. They retail from several hundred
dollars for a planter to $12,000 for a gilded four-poster bed. Her
Colors of Provence Collection, co-created by Bairstow and
Savoir-Faire, an Atlanta decorative painting business, includes
hand-painted tables ($750) and chairs ($250) in pastel country
French shades. And in her newest line, the Home Collection, she
teamed up with Atlantan Jo Santospirito to offer upholstered pieces
in a ``shabby chic'' yet tailored look, including a tufted daybed
and sexy sheer-slipcovered plume chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got very diverse lines, from French Provincial to her
black pieces with gold on them _ something for a lot of different
tastes _ and all very romantic,'' says Kim Freeman, a New York
designer and contributing editor for Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   From magazines to Web sites. The design process begins in the
basement office of Bairstow's 1950s Blackland Road rancher, which
she and husband Robert have renovated, including updating the
kitchen and remodeling the den.
</P>
<P>
   ``We entertain a lot, and people tell us they feel so
comfortable here'' among the pieces, Bairstow says. ``It's all here
to be touched and lived with'' _ especially with three kids around.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Bairstow comes up with a design concept by scanning
European magazines. A photo of an antique chair inspires her design
for a foot; the corner of a bedpost yields an idea for a headboard.
``You have to look at the whole spectrum of design, from fashion to
cars to homes _ casual clothing, SUVs, second homes,'' she says,
when creating home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   After assembling photo clippings of things she likes, she begins
to notice trends, then asks herself what she would like in her own
home. She then culls a collection of ideas that she presents to
artists and her manufacturer, Nottingham Antiques, without even a
sketch. ``I don't draw. I don't even sketch worth a hoot,''
Bairstow says. ``But I'm very visual and good at communicating my
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Artist Mimi Chekroune, her Savoir-Faire painting partner,
vouches for that. ``Mary is very professional and knows what she
wants,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   New pieces take about four months to create and because of the
small production, the company is able to deliver custom orders in
six to eight weeks _ about half the time of most large
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed delivery is one of the biggest issues dogging the
furniture industry and one reason consumers increasingly are
turning to online shopping. Direct sales allow small companies such
as Bairstow's to bypass the retailer, which typically doubles or
triples manufacturer prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, I think most furniture will be sold on the
Internet,'' she says. ``Sure, there will be stores and shows but
not on the same level that exists today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bairstow's basking in the success of the mix _
at home and in business.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is home to one of the country's largest design
communities. To suggest an architect, builder or designer for How
the Pros Live, call 404-526-5969 or an e-mail dflanders(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER SNAPSHOT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vitals: Pensacola, Fla., native; 48
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: B.A. political science, international affairs,
Florida State University
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Business: Founded Bairstow Designs, 1995 (Information:
www.bairstow-furniture.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Favorite object: ``Anything my kids make me, whether it's
crafts, a painting or pottery,'' such as daughter Elizabeth's clay
saucer, right.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Favorite place to bargain shop: Simpler Times, McDonough
</P>
<P>
   T h e a r t o f t h e m i x
</P>
<P>
   Mixing styles and materials of furnishings and accessories can
give a room rich texture. Designer Mary Bairstow suggested these
ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't be afraid to combine traditional with contemporary.
(Hang modern art over an antique chest, for example).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mix styles of furniture _ matching pieces can be static and
boring. Throw a painted armoire or painted lamp into the mix,
adding one piece at the time. Just don't overdo it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Display your children's artwork for a personal touch, but be
sure to frame it professionally.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use fresh flowers to add warmth to a room. Markets have made
them more affordable. Even a bunch of tall grasses in an urn can
make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create ambience by lighting a room with multiple sources _
canned halogens, floor lamps, picture lights _ and using dimmer
switches and low-watt bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use candles to add personality to a room. In a vacant
fireplace, group lots of them _ not just two _ in different shapes
and sizes but the same color. And don't discard them after they've
burned down a bit; the worn look has character.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rearrange furnishings often. Move everything out of the room
and add back one piece at the time, trying different arrangements
and pieces from other rooms. Use a daybed as a couch in the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create a focal point, whether it's a large piece of art,
painted furniture, a floral arrangement or large palm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accessorize a sofa or chair with pretty scarves or throws.
Cover an ugly coffee table with a tapestry rug.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use books for texture and height. Stack them on the floor, on
tables to raise a lamp and under accessories in bookcases. Open
some to display beautiful pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
