<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's something primeval about a mushroom
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   July's scattered cloudbursts may have rained on a parade here
and a picnic there, but they made up for that by growing enough
mushrooms to make a million umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the number and variety I found during walks in the
garden and woods, that damp rot that hung around for weeks must
have been just what the fungi ordered. Turns out, the sogginess was
a kind of gardening opportunity, one that came in real handy
recently, as I didn't feel much like digging and pruning and
weeding in the wet.
</P>
<P>
   But hunting mushrooms hit the spot.
</P>
<P>
   With some 10,000 known types, the possibilities seem infinite.
From tiny to gigantic, in myriad colors, with and without stalks,
popping out of the ground or jutting from rotting stumps and logs,
they intrigue. Always have, from the time we children admired the
magical, mystical toadstool. To this day, I appreciate mushrooms
wherever they pop up _ in the forest or in my garden, where, like
mosses, they enhance my grass-free
</P>
<P>
   spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Once, I tried to grow them. On one of those logs that had been
``seeded'' with spores. Following directions, I kept it inside
until spring, then took the log outside and banged it on the ground
(to wake the sleeping spores?). I did everything but turn around in
three circles and murmur incantations, but no mushrooms appeared _
reminding me again of mosses; they grow where they are happy.
</P>
<P>
   There's something primeval about a mushroom; it is wonderfully
pungent, like the earth itself.
</P>
<P>
   It grows in dead wood and on lands laid bare, but it reeks of
life. And in another contradiction, its happy image also is
haunting for those of us who grew up in the 1940s and '50s,
watching killer bombs produce mushroom clouds.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Psilocybin Mushrooms of the World,'' published in 1996, one
of his several books on mushrooms, Paul Stamets notes that he has
found them everywhere, from canyons to waterfalls to ravines ``that
led into the heart of dormant volcanoes'' and calls mushrooms
symbols of ``the bridge between life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, that fantastically beautiful bridge can take you
right out of here. I look, but I don't eat, as I'm not expert
enough to identify edible mushrooms with certainty nor foolish
enough to eat them on a guess, even one bolstered by picture books.
</P>
<P>
   While I love the taste of good fungi _ morel, shiitake, oyster,
truffle, chanterelle come to mind _ I don't love them as much as
the rich man I recall reading about years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those stories that's as likely apocryphal as not, this
man ordered his cook to prepare a mess of mushrooms that had a
reputation for a heavenly taste. He knew they were quite deadly, as
are the two most often eaten mistakenly, the aptly named destroying
angel and death cap.
</P>
<P>
   After enjoying his meal of a lifetime, the man supposedly made
himself comfortable in his bed and said with a contented sigh,
``Now I can die in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   I must say, some of the mushrooms I saw recently were
tantalizingly beautiful. If looks determined taste, these would
have been to die for. Little red ones, with white-edged 1-inch caps
and raised white dots all over. Jewels.
</P>
<P>
   A brown-leather-looking one about 6 inches across grew curled
edges that gave it a saddlelike quality, looking for all the world
as if some creature from Lilliput had just dismounted and strolled
into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Clustered, one on top of another, three mushrooms the color of
creamed coffee stood on short stems amid decaying pine straw.
Nearby, a white one looked just like a pancake as the skillet's
heat pushes tiny holes through its uncooked side. Another one,
golden, resembled tea cakes waiting to be eaten. And one mimicked a
small black grapefruit half, fleshy side up, perched on a 3-inch
stalk.
</P>
<P>
   Most seductive on one hungry afternoon was a grouping that I
could swear was the delicious morel. I could almost swear.
</P>
<P>
   The maybe-morel stayed where it was, to entertain and entice
others. I remain a strictly ornamental mushroom man _ enjoying them
where they come.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
