<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKSHOP-VERDIGRIS29-     07-27 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-VERDIGRIS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Create a patina of time in minutes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, July 29.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill,
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the final installment in our Summer Workshop series, a
step-by-step guide to doing inexpensive weekend projects for the
home or garden. The Fall Workshop series will begin in September.
</P>
<P>
   Some people long for a home full of new furniture and
accessories. Others want their furnishings to have that weathered
or rustic look, without the benefit of time taking its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Brownlee, owner of Decor, an accent furniture and
accessories shop on Howell Mill Road in Atlanta, says the antique
look is easy to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The process of aging metal and some wood products is called
verdigris, and the simplest way to get this age-old look is with an
antique surface kit that contains a selection of copper, brass,
bronze or metal finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This look is very popular on the interior, and it certainly
works on the outside,'' Brownlee said. ``But on the inside it makes
objects look like a valuable antique.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplies:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patina Antiquing Kit, which includes cleaner; metal, copper,
brass or bronze finishes; gloves; sponges; brushes. (Depending on
size of object, more than one kit may be needed.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2 plastic cups (optional).
</P>
<P>
   Getting started:
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Using a brush, clean object with cleaner. Let dry for at
least 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Pour your choice of finish into a cup, or use from the
can. Paint first coat of finish on object and let dry for 30 to 45
minutes. (For a more rustic effect, apply sealer to first coat of
finish while it is sticky to the touch.)
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: Apply second coat of finish to the object. Final coat
can be poured on to make object appear as if it has aged naturally.
(You need at least two coats of finish.)
</P>
<P>
   Step 4: When desired rustic effect is achieved, brush on paint
sealer. The sealer stops the rusting process. Allow sealer to dry
thoroughly before putting object in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
