<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5491 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GORGEOUS-DIRECTO     07-27 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GORGEOUS-DIRECTOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKEN EMBRYO VIDEO PRECEDED FILM DIRECTOR'S DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' might be Michael Patrick
Jann's debut as a director of feature films, but it isn't the first
movie he ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Far from it. For that, you have to go all the way back to
the mid-1980s and the hallowed halls of Albany Academy.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jann's sophomore year. Somewhere he got ahold of a school
videocamera, and somehow he used it to make a short film as a
project for biology class. The subject? Chicken embryos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a funny little movie,'' recalls Jann, who was
born in Buffalo, moved to the Albany suburb of Colonie at age 6,
and now makes his home in southern California. ``That was the first
thing I actually shot and edited. It was like, `Here! I made
this!'''
</P>
<P>
   Jann doesn't actually chuckle _ his sense of humor is far too
dry _ but a sharp point of irony pokes through the self-effacement.
A half-hour phone interview is one torrent of words after another,
a downpour of comic musings that curl at the end with a Gen X lilt.
He's 29, he's smart, and his debut feature film is opening to a
loud media hum. He's also in a very good mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop Dead Gorgeous,'' a black-black-black comic mockumentary
about murder and mayhem in a small-town beauty pageant, premiered
July 12 to a large (and appreciative) Hollywood crowd. ``I
recommend everybody has their own Hollywood premiere.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, he says, ``really, really cool.'' Jann doesn't say ``gee
whiz,'' but you can hear the amazement in his voice _ the stunned
realization that, yikes, this Hollywood Thing is happening to him.
He's wary of the industry's endless glad-handing (``No one will say
anything nasty about you, but they'll think terrible things about
you'') and suspects he'll always be a bit of an interloper.
``Certainly I'm an outsider _ the oddball,'' he says. ``But I'd
rather be that. I'd rather be the guy who's unique.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he is. First, he managed to turn around a
mainstream, studio-backed picture for less than $10 million.
Second, he managed to get it made at all. Mean little mock
documentaries with a tone best described as noir-meets-Mary Kay
Cosmetics-on-a-tractor don't get made every day.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a fictitious small town in Minnesota (actually a pastiche
of seven small towns), ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' stars Kirsten Dunst
and Denise Richards as beauty pageant contestants, Ellen Barkin as
Dunst's rough-trade mom and Kirstie Alley as Richards' demon mother
from hell. The film follows these and others through several weeks
of pageant preparation, during which one character dies on an
exploding thresher, another grafts her hand to a detonating beer
and a third expires while riding a gaseous parade float.
</P>
<P>
   It's all-or-nothing humor: You either bust a gut or wince. Any
movie in which the heroine says ``I owe my life to that deaf baby''
and gets a laugh doing it isn't the sort of multiplex fodder we've
grown accustomed to. The director accepts that. In screenings,
``about halfway through the movie it reaches a critical mass, where
people just can't stop laughing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier for people to enjoy it. ... But sometimes
people are sitting there saying, `Should I laugh at this? Is it OK
to laugh at this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jann is probably best known as a member of The State, a New York
University comedy troupe that found fame a few years back on MTV
and, briefly, CBS. Since then he's made his mark in commercials,
directing spots for Sprite and Roundtable Pizza, among others. ``I
have no other skills. I'm really glad that this worked out, because
otherwise, I'd be landscaping at the Holiday Inn at Wolf Road'' _
which, it turns out, he used to do.
</P>
<P>
   He was the assistant groundskeeper, way back when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' came to be when Jann, combing through
scripts, stumbled across Lona Williams' biting screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just jumped out,'' he says. Williams knew whereof she
wrote, having been a Minnesota Junior Miss title holder and
runner-up in the national pageant. ``People see (the movie) and
say, `Oh my God, it's so absurd, it's so over-the-top, it's so
weird' _ and stuff like that. But most of the things in it are
fairly realistic. It's kind of the entire history of beauty
pageants, condensed into one pageant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jann has nothing against small-town America or Minnesota in
particular, he emphasizes. To the contrary. ``There was a feeling
about Minnesota that reminded me of upstate New York. People were
kind of friendly, and they weren't really fast-talking. ... It was
kind of low-key, nice, a kind of ersatz charm.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Albany area (his mother still lives in Colonie), ``I
really like it up there. It's a fabulous place to raise children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' was originally titled ``Dairy Queens,''
but the venerable ice-cream chain, not charmed by the humor in
Jann's dark romp, sued. Jann finds in this cause for a bone-dry bon
mot.
</P>
<P>
   ``(DQ owner) Warren Buffett is not known for his sense of humor
_ that's not in the Who's Who,'' he says. ``It doesn't say, `Warren
Buffett, corporate executive, noted for his sense of humor.'''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the title swap, he's pleased with the final product.
``I was saying to (Williams) that now that we've finished the
movie, there's a certain sort of anticlimax to it. You finish it
and you're proud of it,'' he says. ``But then, the only thing both
of us wanted was for every man, woman and child to walk up to us
and say, `Nice job.' We just wanted that acknowledgment from
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lull following ``Gorgeous,'' Jann plans to make a few
more ads (``pump up that bank account'') and direct a Fox
television pilot from one of the writers for ``Seinfeld.'' After
that, maybe another feature film _ a script he wrote, another
comedy, called ``You Are Going To Prison.'' And who knows? Maybe
he'll spread his wings, do something else _ a big fat action flick
or a brooding drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know about Arnold Schwarzenegger,'' he says,
when the idea is proffered to him. ``But I just love movies. I
think that I have a sense of comedy _ that's just what I've been
doing for the past 10 years. That's my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would love to branch out into other things and work in
different genres. I really like old Hollywood movies, all the
different genres _ your detective movies, your war movies. I'd love
to make a western. I love that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute _ there's a western dance in ``Drop Dead
Gorgeous.'' ``That's right,'' he says. ``I wanna make the first
all-line-dancing musical.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
