<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-IMPACT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMICIDES CREATE UNEASE AT YOSEMITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK and MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ Four recent homicides in the
Yosemite area have taken a heavy toll on park employees, especially
because the latest victim belonged to their own tight-knit
community.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly death last week of Joie Armstrong, a naturalist with
the Yosemite Institute, hit home more than other recent incidents
in the park, said Peter Werner, a bartender at the park's historic
and upscale Ahwahnee hotel and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The murders of the three women was one thing,'' he said,
referring to the deaths in February of tourists Carole Sund, her
daughter Juli and family friend Silvina Pelosso. ``But this other
woman was an employee and we knew her.''
</P>
<P>
   Peer counselors have met with 80 to 100 National Park Service
employees since Friday, said team leader Scott Brown. He said
employees have felt a flood of emotions _ anger, grief, fear _ and
they did not ebb with the arrest of Cary Stayner and reports that
the 37-year-old handyman has confessed to all four killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``During an instance like this, emotions are constantly
changing,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, hundreds of Armstrong's friends and members of her
family gathered in the park for an outdoor memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   John Carlstroem, executive director of the Headlands Institute,
where Armstrong had once been employed as a field instructor, said
plans were being shaped for some kind of a lasting memorial tribute
to Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The somber mood in El Portal, the tiny town near the park
entrance where many of Armstrong's colleagues live, was mixed
Monday with a growing anger directed at reporters who have invaded
their usually quiet and laid-back community.
</P>
<P>
   At the El Portal Market, next to the Yosemite Institute, a group
of locals sitting on the shady porch steps shouted at an
approaching reporter to go away. Inside, the cashier complained
about dozens of reporters who called him. He said he hung up on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Television news vans were parked outside Cedar Lodge, where the
FBI continued to question employees about Stayner. One employee,
who declined to give his name, complained that all this attention
is scaring away business.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Cedar Lodge, where Stayner has worked and lived
intermittently for almost two years, was booked solid Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
