<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-27 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: LESSONS FROM BORDEAUX'S UP-AND-DOWN PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``From the moment when you start to think of wine as an
investment and not as something to be drunk, that's the end,'' Elie
de Rothschild said almost 30 years ago, when he was managing
partner of Chateau Lafite-Rothschild in Bordeaux. His words,
applied to today's frenzied market, are still wise, if anyone will
heed them.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the Bordeaux wine market had gone mad. After a string
of mediocre vintages, the world was ready for a good Bordeaux, and
1970 supplied that demand. Americans, for the first time, had
become important players in the Bordeaux market. Thanks to the
publicity engendered by the excellent 1959 and the legendary 1961
vintages, Bordeaux sales to the United States had been increasing
10 percent a year through the 1960s. In 1969, they increased 50
percent from the prior year. The value of good older vintages shot
up as well.
</P>
<P>
   As de Rothschild said, Bordeaux wine had changed from a drink to
an investment. But his timing was a bit off; it wasn't until 1973
that the Bordeaux market collapsed, and it took almost a decade
before the market fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Since those days, a new generation of wine drinkers _ and wine
investors _ has appeared on the scene, just as eager to pay any
price for high-end Bordeaux wines and to hold them as investments
rather than to consume. The Bordeaux trade has gone through
fundamental changes since the early 1970s but there are few signs
that it is any less susceptible to the boom-and-bust cycles of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   New investors in Bordeaux with little sense of the past and big
spenders who think the party will go on indefinitely would do well
to read ``The Winemasters of Bordeaux,'' Nicholas Faith's absorbing
book about the Bordeaux wine trade. First published in 1978, it has
been thoroughly updated and just released by Prion ($29.95). Given
the current state of the Bordeaux market, with wines like Chateau
Petrus selling for $500 a bottle and more, Faith could not have
chosen a more opportune time to reissue his book.
</P>
<P>
   Faith, a former business editor of The Sunday Times of London
and a contributor to The Financial Times, first explains Bordeaux's
beginnings as a medieval trading center. But he concentrates on the
wine trade's long, painful transformation from a fusty,
inward-looking community based on family ties, to a business that
has opened itself to the modern world, though somewhat grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, he writes about the rise and fall of the Chartronnais,
the small group of powerful merchants, mostly of foreign origin,
who controlled the Bordeaux market for two centuries. Originally
banned from the center of Bordeaux by the local wine merchants, the
foreigners, who came from Germany, Scandinavia, Britain and
Ireland, settled just outside the city along the Quai des
Chartrons. Beginning with the export markets to their countries of
origin, the Chartronnais came to dominate the entire Bordeaux wine
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of the Chartronnais families _ the Cruses, the
Eschenauers, the Bartons and the Johnstons _ began to wane after
World War II. To Faith, it was Baron Philippe de Rothschild, who
took over his family's property, Mouton-Rothschild, just after
World War I, who began to change things. Traditionally, the
Chartronnais bought wine from the chateaus, bottled it, aged it,
sold it and shipped it. Philippe de Rothschild chose to do it all
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually many other chateau owners did the same, taking
control of their own wine. In 1973, the most powerful of all the
Chartronnais families, the Cruses, were convicted of buying cheap
wine and selling it as higher-quality Bordeaux. The trial, which
became known as Winegate, made it clear that many of the merchant
families had routinely done the same.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 1971 and 1972 vintages were of indifferent quality,
investors snapped them up. With prices still high and a glut of
wine from the enormous 1973 crop, demand began to drop rapidly. The
world oil crisis and, to some extent, suspicions raised by the
Winegate affair turned off would-be buyers. Investors who bought
the 1971 and 1972 wines before they had been bottled watched
helplessly as the prices of those wines plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   The golden days quickly ended, as they almost inevitably will
again. How long will the current boom last? In this country, at
least, as long as the economy, which fuels it, continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Will Bordeaux survive the next crisis? Almost certainly, as it
has each crisis in the past. The Chartronnais are gone, and so for
the most part are the international liquor companies that invested
in the chateaus for a time. A new breed, including insurance
companies and wealthy private individuals, has moved in.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the old families who had been under the thumb of the
Chartronnais have come to the fore. They are typified by
Jean-Michel Cazes, who owns Chateau Lynch-Bages in Pauillac and Les
Ormes-de-Pez in St.-Estephe. He also manages half a dozen
properties, including Chateau Pichon-Baron in Pauillac for AXA, an
insurance company with wine investments in France, Portugal and
Hungary. Like many of the new Bordeaux wine merchants, he was
educated in the United States and is at home selling wine anywhere
in world.
</P>
<P>
   The prestige of owning a Bordeaux chateau has always been high
and, if anything, has grown over the last 15 years, when so many
vintages have been good to superb. But as Faith shows and as any
serious wine buyer should know, the Bordeaux wine trade is like no
other business anywhere. To sum it up, Faith, paraphrasing Winston
Churchill's description of democracy, calls it ``the worst system
ever invented, except all the others that anyone has ever thought
of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESSERTS-ART-2TAKES-N     07-27 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LONG LAST, BANQUET: THE NEW DESSERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In one night at Gramercy Tavern, I had a dish of
creamy lemon panna cotta, a coconut tapioca pudding with cilantro
syrup, a chocolate ganache cake, an intense chocolate caramel tart,
a scoop of burned caramel ice cream, and bay leaf ice cream, too, a
chestnut cookie, a black currant gelee, a chocolate filled with
hazelnut cream, an orange macaroon and a white chocolate square
with toasted coconut.
</P>
<P>
   And all I did was order dessert.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of experience that sticks fast in your mind, but
these days it's not all that uncommon. Starting with a small taste
before the dessert and then progressing to a flight of desserts
arranged on a plate and a petit four selection that looks more like
a pastry shop, dessert is becoming a longer, more sophisticated and
often outrageous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Until about five years ago, dessert in American restaurants had
merely been a way to punctuate the end of a meal. A buttery pastry
and sweet apples, perhaps. Or a wallop of chocolate. It was
something clear and concise that told you it was time to get up
from the table and go home.
</P>
<P>
   But pastry chefs are being taken more seriously, with their
names on the menu and a celebrity quotient of their own. And their
patrons are going out to dinner in search less of sustenance than
of entertainment. The result: dessert has ballooned from a single
course to a banquet.
</P>
<P>
   Cello, a new restaurant on East 77th Street, leads diners into
dessert with a sorbet. The actual dessert follows, as does a whole
lot more: a petit four plate, a dish of chocolates and, with the
check, hot orange flower beignets. Cafe Boulud serves a similar
progression, starting with soup and ending with madeleines instead
of beignets.
</P>
<P>
   If you order the $93 fixed-price menu at March, you get sorbet
to start and almond pralines as a kicker, and in between a sampling
of three desserts off the regular menu. This sampling is also
available on the $68 menu. Eighty percent of diners order the
sampling, said Wayne Nish, the chef.
</P>
<P>
   Culinary schools are training the next generation to meet the
new demands. The French Culinary Institute in New York, for
instance, includes dessert composition, petits fours and tasting
plates in its curriculum. Pastry students are also required to dine
at restaurants and report back on the style and design of the
dessert menu.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the old days of the single dessert, Gramercy
Tavern's pastry chef, Claudia Fleming, said: ``I think when you
realize that nobody finished their desserts that you were very
limited in terms of your creativity. And for me the fun of eating
dessert is these little tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I had so many tiny courses at her restaurant,
working through a flavor spectrum starting with fruit and cream and
finishing with intense chocolate. Often, Ms. Fleming sneaks in
tasting plates, too, like permutations on apple _ an apple tart,
apple ice cream and an apple napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   At Union Pacific, diners can pay a supplement of $12 on the $65
fixed price menu for a ``flight of desserts.'' Three not-so-small
plates of dessert are delivered at once; as with a cheese plate,
the server describes the order in which to eat them. One evening, I
began with a peach goat cheese tart, moved on to a chicory bombe
with chocolate puff pastry ravioli and finished with a molten
chocolate cake. Temperatures flip-flopped from hot to cold to hot,
while the flavors progressed from sweet to smoky to bittersweet,
each richer than the next.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it was a bit much. By the time I got to the third
flight, the peanut butter ice cream on the chocolate cake was
melted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of this has to do with pastry chefs showing off
their range after a long period of time being stuck in the back
room,'' said Tish Boyle, an editor at Pastry Art and Design
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But all those sweets did make an impression that just one
dessert would not have. It was lavish and decadent, just the kind
of finale you feel you deserve from a top restaurant charging top
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Pastry chefs with less latitude may not be doling out as many
courses, but they are packing more onto a single plate. At Payard
Patisserie and Bistro, a tasting plate includes five pastries;
diners can choose their own. Oceana offers two samplers for an $8
supplement, with five mini-desserts on each plate.
</P>
<P>
   At Lespinasse, diners receive a sweet amuse-bouche before
dessert and petits fours after _ but just a single main dessert.
The menu always includes one option that is a tasting, like a
pineapple dessert of a pineapple beignet, pina colada sauce,
pineapple jam, pineapple tarragon sorbet and pineapple chips.
``It's a way of showing your ability to manipulate a flavor,'' said
Christopher Broberg, Lespinasse's pastry chef.
</P>
<P>
   Other pastry chefs are serving variations of the same dessert.
Rather than presenting a single large dish of vanilla creme brulee,
for instance, they serve a handful of tiny riffs on the theme. At
Bayard's, the creme brulees are peach, raspberry, vanilla, ginger
and banana. Each dish contains about three spoonfuls, enough to
enliven your palate before the intensity dissipates. Mercer Kitchen
squeezes four onto a plate, all based on tea flavors: citrus, Earl
Grey, chocolate mint and lemon verbena.
</P>
<P>
   Bayard's does not serve a sweet before dessert, but afterward
nine kinds of petits fours and a basket of freshly baked madeleines
arrive. The madeleines are warm, fragrant and bite-size. Before you
know it, you've eaten a half-dozen. Your last impression is pure
bliss or, more likely, bloat.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Luc Dendievel, the chef and pastry chef, is not concerned.
``Well, they eat them,'' he said. Being served madeleines on top of
everything else is part of the experience. ``It's a large room,
there's a big wine list _ everything here is big,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Broberg said, ``I think everywhere in New York now, everyone is
trying to make a lasting last impression.'' Understandably, many
pastry chefs relish making that last impression.
</P>
<P>
   Dessert has traditionally been peripheral to a meal. Like the
appetizer, it's optional. And that may be one reason that pastry
chefs in America have until recently lacked the respect accorded
the chefs producing appetizers and main courses.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Fleming, expanding the dessert course was partly
dictated by the restaurant and partly natural. Gramercy Tavern has
a fixed price menu of $62, but, she said, ``There's always a very
conscious effort to provide good value and to provide unexpected
pleasures and courses and things that haven't been ordered.'' She
also found that she wanted to emulate the chef, Tom Colicchio. ``I
wanted to do what Tom was doing. I wanted to serve three courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Other restaurants have the opposite philosophy of dessert. At
Chanterelle, dessert is reserved and traditional: one plate and
then petits fours. ``For me, intellectually,'' said Karen Waltuck,
an owner, ``the meal ends in a very solid way after the main course
and before cheese. Everything that has come before is taken off the
table _ extra glasses, salt and pepper, bread, butter, crumbs.''
   Dessert, the last imprint of the meal, she said, ``should end
with a certain opulence and generosity and whimsy, but you don't
have to do that with more than one course; people are very full.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, volume never seems to matter. Petit four plates
almost never go untested. Lespinasse even gives a wicker basket to
transport any extras home.
</P>
<P>
   At Park Avenue Cafe, diners should get a shopping cart. The
petit four plate has 14 tastes. Chef David Burke was one of the
first in New York to put dessert on a pedestal _ literally. When he
was at River Cafe in the late 1980s, he served petits fours on a
petit four, a miniature cast-iron oven, containing burning
cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there's the petit four tree at Le Cirque 2000. In
addition to Jacque Torres' exaggeratedly large desserts, you may
get a chocolate tree dangling with hazelnut chocolate squares,
cherries and tuiles.
</P>
<P>
   With their new, larger role, pastry chefs face a much more
imposing obstacle _ blending their style with that of the cuisine.
Ideally a meal should be like one long cohesive conversation
sprinkled with ideas and thoughts that meld rather than contradict.
</P>
<P>
   And in most cases, pastry chefs must still defer to the chef. At
Lespinasse, for instance, Broberg purposely mimics the style of his
four-star boss, Christian Delouvrier. ``I look how he sauces his
foie gras,'' he said. ``I look at how he sauces his lamb.'' Then he
applies the same philosophy to his desserts. ``It shouldn't be so
different, either,'' he said. ``Otherwise it's going to be jarring
to the guest.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept seems logical enough, but intellectual harmony
between cuisine and pastry is something of a novel concept.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago at Le Bernardin, for instance, the cuisine
and desserts were out of sync. The style of the chef, Eric Ripert,
was simple and unadorned, the refinement left uniquely in the
flavors of the dish. The desserts, though, were much more
monumental and decorative. Cookies looked as if they had been cut
to shape with a ruler and an Exacto knife. Chocolate tarts were
pristine. After eating an amuse-bouche and two courses of Ripert's
food, it felt like putting on a frilly dress after wearing jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Then in October 1997 he hired a new pastry chef, Florian
Bellanger. ``Until Florian came, I always let the pastry chef do
what he wanted,'' he said. ``I wanted to have the pastry chef
closer to the kitchen and closer to the idea of what I had in mind
for the fish.'' Their styles have merged, but it is a work in
progress, Ripert said. Ultimately, he would like to treat the
components of the desserts with the same reverence with which he
treats fish. ``If we do a peach dessert,'' he said, ``we have to
find the best peach, like we do with the fish. Then the peach is
the star of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bouley Bakery, pastry chef Bill Yosses likens the diner's
experience to a journey. ``They've been through these nuances of
taste and texture up until they get to dessert, and it seems that
should continue through the dessert experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He eases diners from their savory world gently, with either a
clean-tasting, lightly acidic fruit soup or a dish of cheese and
fruit, like the mellow blue fourme d'Ambert with a roasted pear.
Restraint ends there. After that, diners are his to indulge. They
order a main dessert. But extra plates _ like chocolate brioche
pudding, sable breton or whatever Yosses thinks they should sample
as their journey nears its end _ could come their way without
warning. Then, of course, there are the petits fours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chefs had their epiphany with nouvelle cuisine in the '70s,
and pastry chefs haven't had that yet,'' Yosses said. ``Maybe
that's what the year 2000 is all about. The dessert messiah is
coming; the end is near.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure. The end of the meal is getting farther and
farther away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
