A5574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TARIFFS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TARIFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING IMPACT OF NEW TARIFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Washington imposes 100 percent duties on an array of
European foods Thursday, as announced last week, the effect may be
less a bang than a ripple. The prices of Roquefort cheese, Dijon
mustard, tins of foie gras and fresh truffles could double. But for
the most part, it seems that the impact will not shake the consumer
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The tariffs, meant to pressure countries in the European Union
to lift a ban on American beef raised with hormones, apply to a
tangled shopping list of items. Foods as common as Dijon mustard
and rusks are affected, but so are preserved and prepared goose or
other liver products and juices made from one fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Nish, the chef and an owner of March restaurant, is upset
over the prospect of prices doubling for fresh truffles, especially
the white ones, which are starting to become available now. They
flavor and perfume up to a dozen dishes on his menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We charge a $50 supplement for some of the dishes and we just
about break even,'' he said. ``But I don't think people will pay
$100.''
</P>
<P>
   Black truffles, which are also affected by the increase, can be
replaced with the frozen or canned variety.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared or preserved Italian, French and German tomatoes
(except any in vinegar) are also on the list, meaning the price of
San Marzano and sun-dried tomatoes could double in supermarkets and
for restaurateurs. Filled chocolate bars from France and French
lingonberry and raspberry preserves will also be subject to the
tariffs, along with French and German soups.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the other items, like fresh or frozen pork and beef
products used by food processors, are not sold directly to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Some stores, including Zabar's, say they will try to work with
suppliers to adjust prices so that the total increase is not passed
on to the consumer. But others, like Citarella, are taking a harder
line. ``If it's a 100 percent tariff we'll double the price,'' Joe
Gurrera, Citarella's owner, said.
</P>
<P>
   If Waldbaum's price of a 13.4-ounce jar of Maille mustard
imported from France goes from $3.06 to $6.12, as may eventually
happen once the jars now in the warehouse are sold, it won't be as
damaging to the food budget as a wedge of Roquefort.
</P>
<P>
   Roquefort may become such a high-end luxury it will no longer be
sold in supermarkets. At Zabar's, Papillon brand is $12.98 a pound
and Societe is $11.98 a pound. The store has stocked up on enough
for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the suppliers or the manufacturers will arrange a
promotional discount so the price won't have to double,'' Olga
Dominguez, the cheese buyer for Zabar's, said.
</P>
<P>
   Petrossian expects prices on its truffled foie gras prepared in
France to increase as the tariffs are factored in. ``We took the
precaution of bringing in some extra stuff, but it won't hold us
through the holiday season,'' said Eve Vega, the company's director
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh white truffles that have Nish worried may not be
priced out of reach after all. In his head, Nish doubled last
year's prices, which ranged from $900 to $1,800 a pound, depending
on the quality.
</P>
<P>
   But last year was a poor season. Rosario Safina, an owner of
Urbani USA, an importer in Queens, N.Y., said this is expected to
be a very good year, with plentiful truffles selling for much less,
$600 to $800 a pound. After the duty is applied, the prices may not
be much higher than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   The increased tariffs are intended to offset the $116.8 million
lost annually by American beef producers because of the ban.
Intensive lobbying by importers got some high-profile products off
the original list published last spring, like bottled water and
prosciutto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
