<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TASTINGS: A RED SEEKING A NEW IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lang &AMP; Reed Cabernet Franc 1997, Napa Valley, Calif. About $18.
</P>
<P>
   Cabernet franc is the vinous equivalent of the decent guy in the
movies who never gets the girl. It's always there, but never seems
to rise to star status. One exception comes to mind: Chateau Cheval
Blanc, one of the most famous properties in St.-Emilion. The
magnificent wine of Cheval Blanc is invariably a blend of
two-thirds bouchet, which is what cabernet franc is called in that
part of the world, and merlot.
</P>
<P>
   Cabernet franc is also the grape in Bourgueil, Chinon and
Saumur-Champigny in the Loire Valley. Washington state has produced
some fine cabernet francs, and so has New York's Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   California has produced its share of good ones, but the wine has
yet to emerge as an important varietal. Lang &AMP; Reed, a new winery
in the Napa Valley, is among those hoping to create a new image for
the grape. Its version is worth trying. It has the intensity of a
good cabernet sauvignon, plenty of fruit and an intriguing bouquet,
but the structure is leaner and less complex. And it isn't marred
by too much oak. Unlike so many merlots, which can be mistaken for
cabernet sauvignon, this wine has its own attractive personality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
