A5579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      07-27 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THICKENER FROM SEAWEED  
 SORTING OUT VANILLA EXTRACTS  
 DRUGS IN SALMON  
 GUNPOWDER GREEN TEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I want to make vanilla pudding for a vegetarian friend, so I
cannot use gelatin, which contains animal products, as a thickener.
As a substitute, is agar-agar any better than cornstarch? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Agar-agar, which is also called kanten or Japanese gelatin,
is a flavorless dried seaweed usually sold in powder form or in
long strips or sheets. Dishes made with agar-agar will set and
remain firm without refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   In a pudding, the difference between cornstarch and agar-agar is
one of texture.
</P>
<P>
   Cornstarch leaves puddings with an ever so slight gritty, floury
texture. (Think of packaged instant puddings, which are usually
cornstarch-based.). Agar-agar results in a wobbly, slightly
rubbery, Jello-like texture. It's really a matter of preference.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know that pure vanilla extract is better than artificial,
but I have noticed differences in strength and flavor even among
pure vanillas. There is also a large price range among many brands.
What are the best? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Vanilla beans, and therefore vanilla extracts, vary greatly
in terms of quality and price.
</P>
<P>
   Extracts made from Madagascan beans are commonly considered the
best. Tahiti, too, produces superior, extremely aromatic beans.
Look for brands that list only vanilla and alcohol among their
ingredients; cheaper brands may be diluted with water.
</P>
<P>
   Penzey's Spice House, a mail-order source (414-679-7207), sells
a vanilla extract that uses twice as many Madagascan beans as
regular extracts, making it so intense that you should use half as
much as recipes call for. The extract, called Double Strength
Vanilla, is $9.95 for a four-ounce bottle. Penzey's also sells
Single Strength Vanilla, at $6.95 for four ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The Baker's Catalog (800-827-6836) offers Madagascan Bourbon
vanilla extract at $6.25 for four ounces.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, most specialty shops have a variety of fine
vanilla extracts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Zabar's (2245 Broadway, between 80th and 81st
Streets; 212-787-2000) sells Nielsen-Massey Madagascan Organic
Bourbon vanilla extract at $6.98 for a four-ounce bottle; a
four-ounce bottle of the company's Madagascan Bourbon extract, is
$4.98.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Since most salmon are farm-raised, how can one find out if
the fish have been fed hormone-laced or antibiotic feed?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fish farming in the United States is tightly controlled, and
the use of antibiotics and hormones is virtually nonexistent, said
Dr. Michael B. Timmons, a professor of agriculture and biological
engineering at Cornell University and the director of the Cornell
aquaculture program.
</P>
<P>
   Imported fish, however, are not subject to controls, and farmers
outside the United States may treat problems in their stock with
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Since fresh fish is not labeled, it is up to the customer to try
to find out where it came from. (The fishmonger should know.)
Besides salmon, tilapia and catfish are also farmed.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently, I received a box of Special Gunpowder China Green
Tea. Why is it called gunpowder? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Gunpowder green tea is drunk widely in China, and like all
green teas, it has a fresh, herbal flavor. It is made by rolling
dried green tea leaves into tight, tiny balls. This helps the tea
stay fresh and therefore retain its flavor longer than other green
teas.
</P>
<P>
   When boiling water is poured over the rolled pellets, they burst
open like flower buds, perfuming the brew.
</P>
<P>
   The tea's name is said to have come from a young British tea
trader, who, upon seeing the little tea pellets, decided they
resembled gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York
10036-3959, or by e-mail to dining(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
