<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      07-27 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE COOKING: PUREEING A MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipes at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the time of year when you can lose your mind buying fruit.
After so many months of barely acceptable produce, now the fruit is
marvelous and cheap, so naturally, when you stop at the farm stand,
you don't buy just one peach. You might just bring home a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   While everybody knows what to do with an excess of tomatoes
(make vats of sauce), a peach glut is a real problem _ unless you
learn to use fruit more creatively. Fruit purees, for instance, are
underappreciated in the home kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit purees are a staple of the restaurant kitchen, an
easy-to-make base for delicious and unusual sauces, dressings,
sorbets and other frozen desserts, and an all-purpose way to add
flavor to both sweet and savory dishes. It's impossible not to
appreciate something so versatile _ and so beautiful on the plate _
that takes just minutes to produce and requires no equipment beyond
a blender.
</P>
<P>
   With a little added butter or oil and fresh herbs, fruit purees
form the backbone of great sauces for meat or fish. They add
beguiling flavor to otherwise standard vinaigrettes. Add sugar and
a spice and, with the aid of an ice cream machine, they produce
four-star sorbets. (You can also make granitas with them or swirl
them into ice creams.) Fruit purees, sweetened, salted or otherwise
seasoned, make bright toppings for ice cream, cakes or cereal. Or
stir them into yogurt, enhance reductions or barbecue sauces or use
them as the basis of cold fruit soup.
</P>
<P>
   You can even freeze them as ice cubes to add flavor to iced tea
or mixed drinks. (Remember that although all the accompanying
recipes use specific fruits, you can experiment freely,
substituting one for the other without giving it much thought.)
</P>
<P>
   There are just two requirements for fruit that you intend to
turn into a puree. The first is that it be ripe, well ripe, even a
tad overly ripe. In fact, the puree is the first thing your mind
should turn to when confronted with the question ``What was I
thinking when I bought all these peaches?''
</P>
<P>
   The second is that the fruit should be easy to clean and, if
necessary, pit. Grapes, for example, will not do, nor will
cherries. Pits and skins must be removed before pureeing, and
fruits like these make that task formidable. Strawberries,
raspberries and blueberries are all good candidates, but if you
strain out the tiny seeds (and in the case of blueberries, bits of
skin) the puree becomes thinner and loses some bulk. More trouble
than it's worth, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The best fruits for pureeing are those that carry some weight. I
have had great success with the stone fruits: peaches, nectarines
and especially plums, which seem to become more assertive. Melons
also work well, especially firm cantaloupe, which is not too watery
and requires almost no effort whatsoever. And pineapple puree is
simply irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Making purees follows a predictable pattern. A stone fruit must
be peeled; do this by immersing it in boiling water for about 30
seconds, or until the skin loosens, then plunging it into ice water
to stop the cooking. At that point, the skin comes off easily with
a paring knife. Cut the fruit into halves or quarters, remove the
pits and it is ready for the blender.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, about a pound of fruit will produce just over a cup
of puree.
</P>
<P>
   Melons are even easier: cut them in half, remove the seeds and
scoop out the pulp with a spoon. A smallish melon, around two
pounds, yields about two cups of puree.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapples must be rid of all hard, prickly elements, which
takes some work. First cut off both ends. Stand the pineapple on
its broad end and cut it into quarters the long way. Cut off the
half-inch-wide band of woody material that runs along the long
angled edge of each quarter. Now remove the fruit from the skin;
it's easiest if you cut under it with a grapefruit knife. Cut the
meat into chunks.
</P>
<P>
   The pureeing itself takes a few minutes. Cram the fruit into the
blender, literally pushing it down onto the blades and squeezing
some of the water from it. This will help get the machine started
and should make it easy to puree the fruit without any intervention
or added liquid. If the machine is having trouble, turn it off and
use a wooden spoon or rubber spatula to mash the fruit down onto
the blades.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit purees are stable, but their flavor is fleeting and
becomes less intense with every passing hour. Use them right away,
but if necessary, they can be refrigerated in a tightly covered
container for a day.
</P>
<P>
   PLUM PUREE SAUCE FOR GRILLED MEATS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plum puree
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the butter in a small saucepan, and turn the heat to
medium. Cook, shaking the pan occasionally, until it turns light
brown, about 5 minutes. Lower the heat, and stir in the puree.
Cook, stirring, about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the other ingredients, and serve within 10 minutes, or
keep warm over the lowest possible flame, stirring occasionally,
for up to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cup (4 to 6 servings).
</P>
<P>
   PEACH PUREE VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   { cup peach puree
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup balsamic or sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   10 leaves fresh basil, washed.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all of the ingredients in a blender and blend until they
are smooth. Use within 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 cup (enough to dress 6 to 8 cups of greens).
</P>
<P>
   PINEAPPLE-GINGER SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus freezing
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pineapple puree
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons very finely minced fresh or candied ginger, or {
teaspoon dried ginger, or to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the sugar and ginger into the puree and freeze the mixture
in an ice cream maker, according to the manufacturer's directions.
This sorbet is best when it is served straight from the machine, or
after it has spent no more than an hour or two in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 pint.
</P>
<P>
   MELON SAUCE FOR STEAMED, GRILLED OR ROASTED FISH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup melon puree
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup minced cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all ingredients except the cilantro. Taste and adjust
seasoning as necessary, and set aside to let the flavors meld.
(Meanwhile, you can cook the fish.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Just before serving, stir in the cilantro. Make a puddle of
the sauce on each of four plates and top with a piece of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 cup (4 to 6 servings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
