<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-OUTLOOK-2TAKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS, CONCERNS SURROUND THE 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By Lowell Cohn   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Every year it's the same thing. We wonder
if this is the season the 49ers finally will drop out of the NFL
elite, becoming just another ordinary team. And every year, the
49ers embarrass the doubters by making it to the playoffs, although
lately the Super Bowl has been beyond their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again. Once more the 49ers are a team loaded with
questions, except this season there are more than usual:
</P>
<P>
   _ Is the offense still a potent machine?
</P>
<P>
   This is a major question, although it's not the biggest
question. (The BIG ONE will be revealed later.) The standard
thinking is that with Steve Young, Terrell Owens, J.J. Stokes and
Jerry Rice, the 49ers always will score tons of points. In other
words, we're not supposed to worry about the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But that thinking is limited. Another way to phrase this
equation is to say the Niners have a great quarterback and three
fabulous receivers. And that's it. Period. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've forgotten, the 49ers need a running back. And the
reason is simple. When they didn't have a threat in the backfield
(See the Derek Loville Years), defenses piled on Young. He lost
confidence in himself and his offensive line, and he suffered
concussions and hurt his arm. So a running back like Garrison
Hearst keeps everything in balance and keeps Young alive.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that the Niners have the runner they need.
They've lost their top four backs from last season. Hearst is
seriously injured; Terry Kirby is gone and so is Chuck Levy.
General manager Bill Walsh traded fullback Marc Edwards, which made
several assistant coaches gag. Walsh replaced Edwards with Tommy
Vardell who is six years older and doesn't block as well. This is
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Phillips is supposed to be the answer to the question
at tailback. Until now, all the talk about Phillips has focused on
the fact that he's a thug. (Oh, sure, he's allegedly become an
angel. Seeing is believing.) But his character is not the issue
here. His ability is.
</P>
<P>
   We already know he couldn't play for Dick Vermeil or Jimmy
Johnson. He was effective in college and Europe where he was
bigger, stronger and faster than the guys he played against. In the
NFL he isn't, which may explain why he's averaged only 3.3 yards
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Garner also will get time at tailback. He's a willing
contributor, but at 5-9 he's too small. He's a third-down back,
someone to catch a pass, to change the pace. And he's certainly not
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Think about this. When Hearst went down, the Niners lost the No.
3 rusher in the league, and so far they have not improved
themselves at all, or even gotten back to where they were.
</P>
<P>
   _ How good is the offensive line?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is unknown. The 49ers have two holes to fill because
Kevin Gogan and Kirk Scrafford are gone. Derrick Deese, a perennial
replacement, will probably take over for Gogan at right guard. And
either Jeremy Newberry or Chris Ruhman will be right tackle, an
important position because this guy protects Young's back.
</P>
<P>
   In the past everyone could feel confident the line would come
together. That was because of coach Bobb McKittrick, the best in
the business. But McKittrick is seriously ill and may have limited
input in the game plan. Pat Morris, who coached the tight ends last
season, has taken over the line. We don't know if he's as good as
McKittrick. Which means there's yet anther question requiring an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do the 49ers have an adequate backup quarterback to Steve
Young?
</P>
<P>
   In a way this is an unfair question. Sure, the Niners would be
cooked without Young, but most teams die without their starting
quarterback. Having said that, it's important to point out that
last season the 49ers had Ty Detmer, a former starter, backing up
Young. This season the drop-off is steeper.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner for second banana seems to be Jeff Garcia, who
played well in Canada, but did not impress in mini-camp. Steve
Stenstrom played for Walsh at Stanford and was a fine college
quarterback. He must prove himself in the NFL. Jim Druckenmiller?
He'll be gone soon. At least he should be.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now we come to the big question, to the most important issue
facing the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can the defense stop anyone?
</P>
<P>
   A positive answer here is crucial because defense wins ball
games. Remember all those great Joe Montana teams? Sure Montana was
special, but what made those teams consistent winners, what kept
the Niners in the game was the defense which consisted of guys like
Ronnie Lott, Eric Wright, Hacksaw Reynolds, Fred Dean, etc.
</P>
<P>
   So we start with the defensive line, and we notice that three
important contributors from last season are gone: Chris Doleman,
Roy Barker and, of course, Bryant Young, who may not return until
midseason. The loss of Young is particularly horrible because he
was San Francisco's best performer on defense, perhaps the best
player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Niners hope their No. 1 draft selection, tackle Reggie
McGrew, can pick up the slack because, quite simply, a team that
can't stop the run is in trouble. But McGrew missed mini-camps with
knee problems. They need him to be an impact player out of the
gate.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the issue of the pass rush. The 49ers were so
freaked about not having one that they signed Charles Haley. This
is highly scary. Not only because Haley has a tendency to go nutso,
but also because Haley has a bad back and could fall apart at any
second. End Gabe Wilkins should help now that his knee is healthy.
But he still has to prove himself on the field.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are the 49ers cornerbacks former Munchkins?
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't noticed, these guys are midgets. The
incumbents, R.W. McQuarters and Darnell Walker, are 5-9 and 5-8.
Walsh was concerned about having a couple of shrimps back there, so
he drafted two more corners, Anthony Parker and Pierson Prioleau.
Unfortunately, neither was impressive in mini-camp. After seeing
them, Walsh picked up Marc McMillian. He may be San Francisco's
best cover man, but he's only 5-7. You get the impression tall
receivers will go wild against the Niners secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Merton Hanks will again start at free safety. He was awful last
season, so much so that Walsh badmouthed him after taking over, and
said he'd cut Hanks from the squad. That never happened. Hanks
promised to do better this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McDonald returns at strong safety. He is really good.
Really, really good.
</P>
<P>
   The Niners linebackers are generally solid and above average.
Winfred Tubbs took over Gary Plummer's role last season but seemed
miscast. He has to show he can take on interior linemen and make
more tackles at the line of scrimmage. Oh, by the way, last year
Jim Mora coached the defensive backs. This year he's defensive
coordinator. That raises another obvious question: Is he ready?
Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the infighting at the ownership level affect the team?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Last year, there was uncertainty about Eddie
DeBartolo Jr., Carmen Policy and Dwight Clark. But what went on
with them never bothered the team. In fact, the players couldn't
have cared less. So this year's Eddie/Denise soap opera should be a
non-issue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ Can the team survive Bill Walsh's philosophy?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his reign in San Francisco, George Seifert was
criticized for being shortsighted because he signed older free
agents. How was his strategy any different from Walsh's?
</P>
<P>
   We've seen Walsh go after Haley and Vardell, both moves of
desperation. He went after Phillips, not old, but troubled.
Phillips is someone Walsh wouldn't have touched in the past. Walsh
gives the impression of frantically trying to get back to the Super
Bowl while he still has Steve Young and Rice. Whether or not he can
succeed is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   _ How good will the 49ers be?
</P>
<P>
   This is a tough one. In the areas where they're still good,
quarterback and wide receivers, the Niners are terrific. They play
in a weak division, and frankly, the NFC as a whole is no big deal.
How can it be with teams like the Lions, Redskins, Saints, Cowboys
and Eagles? So you figure the Niners can make the playoffs by
default.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they play road games in Jacksonville,
Arizona, Minnesota and Atlanta. They've not won an away game
against a team that finished with a winning record since 1996. So,
yes, there are questions.
</P>
<P>
   You could see the Niners ending up with a record of 8-8, or they
could win 13 games. But to do the latter, they'd need positive
answers to most of their questions, especially about cornerback,
defensive line (Haley in particular), and Phillips. My guess is
they'll win 11, and qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
