u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOAN-BAEZ-NYTR &LR;      07-27 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOAN-BAEZ-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAN BAEZ BATTLES HER WAY BACK TO THE LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MEG McCONAHEY   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depending on the content, it can be deeply flattering to get an
advance reading of one's own elegy. Yet, for 58-year-old Joan Baez
_ still very much exercising her silky soprano in the studio and on
stage _ the very idea of being prematurely written off as a '60s
legend, made her angry.
</P>
<P>
   Her ``tantrum period'' is how Baez characterized, to one
interviewer, her high dudgeon at seeing contemporaries like Bob
Dylan celebrated with sellout performances before thousands, while
she foundered for a record label, air play and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But Baez admits she wasn't entirely a victim. Not just asleep at
the wheel, she realized she wasn't driving her own career at all _
and neither was anyone else. It inevitably led to a personal crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago I realized I didn't fit in anywhere because I
wasn't paying attention musically,'' she said. ``I woke up and
realized, `Oh my God, what have I been doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Baez, who is halfway through a short summer tour, recently
reflected on her professional and personal reawakening, and the
vicissitudes of maturing, particularly in a business so
youth-driven that Ricky Martin, half her age, can wage ``a musical
comeback'' at the advanced age of 27.
</P>
<P>
   She recognizes that she and a lot of contemporaries who were
``riding the big golden train'' during the protest generation, when
politics and music fused into a powerful descant for the early baby
boomers, ``just didn't know how to deal with it,'' when the train,
as she says, ``rusted'' and slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Baez, whose career had floated on ``handshake agreements,'' for
the first time hired a management company, and for her last album,
``Gone From Danger,'' she selected new music by up-and-coming young
songwriters like Richard Shindell and Ireland's Sinead Lohan, songs
that explored the personal struggle more than the political and
gave her a hipper sound without sacrificing her musical soul.
</P>
<P>
   She's even got her own Web site _ http://baez.woz.org. There's
the expected discography, bio information and tour schedule. But it
also shows a lighter side of the same woman who went to jail twice
for blocking the entrance to the Armed Forces Induction Center in
Oakland, Calif., and whose draft evasion remarks during taping led
to a preemption of the Smothers Brothers TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can click onto vacation snapshots of a grinning Joan
hiking and fishing, ``load up the shopping basket'' with ``Gone
from Danger'' T-shirts, or catch up on chatty news _ from a plug
for her favorite Paris bistro, where her artwork adorns the walls,
to a recounting of her harrowing pulley ride with Bonnie Raitt, up
a 1,000-year-old redwood in Stafford, Calif., to visit and sing for
tree-sitter Julia Butterfly Hill, who has spent more than 500 days
in the tree to protest the logging of ancient redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhilarating to be with Bonnie Raitt and have her look up
and say, `Oh s---. I'm going to hurl. Are we really going to do
this Baez?' '' she said, laughing at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, now that the sonorous folk singer, known as much for
her activism as her music, is tending more to her career, she seems
to be worrying less about the competition, not only from her
contemporaries but a new generation of female folk singers like
Sarah McLachlan and Cheryl Crow, for whom she paved the
professional way. Wising up, for Baez, has also meant loosening up
and letting go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I've grown up and come to my senses,'' said Baez, ``that
what could kill you revolves around jealousy and scrambling and
feeling inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to go on tour. I keep vacillating back and forth, and
thinking it's just time to go back and milk my goats,'' said Baez,
whose kick-back home life in Woodside, Calif., also revolves around
a big organic garden, two dogs, a flock of chickens, and time at
the easel and potter's wheel. ``But I love my band. And I love
being on the bus. Why stop now? In this industry you really have to
spot it with new albums and, if for no other reason than to keep
myself updated and feeling fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone from Danger'' was released in late 1997, and Baez said
she has another album forming in her mind but may still be another
six months away from the studio.
</P>
<P>
   If she's finally arrived at a certain comfort zone, Baez reveals
it was only after serious internal work. In truth, the unblenching
Folk Diva, who headlined at Woodstock and sang ``We Shall
Overcome'' before a quarter of a million people at the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s historic Washington rally in 1963, was
tormented by self-imposed demons, everything from panic attacks to
fear of flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just disguised it so well. I was such a cucumber on the
stage from the age of 18 ... I never really knew what it was like
to walk free on stage and just sing for the pleasure of it. I was
always under enormous pressure that mostly was my own.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of ``very deep therapy,'' running the gamut from
dance and painting to guided imagery and age regression, she says
she's ``out of the tunnel ... all the awfulness and lifelong
phobias are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The title of her last album, ``Gone from Danger,'' could speak
to her new ease, although the covers are clearly not party music.
There's Lohan's declaration of female independence, ``I'm No
Mermaid,'' ``February,'' Williams' achy poem to love misplaced, and
Betty Elders' ``Crack in the Mirror'' about child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers respectfully praised Baez for continuing her
career-long tradition of boosting the music of unknowns, something
she did decades ago with Phil Ochs, Tim Hardin, Eric Andersen and
Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   But Baez also knows she has something to learn, reflecting a
humbleness that comes with maturity and hard lessons. ``There are
these kids writing this stuff now, and it's good. What really
interests me now is the younger generation.''
</P>
<P>
   She also is careful to graciously mention her younger band
members _ guitarist Adam Kirk, who toured with Lohan; bass player
Mark Peterson; violin, mandolin and sax player Joshua Segal, a
member of The Borrowers, who toured with the Indigo Girls; and
percussionist Carol Steele.
</P>
<P>
   Right now she has a particular interest in one protege, niece
Pearl Bryan, who is touring with her and for whom she will do
back-up vocals on a couple of numbers. She said the 26-year-old
concealed her prodigious vocal gift from everyone, including her
own mother, Baez's older sister Pauline. But the Earth Aunty of
folk discovered it by chance when she invited the younger woman to
come live with her during a difficult time. Baez at first thought
the sweet voice filtering through a closed door was the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her, `You want to sing?' She said, `Yeh.' I said,
``Let's go upstairs and play the guitar and sing something.' And
she has been singing since.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Remaining dates in this tour: 7/28/99, Bozeman, Mont.;
7/29/99, Boise, Idaho; 7/31/99, Portland, Ore.; 8/1/99, Seattle;
8/3/99, Billings, Mont.; 8/5/99, Edmonton, Alberta, Canada
</P>
<P>
   Meg McConahey writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
