<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUCUMBERS-ART-2TAKES-     07-27 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUCUMBERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CUCUMBER GANG IS TAKING OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For vegetables, they are a motley crew. One looks like a pale
green hand grenade. Another is a dark curlicue as gnarled as a
ram's horn. There are lemony spheres and skinny wands, ivory
torpedoes and tiny, spiny ovoids like stretched golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   These unlikely specimens are all cucumbers, but not the usual,
reticent vegetables that achieve their greatest moments only after
a bath in brine. Like a bunch of shy eggheads masquerading as a
motorcycle gang, these are cucumbers transformed into shocking
characters, yet they retain the essential cucumber qualities of
crispness and coolness.
</P>
<P>
   With subtle alterations in taste, crunch and texture, they
simply do the job better than the familiar hulking waxed behemoths.
And more than likely, they have moved into your neighborhood.
Produce specialists like Gourmet Garage and Agata &AMP; Valentina are
carrying them, and so are some supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   The cucumber encroachment began in New York Greenmarkets. For
years, farmers have been selling lemon cucumbers, which look
surprisingly like lemons yet are unmistakably cukes, and any number
of Asian specimens, which vary considerably in the thickness of
their skin, the springiness or firmness of their texture and in
their seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their appearance, these cucumbers are more intensely
flavored than the ordinary, watery ones and, at $1.50 to $3 a
pound, cost just a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed the Greenmarket for 15 years, and I've seen them for
15 years,'' said Jay Petraker, who is now buys the produce for the
Gourmet Garage chain. He said their popularity is growing as people
become aware of them, just as arugula, once an obscure green,
became a salad regular.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs have certainly discovered them. ``What I think is really
wonderful is that they're very dense, and they've got great
texture,'' said Peter Hoffman, the chef and owner of Savoy in
Manhattan, who makes his own pickles and uses unconventional
cucumbers for a salad with cold marinated halibut.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Batali of Po and Babbo in Greenwich Village has embraced
them even more fervently. ``I love the cucumbers,'' he said. ``They
have great flavor, great texture.'' Batali juices cucumbers to make
a broth for fish, and shaves remarkably clean-tasting lemon
cucumbers over baccala, the Italian salt-cod dish.
</P>
<P>
   Asian cucumbers have always been available in Chinatown markets.
Others, like the lemons, are heirloom varieties, which were shunted
aside by the waxy torpedoes in the battle for market supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   David Size of Heirloom Harvest Farms in Blairstown, N.J., who
sells Asian, lemon and even Jamaican cucumbers, says they don't
need special treatment. Like all cucumbers, the spiny ones can be
eaten with the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you refrigerate them, they have the same storage and
shelf-life characteristics as regular cucumbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with any cucumber, though, is that
ultimately it is simply a cucumber. ``It doesn't get the respect of
a tomato,'' Petraker said. ``It doesn't get the respect of a
dripping peach.''
</P>
<P>
   In Asian kitchens, however, it has always been part of hot and
cold dishes. Petraker's brother, Joel Petraker, the assistant
director of the greenmarket program, has observed the cultural
cucumber divide at his own dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mother-in-law from Korea, cucumbers are right up
there,'' he said. ``To my Jewish mother from Long Island, they're
something you pick out of your salad.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Cho, the chef and owner of Bo, a Korean restaurant in
Flushing, Queens, adds Asian cucumbers to her kimchi, makes pickles
with kirbys and serves a sort of cucumber sandwich as an appetizer,
with bits of shrimp or boiled beef between thin slices of cuke,
decorated with an egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the body cold,'' she said. Something any culture
would agree on. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PANZANELLA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Po &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, cut into \-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes, preferably beefsteak or heirloom, cut into
{-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 lemon cucumbers, halved, seeded and cut into \-inch half-moons
</P>
<P>
   1 large Kirby cucumber (6 to 8 inches long), seeded and cut into
{-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups day-old Italian bread, cut into {-inch cubes, or fresh
bread, cut into {-inch cubes, lightly toasted under a broiler for 1
minute
</P>
<P>
   \ cup good-quality red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup torn basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large mixing bowl, combine the onion, the tomatoes, the
lemon cucumbers, the Kirby cucumber and the bread. Toss gently to
mix.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add vinegar and olive oil, and toss to coat. Add basil and
oregano, and mix gently. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
Allow to rest for 20 minutes; refrigerate while resting to serve
chilled, or leave at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 appetizer servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUINOA SALAD WITH CUCUMBER AND SORREL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Quiltys &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 55 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the quinoa: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup quinoa
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the salad: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pancetta, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 lightly packed cup sorrel leaves, cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons high-quality sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare the quinoa, place it in a very fine strainer,
rinse well, and drain. In a small saucepan over medium heat, melt
butter. Add the quinoa, and toss with butter for one minute. Add
the shallots, and saute until softened, about 2 minutes. Add 2 cups
of water and the salt. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low.
Simmer until the quinoa is firm but tender, about 30 minutes. Pour
out onto a baking sheet to cool to room temperature, then
refrigerate while preparing the salad.
</P>
<P>
   2. To prepare the salad, heat olive oil in a small saute pan
over low heat, and add the pancetta. Saute until pancetta begins to
crisp. Immediately remove it from heat, and set aside. Reserve fat
in pan.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large bowl, combine chilled quinoa, pancetta, cucumber
and sorrel leaves. Toss gently. Add reserved pancetta fat, sherry
vinegar and salt and pepper to taste. Mix well. Serve as an
accompaniment to grilled chicken or pork or rich fish like salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KIRBY PICKLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Savoy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus 3 days' refrigeration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   } cup salt
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 dill flowers or dill sprigs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   18 firm Kirby cucumbers, well washed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large enamel-lined pot, combine vinegar, wine, salt,
sugar, dill, caraway seeds, red pepper flakes and garlic. Add 4
quarts of water. Place over high heat, and bring to a boil.
Immediately turn off heat, and allow mixture to steep for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place cucumbers in a very large glass or plastic bowl. Pour
vinegar mixture over the cucumbers, and submerge them by placing a
plate on them (make sure no air is trapped beneath). Weight plate
down with a glass or ceramic pot.
</P>
<P>
   3. Allow mixture to cool, and refrigerate for at least three
days before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 18 pickles.
</P>
</TEXT>
