<HEADER>
A5623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASS-COLUMN-COX     07-27 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fair jurist generated moral force in South
 &HT;    By Jack Bass
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was curious about why Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, the editor
for my biography of Judge Frank M. Johnson Jr., felt so intensely
about him. When I asked how she became interested, she leaned back
reflectively at her desk at Doubleday, then said, ``He's long been
a hero of mine. I guess it goes back to the White House and hearing
Jack and Bobby talk about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest federal judge in the nation when appointed by
President Eisenhower in 1955 a few days before his 37th birthday,
Johnson stoically endured death threats, cross burnings, a bombing
of his mother's home in the belief it was his, and social
ostracism.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 15 years, federal marshals provided him with
round-the-clock protection. His civil rights rulings helped
transform the South and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He changed Alabama, guiding the state he loved to move beyond
the legacy of George Wallace, his former law school classmate and
friend. It changed so much that at the dedication a few years ago
of the Frank M. Johnson Jr. Federal Building and Courthouse in
Montgomery, a legislator presented a unanimous resolution praising
Congress for putting his name on the building. Twenty-five years
earlier, the Legislature had called for Johnson's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. once said, ``Judge Johnson gave true
meaning to the word `justice.' '' Wallace said he needed ``a barbed
wire enema.'' Before his death, however, Wallace told me that in
the long run he was ``wrong'' on segregation and Johnson was
``right.''
</P>
<P>
   His rare combination of strength, courage, integrity, intellect
and wisdom generated a powerful moral force. Judge Johnson made the
rule of law prevail during a period of violent upheaval. He took
literally his oath of office to ``administer justice,'' which he
came to define as the absence of injustice. In Alabama, he issued
orders desegregating schools and a host of other facilities,
striking down barriers to voting and serving on juries, breaking
new ground in gender discrimination and First Amendment issues, and
extending constitutional protection to abused inmates and state
mental patients.
</P>
<P>
   Although his orders helped transform the social order in the
South, Johnson never viewed matters before him as societal issues.
To him they were always legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   When I first interviewed him, in 1974, he explained, ``When you
have a voting rights case and you find that there's been a pattern
and practice of discrimination against the blacks in registering to
vote, you don't register the blacks to vote so that they can gain
political power. You are faced with some legal issues, and if they
are entitled to relief, you give them relief and you order that
they be registered. Now the effect of their registering and voting
and electing a sheriff and other county officials is something that
the court's not concerned with, and has no interest in it. The role
federal judges have played in the South has been one of effecting
resultantly a social change. And there's no question about it. But
that wasn't the motive and it wasn't the purpose and it wasn't the
intent.''The Republican ``Southern strategy'' kept him off the
Supreme Court. His friend, Chief Justice Warren Burger, once called
Johnson in from a fishing trip in the Gulf of Mexico to tell him
President Nixon was appointing
</P>
<P>
   him to succeed Justice Hugo Black. Years later, a contrite
Alabama congressman told Johnson that he and the state's two other
Republican representatives learned about it and told Attorney
General John Mitchell such an appointment would hurt them
politically. The congressman told the judge, ``We made a mistake
and I want to apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson addressed his own legacy in a 1980 interview with Bill
Moyers. ``I realize that a good many people here in this section of
the country were dissatisfied with some of the constitutional
decisions that I found it necessary to make,'' he said. ``But ... I
gained a reputation among a large majority of the people in this
section of the country, that Judge Johnson's tough, Judge Johnson
will rule the way he sees the Constitution, but there's always one
thing _ that he's fair. And that's the only reputation that a judge
can hope to get. And that's the only kind of a reputation he ought
to want.''
</P>
<P>
   They buried Judge Frank M. Johnson, Jr. Tuesday in his native
Haleyville in mountainous Winston County, a Unionist stronghold
during the Civil War. I once drove the four hours there from
Montgomery with him. As the terrain became more rugged, he said
softly, ``I always enjoy coming to the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll endure, as will his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bass wrote ``Taming the Storm: The Life and Times of Judge
Frank M. Johnson and the South's Fight over Civil Rights,'' which
won the 1994 Robert F. Kennedy Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
