<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP BLUE SEA': LAB SHARKS TURN MEN INTO SUSHI 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much water leaks, gurgles, sloshes and jets through Renny
Harlin's waterlogged man-versus-shark horror epic ``Deep Blue Sea''
that when it comes to choosing the season's strongest, sturdiest
most absorbent paper towel of a movie, there's no just contest;
this one takes the prize. Think of it as cinematic Mega-Brawny with
a familiar horror-movie message: Don't mess with Mother Nature or
she'll turn on you.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid that this product sops up isn't just ordinary sea
water. It's water frequently thickened and made crimson with human
blood, as three genetically ``improved'' 8,000-pound mako sharks
viciously turn against the staff of the Aquatica Research
Laboratory, a gleaming multilevel station floating in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Enter a bogus tropical storm that causes a helicopter crash that
sets the place on fire and destroys most of its power, and the
tables are suddenly turned. The evil researchers become little
fishes toyed with and then devoured by their laboratory subjects
one by one. The sharks' favorite mode of attack is to leap up out
of the water like giant, demented razor-toothed porpoises, seize
their prey and dispose of them in two or three quick chomps. A
relentless shock-effect soundtrack supplies the clanging audio
equivalent of shark growls, along with many nerve-jangling false
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   The most villainous human, Dr. Susan McAlester (Saffron
Burrows), is a beautiful, icy marine biologist whose scientific
hanky-panky involves implanting human brain tissue in creatures
that the movie redundantly insists many times are the most
efficient killing machines in all of natural history. Although
Susan's work is supposed to hold the key to curing degenerative
brain diseases like Alzheimer's, exactly how it relates to medical
science is never addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Susan's upper-class English accent is one sign that she is too
ruthlessly ambitious to be trusted. Still, you've got to hand it
her. She's got nerve. Late in the movie, she deliberately slashes
her hand and dives into the ocean, offering herself as live bait
for one of the monsters so it will come close enough for her fellow
survivor, Carter Blake (Thomas Jane), a self-proclaimed ``shark
wrangler,'' to kill it. As Susan slides into the water, she
foolishly challenges the fish to ``come to mama.''
</P>
<P>
   The most courageous character is Carter, a muscular daredevil
with a shady criminal past, whose idea of fun is grabbing onto a
killer shark's fin and taking an underwater ride. For comic relief
there's the house chef, Preacher (LL Cool J), who after watching
his beloved foul-mouthed pet parrot become a shark snack flees into
a giant oven with the gas turned on. In a movie that's generically
self-referential, Preacher comments bleakly on his probable fate by
observing that his black brothers are usually killed off early in
movies of this type.
</P>
<P>
   Other stars whose characters the movie barely bothers to define
include Michael Rapaport as the lab's engineer, Stellan Skarsgard
as its physician and Samuel L. Jackson as its chief financial
backer, who chooses exactly the wrong moment to fly in for an
inspection. Jacqueline McKenzie plays a character so vague she
might best be described as the movie's extra (and most disposable)
woman.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of ``Deep Blue Sea'' follows a dwindling core of
survivors from the accident as they struggle to make their way from
the bowels of the research station to the surface before the
structure sinks and without being eaten alive. Imagine a cut-rate
``Titanic'' (``Deep Blue Sea'' is filled with scenes of flooding
corridors) stripped of romance and historical resonance and fused
with ``Jaws,'' shorn of mythic symbolism and without complex
characters, and you have the essence of this live-action horror
comic.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in its dumb, bludgeoning way, it's fun. To quote the ever
voluble Preacher who makes it to the surface barely in one piece:
``Bring me some sushi!''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DEEP BLUE SEA'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Renny Harlin; written by Duncan Kennedy, Donna
Powers and Wayne Powers; director of photography, Stephen Windon;
edited by Frank J. Urioste, Derek G. Brechin and Dallas S. Puett;
music by Trevor Rabin; production designer, William Sandell;
produced by Akiva Goldsman, Tony Ludwig and Alan Riche; released by
Warner Bros. Running time: 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Saffron Burrows (Dr. Susan McAlester), Thomas Jane (Carter
Blake), LL Cool J (Sherman ``Preacher'' Dudley), Jacqueline
McKenzie (Janice Higgins), Michael Rapaport (Tom Scoggins), Stellan
Skarsgard (Jim Whitlock) and Samuel L. Jackson (Russell Franklin).
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Blue Sea'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has some gore and some strong
language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
