<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS HURLER PITCHING WEB PAGE TO HIS FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Detroit Tigers pitcher C.J. Nitkowski leaves major-league
baseball, he should have one pitch remaining in his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   He could convince someone that he'd make a good Webmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski, who has a 3-5 record for the Tigers, is the only
known major-league baseball player to operate his own Web site
(www.cjbaseball.com).
</P>
<P>
   It's not one of those sites created for the players by a hotshot
Internet company _ you know, the ones where a player personally
responds to e-mail on a standard form. And it's not one of those
tribute sites created by someone with a case of hero worship.
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski actually created his own site _ not as a vanity
exercise, but as a way to interact with his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be good for my fans _ and it has been,''
said Nitkowski, who taught himself HTML (hypertext markup language,
Internet coding). ``It's the e-mail that keeps it going for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski started his site in September 1997 when he was
pitching for the Houston Astros. In January, he was traded to the
Tigers _ a move that generated more than 300 e-mails from his fans.
</P>
<P>
   He also built traffic through an 11,000-member Astros newsletter
that he authored. During the '98 season, the site received more
than 43,000 hits, Nitkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in Detroit, Nitkowski has improved his Web skills, and the
site is taking shape. He also bought Web-authoring software and a
digital camera (his best photo comes from his motel room in St.
Louis,where he can't believe how close the hotel is to Busch
Stadium).
</P>
<P>
   He updates his site several times a week or ``when I can,'' said
Nitkowski, who no doubt mulls his site's changes while he's in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   His best updates offer an inside look at the team or his
performances.
</P>
<P>
   One of those inside stories is Nitkowski's suspension letter
from American League president Gene Budig.
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski posted a scanned image of the letter along with his
response to a May 22 incident in which Nitkowski threw inside to
Cleveland's Kenny Lofton after a warning had been issued to both
teams. In a reply letter, Nitkowski pleaded his case. In a
subsequent letter, Budig thanked Nitkowski and returned the $500
fine that Nitkowski was assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski also posts tips on getting players' autographs,
reviews of his favorite restaurants on the road (including two in
Arlington), reviews of his favorite golf courses and his favorite
Web-site links.
</P>
<P>
   The site is not too high-tech _ no polls, chats or fancy gizmos.
Nitkowski said he doesn't foresee himself getting too fancy with a
site that he believes is user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going overboard here,'' he said. ``I don't plan on
taking my Internet talents much farther. But you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL HOT DOGS, TOO? MSNBCSports.com is taking users on a
virtual interactive tour through the top ballparks in the major
leagues. MSNBC rates the best five parks overall, best in the works
and best new ballparks. The site includes audio commentary by Bob
Costas. Fans of The Ballpark in Arlington will be disappointed to
find out it's not included.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO CHAMP: Cowboys linebacker Randall Godfrey's chat on
NFL.com last week revealed his passion for video games: ``Once we
hit camp, that's all we'll do with our spare time, so I've got to
be ready. Who's the team champ? Me, of course. Some of these young
guys are good, though, so I look forward to playing some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   TRAINING WITH THE COWBOYS: Sites where Cowboys fans can follow
preseason training:
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys Official Site (www.dallascowboys.com): Daily 5 p.m.
updates from Valley Ranch or Wichita Falls. Also, ticket
information and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys Internet Resource Center
(www.eden.com/~fgoodwin/links.htm): Fred Goodwin of Austin has
every Cowboys link imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The Boys.com (boys.com: Unofficial site features interactive
polls, fan editorials and chat areas.
</P>
<P>
   NFL.com (www.nfl.com/news/99trainingcamp.html): Official site
lists information from all of the training camps.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
