A5653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-TEACHERS28-COX     07-27 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-TEACHERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HELP FOR NEW TEACHERS CUTS DEPARTURE RATE
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One in 11 newly hired teachers quits before
finishing the first year and must be replaced, disrupting the
education of students and exacerbating teacher shortages.
</P>
<P>
   But that 9.3 percent dropout rate falls to 7 percent in urban
districts that create a formal support system for novice teachers,
says a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said the new-teacher programs they examined in
118 city and large-town school districts in 35 states ranged from
``comprehensive to cursory.'' Most depended heavily on mentoring of
the newcomers throughout their first year by specially trained
veteran teachers, who coached them on everything from paperwork to
classroom management and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in urban districts, it helps (to counteract) the
so-called reality shock as they encounter the problems of real
students in a real classroom,'' said lead researcher Elizabeth F.
Fideler, executive vice president of Recruiting New Teachers Inc.,
a national, nonprofit, teaching development organization in
Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies showed that only 56 percent of teachers in the
typical public school district _ and about 60 percent in the urban
districts, which often present the greatest teaching challenges _
obtain formal help in their first year, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers who make the transition from novice to seasoned
professional too often do so by navigating solo through uncharted
waters,'' Fideler said. ``Contrast that to the experience of
medical residents, law associates and even rookie basketball
players, who are required to go through extended training,
development and mentoring'' after they are hired.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, she and David Haselkorn concluded that
formal first-year programs ``improve new teachers' knowledge skills
and performance, provide personal support, introduce new teachers
to school system norms and procedures, and familiarize them with
school system values.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, they also found that programs for
first-year teachers come and go as budget levels shift and that few
districts measure the impact of the programs on those teachers'
students.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the nation's two largest teachers unions hailed the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association endorsed mandatory support
systems for new teachers earlier this month, said its president,
Bob Chase. ``As educators and policy makers, we ought to channel
all the resources we can to help new teachers to not just survive
their first year of teaching, but to thrive and succeed in their
most important charge _ boosting student achievement,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Baratz-Snowden, deputy director for education issues at the
American Federation of Teachers, said, ``Part of the problem is
many states have legislation (encouraging such programs), but in
some states it's not mandated, and in others, it is mandated, but
it's not funded.''
</P>
<P>
   Most programs are funded by local districts themselves, because
fewer than 20 states fund them, the researchers found. Sen. Jack
Reed, D-R.I., on Tuesday introduced a bill that would offer $1
billion annually in federal subsidies for professional development
of teachers in districts with the highest number of poor students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation will fund mentorship programs for new teachers
and training for mentor-teachers to ensure they have the skills to
help those teachers,'' Reed said. It would include funds to hire
substitutes to handle the classes of mentors and novices who are
conferring.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
