<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5660 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV03-     07-27 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY DEATHS CREATE COMPARATIVE GRIEVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Aug. 3)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celebrities die as differently as they live from ordinary people
and are mourned in a separate fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It began within 24 hours following the announcement that John F.
Kennedy Jr. was missing and presumed dead. People started talking
about whether they felt worse about losing him or Princess Di.
</P>
<P>
   When Uncle George dies, you don't hear someone comparing the
tragedy of his train wreck to Cousin Mal's skiing accident.
</P>
<P>
   But with a celebrity death there's comparative grieving. Who
affected the public the most? Even before the bodies were found
came the headline: ``Cable ratings beat Di coverage,'' with a
report showing that the Kennedy death coverage edged out not only
the death of Princess Diana but the Littleton High School
massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, I met some people at a campground who had
been without TV, newspapers or radio for days. The last they heard
before packing off into the wilds was that Kennedy's plane had
disappeared and that he, his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and
her sister, Lauren Bessette, were feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, this band of uninformed campers was still in the
first stage of breaking news, stunned and sad and shaking their
heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Having missed the media aftermath, they were fresh in their
sorrow, like we had been on that first day.
</P>
<P>
   The world had moved on for those keeping the Kennedy watch.
Within days, we were approaching information overload. In less than
a week we had gone from shock to near-saturation.
</P>
<P>
   It was predictable, though. There are stages of public mourning
that seem to attend the sudden death of celebrities, especially
those who are rich, famous and wonderful to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately upon hearing that the famous person has died or is
presumed dead, we start seeing file photos of them in happy days.
The first photos are heartbreaking but they become sadly routine
after a few days. Sometimes something will appear from old
videotape or film archives that show the person in scandalous days,
although the media usually hold back for a time. However, if a
member of the competition chooses not to be respectful, they all
succumb.
</P>
<P>
   Following file photos, sound bites and film clips comes
commentary. The media search high and low, but not too far, for any
friend, co-worker or family member several in-laws removed to speak
of the deceased. Real friends and family members don't talk to the
media right away because they simply cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Find the local angle. This is when newspapers, big and small,
across the country beat the bushes to find anyone in their
circulation area who might have once known the deceased, went to
boarding school with them, attended a party in the same apartment
building, sold them gas when they drove through town.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they score with a nice little anecdote. Often they
bomb and have to turn to some guy at the mall willing to share his
favorite memories of a person he never met.
</P>
<P>
   No news is more news. This is the period when there is nothing
more to report, at least for the time being. Special sections and
TV documentaries are being hastily assembled and meanwhile the
daily update is all of the above, over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a theory. Experts talk about how a plane might have
crashed into the Atlantic, a car into a tunnel on a Paris street.
Many people usually not asked for their input get to hold press
conferences. Valuable TV time is filled with how altimeters work.
</P>
<P>
   Economic impact. This is when it gets a little weird, when
stories emerge like how news of the death of the famous person
affected the Saturday night ticket sales at the local movie
theater. And what kind of memorial T-shirts and ceramic figurines
you can buy on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Spite and resentment. Some begin to hint that it might have been
the deceased's fault. Some whisper mean-spirited things about the
famous dead person and reveal general bitterness toward anyone with
fame, wealth, beauty, education, social status and special
privilege. They snipe about the cost of investigating the famous
person's death. Some even make rude remarks and jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturation. Finally, the listening and reading public starts to
grumble for something else on the nightly news and the front page.
They blame the media for overindulging their endless curiosity.
They say they are tired of the frenzy and the circus, and on this
point the public mourners are finally in sync with the grieving
family.
</P>
<P>
   Once the world stops mourning, the families can. They can grieve
the way that families do when someone loses his daughters and
someone loses her sisters and someone her brother. Vanished people
who were someone's somebody. Not everyone's somebody.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
