<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28-CO     07-27 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: What I saw in Warsaw, 10 years
later
 &HT;    (With photos.)
 &HT;    (Eds: Cox News Service columnist Joe Murray reported from
Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago, just before the fall of
the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to write about the changes
that have led three former Eastern Bloc countries to become the
newest members of NATO _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland.
This column is the first in the series that will move over the next
couple of weeks. At the end of the series, CoxNet will compile
these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for running as a
Perspective-type page or op-ed feature. These pages are available
for sale to New York Times News Service clients at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ Ten years ago, when Eastern Europe was still
semi-Soviet in the last months before the fall of the Berlin Wall,
I had to sneak into Warsaw with a tourist visa, scared silly that
someone would spot me for the journalist I am.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that silliness must have carried over, even though
nowadays the namesake of the erstwhile Warsaw Pact is one of our
newest NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, my first evening in Warsaw, dining with a
journalist friend at a French restaurant that was everything anyone
could ask for, in Warsaw or wherever ...
</P>
<P>
   And what I meant to tell the waiter was that I wanted gazpacho.
It came out instead:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have the Gestapo.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. You can take the boy out of the country, but be
careful which countries you put him into.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose of my trip was to revisit cities where I traveled in
1989, Warsaw, Prague and Budapest, what was then Eastern Bloc and
today are European democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays you shoot through customs with a wave of your American
passport. Ten years ago you felt like you might be shot just for
being an American.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium nears, Warsaw is a city surprising itself with
its own prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles south of the central city, in an area of empty
fields a year ago, malls, supermarkets and even warehouse-style
superstores serve as glittering mile markers on Poland's road to
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Just watch out you don't get run down.
</P>
<P>
   Cart traffic is dangerous along the gleaming aisles, as shoppers
rush from one announced special to another, a free-market
free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risk worth taking for a country that once got along
mainly on sausage, cheese and a bit of bread layered in between for
variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have but one choice of yogurt,'' a woman shopper
exclaimed. ``Now there's an entire shelf of different yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget borscht. Think barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   BBQ grills, utensils, briquettes, cans of lighter _ everything
you need for an outdoor cookout is on sale, plus an array of patio
furniture. With roast beef priced at about $1.50 a pound, it's
dining out at its cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   Not that barbecue is really all that new to Poland. If anything,
it's a return to an ancient way of life, Poles say.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, they called it roasting an ox.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all is Neiman and Marcus in the making.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown flea market _ a village of kiosks called ``Jaws''
because of the steel grates that secure them at night _ is where
most of Warsaw everyday folks shop, though not necessarily by
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The price may be right, but you get what you pay for _ fake
designer goods and pirated CDs _ and if you're not careful, your
pocketbook or purse may be snatched in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   This is the complaint you hear, that between the flea markets
and the limited selection of expensive designer shops, there's not
much in between. That's where the strength of Poland's economy,
like that of any democracy, lies _ in the middle class, newly
emerging.
</P>
<P>
   And all those cell phones you see aren't necessarily signs of
affluence. In a city where it may take a year to get a line
installed in your home, a cell phone often is the only phone that's
quick and easy to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Polish currency, the zloty, enjoys what seems to be a
respectable rate against the dollar, about four for a buck. But
outside Poland, the zloty isn't worth diddly to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that the hard way, that their money isn't on par with
hard currency. I had about $100 worth of zlotys when I left Poland,
only to discover that you can't trade them in neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But I shouldn't complain. Ten years ago when I was here I got my
pocket picked. At least this is more businesslike.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Address is P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
