<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-ON-A-WHALE28-CO     07-27 1824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-ON-A-WHALE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sight of dead man in whale tank chilled sheriff's deputies
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Daniel Dukes lived anonymously but died
famously.
</P>
<P>
   The world notices when you're found dead at an Orlando theme
park on the back of a killer whale.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning of July 6, SeaWorld trainers discovered a
scene with front-page sizzle and made-for-TV potential.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Captain Ahab, who went down in a violent ocean lashed to
Great White Moby Dick, Daniel Dukes was draped over the back of a
shiny-black killer whale in a stark, concrete pool at the deserted
theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Who would jump in a pool with a 5-ton animal that could make
short work of the biggest shark?
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old drifter's family apparently can't explain _ and
if they have any insights, they're not saying. Dukes' parents, who
own a Columbia, S.C., real estate business, have had little contact
with their son for the past 10 years _ and no contact with the
press.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes spent most of the past decade in Austin, Texas, compiling
a rap sheet of arrests for bizarre crimes including stealing a
Barbie doll, briefcase and women's camisole from a Target store;
clocking a fellow patron in the head at Joe's Generic Blues Bar;
and breaking into a home where he was discovered resting in a
downstairs bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Court records list an employer as a ``C Thru U Productions,''
which no longer exists and perhaps never did.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was unremarkable enough that a parole officer assigned
to Dukes' case does not remember him. And workers at Austin
homeless shelters recognize photographs of Dukes, but can recall
almost nothing about him.
</P>
<P>
   After being released from jail on the assault charge last fall,
Dukes headed to Florida and was arrested for possession of a
marijuana joint on Christmas Day in Marion County. In March he was
arrested in Volusia County for resisting arrest without violence.
</P>
<P>
   By April, though, he found his way to Coconut Grove, where he
turned up at the Hare Krishna Temple for the weekly Sunday feast
that's open to all.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived with a knapsack and a suitcase containing leather
chaps and a cowboy hat. He frequently carried a notepad and wrote
notes to try to convince people he couldn't speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if something important happened,'' says Krishna member
Cakrapani, ``he'd talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Keshava Swami, the leader of the Coconut Grove temple, wouldn't
tolerate the silent act and told Dukes to speak or leave. He spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes spent about two months, off and on, at the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Among his possessions found at SeaWorld: a picture of Lord
Juggernaut, who, Hindu beliefs say, saved a village from a whale
terrorizing the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes took in the shows
</P>
<P>
   Dukes _ a thin man with stringy, dirty-blond hair, a bum's beard
and blue eyes _ broke from anonymity when he visited SeaWorld.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives working the case say Dukes spent one night in heavy
landscaping near the SeaWorld entrance, making a small camp that
included a Hare Krishna shrine (with items he stole from the
temple's gift shop). He saw the dolphin show and stingray show,
took a few snapshots _ mostly of obese women and dolphins _ and
played in the arcades.
</P>
<P>
   And then some time after dark on his second night in the theme
park, unnoticed on a surveillance monitor watched by SeaWorld
security, Dukes slipped off his pants, shirt and shoes and jumped
into a 52-degree saltwater pool. It was the home of Tilikum, a male
breeding whale, the largest in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes' act shocked everyone in Orange County's death business.
And accustomed as they are to shootings, stabbings, beatings, car
wrecks and headers off high-rises, they don't shock easily.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Solomons of the Orange County Sheriff's Department arrived
quickly that morning at SeaWorld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to hundreds of crime scenes the 14 or so years I've
been doing this,'' said the public information officer. ``I'm
usually pretty stoic.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Solomons thought Tilly had a tumor as it swam toward
him. ``I'm standing next to a fireman and a couple of our
detectives and I went, `Holy sh--, that's a naked guy.' I said it
out loud. I've never been affected that way. It was like a fireman
would carry a victim out of a burning building.''
</P>
<P>
   Killer whales, said to be smarter than dolphins, have been known
to hoist humans on their backs to save them from drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers had no problem getting the willing whale to swim to a
scale, flop out of the water and let two petrified firemen remove
Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   And then the whale, calm and precise, slid back into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Shashi Gore, Orange County's chief medical examiner for 30
years, said he had never seen a death as weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen death from hypothermia but not in a whale tank,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has several theories about how Dukes died: When he hit the
water, he immediately went into hypothermic shock as he shivered
and expended valuable energy. Add to that panic, fear, and
flailing, and hypothermia would be quick and deadly. And at
5-feet-11 and about 150 pounds, Dukes was no endurance athlete. He
probably didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   While people can survive four to five hours fully clothed in
frigid water, even the U.S. Coast Guard won't venture a guess as to
how long a nearly naked person could last.
</P>
<P>
   Gore guesses Tilly, a territorial animal, probably moved quickly
to check out the visitor. The animal _ with huge, white,
mound-shaped teeth _ scratched Dukes as it removed his green
shorts, possibly attracted to the color. There was also bruising,
which leads the medical examiner to believe Tilly may have flipped
and tossed Dukes like one of the giant balls pitched in the pool by
trainers during playtime.
</P>
<P>
   Tilly, though, didn't break bones or bite. Killer whales swallow
food whole and are not known to attack humans. Maybe, Gore guesses,
a panicked and freezing Dukes got caught underneath the huge
animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatigue leads to drowning,'' explains Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Called childlike, harmless
</P>
<P>
   At the tranquil Coconut Grove Hare Krishna Temple, Keshava, a
52-year-old former engineer from Rio de Janeiro, listens to the
details of Dukes' demise. As a Krishna swami, he's in charge of the
Miami temple, which has a staff of 30 and about 1,000 followers. He
had to give the OK for Dukes to stick around the compound doing odd
jobs from April through late May.
</P>
<P>
   The Krishnas, practicing a 5,000-year-old Hindu religion, don't
take in the homeless because it leads to problems. But Keshava says
Dukes was so childlike, so harmless, that he could have stayed as
long he wanted if he followed minimal rules and did minimum work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came here, he started by washing the pots,'' said
Keshava, pointing into the cafeteria to the small, sweltering
kitchen. Then he smiled and mentioned the time Dukes replaced the
meditation music normally played on the kitchen boombox with a
Metallica tape. At the sight of Keshava in the doorway, he quickly,
sheepishly, returned the meditation music.
</P>
<P>
   People in Austin say Dukes may have become interested in Eastern
religions when he was taken in by a man who frequently sheltered
the homeless. The man, a former worker at a restaurant called
Veggie Heaven, left Texas for a California monastery to study
Buddhism, co-workers say.
</P>
<P>
   One constant problem the Krishnas had with Dukes was his long,
dirty hair and beard and filthy clothing; Dukes didn't meet the
strict Krishna code of cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
   While Dukes wouldn't cut his hair, he met his hosts halfway. He
shaved his beard, tied his hair back and took regular showers. He
also wore clothes given to him.
</P>
<P>
   He asked to be given a spiritual name but the Krishnas knew
there was no way he'd complete the rigid, six-month session to
become a member. He instead was called Bhakdas Daniel, ``bhakdas''
being a title used for friends or newcomers to Krishna.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became very normal when he was here. He was dirty but
harmless when he came. In one week he became happy,'' reports
Keshava.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes took part in Krishna chanting on the streets of Coconut
Grove. He sat for hours in the temple's library painstakingly
copying Sanskrit and English translations from the Krishna bible.
He attended Keshava's lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes' longest, uninterrupted stay at the temple was two weeks.
Usually after three or four days, he'd disappear. Krishnas would
see him drinking beer and reading skin magazines around Coconut
Grove. He shoplifted, sometimes from them, Krishnas say, even
though he had food stamps and a Shell credit card, the monthly
bills paid by his mother in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dukes had a bed at the temple, Krishnas, who rise at
3:30 a.m. daily to begin prayers and meditation, would find Dukes
sleeping in the garden at the front of the former Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Three women at the temple, each middle-aged with grown adult
sons near Dukes' age, describe him as childlike and prone to
outbursts at inappropriate times, such as during meditation.
</P>
<P>
   He could burst out laughing at nothing and then instantly fall
silent for three hours, staring straight ahead, saying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a child,'' says Geetavali, shaking her head.
``Look,'' she says, opening a notebook of doodles and drawings he
gave her when he left. ``The work of a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Nartaka Gopala sorts mail at the temple, and says she twice gave
Dukes letters from his mother, urging him him to write back. ``But
it was like he couldn't get it together enough to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nartaka would scold Dukes. ``What are you doing here? We don't
want people who are halfway here, halfway out the door. He said,
`OK, like, I'll try.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I treated him like my son,'' adds Sonja Lerner, whose Krishna
spiritual name is Gandharrika dasi. ``He liked having a mother. He
called me mother.''
</P>
<P>
   She tends the garden raising Tulasi plants, a sacred plant from
India used medicinally and spiritually. Dukes' favorite Krishna job
was working in the garden with Lerner, who has a 34-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She points to an Angel's Trumpet alongside the church. ``He
planted that.'' Lerner says she believes Dukes death was an
accident. ``He was very curious. He might have seen the whale show
and wanted to swim with the whales.''
</P>
<P>
   Keshava disagrees. ``He only spoke with me about philosophy,
about god and the power of supreme love. He was intelligent. For
me, he probably committed suicide. He was searching for
spirituality. He asked many questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pushed him. I told him, `You need one way, one path.' He'd
just listen. But he never could commit. He never could follow the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Peyton Woodson of the Austin American-Statesman and Michael
Alicea of the Palm Beach Post contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
