<HEADER>
A5721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEINSTEIN-VEEP-HNS &LR;      07-27 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-VEEP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 FEINSTEIN'S NAME FLOATED AS POSSIBLE VEEP CANDIDATE   (EDs: FILED
in ``p'' and ``w'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The name of Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a California
Democrat, is being floated in party circles as a possible vice
presidential candidate in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings, D-S.C., said Tuesday that her
name has been put forward in informal discussions ``in the
cloakroom'' among Democratic senators. He was referring to a
gathering place just off the Senate floor where lawmakers hold
private conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why Feinstein is being mentioned, Hollings told
reporters, ``She's a dynamic speaker and public servant on the one
hand, but (also) she'd bring California'' behind the Democratic
ticket. The state, with 54 of the 270 electoral votes required to
win the White House, is the largest prize in the presidential
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., who heads the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee (DSCC), which helps recruit and fund
Democratic Senate candidates, said Feinstein's name tops every list
he's seen for the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has gained a lot of experience at different levels of
government,'' Torricelli said. ``She has the depth of knowledge and
the independence that many of us want in a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. J. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., who formerly headed the DSCC,
said Feinstein would be ``very strong'' on a national ticket.
``She's got charisma; she's got the spark that people recognize,''
Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maslin, an Oakland-Calif.-based Democratic pollster, said
Feinstein ``would add an awful lot to any ticket ... There aren't a
whole lot of people at this level of the Democratic Party who have
the kinds of credentials that she has.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the talk of her as a Democratic running mate,
Feinstein stressed that neither Vice President Al Gore, the party's
leading candidate, nor former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, his
challenger, has discussed the office with her.
</P>
<P>
   If she were invited to join the ticket, she said in an
interview, ``it would be a hard decision.'' She added that she does
not foresee any such invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation concerns her, she said, because she doesn't want
her constituents to think she isn't running for the Senate. As it
stands now, she said, ``I am not going after anything else (in
2000) but my Senate seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Before winning a Senate seat in a special election in 1992,
Feinstein was the Democratic nominee for California governor, the
mayor of San Francisco for nearly 11 years and a member of the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein is considered a political moderate. She has supported
traditional liberal issues such as abortion rights and gun control
while backing traditional conservative fare such as the death
penalty and the toughening of immigration standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the liberal Americans for Democratic Action gave
Feinstein a 90 percent approval rating in 1998, down from 95
percent in 1996. The American Conservative Union, however, gave
Feinstein a 4 percent approval rating in 1998, down from a career
high of 20 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at the e-mail address
eric(at)hearstdc.com; Judy Holland can be reached at
judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
