<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very humid air streaming northeast from the Mississippi Valley
will fuel a large cluster of heavy showers and thunderstorms over
the central Great Lakes Wednesday morning. The cool, moist
downdrafts within some of the thunderstorms will produce outflow
boundaries, or mini-cold fronts. As these fronts progress southward
and lift sultry air, the stage will be set for additional storms to
erupt over the Ohio Valley and central Appalachians during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Puffy cumulus clouds will dot an otherwise clear sky across the
interior Northeast Wednesday. Meanwhile, breezes from the west
descending and drying on route to the Northeast seaboard will cause
clouds to crumble, bringing abundant sunshine and very warm
conditions from New York City to Washington. Exceptionally hot
weather will cover an expansive region from the northern Plains to
the Southeast. Indeed, beneath mainly sunny skies, daytime readings
will soar to near 100 degrees in many places.
</P>
<P>
   Moist air in the lowest few thousand feet of the atmosphere will
promote patchy clouds and spotty storms over the central and
southern Rockies. As is typical, the clouds and showers will be
most numerous during the afternoon when the uneven heating of the
varied terrain promotes vigorous rising currents of moistened air.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific states will be mainly dry and sunny. A brief
thunderstorm, however, may occur in the late afternoon near the
eastern slopes of the Cascades. Elsewhere, morning clouds grazing
the Pacific Coast will yield to ample afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hot Minneapolis
</P>
<P>
   It soared to 99 degrees in Minneapolis on Sunday, marking the
twelfth time this summer and the eighth time this month that the
mercury has reached 90 degrees or more. The reading was also the
city's highest temperature since the mercury hit 101 degrees on
July 13, 1995. Though hot weather has been a salient, recurrent
feature of the upper Midwest in June and July, this summer cannot
compare to the blistering, tenacious heat of the summer of 1988.
That summer, the mercury climbed to 90 degrees or more on 45 days
in Minneapolis, with 17 of those occurring in July alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
