<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYES-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS ASSAIL RATINGS BOARD OVER `EYES WIDE SHUT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The New York Film Critics Circle has joined Los
Angeles critics in attacking the Motion Picture Association of
America for requiring that Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' be
altered to qualify for its R rating.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by the New York group, signed by 28 members and
issued Monday night, said the association's ratings board was ``out
of control'' and had ``become a punitive and restrictive force,
effectively trampling the freedom of American filmmakers.'' The
association said the board ``had created its own zone of knee-jerk
Puritanism.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was the insistence by the board that a scene of a
sexual orgy warranted an NC-17 rating, which would have meant that
no one under 17 would be admitted. For the film to receive an R
rating _ requiring that anyone under 17 be accompanied by an adult
_ 65 seconds of the movie were digitally altered. Essentially,
shrouded digital figures were placed in front of couples engaged in
sex, partly blocking the audience's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' which was Kubrick's final film, was released
with the R rating on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, chairman of the Motion Picture Association, has
strongly defended the board, saying that its purpose is to provide
guidelines for parents, not critics. In a column in Variety last
week, he described those who had assailed the board as ``this small
band of constant whiners'' who ``talk to each other, write for each
other, opine with each other and view with lacerating contempt the
rubes who live Out There, west of Manhattan and east of the San
Andreas Fault.''
</P>
<P>
   But the New York critics asked, ``How is it possible that a
serious movie about human sexuality, made by one of the world's
master filmmakers, cannot be seen by American adults in its
intended form, when those same adults can watch comparable fare any
night on cable television?'' The statement follows a similar one by
35 members of the Los Angeles Film Critics Association.
</P>
<P>
   The New York film critics asked Warner Brothers, which released
the movie, to provide details on what had been approved by Kubrick,
who died in March, in terms of altering the film. ``The process by
which this bowdlerized edition of Kubrick's final film came into
being has been shrouded in vagueness and misinformation,'' the New
York critics said.
</P>
<P>
   The film itself, starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman as a
married couple in New York on a sexual odyssey, received wildly
mixed reviews. After strong box office sales in its first weekend,
attendance has dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to criticism, Terry Semel, co-chairman of Warner
Brothers, said last week: ``We're not in the NC-17 business. When
one looks at `Eyes Wide Shut' perhaps there was not a huge
difference between what would be an R, what would be an NC-17. But
NC-17 is a whole industry. It includes triple-X-rated porno films.
So to us that's just not a business that we're in. Never have
been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOILETS28-COX     07-27 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOILETS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN CONGRESS, A DAY FOR POTTY POLITICS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee considered a swirling
controversy Tuesday that Congress just can't sit on: unpopular
1.6-gallon flush toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1992 law aimed at conserving water, 1.6 gallons per
flush is the maximum allowed for new toilets manufactured for sale
in the United States. That's less than half the old standard of 3.5
gallons, and many constituents are complaining that it's not enough
to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office has received thousands of phone calls, letters and
e-mails from disgruntled consumers who are angry that their new
toilets repeatedly clog, require multiple flushing, and do not save
water,'' said Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Knollenberg is the author of the Plumbing Standards Improvement
Act, which would repeal both the federal flush standard and a
similar requirement that shower heads use no more than 2.5 gallons
of water per minute.
</P>
<P>
   At a Commerce subcommittee hearing, Knollenberg showed a video
clip from the ``Seinfeld'' TV sitcom in which the characters can't
rinse shampoo from their hair with newly installed shower heads.
``Low flow. I don't like the sound of that,'' Kramer frets.
</P>
<P>
   While the subject might be an easy target for bathroom humor,
the issue is serious, insisted the panel's chairman, Rep. Joe
Barton, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But then Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C., read his opening statement,
which was written on a roll of toilet paper. Burr said he supports
the legislation introduced by Knollenberg, whom he jokingly called
``my dear friend, Congressman Flush.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Energy Policy Act, which passed the House by a 328-79
margin and was signed by President Bush, has resulted in
significant savings of water, said Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla.,
who opposes its repeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Plumbing Manufacturers Institute, which represents the
makers of toilets, also opposes the legislation. The 1992 law has
worked well, testified David Goike, a spokesman for Masco Corp., a
Detroit manufacturer of plumbing fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has been in your bathroom since the 1400s,'' he
said, ``ever since officials determined that emptying chamber pots
out the window into the street caused disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the law said 16 billion gallons of water will be
saved in 1999 from the low-flow bathroom fixtures installed in new
homes built in 1998. If every household used the devices, Americans
could save 5.4 billion gallons _ and $11.3 million on their water
bills _ every day, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., questioned the figures. Toilets
with a 1.6-gallon capacity often have to be flushed twice, he said,
so they don't save much water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core problem,'' home builder Jerry Kosmensky told the
subcommittee, ``is that many low-flow, 1.6-gallon toilets do not
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosmensky, president of Gerald Building Co. in Southgate, Mich.,
said the new federal requirements have jeopardized his professional
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tell a new homeowner that the reason their toilet
doesn't work has nothing to do with the plumbing installation but
is because of a federal mandate on low-flow toilets, they think I'm
joking, that I'm making excuses,'' said Kosmensky.
</P>
<P>
   Knollenberg said the situation is so bad that some Americans are
going to Canada to buy 3.5-gallon toilets, many of which were
manufactured in the United States for export. It is not illegal for
individual homeowners to import the toilets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knollenberg said he is optimistic that his bill would pass if
brought to the House floor. The outcry from constituents is only
going to intensify as more old toilets are replaced by new low-flow
ones, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
