<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVTOUR28-COX     07-27 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Hope' rises from the ashes
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It was the worst blood-letting seen on TV in
years: Dr. Jeffrey Geiger (Mandy Patinkin) returned to Chicago Hope
Hospital for the series' season-ending episode, walked into a room
with a bunch of doctors _ and fired just about all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys haven't been talking about medicine,'' he told the
stunned group. ``You've been talking about everything except
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The housecleaning was quick and final, less a dramatic turn in a
storyline (it earned Patinkin a guest-appearance Emmy nomination)
than a dramatic metaphor for the clean sweep the creator of CBS's
nearly-dead ``Chicago Hope'' knew was necessary if the series could
be revived.
</P>
<P>
   ```Chicago Hope' was in trouble in terms of even getting
renewed,'' says creator David E. Kelley. ``We met with CBS and
agreed that in order for `Chicago Hope' to come back, it would have
to be reborn again, and sweeping changes would have to be
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Out: six regulars, including Christine Lahti, Peter Berg, Jayne
Brook and Eric Stoltz.
</P>
<P>
   In: a boatload of newcomers, including Lauren Holly, Barbara
Hershey and Patinkin, once the show's exasperating soul, who left
four years ago to spend more time with his family, but who returns
in a role whose frequency is still being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving: Adam Arkin, Hector Elizondo, Mark Harmon and Rocky
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving wasn't the easiest position to be in. Those whose
characters were axed found out just shortly before the episode was
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said it wasn't a hard way to end the
season,'' says Arkin. ``It was traumatic. (It was) hard to see
people we had worked with for such a long time have to be surprised
with their own departures. It was a hard couple weeks for everyone
connected with the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dramatic thing was building the underground tunnel
system out of (the studio) and escorting the other cast members out
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of a surprise and a trauma, but we've proven to
be quite resilient,'' adds Elizondo. ``We've lost many people in
the past, so we know how to take a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   The show needs a big punch. It finished the past season 73rd in
the ratings, and lost any direction that pointed toward a future.
It had become more soap opera than hospital drama, a situation
Kelley and new executive producers Henry Bromell (``Homicide: Life
on the Street,'' ``Northern Exposure'') and Michael Pressman
(``Picket Fences'') plan to correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character I want to reintroduce to the show is the
hospital,'' says Pressman. ``When you call it `Chicago Hope,' it's
about this state-of-the-art hospital, and we want to return to
those themes.''
</P>
<P>
   Also taking a more active role in the show is Kelley, who since
creating ``Hope'' five years ago has spent most of his time with
two of his other series, ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice.'' (He
has a new series this year on ABC, ``Snoops.'') While Kelley will
still spend most of his time with ``Ally'' and ``The Practice,'' he
has written the ``Hope'' season opener and will consult more
actively on other scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley knows reviving the series for the longterm is a longshot:
it'll air Thursdays at 9 p.m., opposite NBC's ``Frasier.'' But he
thought he was better off rehabbing what he had than creating an
entirely new medical drama. He also didn't want to pull the plug on
something he believes still has some life left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a future is still there. I may be wrong, but I
would have kicked myself a year or two from now if we just let
go,'' Kelley says. ``The truth is, I do that with `Picket Fences'
from time to time. I still regret letting it go, because I think
there was more life in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I didn't want to live that regret twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Title clash
</P>
<P>
   ABC and CBS premiere dramas this season with near-exact titles:
``Once and Again'' (ABC) and ``Now and Again'' (CBS). Both networks
agree somebody's title has to go, but both say it won't be their's.
Earlier this week, CBS TV president Leslie Moonves said he'd wait
for ABC to blink first. On Tuesday, ABC said they weren't blinking,
that ``Once and Again'' creators Ed Zwick and Marshall Herskowitz
(``thirtysomething,'' ``My So-Called Life'') are committed to the
title and that the series is strong enough to draw people no matter
what it's called. ``People watch shows, not titles,'' said ABC
entertainment head Jamie Tarses. What's that again?
</P>
<P>
   Carey does improv
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drew Carey Show'' will air a live episode in November. The
show will contain a partially unscripted storyline, in which the
cast plays improvisational games. It'll be performed three times _
once for each time zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's live, there's gonna be improv, anything can happen,''
said executive producer Bruce Helford. ``I just hope they don't tap
the keg until after the third show.''
</P>
<P>
   Norm's new show
</P>
<P>
   ABC is developing a political quiz show for Norm Macdonald, who
currently stars in the network's sitcom ``The Norm Show.'' As with
Drew Carey's popular ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?'', the format is
taken from a hit British show. ``The success of `Whose Line' is
testament to what happens if you come up with an original idea,''
said ABC entertainment head Jamie Tarses. Hmmm. The show could air
mid-season.
</P>
<P>
   `Parts' blurred
</P>
<P>
   USA is taking a different approach to airing Howard Stern's
1997, R-rated ``Private Parts'' on Aug. 27: rather than edit out
unacceptable-for-basic-cable language and nudity, the network will
simply bleep and blur it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
