<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BACKS CLINTON'S DECISION TO RENEW NORMAL TRADE WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a rigorous debate over human rights in
China and evidence that China stole U.S. nuclear secrets, the House
voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to back President Clinton's decision
to renew normal trade relations with the world's most populous
nation.
</P>
<P>
   This year's debate was more contentious than in previous years
because of the nuclear spying allegations and reports of recent
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote of 260 to 170 in favor of retaining normal trade
was about the same as last year's 264-166 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we are doing this to ourselves,'' said Rep.
Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., of the annual China debate. ``Every single
year we come up here and beat the tambourine and hit the drum.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1974 law requires that the president make a decision every
year on whether to renew China's trading status _ a status
permanently enjoyed by most of the world's countries expect
Afghanistan, Cuba, Laos, North Korea, Vietnam and Yugoslavia.
Congress then has 60 days to reject the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has never repudiated the White House on this issue. The
closest battled came in 1992 when Congress rejected President
George Bush's decision to renew normal trade relations after the
1989 Tiananmen Square massacre when the Chinese government cracked
down on pro-democracy protesters. Bush vetoed that legislation and
the Senate failed to muster the 67 votes required to override.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of renewing China's trade status _ which included
liberal Democrats and conservative Republicans _ cited human rights
abuses like the arrest of people involved in a spiritual meditation
group referred to as Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we hold this debate the Chinese government is conducting
another major crack down,'' said Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J.,
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong-based Center for Human Rights reported Monday that
China arrested 1,200 people last week for their involvement in the
Falun Gong after China's communist government outlawed the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just about every area I can think of China's record
stinks,'' said Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., citing human rights abuses
as well as allegations that China stole U.S. nuclear secrets and is
giving that information to other countries. ``How all this merits
preferential trade status is beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents like Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., argued that normal
trade status helps China far more than it helps the United States,
producing a U.S. trade deficit with China of $57 billion last year
when the United States imported $71 billion worth of goods from
China while only exporting $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we revoked China's trading status, they are not going to
walk away,'' Pelosi said. ``Where are they going to sell $70
billion worth of goods?''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who also opposed
the renewal of normal trade, noted that the United States sells
more to Belgium, a country of 10 million people, than it does to
China's 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want one-way free trade,'' Gephardt said referring to
China's laws that keep many U.S. goods out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of continuing normal trade relations with China
argued that it's the only way for the United States to coax the
Chinese government to improve its record on human rights and to
further open its markets to U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agrees that the Chinese government violates human
rights, imprisons dissidents, muzzles free speech and forces women
to have abortions,'' said Rep. Joseph Pitts, R-Pa., ``Revoking
trade status would strengthen the Chinese regime and intensify
these human rights abuses,'' he said, citing letters from American
religious workers living in China.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said the Chinese government wouldn't be hurt at all if
China's trade status were revoked. Instead, he argued, the American
economy would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan and Europe would be more than happy to replace America
as a reliable supplier,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote came as China and the United States are beginning
to renew trade talks that include discussing ways to allow more
U.S. goods into China, thereby reducing the trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce David Aaron arrived in Beijing
Tuesday for the first-high level trade talks since the United
States accidentally bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are aimed at resuming negotiations about China's entry
into the World Trade Organization, a Geneva-based organization that
regulates world trade. WTO entry would require China to
significantly lower its trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would have to decide whether to allow China into the
WTO, which includes giving China permanent normal trading status.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the House vote on normal trade relations
``is the right way to advance America's interests'' and said it
``promotes China's integration into the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0194 </DOCNO>
