<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLERS-ART-10     07-27 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLERS-ART-1064&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO WHO INTERVIEWED SERIAL KILLERS FOR TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of the filmmakers is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(EDS: Spelling of ``Sheilagh'' in 12th graf is correct.) 
(yn) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took four years of relentless telephoning of prison
officials, social workers, psychiatrists and others before Maxine
Paul and her Connecticut neighbor and partner, Amy Kalafa, managed
to carve their way through the institutional barricades that stood
between them and their goal.
</P>
<P>
   The two women had set out to make documentaries together. They
wanted to examine psychological therapy, exploring its many forms
and guises. Instead, they wound up interviewing serial killers,
including David Berkowitz, in many forms and guises. The result:
three hourlong programs for Court TV that are, by almost any
standard, unconventional.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paul and Ms. Kalafa (pronounced KAL-if-uh) were the first
documentarians ever permitted inside the Danbury Federal
Corrections Institute, in Danbury, Conn. They have filmed therapy
sessions and interviewed sociopaths in five New York prisons,
including Sing Sing, in Ossining, and the maximum-security Sullivan
Correctional Facility, where Berkowitz is confined.
</P>
<P>
   The program that includes the interview with him is being
broadcast Wednesday night at 10 on Court TV, which bought their
project, called ``Inside the Criminal Mind,'' and is showing it as
part of the cable network's regular primetime series ``Crime
Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had heard, on one of our scouting trips, that David
Berkowitz was a model prisoner,'' Ms. Paul said. ``I found that
fascinating, partly because I moved to New York in the summer of
1977, the year of the Son of Sam murders, and partly because what
we're trying to do is look at what makes these people tick. I
thought, `He's a model prisoner? He's a counselor to
lower-functioning inmates?'''
</P>
<P>
   She wrote to Berkowitz, in care of the deputy superintendent at
Sullivan, in Fallsburg, N.Y., but Berkowitz did not reply. For
once, the tenacious Ms. Paul decided to leave well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy and I talked it over, and we figured, we don't want to be
pushy with David Berkowitz,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But last February, the women were at Sullivan interviewing,
among others, a cannibalistic serial killer named Artie Shawcross.
Berkowitz heard about what they were doing, discussed it with
prison counselors and then, via the deputy superintendent, told Ms.
Paul he wanted to be included in their project.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, done in March, several months before Spike
Lee's film, ``Summer of Sam,'' was released, Berkowitz would not
discuss specific details of his crimes. He did talk about his
childhood, his parents, his early belief in Satan and how he became
involved with therapy in prison. Sullivan has a widely praised
psychotherapy program in which Berkowitz works as an inmate program
aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are essentially almost therapy assistants,'' Ed Rudder,
the program's clinical coordinator, says in the documentary. He
says that Berkowitz is ``highly recommended by the inmates he works
with'' and by the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV may be exploiting the interest in Berkowitz by delaying
running the documentary until now, after the storm of publicity
about Lee's film, but to Ms. Paul and Ms. Kalafa, his was just one
more criminal mind to be explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't consider it exploitive, mostly on the strength of
these filmmakers' work,'' said Sheilagh D'Arcy McGee, Court TV's
senior vice president for programming. ``You look at the three
hours they've delivered and it's an enormous sampling _ of
different prisons, of different men and women, of the programs
they're in before and after their release from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``But clearly Berkowitz and Shawcross are in a category of their
own,'' she added, acknowledging the likely public fascination with
such killers.
</P>
<P>
   To the two documentarians, Berkowitz and Shawcross are two
people in a diverse gallery of women and men to be examined, as
they try to give viewers a sense of what such criminals are
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to provide a window into the ways therapy can be
effective, both in the criminal justice system and elsewhere.
Originally, they had hoped to start a cable network, to be called
Therapy TV. They settled for using that name for the production
company they founded, whose studios are in a cottage just behind
Ms. Kalafa's Connecticut home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paul has an elfin face topped by a crop of dark curly hair,
and the upbeat, high-energy demeanor of a cheerleader. Ms. Kalafa,
slim of face and figure, looks as if she might to be a yoga
instructor or a health food purveyor. Both married and both
mothers, they fit comfortably into the woodsy suburbs of Weston,
Conn., archetypal Martha Stewart country; in fact, Ms. Kalafa's
husband, Alex Gunuey, works nearby as a staff editor on Martha
Stewart's television programs.
</P>
<P>
   But their work jars all those stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Its form is distinctive, first of all. They do not use a
narrator (theirs are the only segments on ``Crime Stories'' that do
not), and their programs look more like cinema verite than like the
smoothly edited documentaries of PBS.
</P>
<P>
   To be as unobtrusive as possible, in hopes of being allowed to
return, they developed what they call ``fly on the wall''
techniques, using mini-digital cameras, which are more
sophisticated than camcorders but almost as small; no added
lighting unless absolutely necessary, and one soundman.
</P>
<P>
   Neither woman is a trained journalist. Ms. Paul was an
entertainment lawyer and Ms. Kalafa was editing a parenting program
for the Lifetime cable network when the two became partners in
Therapy TV five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Questions sometimes go unanswered, and inmates' vague comments
are left unclarified. ``The idea is to stimulate discussion, to
have people to come out of this the way you do from a movie,
saying, `What do you think he meant by that?''' Ms. Kalafa said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunuey, who works as their cameraman and director, added, ``We
are not doing investigative reporting; we're showing a slice of
life, a portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   But many viewers might object that showing counseling sessions
and such therapeutic methods as letting murderers raise puppies is
too sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to find a balance,'' Ms. Kalafa said. ``You can
make someone seem sympathetic, because of his psychosis, or you can
make him seem a monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``And these inmates can be very manipulative. We try not to say,
`This is fact.' We try to give a feeling of a person's mindset, and
suggest the evolution of that mind in prison.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They first approached HBO Downtown Productions with the idea for
eight different series on aspects of psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were interested in the prison series idea, but they
didn't believe we could get into prisons, let alone film their
therapy sessions,'' Ms. Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   So they tried Court TV. When they got a call to come into
Manhattan for an interview last September, Ms. Kalafa was fighting
a serious case of Lyme disease and had an intravenous drip in her
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy had to drip every four hours,'' Ms. Paul said. ``But this
was the only time Court TV could see us. We took the train to Grand
Central and marched down Third Avenue, pushing that IV pole. We
just couldn't miss that opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEINSTEIN-VEEP-HNS &LR;      07-27 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-VEEP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 FEINSTEIN'S NAME FLOATED AS POSSIBLE VEEP CANDIDATE   (EDs: FILED
in ``p'' and ``w'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The name of Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a California
Democrat, is being floated in party circles as a possible vice
presidential candidate in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings, D-S.C., said Tuesday that her
name has been put forward in informal discussions ``in the
cloakroom'' among Democratic senators. He was referring to a
gathering place just off the Senate floor where lawmakers hold
private conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why Feinstein is being mentioned, Hollings told
reporters, ``She's a dynamic speaker and public servant on the one
hand, but (also) she'd bring California'' behind the Democratic
ticket. The state, with 54 of the 270 electoral votes required to
win the White House, is the largest prize in the presidential
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., who heads the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee (DSCC), which helps recruit and fund
Democratic Senate candidates, said Feinstein's name tops every list
he's seen for the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has gained a lot of experience at different levels of
government,'' Torricelli said. ``She has the depth of knowledge and
the independence that many of us want in a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. J. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., who formerly headed the DSCC,
said Feinstein would be ``very strong'' on a national ticket.
``She's got charisma; she's got the spark that people recognize,''
Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maslin, an Oakland-Calif.-based Democratic pollster, said
Feinstein ``would add an awful lot to any ticket ... There aren't a
whole lot of people at this level of the Democratic Party who have
the kinds of credentials that she has.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the talk of her as a Democratic running mate,
Feinstein stressed that neither Vice President Al Gore, the party's
leading candidate, nor former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, his
challenger, has discussed the office with her.
</P>
<P>
   If she were invited to join the ticket, she said in an
interview, ``it would be a hard decision.'' She added that she does
not foresee any such invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation concerns her, she said, because she doesn't want
her constituents to think she isn't running for the Senate. As it
stands now, she said, ``I am not going after anything else (in
2000) but my Senate seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Before winning a Senate seat in a special election in 1992,
Feinstein was the Democratic nominee for California governor, the
mayor of San Francisco for nearly 11 years and a member of the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein is considered a political moderate. She has supported
traditional liberal issues such as abortion rights and gun control
while backing traditional conservative fare such as the death
penalty and the toughening of immigration standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the liberal Americans for Democratic Action gave
Feinstein a 90 percent approval rating in 1998, down from 95
percent in 1996. The American Conservative Union, however, gave
Feinstein a 4 percent approval rating in 1998, down from a career
high of 20 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at the e-mail address
eric(at)hearstdc.com; Judy Holland can be reached at
judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
