<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-KUTI-ART-NYT &LR;      07-27 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-KUTI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SON BUILDS ON HIS FATHER'S AFRO-BEAT AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID HECHT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ With Nigeria's move to civilian rule, one of
the songs being played on the radio is ``What Will Tomorrow
Bring?'' by Femi Anikulapo-Kuti, son of the Afro-beat pioneer Fela.
</P>
<P>
   Fela also fearlessly spoke out against corruption and repression
in successive governments, never fleeing into exile despite
beatings and arrests. Since Fela's death from AIDS in 1997, Kuti,
who bears an uncanny resemblance to his father, has assumed his
political and musical mantles.
</P>
<P>
   The military government that stepped down last spring banned his
hit song ``Beng Beng Beng.'' The title makes a sexually explicit
reference and is not a call to arms, he said. But like his father,
Kuti, 36, has a way of making sex seem like an act of political
defiance. ``It's something people want that the government cannot
give us,'' he conceded. ``It makes them irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no love lost between the musician and the new civilian
government of President Olusegun Obasanjo, who was Nigeria's
military ruler in the late 1970s. The ban on ``Beng Beng Beng'' has
not been lifted. Kuti refused to perform at Obasanjo's inauguration
in May, saying: ``I cannot forget the last time he was in power.
``His regime was probably the worst regime Nigeria could ever dream
of. He burnt houses; he burnt markets. His soldiers were flogging
civilians in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kuti added, ``People can change, and we should give him a
second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was more of a diplomat than Fela was. ``My father
would always say, `The government is a thief.' I say, `I would
prefer if the government stops stealing the money.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are other differences. The son doesn't smoke marijuana;
his father always seemed to have a joint at hand. The father's sax
sounded raw; his son's is richer and more virtuosic, and he insists
that his band members dress well and behave politely.
</P>
<P>
   Kuti's songs have the speedy rhythms and Afro-beat sound his
father invented in the 1970s _ a blend of Yoruba high life with
rock and soul _ but they also reflect pop, jazz and African musical
styles. ``Afro-beat is just my starting point,'' Kuti said.
</P>
<P>
   His songs are more structured and more conscious of market
trends. In his latest album, ``Shoki Shoki'' (Polygram), the
quasi-'70s synthesizer and wah-wah-pedal effects owe more to the
funk revival with singers like Lauryn Hill than to music his father
played in his heyday. Kuti's album was No. 1 on the European world
music chart for two months earlier this year and is scheduled to be
released in the United States later this year.
</P>
<P>
   What the father and son's songs share is a libidinous energy,
while focusing on Nigeria's political failures. In Kuti's concerts
his dancers make sexually suggestive movements to lyrics like
``These politicians and soldiers spoil Nigeria so'' and
``government can scatter your head.'' Sometimes Kuti invites
audience members onstage to simulate sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kuti and his band, Positive Force, have been touring Africa and
Europe and are to perform in the United States in September. His
following in the West is linked partly to the popularity of cover
songs from his father's classics like ``Upside Down,'' at
mainstream dance clubs in New York like Body and Soul. Fela has
become a 1970s icon, celebrated as a Nigerian bad boy.
</P>
<P>
   Born Fela Ransome-Kuti, the musician changed his name to Fela
Anikulapo-Kuti, ``anikulapo'' meaning ``he who keeps death in his
pocket'' in Yoruba. Despite his raw and defiant image, he grew up
in a prosperous middle-class family and studied music at the
Trinity College of Music in London. Later, after being exposed to
the ideas of Malcolm X and Eldridge Cleaver, he came to consider
Western education imperialist propaganda and tried to prevent his
children from attending school.
</P>
<P>
   Femi Kuti got his education mostly from playing in his father's
band. ``I begged him to at least let me study music,'' the musician
recalled. ``But he would say, `Everything you need to know you can
learn on the streets.'''
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years in the band, Kuti formed his own group in 1986.
He said that his concerts did not attract much of an audience then
because people ``couldn't understand why I didn't want to keep
playing under a great man like my father.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was not supportive, he said, and derided his music
after watching him perform. ``I felt like committing suicide,''
Kuti recalled, ``but I kept trying.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, however, Kuti got to try out at the Shrine, his
father's celebrated club in Lagos. ``After one song Fela got up and
danced,'' Kuti said. ``Afterward he announced that I was the only
person besides him who knew how to play Afro-beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Fela's fans agree. Some prefer the music of Seun
Kuti, Femi's younger brother, who performs only original Fela songs
with his father's old band, Egypt 80.
</P>
<P>
   Many Nigerians who campaigned for civilian rule say that Kuti
failed to do his part and sold out his father's dream, but as the
son sees it, the struggle ultimately broke his father, who died at
age 58 during the rule of Gen. Sani Abacha, a military strongman
and international pariah. ``He spent his whole life fighting the
system and nothing changed,'' Kuti said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Kuti founded a political awareness group called MASS,
the Movement Against Second Slavery, which he insists is not like
the political party his father started in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Fela could not accept that Africans gained independence in the
1960s only to have their own leaders oppress them and steal their
riches, his son said. But those of the sons' generation have known
no other reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the worst years we mostly found ways to get by,'' Kuti
said, ``and it is that resourcefulness that we are trying to build
on.''
</P>
<P>
   As MASS's spokesman, Folarin Williams, put it, ``The revolution
cannot be won on the streets. That is where the army and the
government are strongest.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuti said his life style was also different from his father's.
His father had 27 wives and refused to use condoms, contending that
they were part of a conspiracy by whites to prevent black men from
enjoying sex.
</P>
<P>
   His son has one wife, whom he said he is faithful to ``95 to 90
percent of the time.'' When he is not, he said, he always uses a
condom. One thing he has learned, he explained, is that ``if you
don't adapt, you die.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
