<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D/FW-RANKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D/FW AIRPORT BATTLING IMAGE PROBLEMS AMID SOME USERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   D/FW AIRPORT _ Atlanta businessman Ron Hartley hates Dallas/Fort
Worth Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke among passengers is that it takes longer to taxi to
the gate than it takes to fly to D/FW in the first place,'' Hartley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other frequent complaints are about the difficulty of changing
gates for a connecting flight and the wait for baggage at claim
areas.
</P>
<P>
   D/FW has fans, too. They primarily are North Texas residents who
appreciate the convenience of parking near their gates, which isn't
possible at many airports.
</P>
<P>
   But D/FW's ranking among world airports has slipped, and part of
the reason may be its image problems, airport officials say. Once
projected by most aviation industry experts to become the world's
busiest airport by 2000, D/FW was No. 3 in total passengers for two
years after losing the No. 2 ranking to Atlanta Hartsfield Airport.
It then dropped to fifth place in 1998 behind O'Hare, Hartsfield,
Los Angeles International and London Heathrow airports. In flight
operations, Chicago and Atlanta led the pack.
</P>
<P>
   In May this year, the most recent month for which figures are
available, D/FW's passenger count was down 2.8 percent from May
1998, according to the airport's Performance Assessment Report
distributed to the D/FW Airport Board on July 1. Industrywide,
airline passenger counts increased 0.6 percent, according to the
Air Transport Association, which includes the nation's major
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a troubling decrease of 4.9 percent in flight
operations from 1995 to '98,'' D/FW Deputy Executive Director Kevin
Cox said. ``That's not a good trend for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Major improvements to help D/FW grow and to address key problems
are planned. But officials say those changes are stalled because of
a dispute involving Dallas Love Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the areas where we have need for massive funding are
awaiting resolution of these regional aviation issues,'' D/FW
Executive Director Jeff Fegan said.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials say that the airport's design and some
antiquated systems irritate some travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting passengers often find the horseshoe-shaped terminal
layout a challenge, especially because the airport's dominant
carrier, American Airlines, operates at three terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The airport was built that way because, when it opened in 1974,
it was intended to serve area passengers. Airlines didn't begin the
hub-and-spoke operations that bring millions of connecting
passengers to D/FW until after the federal government deregulated
the industry in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two-thirds of American's customers at D/FW connect to
another flight, said John Hotard, an American spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The chief problem for connecting passengers is the slow and
often troublesome tram system that moves passengers among
terminals. Built in the early 1970s, the Airport Train is a one-way
system that takes 20 minutes or more to make a loop of the terminal
area. The automated system is so obsolete that many replacement
parts are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   The taxiing problem, which can mean delays of 15 minutes or more
in reaching a gate after landing, is partly because many flights
land on the airport's west side and must taxi across busy runways
and bridges to reach east-side terminals. Terminals A, C and E, the
busiest, are east of International Parkway. Only Terminal B is on
the west side.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say they do their best to move luggage from planes to
the baggage claim carousels as quickly as possible, but they blame
the airport layout for the delays that customers perceive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most airports, you have to make a 10-minute walk just to
reach the bag-claim area,'' Hotard said. ``During that time, the
ground crews are taking the bags off the plane and getting them to
the claim area. At D/FW, people walk off the plane and are at
baggage claim within a few yards. Of course there is going to be a
wait. It takes time to get all the bags off the airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Fegan and his staff outlined a new master plan to the airport
board in May 1998 that calls for $5 billion in projects during the
next few years. First on the list is a $700 million people mover
system.
</P>
<P>
   As for long taxiing times, the airport plans to build perimeter
taxiways _ a series of routes around the ends of the runways _ so
planes won't have to cross other runways to get to terminals or
remote runways.
</P>
<P>
   But all these projects are on hold because of the 2-year-old
legal dispute between the airport's owner cities, Fort Worth and
Dallas, about the possible expansion of airline service at Love
Field in Dallas. Because of legal concerns, the matter has stopped
D/FW from issuing bonds to finance even the first project.
</P>
<P>
   D/FW officials said that even if the Love Field dispute isn't
settled soon, they will take their request for about $2.1 billion
worth of projects to the Fort Worth and Dallas city councils this
year to seek approval of a bond issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we need to do,'' Fegan said. ``We're ready to
make the investment.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
