<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PAX-TEX     07-27 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WOULD GOD WATCH? PAX THINKS IT KNOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When Pax Net arrived here for the industry's
annual presentation of fall programming, many of the 150 television
critics had already adjourned to the hotel pool. And with Pax
introducing stars like Suki Kaiser, Michelle Rene Thomas and
Spencer Rochfort, the usually star-starved paparazzi didn't even
bother showing up.
</P>
<P>
   For a network whose symbols include doves and white clouds, and
whose show scripts are sent back to writers if they fail a
spirituality litmus test, Pax has had a difficult time convincing
viewers and industry analysts that it's not some wacky cult with a
broadcast signal.
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps, worse: a network so gung-ho about its spiritual
values that the quality of its productions ranks somewhere between
a high school play and cable-access TV.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Pax audience might rival that of a cable-access
show. As it closes in on next month's one-year anniversary, Pax
remains a tiny morsel of a network, one whose highest-rated program
is ``It's a Miracle,'' a reality series devoted to the
investigation of miracles. It draws fewer than 1 million viewers
per show.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 700,000 viewers are tuning in to Pax at any given
time on weekdays, even though most of its schedule is filled with
major-network reruns. This means Pax as a network ranks behind the
most ratings-challenged series on UPN, a network having so much
trouble it seems on a continual death watch.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question for Pax: Why bother?
</P>
<P>
   But creator Bud Paxson has always considered Pax to be divinely
inspired. He built the network with the purpose of filling the
airwaves with family-friendly programming, a radical idea when you
consider a TV landscape in which success is based largely on shows
filled with sexual relationships, crassness and vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   If the networks are indeed youth-obsessed and focused on pushing
taste boundaries (in one new WB sitcom, a mother answers the door
topless, and in the midseason CBS mob series Falcone, a man is
brutally stabbed to death), Paxson believes Pax could successfully
position itself as the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the older viewers first fell away when the networks
decided to get rid of them, and then the families fell away,'' says
Jeff Sagansky, president and CEO of Pax, and former entertainment
president of CBS. ``And the decline of family viewing has far
outpaced general audience viewing, because there's nothing for them
to watch. And this season, you're going to see a falloff of
minority viewing, because there's not going to be enough there for
them, either.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing in Pax's many acquisitions of network shows
(''Eight Is Enough,'' ``Highway to Heaven,'' to name two) or its
originals to suggest that it cares about cultural diversity either.
</P>
<P>
   But Sagansky is right in pointing out that if viewers so craved
``cutting-edge'' TV, then the highest-rated series on the WB
wouldn't be the family-friendly ``7th Heaven.'' And on CBS, it
wouldn't be ``Touched by an Angel,'' the only TV series with God as
a regular cast member.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the networks downplay Pax's very existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's nothing more than a cable channel,'' says the
WB's CEO, Jamie Kellner. ``It won't be much of a threat to anyone
until it moves away from network reruns and moves toward original
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the plan. Beginning next month, Pax offers a pair of
original one-hour dramas, an hourlong anthology series and a
variety show featuring secular music. The series will join the
network's two returning original series, ``It's a Miracle'' and
``Little Men,'' the drama inspired by the writings of Louisa May
Alcott.
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky's favorite is ``Destination Stardom,'' a revamped
``Star Search'' set in Hawaii and showcasing contestants vying for
prizes in various categories, from vocalists to family acts. It's
hosted by ``Entertainment Tonight's'' bubbly Lisa Canning, and
produced by Al Masini of ``Solid Gold'' and ``Star Search'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' is another Sagansky possibility.
It's a drama that will bring to life the books by authors Jack
Canfield and Mark Victor Hansen that focus on hope and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The series with the most promise is ``Hope Island,'' a drama
that easily stands up to anything screened here thus far. Slated
for Sundays beginning Sept. 12, ``Hope Island'' is set in a
seafaring town and filled with quirky characters brought to life by
the whimsical performances of a host of unknown actors. (You could
say it's ``Northern Exposure'' with spirituality.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope Island'' explores a variety of family-oriented themes _
its pilot episode alone deals with the challenges of raising
children, maintaining a sense of family, loyalty and fighting for
one's faith and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   No Pax series makes it on the air without Sagansky asking: Would
God watch this? (Although ``Destination Stardom'' proves that some
programs do make it on the air without obvious spirituality.)
</P>
<P>
   For all its wholesome qualities, Pax is still a business. How it
manages financially with so few viewers is evident in its cost
structure. Rather than develop 100 scripts and produce 30 pilots as
networks do, Pax hones in on a few shows that it is determined to
do. (Getting unknown, low-priced actors also helps the bottom
line.)
</P>
<P>
   And since Pax owns a chain of television stations, it generates
revenue from both national and local advertising spots.
</P>
<P>
   Pax has also done well in positioning its channel on cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Where Pax spends money is on marketing and promotion _ $40
million this year alone, according to Sagansky. John DeRoche,
general sales manager of KPXD, the Pax station in the Fort
Worth-Dallas market, has also partnered with radio stations,
Christian and secular, to draw more eyeballs to Pax.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception after its presentation, Sagansky didn't seem
fazed by the low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all unexplored territory, we know,'' he said. ``Our
challenge isn't getting people to watch, because we're certain that
that will occur as long as we do this and still make it
entertaining, make it dramatic, make it moving. People will come.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
