<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5810 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     07-27 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN GAVE LITERARY ROOTS TO SOAP OPERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subject is soap opera of the literary kind.
</P>
<P>
   The genre endures healthy in the marketplace. Danielle Steel has
worn the commercial crown more than two decades, producing novels
on an average of one every eight months. Knocking Steel is a vested
fashion of literary snobbery. It speaks no disrespect of Steel to
suggest, as I do, that better soap opera has been written _ if not,
perhaps, lately.
</P>
<P>
   I offer a candidate title for the mythical crown as best soap
opera ever delivered in the form of a novel. It goes back 72 years,
and was already an old book when I encountered it in, I believe,
the early 1950s. The author was a Canadian woman by the arresting
name of Mazo de la Roche. Research confirms that her ``Jalna'' was
the talk of the book world in 1927, a sensational seller not only
in her own country, but in the United States, Great Britain, Europe
and the Orient. More than that, it was a considerable critical
success and copped the ``Atlantic Monthly'' prize as the year's
best novel published in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalna'' is the name of a family estate in Ontario. The family
name is Whiteoak, and many bear the name. I could confuse and
bewilder any reader by enumerating them by name and familial
relationships, even if I could remember them all, and their
intertwined personal dramas. That's the essence of soap opera. Much
ado among many people, the closer-connected the better. If you want
a good laugh, just read in this newspaper the weekly summaries of
happenings in the popular TV soaps.
</P>
<P>
   There's melodrama aplenty, there's romance and marriage and
infidelity and misunderstanding, and there's outright villainy.
Courtroom trials are a staple of the genre, with the wronged person
usually acquitted, mercifully, to conclude what would be a chapter
if it were in a book. Another convention of soap opera in any form
is the triangle consisting of two strong women (one good, one bad)
contending for an easily manipulated man who really isn't worth
their trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Mazo de la Roche may have addressed ``Jalna'' and its many
sequels to a feminine readership, and her women are more
resourceful than the men. Yet ``Jalna'' captured a substantial male
audience, and was passed around the family, especially when the
family identified with the affluent Whiteoaks, if only wishfully.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jalna,'' something is always happening or is about to. It
is chessboard movement involving dozens of characters, most of whom
are in the family. Some are trying to get into the Whiteoak clan,
others seeking desperately to escape. The author writes clearly,
imparting individual distinctions to her large cast, so the reader
usually understands who's who and doing what. And the goings-on at
the old plantation are rather spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Mazo de la Roche decided she had a good thing going, and began
cranking out the sequels, introducing still more Whiteoaks along
the way. Eventually there were more than a dozen works in the
series, usually getting the estate into the title (''Whiteoaks of
Jalna,'' e.g.); and the succession obeyed the law of diminishing
returns. I read only the first installment; that was enough. Yet
faithful thousands just couldn't get enough of the Whiteoaks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet that ``Jalna'' is superior to its progeny, not
only for its original imagination, but for its wonderfully
convoluted design. It is sagalike, giving background to the family
history, and revealing via flashbacks its most disarming character
_ feisty Grandma Whiteoak, almost 100 _ in her romantic youth.
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Jalna'' remains in print, and I'm told that most
of the books still get considerable play in the public libraries.
So if literary soap opera is your suppressed desire ...
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
