<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Wednesday, July 28. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   FBI-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ Developments concerning an
administration plan to deploy a system of monitoring software to
protect the nation's data networks from intruders. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLDIERS (Leskovac, Yugoslavia) _ Life at war was
exhilarating and terrifying, and life afterwards is pallid and full
of worries, especially in a war-broken, sanctions-battered economy,
say men like Vlada, 31, who fought with the Yugoslav army. He and
other soldiers have taken part in the daily demonstrations of army
reservists in Leskovac for their back pay and for the resignation
of President Slobodan Milosevic. There is fury here, but it is
unfocused, a tinder box waiting for a leader and a spark. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-DETECTIVES (Wichita, Kan.) _ One of America's wealthiest
and most private families found itself in an unwanted spotlight
last summer as its fractious members waged a bitter courtroom fight
over the family business, Koch Industries, the vast oil and gas
company with headquarters on the prairie at the edge of town here.
By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DANGEROUS-SCHOOL (Los Angeles) _ It looms on a lonely lot
at the edge of downtown, a hulking pile of buff brick and brown
stone, like some half-finished temple or Pharaoh's tomb. It would
be the most expensive public high school ever built in the nation,
at a cost of more than $200 million, but now the Belmont Learning
Center may never be finished _ and if it is, no one may want to go
to school there. The school was built atop an abandoned oil field,
despite repeated red flags and warnings, and officials now say
there may be no way to vent away seeping methane gas and other
hazards to make it safe enough to occupy. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-ARK (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
came to the South Tuesday for a fundraising tour and to poke fun at
Hillary Clinton, the mayor's potential rival for the U.S. Senate.
Giuliani has tried to portray Mrs. Clinton as a carpetbagger
because she has never lived in New York. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-UMPIRES (New York) _ From wires: In what appears to be an
overwhelming defeat, the threatened walkout by major league umpires
collapsed Tuesday, with all umpires withdrawing their resignations.
By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Anxious to pass managed care
legislation before the congressional recess, House Republican
leaders Tuesday made a tentative decision to bypass their own
committees and bring a modified version of the Senate legislation
to the House floor. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
