<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORKY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-27 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORKY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FROM A HIGH PLACE': UNEVEN TALE OF AN ARTIST IN A BORROWED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(yn) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lives of great artists tend to be overshadowed by their art.
It's a measure of their greatness that we don't really care who
they were. We have our esthetic experiences first and ask questions
later. The answers only rarely trigger a reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   But some artists are more overshadowed than others, and among
outstanding 20th-century painters, few are more obscure than the
American Abstract Expressionist Arshile Gorky, the Armenian youth
who, as Vostanig Adoian, arrived in the United States in 1920
determined to become an important painter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 20 years, he created an almost completely false
persona that variously included a Russian background, kinship to
Maxim Gorky, study in Paris and a degree in engineering from Brown
University. (This disguise was so complete that Gorky's wife, Agnes
Magruder _ whom he nicknamed Mougouch _ did not learn his real name
until nearly a decade after his death.) More important, he entered
a dogged apprenticeship to the styles of European masters like
Ingres, Cezanne and finally Picasso and Miro. And he spent a great
of time talking, hashing over artistic issues, especially with his
closest friends, Stuart Davis, John Graham and de Kooning.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1940s, his goal was in sight. Contact with the
European Surrealists who were sitting out World War II in New York
(most notably Andre Breton, the style's autocratic leader, and the
painter Roberto Matta) and two summers spent drawing the lush
landscape of northern Virginia (at his in-laws' summer retreat),
brought a sudden ripening of his art. Basically he took Surrealist
automatist drawing and pointed it in a new direction, adding color,
scale, body and physical accident and an emotional fervor it had
never previously possessed. The example of his liberated line
alternating with clouds and plumes of hothouse color _ conjuring an
abstracted, ecstatic, eroticized vision of nature _ was not lost on
de Kooning, Jackson Pollock and Mark Rothko, or later on Cy
Twombly.
</P>
<P>
   But just as success loomed, disaster struck and struck again.
Gorky's misfortunes included colon cancer, a fire that destroyed a
studio full of new paintings and drawings, a car accident that
broke several vertebrae in his neck and left him in excruciating
pain, and an estrangement from his wife and two young daughters
that left him in despair. In July 1948, alone on his family's
rented farm near Sherman, Conn., Gorky went to a small shed and
hanged himself. His final words, scrawled onto a small blackboard,
were ``Goodbye my loves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorky's tragic end echoed a beginning so horrific that, as
Matthew Spender argues in his alternatively illuminating and
tedious biography of the artist, it could ultimately neither be
faced nor shared. The poor farmers of northeastern Armenia
inhabited an idyllic landscape on the shores of Lake Van, living
close to nature but also in continuous fear of persecution by the
Turks. The Turks began their most savage campaign in 1915, a series
of massacres, sackings, sieges, forced marches and political
betrayal that count as the 20th-century's first genocide. Gorky and
his sister, Vartoosh, endured this chaos for four years, but
watched their mother succumb to a paralyzing depression and death.
</P>
<P>
   Irritating and plodding as it can sometimes be, Spender's book
is a gift to anyone interested in 20th-century American art. He has
been married since 1967 to Gorky's elder daughter, Maro, and his
access to both people and papers has enabled him to separate fact
from fiction as never before. He untangles the protective web of
lies that Gorky wove around himself and in the process tells a
story and presents a truth that is even more staggering.
</P>
<P>
   The book drags along for great stretches of time, spelling out
the intricacies of Gorky's ancestry and the simplicity of village
life in Armenia, the network of surviving family members who ended
up in the United States, the ups and mostly downs of Gorky's
pursuit of love and the development of his art. Spender seems to
have packed every available shred of family memory into his
narrative, which contributes to the slowness. And he doesn't have
much feeling for Gorky's art or its fits-and-starts development.
(Although the absence of color reproductions doesn't help.) The
pace quickens here and there, especially in portions based on the
reminiscences of de Kooning and Davis, or others who were close.
</P>
<P>
   But as the book builds toward its harrowing finish, things
become clearer and clearer. Spender is telling the story of an
outsider, an autodidact in the extreme who came from a world that
was not only rural and Eastern European (like that of Chagall and
Soutine) but in many ways medieval. That Gorky made his way in the
United States at all, much less to the forefront of 20th-century
art, is an astounding testament to his will, intelligence and
innate sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Spender makes sure that we understand the great stress that the
assimilation effort placed on the artist and those around him,
especially his devoted Mougouch. And in the end he also shows us
that parts of Gorky remained unassimilated, hampering him
throughout his career and becoming intransigent and crippling as
his health deteriorated: his chauvinism toward women, his
uncommunicativeness, his inordinate pride and sense of privacy, and
his perhaps understandable tendencies toward violence and paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   It makes painful reading. Spender describes those last several
days during which Gorky, in physical pain, distraught about his
marriage and destabilized by pain killers, roamed the streets of
New York, calling up friends and making strange requests that no
one could quite respond to, while Mougouch waited by the phone in
Virginia. But it did seem that a time bomb set years ago in Armenia
had finally gone off.
</P>
<P>
   To a great extent the final explosion casts Spender's own book
in a different light, giving it a meaning and a momentum that it
lacks during the actual reading. It does not obscure the fact that
both the artist and his art deserve a more psychologically and
esthetically perceptive account. But Spender has provided an
essential foundation that is, for all its flaws, also
unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FROM A HIGH PLACE'
</P>
<P>
   A Life of Arshile Gorky
</P>
<P>
   By Matthew Spender.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 417 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $35.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
