<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5820 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ONCE-AGAIN-2TAKES-     07-27 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE-AGAIN-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 40, LETTING GO OF HAPPILY EVER AFTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Divorce has been stamped on the lives of Edward
Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz, the film and television
writer-directors who created the series ``Thirtysomething.''
Herskovitz was divorced in 1993 after a 15-year marriage and two
children. Zwick's parents were divorced when he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother married for the second time, I was 22 or 23,''
recalled Zwick, who has also directed films like ``Glory,''
``Courage Under Fire'' and ``Legends of the Fall.'' ``I used a
quote from Rabbi Nachman of Bratslav in the Talmud as a toast: `It
is said that marriages are made in heaven, but the Lord above is
not always as wise as we would hope Him to be, which is why second
marriages are made on earth.'''
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated Zwick-Herskovitz television series on ABC,
``Once and Again,'' deals, most assuredly, with earthbound issues
involving two divorced parents (played by Sela Ward and Bill
Campbell) who meet and struggle to figure out how to date while
dealing with their respective teen-age children, former spouses and
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The series is one of the few new shows to actually deal with
grown-ups and grown-up issues _ as opposed to the avalanche of new
series involving roommates in New York or teen-agers overflowing
with angst.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has high hopes for the series. It will be introduced for
seven weeks, starting Sept. 21, at 10 p.m. on Tuesdays in the
choice ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' time slot. When the police show returns
for its premiere, ``Once and Again'' will leave the air and return
in January, but at a different time and possibly on a different
night. (Although the shifting time slots are jarring for viewers,
ABC followed a similar plan with ``The Practice,'' which is now a
hit.)
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Tarses, president of ABC Entertainment, said the network's
enthusiasm for the Zwick-Herskovitz series was based on several
factors. ``Given their track record, they have demonstrated a
particular talent to zero in on whatever the climate of the country
is,'' said Ms. Tarses. ``They sort of understand what's in the air
in terms of what people are feeling and thinking and wondering
about. They're really doing a detailed exploration of a complicated
situation that's more commonplace now than it's ever been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tarses said another factor had gone into the network's
decision to proceed with the show. ``It's a genre we haven't seen
before: a slightly older relationship show, people 35 to 40 years
old with children,'' she explained. ``We didn't have anything like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwick, who is 46, and Herskovitz, 47, were seated the other
morning in the sedate Southwest-style offices in Santa Monica of
their production company, Bedford Falls (named after the hometown
of George Bailey, the James Stewart character in Frank Capra's film
``It's a Wonderful Life'').
</P>
<P>
   The two met as students at the American Film Institute in Los
Angeles in the mid-1970s, became television writers after that and
struck gold with ``Thirtysomething,'' which ran on ABC from 1987 to
1991.
</P>
<P>
   That series sharply divided critics, who either adored or
resisted the exploration of marriage, relationships and interior
lives among a self-absorbed and remorselessly serious group of two
couples and three singles. When the show ended, Zwick and
Herskovitz embarked on separate film careers.
</P>
<P>
   They also served as executive producers on two critically
acclaimed if not wildly popular series.
</P>
<P>
   One was ``My So-Called Life'' (1994-95), about a confused,
soulful teen-age girl. The series expired after only 19 episodes,
largely because ABC seemed confused about where to place it. The
show, which stars Claire Danes at the age of 15, was later
resurrected on MTV and has been highly popular in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The other show was ``Relativity'' (1996-97), about a couple
whose chance meeting in Rome leads to a love affair and a
relationship back home in Los Angeles where families collide and
intrude.
</P>
<P>
   Both series had ardent, almost cultish, fans but failed to
generate large audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Are Zwick and Herskovitz then perhaps too idiosyncratic for
television? Are they the darling of television critics and network
executives but not mass audiences? The two men shied away from such
thoughts. Herskovitz said that even ``Thirtysomething'' was never a
ratings hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about the American television watching
population is that they're happy to watch junk and they're happy to
watch good stuff,'' said Herskovitz. ``They'll watch both. And
they'll recognize the good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who will take periodic turns directing the new
series (along with other filmmakers), said their individual
strengths as writers had made the creative marriage work.
Herskovitz said that his partner had ``a remarkable story
structuring ability _ you could drop him anywhere in a story and in
five seconds he would know where it began and how it should end.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwick, on the other hand, said that his partner was unusually
willing to confront deeper and more personal issues on television.
``He was much braver as a writer than I was,'' said Zwick.
</P>
<P>
   In returning to television as a team, the two acknowledged that
while still engaged in movie careers, they have been left
bewildered and frustrated by the business of making feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Especially Herskovitz, whose two films, ``Jack the Bear'' (1992)
and ``Dangerous Beauty'' (1996), fared poorly at the box office.
``You spend at least two years of your life making a movie and
you're creating two hours of entertainment and it's forgotten,''
said Herskovitz. ``Even if it's not the whole story of making
movies, that part of it is unbearable. It's very, very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwick echoed his partner. ``The notion that something may be so
ephemeral as to live or die in a single weekend is frustrating,''
he said. ``Indeed with a television series you can dig into the
culture. You can mouth off on this host of concerns you have. And
the fact that you can penetrate the culture in certain ways can be
very heady.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwick and Herskovitz said that there had, of course, been
classic white-bread sitcoms about couples who bring children into
their marriages like ``The Brady Bunch'' and ``Eight Is Enough.''
But the themes for ``Once and Again,'' which the two began
discussing as far back as the late 1980s, while they were creating
``Thirtysomething,'' are far more sober.
</P>
<P>
   In the new series, Ms. Ward plays a newly single mother who
nervously embarks on a budding relationship with a divorced man
(Campbell) who is as tentative about romance as she is. Both are
consumed with their children: Ms. Ward has two daughters, including
a teen-ager who is overweight and lonely and dismayed, if not
threatened, by her mother's new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has trouble coping with one of his children's learning
problems. Their former spouses add doses of guilt to the mix. The
issues seem peculiarly real, which is uncommon on network
television series.
</P>
<P>
   A single theme seems to dominate the series: the realization
among 40-somethings that relationships, and life, have limits and
possibilities. ``If you've been through a divorce and you've
reached a certain age, you understand the finiteness of life and
you understand that every choice entails making some other
choice,'' said Herskovitz. ``There's no such thing as living
happily ever after. So you must construct for yourself a life that
makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward, a one-time model and an Emmy Award-winning actress for
her role on NBC's ``Sisters,'' said she had vowed not to do another
television series largely because it would take so much time away
from her two small children. ``But then I read the pilot and kept
thinking, `I know this woman; I am this woman,''' she said. ``There
are so few roles like this for women _ a role that's complex and
interesting and vulnerable. When I started making this I felt like
I was flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward identified with the role of Lily, a woman starting over
in a deeply personal way. Ms. Ward, who is 42, has been married for
the last seven years to Howard Sherman, a businessman. Although Ms.
Ward said she had had several earlier long-term relationships that
ended like a series of divorces, it was her experience after
``Sisters'' that led her to identify with the character she plays
in ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got off `Sisters' after six years and was ready to take on
the world,'' she said. ``The first thing that a film director said
to my agent was, `What I really want is Sela Ward 10 years ago.'
This is, like, when I'm 37. I was stunned. You mean I'm no longer
sexually viable? I'm no longer attractive? It was starting all over
again. And it was not unlike Lily at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For the series Zwick and Herskovitz have hired a top-drawer list
of writers, unusual by television standards. These include
playwrights like Michael Weller (``Moonchildren'') and Donald
Margulies (``Collected Stories'') and the screenwriter Pamela Gray
(``A Walk on the Moon''), as well as television writers from
``Thirtysomething'' like Winnie Holzman, who went on to create ``My
So-Called Life,'' and Richard Kramer, who later wrote the first
``Tales of the City'' mini-series and worked as executive producer
on ``Nothing Sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwick and Herskovitz insisted that that the new show was not
autobiographical or personal _ up to a point. ``I haven't been in a
serious relationship with a woman who has children of her own, for
example,'' said Herskovitz, the taller and lankier and slightly
more reticent member of the team. ``But I've certainly faced the
struggle and also the sort of excitement and possibility and
thinking that there is another chance of finding someone after
you've been divorced. That's been a part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zwick said: ``We are ruthless, we are merciless in our
trading on those things that we see and hear and know, but they're
shaped or mutated in some way; they're transmogrified into
something else. Nothing is true in the interest of everything being
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The show itself came about as part of a series deal between the
creators and two networks, ABC and Fox. The deal involves, among
other issues, Zwick and Herskovitz forgoing considerable up-front
fees in exchange for more than 50 percent of later profits, if
there are any. One of the architects of the deal, Lloyd Braun,
co-chairman of the ABC Entertainment Television Group, said signing
on Zwick and Herskovitz was one of his first priorities last year
when he was named chairman of Walt Disney's Buena Vista Television
Productions. Its subsidiary Touchstone Television produced the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatively they're as good as it gets,'' said Braun. He said
he was not especially concerned about the sophistication of the
show. ``It's a somewhat sophisticated show that's going to deal
with real life issues,'' he said. ``The hope is that people will
embrace that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Zwick and Herskovitz seem as close as brothers _ they
defer to each other and apologize if one or the other interrupts a
sentence _ the two try, in some ways, to keep out of each other's
way after work. During the making of ``Thirtysomething'' (and since
then) they tacitly decided to create boundaries in their separate
domestic lives to allow each other more breathing space.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements, they said, are handled with surprising ease.
``It's usually about passion,'' Zwick said. ``In other words,
whoever feels the strongest usually wins.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems to mark the relationship, too, is the ability of both
men to criticize each other's work bluntly. ``The more successful
you are in this business, the fewer people there are who are
willing to tell you the truth about anything _ particularly about
your work,'' said Zwick. ``And to have someone upon whom you count
tell you that it could be better, tell you that you didn't go deep
enough, you didn't go far enough, tell you that you made a misstep
is precious and rare.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the two men, and their writers, are writing and
rewriting scripts that are set to go into production over the next
few weeks. What are the major concerns of the team?
</P>
<P>
   ``We think about the fact that there are a lot of divorced
people in this country and a lot of children of divorce, so we
imagined that there's a constituency out there that might enjoy the
show,'' said Herskovitz. ``Our concerns are more personal than
that. It's like, Will we look like idiots? Will we be foolish? Will
we run out of stories after 10 episodes? Will it be something we're
proud of?''
</P>
<P>
   But Herskovitz said that the actual success or failure of the
show was now out of the hands of the team. ``Whether it's a success
or not,'' he said, ``we feel, somehow, that it's up to the gods in
some way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
