<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-TV-COX     07-27 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What happened to black families on network TV?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crabby junkyard dog Fred Sanford is long gone. So is
``movin'-on-up'' rich guy George Jefferson. Even America's favorite
dad, lovable Dr. Cliff Huxtable, is but a fond memory.
</P>
<P>
   The television landscape has been turning a whiter shade of pale
for several seasons, and come fall, America's real-life diversity
will be reflected more in commercials than in prime-time
entertainment on the four major networks.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP President Kweisi Mfume recently criticized the major
networks for the ``virtual whitewash'' of their new fall
programming, drawing attention to a problem that's been smoldering
for years. Actually three new shows do feature minority characters
in prominent roles, but the spirit of Mfume's charge is clearly
valid.
</P>
<P>
   Although a few existing ensemble dramas feature diverse casts
and one major network sitcom (ABC's ``The Hughleys'') is largely
African American, most series with minority leads are congregated
on so-called ``weblets'' WB and UPN and on niche cable networks
like BET and Univision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be named a niche market is to have your isolation from
mainstream underscored,'' said Timothy Burke, who teaches African
history and popular culture at Swarthmore College in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is this segregation splitting programming, it's
splitting audiences as well. A survey last year by New York ad
agency BBDO found only four crossovers in the Top 15 favorite shows
among black and white households _ ``Monday Night Football,''
``Touched by an Angel,'' ``60 Minutes'' and the ``CBS Sunday
Movie.'' None has a predominantly minority cast.
</P>
<P>
   The top three shows in black households _ the WB's sitcoms ``The
Steve Harvey Show,'' ``The Jamie Foxx Show'' and ``For Your Love''
_ are at the very bottom of preferences among white households.
Black households feel similarly indisposed toward white favorites
``Friends,'' ``Frasier'' and ``Veronica's Closet.''
</P>
<P>
   But is television causing this pop culture split or merely
reflecting the racial divide that already exists?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think television is simply reacting to an aggressive mental
apartheid,'' Burke said. ``It's reflecting culture in that it's
harder and harder for some people to imagine they'd find the lives
of black characters interesting, and that speaks to a hardening of
attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees with that theory. Advertisers and
agencies defend the networks, claiming trends are prompted by
economic goals, not social prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings don't portend any broadening of the racial
divide,'' said Doug Alligood, author of BBDO's survey and senior
vice president for special markets. ``What they do reflect is a
maturing of the television medium in which viewers, particularly
black viewers, have more network programs to choose from than ever
before that are in synch with the style, language and attitudes
that have been called the 'black experience.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sheer numbers on all networks, Alligood is right,
but in terms of programs on the major networks and programs that
will appeal to a crossover audience, television has lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky start in the early '50s with over-the-top sitcoms
like ``Amos and Andy'' and ``Beulah,'' the high point came in the
mid-'70s when ``Sanford &AMP; Son,'' ``Chico and the Man,'' ``The
Jeffersons'' and ``Good Times'' were in the Top 10 programs. And
the No. 1 show at the time, ``All in the Family,'' dealt with
racial themes on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest crossover hit in TV history was ``The Cosby Show,''
which zoomed to No. 1 in 1984 and stayed there for several seasons.
Some segments of the African-American community criticized the show
for not being ``black enough,'' but ``Cosby'' was a huge hit among
all demographics and was lavishly praised by most blacks and
whites.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a ``Cosby''-style hit since. And what bothers
many observers most is why there isn't a mixed-cast sitcom like
``Friends.'' It seems unrealistic to have so many New York-based
comedies with all-white casts, and yet there are probably many
young whites who don't have any black friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hard time sometimes figuring out whether we want
popular culture to reflect our best selves or our realistic
selves,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be even more all-white shows come fall since the
networks are targeting white teen-agers in a big way. They want
teen eyeballs because advertisers want teenagers' present and
future bucks. Not wanting to seem insensitive, the networks concede
they need more diversity, but they don't seem particularly eager to
do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   CBS President Leslie Moonves issued a response to Mfume's
charges, saying he agreed that the entertainment industry should
``make sure the characters on our screen reflect the diversity of
the population as a whole.'' ABC entertainment President Jamie
Tarses had a similar response, adding that her network planned to
introduce a few minority characters on the new shows before they
debut in September.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in response to Mfume's blast, accompanied by the threat
of legal action and a boycott, NBC, home of many white comedies,
recently announced a midseason ``Seinfeld'' spinoff featuring the
Johnny Cochran-inspired lawyer Jackie Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do these people believe minority shows won't succeed?''
asked Curtis Simons, executive vice president of marketing for
cable's Black Entertainment Network. ``African Americans watch more
television than any other segment of the population, but there's no
programming that reflects the culture (of the people) who really
want to watch. The networks have gotten very selfish about where
they are in today's world. They're going to get their advertising
dollars, and they think they'll get African Americans anyway
because they watch so much TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable and the smaller networks have gone after minority viewers,
and that's one reason the bigger networks have lost viewers. The
WB, with lots of African-American programs, is the fastest-growing
commercial network, and Univision, which caters to Spanish-speaking
viewers, is the fastest-growing cable network.
</P>
<P>
   Racial divisions are considerably less pronounced in music and
movies, where minority performers have been embraced by young
whites. For example, black entertainers Chris Rock and Brandi are
wildly popular. Puerto Rican singer Ricky Martin didn't get to be
the phenomenon he is today by appealing only to Latinos, and rap
and hip-hop exploded a few years ago thanks to popularity among
white teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been the trend-setters in entertainment and
sports,'' Simons said. ``But a lot of the TV shows that are pitched
to the networks by minorities aren't even looked at because the
people at the top aren't sensitive to the culture. How many black
executives are at the Big Four? None. The only way to make changes
is at the top, and these guys have too much money to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe we should be concentrating on quality rather than
quantity. Maybe counting faces is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be worried, but our worries should be more
complex,'' Burke said. ``To say we need more black faces on TV
starts the debate on the wrong foot, reducing it to numbers. We
know the networks can rush out a couple of shows to counter the
criticism. It's easy to get a pencil and color in some character's
face, but that doesn't alter the way TV reflects reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are fewer predominantly minority shows on the major
networks, but the ones that are there do a better job of presenting
complex issues of race. NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' was
a master at depicting tough racial situations in raw, realistic
terms. ``ER,'' ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Law &AMP; Order'' also tackle tough
subjects with stark realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quite a few dramas that are complex in the way they
talk about race, and that's progress,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy is a different matter. Young whites, who think nothing of
``affecting blackness as a style statement,'' according to Burke,
are uncomfortable watching a domestic sitcom about black people
``because they'd have to watch black people acting black. In the
world of the WB sitcom, there aren't any white kids acting black.''
</P>
<P>
   Will this racial divide ever end? Hoping to influence the
networks, Mfume last week bought $20,000 worth of stock in the
companies that own the four major networks. That's not much, but it
might give him an insider's voice.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the divide could end in the blink of an eye. All it
takes is one big crossover hit, and then all the networks will
splash rip-offs across their prime-time schedules. Whether they
will deal realistically or fantastically with race relations as
they exist is another matter. If the shows are realistic, like
``Homicide,'' history tells us their crossover appeal is very much
in question.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING SHOWS WITH PROMINENT MINORITY CHARACTERS
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' (Fox): Ally's best friend Renee is African
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' (NBC): Dr. Peter Benton and physician's assistant Jeanie
Boulet are African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys'' (ABC): The principal cast is African American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touched by an Angel'' (CBS): Angel Tess is African American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' (ABC): Boss Isaac Jaffee is African American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City'' (ABC): The mayor's assistant is African American.
And gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order'' (NBC): Briscoe's boss and new partner are
African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nash Bridges'' (CBS): Nash's partner Joe Dominguez is Latino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martial Law'' (CBS): Sammo Law is from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   New shows with prominent minority characters
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch'' (NBC): The main paramedic and the lead rookie
cop are African-Americans; another rookie cop is Latino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snoops'' (ABC): One of the main detectives is African
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield'' (Fox): Ryan's friend and cop colleague is
Latina.
</P>
