<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH AGE, IT'S STILL NOT EASY TO GET OVER HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' I whispered after scanning the large crowd, ``I think
we're the oldest couple here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' my spouse replied confidently. ``I'm sure there are a
lot of people here our age or even older.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are they?'' I asked. I silently directed his gaze to the
stream of fashion-conscious youngsters parading before us. He was
about to respond when a gorgeous waif in a bikini passed by. ``What
woman?'' he actually said with a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, hello? The Tyra Banks look-alike with the skin-tight
shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, she was wearing a shorts set, I suppose, but for
all intents and purposes, it was just a red bikini. Every head,
male and female, within a half-mile turned to watch her progress as
she slithered by on 10-inch heels _ every head but my husband's.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, he did not rotate his head or drop his jaw, but I
swear I saw his right eye burrow backward into his brain and peek
out of his ear canal as she passed. That's quite a trick. When I
have some spare time, I'm going to sign him up for the carnival
side show. Imagine his relief when I commented, ``Did you see that
woman?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't notice, dear, but you're certainly looking lovely
this evening.''
</P>
<P>
   I should have taken a cue from my mother and skipped the
concert, but I just love Lauryn Hill. Even before her platinum
album and all the Grammys, I was a big fan. There was no way she
could perform a concert in Dallas without me being present. I've
listened to her CD so many times that she's almost like my friend,
you know.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, when I bought the tickets, I called my mother all
excited and stuff and I said, ``Mom, guess what? We're going to the
Lauryn Hill concert. The tickets went on sale today, and I got some
great seats.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother has a limited repertoire of contemporary artists, but
Lauryn Hill is so unusual that she transcends generation gaps. That
was my feeling, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she related to Lauren Bacall?'' my mother said. ``I like
Lauren Bacall. I saw her in `Mommie Dearest,' and she was so
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom. I think that was Joan Crawford, or Faye Dunaway playing
Joan Crawford; and no, Lauryn Hill is not related to Lauren Bacall.
Lauryn Hill is African-American and she's a singer, not an
actress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an album by Joan Crawford that I used to play all the
time. Don't you remember? And they could be related. I was reading
an article about Thomas Jefferson and his descendants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama, please! That was Joan Baez on your album. Bacall and
Hill! They don't even have the same last name. I'm sure they're not
related. I just need for you to please, please baby-sit that night
and don't play that album; the boys hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   See, that was a sign. A bad sign. I will not go to any more
concerts unless my mother knows the artist, and then I won't have
to hear opening acts like Outkast. Don't get me wrong. I like
positive rap, and I'm sure they were good rappers. They were
certainly loud enough. I just didn't understand a word they said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, I turned to my husband and yelled, ``I hope
they're not telling these kids to beat up the old couple that's not
singing along! If they are, we're goners for sure!''
</P>
<P>
   I read a review the next day and learned that Outkast actually
did a tribute to civil rights heroine Rosa Parks at some point
during their performance. I have no idea when that happened, but
I'm glad to know about it. Anyway, I couldn't wait for them to
finish so I could hear Lauryn sing.
</P>
<P>
   She was awesome. It was worth all the stares and all the kids
asking if I had the time. I understood every word she said and I
stood on my feet for the whole concert. For a while, I even forgot
that we were the oldest couple there.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened. I was in the restroom washing my hands when a
young lady stared at me and said, ``Are you really wearing
pantyhose? Man, I didn't even know they still made those things.''
</P>
<P>
   I went into a stall, removed the hosiery and stuffed them into
my purse, which was probably the largest purse there, too.
</P>
<P>
   When I joined my husband again, he said, ``What happened to your
panty hose? Did you get a run?''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that grand? I guess that's why the poet Robert Browning
said, ``Grow old along with me! The best is yet to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So we were the old guys in the group. That's OK. We had fun, and
I suffered only minimal hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
