<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     07-27 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LOSES INTEGRAL RANCHING FIGURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Montgomery Harrison Wadsworth ``Montie'' Ritchie died last week,
and Texas' ranching heritage was diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The 88-year-old Ritchie wasn't a household name in most of
Texas, but in the Panhandle, he and his family have been an
integral part of the landscape for more than 100 years. He was
owner and operator of the famed JA Ranch, the Palo Duro ranch near
Amarillo established by Charles Goodnight in 1877.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, like Goodnight, wasn't considered one of the state's
most lovable characters. He was an Englishman, and that set him
apart from the rest of the workaday cowboys. He was a man of some
wealth and that set him apart even more.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ashwell, England, Ritchie was the grandson of JA Ranch
founders John Adair and Cornelia Wadsworth Ritchie Adair.
</P>
<P>
   Adair was an English aristocrat of Scots-Irish descent. He made
his first visit to the United States in 1866 when he established a
brokerage in New York City. A year later, he met and married
Cornelia Wadsworth Ritchie. In 1874, the couple went on a buffalo
hunt in northern Colorado, and although Adair didn't kill a
buffalo, he did manage to shoot his own horse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he loved the new land and moved his brokerage house to
Denver, where he eventually entered into a business agreement with
Goodnight. Adair put up the money to establish the JA Ranch, and
Goodnight took over the management for one-quarter of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Adairs accompanied Goodnight to the new ranch but didn't
stay. Adair was erudite and considered abundantly arrogant. He
didn't sit well with the ranch cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1885, and his wife inherited the ranch. The
relationship with Goodnight ended two years later. Cornelia died in
1921.
</P>
<P>
   James Wadsworth Ritchie, Montie's father, had a shot at running
the ranch, but ran afoul of Goodnight.
</P>
<P>
   James was educated in France and England, and in 1887, he came
to the Palo Duro ranch to learn the ranching business. Goodnight
took him on as a cowhand and trained him, eventually elevating him
to foreman of the ranch's Tule Division.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodnight would not abide gambling on the ranch, and James
was caught wagering. He was quickly demoted. His mother shipped him
off to New York, where he sold JA horses to the New York City
Police Department. He never returned to the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Montie, however, did move to the JA in 1931. He stayed,
directing the ranch's management with his brother, Richard Morgan
Wadsworth ``Dick'' Ritchie, and sister, Gabrielle M. Ritchie
Keiller. Dick Ritchie died in 1941, and Gabrielle became a British
citizen and sold her interest in the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Montie Ritchie took over sole control of the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, he retired as ranch president, turning control
over to his daughter, Ninia Ritchie Bivins. His wife, Hildegard
``Hildy'' Neil, died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie was an avid photographer and art collector. His
collection includes works by Monet, Renoir, Cezanne and Gauguin. He
was a director of the Continental Bank in Fort Worth and an
honorary vice president of the Texas and Southwestern Cattle
Raisers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie played an important part in preserving Texas' ranching
history with several donations to the Ranching Heritage Center in
Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
