<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXENGLISH-COX     07-27 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXENGLISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immigrants offer Alabama tax assessor settlement in English-only
suit
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Ala. _ In multiple languages, ``Welcome!'' flies on
blue banners fluttering from light posts. The local chamber of
commerce promotes international trade. Companies from Greece, South
Korea, Japan and Indonesia have offices in town. The local
populations of Hispanic and Asian residents are among the fastest
growing in Alabama, and it's here that the Marshall Space Flight
Center conducts tests for the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   It's also here that Julio and Carmen de Paula chose to retire
and ultimately found themselves involved in a dispute that began
with their difficulty in speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants from the Dominican Republic, the de Paulas moved from
New York City in 1995 and bought a three-bedroom brick house for
$54,000.
</P>
<P>
   They were welcomed at grocery stores and gas stations. In fact,
they were welcomed everywhere _ except in the office of Madison
County Tax Assessor Wayland Cooley. The 83-year-old official
refused to grant them homestead exemptions because they couldn't
speak English. Without the exemption, the de Paulas pay nearly
triple in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, the de Paulas and Byong-Rye Ahn, an
immigrant from Seoul, South Korea, filed a civil suit against
Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   Their attorney from the Southern Poverty Law Center in
Montgomery on Tuesday sent an out-of-court settlement offer to
Cooley. Attorney Rhonda Brownstein has asked that Cooley allow
non-English speakers the right to use an interpreter, which he has
prohibited in the past. Under the proposal, Cooley cannot withhold
exemptions merely because a property owner cannot speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the de Paulas would receive nearly $1,500 in taxes they
contend they have overpaid while Ahn would get about $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a language-discrimination case,'' Brownstein said.
``Mr. Cooley's intent is to discriminate against foreign-born
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison County Attorney Julian Butler, who is representing
Cooley, has not returned phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Cooley, a Democrat who's served nearly 22
years, claimed he was trying to prevent fraud by residents who
cannot speak English. He also claimed he was immune from damage
claims because he is a public official.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to let the de Paulas and Ahns use interpreters
because he wasn't sure the interpreters were translating
truthfully, court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs and their allies say Cooley is an exception in
Huntsville, whose people have welcomed them to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Mr. Cooley is like the weed in the garden,'' said Rosa
Almanza, a friend who has helped translate for the de Paulas. ``The
city of Huntsville is not the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The de Paulas, who are naturalized citizens, moved to Huntsville
after visiting friends in 1995. Julio de Paula, 71, left his job as
a solderer for Ford Motor Co. His wife, 59, sewed women's underwear
in a Brooklyn factory.
</P>
<P>
   Every dollar mattered since they lived on a fixed income and
were saving for their son to attend college. In 1996, Julio de
Paula applied for a property tax break given to the elderly. The
Spanish-speaking de Paula took his son, Ricardo, to the county tax
assessor's office to translate.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of completing the application, a clerk summoned
Cooley, who told the de Paulas they didn't qualify for the
exemption because they didn't speak English. In interviews and
affidavits, the de Paulas recalled Cooley said an immigration
officer instructed him to revoke all their property tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Through an interpreter, Julio de Paula recalled in an interview
that Cooley told him, ``I make the law here. You don't speak
English, you're not going to get anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said de Paula: ``When he treated me like that, I felt like
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case mentioned in court papers, Mary Catherine
Graham, a financial analyst for the FBI, accompanied a Mexican
native who had purchased a home in Madison County last year. With a
real estate agent, Graham tried to show Cooley a copy of an opinion
by Alabama attorney general Bill Pryor that said an amendment to
the state constitution declaring English the state's official
language did not restrict non-English speakers from claiming
homestead exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that he had to watch out for people who were trying to
come in from all over the world and skin us on taxes,'' Graham said
during a February deposition.
</P>
<P>
   According to Graham, Cooley screamed during the office
encounter, ``If you'd had as many ancestors die fighting for this
country, then you'd understand why it makes me so mad when people
come in here from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A display of U.S. military service medals sits outside Cooley's
courthouse suite.
</P>
<P>
   The de Paulas and Ahns are part of a growing minority population
of Hispanics and Asians in the South. While Alabama added 6.9
percent more residents (278,765 people) from 1990 to 1997,
according to the U.S. Census Bureau, the Hispanic population grew
60 percent (14,675) and the Asian population grew 27 percent
(5,830).
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Madison County had an estimated 5,038 Hispanics
and an estimated 5,717 Asians _ the most in both categories in
Alabama. In seven years, the county's Hispanic population grew 60
percent, and the Asian population grew 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dramatic increases, residents from those population
categories represent only about four of every 100 people in Madison
County, which has more than 270,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Madison County remained an Old South cotton belt town through
the 1950s. But after World War II, an Alabama legislator invited in
German scientists who brought with them rocket technology that
helped develop a new industry for the area.
</P>
<P>
   The remade economy has boosted the county's per capita income to
one of the state's highest. But the prosperity hadn't reached Ahn
in such proportions that she could afford to pay the $3,000 in new
taxes she said Cooley threatened her with because her English was
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Through an interpreter from a Korean church, Ahn, 64, a
housekeeper at Huntsville Hospital, said Cooley's face turned red
when she visited him in 1997. Her husband died eight years earlier
and she failed to claim the homestead exemption in her name.
Brownstein said the exemptions are good for either spouse but the
death of Mr. Ahn put Cooley in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley exclaimed, ``What?! That's your problem,'' Ahn recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Ahn said she started crying in the office and offered her
housekeeping services to Cooley as partial payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crying is your problem, too,'' Ahn recalled Cooley saying.
``If you don't speak English, why did you move to America?''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
