<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEF-WANNABES-ART-2TA     07-27 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEF-WANNABES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG HOURS, NO PAY: ONLY CHEF WANNABES NEED APPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Michael Zinner, whose day job is running the
surgery department at Harvard Medical School, stood in the kitchen
of Le Bernardin dressed in chef's whites instead of surgeon's
greens and tried to get used to the fact that 22-year-olds thought
it was perfectly all right to yell at him. For cutting the
mushrooms wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling I had when I was an intern and couldn't draw
blood right,'' said Zinner, 54, the surgeon in chief at Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston. ``I didn't know exactly what I was
supposed to do because I hadn't had enough experience.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone who confessed to a ``romantic notion of having a
restaurant,'' working in one for six 12-hour days without pay
turned out to be a lot harder, and more humbling, than he had ever
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Zinner is among a small group of chef wannabes turning up in the
world's most celestial kitchens. Some, like him, are signing up for
a new program and paying thousands of dollars for the privilege.
Others just talk their way into working long, hot days as a galley
slave in a stress-filled and windowless kitchen in return for the
chance to absorb the knowledge and mysterious skills of a star
chef, and maybe even bask in reflected glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think these guys are some kind of deity,'' said Wayne
Kimbell, a New York stockbroker who has also worked with Eric
Ripert, the executive chef at Le Bernardin. ``My friends think it's
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have worked free in top kitchens are a
disaffected Japanese housewife, a bored Microsoft executive, a
retired Wall Street broker and a dentist. Some are contemplating
midlife career changes. Others simply want to impress their dinner
guests. All are willing indentured servants pursuing culinary
excellence. Or something. After all, they can quit anytime their
feet hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the George Plimpton complex,'' said Christine Patton, the
retired broker. ``You like to have another life for a week and then
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other amateurs in the kitchen, Zinner never went to
cooking school. ``To me, like many guys my age, grilling was
indistinguishable from cooking,'' he said. He did not have to beg,
plead and wield connections to get through the swinging doors at Le
Bernardin. He paid $2,450 to L'Ecole des Chefs when the program
expanded to the United States from Paris this year.
</P>
<P>
   Participants spend five and a half or six days in one of the
country's best-known kitchens, like Jean Georges, Daniel, Payard
Patisserie and Bistro in New York, Citronelle in Washington or Le
Bec-Fin in Philadelphia. Along with all the abuse they can take,
they get two staff meals a day and one half-price dinner in the
dining room, wine not included.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch service, when Zinner was told to assist the chef de
cuisine on the line, he looked worried. ``He's suffering,'' Ripert
said with a sympathetic laugh. ``He looks tense.'' And he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to screw anything up, but it's still too new to
do it quickly,'' the surgeon said during a lull. He filled a little
notebook with tips and recipes and stayed an extra day because a
Saudi prince canceled surgery. ``Seeing it makes all the difference
in the world, because you couldn't get it just out of reading a
book,'' Zinner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he realized he was here to work, it actually was a
help,'' said Andrea Glick, a line cook and chef's assistant. ``I
would spend 10 minutes showing him something that would take me
half an hour to do. During service, it would be a little hairy, but
he's a very smart man, and he knew how to step out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Patton, who quickly tired of the lady of leisure role
after retiring from Wall Street, an interest in food became an
obsession, however short lived. ``Whenever I'm bored, I learn
something,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She spent six months at the French Culinary Institute in
Manhattan and was an apt enough student to be hired as an
instructor. But she still was not satisfied and sought the
validation of a restaurant kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two days at Daniel, I never went back to the French
Culinary Institute,'' she said. In the kitchen she had discovered
the adrenaline rush she missed from the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Patton, in her mid-50s, has a new calling: golf. ``I
am a golf fanatic, going to golf school four days a week,'' she
said. ``Think how much healthier it is out on a golf course,
instead of in windowless rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Satomi Inoue prefers a windowless kitchen to sitting at home in
front of a television. She is in the United States with her
husband, a Japanese businessman, and her visa does not permit her
to earn money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is a traditional Japanese man,'' she said. ``He is
happy if I stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Inoue, 31, is not a traditional wife. Though she makes
her husband's lunch before she leaves for work and has his dinner
on the table when he gets home, she also works full time at Payard.
Without pay.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two years in France, she became interested in
food and put in three months at Peter Kump's Cooking School, then
did a six-week internship at Payard, where she combined cooking
with perfecting her French and English. She has been working in the
bistro almost a year. When she returns from vacation in September,
she will go back to the pastry kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not for my husband,'' she said. ``This is for my
future. I want to teach or translate or write cookbooks when I go
back to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bert Goldfinger, 47, a New York dentist, is equally serious
about life after inlays. He began cooking as a young boy, earned a
living as a camp cook and took a day job as a dentist but never
gave up his first love. He graduated from the French Culinary
Institute _ first in his class, he is proud to say _ and spent nine
months at Aureole in the pastry department, devoting as much time
as he could spare from his practice. Unpaid, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Now each week, he spends two evenings and all day Saturday in
the pastry kitchen at Le Cirque 2000, still unpaid. ``Somewhere
down the line, my wife and I are going to open a small restaurant
near Hudson, N.Y,'' he said, as he helped to box candies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do during the day is noble, but people don't look
forward to it,'' he said. ``When I cook a meal, people look forward
to it. Dentistry is much like pastry. It's artistic, creative and
very scientific. But dentistry is physical, very exacting,
stressful, emotionally draining, and this is relaxing, compared to
that. This is much more fun than dentistry, I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will argue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Myhrvold, who became a millionaire many times over as
chief technology officer of Microsoft, has never had a desire to
open a restaurant, but he can reel off the names of his good
friends who are chefs: Gray Kuntz, Christian Delouvrier, Daniel
Boulud, David Bouley.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold is a self-taught cook who was responsible for
Thanksgiving dinner from age 9, but La Varenne in Paris would not
accept him until he had done a short apprenticeship, so he started
working at Rover's, a restaurant in Seattle. A couple of months
grew into a two-year commitment. He worked one day a week from noon
to 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``In small doses, it was interesting and invigorating,'' he
said. ``I've raced Formula One cars, sky diving, bungee jumping.
There's an intensity in cooking that does match that _ well, maybe
not sky diving _ and doing it well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Myhrvold, who has left Microsoft to pursue his first love,
scientific research, rates himself as just OK as a chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is better off with me patronizing great restaurants
than trying to cook in them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE CRAB SALAD WITH ENGLISH PEAS, CUCUMBER, MINT AND MACHE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Payard Patisserie or Bistro &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the coulis:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   \ cup peeled diced potato
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   { pound (about 2 cups) shelled English (green) peas
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces Maine crab meat, all bits of cartilage removed; other
fresh crab meat may be substituted
</P>
<P>
   { cucumber, peeled, seeded and cut into \-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely diced fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup shelled English (green) peas, blanched in salted water
</P>
<P>
   Lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 cups mache.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare coulis: In a medium saucepan over low heat, warm
olive oil and add onion. Cover and cook until tender, about 5
minutes. Add potato, garlic, thyme and chicken stock. Raise heat to
high, and bring to a boil. Add \ cup of peas, and salt to taste.
Simmer for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour mixture through a strainer over a bowl, and discard
solids. Return liquid to pan, and place over medium heat. Add
remaining uncooked peas, and simmer until peas are tender. Using a
blender, puree mixture until smooth. Pour through a fine strainer
into a bowl placed over ice cubes. Whisk quickly until chilled.
Refrigerate until needed.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare salad: In a mixing bowl, combine crab meat,
cucumber and mint. Reserve about 1{ tablespoons of the blanched
peas for garnish, and add rest to crab meat mixture. Add lime juice
and olive oil to taste. Season with salt and pepper. In another
mixing bowl, combine mache with additional lime juice and olive oil
to taste. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve: place crab in a ring in center of each of four
serving plates. Put a serving of mache in center of ring. Adjust
seasonings of chilled coulis with salt and a few drops of lime
juice to taste. Pour coulis around crab, and garnish with reserved
peas.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP DUMPLINGS IN CURRY-COCONUT BROTH WITH SHIITAKE MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Le Bernardin
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the curry-coconut broth: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thinly sliced garlic
</P>
<P>
   \ cup thinly sliced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   \ cup coconut milk (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   For the dumplings:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely minced scallions
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   24 large shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Flour
</P>
<P>
   24 egg-roll wrappers, cut to 4{-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, cut into 24 pieces
</P>
<P>
   For the garnish:
</P>
<P>
   4 shiitake mushrooms, stems removed, julienned and lightly
sauteed in oil, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon toasted curry powder, optional
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 tablespoons lime juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. Make broth: Melt butter in a small saute pan and slowly cook
garlic and shallots over low heat until they soften but do not
brown. Add chicken stock and simmer for 10 minutes. Add lemongrass,
1 tablespoon cilantro, coconut milk and curry powder, and simmer
for 5 minutes. Pass through a fine strainer. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make dumplings: In a small bowl combine scallions, ginger and
3 tablespoons cilantro, and mix well. Season shrimp with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lightly flour a work surface and place the cut egg-roll
wrappers on it. On each wrapper, place a shrimp near the bottom
third, a piece of butter and { teaspoon of scallion mixture.
Moisten two edges of the wrapper and fold the wrapper over to form
a triangle, pressing down edges to seal. Refrigerate on plastic
wrap and cover with plastic wrap until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, bring a large pot of water to boil and gently boil
dumplings for 4 minutes, turning once. Meanwhile, reheat
curry-coconut broth.
</P>
<P>
   5. Drain and place three dumplings in each of eight bowls. If
using shiitakes, place a few slices on top of each dumpling. If
desired, sprinkle each plate with toasted curry powder. Sprinkle
each dish with lime juice and cilantro. Then pour 2 tablespoons of
broth over dumplings and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Use a brand of coconut milk that contains coconut and
water only.
</P>
</TEXT>
