<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PUSH TO PROTECT PERSONAL PRIVACY ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Trade Commissioner Sheila F. Anthony warned
Congress Tuesday that new laws are needed to protect the privacy of
Internet users from companies that employ new technologies to
gather and sell their personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony told a panel of the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee that some companies have made a business
of collecting personal information online and selling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered just how much information these companies can
gather on you when I checked into what one of these `information
brokers' had on me and my husband,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She found that the company had acquired the couple's names,
address, house value, Social Security numbers and the years in
which they were issued, mothers' maiden names, and addresses where
they lived before coming to Washington, D.C. The company also had
collected the names of the couple's two daughters, the names of the
daughters' husbands, all four of their Social Security numbers,
every address they had lived and the name of her 3-year-old
grandchild and the child's Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony did not name the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least, I was shocked and more than a little
disturbed by a company being able to gather that kind of
information on me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``information brokers'' are able to cobble together complete
profiles on individuals by buying bits and pieces of personal
information from many different companies and compiling them into
one databank.
</P>
<P>
   Since many Web sites that sell products also ask customers to
fill out forms that include name, address, Social Security number,
credit card number and other personal information, privacy experts
fear that some or all of that information could be sold to
information brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the computer accessing a Web site leaves an
electronic signature that can identify the incoming computer and
record what the computer user does while at the Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony said that she favors legislation that would require each
Web site to inform visitors of what information is being collected
on them and how it will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., who has proposed such legislation,
said firms should not be able to sell people's personal information
without their permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know what's being done with their information
so they can know who to trust and who not to trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the views of Anthony and Burns were not shared by three
other FTC commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think more needs to be done, I believe the Internet
industry has done a good job at self-regulation,'' Robert Pitofsky,
FTC chairman, told the senators.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a recent survey by Georgetown University that
found that almost two-thirds of the World Wide Web's busiest sites
post their policies regarding use of the personal data.
</P>
<P>
   A similar survey last year by the FTC, which enforces federal
competition and anti-fraud laws, found that less than 10 percent of
sites disclosed how personal information was gathered and used.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC survey also reported that more than nine out of 10 of
the Web's top 100 sites, which account for around 90 percent of
traffic on the Internet, have some privacy statements;
three-quarters of those give computer users some choice about how
their information is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online firms deserve considerable credit for making progress
over the last year,'' Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   But Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, a Washington-based advocacy group, told the
panel that the Georgetown survey also showed that only 10 percent
of sites met standards agreed on by the FTC and the Internet
industry for giving consumers adequate privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Those standards include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Telling computer users how information is collected;
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving them a choice on how it is used;
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving people access to their files;
</P>
<P>
   _ Describing the company's security system;
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing a contact person.
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg said the incomplete nature of the privacy disclosures
cited in the survey is evidence that legislation is needed to
guarantee that Web sites use information appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the time for self-regulation is running out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns' bill joins more than a dozen others introduced this
session that contain some provision for protecting personal
information that is transmitted electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The measures address online privacy, policies requiring
businesses to post privacy notices, privacy of medical records,
privacy of encrypted messages and privacy of Social Security
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
