<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-27 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH OF A BAD THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel law died a richly deserved
death four weeks ago with the approval of President Clinton's
nemesis Kenneth Starr, who has conceded that he is winding down his
own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Only the pending August trial of former Associate Attorney
General Webster Hubbell remains on Starr's public agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But the nasty consequences of the law are still with us in the
continuing independent counsel probes of two present and two former
Clinton Cabinet officers.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-year probe that cost taxpayers more than $19
million, former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy was acquitted last
year of charges that he received gifts from companies regulated by
his department. Appeals of lower court decisions by peripheral
figures, however, keep the case alive, and Independent Counsel
Donald Smaltz has yet to release his final report.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman is being investigated for possible
influence-peddling and soliciting illegal campaign contributions.
Independent Counsel Ralph Lancaster Jr. began his probe little more
than a year ago, and thus far it has cost the taxpayers only
$264,000, a relative bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt is being probed for possibly
lying to Congress about political favoritism in the rejection of a
casino proposal from three Indian tribes. This too has been in the
works only since last year, but Independent Counsel Carol Bruce has
run up a cost of $1.4 million. Neither Herman nor Babbitt has been
indicted, and both remain in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the most outrageous example of overreaching on the part of
investigators spending public funds and exercising unchecked power
is the unhappy saga of former Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Henry Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1995 Attorney General Janet Reno concluded that
evidence Cisneros had lied to the FBI about support payments to a
former lover justified the appointment of an independent counsel to
look into criminal charges. Four and a half years and $7 million
taxpayer dollars later, Cisneros is scheduled to come to trial in
September on 18 felony counts of conspiracy, obstructing justice
and making false statements to the federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel David Barrett accuses Cisneros of concealing
the amount and frequency of payments he made to the former
mistress, Linda Jones, in order to win confirmation to the Cabinet
post. The affair itself was already public knowledge and he had
reconciled with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros left the Cabinet voluntarily at the end of Clinton's
first term still enjoying the president's support, at least in
public. Cisneros is now president of Univision, a Spanish-language
television network based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The case has mostly rumbled along out of the public eye. But on
Monday a federal judge ruled that the jury in Cisneros' pending
trial could hear 26 of 88 disputed tapes secretly recorded by Jones
of their conversations during the 1990-1993 period when he was
making payments to her. She has admitted to editing some of the
tapes to eliminate segments unflattering to her.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers fought admission of the tapes. If convicted
on all counts, Cisneros, who has pleaded innocent, faces 90 years
in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he is guilty or innocent, things should never have
come to this. Nor should the probe have taken so long. Cisneros has
already paid a psychological and financial penalty far out of
proportion to the alleged wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to cover up the consequences of infidelity is not
behavior to be condoned in presidents, Cabinet members or anyone
else. But neither is it a crime deserving of the full legal wrath
of the federal government and the threat of a lifetime jail
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett claims Cisneros lied about the payments to Jones because
they were hush money to buy her silence and protect his HUD
nomination. If that is so, Cisneros foolishly laid his neck on the
line for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the leaders of the Senate Banking Committee, which
passed on Cisneros' Cabinet nomination, were not inclined to view
the real scope and frequency of his payments as fatal to his
political career. Both former Sen. Donald Riegle Jr., a Democrat
who was then committee chairman, and former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a
Republican who was then ranking minority member, have said that had
they known the truth, they would have approved Cisneros for the
post anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There is about the Cisneros case, as about the impeachment trial
of President Clinton, a sense of official vindictiveness that goes
beyond earnest enforcement of the law. It's not just Starr that's
guilty. Repeatedly, other independent counsels have demonstrated
that their absolute power drives them to dangerous extremes to
punish their targets and prove their own self-righteous
superiority.
</P>
<P>
   Do Americans really think justice demands that Cisneros go to
the pokey if he lied to the FBI? He sold no state secrets. He
pocketed no federal funds. He cheated no one except his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Where no big name and no big federal money is involved,
prosecutors don't waste their time on such minor infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wanted to make an example of Clinton because, he said,
even a ``little white lie'' is illegal. However technically true
that may be, it defies common sense and human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett seems similarly bent on twisting an apparent lapse of
ethics into a legal monstrosity. We hope Cisneros' trial is brief
and fair and the jury is more realistic about what's appropriate
than his pursuers have been.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
