<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-NYT     07-27 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS' DISTASTE FOR CLINTON AND U.N. SANDBAGS HOLBROOKE
NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Neb., Okla., N.C., Va.)   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's decision to
take a ``second look'' at the nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be
the chief U.S. diplomat to the United Nations appears to have less
to do with Holbrooke's qualifications than with the Senate's low
esteem for both the United Nations and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination has been in limbo for well over a year, stalled
initially by ethical questions about Holbrooke's business dealings
as an investment banker. But now Lott and other senators are
holding the nomination hostage in exchange for various demands on
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate that has developed reflects the anger and distrust
between the Republican-controlled Congress and President Clinton
the year after his impeachment. It also underscores the
unpopularity of the United Nations, both in Congress and among the
public, and the fact that there is little price to pay for turning
down an official whom many senators consider arrogant and whose
job, unlike that of secretary of state, is largely unknown to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Lott ordered his aides last week to conduct yet another review,
even though the Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved
Holbrook in June without dissent after four exhaustive hearings.
But the ``second look'' at Holbrooke by the senator's staff, Senate
Republican aides said, had less to do with the nominee's fitness
for the job than with saving face for Republicans who are stalling
a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lott had placed a ``hold'' on the nomination, in a show
of loyalty to Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has sought the
appointment of a conservative to the Federal Election Commission
whom the White House and many congressional Democrats oppose. The
Republicans were attempting an old-fashioned horse trade: Holbrooke
would be confirmed if Bradley Smith, an Ohio law professor, was
appointed to the FEC by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only leverage we have with the administration is the power
to confirm,'' McConnell said in an interview. He said the White
House was trying to usurp a long tradition that permitted
Republicans and Democrats to each pick members of the commission.
But he said that discussions continue with the White House to break
the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prolonged delay of a Cabinet-level appointee is rare,
particularly when the reasons are largely unrelated to the nominee
himself. The Senate's historian, Richard Baker, said in an
interview that he could not recall a case like Holbrooke's in the
past quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented in the way they've beaten this around,''
said G. Calvin Mackenzie, a professor of government at Colby
College. ``The appointment process has become an opportunity for a
Senate controlled by one party to get leverage on a president of
another party.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lott and McConnell, two other senators also have
holds on the nomination. Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, wants to
protect a woman he thinks was a whistle-blower at the U.S. mission
at the United Nations. And Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, is wary
of Holbrooke's role in the administration's Balkan policymaking.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet appointees have, of course, been defeated. The Senate
rejected President George Bush's nomination of former Sen. John
Tower, R-Texas, to be defense secretary in 1989. Since 1801,
however, only 18 Cabinet-level nominations have been rejected or
not confirmed for other reasons, according to the Senate Historical
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lott says Holbrooke will be confirmed eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate rules, any lawmaker can delay a final vote on
legislation or a nomination indefinitely, usually to force an
administration to accept something, or someone, it would not
otherwise approve. But Senators typically exercise this prerogative
on middle-level appointments, like ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a Senate tradition of holding presidential
nominations hostage for other ends, but what's unique is this one
is at the level of the U.N. ambassador,'' said Marshall Wittmann,
director of congressional relations for the conservative Heritage
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Cabinet-level nominees are created equal. When Sen.
James Inhofe, R-Okla., threatened in June to block all presidential
nominations, including that of Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers to be Treasury secretary, the world financial markets
briefly quaked. Senate leaders and Clinton quickly worked out a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In this Senate, Washington's envoy to the United Nations does
not command that respect, many scholars said. The Cabinet-level
status for the U.S. delegate to the United Nations has been
conferred by Clinton, but it is not automatic, as with other
Cabinet posts. The United States has been without a permanent
representative to the United Nations since last September, when
Bill Richardson left the position to become secretary of energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocking the nominee to the U.N. is a good way for Senate
Republicans to frustrate the Clinton administration without drawing
a great backlash,'' said John Pitney, a political science professor
at Claremont McKenna College. ``Plus, a vast number of Americans
have no idea who Richard Holbrooke is.''
</P>
<P>
   His nomination was held up most of the last year as a result of
federal ethics investigations that ended without any criminal
charges. The Foreign Relations Committee approved Holbrooke only
after the administration agreed to endorse reductions in the U.S.
assessments to the United Nations, championed by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., the committee's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the panel's approval, however, the four Senate
Republicans moved to block a final vote by the full Senate. Lott's
commitment to his cause came under scrutiny two weeks ago when Tim
Russert, the host of NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' asked the senator
about Smith. Looking surprised, Lott replied, ``Bradley Smith? Now,
let's see. That sounds familiar. Who is Bradley Smith?''
</P>
<P>
   Only after a little coaching from Russert did Lott recall the
connection. The senator's spokesman, John Czwartacki, who refused
to confirm that Lott had put a hold on the nomination, dismissed
the exchange over Smith and the review of Holbrooke's record as ``a
tempest in a teapot.''
</P>
<P>
   The delays have angered Senate Democrats, and now even some
influential Republicans are growing weary of the stalling. Sen.
John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee, and
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., a member of the Foreign Relations
Committee, have demanded a quick vote on Holbrooke to fill an
important U.S. foreign policy job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holbrooke issue is a clear example of how bipartisan
foreign policy and national security have frayed to the point where
no cloth is left,'' Hagel said in an interview. ``This kind of
conspiratorial, back room nonsense is holding Holbrooke hostage.
America's interests in the world are being held captive by a small
partisan band.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
