<SLUG> BC-ENTREPRENEUR-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEURS FINDING IT HARD TO GET FUNDS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the United States, by far the world's most
entrepreneurial nation, has an annual $60 billion available in
private equity for new start-up businesses, entrepreneurs have a
tough time getting to it, a study on US entrepreneurship concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Entrepreneurship Monitor 1999 National Assessment, a
joint study by Babson College and the Kauffman Center for
Entrepreneurial Leadership, is scheduled for release at a meeting
of the Congressional Economic Leadership Institute in Washington
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Each year Americans create approximately 600,000 to 800,000 new
businesses with employees, a birthrate of 14 to 16 start-ups of
every exisiting company, according to the report. About another two
million self-employment ventures are formed without employees.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, ``As many as 8.4 out of every 100 US
adults _ 16 million Americans in all _ are currently trying to
start a business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong entrepreneurial culture in the United
States,'' said Andrew Zacharakis, entreprenuership assistant
professor at Babson College and the lead Global Entrepreneurship
Monitor researcher. ``You're not a failure if you tried and did not
succeed. You're a failure if you have never tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The report states that it is more difficult to obtain equity
seed than debt capital. Of the available $60 billion, which may
account for 71 percent of the world's available capital, $56
billion comes from family and friends, and only $4 billion comes
from venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   The research was conducted during the last two years to analyze
the relationship between entrepreneurship and economic growth in
the United States and nine other countries, including the other G7
nations and Denmark, Finland, and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of entrepreneurship experts, who were interviewed
for the study, said that entrepreneurs don't even know about the
many federal, state, and local government assistance programs that
are available because of poor marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 to 3 percent of small businesses receive government
assistance from the Small Business Administration loan guarantee
program, most of which are not even start-ups, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the entrepreneurs out there to get the available
equity so they will start creating new jobs,'' Zacharakis said.
``The idea is to help entrepreneurship in these countries and
develop policies that would either help or hinder entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage more US entrepreneural activity, the study
sugggests an increase in entrepreneural education, more simple
government tax regulations, a clearinghouse to detail government
programs, and greater federal analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASEAN-NKOREA-NYT &LR;      07-27 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASEAN-NKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA WARNED AGAINST TESTING MISSILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and her
counterparts from South Korea and Japan appealed to the isolated
Communist government of North Korea on Tuesday to accept engagement
with the world rather than to risk ``serious negative
consequences'' with a long-range missile test.
</P>
<P>
   The warning, in a joint statement here, is part of a full-blown
diplomatic effort to keep North Korea from going ahead with the
anticipated test. It was the latest in a series of admonitions from
American officials, including Secretary of Defense William S.
Cohen, who is visiting Japan and South Korea this week in a
specific effort to discourage North Korea from going ahead with the
test.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of another such test by North Korea, after a
surprise test last August, has dominated the annual meeting of the
Association of South East Asian Nations here.
</P>
<P>
   It has added to the sense that security concerns have replaced
economic matters as the top focus of the region. As the countries
that were battered by financial crisis two years ago begin to
recover, attention has turned to new tensions between China and
Taiwan and to the threat of North Korea's missile and nuclear
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The prime concern of the United States is that another test by
North Korea could set off a chain of potentially destabilizing
actions around the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence data has pointed to steady preparations by
North Korea for a second launch. The missile that the regime
apparently intends to test is a Taepodong-2, which has an estimated
range of up to 3,750 miles, making it capable theoretically of
reaching Alaska or Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The new rocket is described by officials as an advanced version
of the Taepodong-1, which North Korea fired over Japan and into the
Pacific Ocean in August.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese foreign minister, Masahiko Koumura, said at a news
conference here Tuesday that if North Korea went ahead with its
test, the Japanese government probably would withdraw the $1
billion it recently allocated for the Korean Energy Development
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should there be another test launch by North Korea, in view of
the Japanese people's sentiment, it will be extremely difficult for
Japan to continue its cooperation'' with the development
organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This development consortium, which is also backed by the United
States, has agreed to build two light water reactors in North Korea
in return for the regime ending its nuclear program. The United
States gives North Korea 500,000 tons of fuel oil a year as part of
an effort to create an alternative to nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
   But a break-up of the consortium could induce North Korea to
resume construction of nuclear reactors that produce plutonium for
nuclear weapons, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is also worried that another launch
by North Korea would encourage South Korea to move ahead with
several missile projects of its own, further fueling an arms race
on the Korean Peninsula. South Korea recently proposed building a
generation of medium-range missiles that could strike much of North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean foreign minister, Hong Soon-Young, addressed
this concern Tuesday, saying that, ``The whole purpose of missile
development on the part of South Korea is to reinforce the
deterrence against North Korean act of adventurism.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong added that his government was ready to abide by the
``spirit'' of the Missile Technology Control Regime, an
international agreement that obligates signers to restrict the
range of their missiles.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The test last year, which the North Koreans insisted was for a
satellite launch, set off such concern in Japan that the government
decided to make an initial investment in the U.S. theater missile
defense program. Another launch by North Korea would almost
certainly increase Japan's interest in the proposed system _ thus
irritating China, which views Japanese participation in missile
defense as aimed at the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
   In their three-way appearance this morning, Ms. Albright and the
two foreign ministers tried, without being very specific, to stress
the positive incentives for North Korea not to test.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright said the policy of the South Korean president, Kim
Dae Jung for engagement with North Korea, its longtime enemy, and a
program to be announced by former defense secretary, William J.
Perry, President Clinton's special envoy for North Korean affairs,
give North Korea a ``good chance to strengthen its economic and
political ties with the world.``
</P>
<P>
   Perry said last month that a second test by North Korea would
jeopardize a gradual effort by the administration to normalize
relations with that nation and to lift economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Perry visited North Korea in May to present his comprehensive
package for improving relations. While officials said he was
received politely, the regime told him it retained its right to
test a second missile. Several weeks after Perry left, North Korea
provoked a naval clash with South Korea in disputed waters in the
Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is under pressure from Congress on
its policy toward North Korea, in part because the United States is
sending the oil and also food aid to North Korea, which has
suffered from drought in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Some administration officials have acknowledged in recent weeks
that they are in a quandary over how to deal with North Korea. So
far, the food and fuel have not curbed the missile development or
the export of missile technology to countries such as Iran, Syria
and Pakistan, they said.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that, although the closed nature of the regime
makes it hard to know its intentions, it was possible that the
signs of preparation for a missile launch were being made as a
tactic to win more favors from the United States and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan D. Pollack, a senior adviser at the Rand Corp., said
that the efforts of the administration to forge a stern common
policy with South Korea and Japan may not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North Koreans may believe they can dodge the bullet one
more time,'' he said. ``In the past, every time they have done
something to defy the United States or South Korea _ including last
year's test _ we tried to funnel more money to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
