<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-SOUTH-COX     07-27 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping cool tricky in heat-saturated South
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Here's a trick to beat the heat: Roll in the mud
and use your ears as an air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the elephants were keeping cool Tuesday at Riddle's
Elephant Breeding Farm and Wildlife Sanctuary in central Arkansas.
They roll in the mud to keep the bugs off and prevent sunburn, but
their secret weapon is their ears.
</P>
<P>
   ''The elephants cool off by slapping their ears,'' said Heidi
Riddle, who, with her husband Scott, runs a sort of retirement home
for elephants. ''It doesn't create a breeze, but the skin on the
inside of their ears is very thin, and there is a large network of
blood vessels there. Flapping their ears pumps cooled blood through
the body. It's like a giant air conditioner.''
</P>
<P>
   The South could use a giant air-conditioner. Although the heat
wave has been more dangerous in the Midwest and the Northeast,
where 31 people have died, two people have died in North Carolina
because of the heat. No relief is in sight for the next several
days, forecasters say.
</P>
<P>
   And temperatures around the South have been plenty
uncomfortable. It has been in the 90s from the beaches of North
Carolina to the Mississippi Delta. Temperatures have hovered around
100 degrees in Little Rock since last week, and it was 102 degrees
Tuesday at the Riddles' place in Greenbrier, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't roll around in the mud, but maybe we should,'' Riddle
said. ''We just drink lots of water. And I try not to look at the
thermometer after it goes above 90.''
</P>
<P>
   You can tell Southerners it was hotter and drier last summer,
and you can tell them it's always steamy in July, but it just
doesn't make it feel any cooler when a heat wave rolls in.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, temperatures rose to the mid-90s across much of the
state, leaving tourists and residents sweating but not complaining
of any unusual heat. Many recalled June 1998 when the mercury
soared above 100 degrees and the Sunshine State was scorched by a
record-setting drought and dangerous wild fires.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not unseasonably warm,'' said Robb Chase, 35, a bartender
at Key West Taco in Cocoa Beach, an open-air establishment where
patrons swigged cold beer as they sweated under ceiling fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's July,'' said Hank Meinhart, who owns a local bar. ''It's
supposed to be hot.''
</P>
<P>
   But tourists Donald and Cathy Ferguson found the heat stifling.
Mrs. Ferguson glowed a bright red after only an hour on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hotter than hell,'' said David Ferguson, who recently
moved from Florida to the North Carolina mountains near Asheville.
''It never used to be this hot in the summer. The weather has gone
crazy. And we must be crazy coming in a taco place and eating hot
food.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flat, treeless expanse of the Mississippi Delta,
non-irrigated farms are suffering from too little rain in recent
weeks. Soybeans planted for early harvest may not make it if the
rain doesn't come soon, farmers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It rains here for a little while and it doesn't rain over
there,'' said Bill Pearson, a retired farmer from Sumner. He farms
250 acres of soybeans ''as a hobby'' and he says they are starting
to wilt.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not as bad as last year, he added, when it was hotter
and it didn't rain at all. Crops and livestock across the Southeast
were devastated last summer by record temperatures and a relentless
drought.
</P>
<P>
   But still, Pearson, 77, finds it too uncomfortable to go
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm reading a lot,'' he said. ''I wonder what we did before
air conditioning? I was just a boy then and I don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   On Avery Island off the coast of Louisiana, Paul McIlhenny,
president of Tabasco Brand Products, says the peppers used in his
hot sauce are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hotter than the hinges of Hades on the island but the
peppers love it,'' he said. McIlhenny doesn't love it quite as much
as his peppers do, but he fights fire with fire by dousing all his
meals with Tabasco.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we fry our eggs on the sidewalk here, we always add a
couple of drops of Tabasco,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So why do people in hot climates eat spicy foods, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm told it makes you sweat more, and perspiration makes you
feel cooler,'' McIlhenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Mike Williams contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
