<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODERN-BOOKS-COLLECTI     07-27 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-BOOKS-COLLECTING-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD REASON TO HOLD ON TO THAT EARLY STEPHEN KING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass.)   (af)  
 Christa Worthington writes about arts, antiques and design.  
 By CHRISTA WORTHINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Browsing at a book fair one day, Chris Offutt, the author of
``Out of the Woods,'' a collection of short stories, discovered the
value of his library of contemporary fiction. ``I'd pick something
up and it was marked $100,'' he recalled. ``And I said, `Hey, I
have that, only my copy is signed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now he treats his books with a new respect. ``I figure they can
help put my kids through college. Writing won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the early '90s, prices for first editions of modern
literary works have hit the stratosphere: $35,000 for a signed copy
of Jack Kerouac's ``On the Road''; $250,000 for a copy of
``Ulysses'' signed by James Joyce for Ezra Pound, and $15,000 for
Harper Lee's ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   The gold rush in such literary ``high points'' _ the industry
term for well-known titles by name authors _ has also fostered
speculation in recently published books: first editions printed
within the last five years that are still in pristine condition and
preferably signed by the author. The challenge of so-called
hypermodern collecting is to spot future best sellers while they
are still in small first-print runs and in stores.
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, you had bought a first edition of ``Angela's
Ashes,'' Frank McCourt's 1996 memoir of growing up poor in Ireland,
you would own a book that sells on the Internet for $500. The Civil
War novel ``Cold Mountain,'' by Charles Frazier, has a similar
asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Both books became blockbusters after small first print runs. If
the major motion picture of the book is a hit, the first edition
will be worth much more. If not, the book's trading price could
suffer, as happened in the case of Tom Wolfe's ``Bonfire of the
Vanities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speculation is a '90s thing,'' said Francis Wahlgren of
Christie's, where books published as recently as the 1980s have
generated interest, including sought-after first editions by
Stephen King and Ian Fleming, the creator of James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with the film influence,'' Wahlgren
added. ``It's created a market for certain authors.'' He said
``Merchant Ivory type films'' had had an impact on books by Thomas
Hardy and Jane Austen. A copy of ``Pride and Prejudice,'' he said,
would go for a ``very strong price.''
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated hypermodernists don't read the books they intend to
collect. They read reading copies. They keep books for their
collections bound in Mylar covers, turning the spines inward away
from sunlight. Preserving the books in mint condition is often what
makes them rare.
</P>
<P>
   An author's signature increases the value greatly, especially
that of writers who avoid book signings like Don DeLillo, John
Irving and Cormac McCarthy. Dust jackets are essential, without
which the value of any book published after 1920 drops
precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypermodern collecting has been around in some form forever,''
said David Brown, the publisher of Bookline, a newsletter published
in San Rafael, Calif., that offers tips on the investment value of
books. ``The phenomenon of having these books jump in price quickly
is what's new.''
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary books start at about $35 a copy and some postwar
books can go up to $2,000. Mysteries, the genre that started the
trend, see the biggest jump in price early on; literary fiction is
slower to rise in value but worth more in the long run. Hypermodern
collectors also seek out science fiction and Western regional
fiction, along with memoirs and literary nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of the hypermodern phenomenon, bookselling has
become more like the art and stock markets. Today's buyers often
come from Wall Street and the entertainment industry, and many are
interested in the same 50 or so big-money titles _ the books that
were most likely on the baby boomers' high school reading lists.
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders say that William H. Gates, chairman of the
Microsoft Corp., is a collector of the books of J.D. Salinger and
F. Scott Fitzgerald and is thought to have been behind some of the
big-ticket auction sales in which the buyers are not always
identified publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting is less esoteric and quirky than it used to be,''
said Ken Lopez, who sells postwar fiction in Hadley, Mass. ``A lot
of the people who are collecting now have started fairly recently.
They'll collect the Pulitzer Prize winners or National Book Award
winners, or extremely notable high spots that are no-brainers.
Everybody wants a `Catcher in the Rye' or a `Catch-22.' It's a
little more like collecting trophies.''
</P>
<P>
   How did modern books come to seem so rare? The change is partly
because of a 1978 tax law that made it difficult for publishers to
keep books in stock for more than a year, making first editions
harder to find. A first edition with a remainder stamp is less
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Though hypermodernism can be seen as a pop phenomenon, it
reflects an American tradition of book collecting in which popular
taste, not the judgments of experts, directs the market. (European
booksellers are mystified by this trend and don't take modern
fiction as seriously.)
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the Web and at book fairs has further eroded dealers'
authority. But even if collecting is more profit-driven, the
literary value of books is not lost on today's collectors. As
Wahlgren put it: ``Good authors sell. That's the one truth that's
been proven with time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
