<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-TALKS-NYT     07-27 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA AND U.S. PLAN HIGHER-LEVEL TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China and the United States held trade talks here
Tuesday and agreed to higher-level discussions later this year, a
new sign of slowly thawing relations. But they remained frozen on
the most important issue _ China's proposed entry to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   David Aaron, the deputy commerce secretary, met with Shi
Guangsheng, the Chinese foreign trade minister, and two other
senior Chinese officials to discuss a number of commercial issues.
Yet the Chinese officials only talked about trade organization
membership indirectly, Aaron said, and they showed no willingness
to establish a timetable for new negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're still waiting,'' Aaron said. ``The decision
remains to be theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials have said they are still determined to enter
the trade organization, the 134-nation group that makes the rules
of global commerce, by the end of the year. Entry would require
approval of the United States and other big influential members of
the group.
</P>
<P>
   Yet China and the United States have been unable to recover the
ground lost in April when President Clinton rejected a proposed
deal, with significant concessions, offered by Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji during a visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Widely criticized for missing the opportunity, President Clinton
later reversed himself and expressed a willingness to close a deal
quickly. But before it could be secured, NATO bombed the Chinese
Embassy in Yugoslavia on May 7 and seriously angered Beijing. Talks
on trade organization membership, human rights and security issues
were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing and Washington still cannot agree on how the United
States should compensate China for the three Chinese journalists
who were killed in the attack, which NATO has called unintentional.
Chinese officials have been unwilling to reopen trade organization
negotiations until the compensation issue is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said he found it encouraging that Chinese officials
invited him to China at all. In addition, he said, Chinese
officials told him repeatedly that Beijing wanted to strengthen its
relationship with Washington. They also refrained from lecturing
him about U.S. faults, as Chinese officials often do when ties at
their worst.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that he and Shi agreed to lead a meeting of a joint
commercial forum later this year in Beijing with U.S. Commerce
Secretary William Daley. An exact date was not set.
</P>
<P>
   The forum, called the Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade,
will include working groups to meet on information technology,
aviation, environmental technology and other areas, Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said he thought it still possible that an agreement could
be reached on trade organization membership this year. Other
officials have said that reaching a deal this year will only be
possible if endorsed by Presidents Clinton and China's President
Jiang Zemin when they meet in New Zealand in September at the Asia
Pacific Economic Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
