<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CABLE-COX     07-27 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buying spree over, Cox to emphasize qualityBy Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since April, Cox Communications has spent $10.15
billion in cash and stock to buy cable TV systems nationwide _
including a $2.7 billion play announced Tuesday _ but the company
still ranks number five in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with this Atlanta-based cable TV operator, which has
stressed quality over size. Now the company is wrapping up its
buying binge and returning to a focus on execution.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the recent focus on acquisitions wasn't
important. The company had to get much bigger to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But what Cox Communications bought was not so much bulk as
market share in key regions. No cable TV operator dominates more
lucrative big city markets than Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   It owns such markets as New England, Northern Virginia, Southern
California, Phoenix, Ariz. and now Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically, Cox Communications remains a strong second tier
player _ despite all their spending,'' says Bruce Leichtman, a
media analyst at industry consultant the Yankee Group. ``But in
terms of cable TV plant, market share and quality of service, Cox
Communications is second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   In its latest deal, announced Tuesday, Cox Communications will
pay $2.7 billion in cash to buy cable operator Multimedia
Cablevision, owned by media giant Gannett Co.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia Cablevision serves 522,000 subscribers in Kansas,
Oklahoma and North Carolina. In Oklahoma, for example, Cox
Communications will now have 490,000 subscribers, a commanding
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is paying the equivalent of $4,500 a
subscriber for Gannett's properties, among the higher prices paid
for cable systems. It's a price more than double what systems
fetched two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While expensive, the purchase has been structured in a way to
give Cox Communications $350 million in tax benefits, say company
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications says the deal is well worth the price. It
will push the company beyond the 6 million mark in terms of
subscribers, making it approximately fifth in size among operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that 6 million customers is a formidable size in
today's environment,'' says Cox Communications Chief Executive and
President Jim Robbins. ``Our recent acquisitions provide us the
size and scale that will enable us to remain a significant player
in the broadband communications industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal caps a four-month period in which Cox
Communications, through acquisition, has added 2 million
subscribers, growing its base by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, for example, Cox announced it would trade
$2.8 billion in AT&AMP;T stock for systems in the south-central part of
the country. The systems are now owned by that long distance
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   These systems, will add 495,000 subscribers in Louisiana,
Oklahoma, Texas and Arkansas, fill in a cluster of cable TV systems
Cox Communications has been building in this region.
</P>
<P>
   And in May Cox Communications agreed to pay $4 billion in cash
and stock to buy TCA Cable TV, based in Tyler, Texas. TCA has
883,000 customers in systems in small to mid-sized towns across
Texas, Louisiana and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   These deals leave Cox Communications' systems clustered in four
regions, New England, the Southwest, Virginia and the South-Central
states.
</P>
<P>
   That footprint isn't as extensive as that of industry leader
AT&AMP;T, which will have some 17 million cable TV subscribers when it
closes its purchase of MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox Communications' holdings are in markets with not only
lots of high income families but those interested in digital
services.
</P>
<P>
   Examples include its systems in New England and in San Diego and
Orange County, California. These are areas with some of the highest
usage of computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems are critical to Cox Communications' strategy. The
company has positioned itself as a leader in providing digital
services such as high-speed access to the Internet, vast new
channel offerings, digital television and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as delivering all three of these services at the same
time, Cox Communications is the leader,'' says Leichtman. ``And
they are neck and neck with MediaOne in providing telephone
service.''
</P>
<P>
   As of June, for example, Cox Communications had 59,793 telephone
customers across its systems. There were 112,006 Internet
subscribers as of the same date.
</P>
<P>
   While these numbers represent only a small portion of Cox
Communications' subscribers, they are heading up every quarter. And
that's good news for Cox Communications, which has invested heavily
in a digital future.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent heavily in the past five years to turn its
systems into digital networks. And that, in turn, has required the
company to expand in order to justify the high cost of
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable operators need a critical mass of subscribers to deliver
digital services,'' says Leichtman. ``It helps in both deploying
the services and marketing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gannett purchase dovetails with Cox Communications'
strategy. Nearly 90 percent of its systems in Oklahoma and North
Carolina are digital, which will expedite Cox Communications'
ability to offer Internet access and telephone service to these
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gannett's cable properties are a natural fit with our growth
strategy of adding large, technologically advanced properties in
stand-alone markets and in markets contiguous to our existing
operations,'' says Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Gannett marks a strategic shift at Cox
Communications. ``This is it,'' says Robbins about whether the
company plans other acquisitions. The reason is twofold.
</P>
<P>
   First, there aren't many good independent systems left for sale.
``Two years ago, the purchase of Gannett wouldn't have been a big
deal,'' says Leichtman. ``That it is (now) shows how few good
systems are left.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Cox Communications has reached critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox Communications is pretty set now,'' says Spencer Grimes, a
media analyst with New York investment bank Solomon Smith Barney.
He says that 6 million is a good size for Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins agrees. He says the focus of his company now will be
``execution, execution, execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins says the company's challenge is rolling out digital
services without affecting the company's quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   Robbin's acquisition campaign has also increased his company's
size and importance within controlling shareholder Cox Enterprises
Inc., which also owns the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, a privately-held diversified media company, owns 73.3
percent of Cox Communications. Last year, according to the latest
figures, Cox Communications represented slightly less than a third
of its parent's $5.4 billion in revenue, outstripping both the
newspaper and broadcast divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Cox does not release sales figures for any of its private
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
