<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0728-C     07-27 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUMMIT FAILS TO PRODUCE PROGRESS IN WYE PEACE PROCESS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ They kept up the honeymoon atmosphere, but new
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in a meeting with Palestinian
Authority President Yasser Arafat Tuesday maintained a freeze on
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1/2 hour meeting at the Erez Crossing Point between
Israel and the Gaza Strip, Barak asked Arafat for more time before
resuming land transfers planned in the Wye River Memorandum. Arafat
agreed to consider the request for two weeks, while aides try to
find middle ground between Barak's plea and Arafat's insistence
that Wye be resumed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli land handovers planned in Wye are already more than
five months late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must seek the precise and accurate implementation of
agreements signed on the basis of reciprocity,'' Arafat said in a
joint news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was elected in May promising to restart the peace process
that had been halted by predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu. Now, he
appears to be having some of the same hesitations about
implementing the Wye accords -- that it could leave Israelis
vulnerable to terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to merge the Wye land transfers into negotiations
over remaining major issues in the peace process. But unlike
Netanyahu, he is seeking Palestinian approval and has stayed on
cordial terms with the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like again to emphasize that we are committed to Wye.
We will implement Wye,'' Barak said. ``Any change in the agreement
will be made only by the consent of both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   By asking for consent, Barak maintains his image as the team
player. But he also keeps the process frozen in the meantime -- a
condition that cannot be peacefully maintained for long.
</P>
<P>
   Tension in the region has risen steadily following the high
expectations after Barak's election victory. This was the third
time the two have met but the first two meetings were largely
ceremonial, including one at Sunday's funeral of Morocco's King
Hassan II. Pressure is building for some substantive results.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly restless Palestinians have waited as Barak has
traveled to the United States, Great Britain, Egypt and Jordan to
discuss the peace process. He goes to Russia next week, a trip sure
to be a political success with the 1 million Russian immigrants in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A militant Palestinian group opposed to peace with Israel
recently announced that it would renew efforts to commit terror
attacks and Israel's Chief of Staff, Shaul Mofaz, reported Tuesday
that small terror attempts were increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show most Palestinians do not trust Barak and many are
growing impatient with Arafat, who led them into the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two leaders cannot afford a failure,'' said Palestinian
political analyst Ghassan Khatib. ``Arafat is desperate for some
progress and he cannot say that this (Israeli) government that we
have waited for is not giving anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Signed at the White House in October, the Wye River Memorandum
laid out a three-month timetable for the transfer of 13 percent of
land in the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, it would give the Palestinians control of 40
percent of the West Bank, which Israel captured from Jordan in
1967. Although Israel has not made the West Bank formally part of
the country, about 180,000 Jewish settlers have been scattered amid
the 1.5 million Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye plan was actually a refinement of the Oslo peace
process, signed in 1993. Then-Prime Minister Netanyahu, who had
early on opposed Oslo, froze the process claiming that the
Palestinians were not doing enough to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has been seeking ways to restructure the Wye deal and meld
it into the so-called ``permanent status'' discussions of the
toughest issues at stake. These include the control of Jerusalem
and whether 3.5 million Palestinian refugees can return to land in
Israel they lost in wars.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians oppose delaying Wye because it lets Israel hold
land as a bargaining chip in the permanent status talks. Israelis
are hesitant to cede land unless they are confident the permanent
status issues can be resolved and end Palestinian resistance to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak fears that Wye will leave several Jewish settlements
isolated and vulnerable to Arab attacks. He also opposes the deep
involvement of the U.S. CIA, which is called upon in Wye to monitor
Palestinian compliance with the plan. U.S. officials during the
Netanyahu era rarely criticized Palestinian compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the land transfers planned in Wye, Israel is supposed
to allow the Palestinians to construct a long-delayed port, which
would create thousands of jobs, and let Palestinians have ``safe
passage'' routes through Israel to their enclaves in the Gaza Strip
and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
