<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-DANGEROUS-SCHOO     07-27 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DANGEROUS-SCHOOL-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARDS MAY PROMPT LOS ANGELES TO SCUTTLE NEW
SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It looms on a lonely lot at the edge of downtown,
a hulking pile of buff brick and brown stone, like some
half-finished temple or Pharaoh's tomb. If would be the most
expensive public high school ever built in the United States, at a
cost of more than $200 million, but the Belmont Learning Center may
never be finished _ and if it is, no one may want to go to school
there.
</P>
<P>
   The school was built atop an abandoned oil field, despite
repeated warnings, and officials now say there may be no way to
vent away seeping methane gas and other hazards to make the
building safe to occupy. Last week, the Los Angeles Board of
Education, with four newly elected members, voted to create a
commission to recommend whether to abandon the project, after $125
million has already been spent on it, or to spend millions more to
make it work.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont story is a classic Los Angeles tale of sunny civic
boosterism and noir real estate speculation. It is also a tale of
the ever-present environmental hazards in a city that a century ago
was a sparsely populated outpost dotted with oil wells and bean
fields and is now a metropolis built astride constantly shifting
earthquake faults. As the drama has dragged on for more than a
decade, the problem that Belmont was meant to address _ severe
overcrowding in schools in the city's downtown neighborhoods _ has
remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to go away,'' said state Sen. Tom Hayden of Los
Angeles, one of the Belmont project's most persistent critics,
noting what he sees as a no-win situation. ``If they abandon it,
it's going to be the subject of screenplays and East Coast
merriment for years. And if they open it, they're going to face
endless litigation by parents who think it's going to one day be
the site of a methane fire or explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort began more than a decade ago with a plan to build a
high school on the site of the old Ambassador Hotel, the once-grand
hostlery where Sen. Robert F. Kennedy was assassinated in June 1968
after winning California's Democratic presidential primary. The
school district condemned the property, but its owner, the New York
developer Donald Trump, who wanted to build a skyscraper on the
site, threatened a legal challenge over the price. In the real
estate recession of the early 1990s, the Board of Education dropped
that location in favor of one of the last remaining open parcels of
land near downtown, a former oilfield at First Street and Beaudry
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the plan envisioned what school officials
said would be the most expensive high school in the country, a
5,300-student complex comprising eight ``academies,'' plus a
housing and retail development that would be built in an unusual
partnership with a private developer, Kajima Urban Development. But
the retail and housing elements have long since been dropped, in
part because retail tenants were not interested in the somewhat
isolated site, a gritty hillside near the intersection of two
freeways.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1993, officials of the state Division of Oil and Gas
warned Los Angeles school officials about the dangers of building
over an abandoned oil field, but the school district and the
developer forged ahead, taking soil samples that district officials
and outside critics now say were clearly inadequate. The outside
legal counsel for the Board of Education, David Cartwright of the
city's leading law firm, O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, helped negotiate with
the developer, Kajima, and assured the board that it was safe to go
forward without a full environmental study. It was later disclosed
that his firm also represented the developer, a subsidiary of a
giant Japanese construction company.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright has defended his actions as proper, but last winter
the school board relieved him of duties on the Belmont project,
although he continues as counsel on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Construction began two years ago, with just two dissenting votes
on the seven-member school board. But before the groundbreaking,
Assemblyman Scott Wildman, who represents the nearby communities of
Glendale and Burbank and heads the Joint Legislative Audit
Committee, which has oversight of public entities like school
districts, had begun raising questions about contracting and safety
issues for the project. He urged the district to hold off.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Wildman has made public nine reports that are
critical of the plan, and environmental consultants hired by the
district have found dangerous concentrations of methane as well as
hydrogen sulfide, a toxic gas with the sickening smell of rotten
eggs that can cause neurological damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the district's own experts have suggested that the
entire first floor of the building should be off-limits to
children, to protect them from any buildup of dangerous gases. Even
if a system could be devised to vent the dangerous gases, reports
have suggested, it would cost perhaps $100,000 a year to operate it
for the life of the school. And an earthquake fault running under
the property could leave the mechanical systems subject to sudden
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the project should be abandoned and torn down,''
Wildman said in a recent interview. ``There shouldn't be children
who go there and there shouldn't be people who work there. They
made a mistake. We tried to stop them before they started, but they
went ahead anyway. Frankly, they should have made the decision two
years ago.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But a range of local officials, including Mayor Richard J.
Riordan, had supported the project, and it was not until last fall,
when the state Department of Toxic Substance Control concluded that
the site had never been adequately assessed, that momentum grew for
re-evaluation. After commissioning new tests, the district
suspended most construction in February.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatives would be expensive, including building several
smaller high schools in the area at a cost of perhaps $75 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   A new, four-member majority was elected to the school board this
spring on a promise to take a hard look at the Belmont project.
They had been expected to call a permanent halt to the scheme,
perhaps last week. Instead, after a daylong closed session and a
spirited public hearing last Tuesday, the board voted to secure the
site by installing doors, windows and roofing to protect it from
the elements, but postponed a definitive decision on its future.
The board appointed a citizens' commission that will make
recommendations by mid-October, and imposed a gag order on its
members and the district staff, barring any comment on the project
in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with this project is there hasn't been a
great deal of planning ahead,'' said one of the new board members,
Caprice Young.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the environmental controversy, several parents testified
at the hearing in support of finishing the school, saying the
neighborhood badly needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concerns are not being heard and we are more overcrowded
than ever,'' said Tina Hough, a 35-year resident of the
neighborhood who had been bused to far-flung neighborhoods to go to
school. ``Am I to put my children through the same thing I went
through.?''
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Shambra, a now retired school official who had overseen
the Belmont project as the district's director of planning and
development, also testified. He dismissed the environmental
concerns as ``unsubstantiated allegations,'' and told board
members: ``You are now surrounded by an environmental hysteria
created by the district's own consultants.'' He said the problems
could be remedied and that conclusions that the site is beyond
repair are exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   But Wildman said it was too late to make the project work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one thing after another,'' he said. ``We keep
finding more problems. Bureaucrats need to have permission to cut
their losses and stop throwing good money after bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
