r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CHICAGOHOPE-SFCHRO     07-27 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHICAGOHOPE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHICAGO HOPE' RETURNING AFTER MAJOR SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ They didn't line up the ``Chicago Hope''
actors and shoot them at the end of last season, perhaps because it
would have been a shame to waste perfectly good ammo on actors.
</P>
<P>
   But the result was about the same.
</P>
<P>
   In a startling season finale, Mandy Patinkin returned to the CBS
medical drama as Dr. Jeffrey Geiger and bluntly fired most of the
doctors at the fictional Chicago hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, most of the cast. The victims were Christine
Lahti, Vondie Curtis-Hall, Peter Berg, Jayne Brook, Stacy Edwards
and Eric Stoltz.
</P>
<P>
   The cast members learned their fates just about as abruptly as
their characters did. One studio insider told me this week that
Lahti, an Emmy winner for ``Chicago Hope,'' was so upset by the
massacre that she initially balked at playing her climactic scene
with Patinkin.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, ``Chicago Hope'' will return for a sixth season with
a different focus, a rejiggered cast and, it seems, some unresolved
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   During a press event in Pasadena to promote the show, CBS spread
11 producers and cast members across a stage. Anyone in the room
could sense about four different climatic zones in the 30 feet or
so from Patinkin on one end to Hector Elizondo on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone up there, it seemed, was terrifically fond of
everyone else. That shouldn't be surprising, really; it's true
among most job entourages. But seldom so palpable.
</P>
<P>
   The returnees besides Elizondo are Rocky Carroll, Mark Harmon
and Adam Arkin. Patinkin, who left ``Chicago Hope'' after its first
season, is back for an undetermined number of episodes. It will
probably be plenty; maybe nine or 10 out of the season's first
dozen, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   That group is joined by newcomers Lauren Holly as a plastic
surgeon, Barbara Hershey as a thoracic surgeon who seems destined
to butt heads with Patinkin's Geiger, and Carla Gugino as a
neurosurgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The show's prolific creator, David E. Kelley _ he also produces
``Ally McBeal,'' the half-hour ``Ally'' spin-off, ``The Practice''
and a new ABC series, ``Snoops'' _ said he's written the new
season's first episode and will keep closer tabs on ``Chicago
Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said the purge was more or less a matter of having to
destroy the show in order to save it.
</P>
<P>
   ```Chicago Hope' was in trouble in terms of getting renewed,''
he said. ``Along with that, Mandy had expressed an interest in
coming back. We met with CBS and pretty much agreed that in order
for `Chicago Hope' to come back, it would really have to be reborn.
Sweeping changes would have to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   One change is a shift in dramatic direction. CBS, according to
the 20th Century Fox Television source, ordered the show to shift
emphasis a few seasons ago from the hospital to the character's
personal lives. A mistake. This fall, the hospital will re-emerge
and the practice of medicine will be in vogue again.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the delicate matter of sorting out the cast.
Kelley said he started as any humane manager would, with natural
attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Berg was developing his own pilot, and so he figured not
to be around,'' Kelley said. ``And Christine Lahti's directing
career was heating up, and there was a good chance she wouldn't
want to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said Brook was cut because her role was closely tied to
Berg's. Curtis-Hall's character ``seemed to be evolving into one
that was getting frustrated with medicine.'' Not anymore. Gone.
Stoltz had a one-year deal to appear on the show. Also gone.
Edwards was ``pretty arbitrary for me'' because ``I didn't really
have a strong sense of that character.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahti wasn't a favorite among all her colleagues, but the
wholesale slaughter has tested the professional mettle of Elizondo,
Harmon, Carroll and Arkin. Arkin seemed readiest to speak, however
cautiously, for the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy we're still here,'' he said. ``I don't think David
was kidding when he said the future of the show probably hung in
the balance. ... There was some press I received in which I talked
about how hard it was to see people we'd worked with for such a
long time have to be surprised with their own departures.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkin went on to say that it was ``wonderful we have a future''
but added, ``I'd be lying if I said it wasn't a hard way to end the
season. It was traumatic in its own way. But I guess, on some
level, it had to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While the additions give ``Chicago Hope'' one of TV's most
impressive casts, the show has hardly recovered from its radical
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   It's moving, again, this time from Wednesdays to Thursdays. Want
to watch ``Chicago Hope''? It'll be on at 9 p.m., against NBC's
``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Prognosis? One more year, but a good one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
