<HEADER>
A5879 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES28-COX     07-27 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC Notebook: Fumble still haunts Arkansas' Stoerner
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ Perhaps the most talked about play in the
Southeastern Conference last year was Arkansas quarterback Clint
Stoerner's fumble with 1:43 remaining and the Razorbacks holding a
24-21 lead on Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols, of course, came back to score the winning touchdown
with 28 seconds left and went on to take the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Stoerner was forced to relive the infamous incident
during the first day of the three-day annual SEC Football Kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get mad at you for asking me that question, because
I've asked myself the same question a hundred times,'' he said.
``It has been hard to swallow, but it's something that comes with
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he be able to put it behind him? ``Can I get it out of my
mind? Not a chance,'' Stoerner said. ``I'll never forget it, and
even if I could, you guys wouldn't let me.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior said he received about 180 E-mails after the game,
and all but two were positive. ``These two guys were dog-cussing me
for fumbling the ball, but most of the others were very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick, very sick,'' Arkansas coach Houston Nutt said
about the fumble. ``I felt like the game was won, and it's a very
sick feeling. The bad thing was we woke up about 110,000 people.
That crowd was very quiet until the fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Late starters
</P>
<P>
   Georgia head coach Jim Donnan explained the Bulldogs' loss to
Florida this way: ``We thought the game started at 4:30 (p.m.), but
it started at 4, and it was 21-0 fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan on how the game has changed since he played quarterback
for N.C. State: ``Well, they're wearing face masks now.''
</P>
<P>
   And on his Bulldogs' record over the past few years: ``There are
only eight teams in the country who've won more games than we did
in the last two years, but unfortunately, two of those are teams
we've got to beat (Florida and Tennessee), and they've won a whole
lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   On why some schools don't play more top-level out-of-conference
games: ``It's hard to play what we call 11 Ben Hurs in a season,
every game being an epic.''
</P>
<P>
   Changeovers aplenty
</P>
<P>
   Gerry DiNardo, LSU head coach, says money is the main reason for
the turnover in head coaches around the country. ``I know we're
adding seats, and we'll have 91,600 by the year 2000. That means
there will be another 10,000 coaches and coordinators at each
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning point
</P>
<P>
   LSU defensive tackle Johnny Mitchell didn't hesitate to point to
the start of the Tigers' downward spiral last season. LSU had been
picked to win the SEC Western Division but finished 4-7. ``The
Georgia game in the fourth quarter was the turning point of the
season,'' Mitchell said. LSU was 3-0 and ranked No. 6 in the
country when the Bulldogs beat them 28-27. ``We never seemed to be
able to come back from that,'' Mitchell said. ``We lost a lot of
games in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick kicks
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference football championship game, which
will be played in The Georgia Dome the first weekend in December,
sold out on June 11. . . . The difference in the SEC Football
Kickoff and the ACC Football Kickoff, held last week, can be
measured in numbers. Some 125 media representatives attended the
ACC meetings. The SEC get-together drew more than 650 media
requests. . . . DiNardo is the first coach to last at least five
seasons at LSU since Charlie McClendon, who left in 1979. . . .
Donnan's picks for who's going to be good this season in college
football: Arizona, Florida State and Penn State. . . . And finally,
Georgia's Orantes Grant on whether the Bulldogs are closing the
talent gap on Tennessee and Florida: ``I don't think we've ever
been behind them. It was more a couple of bad breaks, a couple of
bad games, a lack of focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
