<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-COSTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COST AND CORRUPTION PREVENTS NEW CONSTRUCTION, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Texas)  (nk) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A study commissioned by New York City has found that
the cost of residential construction in the five boroughs is the
highest in the country, with pervasive corruption, outdated
regulations and excessive labor and material costs continuing to
make it prohibitively expensive to build new homes.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that it costs an average of $183,000 to build
one apartment in a typical six-story building in New York City.
That is 22 percent higher than Dallas, 10 percent more than Chicago
and 4 percent higher than Los Angeles, where added costs to reduce
earthquake damage narrow the gap.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, residential construction in New York City has
failed to keep pace with demand, the report says, pointing out that
although building permits for 52,000 new units were issued between
1980 and 1996, the city's population grew by 120,000 households
during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shortfall contributes to low vacancy rates, skyrocketing
rents and incredible rent-to-income burdens,'' said one of the
report's authors, Michael Schill, the director of the Center for
Real Estate and Urban Policy at the New York University School of
Law. ``We found that rents in New York are the highest in the
nation, and that one out of four renter households pays more than
half its income for rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor is by far the largest contributor to the higher costs. The
report said the base hourly wage and fringe-benefit rate for
bricklayers in the city is $46.64, 35 percent more than Chicago, 42
percent more than Los Angeles and 155 percent more than Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   While the cost of living has long kept wages high in New York,
labor costs are also inflated, the report says, because of
featherbedding and inefficient work rules, like the requirements
that plumbers install toilet paper holders and electricians install
mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The report was commissioned by the city's Department of Housing
Preservation and Development and the New York City Partnership and
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's major recommendations are a ``broad
redrafting'' of the city's 38-year-old zoning code, which it calls
``arcane and byzantine''; replacement of the building code with a
model code written by a national engineering association to reflect
current construction technology; and elimination of environmental
reviews for new buildings, those with 90 apartments or less, and
those with 150 apartments of affordable housing for the poor.
Currently, all buildings with three or more apartments require an
environmental review.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that ``contrary to allegations of some
members of the real estate industry, rent regulation is unlikely''
to contribute to higher building costs, except when a developer
seeks to demolish an old building. In that situation, the report
calls for the rewriting of the rent law to allow for the removal of
holdout tenants, with fair compensation, if the new building will
have 20 percent more floor space than the demolished one.
</P>
<P>
   In conducting the study, the authors retained architects to draw
up specifications for a town house, a six-story apartment house and
a 15-story luxury building. Then they compared construction-cost
estimates for New York with those in Chicago, Los Angeles and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Schill called the cost gaps ``extremely conservative, because
they factor out the far higher costs of land and soft costs,'' like
professional fees in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Along with wage rates and inefficient union rules, the report
cites corruption as a significant contributor to high labor costs
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extortion, bid-rigging, bribery and other illegal practices
are pervasive in the construction industry,'' it says. ``These
illegal practices often take place because organized crime has
infiltrated labor unions and construction companies.''
</P>
<P>
   While federal officials have been cracking down on corruption in
some of the city's largest building unions, the report says that
more needs to be done. It recommends that the city create a
commission to investigate and license all construction managers to
weed out those connected to organized crime, something Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has already proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommends that builders and labor unions
``negotiate a lower wage rate for construction outside the central
core of Manhattan,'' and that wages ``reflect the complexity of
construction, and vary depending upon whether the development is
low-, mid- or high-rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Malloy, president of the city's Building and
Construction Trades Council, questioned the cost estimates in the
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing good-sized projects in the Bronx and have
negotiated agreements on these projects that brought the price down
to a number that the construction manager and the developer found
competitive,'' he said. ``I do not believe that there's that big a
disparity in the wage package between New York, Chicago and Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the report's conclusions regarding featherbedding
and corruption, Malloy said: ``If you told me that 10 years ago, I
would probably agree with you. But in today's market, all the
agreements have been changed to reflect the competitive market, and
most of the so-called featherbedding clauses have been
eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The report says that a major reason why material costs in New
York are excessive is that the city's building code is
``stringent'' and ``cumbersome.'' The report cites as one example
that plastic pipe can be used only in one- and two-family buildings
in New York, while other cities allow it in larger buildings.
</P>
<P>
   And the report says the city's zoning regulations ``can only be
described as arcane and byzantine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only experts can wade through the multiple levels of
regulation that may affect a single piece of property,'' it says.
``This discourages new developers from entering the market and
expanding the capacity of the city to produce housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Salama, who wrote the report with Schill and another
professor, Martha Stark, said that to meet housing needs the city
must convert more manufacturing areas to residential use, something
that zoning rules inhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we recommend,'' Salama said, ``is that the mayor and the
city council create a task force to undertake a broad redraft of
the zoning resolution with the driving vision being to make it
easier and more cost-effective to build housing.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner of Housing Preservation and Development,
Richard T. Roberts, called the study ``a very good document,'' and
said, ``It really reaches the mark in terms of outlining specific
steps that can be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to consult with the mayor, the City Council and
policymakers in Albany,'' Roberts said, ``and see how many of these
recommendations we can put into effect in the next couple of
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
