<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY PROMOTES CAMPAIGN ISSUES IN WHIRLWIND DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton capitalized on
her White House role Tuesday to showcase support for women, the
poor and Jewish voters _ all potentially important constituencies
in her possible Senate campaign from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady staged four public appearances across the
nation's capital in barely 10 hours, setting the stage for
resumption of her summer-long, campaign-style ``listening tour''
across New York on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Washington whirlwind also appeared designed in part to
steal some of the thunder from her most likely Republican rival for
the Senate seat being vacated by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has criticized the first
lady for being an Illinois-born, Arkansas-based carpetbagger
candidate in New York, traveled to the Clintons' turf in Arkansas
Tuesday to highlight his criticisms and raise money for his own
burgeoning Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With no additional public events on her schedule before she
leaves for New York on Thursday, the first lady's rapid-fire
appearances here marked the end of a self-imposed moratorium on
campaign activities following the death of and memorial services
for John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy and her
sister, Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to return to the Empire State Thursday for a third
campaign-related foray since creating a campaign fund-raising
committee on July 6. She plans visits to Elmira, Bath and Ithaca
before returning to Washington on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, appearing twice with President Clinton at the
White House, struck the partisan themes of a prospective Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   She challenged the Republican leadership in Congress to enact
the Clinton administration's proposed overhaul of Medicare, saying
changes are needed to provide better health care to elderly women
who make up 60 percent of the nearly 40 million people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during an East Room appearance to celebrate the 25th
anniversary of the Legal Services Corp., Clinton warned that ``we
again face a challenge from those in Congress who are working to
slash'' a $300 million-a-year federal program that recruits 150,000
volunteer lawyers nationwide to provide representation for civil
suits by the poor, regardless of ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noting that nearly half the 40 million Americans in
poverty are children, said expanded efforts are needed to make sure
that the poor have legal representation to obtain child support,
health care for children, adequate housing, nursing home care and
protection from physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Without the help of Legal Services Corp.'s 258 legal aid
programs across the country, ``many of those children and their
parents would have no place to turn,'' said Clinton, who served as
chairwoman of the organization from 1978 to 1980 while her husband
was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the first lady:
</P>
<P>
   _ Presided over the National Jewish Democratic Council's
presentation of a humanitarian award to honor former Democratic
Party Chairman Steve Grossman and his wife Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   _ Received the Henrietta Szold Humanitarian Award from the
87-year-old Hadassah Jewish women's organization for her efforts on
behalf of issues ``critical to women and families.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped up her campaign-related activities a day after
the release of a Zogby New York poll of 709 likely voters in the
state showing the first lady continuing to trail Giuliani in a
hypothetical Senate contest.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, completed on July 19 and released Monday, showed
Giuliani leading Clinton 49 percent to 39 percent overall in a
general election contest. Giuliani's 10 percentage point edge was
double his advantage in a Zogby survey completed in May.
</P>
<P>
   But the same survey underscored Clinton's intent to appeal to
women, who favored the first lady over Giuliani 44 percent to 42
percent, according to the Zogby survey.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks about Medicare, Clinton said elderly women stand
to benefit the most from the administration's efforts to ``save and
modernize Medicare.'' These women, she said, ``struggle to pay for
out-patient prescription drugs'' and ``skip regular screenings and
check-ups that would enhance the quality of their lives and reduce
Medicare's long-term costs,'' the first lady said.
</P>
<P>
   Women, the poor and Jewish voters proved to be valuable sources
of Democratic support for then-Rep. Charles Schumer in his 1998
upset of the incumbent Republican senator, Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer defeated D'Amato, 55 percent to 45 percent. The Democrat
carried 59 percent of the women's vote, 59 percent of the vote of
voters with incomes of less than $15,000 and 76 percent of the
Jewish vote, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's appearances came as White House Press
Secretary Joe Lockhart formally announced that the first family
will divide its summer vacation between Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
and New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons will spend nine days on the Massachusetts vacation
island of Cape Cod, beginning Aug. 19, followed by seven days in
New York state _ a two-day weekend in posh East Hampton, N.Y., on
the eastern end of Long Island and five days in Skaneateles, N.Y.,
a 205-year-old lakefront community on Lake Skaneateles, one of the
six largest of the 11 Finger Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart emphasized that the Clintons plan no political
activities once they arrive in Skaneateles on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were looking for a place to go to spend the rest
of the vacation beyond Martha's Vineyard, and there are a lot of
people who recommended this part of New York, and they're very much
looking forward to spending some time there,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
