</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOCH-DETECTIVES-4TAKE     07-27 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-DETECTIVES-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY COURT FIGHT SHOWS HOW PRIVATE INVESTIGATORS POSE AS
REPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Texas, Okla., Colo., Calif., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ One of America's wealthiest and most private
families found itself in an unwanted spotlight last summer as its
fractious members waged a bitter courtroom fight over the family
business, Koch Industries, the vast oil and gas company with
headquarters on the prairie at the edge of town here.
</P>
<P>
   But in the corridors and shadows outside the courtroom, another,
more secret battle was taking place, one that reveals a new and
powerful tactic in corporate intrigue. As the jury listened to
evidence, private investigators were infiltrating the press corps
covering the trial in an effort to influence the public's view of
the family struggle and to tip sentiment in favor of its black
sheep, William Koch.
</P>
<P>
   Former news reporters working as investigators on behalf of Koch
(pronounced coke) posed as journalists to try to obtain
confidential information about Koch Industries and to distribute
negative information to legitimate reporters about the company and
Koch's brothers, Charles and David, according to interviews and
documents from the investigative firm that hired them. At least one
newspaper ran a front-page article based in part on the
information.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of the Koch case provides an unusually detailed
look at an increasingly common tactic in business disputes: the use
of private detectives. But it also reveals a growing practice
within the detective industry of employing former reporters not
only for their investigative skills but for their willingness to
trade on their past occupation to gain access to sources who would
be unlikely to speak to a private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   And it raises new questions about the seemingly legal, but
ethically questionable, ploys private detectives use to get
information, at a time when there is increasing scrutiny of what is
fast becoming a major American business.
</P>
<P>
   One of Koch's private detectives sought sensitive documents from
a reporter at The Wichita Eagle by claiming he was working on an
article about the Kochs, according to the reporter. Another
detective said he was writing a book and used articles he had
written for several publications to try to obtain interviews with
Koch Industries executives. The documents show he was actually
working on behalf of Koch, who was trying to learn everything he
could about the company run by his brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In a different type of attempt to influence the press, an
investigator said he was offered a $25,000 bonus if he could
persuade a reporter at any national newspaper to publish a negative
article about Koch Industries. The investigator provided
information to a reporter, but he said the bonus had not been paid.
A spokesman for Koch said he had refused the detective's overtures
to place a story for pay.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics surrounding the trial last summer were only the
latest skirmish in a festering dispute between opposing factions of
the Koch family in which private investigators have often been the
mercenaries. Court documents show that detectives working for
William Koch bought trash from the homes of company lawyers and
investigated the family business, while people working for William
said they were followed and harassed by investigators on the Koch
Industries payroll.
</P>
<P>
   These days a majority of the work done by private investigators
involves business disputes. The demands of these corporate clients
have helped to transform the world of private detectives from a
slightly seedy business dominated by ex-cops into a sophisticated,
multibillion-dollar industry with access to the best surveillance
equipment and computer databases. But this growth has collided with
privacy concerns, particularly over deceptions used to obtain
confidential information about individuals and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Colorado grand jury indicted two investigators who
used various subterfuges to gather information on celebrities and
other people. And Congress is considering legislation to make it a
federal crime to obtain financial information from banks by
pretending to be someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Determining how often investigators pose as journalists is
difficult, but what occurred in Wichita clearly was not an isolated
incident. Internet sites, like Espionage Unlimited in Burlington,
Vt., even sell laminated photo cards for $39.95 that identify the
bearer as an employee of a fictitious organization called American
Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, investigators around the country said pretending
to be a journalist was an accepted practice in the industry, one
rarely discovered by subjects of investigations. Those who use it
often justify the pretext as the only means of getting accurate
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all much prefer being who we are, but sometimes you use a
deception because nothing else will produce the truth,'' said Jack
Palladino, a San Francisco private detective who worked for Bill
Clinton in his 1992 campaign. ``You know if you stated honestly to
this person that you were a private investigator, they would lie to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Palladino said he and his wife and partner, Sandra Sutherland,
claim to be journalists on occasion. In a widely publicized example
in the late 1980s, Ms. Sutherland pretended to be a journalist to
get information about a smear campaign against the banker Edmond
Safra orchestrated by American Express.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in May, an investigator for Kroll Associates, the
world's largest investigative firm, was looking into a huge real
estate project in Hong Kong by pretending to be a reporter for a
Seattle publication until he was unmasked after an amateurish
blunder.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator sent an e-mail to David Webb, the editor of
Cyberport, an Internet publication that had criticized the
development. The investigator said he wanted to discuss Webb's view
on the project as part of his research for an article.
Unfortunately for the investigator, he used an e-mail with Kroll's
electronic address, tipping Webb to the subterfuge and leading to
his exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cherkasky, the president of Kroll, confirmed the account
of the incident, which first appeared on Webb's Web site. Cherkasky
declined to identify the investigator, but he said he was fired for
violating Kroll's policy against misrepresentation. Cherkasky said
Kroll had also stopped using an outside investigator whose standard
procedure was to claim to be a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, an investigator for the Investigative Group
International, another big investigative firm, tried to get
information about a candidate for governor of Tennessee by claiming
he was writing a book. When suspicious campaign officials tried to
take his photograph, the investigator thrust his briefcase in front
of his face and fled, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anthony, the case supervisor at the time, acknowledged
that the investigator, Mike Burns, was working for him. ``They
caught him and he took off running,'' said Anthony, who now works
at another detective agency.
</P>
<P>
   Pretending to be a journalist is not illegal, although several
years ago a Delaware court sanctioned lawyers for allowing Kroll
investigators to pose as reporters and impartial consultants in
questioning former employees of a chemical company.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of former reporters posing as working journalists to
gather information raises broader ethical questions about the use
of ruses and pretexts by private detectives. It also creates
concerns that detectives posing as journalists erode public trust
in the press and jeopardize its independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason people feel confident talking to journalists
is that they believe they are talking to an independent source
representing their interests and the interests of the truth, not to
someone who is part of the police apparatus, whether public or
private,'' said Bill Kovach, curator of the Nieman Foundation for
Journalism at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many former investigative reporters who work as
private detectives are Larry Gurwin, a former Time magazine
correspondent who is with Control Risks Group; Diana Moneta, a
former reporter and editor at newspapers on Long Island, N.Y., who
is with Investigative Consultants International; John Hanrahan, a
former Washington Post reporter who works for the James B. Mintz
Group; and Kathy Lavinder, a former ABC radio journalist who is at
Investigative Group International.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Pankau, a private investigator who teaches techniques to
journalists and detectives alike, said similar research skills are
required for both jobs. And most former journalists, he said, do
not use their old jobs as cover for investigative work.
</P>
<P>
   In the Koch case, the use of investigators posing as journalists
was described in records from the investigative firm that hired
them. The records, from Decision Strategies International, a large
investigative firm known by the initials DSFX, were sent
unsolicited to The New York Times by an employee. The employee has
since left to work for a competing company and insisted that his
identity be withheld.
</P>
<P>
   DSFX disputed the accuracy of its memorandums in a statement:
``We never engaged in the kind of actions described in this
self-serving and inaccurate document. It is a clear violation of
the company's standards and procedures for any of our employees or
contractors to pose as working journalists in the course of an
investigation. Anyone doing so is in clear violation of our
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hershman, the DSFX chairman, said he could not confirm
that the firm had worked for William Koch because contracts with
clients require confidentiality. Brad Goldstein, a spokesman for
Koch, said the multimillionaire had hired DSFX in the past, but the
spokesman would not specify why and said Koch never authorized
posing as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Hershman said DSFX prohibits its investigators from saying they
work for a specific publication, but he said they could identify
themselves as journalists if they held such jobs in the past and
continue to do some journalism work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are indeed a freelance journalist who also does
private investigation, essentially they are not lying,'' Hershman
said. ``I don't want them to misrepresent, but there is a fine
line. It's a difficult world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no accepted definition of a freelance journalist, just
as there is no way to disprove a former journalist's assertion that
he is thinking about writing an article or book about a particular
subject. Many publications and broadcast outlets rely on part-time
workers who hold other jobs, including as private investigators.
Further muddying the issue, some media organizations, particularly
television, hire private detectives to help with research.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the impersonation strategy sparked a debate within DSFX.
</P>
<P>
   According to the internal documents, one manager refused to
supervise the investigation because he objected to the subterfuge
on legal and ethical grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum dated May 22, 1998, the manager, Jim Drinkhall,
wrote, ``This morning, Andy Levetown called to have me manage a
case for Bill Koch where we would have a whole group of reporters
around the country gathering info for us on the Koch Industries
trial, a whistle blower case in Minnesota and an age discrimination
case, in Kansas, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum said that Levetown, a senior manager and lawyer,
saw no problem using reporters and that top management approved the
practice. Elliot Sloane, a spokesman for DSFX, said Levetown could
not discuss the case because of confidentiality restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In a later memorandum, to Bart Schwartz, the DSFX president in
New York, Drinkhall identified two people, Peter Weaver and Michael
Connors, as claiming to be covering the Koch case as journalists
while actually providing information to DSFX. Other unidentified
reporters across the country were being paid to conduct interviews
saying they were writing articles about Koch Industries'
environmental record, ``but are in fact giving us the results of
the interviews,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Drinkhall, a former investigative reporter for The Wall Street
Journal, declined to discuss the memos because of confidentiality
restrictions. He left DSFX early this year and works for another
investigative firm.
</P>
<P>
   A fuller portrait of the strategy emerged through court records
and interviews with some of the investigators, reporters who
covered the trial and Koch Industries officials. These sources also
made it clear that this was not the first time private detectives
were enmeshed in this nasty family feud.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hire a lot of private eyes because of what we're up
against,'' Goldstein, the spokesman for William Koch, said. ``We're
up against a very secretive company that operates like a cult.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries is the country's second-largest privately held
business behind Cargill, the grain merchant. It operates oil
refineries, gas pipelines and chemical companies and had revenue of
$30 billion last year. But the company maintains a low public
profile and its executives are rarely quoted in the press.
</P>
<P>
   The credit for its growth in the last 20 years has gone largely
to Charles Koch, the eldest of four brothers, who serves as
chairman and lives quietly in Wichita. But the prosperity has
sparked a series of lawsuits by William, the most flamboyant
brother, who is best known for financing the America's Cup victory
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that Charles and another brother, David, cheated him
and other shareholders out of $1 billion when they bought out their
interests in the company in 1983. William has filed at least 10
suits against Koch Industries and family members, including one
against his mother shortly before her death and another that is
scheduled for trial this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, William has hired private detectives to do
everything from investigate claims that Koch Industries was
cheating customers to collect trash outside the homes of company
lawyers. The trash collection was halted after security guards
caught an investigator trying to buy trash from the law firm's
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Court files show that Koch paid $5,000 for two investigators to
collect the trash. Among their expenses were $20 to a garbage truck
driver for bags of trash and $18.73 for rubber gloves and masks.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit, Koch said he hired the investigators to look
for evidence that Koch Industries was spying on him and his
employees. For instance, he said, one of his consultants was
subjected to surveillance and harassment by investigators for Koch
Industries and suggested that documents had been stolen from his
offices. The company has denied both accusations.
</P>
<P>
   It was last summer's trial in Topeka, Kan., that spawned the use
of investigators pretending to be journalists, according to the
DSFX records and interviews with participants in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   What the investigators hoped to gain remains unclear, though
Koch Industries officials would be more likely to share information
with a journalist than a private investigator working for William.
One memo said there were suspicions that company lawyers were
providing reporters with documents protected by a court order.
Also, William complained repeatedly that reporters were biased
against him and he may have thought infiltrating them would prove
his hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   One journalist identified in DSFX records as providing
information to the firm was Peter Weaver, a freelance business
writer in Bethesda, Md., who worked for Forbes magazine many years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to DSFX in January 1998, he sought investigative
work and described using his reputation as a financial reporter to
gain access to corporate insiders for other clients. ``Let's see if
we can come up with a challenging assignment where I can employ my
investigative skills and coveted list of sources to your
advantage,'' he wrote, according to a copy of the letter
distributed to DSFX offices nationwide and obtained by The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said in an interview that he was working on a profile of
William Koch for George magazine and provided an e-mail he sent to
the magazine outlining his story proposal. He said the assignment
was based on speculation that Koch would run for the U.S. Senate
and when he decided not to run it was canceled. DSFX helped him
identify sources for the article, Weaver said, and he later sold
the firm information. He said that he saw no conflict in his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some pay for my interviews and things I was going to use
in my story and I sold it to them,'' he said. ``I did get
something, but it was nothing like I would have gotten for the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Michael Connors, a former Denver Post reporter and part-time
journalist, was hired primarily to see if company lawyers were
leaking confidential material to reporters, according to one DSFX
memo.
</P>
<P>
   Connors attended most of the 11-week trial last summer in
Topeka. Reporters covering the trial, including Leslie Wayne of The
New York Times and Bob Cox of The Wichita Eagle, said he told them
he was writing a book about the Kochs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connors showed up at the trial and said he wanted to write a
book,'' said Cox, now at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. ``I had
lunch with him a couple times and kept asking who his publisher was
and he was pretty evasive.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Connors wrote to Koch Industries requesting
interviews with executives. He enclosed copies of some of his
articles, including one for Time magazine, according to a copy of
the letter provided by Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said in an interview that he works as a private
investigator and freelance writer, but insisted that he attended
the trial only as a journalist. He said the book is on hold and
declined to identify the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a journalist and I am an investigator,'' he said. ``I do
both, but never at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   A Web site run by a Dallas private investigation firm identifies
Connors as an employee. Jack Taylor Jr., a former reporter who is
now a licensed private detective, runs the firm. Though Taylor's
name does not appear in the DSFX memos, two people involved in the
Koch investigation said he also worked for DSFX as a subcontractor.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said in an interview that his involvement in the Koch
matter was as a journalist and declined to say whether he worked
for Koch or DSFX. ``Texas law prohibits a private investigator from
revealing anything at all about a client or work done on behalf of
a client without the client's permission, even in a court of law,''
he said. (Goldstein said Koch would not grant permission for
investigators to discuss work they may have done for him.)
</P>
<P>
   Reporters covering the Koch case said Taylor told them he was
working on a long article about the family. Cox, the former Wichita
reporter, said Taylor contacted him before the Koch trial, saying
he was considering writing an article and asking for sensitive Koch
Industries documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started quizzing me about various people and he wanted to
see a document that had been leaked to us that had been prepared by
Koch Industries purporting to expose Bill's record as an
employee,'' Cox said. ``Jack really wanted to get his hands on that
document.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is well known in investigative reporting circles, having
worked at The Daily Oklahoman, The Dallas Times Herald and The Los
Angeles Daily News. Cox said he knew him as a reporter and member
of Investigative Reporters &AMP; Editors, an organization for
journalists and educators. Still, he declined to give him the
document.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the Topeka jury decided in favor of Koch
Industries, but another trial was set for this year in Tulsa,
Okla., and William was still interested in pillorying the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Taylor sent packages of negative information about
the company, including videotape spliced together from depositions
for the upcoming trial, to at least 10 reporters in Kansas,
Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A business card attached to the package identified Taylor as a
journalist, and in a memo he wrote that he discovered the
information while working as a freelance writer for someone who was
concerned about the environment. He suggested that the reporters
might be interested in the material.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said in the interview that he did not distribute the
material as a private investigator, but he still declined to say
who paid him. ``I did it as a journalist and was paid as a
journalist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A search of newspapers in the region turned up one article based
on the material, in Indian Country Today, America's largest Indian
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor acknowledged sending the information to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The search could not determine whether other coverage of Koch
Industries was affected by the information. However, officials at
Koch Industries said they suspect other negative articles were
based on the information.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to influence the press another way, a private
detective in Washington working for DSFX provided much of the same
information to a reporter at The Wall Street Journal, according to
the detective, who spoke on condition that his name be withheld
because of his confidentiality agreement. He said he expected a
$25,000 fee if he succeeded in persuading the reporter to write a
negative article.
</P>
<P>
   The detective identified the reporter as John Fialka, an
investigative reporter in the Journal's Washington bureau. Fialka
acknowledged that he was friends with the detective and that they
had discussed Koch Industries briefly, but he declined to describe
the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't discuss projects that we're working on, especially to
The New York Times,'' Fialka said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, the spokesman for William Koch, said a private
investigator had sought a fee for placing a negative story, but
Koch rejected the offer. ``If you're saying Bill has a bounty
system for stories, you're wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Rosser, director of communications at Koch Industries, said
Fialka has been working on an article about the company since last
spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
