<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BACKS CLINTON DECISION TO CONTINUE TRADE TIES WITH CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted to continue normal trade ties with
China on Tuesday, turning aside concerns that Beijing may have
stolen top secret U.S. nuclear and missile technology and has
intensified persecution of its citizens for their political and
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The approval extending normal trade relations, or NTR, for at
least another year came on a vote of 260-170 after several hours of
debate. Opponents called on Congress to ``wise up'' before rubber
stamping a policy they described as ``anti-American and a threat to
our national security.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote margin on extending NTR, which gives the same low
tariffs to China that most other U.S. trading partners enjoy, was
nearly the same as it was last year in the House, despite the
suspicions of spying and evidence that Beijing's human rights
abuses have continued unabated.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing the charges that China may have stolen secret
material from a U.S. nuclear weapons lab in New Mexico as ``a
nightmare'' for the nation, Rep. James Traficant, D-Ohio, and other
opponents also cited the more than $60 billion trade deficit with
China as evidence that the United States is continuing to lose out
economically in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is spying and buying our nation right out from under
us,'' Traficant declared at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, however, were quick to counter that ending normal
trade ties would cost U.S. jobs and could provoke a trade war that
would give an advantage to competitors interested more in expanding
their own foothold in the Asia market than worrying about China's
human rights' record.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, who helped
lead the effort to win renewal of China's NTR status, cautioned his
colleagues about the fragility of the U.S.-Sino relationship in the
wake of the espionage charges and the recent NATO bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, R-Texas, contended that ending normal trade ties would
result in ``far greater consequences for America, for China and for
the entire world'' than the problems that exist now.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration agreed with Archer's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, President Clinton said that yanking China's NTR
status would undermine America's ability to influence over time ``a
fifth of the world's population'' in hopes of initiating greater
democratic reforms in China.
</P>
<P>
   Congress was required to vote on the annual trade status renewal
for China under a 1974 law that gives the president authority to
extend normal trade ties to totalitarian states on an annual basis
if they meet certain guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued his decision June 3 to grant another year's
extension of NTR, which was formerly called most-favored-nation
trade status, saying he was certain that the U.S. policy of
engagement with China _ the Bush and Reagan administrations
followed the same policy _ was best for America's economic and
security interests.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the vote Tuesday, Clinton said the renewed
trade status would promote ``China's integration into the global
economy,'' which would in turn strengthen market-oriented reformers
within China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expanding trade can help bring greater social change to China
by spreading the tools, contacts and ideas that promote freedom,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has voted every year since 1980 to sanction the
president's decision to grant the extension. Opponents, however,
had hoped that this year would be different, given the reports that
China may have stolen secret material from the Los Alamos facility
in New Mexico and may have tried to influence the outcome of recent
U.S. national elections with illegal campaign contributions.
Opponents had hoped that recent threats from Beijing directed at
Taiwan would also influence the vote outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The vote split the parties with Republicans and Democrats voting
on both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 17 Democrats in the Texas delegation and 11 of the 13
Republicans voted for continuing normal trade ties. Reps. Joe
Barton, of Ennis, and Lamar Smith, of San Antonio, were the only
two Republicans in the delegation to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans who voted in favor of the extension insisted that
their support should not be construed as an approval of China's
policies or of the U.S. policy of engagement at the expense of
other important interests.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, for instance, called on the
administration and Congress to rethink its approach to dealing with
China. Casting what she described as a ``reluctant'' vote to
continue NTR for China, she said the U.S. policy toward China ``has
been wrong and it's time for the United States to get some guts and
gumption and do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, said his vote was driven by concerns
that ending trade ties with China would cost U.S. jobs and give
U.S. competitors who ``are not as sympathetic on human rights as we
are'' a chance to widen their hold on the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, agreed, noting that a vote against
China would amount to ``a vote against the American worker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate also drew lobbyists, labor organizations and
conservative groups, such as the Family Research Council, to
Capitol Hill on Tuesday to condemn the policy of normal trade
relations. Business groups backed by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
meanwhile, sought its continuation, noting that 200,000 jobs and
about $18 billion in annual U.S. exports are dependent on trade
with China.
</P>
<P>
   Trade and business groups warned that revoking normal trade
status for China would kill efforts to conclude talks aimed at
making China a member of the World Trade Organization. The
administration has argued that China's inclusion in the WTO would
open its markets to major U.S. industrial and agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have bogged down since the accidental NATO bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   While recognizing the importance of trade with China, opponents
still sought to turn the vote into a referendum on China's human
rights record, which they insisted has only worsened since the
Tiananmen Square massacre 10 years ago. They pointed to the recent
crackdown in China on the Falun Gong religious sect to make their
point.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate Tuesday, about 90 or so followers of Falun
Gong sat quietly in meditation on the Capitol building grounds to
protest the ongoing arrests of sect members in China and to remind
lawmakers of the continued human rights abuses there.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any measure conceivable ... this is an abysmal record. Ten
years (after Tiananmen) is long enough to see that things haven't
changed. In fact things have gotten worse,'' said House Minority
Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., who joined with 97 other Democrats and
71 Republicans to vote against NTR for China.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
