<HEADER>
A5904 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEONY-PAVILION-MUSIC-     07-27 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEONY-PAVILION-MUSIC-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK, THE VIRTUE OF A FESTIVAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's no use either admiring or picking apart Lincoln
Center Festival '99. Management had co-designers imposed on it,
Shanghai bureaucracy and Lady Luck among them.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute cancellation of ``The Peony Pavilion'' in 1998
left a hole in the center of the event a year ago. The
resuscitation of this 19-hour Ming Dynasty classic in 1999 was
welcomed by nearly everyone, but it certainly altered any theme
Lincoln Center might originally have had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Do themes matter? ``Balanced opposition'' might be the better
term. The Salzburg Festival this year runs from Rameau to Berio,
with heavy hitters from the Romantic and post-Romantic eras in
between. Busoni's ``Doktor Faust'' and Berlioz's ``Damnation of
Faust'' line up by definition, but don't tie yourself in knots
making intellectual links between Rameau's ``Boreades'' and Berg's
``Lulu.'' Savor instead the balance of styles and the quality of
the productions.
</P>
<P>
   At Lincoln Center, ``The Peony Pavilion'' and John Eliot
Gardiner's four-concert, period-instrument survey of Schumann
shared the rarefied air of historical investigation, but here
again, significance should tread lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner's chatty style, amiable demonstrations and good
musicians seem to have had their fans. And if the Steve Reich
series was largely a retrospective of pieces we already knew, their
ability to draw young audiences made everyone grateful. Crowds at
Alice Tully Hall indicated an audience hungry for new slants on old
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Philharmonic's performances of the Beethoven piano
concertos had little to do with any kind of festival: a tired,
make-work kind of enterprise, repeating the obvious. What an
opportunity squandered: Emanuel Ax, one of the world's important
pianists, shows great curiosity about new repertory; this orchestra
can do anything that brave and imaginative leadership asks it to.
The Philharmonic's participation seemed more like business than
art; such policies undermine a young festival looking hard for an
image.
</P>
<P>
   Thematic symmetry had a chance here recently with the opera that
almost was, Messiaen's ``St. Francois d'Assise'' in Peter Sellars'
Salzburg production. If finances and logistics had allowed, New
York would have been in for a treat, and rumor has it that it might
still be: a deeply Christian opera at the center of contemporary
religious pieces in all shapes and sizes. What a time we would have
had with Stravinsky, Ligeti, Debussy and Arvo Part. How well this
year's gospel marathon, House Full o' Praise, would have fit.
</P>
<P>
   Festivals, as they have come down from the Greeks, take
audiences and performers from urban settings and ask their spirits
to chew on important matters, dispensed in intensive doses.
Festivals in the old sense have something in common with the
business or religious retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshment and relative freedom from distraction are promised.
People examine themselves and those around them in simpler
surroundings. New York in summer is presumably what the classic
festivalgoer is trying to get away from.
</P>
<P>
   So either Lincoln Center is violating the spirit of the festival
and should be ashamed of itself, or it is saying that it will have
any kind of festival it pleases, and that it will define the word
according to its own needs.
</P>
<P>
   It shares one thing in common with its colleagues around the
world, and that is a sense of place. The festival at
Aix-en-Provence in the south of France is as much about the
charming and secluded outdoor spaces as about what goes on inside
them. The complex of theaters in Salzburg, including one carved out
of rock, becomes a destination in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center is a collection of theaters as well. They sit on
common ground while going in different directions, and sometimes
need to prove that they are all of a piece. They are also very
large for the night-after-night festival audience, which thrives on
intimacy and a gradually growing mutual acquaintanceship.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Tully Hall, just over 1,000 seats and host to Gardiner's
Orchestre Revolutionnaire et Romantique, has been serviceable in
this respect. The La Guardia Concert Hall, down the street and
holding just under 1,000, has been a pleasant find. ``Peony
Pavilion'' audiences, which ranged from satisfactory to sold out
over the many performances and repeated cycles, would have been
lost in the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lincoln Center Festival needs an identifying theme, I
nominate the concept of hard work. ``The Peony Pavilion'' may be a
marathon of delight, but it is a marathon nonetheless. Stamina and
loyalty go along with the price of admission: six visits to one
event to absorb a culture a lot of us Westerners will never fully
grasp anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the labor in question was ``Palestrina,''
Pfitzner's four-and-a-half-hour exercise in operatic gluttony.
Comforted by the testimony of experts, I went to ``Palestrina''
with high hopes and a pair of comfortable shoes. Most of Act I was
revealing, the rest _ well, hard work. New York ticket buyers voted
with their feet on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet trial by ordeal may have a particular resonance for a New
York festival, and here I offer another overarching theme: art
imitating life. We all ride the subway, brave the bouts of heat and
humidity, fend off the noise and, at the end of the day,
congratulate ourselves on being able to live in this city. Being
happy in New York is hard work, and maybe ``The Peony Pavilion''
and ``Palestrina'' underline that fact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
