<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-`DEEPBLUESEA'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING DOWN TO THE `DEEP BLUE SEA' _ FOR SOME UNINTENDED LAUGHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What this summer has been missing at the movies is a
preposterous action tale. No, ``Wild Wild West'' doesn't count.
We're talking about something even more absurd, something that
pummels you with its total disregard for actors, dialogue, subtlety
or common sense. Something along the lines of a ``Rock,'' a ``Con
Air'' or an ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Renny Harlin, who gave us ``Die Hard 2'' and
``Cliffhanger,'' to fill the void. In his latest, the shark-vs.-man
fish story ``Deep Blue Sea,'' the director actually stages an
action sequence that manages to incorporate all the elements:
earth, wind, fire and water. Never let it be said that Harlin
leaves anything out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sea'' is bizarrely entertaining, perhaps even in ways that
Harlin meant it to be, even though it's really not very good. If
you've seen its ads with a huge shark creeping up behind a woman in
the drink, you might think it's a ``Jaws'' rip-off, but you'd be
wrong. It's actually a rip-off of ``Jaws'' and just about every
disaster movie since ``Jaws.'' At one point, Harlin even steals
from himself, in a sequence that echoes the opening of
``Cliffhanger,'' perhaps the finest eight minutes Harlin has ever
directed. He didn't know when to quit in that movie, though, and
that's a problem he has in ``Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   You might also think that we've had one ``Jaws'' imitator this
summer in ``Lake Placid,'' so why do we need two? But ``Sea'' is
better than ``Lake'' _ well, at least it's more fun simply because
the forced ironic tone of ``Lake'' isn't as funny as the
unintentional humor in ``Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Can you really make a movie this ridiculous without
knowing it? A movie that gives us a gee-whiz Samuel L. Jackson who
turns into Evangelical ``Pulp Fiction'' Man when he loses his
glasses as things turn grim? A movie that asks us to buy willowy
Saffron Burrows, who apparently believes that constant frowning
gives her an air of authority, as a scientist whose obsessive
Alzheimer's research leads to the development of some hypersmart,
voracious supersharks?
</P>
<P>
   A movie that makes you wonder if Thomas Jane, who looks like a
cross between Matthew McConaughey and Brad Pitt, was cast as a
Zen-like ``shark wrangler'' because McConaughey and Pitt choked on
their laughter when the part was offered? A movie that gives us LL
Cool J as a chef nicknamed Preacher, who in all fairness gets the
most exciting one-on-one encounter with a shark? A movie whose
effects are so cheesy that when the sharks chomp on humans, they
look like they're chowing down on punctured party balloons?
</P>
<P>
   Not that the actors matter. The real star is Harlin, whose
excessiveness has a what'll-he-do-next quality, as if you'd
unleashed Beavis and Butt-head in a fireworks factory. It's fun to
watch for a while, but eventually you realize it's just a bunch of
noise, as Harlin's cameras swoop, spin, dive and swim, and he and
the trio of screenwriters layer calamity upon calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Harlin revels in it all, as if he can't believe that someone
actually gave him money to make a movie after the megaflop
``Cutthroat Island.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the plot? If you care about the plot, this isn't the
movie for you. If you want to watch a director run amok, though,
it's enough to qualify as a guilty pleasure. It probably won't make
you afraid to go back in the water, but it'll probably make you
afraid to see another movie with water in it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FILM: Deep Blue Sea
</P>
<P>
   RATING: 21/2 out of a possible 5
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Renny Harlin
</P>
<P>
   STARS: Samuel L. Jackson, Saffron Burrows
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 105 min.
</P>
<P>
   RATED: R (violence, gore, strong language)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
