<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VISITS LIKELY SENATE OPPONENT'S ONE-TIME HOME TURF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ala.)  (js) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stood on the
porch of Hillary Rodham Clinton's former home here Tuesday morning,
proclaimed his admiration for the people of Arkansas and said that
he was visiting ``to get a sense of how united the Republican Party
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his brief swing through Little Rock was also a
swipe at Mrs. Clinton, his likely opponent in the U.S. Senate race
next year, Giuliani said, ``It's not in my personality to do
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He then announced that he would fly the Arkansas flag over City
Hall for a few days, to thank Gov. Mike Huckabee and his other
Republican hosts for their hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put up a big Arkansas flag at City Hall,''
Giuliani told a swarm of 60 reporters, photographers and television
crew members from around the nation, who were trying to record his
visit to the Governor's Mansion without expiring in the 91-degree
heat. ``We'll fly it for a couple of days, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Huckabee and his wife, Janet, and touring the
first floor of the Governor's Mansion, Giuliani proceeded to a
fund-raising lunch at the Capital Hotel, where 62 people paid $500
each for filet mignon and a 15-minute speech in which the mayor
boasted of his success as a Republican in a largely Democratic
city. The lunch raised about $40,000 for Giuliani's political
committee, and his aides predicted that he would pull in at least
$90,000 more at fund-raising events in New Orleans Tuesday night
and in Alabama on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But while the two-day trip was billed as a fund-raising tour of
the South, Giuliani's six hours in Little Rock Tuesday seemed more
like a traveling circus, or at least a movie shoot. Local camera
crews shot footage of out-of-town camera crews. Out-of town
reporters interviewed local reporters. And Giuliani's press
secretary, Sunny Mindel, gleefully snapped pictures of them all.
Waiters served pink lemonade and chocolate cookies under a magnolia
tree at the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   And just outside the fancy iron gates _ near a bust of a smiling
Bill Clinton _ a group of women who called themselves The Vast
Right Wing Conspiracy waved signs shaped like hogs that read,
``Razorbacks for Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so tired of Bill and Hillary's scandals and we think
Rudy has done a good job,'' said Jamie Simmons, who said she and
the other sign-wavers had traveled from Memphis, Tenn., to catch a
glimpse of Giuliani. ``We are probably more conservative than he
is, but if it's between him and her, he is the man for the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
