A5918 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-CABLE-HNS &LR;      07-27 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-CABLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T WINS ROUND IN CABLE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Caught in the middle of a high-stakes cyberspace
turf war, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors has granted AT&AMP;T a
monopoly on high-speed Internet access over its cable lines for
now.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Monday means that AT&AMP;T, along with its subsidiary
Excite &LR; Home, will not be forced to share its cable lines with its
competitors in San Francisco for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The city may wait, for example, until legal battles in Oregon
and Florida over the same access issues are resolved. The board
requested a status report for Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The move came on a 9-2 vote to transfer control of the city's
cable system to AT&AMP;T, which bought cable franchise operator TCI.
</P>
<P>
   With the transfer, the city could have forced AT&AMP;T and
Excite &LR; Home to share its cable lines with America Online, GTE,
Pacific Bell and other competitors. Those companies want the chance
to give their customers access to the Internet over high-speed
cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   But after fierce lobbying from both sides, the board decided to
put off compelling AT&AMP;T to open its lines.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the decision would allow the city to avoid a
protracted legal battle with AT&AMP;T and would ensure that the new
cable operator would rebuild the aging system to state-of-the-art
standards at a cost of $50 million over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed with the board's action, supporters of open access
have vowed to go to the voters to overturn the decision by
referendum next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano and Supervisor Leland
Yee voted against the franchise agreement, which addressed both the
transfer and the open access issue.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was preceded by one of the most intense and pricey
lobbying campaigns ever to hit City Hall. Estimates put the effort
at more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors were inundated with thousands of electronic mail
messages, faxes and phone calls from both sides.
Corporate-sponsored advocacy groups aired TV commercials, operated
sophisticated phone banks and took out full-page newspaper ads.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's meeting, open access supporters and opponents came
out in force. Many of them had direct financial links to the
companies that had something at stake. ``Support open access''
baseball caps were handed out by one side, candy by the other.
</P>
<P>
   Both carried the same message: The consumer will benefit. What
wasn't addressed directly Monday were the financial stakes for AT&AMP;T
and the other affected Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Internet depends on the availability of
high-speed access. Cable lines aren't the only way to achieve it.
Digital and satellite systems are also competing in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Both Portland, Ore., and Broward County, Fla., have already
moved to impose open access requirements on AT&AMP;T's cable lines, and
the company is fighting back in court.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco has become ground zero in the battle among
Internet titans. The thinking has been that as goes San Francisco _
one of the country's key technology hubs _ so will go the rest of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Friedlander, acting director of San Francisco's
Telecommunications and Information Services Department, noted that
the debate over open access was merely hypothetical now because the
existing cable system couldn't handle the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   The legal cases in Portland and Broward County could have a
bearing on what happens here.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T sued when Portland required it to open access to its
Internet competitors; the city has won the first legal round. And
Monday AT&AMP;T filed a federal lawsuit against Broward County to try
to overturn its open-access ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T loses its court battles against the other jurisdictions,
San Francisco supervisors have reserved the right to seek open
access requirements in the city. They also said they could push for
open access under any other legal power granted to them.
</P>
<P>
   However, they chose not to write the law approved Monday so that
open access in San Francisco would be triggered automatically if
Portland eventually prevails or the federal or state governments
give the green light. The transfer agreement simply says San
Francisco ``may impose'' open access.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano had wanted an open access requirement to kick in
immediately. When that failed, he tried to hinge open access here
to the outcome of the Portland case.
</P>
<P>
   He called the legislation adopted by the board Monday little
more than ``hocus-pocus and hooey'' because it gives the city
leeway in deciding later whether to take on AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make AT&AMP;T do anything,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
