<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-EARNINGS-C     07-27 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mindspring to exceed ad spending estimates By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises announced plans to pour
approximately $45-55 million more than it had originally planned
into advertising and marketing to aggressively accelerate growth
over the next three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   President and chief operating officer Michael S. McQuary said
the increased advertising and marketing push is an indication that
MindSpring has confidence in its ability to bring in new
subscribers through growth as well as acquisition. The company had
originally planned to spend 20 per cent of revenue on marketing and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The company also reported it had revenues of $85.6 million, up
from $25.1 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring lost $7.1 million, or 11 cents per share, in the
second quarter compared with income of $2 million, or 4 cents per
share last year. The results included amortization from recent
Netcom and SpryNet acquisitions. Excluding these items, MindSpring
earned $7.5 million, or 11 cents per share, in the latest quarter,
up from $2.7 million, or 5 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   First Call analysts called for MindSpring to earn 9 cents per
share, excluding amortization.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second consecutive loss after five profitable
quarters, but McQuary says MindSpring is willing to suffer
short-term losses to pursue larger, loftier goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are foregoing short term profitability to be more valuable
in the long term. We can only do this because we have proven we had
a business model that was profitable and proven we could set a plan
and manage to that plan. Our shareholders and they analysts who
follow us are comfortable that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said that MindSpring would continue to exercise the
fiscal discipline it has become known for. ``The targets and the
milestones we've set for ourselves are longer leaps, but we have a
lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Since MindSpring announced a few weeks ago it was in discussions
about ``possible business combinations,'' rumors of mergers and
takeovers have been rampant. One of the most prevalent rumors
linked MindSpring with Dell Computer. However on Tuesday, Dell
announced it would form its own Internet access service that did
not involve MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   McQuary would not comment on whether MindSpring had been talking
with Dell, but he did say the Dell ISP has its work cut out for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardware companies are going to be absolutely shocked at
the skill set it takes to make subscribers happy and run an
internet service,'' he said, adding that MindSpring didn't have any
immediate plans to begin manufacturing and selling PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have skill sets in that area. You can teach a pig to
dance, but it's not a pretty dance and the pig doesn't like it
much. It's not as easy as it looks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
