<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKED-DISABILITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14 WHO FAKED DISABILITIES FOR PARKING SPOTS FACE PENTALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 14 current and former UCLA football players
who faked medical excuses to secure handicapped parking placards
could face six months in jail each or a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   But Enid Awad has another penalty in mind. The executive
director of Southern California Rehabilitation Services wants to
see them sentenced to work with the people whose parking spaces
they allegedly stole.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young men obviously have no clue how difficult it might
be to have limitations on your mobility,'' Awad said. ``They should
have to see what it's like when you can't just get up and throw
your clothes on and run out the door. I really believe that will
help them come to see that what they did was wrong, not just that
they got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The athletes _ who claimed to have medical conditions ranging
from bad knees to the facial nerve ailment known as Bell's palsy _
are scheduled to be arraigned Wednesday in Los Angeles. As the
result of a six-month investigation launched after a university
police officer spotted a car with an improperly displayed placard,
each is charged with illegal possession of a parking placard and
filing a false report with the state Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   While officials at the University of California at Los Angeles
and the athletes themselves have largely kept quiet on the scandal,
disabled activists throughout the city have taken it as an
opportunity to underscore problems with accessible parking that
they say are not limited to UCLA. A protest is planned outside the
courthouse, with demonstrators expect to demand both an
investigation into the state system of awarding the placards and
the suspension of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a blessing in disguise for the community, because this
practice is really pervasive but it has never been put on the map
as an issue until now,'' said Lillibeth Navarro, who gets around in
a motorized wheelchair. ``Thousands and thousands of people respect
accessible parking spaces, but many people abuse them and laugh
about it. Well, the party's over.''
</P>
<P>
   DMV spokesman Evan Nossoff said the agency has no way to measure
handicapped parking fraud, but that it had run sting operations at
UCLA before a change in the law allowed local parking authorities
to do their own investigations. Statewide, there are about 1
million disabled parking permits, 200,000 of them assigned on a
temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
   On UCLA's rolling campus, located in the heart of Westwood, any
parking space is coveted, even at $225 per semester. The
university, which has about 37,000 students and another 22,000 or
so non-student employees, does not charge for disabled parking
permits. There are 551 of them, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain the permits, the football players allegedly bought
doctors' forms with forged signatures, filled in their own
ailments, then sent them in for approval. Chicago Bear Cade McKown,
a former UCLA athlete, told the Chicago Tribune he had a
handicapped placard from Feburary through mid-June 1997. ``I didn't
use it for handicapped spaces,'' he said. ``I can count on one hand
the number of times I used it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one time too many for Brian Williams the Los Angeles
city attorney overseeing the case. Although the athletes are
charged with misdemeanors, he said he considers their alleged
offenses serious. He said he wants to use the case to send a
message to anyone who would abuse handicapped parking, especially
in the car culture that is California.
</P>
<P>
   Jail time would not accomplish that, he added. The athletes,
however, will have to cite the arrests and charges on future job
applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a disposition in this case that the defendants
will never forget,'' Williams said. ``But it isn't a problem that's
endemic only to athletes. It occurs everywhere and people don't
take it as seriously as they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in a prepared statement, UCLA Chancellor Albert
Carnesale condemned the student-athletes' alleged conduct. Head
football coach Bob Toledo went so far as to say he was
``embarrassed and disappointed for the young men who were involved
in this problem.'' He added that he would discipline the players
involved. UCLA is expected to have an announcement Wednesday after
the athletes' appearance in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a pretty lowdown person to do what they did,'' said
Nossoff, of the DMV. ``I think it would certainly be appropriate
for these football players to provide their services over a period
of time for disabled people who could use their strength and who
wouldn't take it for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
