u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ARGENTINA-NYT &LR;      07-27 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ARGENTINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL CUTS OFF TRADE WITH ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazil has halted all commercial
negotiations with Argentina after the two countries, South
America's largest economies, clashed in a series of trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the Argentines on Monday to review imports for
evidence of unfair trading practices and possibly to impose
restrictions in some areas led to Brazil's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians also called for a meeting next week with
Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay, the members of the Mercosur
regional trade zone, to discuss the bloc's future. Mercosur has
economically benefited all its members by stimulating cross-border
trade through lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of protection by Argentina is not legally foreseen
within Mercosur, which was created under the principles of free
trade,'' Jose Alfredo Graca Lima, an undersecretary in Brazil's
foreign ministry, said to reporters in the capital, Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the bloc's two largest members represents
the most serious crisis to confront Mercosur since it was formed in
1991. Mercosur ranks as the world's third-largest trading bloc,
though well behind the North American Free Trade Agreement and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mercosur expanded trade among its four members to $18.2
billion last year from $3.6 billion in 1991, a severe regional
economic slowdown has strained relations between Brazil and
Argentina. The flash point of recent tension can be traced to
Brazil's currency devaluation in January, which destabilized the
flow of regional trade.
</P>
<P>
   After the devaluation, Argentina's exports to Brazil, its
largest trading partner, tumbled more than 30 percent in the first
quarter of the year. And although Brazilian goods were made cheaper
with the decline of the real against the Argentine peso, which is
locked into the exchange rate of the U.S. dollar, exports to
Argentina also declined, falling 22 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The slump in economic activity in both countries explains the
fairly severe decline in trade. And Argentina, which is more
dependent on the larger, more varied Brazilian economy than vice
versa, appears to be under greater strain.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there have been an estimated 10 bond defaults by
Argentine borrowers in international markets so far this year,
compared with half that number by Brazilian borrowers. Argentina's
gross domestic product is forecast to shrink 3 percent this year,
compared with a 1 percent expected decline in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's first serious dispute with Brazil came in the form
of an anti-dumping charge against the Brazilian steel industry late
last year, and was followed by restrictions on Brazilian textiles.
Similar actions involving Brazilian shoes and sugar are under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Europe and the U.S. are also our significant trading
partners, the problems with Argentina don't always merit great
attention,'' said Michel Alaby, vice president of the Mercosur
Integration Association of Brazilian Companies. ``But in Argentina,
where trade with Brazil is so important, this is a very big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   While economic concerns are overriding, Brazil's pressure on
Argentina is also political.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, who are seeking to exert greater influence in
Latin America, were irked by Argentine overtures to become closer
to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Speculation that
Argentina might adopt the dollar as its currency has also worried
Brazil's government.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, relations between the two countries are better than
they were 20 years ago, when Argentina and Brazil were stockpiling
weapons and considered each other potential enemies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
