A5933 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARNIVAL-CENTURY-FEST     07-27 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-CENTURY-FEST-ART-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING AN IMPRESARIO OF THE OUTDOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Leonard De Pair is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the dancer-choreographer David Parsons.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To many New Yorkers, Lincoln Center Out of Doors has
always been there _ an extravaganza every August that offers a
diverse fare of free dance, music and theater. The forthcoming
series, Carnival of the Century, starting Friday through Aug. 29,
is solidly within that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It includes the jazz pianist Dave Brubeck, a Greek blues singer,
Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo, music of the Jewish
Diaspora, a Peruvian dance company and the Colorado String Quartet,
plus entertainment for children.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1970, when Leonard de Paur, who died last year
at 83, introduced outdoor events to Lincoln Center, that anyone
took advantage of the potential of an arts festival on the site.
Before then _ long before Summerstage in Central Park and Celebrate
Brooklyn _ an outdoor festival would have been a novel concept any
place in New York City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When de Paur (pronounced pour) became director of community
relations at Lincoln Center in 1968, he had already achieved
success as conductor of his own popular choral groups, Broadway
musicals and symphony orchestras and as musical director of the
Negro Federal Theater in New York City. In many ways, Lincoln
Center proved a logical next step for a man committed to bringing
the arts to the widest possible public.
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival is dedicated to de Paur. On opening night,
Andrew Young, de Paur's brother-in-law and a former ambassador to
the United Nations, will join other speakers in honoring the man
from Summit, N.J. ``As a conductor,'' Young said in a recent
interview, ``Leonard brought the American idiom, jazz and
spirituals, to classical music, which was then largely European.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, there would be no Wynton Marsalis. In a sense, he
was to classical music what Jackie Robinson was to baseball, except
in baseball it was about color. In classical music, segregation
went deeper, depriving us of a world of diverse rhythms and
harmonies. At Lincoln Center, he broadened the audience for all the
arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics prove this. Every summer, at least 250,000 people
sample the festival's varied events, many of them newcomers to
Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   De Paur's history is well tended by his widow, Norma. On the
piano in their apartment in Harlem, she has arranged a large
selection of family photographs. Many of them feature their son and
daughter, Leonard (known as Laddie) and Norma Lynn, and Laddie's
three children.
</P>
<P>
   A scrapbook contains pictures of de Paur conducting his choirs
all over the world. In a formal portrait, with pipe in hand, he
looks distinguished in a well-cut tweed jacket and stylish tie,
though his expression suggests a certain irony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard could never hide the twinkle in his eye,'' Mrs. de
Paur said. ``He inevitably saw the humor in a situation.'' From the
bookshelves, she brought out his recordings of Virgil Thomson's
opera ``Four Saints in Three Acts'' and Gershwin's ``Porgy and
Bess,'' with Leontyne Price and William Warfield. ``The outdoor
festival didn't happen in a direct fashion,'' she explained. ``It
came out of music, out of his arranging the International Choral
Festival at Lincoln Center. He invited choirs from 58 different
countries. Afterward, they asked him to take on more
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lincoln Center offered no specifics. When John Mazzola, then
president of Lincoln Center, hired him, de Paur asked what his job
would entail. A few hours later, Mazzola's secretary arrived with a
couple of index cards, on which were typed the simple, albeit
daunting, instructions: Get the community to Lincoln Center, and
take Lincoln Center to the community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to cast about for things that I could do that would
bring some life to the place,'' de Paur said in an oral-history
interview, which is in the Lincoln Center archives, ``and I had
some luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck arrived in the form of Con Edison, which was interested in
sponsoring community arts groups. He had already been trying to
figure out how to create community nights; now he had financial
backing to go forward. ``We'll give you the facilities, and we'll
support you,'' he announced to arts organizations in all the city's
boroughs. ``You've only got to do two things: bring the attraction
and bring an audience from your community.'' Thus the Community
Holiday Festival was born and continued every Christmas season
until 1994 in Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Now de Paur had to deal with the summer season. ``The minute I
took over the management of things on the plaza,'' he said, ``I
clashed with a few administrators because their idea of a plaza was
freshly scrubbed, totally unencumbered by humanity and, if
encumbered by humanity, only by those people who were heading into
the opera house or to Philharmonic Hall with tickets for the right
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what appalled me so. I looked out the window and here's
this magnificent plaza and not a thing on it but pigeons. I thought
of some of the places I had seen in Europe, like St. Mark's, and I
said: `God, what a shame! It's gorgeous, it's beautiful, it's
wonderful, and nobody's making any use of it or deriving any
benefit from it.' Lincoln Center is a home of the living arts, and
by God, if we can't bring some life in here we're not fulfilling
our mandate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   De Paur quickly defeated his adversaries and moved on. ``I
wanted the things on that plaza open to the broadest possible
public, in programmed fashion, so that you could come in the
morning and stay to midnight and see something every minute you
were there,'' he said. ``I did a good job of mixing, but I needed
money.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He soon made a deal with Exxon to underwrite the festival costs,
even though his job didn't include development. When he told
Mazzola about the deal, Mazzola thought he was kidding. But before
long he also had the Chiquita Brands company on the bandwagon. For
at least one season, little donkey-pulled folk carts were dotted
around the plaza, stacked high with bananas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had kids with Chiquita banana hatbands handing out the
bananas,'' he said. ``I have a picture of my daughter back there in
one of them. New Yorkers couldn't believe they were getting
something free.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His son also helped. ``There was little money to spare,'' Laddie
de Paur recalled, ``so Pop had me and other 16-year-old kids doing
technical production for the shows.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The festival's first three seasons were dominated by street
theater, which cast amateurs as well as professionals in socially
conscious plays. In 1974 it began offering all kinds of
entertainment: a Hispanic version of the Broadway musical
``Kismet,'' the Symphony of the New World String Quartet, the
Jazzmobile Workshop Orchestra, Ballet Hispanico, Art Blakey and the
Jazz Messengers, and Dianne McIntyre's Sounds in Motion.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Leventhal, the current president of Lincoln Center, said
in an interview, ``Leonard quickly demonstrated that even though
what went on outside at Lincoln Center was free, it was just as
good as what went on inside.''
</P>
<P>
   De Paur's experience lay chiefly in music and theater, but he
also enjoyed dance. ``We were in a position,'' he said, ``to
introduce companies to much broader-based community audiences than
they got when they performed in City Center and places like that,
with ticket tariffs. We put them in Damrosch Park, on that stage in
back of the band shell, and we gave them everything we could _
lights, dressing space, good amplification. It was a good place to
perform. Dance did very well back there, and it became a
well-attended series every year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The festival soon grew to be an important showcase for
up-and-coming modern-dance troupes. Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane, Garth
Fagan, Trisha Brown, Philadanco, Pilobolus and Steven Petronio all
presented work there in the early years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jenneth Webster, who became director on de Paur's retirement in
1988, carries on the tradition. This year, she awarded two of her
largest financial commissions to dance. They went to Philadanco,
which will perform Ronald K. Brown's ``Ode to Ellington'' on Aug.
19 and 20, and to the New York Baroque Dance Company for ``Vivaldi
Carnivale,'' which is choreographed by Catherine Turocy and
scheduled for Aug. 25 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   While the festival does offer some big names, it banks on the
participation of local talents. ``Today we're just as involved with
them as ever,'' said Ms. Webster. ``When we present Indian,
Chinese, Haitian or Mexican events, often the performers are from
right here in New York. What money we have to advertise, we spend
on their radio stations and in their newspapers. An entire Mexican
soccer team came to our Mexican concerts last year. Leonard wanted
everyone to feel welcome here, and I think they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
