<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-GOP-HNS &LR;      07-27 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BLASTS PROPOSED GOP TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seizing on what could become a key campaign issue,
Vice President Al Gore on Tuesday lambasted proposed GOP tax cuts,
arguing they would lead the nation back to the red ink of the Bush
and Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the rhetoric of House and Senate Democratic leaders who
joined him at a Capitol Hill rally, Gore charged that the
Republican tax cuts would not only increase federal debt but
preclude efforts to strengthen Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember what happened the last time they tried to pull this
kind of accounting stunt,'' he said, referring to GOP tax cuts of
the early 1980s. ``We ended up quadrupling our national debt in
only a dozen years. We created annual budget deficits of $300
billion a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments came the day before the Senate was to take up a
GOP-sponsored $792 billion tax cut. Last week the House approved a
tax cut of the same size but of a different composition.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan is targeted more at lower income taxpayers and
excludes some reductions included in the House bill, such as
capital gains tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton also continued to sound
the alarm by releasing a report showing that GOP tax cuts would put
at risk elderly women who rely on Medicare. Clinton has requested
that $375 billion of the surplus be set aside to extend the life of
Medicare and provide a new prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have not allocated a specific amount for
Medicare, they argue that there will be plenty of money left over
after they deal with Social Security to take care of the health
care program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the debate is more about the size and details of
any tax cut. He and other Democrats are backing $320 billion in
targeted tax reductions proposed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Charging that the ``Republican leadership is beholden to special
interests,'' Gore criticized some of the benefits tucked into the
House bill, including tax breaks for the restaurant and oil and gas
industries.
</P>
<P>
   While he did not single out GOP presidential contenders, Gore
called on Republican party leaders to repudiate the tax cut. And he
sought to remind voters that they do not want to return to the
economic policies of Republican administrations that helped create
big deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when Republicans come back and offer the hair of the dog
that bit them, offering to take us back to the old ways that ran
the economy into the ground, surely members of their own party will
stop and think back before they go back,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore did not mention Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a leading
GOP presidential hopeful, the Democratic National Committee made it
clear in a news release that it believed the governor was
vulnerable on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush cannot simultaneously support the Republican Party's tax
plan and credibly claim he wants to `leave no one behind,'' stated
DNC chairman Roy Romer.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been encouraged by polls showing that the public
does not rank tax cuts as a top priority. The polls also show that
women in particular tend to favor Clinton's emphasis on saving
Medicare over giving out big tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign stump speeches, Bush says he supports tax cuts
and last week, when asked by reporters in Iowa, the governor said
he would sign the House GOP tax proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said that the governor holds that
``if you have a president who will set priorities and follow
through on them, he believes you can fix Social Security, modernize
Medicare, rebuild our defense and give working people tax relief,''
</P>
<P>
   While the Texas governor has endorsed GOP tax plans he has not
made their passage a central element of his campaign message.
Tucker also said she had not heard the governor address certain
controversial specifics in the House GOP bill such as reducing
capital gains taxes and increasing tax deductions for business
meals.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders continued to defend the cuts, arguing there
is a healthy enough surplus to save Social Security and Medicare
and return money to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton and his Democratic allies don't trust the
American people to spend their money wisely. But Republicans do,''
said Rep. J.C. Watts, the House Republican Conference Chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the partisan rhetoric there have been divisions within
both parties on the size and shape of a tax cut. Some moderate
Republicans rebelled at the size of the reduction pushed by House
leaders. In the Senate, some centrist Democrats are advocating a
compromise $500 billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Democrats, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., writing in
Tuesday's Washington Post, said that it was ludicrous ``to suggest
that we can't afford to cut income taxes when we are running a $3
trillion surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said that it wasn't tax cuts that were standing in the
way of shoring up Medicare and Social Security but the reluctance
of lawmakers to make the painful structural changes in those
programs. Kerrey, who has been somewhat of a maverick in the
Democratic Party, is backing Gore's opponent, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley, in the presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
