<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-CUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERE BUDGET CUTS THREATEN RESEARCH, NASA OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than one week after the nation triumphantly celebrated the
30th anniversary of its greatest glory in space _ the first Moon
landing _ Congress is poised to slash the space program's budget to
an unprecedented degree. The agency's head says the proposed cuts
would be ``devastating,'' and advocates of space exploration call
the proposal ``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cuts, agreed to in a surprise move late Monday by a
House subcommittee, would trim the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's overall budget of $13.665 billion by nearly 10
percent, and cut its scientific research by almost one third. The
proposed budget will be voted on by the appropriations committee on
Friday and the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
   NASA administrator Daniel Goldin said Tuesday that ``not only is
this cut devastating to NASA's programs, it is a knife in the heart
of employee morale.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's budget has already been trimmed by 30 percent over
the last seven years, allowing for inflation. Yet many analysts say
that by improving efficiency NASA during the last decade has
actually shown it can accomplish more with less. That management
success may be haunting the agency now as it contemplates more
missions to Mars and expanded scientific projects.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Friedman, executive director of the nonprofit space
advocacy group the Planetary Society, said the cuts would be ``the
most devastating in NASA's history, and effectively curtail space
exploration after 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA's space science budget of $2.2 billion would be cut by $640
million, or 29 percent, under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's budget peaked during its glory days of project
Apollo when its $5.25 billion in 1965 amounted to almost 4 percent
of the entire federal budget. This year's budget of $13.665 billion
represents less than one percent of the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cuts, pushed by the subcommittee's Republican
leadership in a last-minute move that had not been anticipated by
space policy analysts, is an attempt to comply with budgetary caps
that were passed years ago to control the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republican leaders are already facing some
criticism for having exceeded the 1997 budget caps in several other
fiscal 2000 appropriations, and so may be feeling pressure to toe
the line on the caps wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
   But NASA has also earned the ire of some in Congress as it
fought intensely almost every year to preserve funding for large,
expensive programs. In particular, many in Congress see the
International Space Station as an overpriced project that will not
produce enough scientific or technical return to justify its cost.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, then-House speaker Newt Gingrich made some unusually
harsh comments about NASA, suggesting that the nation's access to
space had actually been hindered by the space agency's bureaucracy,
and that the agency lacked vision and direction.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee Chairman James Walsh, R-N.Y., the bill's chief
author, said the cuts in space spending were ``perhaps the most
difficult and painful choices'' he made in writing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to that and other reductions, he said he would ``make
every effort to address these difficulties'' later this year, when
the legislation is likely to be part of budget negotiations with
the Clinton administration expected to result in higher spending.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts fear that may come too late to save the space
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once passed, it takes on a life of its own,'' Friedman said.
``It really is a threat.'' While the initiative for cutting the
budget has come from the Republican side, Friedman said there has
been little response from the Democrats: ``Nobody has come up and
started championing a different course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among NASA's programs that would almost certainly face the ax if
the cuts stick, according to Friedman, are all missions to Mars
after 2001, including a planned mission to bring Mars rocks back to
Earth to search for evidence of life; an orbiter for Jupiter's moon
Europa, which may harbor oceans larger than Earth's; missions to
the outer planets; and the next ``great observatory'' satellite,
designed to join the Hubble telescope and the just-launched Chandra
X-ray telescope.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Goldin suggested that such a deep cut ``may force
the closure of one to three NASA centers, and significant layoffs
would most certainly follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the House itself had voted just a few weeks ago to
accept a report that recommended spending more on research in
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts found the subcommittee's move especially puzzling.
``It came out of nowhere, frankly,'' said John Pike, a space policy
analyst with the Washington-based Federation of American
Scientists. ``Most people figured that we had had the budget battle
over NASA a couple of years ago. The main budget battle this year
has been trying to figure out how to spend the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the context of Washington's typically heated budget
debates, Pike said, ``it is really rather extraordinary and
unanticipated that they've chosen this moment to chop NASA up into
little tiny pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Pike said that practically speaking, whatever comes out of the
House budget process can be seen as an initial bargaining position
that will change during negotiations with the Senate, which has not
yet taken up the NASA budget. ``I assume that all of this is going
to get negotiated away in the conference committee, since there's
evidently not a basis for this kind of cut.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``everyone has to assume it's real, because it's
going to be real unless people do something to make it go away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
