<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALDRIN FINDS HIS WAY INTO HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moon-walking astronaut  &UR; Buzz Aldrin &LR; , 69, who two months ago
helped Givenchy introduce its new men's scent, p, will be on hand
Friday at a Washington hotel to help introduce Hasbro's G.I. Joe
Classic Collection, which features an ``action figure'' (doll for
boys) based on him.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrin, who had said his role in the perfume unveiling had to do
with the product's opening up ``our understanding of the world,''
told the Washington Post why it was important that he allow his
likeness to be used by Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic toy will have ``a lot more long-term life'' than the
actual feat of walking on the moon, and he hopes it ``will be a
collectors' item of historical value,'' said Aldrin, eager to take
his place among Beanie Babies and Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SMALL PROBLEMS OF GREAT BRITAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The temperature of heated seats in certain new model
Rolls-Royces and Bentleys might fry the behinds of owners and
passengers, says a report in the Times of London, which notes that
597 cars have been recalled. ``The seat could heat up to a
potentially dangerous level if the heater is inadvertently left on
while no one is sitting on it,'' said Janette Green of the company.
``Thankfully no one has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been isolated incidents in which owners have
accidentally knocked the switch turning the heater on. You would
notice if you were sitting on the seat, but not know, if you
weren't, that the seat was getting rather too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr.  &UR; Nicola Hargreaves &LR;  of the Liverpool School of Tropical
Medicine and Dr.  &UR; Elizabeth Hyman &LR;  of the Nottingham City Hospital
report in the journal Hospital Medicine, that people _ like cats _
can get hair balls. The human hair balls usually result from a
habit usually suffered by girls between the ages of 10 and 19 of
swallowing hair from their own heads, their pets, or from blankets
or carpets.
</P>
<P>
   _ A survey by the British supermarket chain Tesco survey &LR; ,
reported in Details magazine, found that women buying melons
subconsciously compare the sizes with the sizes of their breasts
(and never mind the men and their zucchinis). ``We were very
surprised by the results of the market research,'' said a spokesman
quoted in the magazine, ``but it's certainly produced results.
Since we introduced smaller melons two months ago, we've sold more
than a million. That's quite a lot!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Photographer and ``Shaft'' director  &UR; Gordon Parks &LR; , 86, has
written a 600-page novel based on the life of the painter  &UR; J.M.W. &LR; 
 &UR; Turner &LR; , and according to artnet.com, is talking with  &UR; Ismail &LR; 
 &UR; Merchant &LR;  about turning it into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Lausanne, Switzerland, on Saturday afternoon,  &UR; Phil &LR; 
 &UR; Collins &LR;  married  &UR; Orianne Cevey &LR; , who wore a custom-made Armani
gown with a 20-foot-long train. Getting the bride and her dress
safely through the revolving door and into the Beau-Rivage Palace
hotel, where the ceremony was held, posed a problem for her staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had visions of Orianne getting throttled as the door spun
round,'' an aide told the Mirror, ``like the famous dancer Isadora
Duncan. ... It took a lot of care to get Orianne into the hotel
without tearing or snagging the train.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Discus Dental, which makes products sold to dentists, now
uses, &LR;  ``tooth-whitening agents approved by the Union of Orthodox
Jewish Congregations of America's rabbinical council,'' reports
Self magazine. These dental products are kosher, animal-, dairy-and
cruelty-free.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nakapan, the Thai restaurant that is a neighbor of KPFA in
Berkeley, has been suffering so much during constant protests that
have blocked the street, &LR;  that at last week's  &UR; Joan Baez &LR;  concert,
a speaker referred to its plight and urged people to eat there,
reports  &UR; Gar Smith &LR; . In the Nakapan window, right next to the site
of Camp KPFA, is a sign reading ``Campers' Special: $5.''
</P>
