<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5958 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-TAPE-THEATER-2T     07-27 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-TAPE-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLASHING AROUND IN THE SHALLOWS OF WHITEWATER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Sylviane Gold, who reviews dance for Newsday, has been a theater
critic for The Wall Street Journal and other publications.  
 By SYLVIANE GOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evidence is unimpeachable. Two stubbornly left-wing adults
who should know better have conspired to commit satire on the
person, the prosecutions, the very idea of Kenneth W. Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel. Their confessions are on tape, and
this referral submits substantial and credible information on their
doings. It consists of several parts: five narratives and six
excerpts from the incriminating tapes.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD LINGEMAN (senior editor, The Nation): We only did what
we were told by our muse to do.
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR NAVASKY (publisher and editorial director, The Nation):
We were subpoenaed. We couldn't say no!
</P>
<P>
   NARRATIVE I What they did is write ``Starr's Last Tape,'' a
one-man play in which a character named Starr, dressed in a prison
jump suit and surrounded by tapes and tape recorders, sings hymns,
tunes in to phone taps and dictates his memoirs: ``Chapter 1.
Mission: To Trap a President.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his dictation, he plays excerpts from his
thousands of hours of everyone on tape, including the president,
the First Lady and, of course, (italics)that(end italics) woman,
who is overheard opening her gift copy of ``Leaves of Grass'' and
saying ``Whoa, hey, is this about pot?'' Starr himself is caught on
tape interviewing a phone sex operator and personally wiring Linda
Tripp for sound.
</P>
<P>
   The play will have its world premiere in Stockbridge, Mass., at
the Berkshire Theater Festival's second stage, the Unicorn, from
Aug. 24 through 28. Brian Reddy, who played Stephen Douglas in the
1993 Lincoln Center Theater revival of ``Abe Lincoln in Illinois,''
will star as Starr, directed by Eric Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Maguire, the festival's producing director, was given the
play by a board member who is a friend of Navasky's. ``I laughed
out loud,'' she said. ``I thought that was a good sign. And no
matter what side you're on, the character of Ken Starr is
fascinating. He's like Ahab, this male character who goes after
something no matter what. A hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Starr's Last Tape'' bears any resemblance to ``Krapp's Last
Tape,'' the great solo tour de force by Samuel Beckett, it's not
exactly accidental, Navasky says.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: The title seemed written in the ether. And once you
have that title, everything else sort of falls into place. From my
point of view, the elements that Beckett contributed are the title,
the concept and the banana.
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN: Krapp eats a banana in the play, and so does Starr.
But we felt free; we felt uninhibited by Beckett's text. Reading
it, you have a sense of a much higher level of art__
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Which is the higher level of art?
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN (laughs): Our play. No, Beckett's man talking with his
past sort of fertilized our imagination.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Richard has a weak memory. I had the idea. The play
wrote itself. And Richard wrote all the jokes.
</P>
<P>
   NARRATIVE II Sitting in Navasky's office at The Nation, on
Irving Place, the two men trade their drolleries as if they have
been practicing for decades. They have. They met as students at
Yale Law School in 1956. In 1957, still students, they founded
Monocle, which they called ``A Leisurely Quarterly of Political
Satire.'' According to Navasky, that meant it came out twice a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in New York, they tried publishing it as a business
venture, which lasted until 1965. ``Our last price,'' Navasky said,
``was $7.50 for 10 issues, or $5 for a lifetime subscription.''
</P>
<P>
   Lingeman is a laconic foil for the more gregarious Navasky.
Named editor of The Nation, the proudly leftist near-weekly, in
1978, Navasky brought Lingeman on board the following year, and
they have been colleagues since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr's Last Tape'' is not their first flirtation with show
business. Navasky had written plays in college. At Yale, Lingeman
wrote some Monocle pieces in the form of dialogue, and one was
performed at a New Haven cabaret with the actor and director Austin
Pendleton, then also a student, playing an Allen Ginsberg-like
character. In 1959 they wrote a musical, never produced, about the
Communist paranoia of the '50s. And in the early '60s Lingeman
tried his hand at comedy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: We put our drama-writing careers in mothballs because
someone told us that George Kaufman had said satire is what closes
on Saturday night. And then we found a theater where they're
running this play from Tuesday to Saturday night. So we knew we had
written a real satire.
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN: But it is grounded in political realities and real
political values. As for Kaufman, he won the Pulitzer Prize__
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: ``Of Thee I Sing'' ran for 441 performances, 55
Saturday nights. I looked it up.
</P>
<P>
   NARRATIVE III That 1931 musical, a gibe at a fictitious
presidential candidate running on a love platform, has far less
venom than does ``Starr's Last Tape'' (although, Navasky pointed
out, President Clinton is not exactly spared). Navasky sees the
play's cruelty as akin to caricature. ``A great caricaturist can
get at certain truths by not presenting a balanced picture,'' he
said. ``You go right for (italics)it,(end italics) you present your
view of what's at the center of what you're writing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what they have written about has been rather
extensively covered already.
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN: It's cheaper than the Starr Report. And also dirtier.
In the course of parodying the subject, you are forced to discuss
certain sexual matters__
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Which otherwise would be inappropriate for people over
a certain age.
</P>
<P>
   NARRATIVE IV The play was written in the same back-and-forth way
they talk, each writing material and then handing it off to the
other for editing. Navasky says he would pull it out and show it to
anyone who asked what he was up to. One was that Berkshire Theater
Festival board member. Another was his friend Arthur Penn, the
director who heads the Actors Studio.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: I'd show it to everyone I ran into. ``Hey, whattaya
doing?'' ``We're writing a play! Wanna read it?'' ``Well, er, uh.''
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN: We got a lot of discouraging remarks.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Except for Arthur Penn, who was a very helpful
kibitzer, for three drafts.
</P>
<P>
   NARRATIVE V Penn says that even though the first draft was too
informational, its potential as an appropriately vicious satire of
Ken Starr was evident. Now, he says, the biggest problem is that it
is a huge job for an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, the agent Sam Cohn, volunteered no comments on
the first version. But when he read the second draft, he offered to
take on the project. ``I thought it was politically and
historically important,'' Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Navasky also showed the script to Bob Balaban, the actor and
director.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Next thing we knew, we got a call from Bob saying
Richard Dreyfuss is coming by and he's agreed to do a reading. He
also got some other actors to be the taped voices. For the first
time, we could see there were parts of it that didn't work and
parts of it that were very funny. People were laughing out loud. So
we took out the funny parts and expanded the parts that didn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   LINGEMAN: We took it closer to the Beckett model, which is: Life
is grim.
</P>
<P>
   NAVASKY: Don't give away the ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
