<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-KENNEDY-BOS &LR;      07-27 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBDUED KENNEDY RETURNS TO SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy came to work at noon
Tuesday, hours later than usual. He went to a weekly Democrats'
luncheon in the Capitol looking tired. People around him said he
seemed subdued.
</P>
<P>
   But he was here. Four days after scattering the ashes of his
nephew, John F. Kennedy Jr., into the sea, Kennedy returned to the
office he has held for 37 years and began the familiar process of
readjusting to routine life _ surrounded by the work that has, in
many ways, been the most permanent fixture he has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said he seemed a far cry from the man who two weeks
earlier waged a fierce battle on the Senate floor over managed
health care. Some aides to other senators also privately wondered
whether it might take longer for him to recover this time, whether
there might be a cumulative toll to so much tragedy in one person's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Among senators, however, few were surprised when Kennedy
returned to the Senate chamber Monday night to cast two procedural
votes, with his son, Representative Patrick Kennedy of Rhode
Island, at his side. Tuesday, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle
began the Democratic policy luncheon by welcoming Kennedy back _
``back to his family here in the Senate,'' Daschle later said. Many
agreed that Kennedy has never run from work during tough times.
This time, they said, would be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us would have understood if he wasn't back right
away,'' said Senator Tom Harkin, a Democrat from Iowa, after the
lunch. ``But his coming back is just another indication that he's
not going to dwell on the setbacks in life. He's going to dwell on
what's possible. And that's an inspiration to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had planned on a hectic legislative calendar this year,
with debates on all his pet issues: health care, education and the
minimum wage. Before July 17, when John Kennedy Jr.'s plane was
reported missing, he was on a roll, repeatedly leading the
Democratic rallying cry _ after impeachment, over gun control, over
securing rights for medical patients.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest political victory this year came two weeks ago.
After singlehandedly holding up the Senate for days to force
Majority Leader Trent Lott to debate health care, Kennedy led the
charge with a so-called Patients Bill of Rights, delivering such
rousing speeches that other senators began ribbing him about his
enthusiasm on the floor. Democrats ultimately lost, but it was seen
as a public relations triumph, with Republicans cast as villains
for killing a measure that would help women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the final vote July 15, Kennedy bounded down the
Capitol steps, talking excitedly about his weekend plans to attend
his niece Rory's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, it was on to the next piece of legislation to
expand the definition of a ``hate crime'' to include sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crash occurred the next night, killing the young
Kennedy, his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister, Lauren
Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   All other plans were instantly changed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, after 10 days of horrifying developments and family
tragedy, Kennedy began to ease back into the world of politics. He
was briefed twice by his staff about prescription drug coverage and
attended the Democratic luncheon. He got news about the ongoing
debate over taxes in Congress and made tentative plans to introduce
an amendment _ again, related to prescription drug coverage _ later
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Capitol, his son also went back to
work. Patrick Kennedy attended meetings at the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, which he heads, and cast several
votes. He was ``easing his way back into it,'' spokesman Tony
Marcella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's going to take them awhile to get back into their
full routine,'' Marcella said of both Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   When that will occur remains to be seen, although Senator
Kennedy may speak on the floor of the Senate as early as this week,
addressing measures concerning prescription drug coverage and the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, he began his gradual return to public speaking
with remarks to fellow Democrats. At the luncheon, Senator John F.
Kerry said, Kennedy ``thanked everybody for their expressions of
concern, their telephone calls, and said how much it meant to him
and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Kerry said: ``He expressed his own happiness at being back
in the fold, back in the Senate family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fight is needed, Ted Kennedy will be there without
reserve, because that's the way he is,'' Kerry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
