<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-ART     07-27 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV SOLDIERS NOW FIGHT FOR BACK PAY AND BREAD
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add map note)   (ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LESKOVAC, Yugoslavia _ Vlada sleeps late and often doesn't
bother to shave. He says he has stopped talking in his sleep, but
often finds himself shuddering uncontrollably, staring down at his
trembling body as if it belonged to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   His business as an artisan is suffering, but he is forgiving
people their debts, because he knows they have no money to spare.
``I'm satisfied with small things now,'' he said, licking the paper
on a cheap Drina cigarette, so it would burn longer. ``I want to
make a lot of friends and not argue over anything petty. But if
there's a car accident and there are dead _ I'm utterly
indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   Vlada, 31, was a unit commander of the Yugoslav army in Kosovo.
He hated it, but he's proud that he passed through, and he thinks
he has kept his soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was awful in Kosovo,'' he said. ``It was full of
horrible things. Not on the level of massacres, not that I saw
happening, at least, but there was nothing good. I think of myself
as a form of pacifist, and even going there was horrible enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was ethnic purging, and some of his men helped carry
it out. They held the ground while police and paramilitaries moved
through villages, killing and expelling Albanians, then secured the
villages afterward. They looted freely and burned houses and stood
by while others did the dirtiest work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a war down there, and the main thing was to stay
alive,'' Vlada said. ``Mostly when I arrived the cleansing was
done, and it was done by police and paramilitaries, and it was
awful and stupid. We soldiers are softer, we are not murderers, and
it's an ugly thing to say, but those guys did a job for us, and if
we did it we would have a lot more dead on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his men spent 60 days without water or electricity,
usually sleeping on the floor of an abandoned or cleansed Albanian
house in the hills, moving between Gnjilane and Kacanik. They drank
water from which they removed the tadpoles and dumped in purifying
tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Vlada watched his friends crack up or die or turn into avid
looters or killers. They dug in against NATO bombing, and they
lived with the constant fear of being uniformed soldiers in a
hostile countryside facing a peasant army. It wasn't just the
Kosovo Liberation Army, for whom Vlada has only marginal respect,
but of booby-traps and ambushes and almost any Albanian civilian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dangerous to turn your back, even on an old lady,'' he
said. ``You always had your gun in your hands or within reach.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the story of an Albanian in civilian clothes walking
toward a Serb soldier, who approached him, while two uniformed
Albanian fighters shot from an ambush. ``It was a tactic,'' Vlada
said. ``And the guy who didn't shoot was a fool, and his family is
without him. But if he shot first, then he's a murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   He rubbed his face and licked another Drina.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was mobilized, I went to church and prayed for two
things,'' he said. ``First, not to kill anyone. And second, to come
back alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the first prayer was answered, he said. At least he thinks
so.
</P>
<P>
   But then he tells the story of three members of his unit who
killed three Albanian fighters at close range at the end of the
war. ``Each one thinks he didn't kill someone,'' Vlada said. ``But
those guys had so many bullets in them, each one must have hit them
all.''
</P>
<P>
   He commanded a small unit of 14 or so soldiers who patrolled,
and ``we became very good,'' he said with some pride. ``We
protected each other and we were faithful to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of looting, he said. ``In the beginning, it was
silently licensed by the officers, under the theory, `Take what you
need or want and use it when you're here.' Then people got crazy
and took a lot of things. The first thing stolen from a house was
the television. Our unit sometimes had seven sets, but of course
there was no electricity,'' he said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no way to bring the loot back, except for the
officers, who had access to trucks. So there was a lot of
destruction, too, especially of expensive things like televisions,
video recorders, refrigerators and tractors.
</P>
<P>
   About the expulsion and murder of Albanian citizens, his stories
track with those of others. In general, the army held the ground;
special police units and paramilitary units, sometimes with long
hair, beards and bandanas, like actors in Hollywood movies, cleared
the villages, often killing those who resisted leaving; the
civilians were channeled along certain roads toward buses or the
border; bodies were often cleared out by other police units; and
then the army checked through the villages again.
</P>
<P>
   But there was some army involvement. For these special actions,
``to expel or cleanse or whatever you say,'' Vlada said another
officer would come to collect two men, who would be gone for 48
hours or so.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers mostly kept away from the paramilitaries and
special police units, particularly the legendary ``Frenki's boys,''
named after a former commander of the special antiterrorist units
of the police, Franko Simatovic. They are big, well-equipped,
ruthless and ordered to not even discuss their training.
</P>
<P>
   Vlada described the clearing of Zegra, south of Gnjilane.
``About 260 of them cleaned Zegra in 12 hours, 6,000 to 7,000
people. They took about a minute a house. There was shooting. The
volunteers got to the center of town and started to shoot the first
people to come to them. The whole village heard this and people
started to run away on their own, and there were police to guide
them toward Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they went into the houses, looking for people, and
sometimes Albanian fighters remained and there were firefights.
``Soldiers couldn't do that,'' Vlada insisted. ``It would have
taken us three days to do all the houses. Soldiers couldn't just go
into a house and start shooting all the people in the house right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, sighed, continued. ``It was ugly but it happened,
and everyone you saw felt like an enemy. It's the worst kind of
war. A granny could have a grenade. The first blood demands second
blood, revenge, and so it goes. The KLA had their positions and
their bunkers themselves, and as we were drafted, so were they, and
their orders were to stay and cause trouble, and many of them were
sacrificed.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, he said, some people liked the killing. ``You find
out a lot about people in 24 hours in a war,'' he said. He
described clearing a house in a village where there were elderly
Albanians still inside. One man went in while he and another
soldier kept guard over the house, when another group of Serbs
arrived, pulling out knives and wanting to kill the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my Albanians, and if you want to kill Albanians you
go catch them in some other house,'' Vlada told them. ``But I was
scared. It was stupid. We were yelling and nearly shooting each
other and we were all targets, and if someone was hiding in the
stable he could have killed us all.''
</P>
<P>
   They burned many houses, ``especially the big, rich ones,''
Vlada said. ``If we got in a house where we found KLA insignia, or
uniforms or pictures of men in KLA uniforms with arms, you cannot
stay calm. They are not the only ones guilty for this war, but they
are among them. And a lot were in big houses, with Jacuzzis, and
Albanian flags, when 70 percent of those in Albania don't have
electricity, and you can't be calm. There's rage in you and you ask
yourself, what more does he want than this? There is no sign inside
of this country, but only of another country, and it burns.''
</P>
<P>
   He became mystical about the houses, he said. ``Sometimes, they
won't burn, even with oil. It's like the house protects itself,''
he said. ``Then I thought, `This is the house of honest people,'
and I ordered, `Leave this house alone, you can see it won't
burn.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Serbs thought the Albanians would never be back to
demand an accounting, Vlada sighed. ``People thought there would be
some deal with NATO or a partition of Kosovo or something. They
were stupid. You can't clean out 2 million people or kill 100,000
people, but some thought you could. There were a lot of army and
police, and you had the weapons, and the Albanians were too few and
poor. And without NATO, they could have done nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Life at war was exhilarating and terrifying, full of adrenaline
and sensation, and life afterwards is pallid and full of worries,
especially in a war-broken, sanctions-broken economy where money,
gasoline, sugar and even cooking oil are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Vlada has taken part in the daily demonstrations of army
reservists in Leskovac for their back pay and for the resignation
of President Slobodan Milosevic. His experience is typical of many
of the reservists interviewed, but he was a commander and more
insightful than most. There is fury here, but unfocused, a tinder
box waiting for a leader and a spark. But the daily demonstrations
are dwindling, last only about 15 minutes, and often no one even
speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's apathy,'' Vlada said. ``There are lots of problems to
deal with, daily things like money and bread, and like an animal,
you deal with those things only.''
</P>
<P>
   No one here really wants to hear about the war. There are
already a lot of divorces among his friends, he said. ``People
can't talk about it. Your life is awful and you're trying to
survive that. People ask, `How are you?' The answer now is: `Same
as you,' and everyone's face falls.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, ``people feel like the war was two years ago _
they're trying to cope with current problems, trying to get money,
trying to prepare for the winter,'' canning and storing food, when
they can afford it, or cutting wood.
</P>
<P>
   As for questions of war crimes, ``it's the same as in
Belgrade,'' Vlada said. ``No one wants to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't much matter now, he says. ``Kosovo and its
problems are too far away. It's a luxury to think of Kosovo when I
have such problems here. People are so poor that when they go to
the shops they just write IOU's. It makes you feel guilty, you feel
somehow lost, you lose all the self-confidence that you had when
you were there, in Kosovo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first days after the reservists came home, the police were
absent. Now, with the protests, they cruise around the town, not
just in their little Zastava cars, but big blue four-wheel drive
vehicles with white bars on the windows. Many of them are from
surrounding towns, Vlada says. ``It's good thinking. It's hard to
beat or arrest your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes now, he says, he dreams that he is being arrested, but
he's not sure for what. ``Not for Kosovo, but because of the
protests, or because I owe money for electricity or whatever,'' he
says. ``But it's a horrible feeling of insecurity, and for all the
reservists it's the same.''
</P>
<P>
   They talk to each other; they go fishing. ``This is like the
golden age of fishing,'' he said. ``It's the cheapest form of
entertainment and escape from reality,'' he said. ``Really, a
perfect escape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
