<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY PROBE DISCOUNTS MECHANICAL FAILURE IN KENNEDY CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal investigators picking through the wreckage of the single
engine plane in which John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
sister-in-law died last week, have found no sign of mechanical or
structural problems and no indication of fire on board the
airplane, two highly placed aviation sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators are still months away from pinpointing the
cause of the crash, and one source warned it would ``be premature
and irresponsible'' to say the focus has shifted to determine if
Kennedy, who was at the controls that night, may have committed an
error which sent the plane into the ocean off the coast of Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely unlikely that further scrutiny of the crash
would reveal a mechanical or structural problem in the Piper
Saratoga, one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is being dismantled under National Transportation
Safety Board supervision by Textron Lycoming, the manufacturer, but
the preliminary examination indicates the 300-horsepower engine was
working when the six-passenger plane slammed into the water,
killing Kennedy, his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy and her sister,
Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   However, investigators have not completed a review of the
plane's electrical system or the avionics, which include its
navigational instruments and auto-pilot, one source said. That
review could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, investigators are unwilling to single out pilot
error as the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a novice pilot, was at the controls of a newly
purchased, high-performance airplane in a flight from Fairfield,
N.J., to Martha's Vineyard last Friday, en route to a cousin's
wedding in Hyannis Port the next day.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:39 p.m., about an hour into his flight and less than 20
miles from the Martha's Vineyard airport, Kennedy's plane vanished
from air-traffic control radar screens. After a four-day search,
the wreckage was found about seven miles off the coast of Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a tell-tale sign of mechanical problems _ and the
detailed radar tapes which show the plane twice veered off course
from Martha's Vineyard and then plunged into a steep dive _
indicate that Kennedy most likely became disoriented as the plane
turned, and did not realize the plane was headed down until it was
too late.
</P>
<P>
   When a plane turns, the wings bank and the speed of the air
flowing over the upper wing increases. That imbalance, left
uncorrected, will cause the plane to tilt even more steeply. The
steeper the bank, the less lift there is in the wings, and the
plane begins to descend.
</P>
<P>
   On a dark night, flying over water with haze restricting
visibility, Kennedy may not have been able to see the horizon which
would have indicated to him that the plane was not in level flight.
'
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was licensed as a VFR, or visual flight rules, pilot. As
such, he was trained only to fly by what he could see, and was
grounded when flight visibility was less than three miles or the
cloud ceiling was at 1,000 feet or lower.
</P>
<P>
   But one source bristled at the suggestion that Kennedy used poor
judgment when he decided to fly that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature to state anything about the cause,'' the
source said. ``There have been a lot of reports that he failed to
get a weather update and we know that he called (the Federal
Aviation Administration) at 6:30 and got a weather update and in
that there was nothing that would indicate trouble for a VFR pilot
on takeoff or en route.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his death, Kennedy was attempting to become certified to
fly by instruments only and had passed the written portion of the
examination, but had yet to take the practical examination. In many
countries, VFR pilots are not allowed to fly at night and the US
military trains all its pilots to fly by instruments by the time
they leave flight school.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators, reviewing Kennedy's flying time, have found
he had more than 300 hours in the air, much of that as a student
pilot. ``We are still counting, but it is much more than 100 hours
or so that was in several reports,'' a source said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, FAA officials said Kennedy had just 47 hours of
flying time, but that was an outdated figure listed on a change of
address form and entered into a computer, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy bought the Piper in April, a year after getting his
private pilot's license. According to the previous owner, the
airplane had 575 hours of flying time when Kennedy took possession.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has said at the time of the crash, the plane had 622
hours of flying time, which would indicate that Kennedy had about
48 hours of flying time in the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, television news stations reported that Lauren
Bessette had purchased an electronic ticket for a Continental
Airlines flight leaving from Newark the night of the crash, but she
never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Other television stations have also broadcast the same report,
some of them attributing the information to Continental. Michelle
King, an airline spokeswoman, said she has heard the report but
would not confirm it because passenger records are confidential.
</P>
<P>
   She said the last flight from Newark to Martha's Vineyard the
night of the crash was scheduled to leave at 8:15 p.m. but was
delayed an hour and 40 minutes due to weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As for the TV report, King said, ``I have no idea where they're
getting that from.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cindy Rodriguez of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
