<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5970 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-A     07-27 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS SET DEADLINE FOR ACCEPTING ISRAEL'S CHANGES TO PEACE
AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders Tuesday night set a
two-week deadline to determine if the Palestinians would accept the
new prime minister of Israel's proposal to rewrite the time-frame
and terms of the most recent peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second meeting in 16 days between Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, and Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime minister, and
the tone had changed considerably. The bonhomie of their first
encounter, which was meant to establish rapport, gave way to the
polite hardball of their first real negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking late Tuesday night at the Erez checkpoint in Gaza,
Arafat repeated, almost word-for-word, the demands he had made
after their first meeting. He sounded as if he would in no way
consider Barak's request to delay compliance with some parts of the
most recent agreement, the so-called Wye River memorandum, an
American-brokered land for security deal concluded last fall in Wye
River, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a frank meeting,'' Arafat said. ``I told Prime
Minister Barak that it is very necessary to immediately begin full
implementation of the Wye agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinian leader did agree Tuesday to take 14 days to
consider through lower-level talks if there was something to gain
by doing things Barak's way. Palestinian officials have said it is
difficult for them to see anything in Barak's request but a
reluctance to concede territory.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did make it clear that if the Palestinians rejected his
proposal, he will be prepared to carry out the Wye agreement as
written. ``Any change made to the agreement will be made only by
the consent of both parties,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   As they met behind closed doors at the Erez checkpoint _ a kind
of neutral zone between Israel and Palestinian-controlled Gaza _
Barak outlined his thinking to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak would prefer to transfer the West Bank territory promised
under Wye in a piecemeal fashion as talks get under way for the
outlines of a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Wye agreement troop withdrawal occurs in three phases;
Israeli troops withdrew from the first chunk of land last fall and
Barak is reportedly willing to withdraw from the second in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak has said the third transfer of territory would create
a volatile situation in the West Bank, leaving 15 settlements like
islands _ and sources of friction _ within Palestinian-controlled
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Such friction could lead to bloodshed, which would jeopardize a
successful negotiation of the final peace, Barak has said.
Terrorism would halt the negotiations, he has said. And Tuesday
night, he repeated that thought to the Palestinians, encouraging
them, with a touch of warning, to be what he sees as far-sighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event that we decide not to make these adjustments we
have requested, of course both sides will understand with open eyes
what risks are entailed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said that Barak aspires to start final
status negotiations, which will deal with the thorniest issues,
such as borders, the status of Jerusalem, and refugees, within a
month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak never liked the incremental approach established by the
Oslo peace accords, which set the path for baby steps toward a
final peace by allowing time for trust to be built between the two
sides. He has said he thinks it is backwards to give up land before
discussing the final borders of the Palestinian entity.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is reportedly willing to take some concrete steps, like
releasing Palestinian prisoners, establishing a safe passage route
between Gaza and the West Bank, and allowing the start of
construction on a port in Gaza. He is also reportedly considering
offering more than the Wye agreement demands in certain areas and
making certain critical concessions within the context of the final
status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Haaretz newspaper reported Tuesday that Barak,
during final peace talks, might be willing to discuss transferring
those West Bank settlements that would end up as islands within
Palestinian-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two weeks, Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian
negotiator, and Gilad Schar, an Israeli lawyer and brigadier
general who handled Barak's negotiations to form a coalition
government, will meet to hammer out the issues involved in carrying
out the Wye agreement, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   At Erez Tuesday night, Arafat may have given a signal of what
would be his pre-condition for plunging immediately into final
status talks, before Wye was fully carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked the prime minister to cease all settlement
activities, which are illegal and destructive to the peace process,
so we can resume final status negotiations,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   Since territory is of vital importance to the Palestinians, the
issue of new Jewish settlements staking out acreage in the West
Bank is one of the biggest thorns in their sides.
</P>
<P>
   They were reassured when Israeli army troops dismantled an
illegal settler outpost near Ramallah last week; such actions were
not taken under Benjamin Netanyhau, the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian demands go beyond one-time actions. They want to
see Barak take down other encampments that have cropped up since
the Wye Accord was signed in Maryland last fall, and to suspend
plans to develop the land connecting the largest settlement, Maale
Adumim, to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   These are steps that Barak is unlikely to take in the immediate
future, since they would provoke strong right-wing protest and
upset the political balance within Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat said he had pledged to ``beef up'' security cooperation
with the Israelis and ``within the framework of trilateral
cooperation'' with the Americans and the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are anxious about establishing momentum with
Barak before he gets entangled in restarting negotiations with
Syria. Judging from the messages passing back and forth between
Israel and Syria, through intermediaries like King Abdullah of
Jordan, those talks could get underway very soon.
</P>
<P>
   While Barak has said that he will negotiate on both tracks at
once, the Palestinians fear that they will not get priority.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Barak said, ``I still think that within 15
months, we will know in which of the tracks _ Palestinian, Syrian,
Lebanese _ we will have a break-through and we will move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, seemingly catching himself, he added: ``Without any
preference, any priority to any one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
