u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT &LR;      07-27 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STARTS TO FLY EAGER KOSOVO REFUGEES BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The State Department, having flown more than 10,000 refugees
from Kosovo to the United States, is now offering to fly them back
home _ and is being inundated with requests.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 calls a day have been coming in to a toll-free
number _ (800) 748-4521 _ that was set up to answer questions about
the program, which was announced two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to hire a second Albanian-speaking operator and install
extra telephone lines to roll over into voice mail to handle the
volume,'' said Lauren Engle, a spokeswoman for the International
Organization for Migration, which is managing the return under
contract to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The group has already processed applications from 748 families
to return. At an average of five members for each family, that
would account for more than a third of the refugees here, although
Ms. Engle said many families had eight or nine members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, with the program only two weeks old, it's just
surprising that you would get that many applications,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The desire of the refugees to return to Kosovo echoes the
experience in the camps in Albania and Macedonia when tens of
thousands of refugees a day swept back into Kosovo on the heels of
NATO troops, despite the urging of U.N. relief officials, who
expected them to remain for three weeks or more.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department program brought 10,513 refugees to the
United States from the camps, where they had fled a campaign by
Yugoslav forces to drive them from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The program was intended primarily to relieve pressure on
Macedonia, where the exodus had brought ugly scenes at the border,
with the police clubbing refugees back or holding them in rough
encampments. Macedonia, poor itself, was ill-equipped to handle the
refugees, and some authorities feared they would join the Albanian
minority there to destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
   The usual policy of the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees is to try to keep refugees close to the border in order to
speed their eventual return.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation in Macedonia deteriorated so quickly that by
April 6, not quite two weeks after the outward flood began, 29
other countries were enlisted to take in refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The first flight to the United States, where the refugees were
processed through the old army base at Fort Dix, N.J., was on May
5.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. commission met in Geneva, Switzerland, this month with
representatives of the 29 countries to discuss the return. The new
American policy was announced shortly after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The first return chartered flight, with 289 people aboard, left
New York Monday. After landing in Skopje, the Macedonian capital,
the refugees went by bus to Pristina, Kosovo. Most are expected to
stay in Pristina, the provincial capital, but some are to be sent
to home towns in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   When the refugees were first brought here, each family had to
promise to pay eventually for the voyage, at an average cost of
$3,000. If a family returns to Kosovo by May 1, 2000, this debt
will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   There are still some refugees being flown to the United States
under the original program, the State Department said, mostly
vulnerable cases like people with medical problems or elderly
people without immediate family support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
