<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAUGHT-LAWNS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NUTS &AMP; BOLTS: Wake up your lawn with cool drink of water
</P>
<P>
   By James Cummings
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Lawns tend to go dormant through the hottest part
of the summer, so your yard is probably showing lots of brown spots
unless you have been regularly watering.
</P>
<P>
   When grass plants become stressed _ through cold, lack of sun or
dryness _ their strategy is to go dormant. The blades above ground
turn brown and shrivel while the roots stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Watering your grass avoids the lawn's normal midsummer dormancy
period and keeps it green until cooler, wetter weather arrives in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In periods of average rainfall, like we're in now, you probably
should be watering the lawn every seven to 10 days. But when it's
hot and dry, you may need to water twice as often. Grass dries out
fastest when temperatures are high, relative humidity is low and a
gentle breeze is blowing.
</P>
<P>
   A light watering may be worse than no watering at all because it
can distort the roots of the grass plants. Apply enough water to
wet the ground to a depth of six to eight inches. If you have the
thick clay soil most common in this area, that will take up to an
inch of water. Sandy soils take less water, but must be watered
more often.
</P>
<P>
   Place a few open containers around the yard under the sprinkler.
Monitor the containers to see how long it takes to accumulate an
inch of water. The day after watering, dig a hole or drill a soil
core and check to see how far the water you applied has penetrated.
If the penetration is less than six inches, run the sprinkler
longer the next time.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to water the lawn is early in the morning,
preferably just before the sun comes up. That way the lawn gets a
good soaking, but when the sun rises it quickly burns off the
excess surface water.
</P>
<P>
   You can also water in the evenings if mornings are inconvenient.
Avoid watering during the hot afternoon hours when much of the
water you sprinkle will evaporate. And don't water after dark;
leaving moisture in the grass plants overnight promotes fungal
growth.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to have an automatically timed sprinkler
system, 5 or 6 a.m. is a good time to start.
</P>
<P>
   Manual sprinklers come in two types: oscillating sprinklers that
spray in a fan pattern over a rectangular area, and pulsating or
impact sprinklers that spray a stream over a circular or
wedge-shaped area.
</P>
<P>
   Oscillating sprinklers cost from about $5 to $45 and generally
do an adequate job. But some experts say impact sprinklers provide
more even coverage more quickly. They cost $5 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   The International Society of Arboriculture, an association of
tree-care professionals, said inadequate water supply is usually
the major reason a tree fails to grow to its greatest potential.
</P>
<P>
   The group says leafy trees and shrubs may be suffering from
water deprivation if they show wilting leaves, green leaves that
fall off the trees in drought periods, and leaves that turn brown
or yellow or develop scorched-looking edges.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of water may damage the tree directly or it may weaken the
tree, making it more vulnerable to insects and diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Established trees and woody shrubs may need a good soaking about
once a week if the weather has been hot and dry, though they
usually can withstand the heat if they've gotten adequate rainfall.
Trees planted last fall or more recently may need to be watered
twice a week during dry spells.
</P>
<P>
   It's important not to overwater because excessive water keeps
roots from getting the air they need. If you're not sure if it's
time to water, turn a spadeful of soil to check for moisture a
couple of inches down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the factors determining how often you should water is the
soil around the tree. Clay soil in a depression will hold water
much longer than sandy soil on a hilltop, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Trees and shrubs aren't watered the same way grass is watered.
Grass is watered in a wide pattern with fine spray; the soil around
trees should be soaked, but the foliage should be kept dry.
</P>
<P>
   The best tool for watering trees is a soaker hose. A soaker hose
is porous, and when it is placed on the ground and attached to a
water supply, the water oozes steadily through the body of the
hose, delivering the water to the soil exactly where you want it.
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary garden hose also can be used to water trees. Place
the hose on the ground and turn on a gentle flow. Move the hose
often to spread the water around the tree or shrub's boundary. You
should water out as far as the tree's foliage extends because a
tree's root system usually is the same size as the tree's crown.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the best time of day to water is early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Have an idea, question or concern? Contact James Cummings by
E-mail: jamescummings(AT)coxohio.com, or write to the Features
Department, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio
45402.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
