<HEADER>
A5983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX     07-27 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' drive for NFC repeat begins in S.C.
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ With all but one player showing up today for
Thursday's start of training camp, Falcons coach Dan Reeves and his
staff face a different kind of pressure this year.
</P>
<P>
   They lost a softball game to members of the media on the eve of
last year's camp at Suwanee, and Reeves was crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, every man has his superstitions, and he's wondering
if perhaps the one-run loss was a good thing. The staff whipped the
media the previous season, but the Falcons went 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   After Reeves turned in six erratic innings on the mound last
year, the Falcons went 16-3, setting a slew of franchise records
before hitting Denver's windshield with a splat in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take losing (the softball game) again if it means we turn
around and have a season something like last year,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   And so the softball game at 1 p.m. today at Furman University
will end the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' drive to repeat as NFC champions then begins in
earnest. More than the site of the training camp has changed.
``Last year our goal was to make the playoffs,'' Reeves said.
``This year, it is to defend the (NFC West) title. If you start
thinking about getting back to the Super Bowl, you kind of
overshoot things.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson will be the missing player
as he begins a holdout while contract extension talks continue.
</P>
<P>
   But Pro Bowl cornerback Ray Buchanan, who talked by phone with
Anderson a few days ago, said when practice begins at 3 p.m.
Thursday, everybody will be focused nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anderson) . . . wanted to find out how thing were going with
the team,'' Buchanan said. ``I told him, `We're rooting for you to
get it done, but we can't wait for you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more fun for the rest of us (to show up for camp) when
we're trying to hold our ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will practice twice Friday and may practice twice
Saturday, too, as they build toward an Aug. 8 scrimmage against
Jacksonville at Furman, and an Aug. 13 exhibition game against
Detroit in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a few questions in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Will right guard Gene Williams keep his job? Will the team make
a move to youth and install second-year man Bob Hallen?
</P>
<P>
   At left guard, can Calvin Collins hold off newly acquired Greg
Bishop? Will Bishop move to the right side?
</P>
<P>
   On defense, who will start at the corner opposite Buchanan,
Ronnie Bradford, or Michael Booker? And is it possible Bradford
will change positions and displace Pro Bowl free safety Eugene
Robinson?
</P>
<P>
   The team also may seek a proven deep threat at wide receiver to
replace Tony Martin, who was waived in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Today's first question: Will coaches tank the softball game?
Then the questions get serious.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
