A5985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARAK-ARAFAT-HNS &LR;      07-27 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARAK-ARAFAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT TO CONSIDER ISRAELI DELAY OF LAND TRANSFERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israelis and Palestinians got down to hard
bargaining Tuesday with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
reluctantly promising to consider an Israeli plea to delay land
transfers in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-hour meeting at a crossing separating Israel from
the Gaza Strip, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said he expects
Arafat to give an answer within two weeks. In essence, the Israelis
want the Palestinians to agree to delay land transfers called for
by the Wye River agreement until a comprehensive peace deal is
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's willingness to consider Barak's suggestion was widely
seen as the beginning of a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that by postponing the handover of some West Bank
land to the Palestinians, Barak hopes to avoid a confrontation with
Jewish settlers and with members of the pro-settlement parties
belonging to his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   However, Arafat maintained in public that Israel should
implement the agreement ``accurately'' and ``immediately.``
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said that he is committed to the Wye River accord,
under which Israel pledged to give the Palestinians 13 percent of
the West Bank in stages. He said Tuesday that if, after two weeks,
Arafat still refuses to go along with a delay, Israel would
implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to Wye,'' the prime minister said. ``Any
changes to the agreement will be made only by the consent of both
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Wye land transfers are implemented, about 15 West Bank
settlements will become isolated islands in a sea of
Palestinian-ruled territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Barak) thinks that the internal upheaval that may be caused
by these isolated settlements is not worth the progress in the
peace process,'' said Chemi Shalev, a political commentator for the
daily newspaper Maariv.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to tell Arafat, `Why should we create a dangerous
situation which begs violence?''' Shalev said. ``Then, if we don't
reach an agreement by a certain date, we'll carry out the Wye
accords.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians have reacted with suspicion since Barak began
talking about postponing land transfers when he entered office
three weeks ago. They say his appeal amounts to an attempt to keep
the land and use it as a future bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Israeli suggestion is making the Palestinian leaders
nervous,'' said Palestinian analyst Ghassan Khatib, who directs a
Jerusalem-based media center. ``It signals a lack of commitment to
signed agreements, which was their main problem with the previous
prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalev and other Israeli analysts said they expected Barak to
allay these Palestinian concerns by offering them a series of
gestures as an indication of goodwill, including the quick handover
of around 5 percent of what one analyst termed ``quality''
territory now.
</P>
<P>
   The ``quality'' territory would apparently include swaths of
land in the northern West Bank contiguous to areas already under
Palestinian control rather than territory in the Judean Desert in
the southern West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Wye accords, 3 percent of the desert land near the
southern town of Hebron was to come under Palestinian rule but
remain an undeveloped ``nature reserve.``
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the proposal, these analysts predicted that Barak
would offer to release Palestinian prisoners, open a long-awaited
``safe passage'' that would let them to travel freely between the
West Bank and Gaza, and allow initial work to begin on a deep-water
seaport in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The port and the safe passage route are particularly important
to Arafat because both would provide a much-needed lift to the
Palestinian economy. The economy has been hit hard by Israeli
restrictions that, among other things, prevent Palestinians from
easily crossing from Gaza to jobs in Israel. The restrictions were
imposed as part of an Israeli drive to increase security.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say the expect the Israelis to implement all the
gestures, as well as the land transfers, because past agreements
call for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely Arafat will be happy to see these parts of the
agreement to be implemented,'' said Khatib. ``But he also expects
the other parts to be implemented, including the redeployments.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most analysts predict Arafat would ultimately find a way
to accommodate the Israeli request. President Clinton, eager to see
negotiations revived, has asked the Palestinian leader to consider
Barak's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's last meeting with Arafat on July 11 was marked by a show
of warmth on both sides. After those talks, Barak and Arafat
praised one another's leadership and promised to work together for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the atmosphere of Tuesday's meeting was noticeably
cooler, but it was still warmer than the meetings of Barak's
predecessor, hard-liner Benjamin Netanyahu, had with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu fulfilled the first phase of Wye, a withdrawal from 2
percent of the West Bank, but suspended the pact in December,
charging that the Palestinians had reneged on their security
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli analysts said the Palestinians are trying to win Barak's
goodwill at this early stage. The Palestinians are mindful that an
Israeli breakthrough in parallel negotiations with Syria over the
Golan Heights could undercut their negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians have to make sure they are not being
cheated,'' said one Israeli analyst. ``On the other hand, they have
a very great interest in securing the good will of Barak. They have
to chart their course between these two necessities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
