<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEREAU-FILMS-ART-2TA     07-27 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEREAU-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A METAPHOR FOR LIFE IN A TRIP TO A FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Patrice Chereau is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 Leslie Camhi's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the Belgian director Patrice Toye.  
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part enfant terrible and part national treasure, Patrice Chereau
has built a formidable reputation in France, with three decades of
groundbreaking work in theater, opera and, increasingly, film. His
latest movie, ``Those Who Love Me Can Take the Train,'' had just
had its premiere at the Cannes International Film Festival last
year when Chereau went out to buy a book in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clerk asked what my plans were,'' Chereau recalls. ``I
told her I was preparing another film. `No more theater?' she said.
`What a pity.' Well, her comment ruined my day.''
</P>
<P>
   That momentary disappointment is unlikely to stop Chereau, who
has a long habit of confounding expectations. His iconoclastic
interpretation of Wagner's ``Ring'' cycle, set at the dawn of the
industrial era rather than in a remote Teutonic past, was greeted
with howls when it opened at the Bayreuth Festival in 1976; now it
is hailed as a landmark production.
</P>
<P>
   The Theatre des Amandiers, an experimental theater lab and drama
school he ran for much of the following decade, made the Parisian
suburb of Nanterre an international destination.
</P>
<P>
   His interpretation of ``In the Loneliness of the Cotton Fields''
_ a play for two characters by the French author Bernard-Marie
Koltes, which Chereau performed in and directed at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music in 1996 _ combined a singular dramatic intensity
with Proust's sense of language, Beckett's existential anguish and
the harsh passion of Jean Genet.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 53, Chereau has decided to devote himself to film, a
medium in which he still feels like a beginner, even with seven
titles to his credit. These include ``L'Homme Blesse'' (``The
Wounded Man,'' 1983), about an adolescent's homosexual awakening in
the sordid underbelly of a provincial train station, and ``Queen
Margot,'' a lavish 1994 production, starring Isabelle Adjani and
based on the Alexandre Dumas novel about a 16th-century French
royal family, a story rife with incest, deception, massacres and
poisonings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Who Love Me Can Take the Train,'' which opens Wednesday,
also focuses on a nasty bit of Parisian infighting _ this time,
though, in the milieu of a demanding gay painter, Jean-Baptiste
(Jean-Louis Trintignant), who has just died. The film measures his
effect on a series of characters _ relatives and hangers-on,
colleagues and ex-students, current and former lovers, their wives
and children _ who come together for a four-hour train ride from
Paris to Limoges, where Jean-Baptiste will be buried.
</P>
<P>
   It's an extended meditation on paternity in its many forms,
biological and spiritual, on mourning and survival. Yet it's full
of life's vital agitation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the script came from Daniele Thompson, a co-writer
for both ``Queen Margot'' and ``Those Who Love Me,'' who attended
the provincial funeral of a Parisian friend three years ago. The
dying man had asked to be buried in Limoges, the city of his birth.
When friends objected to the city's distance from the capital, he
responded with the phrase that forms the film's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very prideful thing to say,'' Chereau said by
telephone from Corsica where he was vacationing before traveling to
New York for the film's opening. ``Because it means, if you love
me, you can very well sacrifice a day of your life to accompany my
body. And it also means, we'll see that day who's on the train and
who isn't. I suppose we all wonder what the day we're buried will
be like. But it's an error of vanity to think you can control it in
any way. You can't direct your own funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to draw parallels between the charismatic
director and the imperious figure of Jean-Baptiste, the deceased
artist. Chereau says that character was modeled partly on his own
father, a painter named Jean-Baptiste.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, bits of Chereau's experience are reflected in the
various characters arriving at the Austerlitz train station early
one morning: in the love triangle that develops brusquely between
Francois, an art critic (Pascal Greggory), his boyfriend Louis
(Bruno Todeschini) and Bruno, a young boy (Sylvain Jacques); in the
haggard disputes between Jean-Marie (Charles Berling), the dead
man's nephew, and Claire, his estranged wife (Valeria
Bruni-Tedeschi); in the elderly colleagues, and the little girl who
glimpses her father driving a station wagon carrying the corpse
along a road that parallels the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these people, with their problems and bad moods, running
late, in a hurry, arguing, they push themselves onto the train, the
door closes, and it's like putting them in a pot to cook for four
hours,'' Chereau explains with amusement. ``It can only explode.''
</P>
<P>
   The train comes to a stop at Limoges, a city of 140,000
inhabitants, where 185,000 lie buried in a vast cemetery. The
sudden sight of this sea of graves is a visceral reminder that the
journey's fights, gossip, longings and confusion are the stuff of
life.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion of influences, Chereau cites sources as diverse
as ``King Lear'' and Lawrence Kasdan's 1983 film, ``The Big
Chill.'' Mostly, though, his film was informed by his own knowledge
of funerals.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes an interment is like an incredible jolt of
electricity,'' he said. ``The pain at the cemetery is terrible. But
bizarrely enough, I've sometimes seen an explosion of vitality and
energy an hour or two later. People drink, eat, begin to laugh.
Afterwards the pain returns. But life asserts itself. It's a kind
of animal reaction, very deep and strong, to tell yourself, now
life is before you, and you mustn't ruin it.''
</P>
<P>
   His film also is about a teacher's legacy. Like Jean-Baptiste,
Chereau has helped form a generation of students, several of whom
appear in ``Those Who Love Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a tuning fork, he sounded the true note, against which I
measure the rest of my career,'' said Ms. Bruni-Tedeschi, a rising
star in French and Italian film, who studied acting at the Theatre
des Amandiers more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like to work with Chereau? ``He's a pusher, he takes
you places where you wouldn't normally go,'' said the actor Vincent
Perez. In ``Those Who Love Me,'' Perez plays Viviane, a
transsexual, a role that is a radical departure for a young French
star more often cast as the dashing lead in historical romances
like ``Cyrano'' and ``Queen Margot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chereau _ who has played Napoleon (in Youssef Chahine's
``Adieu, Bonaparte''), the French revolutionary Camille Desmoulins
(in Andrzej Wajda's ``Danton'') and the legendary Resistance leader
Jean Moulin (in Claude Berri's new wartime drama, ``Lucie Aubrac,''
which opens Aug. 20) _ doesn't see himself as a commanding
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrive in the morning,'' Chereau said, ``I look at the
set, I listen to the actors, and I know immediately what I
(italics)don't(end italics) want. But I don't necessarily know what
I (italics)want.(end italics) When you're young, you have a certain
vision that you want to impose. I've learned to search for
something unexpected, and closer to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Years of work in opera have helped to shape his sense of
cinematic rhythm. ``Film is an entirely musical experience,'' he
said. ``In editing, you count time, you establish a partition and
different rhythms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the camera allows viewers a physical proximity and intimacy
with actors that is impossible to achieve on the stage. ``I've made
a lot of films in my life,'' he noted, ``that no one has seen but
myself _ during theatrical rehearsals, when I'm very close to the
actors, and I watch emotions flit across their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Chereau wants to use movie-making to compose a portrait of
contemporary reality. ``I want my work to pose questions about how
people live today,'' he said. ``Is it normal that they live that
way? Why do they get along so badly?''
</P>
<P>
   This last question should resonate deeply in Chereau's next
project, a film adaptation of ``Intimacy,'' Hanif Kureishi's
shattering novel about the end of a relationship, which provoked a
storm of controversy in England last year, appearing just after the
writer's own bitter breakup with a longtime girlfriend. Kureishi is
collaborating on the screenplay, which also draws upon a story from
his collection, ``Love in a Blue Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be about a man who finds himself alone, and has
difficulty forming relationships, and falls in love with a woman
whom he doesn't really know, and who doesn't really speak to him,''
Kureishi said on the telephone from London. ``And they try to have
a relationship without feeling or emotional contact.''
</P>
<P>
   If that description recalls the bleak universe of Chereau's late
collaborator, the French playwright Bernard-Marie Koltes, a world
of dark passion and few characters, don't be too certain. It's just
the next step in an artistic career marked by relentless forward
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always moving toward the things I don't know how to do,''
Chereau said. ``I like the fact that in film I have the feeling
that my major work is still before me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
