<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BURG-ART-NYT &LR;      07-27 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BURG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEAD OF ISRAEL'S PARLIAMENT MAKES HIS PRESENCE KNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (With ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS) 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Burg is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ First, there were the new rules of decorum that
Avraham Burg, the new speaker, instantly imposed on the Israeli
parliament in an effort to tame the unruly body.
</P>
<P>
   No smoking. No cell phones. No sexual harassment. No turning
one's backside to the dais.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members will not stand with their behinds facing the
speakers,'' Burg decreed, proceeding to quote from the Bible.
``Only of God does it say, `And you saw my backside and not my
face.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the tongue-lashings that Burg meted out to
government ministers who, acting as everybody always has, failed to
show up promptly to answer parliamentary questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ministers won't respect the parliament, the parliament
won't respect the ministers,'' Burg said, denying them the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there were the publicity stunts and
attention-grabbing political events _ like the ground-breaking
meeting in parliament on Monday with Ahmed Qurei, a senior
Palestinian official. These have secured Burg daily coverage in
Israeli newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   All told, it added up to an unusually high-profile start for
Israel's new parliamentary leader. But Burg is fashioning himself
as a sort of super-speaker who intends not only to remake the image
of the rowdy, fractious parliament but also to use his podium as a
personal and political platform.
</P>
<P>
   Burg took office in defiance of Ehud Barak, the new prime
minister, who sought unsuccessfully to block his election. And
Burg, a top-ranking member of Barak's own Labor/One Israel party,
is wasting no time in his effort to assert himself as a political
counterbalance to the prime minister's inclination to concentrate
power in his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address early this month, Burg pointedly stated
that ``the consensus of the majority is better than the tyranny of
the individual.'' Later, he somewhat disingenuously said he was
making a philosophical point, which was misunderstood as a personal
challenge to the prime minister. But Burg, who had been openly
angry that he was denied a Cabinet position, was well aware of the
message he had communicated.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Barak said they would be able to work together, and
called Burg's election ``a victory for democracy and for the Labor
movement.'' Burg said that he, too, would like to develop a working
relationship with the prime minister, perhaps by using mutual
associates as buffers. But he also noted that there were ``built-in
conflicts between the heads of two branches neither of whom are
weak personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and voluble, Burg, who is 44 and the father of six
(including two adopted children whose parents were killed in an
accident), is an interesting mix of many strains in Israeli
society.
</P>
<P>
   He is the child of both a Holocaust survivor and a survivor of
the 1929 Arab massacre of Jews in Hebron, where his grandfather was
chief rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   He is a political prince, the son of Yosef Burg, now 90, who
served in parliament for 40 years and retired as the head of the
National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the bosom of the religious Zionist movement, which
represents the West Bank settlers, he is nonetheless a very liberal
Orthodox Jew and an ardent dove. After the Israeli invasion of
Lebanon in 1982, he got his political start as a leftist activist
in the Peace Now movement, gathering thousands of signatures to
demand the resignation of Ariel Sharon, then the defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration in 1983, he was lightly wounded when a hand
grenade was tossed into the crowd by a right-wing extremist,
killing a student beside him. As ``a witness to political murder,''
in his words, the experience opened his eyes to the dangers of
internal rifts in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Burg was first elected to parliament in 1988 and stepped out of
politics for several years to run the Jewish Agency. Among the
membership of the Labor Party, he has always been popular, one of
the top vote-getters in party primaries. In 1992, he placed third,
and this year, after returning to politics, he placed fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But some Labor Party leaders have found him to be too
self-assured, too independent, self-righteous, and, as Yitzhak
Rabin, the late prime minister, once said, ``an undermining
puppy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Burg did not come across as lacking in
self-confidence. He sat at the head of a very long conference table
in the speaker's expansive office, which is much more open than the
prime minister's bunker-like office, with sweeping views of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Burg referred to his ``massive political support,'' and asserted
that as a ``free-thinker,'' he is a threat to the political
establishment that likes to conduct business in ``smoke-filled
rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can communicate individually with every Israeli,'' said
Burg, who is a good public speaker. ``That is a very powerful and
threatening tool. Also, I am never willing to compromise my inner
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, political associates and analysts have
wondered whether Burg was serious or superficial, a loose cannon or
a determined advocate of change.
</P>
<P>
   In his few weeks as speaker, he has alternated moves seemingly
designated to call attention to himself with political gestures
that delivered strong messages about civil rights, peace and the
democratic balance of powers.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Burg sent out a beeper message alerting
photographers to the time of his morning jog and invited them also
to capture him having his blood pressure taken during a
parliamentary health day. (He was declared the fittest among the 60
members of parliament and 140 parliament employees who took part.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other, he ordered all signs in parliament to be made
bilingual in Hebrew and Arabic. And he invited Qurei to visit, and
extended an invitation to Syrian President Hafez al-Assad as well.
</P>
<P>
   His new rules of order for parliament, while mocked by some, are
appreciated by those who agree with his assessment that he
inherited an institution whose authority has been eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My responsibility is to upgrade the Knesset again,'' he said,
using the Hebrew term for parliament. ``First, I have to
fanatically defend its independence. It's unhealthy that, with the
expanded government Barak is making, 30 percent of the members of
the Knesset will be ministers or deputy ministers. What is the
executive and what is the legislative?''
</P>
<P>
   With 15 parties represented in parliament, Burg anticipates that
the level of discord could be higher than ever, especially with big
decisions on peace and social issues looming ahead and forcing the
question of what kind of a state the Jewish homeland wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very vivid democracy, but it's very fragile, partly
because of our inner conflict,'' he said. ``What is the real
authority, the Knesset or the Bet Knesset, the synagogue? Are we a
democracy or a theocracy?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
