<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOROCCO-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGISH ECONOMY PRESENTS BIGGEST CHALLENGE FOR MOROCCO'S NEW
KING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASABLANCA, Morocco _ In the crowded cobbled alleyways of the
old souk, the young men loitering in doorways and old women selling
tattered wares say they know exactly what they want from Morocco's
new king.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem now is jobs,'' said Hussein Khadoe, 28, who like
many desperate young Moroccans spent years in Europe as an illegal
immigrant and is back home trying to make a living any way he can.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 percent of Moroccans are out of work, even by the
most conservative estimates. About half are illiterate, one of the
highest rates in the region. And a huge debt burden has left the
government with little money to create jobs or provide a social
safety net.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that with the regal pomp and the show of
international support that surrounded the funeral on Sunday for
King Hassan II, the new ruler, King Mohammed VI, was already trying
to convert the good will into more tangible dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Abderrahmane Youssoufi was quoted in Moroccan
newspapers as saying that he had discussed with President Clinton
and others ``the support that Morocco expects from foreign
partners, especially the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Moroccan officials hope that Jordan will provide a model. The
accession there in February of King Abdullah, an untested
37-year-old, has been followed by increases in Western aid and by
warmer relations with neighbors, to help him fend off the
discontent that might spill over into regional instability.
</P>
<P>
   In Morocco, the most surprising helping hand has come from
neighboring Algeria, a longtime rival with which Morocco has long
had border disputes. Among the guests at Hassan's funeral was the
new president, Abdelaziz Bouteflika, the first Algerian leader to
visit here in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bouteflika signaled that he was prepared to reopen the border,
which was shut in 1994, at a cost to Morocco that economists here
estimates at $2 billion a year in lost trade. In a letter to
Mohammed made public here, the Algerian said he was strongly
committed to move ``hand in hand with your majesty for the
prosperity of our two people.''
</P>
<P>
   It is less clear, however, Western diplomats here said, that the
United States and its allies are ready to welcome Mohammed with a
new influx of aid. For one factor, Morocco is more than 2,000 miles
removed from the epicenter of Arab-Israeli struggles. Despite its
important role in the past as a broker of a wider peace, it is seen
in the West as a less important strategic partner than Jordan, more
than half of whose population is Palestinian and which borders
Israel, Syria, Saudi Arabia and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   For another factor, diplomats said, the priority that Morocco
has placed on internal security over economic development may mean
that real obstacles stand in the way of improving its economy. For
now, the second most-powerful man in Morocco, after the king, is
widely said to be Driss Basri, the long-serving interior minister,
and many people doubt that Mohammed would be ready to move him
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Basri is a palace hard-liner who has been accused of widespread
abuses in his 20 years in power. He is widely believed to oppose
further moves toward the democratization that Hassan began
tentatively to embrace in 1986 and that is still sought by the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Without outside help or major internal changes, however,
economists here say Morocco has little room to maneuver. Some 85
percent of government outlays cover salaries and payments on a
foreign debt of $20 billion, among the highest for any Arab
country.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of economic growth, which hit an impressive 6.2 percent
in 1998, is expected to slow to a trickle this year because of a
severe drought. And foreign investment, which hit a record $1.2
billion in 1997, shrank last year to less than half that, in large
part because of investors' doubts about the government's commitment
to a further opening of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Youssoufi, a Socialist who was elected 18 months ago, is
technically in charge of economic policy. But the king has
overarching authority, with the power to dismiss ministers and even
the government. Most people here say if economic conditions are to
improve, the change will have to come from the top.
</P>
<P>
   In Casablanca, the commercial capital, Hassan's most visible
legacy may be the enormous mosque that bears his name. The gleaming
structure that towers over the old city at the edge of the Atlantic
was built in 1990 from $500 million in public contributions.
</P>
<P>
   But the shabby back streets are just as dominant a feature of
this city, like the one where Khadoe practices his trade, usually
by collecting commissions from the small shops to which he tries to
guide the few foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Khadoe said, is in jail, for selling hashish.
Khadoe did that himself for three years that he was illegally in
France, until the police caught him.
</P>
<P>
   Youssoufi was, perhaps, referring to people like Khadoe when he
said, over the weekend, ``We achieved positive results in favor of
our people, but there are still economic and social issues to be
solved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
