<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-BELT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAN WINS $10.2 MILLION IN `ROCKET BELT' TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A judge Tuesday awarded $10.2 million to a Houston man
who claims three others conspired to steal a ``rocket belt'' he
helped develop that could hold one person aloft for about 27
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved this phase is over. Hopefully this judgment will
help produce the rocket belt,'' said Thomas L. Stanley, who filed
the suit in 1995 against the three others.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge John Wooldridge also ordered that the
rocket-powered backpack, which has been missing since 1994, be
returned to Stanley. The amount awarded by the judge was more than
three times greater than the $3 million Stanley had asked for.
</P>
<P>
   Wooldridge said just before announcing his judgment that the
two-day trial contained ``evidence of greed, craft, intrigue,
mystery and murder, elements of a cheap novel found on the best
seller's list.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one defendant, attorney Jonette Anderson, showed up for the
trial. Stanley, 54, believes that one of the defendants, Bradley W.
Barker, 44, killed another defendant, Joe Wright, 37, last summer
because Wright had agreed to testify that Stanley's rights to the
machine were improperly taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County sheriff's officials have said Barker is a suspect,
along with another person, who was not identified. Barker filed a
complaint against Harris County sheriff's officials after they
detained him for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Barker insists he is innocent and has phone records proving he
was in Arkansas at the time. He also says he does not know where
the machine is.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was accused of helping draft a phony lien that
transferred ownership of the rocket belt from a company that
Stanley and Barker had formed to a company created by Wright and
Barker.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's attorney, Michael Von Blon, said all the defendants
will share the damages equally. He said is it unclear how much can
be recovered because Anderson claims to have no assets and Barker's
whereabouts are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Wooldridge awarded $7.5 million for loss of income from the
rocket belt and $2.5 million in punitive damages. The rest was
attorneys' fees and and for a beating that Stanley says Barker gave
him in 1994 with a ball peen hammer after they argued over
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley hooked up with Barker in the early 1990s to develop a
rocket-powered backpack that could keep a person airborne for about
27 seconds, or three seconds longer than similar devices.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket belt, a contraption strapped on like a backpack, is
similar to the one used in the 1965 James Bond movie
``Thunderball.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley and Barker built the machine, called the RB2000, at a
car audio shop owned by Barker's friend, Joe Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The device was last flown publicly at a summer 1995 rally
honoring the Houston Rockets, who were at the time playing for the
NBA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, a few weeks before the case was initially set to go
to trial, Wright agreed to contact Barker and try to find out where
the belt was, according to Wright's former attorney, Ronald Bass.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the body of Wright, 37, was found in his home.
He had been bludgeoned to death.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley testified Monday that other operational rocket belts
typically earn $25,000 per flight, plus expenses. The machines are
powered by hydrogen peroxide and nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   He said there are few such devices in the world that are
operational and that they are difficult to make.
</P>
<P>
   The first rocket belt was developed in the early 1960s by
Wendell Moore, an engineer at Bell Aircraft in Buffalo, N.Y. Built
for the Department of Defense, its 20-second flight duration was
deemed impractical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
