<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-RUSSIA28-COX     07-27 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RUSSIA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., RUSSIA SET NEW TALKS ON REDUCING NUCLEAR ARMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Russia agreed Tuesday to
negotiate further reductions in their nuclear arsenals and to
discuss possible U.S. deployment of a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The joint announcement at the White House by Vice President Al
Gore and Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin of Russia followed private
meetings in which the two leaders discussed economic reforms as
well as arms control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement builds on the recent agreement by President
Clinton and Russia's President Boris Yeltsin to begin talks next
month on a new strategic arms reduction treaty (START III) and on
changes to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to allow
U.S. deployment of a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States and Russia have long understood that
reducing nuclear arsenals is in our mutual interest,'' Gore said in
a statement. ``That is why we will continue to press for
ratification of START II and will begin discussions next month
toward START III.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement referred to a longtime roadblock in the two
nations' arms control talks.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 Start II treaty, the United States and Russia agreed
to cut their nuclear arsenals to a maximum of 3,500 warheads by
2003. The U.S. Senate ratified the treaty, but it has languished in
the Russian parliament, and recent strains between the two
countries over the Kosovo conflict are slowing its consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin said the Russian government ``will try to bring Start
II to the Duma (the lower house of Russia's parliament) again in
the fall of this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the two countries will begin discussions on a Start
III treaty in Moscow to reduce the arsenals to as low as 2,000
warheads on each side.
</P>
<P>
   The new talks will also focus on changes the United States wants
in the ABM Treaty that would enable the development of a national
missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is on record as endorsing a defensive shield against
limited missile attack, even though one has not been shown to be
technically feasible. Russia, however, is concerned that such a
system would leave it vulnerable in a nuclear exchange between the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
   While the anticipated arms control measures are considered
relatively modest, the announcement allowed Gore to showcase his
foreign policy credentials and draw a sharp contrast to Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, widely viewed as his chief rival for the
presidency next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a card, a decent card, and Gore ought to play it _ even
though it rarely trumps other cards in a presidential campaign,''
said Charles Cook, editor of the Cook Political Report, an
influential political newsletter in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also briefly silenced Jim Nicholson, chairman
of the Republican National Committee, who earlier in the day used
Gore's appearances with Stepashin to accuse the Clinton
administration of being ``irresponsible and immoral'' in not
pushing harder for a national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``For six years, the Clinton-Gore administration's policy has
been to deliberately leave America vulnerable to a missile attack
by a rogue dictator or a nuclear terrorist,'' Nicholson said in a
statement issued Tuesday morning. He declined comment Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a nuclear arms expert during his congressional career, has
been the Clinton administration's point man in efforts by the White
House to shrink Russia's arsenal of long-range nuclear weapons, the
product of the lengthy Cold War between the United States and what
used to be called the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this new era, strong U.S.-Russian ties will be an essential
component of American national security and global stability,''
said Gore, co-chair of the U.S.-Russian Joint Commission, a panel
created in 1993 to promote nuclear reductions, democracy and a
market economy in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are entering the 21st century _ we have to enter it as
friends,'' said Stepashin, the commission's other co-chair.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
