<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-MARKETPLACE-AR     07-27 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MARKETPLACE-ART-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON STRATEGIES FOR STOCK MARKET WINNINGS MAY BE FALTERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, individual investors in the stock market
have become rich by sticking to a couple of relatively simple
strategies: investing in big-name companies whose products they
know or use and piling into stocks that have already been big
winners.
</P>
<P>
   But no investment trend lasts forever. And recently, these
strategies appear to be losing steam. Some of the stocks that have
been the hottest _ companies as diverse as America Online, Pfizer
Inc., Yahoo! Inc., Gillette and Dell Computer _ are down
considerably from their highs of earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these stocks have been outrun by companies few investors
have ever heard of. Indeed, according to Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, in the second quarter of the year, the 100 smallest
companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index rose 26.5
percent while the 100 largest stocks gained only 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy favored by individual investors for the past
five years has also begun to flag: buying so-called index funds
that mirror the returns of the S&AMP;P 500. For the first time in five
years, during the second quarter, millions of index fund investors
found their returns lagging behind those of most money managers who
buy and sell stocks to try to beat the market. At the end of June,
70 percent of professional fund managers were beating the S&AMP;P 500,
more than double the portion that has done so since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   If anything can jolt investors out of their complacency, this
turnabout should, analysts say. ``Buying what you know or where you
used the products and know the brands has been a good strategy,''
said Byron R. Wien, chief U.S. strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``In addition to that, the index approach to investing has
worked. But it has pushed valuations of the top 50 stocks in the
S&AMP;P to a very high level. We have finally gotten to the point in
the market where there is a difference between good companies and
good stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years or so, good companies and good stocks
have been one and the same, giving investors in blue-chip stocks
annual gains of more than 20 percent each year since 1993, well
above the historical returns of 11 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wien is correct that these stocks have become overvalued,
investors who have made easy money on them could be in for a shock.
With more do-it-yourself investors in the market than ever, online
and otherwise, it is uncertain how many will recognize that the
investing terrain may have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brokerage firms used to exercise a little oversight, they
wouldn't let something get completely crazy,'' said Shad Rowe, a
principal at Greenbrier Partners, a money management firm in
Dallas. ``Now people are dealing completely on superstition and
price action. And they're having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of them are confident that the good times will just keep on
rolling. Indeed, an investor-optimism index tracked by Paine Webber
Group Inc., shows investors' expectations for stock returns at
their highest levels ever. The July figures, released Monday,
indicated that individuals who have invested for five years or less
expect the market to return 22.6 percent annually over the next
decade, and 21.1 percent over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   So far the optimists have been right, of course. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average is up 19.58 percent this year, and the S&AMP;P 500
is up 10.87 percent. And in trading Tuesday, some of the technology
stocks that had been beaten down in recent days recovered a bit;
the Nasdaq composite rose 60.14 points, or 2.3 percent. It is up
22.19 percent on the year.
</P>
<P>
   But those moves mask a good deal of investor carnage in some of
the hottest stocks recently. Yahoo! Inc. is down 43 percent from
its April peak, and America Online, while still up 26.6 on the
year, has fallen 42 percent from its high. Dell Computer is down 24
percent from its February high. Even mighty Microsoft is off 11.6
percent from its high of mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the big-name stocks that have been the market's
hottest numbers for five years running _ Gillette, Pfizer and
Merck, to name three _ have actually lost ground for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one quarter's trading action does not necessarily
translate into a long-term trend. Wien of Morgan Stanley believes
that the trend away from the old favorites will continue through
the second half of the year, but other Wall Street strategists see
the shift as evanescent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the simplicity of indexing and buying big-name stocks
appealed to investors. As more and more stock traders followed
suit, prices of the favored companies rocketed. In the first
quarter of 1999, just 18 stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 index accounted for
all of its 6.1 percent gain. These included Cisco Systems, Lucent
Technologies, IBM and America Online. The other 482 companies were
either a wash or a drag on the index.
</P>
<P>
   This narrowly focused performance naturally attracted even more
individuals to the same handful of stocks. And the Internet fueled
the fire. Online traders bought with abandon, pushing prices of the
favored stocks to unheard-of values. Meanwhile, the vast majority
of listed stocks languished.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the laggards' turn to shine. During the second
quarter, the S&AMP;P 500 rose 6.7 percent while the S&AMP;P Small
Capitalization 600 index, filled with names unfamiliar to most
investors, rose 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in the second quarter, the top-performing industry in the
S&AMP;P 500 was the capital goods group, which consists of makers of
heavy machinery _ not the kind of stock group with which individual
investors have had personal experiences. Ditto for the company that
had the biggest one-month move in the quarter: Marshall Industries,
a distributor of electronic components, whose stock more than
doubled. Marshall is neither a familiar name to most individual
investors nor a stock most would know how to assess.
</P>
<P>
   The invest-in-what-you-know thesis that investors have thronged
to was made famous by Peter Lynch, the extraordinary manager who
brought fame to Fidelity's Magellan Fund in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Berman, a clinical psychologist in Baltimore, became a
do-it-yourself devotee about seven years ago when he was shopping
for a computer and reading computer magazines. ``It seemed like
there were some names that were repeatedly written about as good
companies,'' he recalled. ``I just kept reading about Intel, Dell,
and Cisco, so I started investing in them.'' He said his own picks
in recent years had outperformed the choices of the professional
managers he had consulted in prior years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may have focused on the same relatively small group of
stocks because they felt overwhelmed by information on companies
from both reliable and not-so-reliable sources. The cacophony from
Internet investment chat rooms, increased television coverage of
the markets and countless financial publications contributed to
information overload, prodding some investors to shut out the
clamor and buy the stocks in companies they know best.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the prices of these companies have gotten so out
of whack with their earnings prospects that lesser names are
starting to look like better bets.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the favored Internet and other technology
stocks are still up for the year, their recent slide is a potential
disaster for the thousands of daytraders, some of whom have left
their jobs to play the market. With stocks' daily trading ranges
much more subdued, it has become much tricker to nail down a profit
and much easier to rack up a loss. And who ever thought of
day-trading a steel company or a cement maker? Yet that is what
lies ahead, if the current trend holds.
</P>
<P>
   Cindee H. Sokal is one of the many investors who recently took
up daytrading. A registered nurse for the past 20 years, the mother
of four left her job three months ago and started training for her
new career, then took $50,000 from her family's account at a
full-service broker and began trading it online at a branch of
All-Tech Investments. Although she lost money initially, she is
confident that she will make money. ``I love it. I think it's very
exciting, '' Ms. Sokal said. ``It's where the future is headed.
Initially, you may lose with trial and error but over the long run
you'll reap the rewards of being in touch with it more and aware of
your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   If the handful of household-name companies continues to lag,
however, investors will have to widen their horizons. This will
make stockpicking much more difficult, forcing them to do the sort
of homework, like examining financial statements, that
old-fashioned money managers have always performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real risk is that investors do nothing, that they become
paralyzed,'' said Elizabeth K. Miller, vice president at Trevor
Stewart Burton &AMP; Jacobsen, a money management firm in New York.
``They won't be participating at the greatest opportunity for
value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
