<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDY-ARKANSAS-COX     07-27 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDY-ARKANSAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giuliani plays carpetbagger game, visits Clinton's state
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani may be a
Republican, but that didn't stop him from calling up this city's
Democratic mayor Tuesday and telling him what a swell place he
thought Little Rock was.
</P>
<P>
   That was the New York state flag flying above Little Rock's most
historic hotel, after all. Outside the Capital Hotel, the city
government and much of the citizenry was arguing over whether to
rename a 21-block stretch for President Clinton. Inside, however, a
fundraising lunch brought in more than $30,000 for Giuliani's
presumed New York Senate race against first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even the protesters turned out not to be protesters at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some protesters outside, so I felt like I was really
back in New York City,'' Giuliani said about arriving at the
Governor's Mansion here, only to discover that the small crowd
waving signs with messages like ``Razorbacks for Rudy'' were all
fans. ``That doesn't usually happen that people protest in my
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another typical day in the race for a senate seat that
won't be decided for 16 months, and yet in which everything already
falls into the ``doesn't usually happen'' category. First Mrs.
Clinton took the unprecedented step of forming an exploratory
committee (no sitting first lady has ever run for a Senate seat,
let alone one in a state where she's never lived), then Mayor
Giuliani began joking that he might run in Arkansas rather than in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   That led to Tuesday's fundraising lunch, as well as a press
conference at the governor's mansion, where Gov. Mike Huckabee
seemed to temporarily forget that he and Giuliani disagree on
abortion, gay rights and numerous other social issues. In fact, the
New York born and raised Giuliani may be downright liberal compared
to Huckabee, a Southern Baptist preacher, but at least he's not
Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that it's an important thing to elect people like
the mayor to maintain a Republican majority,'' said Huckabee, who
made Giuliani an honorary Arkansas citizen on the steps of the
mansion where Hillary Clinton once lived as the state's first lady.
``And also, that people representing their states actually know
what it's like to live there.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, meanwhile, seemed the very essence of a southern
gentleman in discussing his reasons for being in Arkansas. As the
mercury soared near 100 degrees, the large press contingent that
hailed from as nearby as Fayetteville, Ark., and as far away as
London and Tokyo, tried to get the normally cantankerous mayor to
slam Mrs. Clinton or at the very least, his down-home surroundings.
Giuliani merely responded by announcing that he'd placed a call
home ordering that the Arkansas state flag be flown above New
York's City Hall. As for his trip here being a p.r. move, more
specifically a ``jab'' aimed at Mrs. Clinton, Giuliani pretended to
look horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would NEVER do that,'' the mayor said, barely suppressing a
smile. ``That's not in my personality to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but he quickly warmed to it. Asked about the
hotly-debated issue of renaming a street here for President
Clinton, the mayor responded with a barely-concealed swipe at the
first lady and her recent ``listening tour'' of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I become a candidate in Arkansas, then that's something I
would have a very strong opinion on,'' Giuliani said. ``But right
now, I'm just listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for parts of the day, Giuliani sounded like a
serious-minded candidate, discussing his record on welfare reform
and crime reduction in New York with a group representng the
Greater Little Rock Republican Women's Club.
</P>
<P>
   He also sounded in serious need of cash. With a possible
Republican primary looming, Giuliani will need many millions to
make a serious Senate run -- his two-day Southern swing, which also
included a fundraiser Tuesday night in New Orleans, followed by
three more today in Alabama, should bring in $150,000 to $200,000,
he said at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should run on HIS record,'' said former Arkansas
Gov. Frank White, before heading into the $500-a-plate fundraiser.
``I don't know what record (Hillary Clinton) has that he could
focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was the Hillary factor, more than money and ideas,
that seemed to attract Arkansans to the man from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they weren't exactly from Arkansas themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care for some of his views,'' conceded Ann Barton,
one of several women who'd driven in from Memphis to the governor's
mansion to wave misspelled signs reading ``The Vast Right Wing
Conspiracy (Loves) Rudi.'' ``But we don't think Hillary should run
for the senate from New York, a state where she doesn't even know
the constitutents.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
