<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHEM-BLUECROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY AGREES TO FINANCE FOUNDATION FOR UNINSURED IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, N.H., N.J., Mass., R.I.)  (mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advancing its campaign to consolidate Blue Cross and Blue Shield
companies in the Northeast, Anthem Inc. agreed Tuesday to finance a
$41 million public health foundation for poor and uninsured people
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement settled lawsuits filed by state officials and a
coalition of consumer, labor and religious groups after Anthem
merged in 1997 with Connecticut Blue Cross and Blue Shield, the
state's largest health insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem, based in Indianapolis, is also acquiring the Blue Cross
plans in Maine, where it agreed two weeks ago to create a public
foundation valued at about $100 million, and New Hampshire, where
the foundation would be about $80 million, a company spokesman
said. Both deals must be approved by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Cross-financed foundations, which have ranged from $28
million in Ohio to several billion dollars in California, respond
to laws requiring compensation for tax breaks and subsidies given
to Blue Cross plans over the years. In the biggest example, the
conversion of California Blue Cross by Wellpoint Health Plans, two
foundations received cash and stock valued at $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A merger between Anthem and New Jersey Blue Cross and Blue
Shield two years ago collapsed after the state attorney general
insisted that Blue Cross assets in New Jersey be dedicated to a
foundation and Anthem refused. Anthem has lately been flexible on
the foundation issue, adjusting to varying state laws and policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although each state is unique, the Anthem-financed foundations
are context for a much larger conversion planned by Empire Blue
Cross and Blue Shield in New York. Empire, which says it is about
to report operating profits for the third consecutive quarter, has
been meeting officials of the state attorney general's office and
insurance and health departments to iron out plans to convert to a
for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   Empire plans to issue stock, all of which would be turned over
to a public foundation. The conversion requires the approval of a
state supreme court. With the settlement in Connecticut, ``Anthem
has decided to take its medicine and pay the bill,'' said Nancy
Wyman, the state comptroller, who joined Richard Blumenthal, the
attorney general, in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem said in a statement that extended litigation would not
have served its policy-holders or taxpayers in Connecticut and
could have affected the company's reputation and goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem, which is a mutual insurance company owned by its
policy-holders, has about 4 million members in Blue Cross plans in
Indiana, Kentucky and southern Ohio, and 1 million more in
Connecticut. Maine Blue Cross has 380,000 members. New Hampshire
Blue Cross has 320,000.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Blue Cross, the biggest in New England, rebuffed
overtures from Anthem and is trying to block a takeover of Blue
Cross of Rhode Island by Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the New England Blue Cross plans is the biggest health
insurer in its state but they are all financially weak and face
competition from bigger regional companies, including Aetna U.S.
Healthcare, Cigna's Healthsource unit, and the nonprofit Harvard
Pilgrim and Tufts health plans. Kaiser Permanente, the nonprofit
California-based health plan, recently decided to cut its losses in
New England and left the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a tremendous opportunity to take advantage of
efficiencies and economies of scale that consolidations can
create,'' said Jim Parker, a spokesman for Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   In a still unresolved bidding war for Blue Cross of
Colorado/Nevada, which has 500,000 members, Anthem raised its
commitment to establish a $140 million foundation to match a
competing offer by Wellpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Richter, a health care analyst at Banc of America
Securities, said Anthem would have ``a very tough time financing
all the deals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arun Kumar, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said Anthem had
a strong balance sheet and a big surplus and could arrange loans if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem reported $178 million in operating income on $5.9 billion
in revenue last year. It had $79 million of operating income in
1997 and $141 million in 1996. With reserves of $1.7 billion,
Anthem has more than twice the reserve level set by the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners, even after setting up
foundations in all the states it hopes to enter, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Wellpoint and Anthem are among the nation's largest Blue Cross
plans, along with Highmark Inc. in Western Pennsylvania, Michigan
Blue Cross, the merged Illinois and Texas Blues plans, and Empire.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Empire said Tuesday that its reserves were
$454.6 million on June 30. Operating income was $13.9 million for
the second quarter of this year, $14.5 million in the first
quarter, and $14.9 million in the last three months of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
