<HEADER>
A6017 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENICE-BIENNALE-2TAKE     07-27 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENICE-BIENNALE-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE MOMENT (AND ONLY FOR THE MOMENT)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ To look at new art is to expect to feel
something or be told something or be tweaked or entertained in ways
that have nothing necessarily to do with tangible objects.
</P>
<P>
   Art less and less is judged by the old priorities of painting,
sculpture and drawing. It is context that increasingly determines
the shape of the art we see. Exhibit No. 1: the 48th Venice
Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   It's commonly being said about the show that video art
dominates, which is true, but only up to a point. There's a
hilarious work, for instance, by Christian Marclay, a young
American, who mixes old film clips of people using the telephone,
and a hypnotic video by Shirin Neshat, a parable about women in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter Roth, the wild German-born recluse who died last year at
age 68, videotaped himself in his studio in 1997 and 1998: ``Solo
Scenes'' presents the tapes he made on 128 monitors that precisely
because they show us nothing remarkable happening, end up being
moving as a record of a private life.
</P>
<P>
   And a rare successful example of video married to sculptural
space comes from Doug Aitken, the Los Angeles artist, whose
Hopperish riff on the city, part hangdog narrative, part hot
technicolor abstraction, set to sound, plays on multiple screens in
a calculated sequence of rooms.
</P>
<P>
   So, there is a lot of video here. But there's no real argument
being made in the biennale for video as the medium of the moment;
different work is brought together on more or less equal ground,
which is how we're supposed to see it. Moving images tend to do
better than static objects in shows like this simply because
they're attention-magnets.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point: we now have a new species of art geared
specifically to the circus environment of the big international
survey show, and video is a part of it. The art happens to
encapsulate the spirit of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Artists having caught on to the nature of these extravaganzas,
their strategy is to accept, rather than fight against, the short
attention span and impatient gaze of people meandering among
hundreds of disparate works. What we get are the visual equivalents
of sound bites, quickly digestible and user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   We might define the '90s as a decade that has rejected the sort
of encompassing movements that used to characterize modern art and
that declared its revolutionary bona fides. Revolutionary ambition
has evidently come to seem a little ridiculous to many young
artists _ the legacy of overreaching expectations and the overhyped
'80s, maybe _ and it has been replaced, in part, by a taste for
spectacle as an end in itself and for art that seems content with
contained, idiosyncratic gestures in any variety of forms and
media.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of work these days _ and this is what you find in
the biennale _ is quirky, accessible and out to please in a low-key
way. I was struck, if not particularly impressed, by artists like
Sarah Sze, Gilles Barbier and others who have made Rube
Goldberg-like sculptures that are just funny contraptions. Max
Dean, a British-born artist living in Toronto, concocted a robot.
It saves or shreds family snapshots he has collected depending on
which button a viewer presses.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech pavilion, you can get tattooed; in the Spanish
pavilion, you can pose in a giant picture frame and see your
reflection in a mirror. In the Belgian pavilion, you can wander
through a dense white fog. I haven't the vaguest idea what it's
about, but it's perfectly pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   The stance struck is a kind of cheerful detachment,
ideologically speaking neither here nor there _ which explains,
among other things, why no one can claim at the moment to have a
particularly good handle on art. There being no prevailing dogma,
or even the strong desire for one, there is no easy way to grasp an
amorphous situation.
</P>
<P>
   We might regard all this, in one respect, positively: art in the
late '90s is more diverse, inclusive and less dogmatic than it has
been. The cardboard politics and theorizing that were commonplace
have lost their steam. Politics mostly comes in subtler forms now.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Chinese artists in the show (there are a conspicuous
number of them, whose works have been borrowed from a handful of
Swiss owners) is Chen Zhen. He has made drums out of old tables and
chairs. Viewers may bang away on them, perhaps contemplating
political brutality (I'm told it's an intended subtext), but also
just to let off steam.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter much that art academies are still full of
instructors and students spouting arcane ideas to justify what's
meant to pass for art in the classroom. Schools being schools,
they're an easy target. In the real world today, you might say that
the most pesky tendency is the usual obsession with sex _ now
justified, of course, as gender politics _ which can make the art
scene occasionally mimic ``Wayne's World.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a lot of prurience at this biennale, and that helps
explain why people seem to like it more than previous ones. It's
curious to be saying that the biennale may actually tell us
something about the state of contemporary art as opposed simply to
the state of those who buy or write about it.
</P>
<P>
   For years, art people have been coming to the show not because
anyone expects it to be good, but because no one can resist the
chance to be here. Reviewers have been writing about the crowds at
the opening and their own surreptitious forays to see older art (as
if an interest in Titian betrayed a lack of faith in what's new),
all of which seemed more interesting than the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the biennale remained a significant occasion nonetheless, if
only because everyone in the art world would definitely be around
in the event that something worthwhile finally happened. And this
year it has.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived, as in the past, just after the show opened to the
public (it stays open through Nov. 7). The art crowd had left,
which meant I wandered peacefully and nearly alone. As an
experience, it's a useful reminder of the gulf between contemporary
art and most of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The biennale remains a novelty item among the vast inventory of
Venice's tourist attractions, which is a pity when the show is
good, but artists are partly to blame. A few of them arranged
performances during the preview only. The Italian Maurizio Cattelan
(several reviewers picked him out in particular) organized the
burial, every two hours, of a Hindu fakir in sand.
</P>
<P>
   So I searched for the fakir, but he was gone by the time I
arrived, leaving only the pile of sand, incomprehensible to anyone
who wasn't at the opening _ an illustration of what alienates
people from new art.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Harald Szeeman, the veteran Swiss impresario who was
appointed director of this biennale, has, in general, organized the
exhibition cleverly and with a subtle showman's touch, eschewing
any particular theme (themes never worked anyway), and expanding
the display to encompass not just the old national pavilions in the
Giardini and the Corderie, the former rope factory at the ancient
military shipyard, but also several other renovated shipyard
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   These buildings, without question, are the biennale's most
impressive new sight (and site), and several artists (the
Hungarian-born Serge Spitzer, who uses hundreds of glass bottles,
comes to mind) have conceived installations specifically to
highlight the architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning the Corderie over to a show of young artists,
which used to happen, Szeeman has also included work from the past
relevant to what's new: a video by Dieter Appelt, the German
artist, from 1981, of a man (supposedly) being sliced in two, is a
shocker that looks new. Bruce Nauman's ``Poke in the
Eye/Nose/Ear,'' which he made in 1994, serves as a precedent for
Rosemarie Trockel's video installation of a giant roving eye in the
German pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   What we get is a spacious, nondidactic, cross-referential and
free-flowing exhibition _ the perfect global survey for the end of
the 20th century _ that paradoxically seems more coherent and
consistent than past biennales. The weight used to be more on the
national pavilions. With each nation picking its own artists for
the pavilions, the result was always a hodgepodge of priorities and
talent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, while the system hasn't changed, it seems to matter
less. It's not really important, for example, that the official
United States presentation is such a disappointment: Ann Hamilton's
installation of red powder falling onto braille texts accompanied
by the piped-in sound of a voice speaking in code, is a work about
incommunication that is itself incommunicative.
</P>
<P>
   But by putting the stress elsewhere, instead of on the national
pavilions, and somehow maintaining a decent level of quality
throughout, Szeeman largely avoids the mix of front-line art and
yard-sale junk that doomed so many biennales.
</P>
<P>
   To be precise, he has taken advantage of the fact that
contemporary artists have finally learned how to adapt to the
peculiar demands of this sort of exhibition. The art may or may not
be marketable outside the festival context, but its true value has
to do not with collectibility but theatricality: a capacity to
command a stage, at least briefly.
</P>
<P>
   From having been a place where different kinds of art from
around the world is gathered, the biennale, along with the other
big international art surveys, has turned into an art form of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker magazine critic Peter Schjeldahl's term Festival
Art fills the bill nicely. It's work that fits with the tune of the
time, according to which anything, in any medium, is now
acceptable, and nothing is particularly essential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
