<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARCLAYS APPOINTS NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For almost a year, Barclays PLC, one of Britain's
largest banks, has been roiled by the resignations of two of its
chief executives. And investors have anxiously awaited the next
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Barclays announced who would next lead the bank:
Matthew Barrett, the chairman of the Bank of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to hire Barrett, 54, as Barclays' chief executive
came in discussions with him over the last six weeks. His selection
was considered a bit of a surprise because he had recently stepped
down as the Bank of Montreal's chief executive and said at the time
that he planned to retire. Known for a brash and media-savvy style,
Barrett is stepping into a pressure-cooker job that could postpone
retirement for years.
</P>
<P>
   Turmoil in Barclays' executive ranks began when Martin Taylor,
the last full-time chief executive, quit in a dispute over
investment banking strategy late last year. His successor, Michael
O'Neill, a top executive at Bank of America, had not even started
on the job before he resigned in mid-April for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The share price of Barclays has been on a roller-coaster ride,
in part reflecting the uncertainty over who would run the bank.
Barclays stock dropped drastically after Russia's default and
devaluation last summer hammered the company's investment banking
business, and after Taylor resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But the shares have since risen 30 percent as some emerging
markets rebounded. Sir Peter Middleton, the bank's chairman and
acting chief executive, significantly cut costs by eliminating
6,000 jobs in May.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Barclays shares rose nearly 5 percent in reaction to
the announcement of appointment of the new chief.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they are getting a seasoned banker with a good
record,'' said Simon Samuels, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney
here.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think that Barrett may be a deal maker. While at the
Bank of Montreal, he tried to acquire the Royal Bank of Canada, but
the Canadian government blocked the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly got a vision as far as consolidation is
concerned,'' said Alan Reid, a credit-rating analyst at Moody's
Investors Service.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Barrett said he had no secret plan for
Barclays. ``It's too early for me to form an impression,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether he might make an acquisition, Barrett did not rule
out the possibility. ``There's a lot of elbow room over here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Middleton's many moves while acting chief executive may have
already set the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the grand scheme of things,'' Reid said, ``the strategy
probably won't change. The success of this organization is not
restricted to one man.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Barrett is returning to London where he began his banking career
as a trainee teller for the Bank of Montreal in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to ``hit the ground running'' when he begins
work in about two months. He will be one of Europe's highest-paid
executives with a base salary of about $1.35 million, in addition
to a bonus and options that could make his compensation package as
high as $9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his compensation, he said his personal style would not
change. ``I have an irreverent sense of humor that gets me into the
soup once in awhile,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
</TEXT>
