A6020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-OHIO-COX     07-27 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore to visit Ohio, meet with labor women
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Ohio will again be in the spotlight of the 2000
presidential campaign Thursday when Vice President Al Gore visits
Cleveland to strengthen ties with organized labor and collect an
expected $200,000 at a private fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be greeted by Ohio labor leaders and by officials from
the national AFL-CIO and will hold an open forum on the issues
facing working women.
</P>
<P>
   The forum, titled ``Ask a Working Woman,'' will include a panel
of five women and 200 invited guests at Cleveland State University.
The topics are expected to include wages, child care, health care,
sexual harassment, long work schedules and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk about all the things that plague women in the
workplace,'' said Karen Nussbaum, director of the national
AFL-CIO's working women department. ``I think Clinton-Gore have
made a lot of progress for women in the workplace, but a lot more
needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum will be a continuation of the AFL-CIO's ``Ask a
Working Woman'' program that kicked off in the spring when First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was campaigning in Buffalo for a U.S.
Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's focus in Cleveland will quickly turn from labor issues to
gathering money for his presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   The forum will be followed by private fund-raiser at the home of
Michael Siegal, president and CEO of the Olympic Steel Co. About
200 people are expected to attend the luncheon at the cost of
$1,000 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit comes exactly a week after Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the leading Republican presidential candidate, made
Cincinnati his first Ohio campaign stop. Bush visited Cincinnati's
predominately black Evanston neighborhood for a public appearance,
then picked up a record $1 million at a ticketed fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Republican Chairman Robert Bennett said Gore's stop in
Cleveland is to maintain support from Ohio's labor leaders, not
from rank and file union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``State and national polls show that about 40 percent of (union
workers) support Republican candidates, but 95 percent of labor's
money is being funneled to Democrats,'' Bennett said. ``And (Gore)
doesn't go anywhere without stopping to raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Democratic Chairman David Leland defended Gore's campaign
stop and his relationship with organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Al Gore and the Democratic party are committed
to helping working families,'' Leland said. ``I don't understand
how the Republicans can criticize the vice president when their
counterparts in Washington are considering giving their wealthiest
contributors a huge tax break.''
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley is challenging Gore for the
Democratic nomination. March 7 is the Ohio primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign stop also comes at time when improving pay for
women continues to be an issue around the Ohio Statehouse and
especially for state Rep. Dixie Allen, D-Dayton. Earlier this year,
House Democrats introduced legislation that would correct
discriminatory wage practices based on sex or race. The
legislation, backed by Allen, was introduced by Democratic leaders,
who say women in Ohio are making 72 cents for every dollar earned
by a man.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the legislation would require employers to
document wages paid to employees and explain how they determine
wage rates for all employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
