<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JULY 28
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-TAX-CONGRESS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
21, about the Congressional debate over taxes misstated the size of
the tax cut approved by the Senate Finance Committee. It was $792
billion over 10 years, not $778 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 26,
about plans by President Carlos Saul Menem of Argentina to run for
President in 2003 referred incorrectly in some editions to the year
he would run in a party primary. It would be 2003, not this year.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-ADDRESSES-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 25,
about the Dot-Com Directory, a new Internet Yellow Pages-type
service being offered by Network Solutions Inc., misstated the
on-line address for the service. It is: &QL; 
http://www.dotcomdirectory.com
</P>
<P>
   BC-MP3-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Monday, July 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 19,
about the initial public offering of Mp3.Com, an Internet music
company, misidentified one of the company's major investors. It is
Cox Interactive Media, not David Easterly, who is chief executive
of Cox Enterprises, the parent company of Cox Interactive.
</P>
