A6025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BROWNS-OFFENSE     07-27 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-OFFENSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns' offense not pleasing in early-going
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ As the Cleveland Browns installed the shotgun
formation and other nuances Tuesday, their overall offense seemed
to shoot itself in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   And if any doubt remained about the defense being ahead at this
early stage of training camp, it was put to rest after a
mistake-filled morning practice when head coach Chris Palmer made
his offense run a lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't make the head coach pleased,'' Palmer said. ``So
the defense had a chance to stand and contemplate how well they
were doing while the offense ran.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it wasn't a good day to be an offensive player, unless maybe
you were Sedrick Shaw, the former New England halfback who
impressed Palmer with his nose for the end zone in goal-line
situations. Or wide receiver Kevin Johnson, the second-round draft
choice who has done enough things right lately to be running with
the first team, relegating Jermaine Ross to backup status.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the morning session even included an offensive
injury. It ended with third-quarterback candidate John Dutton
sitting on a cart, then hobbling off for treatment on his left
foot, which had been stepped on as he pulled away from center
during a nine-on-seven drill. Later, X-rays revealed a broken bone,
meaning he will be out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off slow,'' Palmer said. ``I thought we were a
little anxious. The offensive line came out a little antsy and
jumped offside a couple times. The receivers were not looking at
the ball. They were too busy trying to make big plays and impress
the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sluggishness by the offense did not catch Palmer completely
off guard. The first four practice days had been devoted to
offensive and defensive basics. Tuesday, the playbook opened a bit
wider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to do more stuff,'' he said, ``and their heads
are spinning a little bit. It all starts to happen faster and
faster, with everybody competing for jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of finding out who actually knows what they're
doing on either side of the ball, Palmer at one point swept his
assistant coaches to the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get the coaches off the field and let the players
function by themselves,'' he said. ``They've had the security
blanket of the coaches being there and now they're off the field.
It's the next step in building a team and building chemistry and
things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the offense would have more problems than they did.
The defense blew an alignment call and I wasn't pleased about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains the absolute lack of gloating on the part of the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early,'' defensive tackle John Jurkovic said. ``Anything
you see us doing out there, you've got to take with a grain of
salt. It's always tough for the offense early on.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Derrick Alexander was placed on the
active-physically unable to perform list as he continues to rehab
after undergoing knee surgery. Said Palmer, ``It's just a
precaution meant to give us as many options as we can have.''
Thought to be ahead of schedule, Alexander said he plans to be back
by the third preseason game. Meanwhile, he still counts toward the
roster but will not be able to practice with the team until removed
from the list. He can remain on the list until the Sept. 5 cutdown
date.
</P>
<P>
   According to Palmer, quarterbacks coach John Hufnagel ran the
nightly 11 p.m. bed check Monday and found quarterbacks Tim Couch
and Mike Cook in Cook's room with their playbooks open. This after
a long day at the office for both players, Couch in particular.
``Tim didn't have a great day Monday,'' Palmer said. ``And I let
him know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
