<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILLUMINATA-FILM-2TAKE     07-27 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLUMINATA-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV0-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE TURTURRO TROUPE, ACTING IS A FAMILY OUTING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG 1.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Franz Lidz, a senior writer at Sports Illustrated, is the author of
the memoir ``Unstrung Heroes.'' John Turturro played his father in
the film version of the book.  
 By FRANZ LIDZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's twilight _ the haunting hour that mingles
longing and regret, promise and speculation _ and the world's
youngest method actor is brooding in his Brooklyn bedroom. He's
sprawled under a ``Seven Samurai'' poster, absorbing the warmth and
the silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I (italics)like(end italics) challenging roles,''
says Amedeo Turturro with the magnificent assurance of an
8-year-old. ``But that role was so challenging, they practically
had to force me to do it.'' The ``they'' he's referring to are his
parents, the actors John Turturro and Katherine Borowitz. The
``it'' is ``Illuminata,'' an engagingly heartfelt new film in which
all three appear.
</P>
<P>
   Though Amedeo had only a single line of dialogue _ ``You were
very excellent in the rehearsal!'' _ he had trouble finding his
motivation. ``I told the director, `Why the heck do I have to say
that?''' recalls the precocious Amedeo, who has his mother's gift
for language and his father's seditious streak. ``The director _
who's my dad _ said, `Because it's in the script.' I got terribly
mad and angry. In fact, I almost quit the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother listened and listened and explained the scene. His
father listened and listened and said: ``You can't quit now. You're
already in the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a quintessential actor-director clash, fraught with
Freudian overtones. Amedeo frowns hard. ``Listen, Bucko,'' he
remembers telling his old man. ``That line has nothing to do with
my character. If you make me say it, I'm going to sue, and you
won't have enough money left to pay your agent.'' Evidently, Dad
saw through the bluff. ``It didn't work,'' Amedeo says with a small
shrug. ``My every word went right through him.''
</P>
<P>
   John Turturro not only helped conceive Amedeo, he also helped
write ``Illuminata,'' a bawdy ``Italo-Swedish date movie,'' as he
describes it (think Fellini- and Bergmanesque) on the muddles of
love and lust, faithfulness and infidelity, selfishness and
self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illuminata,'' which opens on Friday, is about a stock company
of 19th-century actors, and the Turturro family has pretty much
become a stock company, too. Husband and wife have performed
together in three plays and three movies, two of which Amedeo
cameoed in.
</P>
<P>
   When Turturro starred as Gogo last fall in an Off Broadway
production of ``Waiting for Godot,'' Amedeo played The Boy, on
weekends. ``I had to deliver a message,'' Amedeo says. ``Other
characters got angry at me, suspicious. It was a very complicated
role for an 8-year-old, or should I say 8-and-a-quarter-year-old?''
</P>
<P>
   His 42-and-a-half-year-old father has made a career of
complicated roles. In more than 40 films across 19 years, Turturro
has brought soulful vulnerabilty and intense dedication to
desperate loners crabbed by society, Molotov cocktails ready to be
lighted: the throttled playwright in ``Barton Fink''; the scrambled
egghead in ``Quiz Show''; the gleefully demented bowler in ``The
Big Lebowski.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian director Francesco Rosi pitched him the part of
Primo Levi, the chemist who became a brilliant author after
surviving Auschwitz, in ``The Truce'' (1997). ``The film is ironic
and grotesque,'' he said, ``and I feel you have both.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Turturro lists toward the ironic. As he speaks,
his hands are constantly on the move, the tapered fingers combing
the air. An affable man, he comes across as open and unprotected,
with an absurdist sensibility as exuberant as the hero's in his
favorite novel, Knut Hamsun's ``Hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Borowitz is a hardy realist, a Yale-educated linguist as
clearheaded as the heroine of (italics)her(end italics) favorite
novel, Charlotte Bronte's ``Villette.'' She totally lacks the
self-importance many actors project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kathie hasn't fully embraced her ambitious side,'' allows her
husband. Though she has appeared in dozens of films, plays and
television dramas, she is perhaps best known for an ice cream
commercial broadcast in the mid-'80s. ``I was the Frusen Gladje
Girl,'' she admits. ``I polished off a carton without sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot certainly drew attention. One film director called her
agent and demanded, ``Get me the Frusen Gladje Girl!'' Ms. Borowitz
was sent a script by messenger and given a private audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no!'' barked the director. ``Read it like the Frusen
Gladje Girl!''
</P>
<P>
   She tried, but the reception was chillier than a pint of Rocky
Road. ``Not a peep, not a laugh, not a smile,'' she recalls. ``Just
dead silence.'' She didn't get the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sad,'' says Turturro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pathetic!'' corrects Ms. Borowitz. ``I couldn't even be
the Frusen Gladje Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   They take obvious pleasure in each other. Over 18 years
together, they have developed an almost telepathic understanding.
They put that knowledge to work in ``Illuminata.'' Turturro plays
Tuccio, a restless playwright; Ms. Borowitz plays the actress
Rachel, his lover and muse.
</P>
<P>
   For an actor who tends to steal the notices of every film he's
in, Turturro shows considerable restraint as a director, satirizing
the tics and foibles of theater people without turning peevish. His
camera observes Rachel in relentless close-ups, and Ms. Borowitz
does not wilt under the glare. In inflections ranging from
armored-tough to archly tender, she becomes the movie's magnetic
center.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro and his co-writer, Brandon Cole, tinkered with the
script for more than a decade. The film could have been financed
years earlier if Turturro had agreed to let a bankable actress play
Rachel. But he stoutly resisted. (Backing finally came after Susan
Sarandon signed on to the film as an aging diva and Christopher
Walken as a flamboyant critic).
</P>
<P>
   MS. BOROWITZ: Many times I told John: ``I know you're sticking
with this because of me, but you've left not one pebble unturned
and prospects are bleak, so maybe you've should bag it before it
sucks us into a black hole.
</P>
<P>
   TURTURRO: A lot of Kathie was written into Rachel. Kathie is
strong, but also gentle and graceful. Her character holds the film
together.
</P>
<P>
   MS. BOROWITZ (teasingly): Couldn't I have had some more subtle
comedic flourishes?
</P>
<P>
   TURTURRO (earnestly): Believe me, you're the soul of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The real strength of ``Illuminata'' is that Turturro and Ms.
Borowitz know each other to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   He says: ``Most movies are about falling in love. This one's
about what it is to love someone over time: the differences, the
obstacles you have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   She says: ``Keeping a relationship alive is a constant, active
process, Especially with individuals whose creativity might draw
them in their own directions.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They became sweethearts at Yale Drama School. He was in his
first year; she, her third. ``They were sensitive, independent
people from diverse backgrounds,'' says Ms. Borowitz's mother,
Lorry. ``Yet their personalities balanced somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in blue-collar Queens, the middle brother of three,
Turturro began working summers with his father, a building
contractor, when he was 10. Ms. Borowitz was the older of two
sisters from moderate affluence: her father, Jim, owned a lamp
factory in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro watched ``The Million Dollar Movie'' (``Boris! Bela!
Edward G.! ... '') with a regularity bordering on addiction. She
played the piano, studied music theory and didn't know Jimmy Cagney
from Jiminy Cricket. Before entering Yale, he got his act together
at the State University of New York at New Paltz, taught history in
Harlem and made his screen debut with one line in ``Raging Bull''
(``Hey, Jake!''). She had majored in music and linguistics at Yale,
earned a master's at Harvard and taught dyslexic teen-agers in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linguisitically, my interest was in how Who You Are affects
What You Say,'' Ms. Borowitz says. ``Now, as an actress, I'm
interested in how What You Say reflects Who You Are _ how the text
informs character, who in turn tells the story.''
</P>
<P>
   It was love at first sight. His sight. ``I saw her in ``Peer
Gynt'' and thought she was the most beautiful girl at Yale,'' he
recalls. (Her face _ long, oval, with an expectant sadness _ so
reminded him of a Modigliani that he gave his son the painter's
first name. ``Since Amedeo Modigliani was Jewish,'' adds Ms.
Borowitz, ``John saw it as a concession to my side of the
family.'')
</P>
<P>
   A month later he spotted her at a mixer. He hooked a finger and
shouted in Queens English: ``You! I want to dance with
(italics)you(end italics) later!''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? thought Ms. Borowitz. Later, they did dance. All night.
Then he asked her out to dinner. ``She didn't want to go,'' he
grumbles. ``She resisted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't resisting,'' she says. ``I just didn't think it would
be as good as the dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, was it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later they married, and four years after that they
collaborated on Amedeo. ``Kathie went into labor during the filming
of `Barton Fink,''' Turturro says. ``Amedeo was born right before
the severed-head scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first film collaboration was ``Men of Respect'' (1991), a
Mafia ``Macbeth'' featuring Turturro as a manic triggerman and Ms.
Borowitz as his scheming Lady. The patched-together patter
(Elizabethan meets Elizabeth, N.J.) won a cult following, and Ms.
Borowitz won praise for her spidery poise, her creepy impassivity
and her ability to keep a straight face while sleepwalking with a
flashlight and scrubbing her guilty hands in a birdbath.
</P>
<P>
   The couple collaborated again a year later in ``Mac,'' his
directorial debut. Shot on a slim, ``Illuminata''-size budget,
``Mac,'' Turturro's passionate paean to the life, work and values
of his immigrant father, won a standing ovation at Cannes and the
Camera d'Or prize for best first film.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they played a less bloodthirsty pair. A loving,
loyal, resourceful woman, she tempers her husband's native
combustibility just as he breaks down her natural reticence.
</P>
<P>
   The explosiveness Turturro displays in his films is a quality he
can adopt or drop at will. There's no trace of it in the serenity
of the spacious brownstone where he, his wife and Amedeo dodge the
Hollywood scene. Walls are hung with vintage posters of Turturro's
acting pantheon: Burt Lancaster, Kirk Douglas, Toshiro Mifune, John
Cassavettes.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the mantle in the back parlor is a jaunty sketch of
Pierre Brasseur in ``Les Enfants du Paradis,'' Marcel Carne's 1945
film meditation on theater and life, perhaps the ideal for
``Illuminata.''
</P>
<P>
   Out back, amid the hydrangeas and climbing roses craning for
sunlight, the couple argue amiably about their favorite singers
(She: Barbra Streisand; he: Frank Sinatra) and agree amiably about
their favorite comic actor (Peter Sellers), tragic actress (Anna
Magnani), musicians (Mozart, Louis Armstrong) and memoirs
(``Survival at Auschwitz'') and food (bread).
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread!'' Amedeo pipes in. ``What about pizza?''
</P>
<P>
   The couple are grounded in Brooklyn. Turturro goes out of his
way to work as close to home as possible, prefering East Coast jobs
to West. Usually, it's Ms. Borowitz who minds the store, though a
few years back she spent 14 weeks in San Francisco performing in
Tom Stoppard's ``Arcadia'' with the American Conservatory Theater.
Amedeo stayed with his father on a movie (``Box of Moonlight'') in
the backwoods of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going away to work for such a long time was a tricky
proposition,'' Ms. Borowitz says. ``Still, I thought it was
important, so I went.'' She wrote a precis so that Amedeo would
understand the play better when he came to visit. ``But I had no
idea he'd be on the edge of his seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Amedeo may also be the world's youngest textual critic. Turturro
often sounds out scripts to him. Last year he got a handsome offer
to play a comic action-hero. He read the screenplay to Amedeo, who
said, ``Dad, this is garbage!'' Turturro also had a downright
homely offer to be in ``Godot.'' He read the play to Amedeo, who
cackled at the black boot, the chicken bone, the metaphysical
musings. ``Now (italics)that's(end italics) funny!'' said Amedeo.
</P>
<P>
   He tried out for The Boy, and got hired. ``It wasn't anything
any of us had pursued,'' says Ms. Borowitz. ``It was more of a
family experience, a chance for him to get up close to his dad at
work.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amedeo got antsy in rehearsals, his mother suggested
weighting him down with lead shoes. Instead, he was outfitted in an
overcoat so heavy he could barely move. This didn't keep him from
sometimes wobbling around onstage like a bowling pin. ``I had this
big coat on,'' he says. ``I thought it would be good to act cold.''
</P>
<P>
   To Amedeo, the hopeless tramps who slouch through ``Godot'' are
not different from the hopeful troupe that scurries through
``Illuminata.'' ``They all have the very same mind,'' he says.
``They pass through huge obstacle courses, and realize they need
other people to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   His family is like that, too. ``To stay happy together without
losing our imaginations, my parents and I rely on each other,''
says Amedeo. ``Or should I say they rely on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Why you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they (italics)know(end italics) they can't get away
with anything. I'm the child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
