<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Basque Peace Opening Seen
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Basque leftist coalition regarded as the
political wing of the Basque rebel group ETA signed a statement
with other parties to condemn ``all'' violence that hinders
political freedom. The coalition said it had done nothing new but
leaders of parties across the spectrum hailed the joint statement
as a positive step for peace, 10 months after the Basque rebels
declared a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Uruguay: Truckers Go on Strike
</P>
<P>
   Some 25,000 truck drivers began a 72-hour work stoppage,
paralyzing the transportation of merchandise across the country as
a protest against vehicle taxes. The drivers said they could not
compete against transport companies from neighboring Brazil and
Argentina because Uruguayan taxes made their costs higher.
</P>
<P>
   Chile: Appeal for the Missing
</P>
<P>
   President Eduardo Frei appealed to his countrymen to come
forward with information about more than 1,000 people who
disappeared after the 1973 coup staged by Gen. Augusto Pinochet. In
a speech to a psychoanalysis convention, Frei said Chile needed a
clearer understanding of the past ``in order to take the necessary
steps into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Rebel Attacks on Police
</P>
<P>
   Separatist tribal militants killed at least five policemen with
blasts of automatic weapons fire in the northeastern state of
Assam, the police said. The rebels are suspected of belonging to
the banned National Socialist Council of Nagaland. Naga tribal
rebels have been fighting for decades for an independent homeland
in the tiny neighboring state of Nagaland.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone: Fighters Disband
</P>
<P>
   Traditional hunters who helped the West African peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG to keep Sierra Leone's government from being
overthrown have begun returning to their villages. The government
ordered the hunters, who are known as kamajors and wear mirrors and
crosses in the belief that they will ward off bullets, to disband
after a peace agreement signed early this month with the
Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   Congo: Rebel Unity Talks Stall
</P>
<P>
   The three rebel factions in Congo left a six-day negotiating
session still at odds over who among them should sign the
cease-fire agreed to by the other warring parties in Congo. The
talks, in Dar es Salaam, Tanzanzia, failed to resolve the power
struggle among the three groups, each fighting to overthrow the
President of Congo, Laurent Kabila. Officials said the discussions
were ``indefinitely postponed'' as both Kabila and the rebels
accused each other of violating the terms of the unsigned pact.
</P>
</TEXT>
