<HEADER>
A6036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-VOLS-COX     07-27 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-VOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mature Vols are prepared for bell
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ Tee Martin was calm and comfortable as he walked
through the hotel lobby. Every third step, the Tennessee
quarterback paused to sign an autograph or handle a reporter's
inquiry. He was all smiles until someone asked the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Tennessee has finally won a national championship,''
an inquiring mind wanted to know, ``do you think this team will get
complacent?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was a firm no and a promise: ``It's my job, and the
rest of the captains' jobs, to make sure that we don't. And believe
me, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason why only one team (Nebraska, 1994-95) has won
back-to-back national championships in the past 20 years. It is
difficult to hit upon the combination of talent, circumstance and
luck to win one national title as Tennessee did last season in a
memorable 13-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the annual SEC Football Kickoff began Thursday,
Tennessee's players and coaches are convinced that this team can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is so much more mature,'' defensive tackle Darwin
Walker said. ``We learned what it takes to win a championship. And
nobody is going to give less than that effort again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words were music to the ears of coach Phillip Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't peer into these guy's heads and tell you exactly what
they are thinking,'' he said. ``I can tell you how they've been out
there in the summer sweating and getting ready. They will be ready
when the bell rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Physically, the Volunteers could be even better than they were a
season ago. The offensive line is stronger, the running game will
be better as Jamal Lewis returns from a knee injury, and Martin
seems ready. A talented defense is still looking to replace
linebacker Al Wilson's inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But will the ball bounce Tennessee's way, as it did last season?
The Vols needed late field goals to beat Syracuse and Florida.
Until Clint Stoerner's famous fumble in the final two minutes,
Arkansas was better. Mississippi State led in the fourth quarter of
the SEC title game. Still, the Vols came home from the Fiesta Bowl
with an unbeaten record and their first national championship since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to think that last year was just luck,'' Walker
said. ``We know how good this team can be. It's just up to us to
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the way are some difficult Saturdays:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Sept. 18 trip to Florida, where the Vols have not won since
1971;
</P>
<P>
   _ A Nov. 13 trip to Arkansas to meet Hogs bent on revenge;
</P>
<P>
   _ A road game against Alabama in Tuscaloosa, a site where the
Vols traditionally lay down;
</P>
<P>
   _ Home games against Georgia and Notre Dame. ``All I know is how
I felt after winning the Fiesta Bowl,'' Martin said. ``I want to
feel that way again. We all want to feel that way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
