<HEADLINE>
ABC HOPES `MILLIONAIRE' WILL WIN OVER VIEWERS HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you want to be a millionaire? Call 900-933-9391 and you may
not have to rue the day you didn't buy Microsoft. The call costs a
buck fifty, but if you're the type with a lot of extraneous trivia
dripping into the brain pan and you can retrieve it quickly, you
just might parlay the investment into some large green next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' is already a huge hit in Great
Britain. Regis Philbin thinks the quiz show will be a winner here,
too, and he has signed to host 13 installments airing nightly
(except Aug. 23) from Aug. 16-29 at 8:30 on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   If viewers like it, ``Millionaire'' could return in a variety of
forms: weekly or twice-weekly show, or perhaps in another special
block of consecutive airings. Either way, the prime-time game show
as alternative to the traditional sitcom is obviously gaining favor
at ABC. A U.S. version of England's ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
started as a summer experiment and won a spot on the fall schedule.
And Daily Variety reports that Norm Mcdonald, star of ABC's ``The
Norm Show,'' may host a political quiz show titled ``Have I Got
News for You,'' also patterned after a British series.
</P>
<P>
   ABC Entertainment President Jamie Tarses said it only makes
sense to see what else might appeal to viewers beyond the usual
fare. ``It doesn't hurt that they cost less to produce (than
sitcoms) in this current landscape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ David E. Kelley created ``Chicago Hope'' but reduced his
involvement after the first season. He returned to write last
season's finale, a now-famous episode that created a shortage of
pinks slips at CBS. In that one show, Kelley eliminated six
characters in what he describes as a necessary effort to give
``Chicago Hope'' new life. Gone are Christine Lahti, Vondie
Curtis-Hall, Peter Berg, Jayne Brook, Stacy Edwards and Eric
Stoltz. To do the dirty work, Kelley brought back Mandy Patinkin as
Dr. Jeffrey Geiger, the ego that ate Chicago. As chairman of the
hospital's board, Geiger cashiered a handful of doctors, lambasting
each as only Geiger can.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley insists Geiger's tirade was not a criticism of the
quality of ``Chicago Hope,'' but he admits the show veered from the
path he'd originally intended, focusing more on personal
relationships and less on doctoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first road we went down was to explore the profession and
the pioneering aspects of medicine,'' Kelley said, ``and there's a
lot of those stories that remain to be told.'' Besides adding
Patinkin for occasional appearances next season, Kelley has brought
aboard Barbara Hershey, Lauren Holly and Carla Gugino, with more
newcomers on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kelley will continue to spend most of his time writing
``The Practice'' for ABC and ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Ally'' for Fox,
he has written the sixth-season premiere of ``Chicago Hope'' and
may do one or two more episodes. Otherwise, he will be an active
consultant, he says, similar to his role on the new ABC series,
``Snoops.''
</P>
<P>
   _ With elaborate production numbers, zany contests and an entire
episode filmed in China, ``The Drew Carey Show'' pushes the
envelope, and often overstuffs it. Next up is an effort likely to
be a collector's item among videophiles, no matter the outcome.
Sometime in November, an episode of the ABC series will air live
and partly unscripted, allowing cast members to improvise. There
will be three versions, so viewers in the Eastern/Central, Mountain
and Pacific time zones will each see a live show _ and one that
potentially is quite different from the others.
</P>
<P>
   Via ABC press release, executive producer Bruce Helford said,
``Anything can happen. I just hope they don't tap the keg until
after the third show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
