<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vexing close to season for Lopez
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The realization that his season is over too soon is
beginning to sink in for Javy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who has not previously had a season cut short, is
scheduled to have surgery to repair the torn anterior cruciate
ligament in his right knee on Monday at Piedmont Hospital. Dr.
Marvin Royster, who operated on Chipper Jones' knee in 1994, will
perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disappointing,'' Lopez said. ``I'm down and I have this
anger that I can't help the team win games, even though I have
confidence in Eddie Perez. He's been great. And Greg Myers has been
around for a while. But still it's going to be very difficult for
me to watch games and know I want to be there to help the team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez plans to stay in Atlanta for his surgery and recovery,
which should take about six months to the start of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the latest in a tumultuous season. Lopez's mother
died suddenly on May 7. He also has a second child on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this is the one year that everything happened,''
Lopez said. ``Hopefully, next year is totally the opposite, the
year 2000 will be the best of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot of stuff worse than (his knee) this year,''
Perez said. ``He wants to keep playing, to forget other stuff that
happened. But there's nothing he can do about it. He'll have his
surgery and work it up for next year. His mom passed away. He wants
to take care of his brothers and his dad. He's going to have a baby
later this year. I mean, he's worried about his knee and he wants
to play. It helps take away some of the things he worries about too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Odalis Perez waits
</P>
<P>
   Odalis Perez awaits word from Dr. James Andrews to see whether
his left elbow requires ``Tommy John'' ligament repair surgery. The
decision will come by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see my career over at 21 years old,'' Perez
said. ``If the doctor's decision is to have surgery, I'm ready for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he remembers feeling something on a pitch in the
third inning of the Yankees game on July 17. Perez gave up two of
the season-high eight runs in that inning. He made one more start
in Florida last Thursday, which lasted only four outs, before the
Braves put him on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's chance
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen will be making his second start as the Braves' fifth
starter tonight and not just the fill-in for an injured John
Smoltz. With the news that Perez is out for the year, Chen's job
just got that much more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still have the same approach,'' Chen said. ``Go out, give
the team innings and do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference in Chen's previous start _ when he pitched 7 2/3
innings and allowed only an unearned run for his first major-league
win _ was his breaking pitch. The Braves had him scrap the slow
curveball for a slider.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz good for now
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz knows well enough by now not to promise much beyond his
next start, considering the state of his tender elbow. So for now
all he can say is he'll be ready for his next start on Friday
against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about the next four or five starts, I can only
worry about the next one,'' said Smoltz, who had his first start
since coming off the disabled list on Saturday in Philadelphia.
``It's not going to just go away. Two different stints (on the
disabled list) haven't made it go away, all kinds of treatment
haven't made it go away.. . . There are going to be some good
starts and some bad ones. I'll just try not to make the bad ones so
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said another elbow surgery like he's had twice before
will not help his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Myers to work
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, manager Bobby Cox put a new player to work
quickly. Myers, the catcher the Braves acquired in a deal from the
Padres on Monday, caught Tuesday night's game against the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Myers played sparingly for the Braves in September of 1997 and
caught only Paul Byrd and Kerry Ligtenberg. So he'll spend the next
several days doing a lot of talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to get a good game plan (from the pitchers), see what
they like to do,'' Myers said. ``Talk to Leo (Mazzone), see what he
says they like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
