<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-ROYALTIES28-COX     07-27 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ROYALTIES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUTCHISON OIL AMENDMENT HITS SNAG
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dancing a parliamentary two-step Tuesday evening,
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, worked to salvage an amendment
protecting oil companies that drill in public lands from paying
higher royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison had hoped to delay any changes in federal royalty
rules until the year 2001, when a new and possibly more
oil-friendly president is in office.
</P>
<P>
   But her amendment, attached to an Interior Department
appropriations bill, got snagged in a procedural dispute after
Democrats insisted that the Senate comply with a rule banning such
``riders'' from spending measures. Aides said Hutchison was
adjusting the language of her measure in hopes of winning its
approval later.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, meanwhile, postponed action on the Interior bill
until late this week at the soonest.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's proposed moratorium would save major energy
companies an estimated $66 million a year in additional royalties.
The Interior Department says that oil companies now underpay fees
for drilling on federal lands because they are calculated on a
``posted price'' set by the companies instead of the actual market
price.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition that includes environmentalists, government waste
watchdog groups and American Indian groups have joined in urging
that the moratorium be lifted. The royalties support a variety of
purposes, including education, conservation and aid to Indian
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, who last week succeeded in attaching three tax breaks
for oil and gas to another bill, has argued that the industry needs
extra support. Although the price of oil has rebounded, she said,
``the industry _ and local economies that the industry supports _
have not.''
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium, if enacted, would be the fourth passed by
Congress to postpone higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   The energy industry is among the most active lobbying power in
Washington. A study by the Center for Responsive Politics estimated
that oil and gas interests spent $93 million on lobbyists in
1997-98 and $14 million in contributions to political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
