<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      07-27 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: CORPORATE CLIENTS WIN INTERNET FARES; ELECTRONIC
BOOKS; JAPAN'S MILLENNIUM TESTS; GREEN IN MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also moving in `t' category) 
(yn) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines' decision last week to make its discount
Internet fares available to corporate customers appears to have
been an important victory for travel managers, who are always
looking to hold down business fares.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pressure behind Delta's decision was applied by the
National Business Travel Association, which had argued that those
fares should be made available to corporations and that such
bookings should count toward the volume quotas that determine the
size of discounts that corporations negotiate with the airlines.
(Internet fares, which are typically lower than negotiated fares,
seldom appear in computerized reservations systems.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Northwest Airlines said it would soon test
negotiated rates and Internet fares for three corporations through
its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two months ago, Mark Johnson, the president of the travel
association, wrote to the major airlines to ask them to load
Internet fares into the computerized reservations systems so that
companies would have access to them. Delta's decision was announced
at the travel association's annual convention last week, even
though it will probably not go into effect until December.
</P>
<P>
   When Delta's plan does go into effect, it is expected to bypass
the computerized reservations systems in favor of its Sky Links
site and electronic tickets. The airline said traditional ticketing
costs $500,000 a year and is four times more expensive than booking
through its on-line site. Delta also hopes to implement a system of
direct payment that will eliminate credit card fees.
</P>
<P>
   But even while some details remain to be worked out, Norman
Sherlock, executive director of the National Business Travel
Association, said Delta's decision was a ``very significant
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We've been talking to other carriers, and we believe
they'll follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Books
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next Monday, British Airways passengers in first-class
or business-class lounges at O'Hare International Airport in
Chicago will be able to pick up an electronic book filled with the
equivalent of 400 pages of daily newspapers, current magazines,
financial information and perhaps even novels or nonfiction books.
Daily newspapers and financial information will be downloaded twice
a day. The e-books, as they are called, weigh 22 ounces and, at 7
by 6 inches, fit comfortably into a reader's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The trial period will last a month, while the airline gauges
consumer reaction with the goal of putting the books in its lounges
at all 22 U.S. airports to which it flies. It also is planning to
make e-books available on British Airways flights worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually passengers will be able to check out the e-books
before their departure flights and return them upon reaching their
destination, or when they complete their journey. If all goes well,
passengers will be able to phone and request a specific book or
books, to be downloaded into the e-book which they can pick up at
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Tests
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines, All Nippon Airways and Japan Air System each say
they have completed their Year 2000 computer tests and are now
fully compliant. Nevertheless the Japan Travel Bureau, the nation's
biggest travel agency, said it would not sell package tours with
flights that are scheduled to be in the air midnight Greenwich mean
time on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, the agency said, is concern that other countries
will not be fully compliant, and it ``puts the safety of its
customers first.'' The agency said it might reconsider, however, if
the International Civil Aviation Organization declared the world to
be 100 percent safe from the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Green in Michigan
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard for some to believe, especially when they think
of the Upper Peninsula in winter, but Michigan is now one of the
top golfing states. A 1998 report, recently released by the
National Golf Foundation, placed Michigan eighth nationally, behind
Florida, South Carolina, California, Texas, North Carolina, Arizona
and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who travel primarily to play golf, it trailed only
Florida, South Carolina, Texas and North Carolina. Michigan
officials say it has more public golf courses than any other state,
nearly 800, and that golfers contribute almost $1 billion annually
to the state's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
