<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDERCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY IS THE TOPIC AS GOLFERS HINT OF A RYDER CUP BOYCOTT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the United States battles Europe at the Ryder Cup in late
September, there may be a battle between the U.S. Ryder Cup players
and the PGA of America.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is money. This fall's Ryder Cup at the Country Club in
Brookline, Mass., will be the most profitable event in golf
history. An article in the September issue of Golf Digest reports
that the event will gross an estimated $63 million, while the PGA
of America, the organization conducting the competition, is
expected to net between $16.5 million and $17.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Players are not paid to compete in the Ryder Cup, nor do they
have a direct say in how the profits are spent. That does not sit
well with many of the golfers, who believe that they should be
paid, or that they should be allowed to allocate a significant
amount of money to the charity of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the Golf Digest article, David Duval, the world's
second-ranked golfer, suggested some players could boycott the
Ryder Cup if the money dispute was not settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen this September,'' Duval said when asked about
the possibility of a Ryder Cup boycott. ``More than likely, though,
next time in 2001. Certainly within two more. It's imminent. This
is just from talking to the guys. Some of them are fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   A boycott by Ryder Cup players would be a drastic move and a
potential public relations nightmare for everyone involved. The
players questioning the current system would prefer that their
complaints lead to a revised form of profit sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara was one of the first players to raise the issue of
paying Ryder Cup players two years ago, and he was sharply
criticized. But O'Meara is not alone in questioning the system.
Duval, Tiger Woods, Scott Hoch, Lee Janzen and Jack Nicklaus are
quoted in the Golf Digest report, expressing various degrees of
dissatisfaction with the situation. Both Woods and Duval insisted
that instead of making money off the event themselves, they would
prefer to see more money go to charity.
</P>
<P>
   For now, players receive a $5,000 stipend to play in the Ryder
Cup. Anyone who makes the team, however, automatically qualifies
for the World Golf Championships, a new event to be played next
month in Akron, Ohio. It is limited to players from this year's
Ryder Cup and last year's Presidents Cup. The purse for the event
will be $5 million, with the winner to earn $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials of the PGA of America have defended the
organization's right to make money, pointing out that it pays for
numerous golf and education programs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, $2.5 million of its television proceeds go to the
PGA Tour. Jim L. Awtrey, the chief executive officer of the PGA of
America, did not respond to phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it appears that unless the players are given more say
concerning the huge profits generated by this year's Ryder Cup,
this dispute will not go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the players, they're not going to have a Ryder Cup,''
Duval said. ``Let's take some of that big Ryder Cup pot and cut it
up and give it away to charity. That's supposed to be what we're
all about, isn't it? Something has to happen here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
