<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-27 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF MONEY, NOWHERE TO SHOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Next to the major-league fact books, the family
portraits and the potted plant on the shelf behind Kevin Malone's
tidy desk at Dodger Stadium stands a framed, black-and-white photo
of his most illustrious predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bow-tied, cigar-chomping Branch Rickey looking over
Malone's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey, in the history texts for escorting Jackie Robinson
across baseball's color line, was the Dodgers' general manager in
an era when the man in that chair could reshape his team _ or his
sport _ with a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. And Malone is reminded of that every day as the
Saturday-night trading-deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that I can do as much as I want to do,'' says the
young GM, not complaining but stating a fact.
</P>
<P>
   Malone doesn't want to change America. He just wants to win a
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And he must have thought that World Series ring was in reach
after he was hired last summer to run the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Once Malone was the GM in Montreal, where money was so short the
job might include planning the bake sales, and where the fans are
so indifferent, they see a run scored and call it a crease
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Now he sits in the newly furnished executive wing at Dodger
Stadium, watching batting practice through a floor-to-ceiling
window, and the only impossible dream should be emptying Fox's bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   How long did it take Malone to realize that the way baseball
runs its business these days, it's easier to be the GM of the Expos
than the Dodgers?
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, during the week of a trading deadline, Malone must
have felt like the most popular man in baseball. His filing cabinet
held the contracts of some of the hottest young talent on either
side of the border, and some of the most underpaid, making them
doubly attractive to rival GMs.
</P>
<P>
   If Malone figured he could get something by trading Carlos
Perez, there would have been no big contract to poison a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But if Malone wants to get rid of Perez now, the problem isn't
only the sky-high earned-run average (7.43) but also the contract
that promises the pitcher $12.5 million over the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And why single out Perez? The same problem applies to many of
the most trade-worthy Dodgers _ those high price tags they carry
around like radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   There's Eric Young, the second baseman who can't turn a double
play and is owed $4.5 million each of the next two seasons. There's
Jose Vizcaino, the platoon second baseman who's really a puffed-up
utility infielder and makes $3.5 million next year. There's Devon
White, the 36-year-old center fielder who attacks the wall only
when the ball's already over it and has $4 million and $5 million
years ahead. There are left fielder Gary Sheffield ($9.5 million
for each of the next four years), first baseman Eric Karros ($5.5
million next year) and Raul Mondesi ($9.5 million in 2000, $11
million in 2001), who would otherwise be the tastiest Dodgers trade
bait.
</P>
<P>
   As for closer Jeff Shaw, he has a no-trade contract.
</P>
<P>
   Each of them _ in fact, every Dodgers regular _ is under
contract for next season as well. If they were in first place, that
would be a blessing. Since they're in last, the that fact none of
them will be leaving for free agency means Malone is boxed in all
winter as well.
</P>
<P>
   Malone never had the luxury of dealing in long-term contracts
and seven-figure salaries in Quebec, or the headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you had limited financial resources, you still had
the resource of young players,'' he says of the simple life he left
behind in Montreal. ``So you always had clubs interested in your
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Expos lacked the Canadian dollars to hold onto those
players, there wasn't much question that saying ``yes'' to trades
for prospects was the way to go. Malone was under no pressure to
win every year, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers, it's a little more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the money, but we don't have the way to spend it. I
can't just go out and get who I want,'' Malone says. ``It's almost
like not having the resources. It's almost like Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   In Malone's little black book, squarely in front of him on the
desk, the numbers of the 29 other major-league GMs are crammed onto
two pages for quick reference. He estimates he's spending five
hours a day with a phone to his ear, not all of that chatting with
his counterparts. He has talked with ``80 or 90 percent'' of his
rivals in the past two weeks, including a couple of conversations
with San Diego's Kevin Towers, that most outspoken of Malone's
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes both lines are ringing and the cell phone is
ringing. But it's not always GMs wanting to make deals,'' Malone
says. ``Sometimes it's the media asking if something is going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The likely answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten clubs are probably looking to add a player. Ten clubs are
looking to trade if they can find what they're looking for. Ten
will stand pat,'' Malone says. ``When we won eight out of 10
(earlier in the month), we were more in a mode to add a player.''
</P>
<P>
   After Monday night's 5-3, 10-inning loss to Cincinnati, the
Dodgers had lost six of seven. Now they're in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're in a mode to unload (veterans),'' Malone
says. ``We like our talent level. This is the club we've committed
to. We're probably in the stand-pat category.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Committed'' is a nice way of saying big salaries and long-term
contracts make the trades the Dodgers would like darned-near
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably a little strong,'' Malone says of my
translation.
</P>
<P>
   A little.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this before you assume money is no object for the
Dodgers' new owners. Overpay a player and the team might be stuck
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this before you say Malone should just dump the
Dodgers' dead weight and pick up, let's say, Alex Rodriguez.
Turning this season around, or overhauling the roster for 2000,
won't be as easy as picking up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to give the fans something to cheer about the
rest of the season,'' Malone says.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck to him. And if Branch Rickey pops out of that picture
frame and decides to try the life of a GM in the '90s, good luck to
him, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a
week. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
