<SLUG> BC-WENDT-FUND-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CHIEF OF GE CAPITAL PLANS TO START BUYOUT FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary C. Wendt, who built GE Capital Services into a financial
powerhouse before leaving last year in a management shake-up, is
planning a buyout and private-equity investment fund that he would
run with other former GE Capital executives.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt expects to focus on Europe and Japan, two areas that have
attracted attention from big U.S. investors because of the large
amount of nonperforming Japanese debt, estimated at as much as $1
trillion, and the quickening pace of reorganizations and takeover
activity in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued late Tuesday, Wendt confirmed a Bloomberg
News report about his plans, saying he had not determined how much
money he would try to raise. He added that if he was able to garner
enough to begin a fund, he and his partners ``will not focus only
on highly leveraged investments but will stress operating
management, not simply financial acumen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, 57, declined to comment further on his plans, as did Paul
Street, a former senior executive at GE Capital and Lazard Freres,
who is expected to be part of the group. But a person close to the
situation said the group would seek to raise more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At GE Capital, Wendt built a reputation as a dynamic executive
who made the company into the biggest and most profitable unit of
General Electric. In his dozen years at the helm, profits at the
unit rose to nearly $4 billion from $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a messy divorce from his high school sweetheart,
Lorna J. Wendt, that ultimately gave him a higher national profile.
In their divorce proceedings, Mrs. Wendt rejected a settlement
offer of $10 million and sought half of Wendt's net worth, which
her lawyer estimated could be more than $100 million. In December
1997, a judge in Connecticut awarded Mrs. Wendt $20 million _ half
the Wendts' hard assets _ but a smaller part of Wendt's stock
options and future pension benefits. To many, her legal fight came
to serve as an exercise in determining the true economic value of a
corporate spouse.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Wendt's success at running GE Capital, he was said
to have had a strained relationship with John F. Welch, GE's chief
executive. During the divorce proceedings, for example, Wendt
acknowledged that he and Welch were not close. And in December,
when Wendt departed, Welch said that Wendt had not been considered
a candidate to replace him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   GE Capital has been very active in Japan, most recently buying
$11 billion in commercial loans from the Long-Term Credit Bank of
Japan. But a person close to Wendt's group said it would stay away
from the sort of investments that might also draw GE's interest.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Wendt's group would join a long list of U.S.
investment funds that have sought to cash in on the growing number
of takeovers, spinoffs and other reorganizations brought on, in
part, by the monetary union. Buyout firms that have set up offices
in Europe or begun funds recently include Apollo Advisors; the
Carlyle Group; Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice; Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst;
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts; Texas Pacific Group; and Warburg Pincus.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Blanks, a partner in Hicks, Muse, a Dallas buyout firm that
is putting together a $1.5-billion European fund, said that
according to IFR Securities, total mergers and acquisition activity
in Europe has risen fourfold since 1984, to almost $600 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe is really undergoing a fundamental change,'' Blanks
said. ``The watchword has become, `Get big, become competitive, or
lose out.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
