<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEEP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORY `DEEP BLUE SEA' IS BORING, BRAINLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After making two legendary flops in a row _
``Cutthroat Island'' and ``The Long Kiss Goodnight'' _ action
director Renny Harlin has pulled out all stops in trying to make
his killer-shark movie, ``Deep Blue Sea,'' into an
audience-pleasing, late-summer blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   If the audience is in a bloodthirsty mood, it could well work at
the box office. The film is a gauntlet of giant sharks jumping out
and gobbling up cast members regularly every 10 minutes or so, and
the visual effects are fairly convincing.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a no-brainer if there ever was one _ so broadly comedic
and filled with macho bluster that it's basically a cartoon, and
such a clumsy ripoff of ``Jaws'' and other, better films that it
often plays like a Zucker Brothers parody: ``Shark! _ the Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about an aquatic research facility off the coast of Baja
California where a group of scientists and medical researchers are
working with giant mako sharks, under the theory their primitive
but resilient brains hold a cure for Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But when the beautiful scientist heroine (Saffron Burrows)
secretly expands the creatures' brain capacity, they instantly
become so intelligent that, when a big storm temporarily
immobilizes the lab, the creatures more or less take over the place
and go after the humans.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the movie turns into a low-rent version of ``The
Poseidon Adventure'' with one ghoulishly mutilating shark attack
after another and a couple of clever and unexpected developments
along the way to give the illusion of originality.
</P>
<P>
   But it lacks real characters, drama and suspense. And we never
know where the endangered humans are trying to get to in their
flight, or how many of the intelligent killer sharks are after
them. As a result, the film is so uninvolving as basic storytelling
that it quickly becomes boring.
</P>
<P>
   Critical disclaimer: I have to acknowledge that ``Deep Blue
Sea'' could be somewhat better than it played to me, since I had
the handicap of seeing it Monday night at Seattle's City Centre
Cinemas with what may have been the rowdiest audience ever
recruited for a critic's screening.
</P>
<P>
   The entire row in front of me talked non-stop in loud voices,
yelled at the screen, often stood up to make gestures, passed a
bottle in a brown paper sack back and forth _ and, at one point,
broke into a small fight. Cellular phones rang throughout the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   When I fled to a seat in the rear of the auditorium, a man
sitting next to me received no less than seven cell phone calls,
and, at one point even (so help me) phoned a friend to describe how
the movie was progressing. I had a distinct feeling I was
witnessing the end of the movies as we know them.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Blue Sea. Directed by Renny Harlin. Written by Duncan
Kennedy, Donna Powers &AMP; Wayne Powers. Cast: Saffron Burrows, Samuel
L. Jackson, LL Cool J, Thomas Jane, Michael Rapaport. Warner Bros.
105 minutes. Rated R for explicit man-eating shark violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
