<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE-KNOWN STOCKS GAIN ON USUALLY RELIABLE ONES
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, individual investors have gotten rich in
the stock market by sticking to a couple of relatively simple
strategies: buying big-name companies whose products they know or
use and piling into stocks that have already been big winners.
</P>
<P>
   But these strategies appear to be losing steam. Some of the
stocks that have been the hottest _ companies as diverse as America
Online, Pfizer, Yahoo, Gillette and Dell Computer _ are down
considerably from their highs of earlier this year. Many of these
stocks have been outrun by companies few investors have ever heard
of.
</P>
<P>
   COX BUYING GANNETT CABLE UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is spending $2.7 billion in cash to acquire a
Gannett cable unit with 522,000 subscribers in Kansas, Oklahoma and
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT REBUFFS AMERICA ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the battle over whether users of its software should
be able to link into America Online's popular instant message
system, Microsoft rebuffed America Online's invitation to discuss a
possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA AND U.S. HOLD TRADE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States held trade talks in Beijing and
agreed to higher-level discussions later this year, a new sign of
slowly thawing relations. But they remained frozen on the most
prominent issue _ China's proposed entry into the World Trade
Organization. Deputy Commerce Secretary David Aaron met with
Chinese officials to discuss commercial issues. Yet the Chinese
only talked about trade organization membership indirectly, Aaron
said, and they showed no willingness to establish a timetable for
new negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House renewed trading privileges with China for
another year, separating United States commercial interests from a
long list of grievances Washington has with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING HOME CHAIN TO TAKE CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Enterprises said it would take a second-quarter charge
of $175 million to $225 million, which could equal earnings for the
last eight years, in anticipation of settling a Medicare fraud
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SURGE ON BARGAIN BUYING
</P>
<P>
   Stocks made their biggest gains of the month as investors sought
bargains. The Nasdaq rose 60.14 points, or 2.3 percent, to
2,679.33. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 15.08
points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,362.84. The Dow Jones industrial
average climbed 115.88 points, or 1.1 percent, to 10,979.04.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES INHALED FLU DRUG
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved a new inhaled drug to
treat influenza _ Relenza by Glaxo Wellcome _ overriding a panel of
independent scientific advisers.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE FELL IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence in the economy slipped in July from its
highest level in more than 30 years even as Americans said they
planned to increase their spending on big items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
