<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-CAMPAIGN-ART-     07-27 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NEW IMAGE, JACKSON CAMPAIGNS OUTSIDE A RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ With Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley set to address the Rev. Jesse Jackson's coalition of civil
rights groups and urban activists next week, Jackson says he will
not endorse either candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination until he sees which one seems more effective in
championing causes he considers crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not who will I endorse,'' Jackson said in an
interview here. ``The issue is whether they will endorse the
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley will have an opportunity to do that next week
at a four-day national conference of Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, where each candidate will give a speech. Officials with
both campaigns said they considered the conference an important
chance for them to address Jackson's core African-American and
liberal urban audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work very hard to get his support and earn his
support,'' said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the vice president.
``We're absolutely not going to take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who sought the Democratic nomination for president in
1984 and 1988 and is often mentioned as a potential candidate,
decided this spring not to run in 2000. He wants to use his
platform and political stature to influence the election from the
outside and ``set the climate for policy,'' he said on Monday at
the South Side headquarters of the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, the
organization he founded more than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says he wants to make sure the candidates _ and not
necessarily just the Democrats _ feel compelled to focus on issues
like health insurance for the poor, workers' rights, affirmative
action and more money for urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 57, said he decided not to run for president this time
because campaign financing has distorted the political process,
candidates are not as free to express controversial opinions and
non-candidates have greater ``moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, another reason is that it seemed clear he could not
win. Nonetheless, political analysts consider Jackson an important
figure in Democratic politics, one who is seen much less as a
controversial gadfly than as someone whose influence with potential
voters has increased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, a senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for
Political and Economic Studies, has been gauging Jackson's
popularity in surveys he has conducted in each of the last four
years. He said that whites are increasingly seeing Jackson in a
positive light.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 30 percent of whites surveyed viewed Jackson favorably
and 50 percent viewed him unfavorably, Bositis said. In a 1999
survey to be published in the next week or so, 57 percent of whites
viewed Jackson favorably and 29 percent regarded him unfavorably.
Bositis also said more self-described conservatives gave Jackson
favorable ratings than unfavorable ones.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Jackson's improved image is partly due to the
man himself and partly a reflection of the political climate. In
the 1992 presidential campaign, Bill Clinton, determined to show he
was not a traditional liberal Democrat, seemed to make a point of
distancing himself from Jackson and the black electorate by
criticizing Sister Souljah, a rap performer who once suggested that
blacks kill whites, at a Rainbow/PUSH Coalition convention. Now,
analysts and Democratic strategists say, the party appears more
well-rounded and the nation's strong economy makes Jackson's talk
about helping the disadvantaged seem less threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the national level there is no longer a sense that you're
going to be opening up the public coffers to tons of welfare
recipients if you say what Jesse Jackson agrees with,'' said Rachel
Gorlin, a Democratic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are less wary of Jackson. His role as Clinton's spiritual
adviser during the Monica Lewinsky scandal has given his religious
persona a higher profile, Bositis said. Jackson's campaign to
encourage corporate investment in urban neighborhoods has
introduced him to more business leaders. And his recent role in
freeing three American soldiers captured in Yugoslavia enhanced
Jackson's public image, even if his intervention rankled the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gorlin says he has evolved ``from being a figure who was
able to inspire fear'' to a point ``where he's almost reached a
statesman's status.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be a bogeyman,'' she added, ``and that's no longer
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Praising both Democratic candidates, Jackson, known for his
lyrical, passionate speaking style, suggested that the
less-than-galvanizing personalities of Bradley and Gore would not
hinder their campaign success.
</P>
<P>
   He described Bradley, who has talked a lot about racial issues,
as ``a very bright guy'' who ``has integrity'' and has ``sought to
deal with real issues.'' He said Bradley's ``background, as a
scholar, as an athlete, as a senator has given him the good
qualities of a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, said the two men have ``known
each other a long time'' and ``have a lot of respect for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson clearly has a closer relationship with Gore. Although
the two were rivals for the Democratic presidential nomination in
1988, Jackson said the campaign ultimately started a friendship
that was strengthened when Jackson comforted Gore after his son,
Albert III, almost died in an automobile accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has supported Jackson's son, Jesse Jr., an Illinois
congressman and has hired several former Jackson campaign
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so smart and so well-prepared,'' Jackson said. ``Gore has
been preparing his whole life for high national service.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was careful not to tip his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exhibition season,'' Jackson said. ``I want to see how
the game is played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
