<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GIULIANI-ARK-1STLD     07-27 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ARK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VISITS LIKELY SENATE OPPONENT'S ONE-TIME HOME TURF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout with new reporting that adds quotes from Clinton
spokesman, Giuliani, Huckabee; adds perspective on potential
Giuliani-Clinton Senate race; adds quotes from Little Rock
citizens; updates with reaction from New York and reporting on late
afternoon meetings in Arkansas.) (js) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stood
on the porch of Hillary Rodham Clinton's former home here Tuesday
morning, proclaimed his admiration for the people of Arkansas and
brushed aside the notion that his journey into the heart of Clinton
country was a gigantic publicity stunt to poke fun at his potential
opponent in next year's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in my personality to do anything like that,'' the
famously combative mayor said as he suppressed a smile.
</P>
<P>
   To thank Gov. Mike Huckabee and his other Republican hosts for
their hospitality, Giuliani then announced that he would fly the
Arkansas flag over City Hall for a few days _ an order that was
carried out within hours back in New York City. .
</P>
<P>
   Denials aside, Giuliani's trip here was clearly designed to
underscore his contention that Mrs. Clinton, who has never lived in
the state where she is planning to run for Senate, is a political
carpetbagger. But for most of his visit, the big city mayor played
straight man as Huckabee delivered the punch lines against the
first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been here before, he's never worked here, he's
never lived here,'' Huckabee said as Giuliani's aides smirked.
``Today he will be announcing his candidacy for some significant
major office in Arkansas, we're told.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's trip _ which had its origins in an offhand response
several weeks ago by Giuliani to Mrs. Clinton's ``listening tour''
in New York _ was the latest odd spectacle in the nascent Senate
campaign. The unofficial race has already seen the first lady
traipsing around upstate New York discussing the tribulations of
dairy farming, and Tuesday it featured the Brooklyn-born Giuliani
cheered on by Arkansas Republicans whose Deep South conservatism is
far from his more moderate stances.
</P>
<P>
   But while the two-day trip was billed as a fund-raising tour of
the South, Giuliani's six hours in Little Rock Tuesday seemed more
like a traveling circus, or at least a chaotic movie shoot. Local
camera crews shot footage of out-of-town camera crews. Out-of town
reporters interviewed local reporters. And Giuliani's press
secretary, Sunny Mindel, gleefully snapped pictures of them all.
</P>
<P>
   At the Governor's Mansion, as reporters and aides wilted in the
91-degree heat, waiters served pink lemonade and chocolate cookies
under a magnolia tree. And just outside the fancy iron gates _ near
a bust of a smiling former Gov. Bill Clinton _ a group of women who
called themselves The Vast Right Wing Conspiracy waved signs shaped
like hogs that read, ``Razorbacks for Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so tired of Bill and Hillary's scandals and we think
Rudy has done a good job'' said Jamie Simmons, who said she and the
other sign-wavers had traveled from Memphis, Tenn., to catch a
glimpse of Giuliani. ``We are probably more conservative than he
is, but if it's between him and her, he is the man for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Huckabee eagerly played his part, saying he was ``extremely
thrilled'' to have Giuliani as a guest and plying him with gifts,
including an ``Arkansas Traveler'' certificate that he said
designated the mayor as an official resident of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After touring the public rooms of the Governor's Mansion,
Giuliani proceeded to a fund-raising lunch at the Capital Hotel,
where 62 people paid $500 each for filet mignon and a 15-minute
speech in which the mayor boasted of his success as a Republican in
a largely Democratic city. The lunch raised about $40,000 for
Giuliani's political committee, and his aides predicted that he
would pull in at least $90,000 more at fund-raising events in New
Orleans Tuesday night and in Alabama on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Giuliani's trip, Howard Wolfson, spokesman for the
Clinton campaign's exploratory committee, said only, ``Instead of
playing politics, Hillary Clinton is listening to New Yorkers and
focusing on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the interest of reporters and politicians, many
people here seemed completely indifferent to Giuliani's six-hour
visit. Callers to the morning talk shows were more interested in
debating whether a portion of a downtown street should be renamed
after President Clinton. Shopkeepers and cabdrivers said they
barely knew who Giuliani was.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even some of the people who had written checks to his political
committee said they knew him only as the former prosecutor who had
cleaned up New York City. ``He's gone about things in a proper
manner,'' said Roger Crowe Gravis, a rice and soybean farmer who
came to the lunch in a seersucker suit. ``I think he'd be a credit
to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Freeman, who owns a software manufacturing company in
Jonesboro, Ark., 90 minutes from Little Rock, said that while
Hillary Clinton was ``really a nice lady,'' he preferred Giuliani's
politics. ``I know his beliefs are just like ours and he is really
a pretty neat guy,'' Freeman said as he emerged beaming from the
lunch with his wife, Lynda. ``What he's done for New York City, he
could do for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fund-raising event, Giuliani spoke before the Arkansas
Federation of Republican Women, whose former president, Joyce
Phillips, introduced him as not only ``one of the most dynamic and
exciting Republican figures on the political horizon'' but ``one of
the most recognizable faces on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   After somberly describing his efforts to cut crime and reduce
the welfare rolls and insisting to the audience that ``I haven't
really thought about Hillary much,'' Giuliani sped off to play a
round of golf with Lt. Gov. Win Paul Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in New York City, mayoral aides had wasted no
time in hoisting the Arkansas flag like a battle pennant over City
Hall, leaving Democratic lawmakers none too pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is politics pushing government a bit too far,'' said
Peter F. Vallone, the City Council speaker and a Democrat. Told
about Vallone's reaction, Giuliani laughed as if it were the best
joke he had heard all day. He defended his decision to fly the
Arkansas flag as ``an act of reciprocity,'' because the Capital
Hotel, where his fund-raising lunch took place, flew the New York
City flag Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the sort of weird world of New York politics would
anybody criticize that,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
