A6076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      07-27 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PLAN TO SKIP COMMITTEE STEP ON HMO BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders made a tentative decision
Tuesday to bypass their own committees in an effort to push
legislation regulating managed care through the House before the
August Congressional recess.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican aides said that Speaker J. Dennis Hastert was
looking to pass a ``modified'' version of legislation that the
Senate approved on a near party-line vote earlier this month and
that Hastert and other Republican leaders wanted the bill to hew as
closely as possible to a Republican package that squeaked by the
House last year on a 216-to-210 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Such a measure would go further than the Senate bill to extend
its consumer protections to 124 million Americans. The Senate, in
many of its provisions, covered 48 million people whose health
plans are rarely the most restrictive kind of managed care
arrangements that have raised most consumer concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from clear Tuesday night how far the Republican
leadership was willing to go on other divisive issues, like whether
to allow patients to sue their managed care providers in state
courts. Democrats and some Republicans have insisted that a
meaningful managed care bill must have an expansion of the right to
sue, which currently is limited.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican aide said leaders wanted to ``tinker'' with the
Senate bill. Another described the Senate measure as the ``starting
point'' and said it had not yet been decided how much the bill
would change on issues beyond the question of how many people would
be included.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he will veto any patients' protection
measure that resembles the Senate legislation, which he has called
``an empty promise to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republicans who are doctors and dentists have been
opposing their party's limited approach to regulating managed care.
One of them, Rep. Charlie Norwood, a Georgia dentist, was meeting
with Hastert Tuesday night. Norwood's spokesman, John E. Stone,
said that Norwood was planning to insist that his own consensus
bill _ which in many respects is closer to Democratic legislation _
be brought up for a vote in any floor debate. Stone said Norwood
would continue to fight the ``watered down, do-nothing Senate
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   John P. Feehery, spokesman for Hastert, did not minimize the
difficulties of assembling a Republican bill that could pass the
House given the narrow Republican majority, where a five-vote shift
can defeat any bill. ``The Speaker wants this on the floor next
week,'' he said, ``but it's going to be very, very difficult to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties consider health care issues to be potent with
voters, and the Democrats have been pushing for several years for
comprehensive regulation of the managed care industry and consumer
protections that would apply to all 161 million people with private
health insurance. Republicans have generally sought a more limited
approach.
</P>
<P>
   For months Hastert, who favors a limited approach, had allowed
two separate House committees to wrestle with the issue. But one
committee, which was considering legislation favored by the
leadership, has been stymied by the opposition of Norwood and his
allies.
</P>
<P>
   In another forum, the Commerce Committee, Chairman Thomas J.
Bliley Jr., R-Va., had been trying to negotiate a compromise with
John D. Dingell, D-Mich., who is the lead sponsor of the Democrats'
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis B. Fitzgibbons, an aide to Dingell, said the two had made
``great progress'' on issues such as who is covered and who decides
what care is medically necessary, but had not reached agreement on
questions such as the right to sue. Impatient Republicans, however,
charged that the Democrats were stalling to keep the issue _ and
House inaction _ center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert met with senior Republicans Tuesday. Several senior
Republican staffers said he made plans to take the issue away from
the committees and turn it over to the Rules Committee, which is
essentially an extension of the leadership. They said one member of
the Rules Committee, Rep. Porter J. Goss, R-Fla., was being asked
to act as an ``honest broker'' and assemble a bill that could draw
a Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Rules Committee was to begin considering questions on
Thursday about how to structure a health care debate, including
what number and kinds of amendments to allow to the floor. House
Republican leaders hope to hold the vote next week before the House
leaves for an August recess.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are expected to hold firm in favor of their own
approach to managed care, and oppose a more limited Republican
approach. ``If they are going to to hand the Democrats an issue on
this, the Democrats are going to accept it,'' Fitzgibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 20 Republicans are considered possible swing votes on
the issue, most particularly a small group of doctors and dentists
in the House who joined with the American Medical Association to
denounce the Senate Republican bill a few weeks ago. Besides
Norwood, they are Rep. Greg Ganske of Iowa, who is a reconstructive
surgeon, and two other physicians, Rep. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma and
Rep. John Cooksey of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, Coburn and Cooksey voted with their party a year ago,
but have been more rebellious this time around.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders plan to have a party caucus on managed
care Thursday, bringing over Senate Republicans to explain their
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would provide $13 billion in new tax breaks for
health care and give an array of rights to consumers, most
significantly creating an appeals process for 124 million Americans
in employer-sponsored health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the bill's protections _ such as access to an
emergency room outside of a managed care network, ``timely'' access
to specialists, and direct access to an obstetrician _ apply to
only 48 million people in self-financed plans offered by large
companies.
</P>
<P>
   These are rarely the kind of restrictive HMO arrangements that
have caused the most consumer concern because they channel patients
through a ``gatekeeper'' physician.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITTEN-MUSIC-2TAKES-     07-27 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITTEN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER BRITTENS, NOT SO WELL KNOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a composer, Benjamin Britten is not without detractors among
critics and concertgoers. But by any reasonable measure he is a
major figure, a 20th-century master whose arresting operas,
brilliant symphonic works, inventive chamber music and literate
songs hold deserved places in the repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Britten was also a gifted pianist who brought lucid musical
thinking and unmannered elegance to his playing, particularly as an
accompanist to singers. Murray Perahia, who became a good friend of
the composer in his later years, has said he was in awe of Britten
as a pianist.
</P>
<P>
   He was a fine conductor as well. But except in recordings of his
own music, including most of his operas, this aspect of his work
has not been widely appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   That situation may be about to change. In recent years London
Records, in its Decca Doubles series, has released some remarkable
performances with Britten conducting the English Chamber Orchestra.
These include what have become my favorite recordings of Bach's
``Brandenburg'' Concertos and ``St. John Passion,'' and insightful
performances of Mozart symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   Now BBC Music has issued five remastered CDs, with more to come,
in a series called ``Britten the Performer.'' Most document live
performances, though a few are taken from studio recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The series includes fascinating performances of Mozart,
Tchaikovsky and Mahler. Britten's 1961 performance of the Mahler
Fourth Symphony alone may alter current thinking about this popular
work.
</P>
<P>
   With the range and excellence of Britten's activities as
composer, pianist and conductor, he would be a strong candidate,
and my choice, for Musician of the Century. Of course, the current
rush of best-of-the-century lists is just so much intellectual
banter. But the breadth of Britten's musicianship is striking when
considered in historical context.
</P>
<P>
   This century has produced an unprecedented shift toward
specialization among classical musicians that has been of dubious
value. Pianists, for example, have pushed piano technique to new
realms of prowess. But overall musicianship and the musical
literacy of the public have declined.
</P>
<P>
   There would be lots of candidates for the title Musician of the
19th Century. Back then, a musician was by definition both a
composer and a performer. Chopin could not have spent one minute in
his life fretting over a choice between the two, because there was
no distinction.
</P>
<P>
   My selection for Musician of the 19th Century would probably be
Liszt, an original and influential composer, and by all accounts a
colossal pianist and a superb conductor, who, more than any other
musician of his day, championed the work of other composers. The
possible choices in the 18th century are even more numerous, though
Bach and Mozart are not-too-shabby candidates for the title.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th-century contenders are fewer, because specialization
has so changed the field. A few great musicians, like the pianist
Artur Schnabel and the conductor Wilhelm Furtwangler, both born in
the 19th century, composed regularly, not because they thought
their compositions would necessarily have lasting value but because
that was what musicians did.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Esa-Pekka Salonen, the exciting conductor of the Los
Angeles Philharmonic, is causing jitters among orchestra board
members by insisting that he be given time off to compose. His
works so far suggest that he is more valuable on the podium, but
his desire to keep composing should be encouraged. After all, the
musical understanding he gains by composing greatly enhances his
insight as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Who else besides Britten would be a contender? Pierre Boulez for
sure: a major conductor and an influential composer of impressively
wrought works. But Boulez's highly complex compositions will
probably be valued more by musicians and historians than by the
public at large, and reaching the public has to be considered when
it comes to such a populist notion as Musician of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein would be another possibility: a dynamic
conductor and, when he put his mind to it, an interesting pianist,
though his esteemed piano teacher, Isabella Vengerova, went to her
grave despairing that her brilliantly talented student did not
practice more.
</P>
<P>
   As a composer of American musicals, theater music and film
scores, Bernstein has certainly reached the public. But his concert
works, though stronger than many critics charge, are not of the
highest distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington was one of the most imposingly complete musicians
ever. Moreover, he was great at improvisation, a skill that also
used to be expected of musicians in earlier times but has
languished among classical artists during this one. Yet though it
has become unfashionable to say so, categories do serve a purpose,
and the jazz tradition in which Ellington was steeped is different
enough to warrant its own debate over the Musician of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Strauss and Stravinsky are plausible contenders. But
Britten, all things considered, remains my choice, at least within
the classical tradition. And the new releases featuring Britten as
a conductor (the intended topic of today's sermon, if you recall)
fortify the case for his encompassing musicianship.
</P>
<P>
   Britten's achievement as a conductor did not stem from brilliant
technique or even an ability to draw the most sonorous colors from
an orchestra. Rather, he brought the ear and intellect of a great
composer to his conducting. He was alert to unusual harmonic
progressions and the interplay of contrapuntal voices.
</P>
<P>
   Though he cared about faithful rhythmic execution, he cared more
about conveying rhythmic character. Most important, he was
remarkably astute about phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   Phrasing in music is somewhat analogous to sentence structure
and punctuation in prose. Each performer must study a composer's
score to determine its rhetoric, in a sense: How are the musical
sentences grouped? Where does the composer place musical commas, or
periods, or question marks?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These matters are more debatable in a particular piece than
nonmusicians might imagine. And even if phrase groupings are
indisputably clear, how much should a performer demarcate them? How
much time should be taken for that comma or between paragraphs? How
should the sentences flow?
</P>
<P>
   Britten had strong convictions about these questions, as the new
recordings compellingly reveal. The Mahler disk (BBCB 8004-2)
includes the 1961 account of the Fourth Symphony, with the London
Symphony at Orford Church in Suffolk. The English Chamber Orchestra
is the ensemble for the ``Lieder Eines Fahrenden Gesellen,'' with
the soprano Anna Reynolds in a 1972 performance, and two songs from
``Des Knaben Wunderhorn,'' with the soprano Elly Ameling in a 1969
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Mahler renaissance didn't really take hold until the 1950s
and '60s, and Britten was in the vanguard of that movement in
Britain. The scholar Donald Mitchell, who wrote the liner notes for
this recording, quotes a letter Britten wrote in 1944, at 29, in
which he refers to ``my precious Mahler Fourth (which I think I
have more genuine affection for than for any piece in the world).''
</P>
<P>
   That affection comes through here, along with a desire to
present the music with freshness and lucidity. The generally fleet
tempo he takes in the first movement will startle some lovers of
this work. But it rescues the music from the lugubrious melancholy
with which many conductors slather it.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly you hear ingenious structure and rhetorical clarity in
this 15-minute movement. If anything, the general buoyancy makes
the music's ruminative, bittersweet passages, for which Britten
gracefully yields the tempo, seem newly moving.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth movements are revelations. Because
Britten's understanding of structure is so keen, he can daringly
prolong the ``ruhevoll'' (``restful'') movement with no loss of
continuity. And in the finale, with its folkloric song setting for
soprano, Britten highlights the music's inner turbulence. Too
often, the song seems like a sweetly bucolic epilogue. Here it
emerges as a fully integrated conclusion to a four-movement
composition.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of the ``Lieder Eines Fahrenden Gesellen,'' sung
with tender simplicity by Ms. Reynolds, Britten shows how
insistently he is willing to articulate phrases. Each four-bar
segment of the theme is carefully shaped and noticeably separated
from the other phrases, lending logic and drama to this deceptively
simple song.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Das Irdische Leben'' from ``Des Knaben Wunderhorn,'' with
Ms. Ameling in rosy voice, Britten's keen ear for detail turns a
seemingly accompanimental orchestral part into something intricate,
shimmering and ominous.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of a wonderful Mozart recording (BBCB 8005-2) is a
1965 performance of the Piano Concerto No. 27 with Sviatoslav
Richter as soloist and Britten conducting the English Chamber
Orchestra. The concert was part of the yearly festival Britten and
his partner the tenor Peter Pears produced in Aldeburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The warmth, breadth and suppleness of the orchestra under
Britten's direction is interestingly contrasted with the cooler,
restrained beauty of Richter's playing. Yet conductor and soloist
are as one in matters of gesture and phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   A Tchaikovsky disk (BBCB 8002-2) contains, among other works,
the Serenade for Strings, in a 1968 performance with the English
Chamber Orchestra that wondrously combines Neo-Classical textural
lightness with vibrantly lyrical phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity of Britten's pianism in a disk of songs, vocal
duets and quartets by Tchaikovsky, Rossini and Brahms, from a
soiree at Aldeburgh (BBCB 8001-2), is not surprising, since his
work as a song accompanist has been well documented in other
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this one is special. An impressive roster of
participating artists sound palpably happy to be making music
together: the soprano Heather Harper, the mezzo Dame Janet Baker,
Pears, the baritone Thomas Hemsley and, sharing the piano-duet
duties in Brahms' ``Liebeslieder,'' Claudio Arrau.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a studio recording of Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas''
from 1959 (BBCB 8003-2), with Claire Watson and Pears in the title
roles, is a dramatically affecting and musically distinguished
account of a work then overlooked. Britten revered Purcell and
performed his music at a time when knowledge of Baroque performance
practice was largely confined to the groves of academe. Here he
conducts from an edition he prepared with his friend Imogen Holst,
the English editor and composer.
</P>
<P>
   So add Purcell scholar, concert producer and festival organizer
to the list of activities with which this Musician of the Century
involved himself.
</P>
<P>
   I rest my case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
