<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 1,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VENICE-BIENNALE (Venice, Italy) _ To look at new art is to
expect to feel something or be told something or be tweaked or
entertained in ways that have nothing necessarily to do with
tangible objects. Art less and less is judged by the old priorities
of painting, sculpture and drawing. It is context that increasingly
determines the shape of the art we see. Exhibit No. 1: the 48th
Venice Biennale. It's commonly being said about the show that video
art dominates, which is true, but only up to a point. By Michael
Kimmelman. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHEREAU-FILMS (Undated) _ Part enfant terrible and part national
treasure, Patrice Chereau has built a formidable reputation in
France, with three decades of groundbreaking work in theater, opera
and, increasingly, film. His latest movie, ``Those Who Love Me Can
Take the Train,'' had its premiere at the Cannes International Film
Festival last year. By Leslie Camhi. (Moved). Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ILLUMINATA-FILM (New York) _ It's twilight _ the haunting hour
that mingles longing and regret, promise and speculation _ and the
world's youngest method actor is brooding in his Brooklyn bedroom.
``Usually, I (italics)like(end italics) challenging roles,'' says
Amedeo Turturro with the magnificent assurance of an 8-year-old.
``But that role was so challenging, they practically had to force
me to do it.'' The ``they'' he's referring to are his parents, the
actors John Turturro and Katherine Borowitz. The ``it'' is
``Illuminata,'' an engagingly heartfelt new film in which all three
appear. ``Illuminata,'' which opens on Friday, is about a stock
company of 19th- century actors, and the Turturro family has pretty
much become a stock company, too. Husband and wife have performed
together in three plays and three movies, two of which Amedeo
cameoed in. By Franz Lidz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-TAPE-THEATER (Undated) _ ``Starr's Last Tape,'' a one-man
play in which a character named Starr, dressed in a prison jump
suit and surrounded by tapes abnd tape recorders, sings hymns,
tunes in to phone taps and dictates his memoirs. The play will have
its world premiere in Stockbridge, Mass., at the Berkshire Theater
Festival's second stage, the Unicorn, from Aug. 24 through 28.
Brian Reddy, who played Stephen Douglas in the 1993 Lincoln Center
Theater revival of ``Abe Lincoln in Illinois,'' will star as
Kenneth N. Starr, directed by Eric Hill. By Sylviane Gold.
(Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARNIVAL-CENTURY-FEST (New York) _ To many New Yorkers, Lincoln
Center Out &UR; - &LR; of &UR; - &LR; Doors has always been there _ a three-week
extravaganza every August that offers a diverse fare of free dance,
music and theater. The forthcoming series, the ``Carnival of the
Century,'' starting Friday, is solidly within that tradition. It
includes the jazz pianist Dave Brubeck, a Greek blues singer, Les
Ballets Trokadero de Monte Carlo, music of the Jewish Diaspora, a
Peruvian dance company and the Colorado String Quartet, plus
entertainment designed just for children. By Valerie Gladstone.
(Moved). Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PEONY-PAVILION-MUSIC (New York) _ It's no use either admiring or
picking apart the Lincoln Center Festival '99. Management had
co-designers imposed on it, Shanghai bureaucracy and Lady Luck
among them. The last-minute cancellation of ``The Peony Pavilion''
in 1998 left a hole in the center of the event a year ago. The
resuscitation of this 19-hour Ming Dynasty classic in 1999 was
welcomed by nearly everyone, but it certainly altered any theme
Lincoln Center might originally have had in mind. By Bernard
Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BRITTEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ As a composer, Benjamin Britten is not
without detractors among critics and concertgoers. But by any
reasonable measure he is a major figure, a 20th-century master
whose arresting operas, brilliant symphonic works, inventive
chamber music and literate songs hold deserved places in the
repertory. BBC Music has issued five remastered CDs, with more to
come, in a series called ``Britten the Performer.'' Most document
live performances, though a few are taken from studio recordings.
The series includes fascinating performances of Mozart, Tchaikovsky
and Mahler. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROPAGANDA-PHOTOGS (Washington) _ The word propaganda originally
meant spreading the religious faith; it acquired a generally
pejorative sense only in World War I, when governments took strict
control of war information that could be used in the mass media.
Long before, every medium that could spread ideologies or enhance
renown and power had been called upon to do so. Popes and kings and
dictators commissioned architecture, sculpture and painting,
enlisted playwrights and speakers, and hired designers to shape the
ruler's image and fashion the servants' livery as well as the
military's uniforms. When photography came along, it, too, was soon
pressed into service. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-BOOKS-COLLECTING (Undated) _ Since the early '90s, prices
for first editions of modern literary works have hit the
stratosphere: $35,000 for a signed copy of Jack Kerouac's ``On the
Road''; $250,000 for a copy of ``Ulysses'' signed by James Joyce to
Ezra Pound, and $15,000 for Harper Lee's ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
The gold rush in such literary ``high points'' _ the industry term
for well known titles by name authors _ has also fostered
speculation in recently published books _ first editions printed
within the last five years that are still in pristine condition and
preferably signed by the author. By Christa Worthington. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ONCE-AGAIN (Undated) _ A look at ABC's forthcoming drama
series ``Once and Again,'' which will be introduced for seven
weeks, starting Tuesday, Sept. 21, at 10 p.m. By Bernard Weinraub.
(Moved).
</P>
