<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLU-DRUG-590&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      07-27 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-DRUG-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCY APPROVES ANTI-FLU DRUG, OVERRIDING RECOMMENDATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Food and Drug Administration on Tuesday
approved a new inhaled drug to treat influenza, overriding a panel
of independent scientific advisers who five months ago recommended
the drug be kept off pharmacy shelves because it is only marginally
effective and may be dangerous for asthma patients.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, Relenza by Glaxo Wellcome, brings to three the number
of antiviral medications now available to treat the flu. Relenza is
the first flu medicine approved to treat both type A and type B
strains of influenza, as opposed to type A only, and it is the
first in a new class of drugs that block the spread of flu germs
throughout the body by inhibiting an enzyme called neuraminidase.
</P>
<P>
   In giving Relenza its imprimatur, the Food and Drug
Administration took a rare step; the agency almost always follows
the advice of its scientific experts. But with so few flu medicines
on the market, Dr. Heidi Jolson, the agency's official in charge of
reviewing Relenza, said the drug merited approval despite the
``very legitimate'' concerns that prompted the panel to reject it
by a 13-to-4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Influenza is a major public health problem,'' Dr. Jolson said.
``There are deaths each year. We think it is a public health
priority to make new medications available if they are found to be
safe and effective.'' She added: ``We feel that this drug has been
found to be effective, but to a modest degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Relenza has been approved for adults and adolescents
ages 12 and older, the drug's label states it has not been proven
effective, and may pose a risk for patients with severe asthma or
other breathing disorders. In clinical studies, some asthma
patients experienced ``bronchospasm,'' a shutting down of the
airways, after taking the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the drug been proven effective for preventing the flu.
Officials at Glaxo Wellcome said on Tuesday that they expected the
medicine to be available sometime next fall, but have not yet set a
price.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, about 30 million Americans suffer the flu. Most
recover after a week of fever, aches and pains, but the disease
kills an estimated 20,000 people annually in this country, most of
them elderly. Although infectious disease experts say the flu
vaccine is still the best safeguard against influenza, many had
high hopes for Relenza, which has already been approved in
Australia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of the medication has been the subject of
intense debate. In foreign studies, Relenza, which goes by the
generic name zanamivir, alleviated the fever and pain associated
with flu roughly two to two and a half days sooner than a dummy
medication. But the drug did not work as well among patients in the
United States; in a study of 777 North Americans, most of them in
this country, Glaxo Wellcome reported that Relenza cut the
seven-day course of the flu by just one day.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jolson attributed the difference to the Americans' use of
over-the-counter cold remedies, which made patients feel better and
confounded the scientists trying to analyze Relenza's effect. Yet
there was division about the findings even within the Food and Drug
Administration; when an agency biostatistician analyzed Glaxo
Wellcome's results, he found that the effect among North American
patients was even more marginal than the company reported, and
concluded Relenza was no better than a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jolson said the agency's medical reviewers did not agree
with the statistician, but the scientific panel found his evidence
persuasive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Leslie Hendeles, a professor of pharmacy at the University
of Florida who served on the committee, explained his reasoning on
Tuesday. ``To me,'' he said, ``if you are sick for seven days and
you take a medicine and you are sick for six days, then you are
still sick for six days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Michael Elliott, who directs influenza research at Glaxo
Wellcome, said the benefits of the drug should not be discounted.
``A day or a day and a half may not sound very great,'' Elliott
said in a telephone interview on Tuesday. ``But to a patient
suffering the flu, the fever and pain and body aches, if you could
reduce that by a day and a half, that is very important. Think of
parents at home, or self-employed people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
