<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: EYES WIDE OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Everyone has been calling, wanting all the gruesome
details.
</P>
<P>
   They ask how it feels when the little lawn-mower device slices
off your corneas and the red laser beams sear your eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   They want to know the price of vanity. Is it worth the risk and
the pain? It occurs to me that we'll never have Omaha Beach, but
thank heaven my generation can exhibit bravery under laser fire.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them that reclaiming 20-20 in five minutes with a laser
feels like one of those old Roger Corman horror movies. First,
you've got to be alarmed by any technology that was developed in
Russia. Second, anyone weaned on Rod Serling is bound to stew about
eerie side effects.
</P>
<P>
   On the operating table in a suburban mall, my eyes propped open
with some scary little eye-propping-open metal things, I felt like
Ray Milland in ``X: The Man With the X-Ray Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was fun for Ray, a scientist named Dr. James Xavier,
when he first drips in his eyes the serum he has invented to extend
the limits of sight. ``My dear friend,'' his partner, Sam, tells
him, ``only the gods see everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear doctor,'' Ray replies, ``I'm closing in on the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   He happily peers through walls and women's dresses. But then he
starts seeing too much _ veins and organs and rushing blood. He
ends up working for Don Rickles in a carnival freak show before
plucking out his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Moral: Leave nature alone.
</P>
<P>
   I told my friends I could see great now, although I knew I would
miss the blurriness at certain moments _ on bad dates, at Iowa
straw polls, frowning in the mirror at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   But they ignored me. They know I always look on the dark side.
If only there were a laser that corrected fatalistic Irish vision.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, boomers are addicts of appearances, the whitening and
tightening, the peeling and priapic products. We are a generation
of Dr. Frankensteins and our monster is us. We don't mind perishing
by the image as long as we get to live by the image.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, we want to see clearly while looking for creative new
ways to indulge the self. There are, after all, so few reliable
ways to turn back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   For the most self-regarding generation in history, the hands on
the clock are swinging wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Our first boomer president is about to retire to the New York
dinner-party circuit. The Age of Aquarius has become the Age of
Collagen.
</P>
<P>
   This month's Vogue has a heart-warming, first-person account of
a daughter who is ``finally able to give something back,'' by
arranging her mother's face lift.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs clog the mailbox, filled with snake-oil promises,
mysterious chemicals and odd devices. The Self-Care catalog offers
Brain Gum to improve ``cognitive functions by restoring a healthy
level of phosphatidylserine in the brain''; the ``Lip Enhancer,''
which ``through a gentle vacuum process ... keeps lips full and
plump up to 12 hours between uses''; Infusia lotion to diminish the
appearance of spider veins, and something that looks as if it had
been invented by the wacky secretary Elaine on ``Ally McBeal'' _
the magnetic face mask, said to increase blood flow to tone facial
muscles. Sagging skin will be gone anon, the blurb vows: ``The
mask's 19 gold-plated magnets have a powerful 1,500-gauss surface,
and are strategically located at your facial acupressure points.''
</P>
<P>
   (In a related development, an Allure magazine ``news bulletin''
announces: ``Bio-mecanica's battery-powered suction bra builds a
bigger breast.'')
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post recently ran a front-page article on the
remarkable boom in sales for products featuring the words
``anti-aging'' or ``age-defying.'' In the last six years, it says,
sales of ``age-repair'' potions filled with weird ingredients like
tanbark oak and chardonnay grape-seed extract have grown from $325
million to $3.6 billion, and at last count there were 1,700
different anti-wrinkle creams vowing to release the luminescence
trapped under those icky old dead skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   It's a losing battle, of course.
</P>
<P>
   We can play with our lasers and magnets and suction and magic
elixirs all we want. We can get phosphatidylserine and
phyto-nutrients pumping. We can Viagrandize to the max. But gravity
and french fries will eventually have their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
