<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GASOLINE-ADDITIVE-NYT     07-27 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-ADDITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OFFICIALS DIVIDED OVER USE OF GASOLINE ADDITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Neb.) (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State environmental officials were divided on
Tuesday over whether Congress should act to reduce the use of MTBE,
a chemical used in gasoline that helps keep the air clean but
sometimes pollutes water.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies were also beginning to figure out how to comply
with the possible change in the rules, while producers of ethanol,
a competing chemical, began work to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, one of the most aggressive states in fighting
air pollution, Nancy L. Seidman, deputy director of the Department
of Environmental Protection, said she worried about what oil
companies would use in place of MTBE. Ms. Seidman said the state
had lost the use of some wells from contamination by MTBE, which,
when leaked, dissolves in water, but ``we're not convinced there
are significant water-supply issues here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials responsible for air quality said that the public
seemed to be more concerned with water pollution from MTBE, which
scientists say may be carcinogenic, than air pollution from
components of gasoline that are proven to cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what you can see and taste versus what you can't,'' said
Jane K. Stahl, the deputy commissioner of the Connecticut
Department of Environmental Protection, in Hartford. ``What made
MTBE come to the forefront is that you could smell it in your
water, and taste it. It smells like you're drinking gasoline, and
that's very scary and very offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Stahl and officials in other states said MTBE was
generally not a public health hazard. She said, though, that they
favored gradual reductions in MTBE use to reduce the risk to water.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed a law in 1990 that resulted in heavy MTBE use in
California and on the East Coast in an effort to cut carbon
monoxide and smog. But clean air experts say its main benefit has
been a reduction in more toxic cancer-causing chemicals in
gasoline, like benzene and toluene. When spilled, though, MTBE
moves through the soil faster than those natural hydrocarbons and
has made some wells useless because it makes the water reek.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of experts appointed by the Environmental Protection
Agency formally reported Tuesday on MTBE, and said its use should
be reduced substantially. Carol M. Browner, the agency's
administrator, said even before the report was released that she
would work with Congress to modify the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act amendments of 1990 require that areas with air
pollution problems use reformulated gasoline that includes an
``oxygenate,'' a molecule that incorporates an oxygen atom. MTBE is
used in 85 percent of reformulated gasoline, while ethanol, which
is made from corn, accounts for almost all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Ethanol producers were planning legislative strategy to maintain
their market, which exists mostly because of the oxygenate
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Todd C. Sneller, the administrator of the Nebraska Ethanol
Board, a state agency, said that ``it would be difficult to advance
a proposal to eliminate the oxygen standard without some
ethanol-related provision,'' and that Congress still liked
ethanol's ability to reduce oil imports and greenhouse gas
emissions. ``The agriculture lobby and the ethanol lobby can have
some influence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sneller said that in the next 10 days supporters in Congress
would introduce legislation requiring that some fraction of
gasoline come from ``renewable'' sources like ethanol, just as some
states, in restructuring their electric utilities, were requiring
that each company have some electricity from renewable sources,
like solar or wind power.
</P>
<P>
   The big oil companies started making MTBE in the early 1980s as
a substitute for lead, which the government had ordered be phased
out of gasoline. Both lead and MTBE raise octane, which is a
measure of gasoline's ability to withstand premature detonation in
an engine.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, MTBE and ethanol are used in places where no
oxygenate is required. So even if the oxygenate requirement is
dropped, it will continue to be used, although at lower levels, oil
executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of oxygenates said that incorporating an oxygen atom
into the fuel makes the mixture in a car's cylinders leaner, and
thus cuts pollution. But in the years since the mandate, cars have
been built with sensors that continuously sense the richness of the
mixture, and adjust the fuel-air mixture accordingly, leading some
experts to say that oxygenates are no longer so useful for
controlling carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies, though, have always maintained that Congress'
reason was political, to help corn growers, and reduce reliance on
imported fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Robert H. Campbell, the chairman and chief executive of Sunoco,
said that if the oxygenate requirement were lifted, his company
would probably reduce its use by 70 to 80 percent, but that
something else would have to take MTBE's place, and ``they're not
going to let us use benzene or other compounds they consider very
toxic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's going to have to invest in producing other barrels
to fill that gap,'' he said, because customers would want the same
number of gallons. A likely candidate to make up the volume, he
said, is alkylates, a class of chemicals produced in refineries by
taking smaller molecules and combining them; the smaller molecules
can cause pollution because they are prone to evaporate before they
are burned, and form the raw materials for smog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
