<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-GEORGIA-COX     07-27 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heisman watch: Launching Carter's campaign
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Quincy Carter sat at a table at the front of
the main auditorium in the Sheraton Civic Center, surrounded so
completely by sportswriters and microphones and tape recorders that
he could hardly turn his head. He fielded all manner of questions,
some of them inane, others pointed. He'd barely get the answer out
for one, then it would be followed by another.
</P>
<P>
   As Carter was ushered to a van that would take him, coach Jim
Donnan and teammate Orantes Grant to their waiting plane, he was
followed through the atrium, down the escalator and out the doors
of the hotel by a column of query-tossing reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It's official. Quincy Carter's Heisman Trophy campaign has
begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just taking it all in stride,'' Georgia's sophomore
quarterback said when asked if he was prepared for the media
onslaught. ``My teammates know what kind of guy I am. We don't talk
about it at school. I try to downplay it so everybody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tuesday's events during the first day of the SEC Football
Kickoff are any indication, Carter's going to find it difficult to
hide from the limelight this year. And unless Georgia's largely
unproven cast around Carter can provide him some protection,
Carter's going to find it equally as difficult to evade opposing
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   That, in a nutshell, was Carter's message here on Tuesday. He
can win neither cames nor the Heisman by himself, nor does he plan
to try to.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the Heisman Trophy, you've got to win games and, to do
that, you have to have some good people around you,'' Carter said.
``I think we've got that. It feels good to be a Heisman candidate
but you can't do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other individuals will have to step to the forefront for
that to happen. The Bulldogs lost their two starting tackles to the
first- and second-round of the NFL draft, their top four receivers,
both tight ends and their leading rusher off the 1998 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Quincy's really crossed the bridge in terms of his
development and this is a big year for him,'' Georgia coach Jim
Donnan said. ``I just hope he can get some help, more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's Heisman Trophy candidacy was endorsed by at least one
other coach attending Tuesday's meetings, LSU's Gerry DiNardo.
</P>
<P>
   It was DiNardo's Tigers who saw Carter at his very best last
season. The beleaguered LSU stood awed on the Tiger Stadium
sideline last as he watched Carter torched his team for 318 yards
passing, 41 yards rushing and two touchdowns en route to a 28-27
upset victory before a sold-out crowd and a national television
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, it's legitimate,'' DiNardo said of Carter's
Heisman campaign. ``He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   While DiNardo lauded Carter's passing and scrambling ability,
it's another trait he said that sets the Georgia quarterback apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was scrambling around on our sideline and our guys hit him
hard, so hard one time that his mouthpiece came flying out of his
helmet,'' DiNardo said. ``But he just reached out, picked up that
mouthpiece, popped it back in his mouth and ran back to the huddle.
Now that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since Herschel Walker drew Heisman consideration as a
freshman and mounted a full-fledged campaign the next year has a
Georgia sophomore experienced such a concentrated push for college
football's top award so early. But after starting all 12 games and
breaking all of Eric Zeier's freshmen passing records for attempts
(290), completions (176), yards (2,484) and touchdowns (13), Donnan
and the UGA publicity machine felt there was no reason to put off
Carter's candidacy. He's featured on the `99 media guide's cover,
with ``Heisman Trophy candidate'' printed in white type across his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like for our players to get individual awards,'' Donnan
said. ``I don't think it's more pressure on him, per se. He's got
enough pressure just playing quarterback at Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The general feeling is last season was just the tip of the
iceberg for Carter. He was unable to practice or study Donnan's
offensive system until a month before the first game of last
season. This year, he's been intensely schooled and even left
professional baseball a month early this summer to join volunteer
workouts with his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was doing pretty good last year But I realize now
I know I lot more now than I did then,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   With a high-profile publicity campaign also comes scrutiny, and
Carter was asked about his partnership with agent Eugene Parker and
the chances of his turning professional at the end of the season.
He deftly dodged each query, insisting he wasn't thinking about the
pros and limiting his focus to the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, however, didn't mince words on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't need to go pro,'' said the fourth-year Georgia
coach. ``At the end of the season, we'll get together and talk
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly:
</P>
<P>
   At least three pieces of Georgia news were revealed during
Tuesday's media conference: Freshmen wide receiver Durell Robinson
will indeed come in as a partial qualifier, senior Adrian
Hollingshed will be moved back to linebacker from defensive end and
former tight end Ian Knight has been moved to back-up center behind
senior Miles Luckie.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
