<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUTKO-OBIT-COX     07-27 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTKO-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats mourn friend, lobbyist
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dan Dutko, a Washington lobbyist and political
powerhouse with deep ties to Texas Democrats, died Tuesday in
Colorado, two days after a bicycling accident during a ride with
former state Land Commissioner Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko, a prodigious fund-raiser for Democrats, was co-chairman
of the Democratic National Committee's fund-raising drive for the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who has endured personal and political hardship in recent
years with a stiff upper lip, called Dutko's death ``the worst
thing that ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was one of my lifelong friends. Seeing something like this
happen is . . .,'' Mauro said, unable to find the words.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Tuesday praised Dutko, 54, a Democratic
National Committee member, as a longtime friend, ally and adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He enriched our lives with his enthusiasm and served his
country with distinction,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro and Dutko were in Aspen for a Saturday fund-raising event
featuring Clinton. The three men met in 1972 while working in Texas
for George McGovern's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko, Mauro and Austinite Kelly Vidovic were riding together
Sunday among a group of riders heading down Maroon Creek Road in
Aspen. Mauro said all went well until the weather changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started raining, and we were going down a hill, and he lost
control of the bike and went over the handlebars,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko was not wearing a helmet. Mauro did not initially think
the fall was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected him to jump up and be upset because we were going
to have to go to the emergency room and get some stitches,'' said
Mauro, adding that he knew it was far more serious once he got to
Dutko.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko was taken to Aspen Valley Hospital and later transferred
to St. Mary's Hospital in Grand Junction, where he died Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado State Patrol said the accident was caused by
``rider inexperience.'' Dutko ``possibly'' activated the front
brake of the mountain bike, a maneuver than can jettison a rider
over the handlebars, according to the state patrol.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Streator, Ill., Dutko served in the Air Force from
1962 to '66. He worked as a missile systems test engineer for
Eureka Williams in Illinois and later for San Angelo Communications
and Electronics in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He began his political career in 1972 as West Texas coordinator
for McGovern and later worked for Bob Bullock, then the state
comptroller, in the agency's San Angelo office.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to Washington, Dutko was chief of staff for
then-U.S. Rep. Bob Krueger of Texas and then-Sen. Donald Stewart of
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, he formed The Dutko Group, a Washington lobbying firm
that now bills itself as ``bipartisan and multidisciplinary'' with
partners who are ``personally connected, at the highest levels, to
the Republican and Democratic parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's client list includes Longhorn Partners Pipeline Co.,
which wants to pump gasoline to El Paso through a dormant crude oil
pipeline that runs through South Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko was vice chairman for finance in the 1996 presidential
campaign and finance chairman for Clinton's 1997 inauguration. This
year, he was raising money for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, longtime political operative Bob Mann said he shared
a small apartment on South Congress Avenue with Dutko and others
when they worked on Krueger's unsuccessful 1978 senatorial race
against Republican John Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was an old liberal who had matured and probably still had
those instincts but learned, as many of us do as we get older, to
compromise and see the two sides to every story,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Dutko is survived by his wife, Deborah Jospin, director of
AmeriCorps, and sons Jonathan, 6, and Matthew, 5.
</P>
<P>
   A private funeral and burial are scheduled for Thursday in
Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is scheduled for Monday at 1 p.m. at Temple
Sinai in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
