<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- TEN-WHEELCHAIR, 07-28 --
Stephen Welch, the No. 2 wheelchair tennis player in the world,
during a practice session at the National Tennis Center in Flushing
Meadows, Queens, on Tuesday. Welch will lead the top-seeded United
States team against Poland on Wednesday in the quarterfinal round
of the World Team Cup. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- CENTRAL-AFRICA-WILDLIFE,
07-28 -- A western lowland gorilla and baby at the Bronx Zoo's new
Congo Gorilla Forest. The gorillas are among Central Africa's
increasingly endangered animals. Even as the many combatants in
Congo discuss peace, the war is also clearly disrupting a complex
dynamic among animals, local people and rich foreign tourists that
some conservationists believe is the best hope for saving the
dwindling wildlife of Africa. (Wildlife Conservation Society/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) JERUSALEM -- July 27, 1999 -- ISRAEL-BURG, 07-27 --
Avraham Burg and his father, Yosef, at Parliament in Jerusalem. The
son, a popular figure like his father, hopes to tame the unruly
chamber. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CHICAGO -- July 28, 1999 -- JACKSON-CAMPAIGN, 07-28 --
Rev. Jesse Jackson in the space that will house the Rainbow/Push
Coalition radio and television broadcast studio on Tuesday.
Jackson, who sought the Democratic nomination for president in 1984
and 1988 and is often mentioned as a potential candidate, decided
this spring not to run in 2000. This time, he wants to use his
platform and political stature to influence the election from the
outside and, as he says, ``set the climate for policy.'' (Cynthia
Howe/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WESTBURY, N.Y. -- July 28, 1999 -- FBI-COMPUTERS, 07-28
-- A controller at the New York Terminal Radar Approach Control
where arrivals and departures from various regional airports
especially John F. Kennedy, LaGuardia and Newark airports are
controlled. The Clinton administration plans to deploy a system of
monitoring software to protect the nation's data networks from
intruders. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 27, 1999 -- SERIAL-KILLERS, 07-27 --
Amy Kalafa, seated, and Maxine Paul, whose documentaries on killers
include one with David Berkowitz, aka Son of Sam. The program that
includes the interview with him is being broadcast Wednesday night
at 10 on Court TV, which bought their project, called ``Inside the
Criminal Mind,'' and is showing it as part of the cable network's
regular prime-time series ``Crime Stories.'' (Joyce Dopkeen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LAGOS, Nigeria -- July 27, 1999 -- NIGERIA-KUTI, 07-27
-- Femi Anikulapo-Kuti has taken over the role of his father, Fela,
as a musical and political voice for Nigeria. The military
government that stepped down last spring banned his hit song ``Beng
Beng Beng.'' The title makes a sexually explicit reference and is
not a call to arms, he says. But like his father, Kuti, 36, has a
way of making sex seem like an act of political defiance. ``It's
something people want that the government cannot give us,'' he
concedes. ``It makes them irrelevant.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
