<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTILITIES CONTINUE BETWEEN MICROSOFT AND AOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hostilities continued Tuesday in the bitter debate over whether
Microsoft should be able to link into America Online's popular
instant message system, with Microsoft rebuffing America Online's
invitation to discuss a possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   The war broke out last week when Microsoft Corp. introduced new
software that allows users to send instant messages both to users
of Microsoft's Hotmail service and to users of the America Online
service and others who use the AOL Instant Messenger, or AIM,
software. America Online said Microsoft was acting like a hacker,
connecting to its system without authorization.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent days, Microsoft has issued several new versions of
its software as America Online has cut off each preceding version.
On Friday, America Online sent a letter to Microsoft, demanding
that Microsoft stop using its system but inviting the company to
negotiate some sort of message exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response Tuesday, Brad Chase, a vice president of
Microsoft, asserted that Microsoft had done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been and is no unauthorized use or access of AOL's
services or products,'' Chase wrote. ``Nor has Microsoft violated
the privacy or security of any AIM users.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter had no direct response to America Online's invitation
to discuss an accord. Rather, Chase simply called on America Online
to stop its efforts to block Microsoft's software.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's reaction was quick and stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear from reading their letter that America Online and
Microsoft still have significant disagreements on privacy and
security,'' said Kenneth Lerer, a principal with Robinson Lerer,
America Online's public relations firm. As for Microsoft's reaction
to America Online's invitation, Lerer said ``their silence speaks
for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Bennet, a product manager in Microsoft's consumer and
commerce business, said that America Online was not in fact
amenable to discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their letter was not a negotiation but a club,'' Bennet said.
He said that Microsoft wanted to work for an open standard through
an industry consortium rather than to negotiate a bilateral deal
with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Lerer of America Online said that the company believes that
instant messaging will ultimately be open so that users of any
instant message software will be able to communicate with users of
any other such program. Currently each system is in effect a closed
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Internet industry executives, however, said they saw no
indication that America Online is moving to open its base of 40
million instant message users to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, America Online cut off instant messaging systems from
Prodigy and Yahoo that also had found a way to link to the America
Online system. Prodigy and Yahoo officials say that America Online
has made no efforts to indicate the terms on which it would allow
access.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, America Online has not been active in the industry
task force that has been trying to write open standards for instant
messages, said Vijay Saraswat, a researcher for AT&AMP;T Labs and the
co-chair of the task force. Microsoft has been active in the task
force and has proposed a standard. But Saraswat said that Microsoft
has yet to show a commitment to those standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``America Online is not alone,'' he said. ``Microsoft is not
following a public protocol, even though they had proposed one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
