<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LOTTO-COX     07-27 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LOTTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite sales slump, officials optimistic about lottery's future
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Lottery officials said Tuesday they may be
able to see the light at the end of the sales slump, an optimistic
view for an operation fresh from its second-worst week in its worst
year since start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Lottery Director Linda Cloud said a multistate,
mega-jackpot game planned for later this year will be postponed
until the middle of next year or later.
</P>
<P>
   The optimism about ticket sales, which headed south and stayed
there in 1997 when lawmakers cut the payout on scratch-off games,
is based on numbers showing slight increases in scratch-off sales
in the weeks since lawmakers restored the prizes to previous
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the good news is that we have begun an upward move in
sales in the past few weeks,'' Toni Smith, the agency's marketing
director, told the Texas Lottery Commission. ``We are very excited
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scratch-off tickets have been the major cause of the prolonged
slump. Sales for those games hit $28.2 million, the highest weekly
total since February, in the week ending July 10. Sales have
slipped a bit in recent weeks but continue to indicate the lottery
may have hit bottom and could be heading back up.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ticket sales for all games, including Lotto and other
online games, dipped to $43.8 million. The only worse week this
fiscal year ended June 12, when sales totaled $41.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's low numbers came after a week that, fueled by a $37
million Lotto jackpot, produced $60.7 million in sales _ the best
week since last October.
</P>
<P>
   Overall sales for the current fiscal year total $2.3 billion,
down 17 percent from the same period for the previous year. This
year's weekly sales average is $49.6 million, down from $60 million
for the same period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1992 start-up, the lottery has sold $20.8 billion
worth of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism at the Lottery Commission increases proportionately to
the number of new scratch-off games that hit the street. Texas
lawmakers, looking to reverse the sales slump that set in when they
lowered prize payouts in September 1997, voted this year to raise
them.
</P>
<P>
   The prize pool for scratch-off games now will be calculated on
an annual average of 57 percent, up from the 52 percent set in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Eight new games, four with prize pools of 60 percent and four
with prize pools of 65 percent, have hit the stores since June 16.
Cloud, the lottery director, said players notice the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing from the retailers that they don't want our old
games anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimism, Cloud said the lottery will not hit
unofficial goals she had set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped . . . that we would see a significant turnaround
by Sept. 1,'' said Cloud, adding that she wanted weekly sales to
get back to about $64 million. ``I'm not sure we are going to see
that that quick. It may be the first of the year before we get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said the lottery lost many ``core players'' while the
payout on scratch-off tickets was lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials also were looking for a major sales boost by
signing Texas up for a multistate game for the first time. Texas
does not participate in Powerball and other multistate games that
produce jackpots over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The first such effort had been scheduled to start Oct. 22 with a
10-state alliance involved in ``Game of the Century,'' which,
officials said, could have carried a jackpot topping $200 million.
Ticket sales for the game, timed to capitalize on millennium
madness, were to end Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Cloud said Tuesday that only four states _ Texas, Georgia,
Illinois and Virginia _ had made all the changes and preparations
needed to get the game going this year. Some of the other states
still need legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are looking at maybe July or the end of next year,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
