long, hot days as a galley slave in a stress-filled and windowless
kitchen in return for the chance to absorb the knowledge and
mystical skills of a star chef, and maybe even bask in reflected
glory. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SERTHAR, China -- July 28, 1999 -- CHINA-BUDDHISM-2,
07-28 -- Young monks pose in front of Serthar Temple earlier this
month. In just a few years, Serthar has emerged to become one of
the largest and most influential centers for study of Tibetan
Buddhism in the world. Despite its extremely remote location in an
ethnic Tibetan region of Sichuan Province, more than 500 miles by
dirt road from the nearest city, Serthar has attracted nearly 8,000
monks and nuns who now live and study here. (Seth Faison/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SERTHAR, China -- July 28, 1999 -- CHINA-BUDDHISM-1,
07-28 -- Monks of all ages gather at the Serthar temple earlier
this month. In just a few years, Serthar has emerged to become one
of the largest and most influential centers for study of Tibetan
Buddhism in the world. Despite its extremely remote location in an
ethnic Tibetan region of Sichuan Province, more than 500 miles by
dirt road from the nearest city, Serthar has attracted nearly 8,000
monks and nuns who now live and study here. (Seth Faison/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- July 27, 1999 -- CIRCUMCISE-NOCUT-B&AMP;W-BOS,
07-27 -- Dr. Lisa Stellwagen applies an analgesic while a nurse
gives a newborn a sugar-coated pacifier during a circumcision.
``For decades, nurses have had to hold down these screaming babies,
and it's a horrible experience,'' says Dr. Stellwagen, a
pediatrician at Massachusetts General Hospital who says she always
uses pain relief. ``There's really no excuse for not numbing up the
baby anymore.'' (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HYANNIS, Mass. -- July 27, 1999 -- WAKE-BOARDING-BOS,
07-27 -- Lance Richardson does a flip on his wakeboard while riding
the waters of Wuquaquet Lake in Hyannis. Richardson, from Essex,
N.H., is sponsored by Hyperlite wakeboards. (Michael
Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LYNN, Mass. -- July 27, 1999 -- REFUGEE-WINDFALL-BOS,
07-27 -- Charles Baadom, 27, and his wife Blessing, 20, who is 9
months pregnant, are refugees from Nigeria now living in Lynn. For
these refugees, the Kosovo crisis, and the intense media scrutiny
that prompted the flood of donations to relief groups, represents
an unexpected windfall, paying for such necessities as food,
blankets, basic furniture, rental assistance and other essentials.
(Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS, 07-28 --
Judy Cato, of Camp Springs, Md., who is the primary caregiver of
her 80-year-old mother, reacts as President Clinton refers to her
as his ``friend'' during an event on Tuesday in the Old Executive
Office Building on Medicare funding. Clinton, who used the
opportunity to criticize the Republican's proposed tax cut, said
the surplus money should instead be used to help secure the life of
the Medicare trust fund. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
