<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Trespasses forgiven _ if the guy can play
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, during his first week of covering the Oilers for
the Houston Post, a certain fresh-faced, fuzzy-haired young sports
writer had a run-in with one of the veterans, a guy with a
well-documented reputation for surly behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Said reporter, unnerved by the incident, spoke to Bum Phillips
about it later that afternoon, figuring the coach might offer some
advice about how to get along with the player in question. He was,
after all, one of the team's defensive stars and would have to be
dealt with on a frequent basis.
</P>
<P>
   Bum nodded sympathetically, pondered the matter for a moment and
then, after spewing a stream of tobacco juice into a plastic foam
cup, said: ``Here's the problem. is a big ol' and there's nothing
either of us can do about it. I'd cut him today if he couldn't
play. But he's a hell of a player, and I need him. So you're just
gonna have to learn to live with him, like I have.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer fresh-faced and somewhat less fuzzy-haired, the same
sports writer is reminded of the incident by the 49ers' decision to
put their injury-depleted running game in the hands of the
notorious Lawrence Phillips, by reputation a bad actor of the
highest rank, the epitome of the stud jock whose trespasses are
routinely forgiven because of his physical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Phillips, a rap sheet rather than a diploma tucked
under his arm, came out of the University of Nebraska, the Niners'
Bill Walsh sanctimoniously sniffed that such a classy organization
as his never would allow a Lawrence Phillips to sully its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Walsh, of course, who announced Phillips' signing
Monday, citing changed circumstances _ and pronouncing Phillips a
changed man.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Lawrence says he is. For example, he doesn't eat meat
anymore, which explains in part why he's down to 209 pounds from a
high of 240.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps Phillips, after a brief, fruitful exile in NFL
Europe _ a league that needs a franchise in Siberia _ has seen the
error of his sociopathic ways and never again will beat up on
females, the most reprehensible of his vices.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Niners, their newfound compassion for this troubled
soul is born of dire straits. Garrison Hearst's fractured ankle,
suffered at the outset of the playoff loss to Atlanta last January,
hasn't come around, and it might never. San Francisco's rushing
yards must come from somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, leaner but presumably not meaner in temperament,
produced a record quantity of them across the pond, thereby turning
a handful of needy NFL executives and coaches _ Bum's son Wade, the
Buffalo coach, among them _ into would-be Father O'Malleys. The
Niners, in no small part because of their legacy of championships
and reputation for being a players' organization, won the right to
give Phillips his third chance (strike?) in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Previous employers St. Louis and Miami, by the way, did not
enter into the bidding. Lawrence was arrested three times during
his brief Rams tenure, believed to be a franchise record. Walsh, to
his credit, didn't try to hide his ethical flip-flop, admitting he
sounded like George Bush. (``Read my lips: No new taxes.'') But
with an appropriately somber countenance, he promised Phillips'
first Niners misstep off the field would be his last.
</P>
<P>
   He also called Lawrence's $1.75 million, two-year contract with
its $425,000 signing bonus a ``good investment'' for the
organization _ an organization whose leader, Eddie DeBartolo, was
banished by the NFL for his involvement in shady dealings down
Louisiana way.
</P>
<P>
   So the Niners, of all teams, had no grounds to pass moral
judgment on Phillips, who probably isn't the worst human being ever
to be in possession of a fat NFL contract. He's not under
indictment for anything, nor has he tested positive for banned
substances or an infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   If he has violent tendencies, then he's perfectly suited for his
chosen line of work, which requires one to commit repeated acts of
violence and mayhem against his peers.
</P>
<P>
   We applaud our football players' nasty dispositions during
games, then wonder why they don't always behave as normal folks do
afterward. We wish they could all maintain distinct dual
personalities, but it's far-fetched to ask.
</P>
<P>
   If one chooses to be a saintly sort and set a good example, we
should stand and applaud him for it. But all we have a right to
demand is he or she earns his or her money, and ours.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen Niners fans up close. Most are of the same subspecies
that populates every stadium on Sunday afternoons. If Phillips
slashes his way to a hundred-plus yards on a regular basis, they
will blissfully ignore his tarnished past. If he doesn't, count on
them to throw it back in his face daily. That's how sports works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
