<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6124 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-BUSINESS-SFCH     07-27 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-BUSINESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO MODERNIZE SHUTTLE FLEET MAY MEAN PROFIT FOR SILICON  VALLEY
FIRMS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The National Aeronautics and Space Administration
may have its launch site in Florida and its mission control center
in Texas. But it is coming to Silicon Valley for its first
conference to publicize plans to modernize the U.S. fleet of four
orbiters and solicit ideas on how to do so.
<P>
   The four-day Space Shuttle Development Conference kicks off
 &LR; Wednesday  &LR; afternoon at NASA's Ames Research Center in Mountain
View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA originally was going to have the conference near the
Johnson Space Center in Houston,'' said NASA spokesman David Morse.
``But we wanted to broaden the horizon, and what better place than
Silicon Valley, which is home to new companies, new technologies
and new ways of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending the event are not only big companies like Boeing,
Lockheed-Martin, BF Goodrich and Hewlett-Packard, but also small
firms like Ideo Product Development, the Palo Alto, Calif., company
that has designed more than 3,000 products, from Nike sunglasses to
the Palm V handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get higher profile than designing something that
would go into orbit,'' said Dennis Boyle, an Ideo design leader.
``This has been the domain of big government contractors, but it
would be very satisfying designing something that astronauts hold,
wear or interact with.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 firms have signed up to attend the event and over
40 companies have taken exhibition space in the huge blimp hangar
at Moffett Field.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is looking for the same sort of scientific know-how and
entrepreneurial spirit that have allowed the electronics industry
to keep doubling the data stored on a microchip every 12 to 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency faces a major challenge. Its second-generation
``reusable launch vehicle'' won't be available for decades.
Meanwhile, NASA has opted to optimize its four existing orbiters
just as the military has upgraded its aging fleet of B-52 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering slashing NASA's overall budget of $13.7
billion by nearly 10 percent, with the ax falling especially
severely on scientific research and missions to Mars and other
planets. However, the need to invest in the four space orbiters and
make them more cost-effective remains a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Each orbiter was designed for about 100 flights, so they have
close to 75 percent of their useful lives ahead of them. But to
meet the agency's goal of going from eight launches a year to 15
without spending appreciably more money or time on launch
preparation, major changes are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   These include making major renovations to launch control and
scheduling systems as well as orbiter avionics, communications,
propulsion and power systems. Many of the upgrades are extremely
complicated, such as using artificial intelligence and neural
networks to control and monitor systems.
</P>
<P>
   But some solutions are relatively simple, like protecting
thermal radiators on the shuttle from orbital debris by wrapping
freon cooling loops with an extra layer of aluminum tape.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's annual budget for upgrading the space shuttle and its
tens of millions of parts is already more than $100 million a year
and the agency hopes to win an additional $200 million a year over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   That presents an enticing lure for industry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the exhibitors at the first shuttle development
conference is Real Time Innovations. Started in 1991 by Stan
Schneider, the former head of Stanford University's Aerospace
Robotic Laboratory, the Sunnyvale, Calif., company makes software
to automate the writing of complex launch testing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Its ControlShell programming system substitutes icons and images
for a lot of text and is designed to help NASA technicians improve
launch schedules by testing dozens of shuttle systems from
thrusters to toilets. Real Time's annual revenues are approaching
$4 million and its largest contract is with NASA.
</P>
<P>
   SRI International also has a booth at the conference. The Menlo
Park, Calif., nonprofit is combining heat sensors with
grain-of-rice-size radio frequency identification tags that could
be embedded in the shuttle's thermal tiles.
</P>
<P>
   This is a major issue, since the shuttle could burn up if its
thermal protection systems break down. It now takes 4,000 man hours
to visually inspect all 24,000 tiles after each flight.
</P>
<P>
   Inspection, repair and recertification of a shuttle's skin
account for about 30 percent of the cost of turning an orbiter
around for the next flight. NASA would like to slash that at least
in half; smart thermal protection systems could help.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's lightweight tiles also are getting more durable
surface coatings that are 20 times more resistant to damage than
the old ones, which could be cracked by a fingernail.
</P>
<P>
   There are earthly uses for NASA's thermal protection systems,
too. Race cars recently began installing silica fiber thermal
blankets in fire walls and around mufflers to shield drivers from
heat.
</P>
<P>
   A number of NASA employees also have used the agency's research
labs to launch their own ventures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ames Research Center information technologist Monte
Zweben developed an artificial intelligence program in the late
1980s that was used to schedule shuttle maintenance, saving more
than $4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   NASA allowed Zweben to modify his software for commercial use,
and in 1992 he started started Red Pepper Software. Three years
ago, PeopleSoft Inc. bought the company, including Zweben's 8
percent stake, for $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zweben, 35, started Blue Martini Software, another
company with a colorful name. The San Mateo, Calif., firm uses
artificial intelligence technology to help companies that sell on
the Internet better target consumers by analyzing their ages,
buying habits, zip codes and other data.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA is a wonderful technology provider to the marketplace,''
said Zweben. ``Some of most vexing automation requirements come
from space applications and NASA Ames is committed to applying its
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Zweben's former boss at NASA Ames' artificial intelligence
research unit, Peter Friedland, also launched his own company in
1995. Intraspect Software of Mountain View helps companies,
including General Motors, share and reuse electronic information.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and entrepreneurs can win significant financing
through NASA. But be prepared for bureaucracy and plenty of
buzzwords, starting with the Space Shuttle Upgrades Program
Requirements Control Board. It is known as SSUPRCB and is one of
your first stops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
