r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETCALLS-RULING-SFCHR     07-27 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETCALLS-RULING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA REGULATORS CONFIRM THAT CALLS TO NET ARE LOCAL  &HT;     By DEBORAH SOLOMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ State regulators have reaffirmed an earlier ruling
that said calls to the Internet are local, a decision that will
require Pacific Bell and GTE to pay their competitors millions of
dollars in fees. For consumers, this wards off the threat of higher
fees for Internet access.
<P>
   The decision is a blow to Pac Bell and GTE, which had asked the
state Public Utilities Commission to reconsider an earlier ruling
that classified calls to the Net as local.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, local phone companies must pay one another a
fee when they handle a local call from each other's customers. That
includes calls placed by Pac Bell and GTE customers to Internet
service providers who use competing phone companies for local
service.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent phone companies fought against paying fees on
calls that its customers placed to local ISP numbers. Even though
the caller's number and the number of the ISP are in the same local
calling area, Pac Bell and GTE argued that Internet calls are
long-distance because they could end up anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the PUC disagreed, saying that Internet calls are
local and that local phone companies need to pay each other
``reciprocal compensation'' for handling those calls.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell and GTE asked the PUC to reconsider its decision, but
the commission rejected that request in a closed-session vote on
Thursday. Pac Bell has been keeping the money its owes to
competitors in an escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors to Pac Bell and GTE hailed the PUC's rejection,
saying it clears the way for them to get the more than $50 million
they say they're owed for reciprocal compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means that the policy of the state of California is for
reciprocal compensation, and it finally resolves what happens to
the money that we're owed,'' said Cindy Schonhaut, executive vice
president for government and corporate affairs for ICG, a
competitive local phone company. Schonhaut said ICG, which provides
phone service to many ISPs, is owed more than $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell said it does not plan to hand over $25 million to
ICG or any of the money its competitors say it owes. Pac Bell
officials say they have no plans to part with the money in the
escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mashek, a spokesman for Pac Bell, said the PUC's rejection
of the company's request does not mean Pac Bell needs to pay its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Mashek also said the company is hopeful that the PUC will decide
to take another look at the issue in a ``generic proceeding'' where
all sides could comment on what the state's policy should be and
who should be paid for what. The five PUC commissioners have
indicated they would like to revisit the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
