<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG WEST SCHOOLS CONTEMPLATE DIVORCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time the California schools drove the fortunes of the
Big West, the conference wasn't even named the Big West. By any
count, it's been at least 11 years since the wants and needs of
Long Beach State and its cousins were considered first.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer. The six California schools in the 11-school
conference spoke as one during a conference meeting in Boise
Tuesday, letting their colleagues know they want to return to an
all-California conference, which is what it was at birth 30 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The message wasn't presented as a demand or a threat. It was a
request for a no-fault divorce based on irreconcilable differences.
</P>
<P>
   The six Californians in the Big West that do not play football
want to separate from the five that do. The proposed divorce makes
twice as much sense when you consider the five football schools are
located in Idaho, Texas, Utah and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since the day the Big West started taking in football nomads in
1992, the conference direction has tilted heavily away from
California. Each time a school defected from the Big West, filling
the football void always seemed the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Long Beach, Fullerton and friends solved the football void
years ago, by eliminating it. Now they are united in owning and
operating a conference that reflects their interests and strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the meeting was for everyone to get together and
hear what each other had to say,'' said Long Beach State athletic
director Bill Shumard. ``There were no threats. No one is bolting
the conference, and there will not be any official action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to get across was that sooner or later, we're
going to get back to an all-California conference. It's what the
A.D.'s and presidents at all of the schools think is best for all
of us, and this was the right time for us to step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the Boise gathering is that it took place during
what is usually a meeting of the athletic directors and coaches of
schools that play football.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada's recent decision to jump to the Western Athletic
Conference (WAC) effective in the 2000-2001 school year was the
impetus for the Californians' (ital) carpe diem (end ital).
</P>
<P>
   When Fresno State left (1992), Nevada replaced them and four
strangers -- Arkansas State, Louisiana Tech, Northern Illinois and
SW Louisiana -- were admitted as football-only schools. When San
Jose State and UNLV began their jump to the WAC, the conference
reached out to Boise State, Idaho, North Texas and Cal Poly SLO.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate of eastward football expansion, the Big West
conceivably could have adopted every directional school in
Louisiana by 2002 and renamed itself the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   The reward for a California-only league is simple. No one
deludes itself regarding football. The emphasis would be on
basketball and those sports that are prolific in California --
baseball, softball, volleyball, track, water sports and soccer --
and the ease of travel and scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   The savings in avoiding expensive and difficult road trips to
Las Cruces (New Mexico), Logan (Utah), Denton (Texas), Boise and
Moscow (Idaho) could be redirected into more attractive
home-and-home non-conference dates for all sports -- say, Kansas
and Purdue in men's basketball, Miami and Wichita State in
baseball, and Penn State and Wisconsin in volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Shumard said all of the mountain schools understand the position
of Long Beach et al, and that now it's just a matter of
accommodating everyone. The status quo will continue through the
1999-2000 season. Nevada does not officially move to the WAC until
next July.
</P>
<P>
   Boise State has applied for membership in the WAC as well, and
Shumard believes it has an excellent chance. ``They have a great
(football) facility, they draw well and they own their own bowl
game (The Humanitarian Bowl),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico State and North Texas will attend a meeting of the
Sun Belt Conference next month, and officials are encouraged about
their prospects, at least in the interim for football. The Sun Belt
is a hodge-podge conference that features schools located in
Florida, Louisiana, Arkansas, Kentucky and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Idaho and Utah State as potentially disenfranchised.
But the WAC remains a constant flux, and it could have openings for
both. It lost half of its members when BYU, San Diego State and six
others left to create the Mountain West Conference, and the three
Texas schools left behind -- Rice, TCU and SMU -- are considering
their own options.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Big West shakeout begins, the process of considering
other California institutions -- like Northridge, UC Riverside and
Sacramento State -- would accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A.D.'s for mountain division schools were respectful of
the direction we're headed,'' Shumard said. ``The one thing they
asked is for us to be patient. You can't just switch conferences
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But for once, Long Beach and friends will be
waiting on their own terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
