r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KSUITS-COURTHOUSES-     07-27 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KSUITS-COURTHOUSES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Y2K LITIGATION ALREADY INVADING U.S. COURTHOUSES  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Y2K came a bit early for Mark Yarsike.
<P>
   The Michigan grocer had just opened his gourmet produce store in
1995 when one of his cashiers ran through a credit card with an
expiration date of 2000. The transaction jammed the store's
computer system, triggering an entire row of registers to crash.
</P>
<P>
   Yarsike called TEC America, which sold him the system, but it
couldn't fix the problem and refused to replace it with a new Y2K
compatible operation.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, after more than 150 service calls and no
running registers, Yarsike did what any normal American would do.
He sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to,'' said Yarsike of the complaint he and his partner,
Samuel Katz, filed. ``We were a new business. You couldn't
calculate the customers who walked out, the stress, the grief.''
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 is still months away, but the pesky Y2K problem
has already spread to dangerous territory _ the courthouse. The
fear of a litigation nightmare _ fanned by Silicon Valley and big
businesses _ prompted President Clinton to sign landmark
legislation last week that will make it more difficult for small
businesses like Yarsike's to sue.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce says it will save American
businesses billions of dollars in legal costs by discouraging
frivolous lawsuits. But trial lawyers and consumer groups respond
that it will hurt the small neighborhood store or home computer
user who will have no recourse when their system fails.
</P>
<P>
   Although the law is intended to limit lawsuits, about 50
complaints across the country have already been filed in
anticipation of a Y2K meltdown. The new law is not expected to have
much impact on them because it is aimed at lawsuits arising from
breakdowns after January 1.
</P>
<P>
   All the commotion is over two digits. Since they were first
plugged in, computers have been programmed to recognize years by
the last two numbers. The fear is over how many computers will go
haywire because they mistake the year 2000 for the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of the suits, including Yarsike's, have been brought
by computer users who have already suffered software or hardware
problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But most are class-action suits filed by consumers, hospitals
and small businesses hoping to avoid computer chaos when January 1
arrives. Relying on consumer warranty laws, they are seeking
upgrades of their systems at little or no cost. Silicon Valley, a
hub of the software industry, has been a prime target of the
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In their complaints, computer users make basically the same
argument _ that the companies providing the software and hardware
knew that 2000 was coming and should have provided products that
were Y2K compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they accuse some companies of holding consumers hostage
by demanding thousands of dollars for upgrades of systems.
</P>
<P>
   The new Y2K law gives companies a 90-day grace period to fix any
problems before they can be sued for Y2K-related damages. It
imposes additional requirements on plaintiffs when they file suit
and restricts whom they can sue. The law also limits class-action
suits by requiring plaintiffs to file in federal court and
restricting the amount of punitive damages small businesses can
collect.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint of Yarsike, the Michigan grocer, was the first
lawsuit filed over a Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In September, Yarsike agreed to settle his suit against TEC
America for $260,000 and has since bought a new $130,000 system
that has his cash registers humming.
</P>
<P>
   Yarsike said he probably would not have been able to find a
lawyer to take his case if the new law was in effect because it
limits attorney fees as well as damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no benefit in this law for the person like myself,''
said the grocer. ``It's all for the protection of the big computer
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Parker, the Michigan lawyer who filed the suit for
Yarsike, said the legislation fails to hold computer companies
accountable. ``The law requires you to give the manufacturer one
good faith chance to fix the problem,'' he said. Yarsike ``gave
them 150 times to fix it,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Marc Pearl, general counsel for the Information Technology
Association of America, a trade group in Arlington, Va.,
representing 11,000 companies, insisted that the law is necessary
to avoid an overload in the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can still sue,'' Pearl said. ``All the law is saying is
slow down, try to work this out without litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who have already sued for upgrades insist that software
software companies have a responsibility to take preventative
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few companies have viewed this as a profit opportunity and
want to charge people money for fixing something that they ought to
fix for free,'' said Michael Spencer, a New York lawyer with
Milberg, Weiss, Bershad, Hynes &AMP; Lerach.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm has filed at least a dozen suits, including a
class-action suit in Santa Clara Superior Court charging Intuit
with failing to make Quicken, the software personal finance
program, Y2K compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the companies are providing free upgrades, but some are
not. ``We never promised the software would last forever,'' said
David Furbush, a Palo Alto, Calif., lawyer who is representing
computer companies in two class-action cases. For the most part, he
said businesses recognize that software is in a constant state of
evolution. But a small number want free upgrades for computers that
have become technological dinosaurs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer companies are not the only ones defending themselves in
Y2K lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   GTE last month sued five insurance companies for $400 million,
which the telecommunications giant said it is spending to make its
system Y2K compatible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The federal suit filed by the Texas company is drawing
national attention because it does not appear to be covered by the
new legislation. John Heintz, a Washington, D.C., lawyer for GTE,
said he expects other companies to file similar suits.
</P>
<P>
   A Concord man with a home computer system filed suit in January
against Circuit City, Good Guys and five others major retail stores
to force them to disclose to buyers whether their products are Y2K
compliant and, if not, what they can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers are in the best position to know that there are
upgrades out there,'' said Richard Ergo, the Walnut Creek, Calif.,
lawyer who brought the suit for Tom Johnson, a swim coach at a
Walnut Creek high school who has a computer system. Last month,
Office Depot agreed to settle by providing customers with Y2K
information.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a dozen of the Y2K-related suits have been settled by
software companies that have agreed to provide upgrade ``patches''
for free or at relatively little cost.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the leading cases, doctors in several states brought
Y2K suits against Medical Manager Corp., the maker of one of the
most popular software packages that physicians rely on to schedule
appointments, track accounts and send bills to Medicare. In August,
the New Jersey company agreed to provide free patches to settle a
series of lawsuits brought by doctors in at least half a dozen
suits.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the settlements have glitches of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The North Marin Water District, which provides water services to
55,000 people, mostly in Novato, was part of a class that settled a
suit with Software Business Technologies of Marin County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The utility received a patch _ a replacement code _ to fix the
program that it relies on to pay bills, do the payroll and run
purchase orders.
</P>
<P>
   But the tiny public utility, which cannot afford a new system,
has gone through several patches since last fall because they have
caused the computer screens to fade or turn colors or the system
crash altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Auditor controller David Bentley noted that the 1995 system came
with a five-year warranty as well as assurances that it was Y2K
compatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've ultimately honored the warranty,'' he said, ``but it's
been a little more painful than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers say the real damages will come with the second
wave of lawsuits _ when January 1 arrives and computer foul-ups
cause injuries and financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure how bad the Y2K problem will be and how
many lawsuits will be filed. The U.S. Small Business Administration
has warned that 330,000 small business could shut down because of
Y2K breakdowns and another 370,000 could suffer severe losses.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say there are bound to be legal challenges over whom it
applies to and how to interpret its restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, backers of the law say emergency measures are
necessary to avoid lawyers from taking advantage of what could be a
national crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to insure that dollars spent go to fixing the
problem and not to the lawyers pockets,'' said Barbara Wheeler,
vice president of legislation for the Civil Justice Association of
California, which sponsored or supported similar bills in the state
Legislature. The five bills have been tabled for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Kreeger, a San Francisco lawyer who is advising
companies on preparing for Y2K, said the new law encourages
businesses to take steps now to inform customers about potential
problems. By taking the initiative, he said, they can build a
defense if things go wrong in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But trial lawyers say a 90-day waiting period will cripple many
small companies. They charge that big businesses are attempting to
take advantage of this onetime event to pass pro-defense laws that
they have been trying for years to get through Congress. In
response to these concerns, the new law expires after 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' said New York lawyer Jeffrey
Klafter, whose law firm has filed a number of Y2K class-action
suits. ``They've done a disservice to potential victims of the
Y2K.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
