<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSTINET-ARCHIPELAGO-     07-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTINET-ARCHIPELAGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTINET BUYS 16.4 PERCENT STAKE IN RIVAL ARCHIPELAGO HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Note in grafs 6 and 7, convert (asterisk) in E(asterisk)Trade
to the symbol, which cannot be transmitted to many newspapers.) 
 (yn) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest round of what is building into an intense
competition between established stock markets and a group of
upstart electronic competitors, Archipelago Holdings LLC, a leading
electronic network for trading Nasdaq stocks, said Tuesday that one
of its rivals, the Instinet Corp. had agreed to buy a 16.4 percent
stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago then announced that it planned to seek approval in
the next few days from the Securities and Exchange Commission to
become a self-regulated, for-profit stock exchange and was
considering an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago's bid for exchange status comes after a similar move
announced by Island ECN, another trading system. Others may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Instinet, a subsidiary of Reuters Group PLC and the world's
largest private stock-trading service for institutions, is also the
oldest electronic communications network for trading stocks. But it
has no desire to become an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It joins a list of big-name investors in Archipelago, an
organization that was founded two years ago by Gerald D. Putnam, a
former stock broker, and partners from Townsend Analytics, a
Chicago software firm.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company was founded, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.,
E(asterisk)Trade Group Inc. and Goldman Sachs Group Inc. have all
bought stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago refused to discuss how much Instinet paid for its
stake. But last January, Goldman Sachs and E(asterisk)Trade each
paid $25 million for a 24.5 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent additions of J.P. Morgan, the American Century
Companies, a mutual fund company in which Morgan has a 45 percent
stake, and now Instinet has diluted the ownership percentages. Now,
each of the major partners owns a 16.4 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas M. Atkin, the president and chief executive of Instinet,
said discussions about a possible stake had been taking place for
six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuesday's announcement is the latest in a flurry of
recent developments in a rapidly evolving web of trading systems
that are vying to compete with the New York Stock Exchange and the
Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, three big online brokers _ Charles Schwab,
Fidelity Investments and DLJ Direct _ announced they were joining
with Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, a big stock-trading firm, to build a
new electronic communications network.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the competition, at the end of last week the Big
Board and Nasdaq said they were seriously considering plans to
convert from nonprofit institutions to for-profit corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of positioning going on, but there is a long
way to go,'' said Dan Burke, a senior brokerage analyst at Gomez
Advisors Inc., an online and electronic commerce research firm
based in Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about half as much to execute a trade through an
electronic network as through an established exchange, and the
growth of such systems has led a lot of top Wall Street firms to
invest in them, Burke said. ``But there is a long way to go,
because there is a lot of stock trading infrastructure that is in
place,'' he added. ``Getting rid of that will not happen
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, Putnam from Archipelago
said he expected to receive a ruling from the SEC on setting up an
exchange in 9 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulatory structure challenges don't seem to be
onerous,'' he said. ``An all-electronic stock exchange is a
reality; it's going to happen. We would like to trade New York
Stock Exchange-listed stocks as well as Nasdaq listings and compete
on an all-electronic basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago, which has about a 2 percent share of the Nasdaq
trading market, is a small competitor with Instinet, which accounts
for about 15 percent of Nasdaq's overall daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Atkin of Instinet said that in the greater scheme of
things, he did not consider Archipelago as a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't buy into what Archipelago is now, but what it wants
to be, which is a for-profit exchange,'' he said. ``In the medium
term, that is not the area of the financial services industry we
want to play in. We are striving to be a global brokerage firm. I
think those strategic differences make this a complementary
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam said that, as an electronic stock exchange, Archipelago
could ``very easily'' operate 24 hours. ``It would be a natural for
us to go in that direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the self-regulation side, Putnam said Archipelago would be
responsible for things like market surveillance. But he said other
functions could possibly be delegated to an outside party in the
future if a single regulatory body for all markets emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love a single regulatory body to come together,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine electronic networks now trade stocks, but that number is
sure to dwindle, Atkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all is said and done, I think the ECNs will be a
footnote,'' he said. ``There does need to be a common operating
platform for trading all of these stocks. The issue is, who is
going to put the model in place? Archipelago has an excellent
chance of being one of the few winners in this space. But if Nasdaq
or the New York Stock Exchange went public, it would be consistent
for Instinet to own a stake in marketplaces where our clients are
trading substantial amounts of liquidity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
