<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERIOR-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS IN HOUSE COVET STATES' UNSPENT WELFARE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)  (mk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a frantic search for the cash that they need to
pass their spending bills, House Republican leaders are considering
asking their party's governors to return $6 billion in unspent
welfare money to the Treasury, senior aides said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was being weighed by Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, the aides said. It is by no means clear that any of the
nation's 34 Republican governors would agree to the idea, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to ask the Republican governors to reprogram $6
billion so we can put it into the appropriations bills,'' one
senior Republican aide said. ``I don't think a single governor will
give a penny back.''
</P>
<P>
   The money would come from federal money sent to the states in
the past few years for welfare benefits but which has not been
spent because of changes in the system, including welfare-to-work
programs, and rising employment among the nation's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's spokesman, John Feehrey, said Tuesday night that no
decision has been made on the idea, but acknowledged that it was
under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Although no member of Congress would comment, senior aides said
the idea was being taken seriously by some members, and regarded by
others as quixotic at best.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana said the idea struck him as a tough
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be extremely difficult,'' he said. ``It would
obviously call on all of us to review where we are at and what
reliance we've placed on these funds. Though we have an urge to
cooperate and participate, we have obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the House Republicans. As their deadline for passing the
13 spending bills required to run the government approaches, they
are in an increasingly tight financial squeeze, largely of their
own making.
</P>
<P>
   They are bound by spending caps that they devised in 1997,
limiting the amount of money they can lawfully spend. They cut $26
billion, or about 11 percent, from the budget for domestic spending
this year, and their fiscal conservatives made hundreds of millions
of dollars more cuts in domestic programs when six of the spending
measures passed the House.
</P>
<P>
   But now the bills to finance programs like health, education,
labor, housing and veterans' affairs are coming due, and Republican
moderates on the House Appropriations Committee say they are at
least $10 billion to $15 billion shy of what they will need to win
approval.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five days, the House Republican leadership has
resorted to increasingly unusual schemes to find the money. ``Some
of it is legitimate and acceptable,'' said the majority leader,
Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``Some of it is more questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, they declared the $4.5 billion found to finance the
coming 2000 Census and the $3 billion for veterans' health programs
as ``emergency spending,'' taking them off the official financial
ledger, but certainly stretching the legal meaning of
``emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   The money is to come from increasingly sophisticated gimmickry.
For example, the $3 billion for veterans would come from the
borrowing authority of the Tennessee Valley Authority, converting,
on paper, one agency's ability to take on debt into another's hard
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that left Republicans billions of dollars shy. Hence the
idea of going to the nation's statehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Feehrey said the idea was only one of many under consideration
as the House works to meet a Sept. 30 deadline for passing the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a remarkable recovery in some areas like
welfare-to-work, but that success is not really reflected in our
budget,'' he said. ``To keep the budget balanced is hard work and
we're looking at all different kinds of options. I'm not sure how
feasible this one is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
