<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWBUSINESS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SUPERSTORES DO BEST ONLINE  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: There's so much publicity about companies getting into
e-retailing. How important is it for small businesses to join the
fray and sell their products and services online?
<P>
   A: Despite the clamor to sell stuff over the Internet, it may
not be a panacea for small businesses, according to a report
released Monday by Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Many tout the Internet as the great equalizer that will let
small firms expand their geographic reach and swim with the big
guys. But the Cambridge, Mass., consulting firm figures the Net
will only accelerate the growth of megabusinesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook for local retailers online is dismal,'' says
Forrester senior analyst Charlene Li. Large national merchants
enjoy inherent advantages in technology, brand and scale that
ensure their e-commerce success.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Forrester figures local retailers will see their
share of online sales decline from 9 percent last year to just 6
percent by 2003 as national players extend their dominance to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the cost of building a full-featured commerce site
running well over $1 million, few local merchants can create a
commerce-friendly online store,'' Li notes. ``Likewise, without a
recognizable brand, local merchants have difficulty driving site
traffic through advertising and portal deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Web superstores like Amazon.com, CDnow and eToys are using wide
selection and low prices to dominate online sales of commodity
products such as books, music and toys. Similarly, large businesses
are using sophisticated online ordering tools, inventory management
techniques and promotions to wrap up the market for other goods
such as health and beauty products.
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, Li suggests that 25 percent of software, 20 percent of
music, 18 percent of books and 10 percent of consumer electronics
will be purchased online.
</P>
<P>
   Local service providers face better prospects because only part
of their business _ such as information, reservations and order
tracking _ are delivered online.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses' best use of Web sites and e-commerce is to
differentiate themselves and drive traffic to their traditional
stores, Li says.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, even though the estimated online market
share for small businesses may decline, the actual dollars are
going up _ way up.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester estimates local online sales will jump from $680
million in 1998 to $6.08 billion in 2003. Over the same period,
total U.S. online sales could soar from $7.8 billion to $108
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, more companies are creating tools to help small
businesses set up shop online.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fee services offered by Earthlink, Mindspring and
others, there are a growing number of free products and
connections. These include offerings from San Francisco's
Bigstep.com, Freemerchant.com of Emeryville, Calif., and Econgo.com
of San Mateo, Calif., which is expected to launch its free service
next month.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to set up an online site to grow your business or
hedge your bets. But do it with your eyes wide open.
</P>
<P>
   TAX PLANNING ADDITION: Several readers called and e-mailed in
response to the column two weeks ago on ways small-business owners
can transfer assets to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   I neglected to mention that many business owners use charitable
tax planning techniques such as charitable lead and wealth
replacement trusts, private family foundations and supporting
organizations to do some good while passing wealth to the next
generations.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 500 community foundations across the
country, including a bunch in the Bay Area. Chris Nicholson,
development officer of the East Bay Community Foundation, notes
that charitable lead annuity trusts can provide income to a
charitable organization for a set period before transferring the
assets to the trust's beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Will Wyman of the Community Foundation of the Napa Valley says
donor-advised funds can dramatically reduce estate taxes and
perpetuate a family's charitable interests without the donor giving
up entire control or use of the stock, real estate or other
resources.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact local foundations or visit Web
sites www.giftplan.org or www.leavealegacy.org.
</P>
<P>
   Working with public land trusts and using conservation easements
to protect farmland and wilderness from development also is a way
to reduce the fair market value of real property and lower estate
taxes as well. For more information and links to other sites, check
out the Land Trust Alliance (www.lta.org).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
