<SLUG> BC-COX-CABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COX IS IN DEAL WITH GANNETT FOR CABLE-TV SUBSCRIBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Okla., N.C., Texas, La., Ark., Neb., Va., Ga.)  (lh) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing to expand its cable-television holdings, Cox
Communications said Tuesday that it had agreed to acquire 522,000
cable subscribers from Gannett Co.
</P>
<P>
   Cox paid a high price to expand its cable operations. It is
spending $2.7 billion in cash to acquire systems in Kansas,
Oklahoma and North Carolina for a record $5,100 a subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   The company said, however, that its effective price was actually
lower since the acquisition was a purchase of assets that generate
a $350 million tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the price was sufficiently higher than earlier
transactions to push up the stock of other cable companies. Cox
lost 81.125 cents a share, closing Tuesday at $38, but Time Warner
stock rose $1.1875, to close at $73.6875 a share. Comcast stock
jumped $1.50, to close at $36.1875, and Cablevision System Corp.
rose 93.75 cents, to $72.0625.
</P>
<P>
   While Cox did agree to pay a premium compared with other cable
deals, the company is considered possibly the best operator in the
industry, and analysts were optimistic that Cox could make the deal
pay off. David Goldsmith, who follows cable for Buckingham Research
Group, based in New York, said that he believed the deal made a lot
of sense, since Cox is ``bulking up on subscribers and doing it in
a clustered way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox already has a huge cluster in the Tidewater area of
Virginia, so acquiring the Carolina system makes a lot of sense,''
Goldsmith said. ``They are buying a scarce resource, and when you
factor in the rollout of new services and what they will do to cash
flow, that is not an egregious price.'' The new rollouts could be
in the areas of digital television, Internet services and
telephony.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the purchase _ Gannett's Multimedia Cablevision
unit based in Wichita, Kan. _ fits into a regional cluster that Cox
is building in the central United States. After its current
acquisition is completed, Cox said it would have more than 2.4
million customers in a region spanning Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana,
Arkansas, Kansas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cox is paying a relatively high multiple of cash flow,
the company was eager to explain the price by pointing out the tax
benefits of a cash transaction. Cox's treasurer, Dallas Clement,
said that the majority of cable deals are done for stock, and the
acquiring company depreciates the value of the assets that are on
the selling company's books. A cash purchase allows the buyer to
write up the value of the assets closer to the purchase price and
therefore higher. Then buyer can expense a larger percentage of the
purchase price and reduce taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is the fifth-largest cable operator in the country and has
been creating regional clusters through acquisitions. After its
current and pending deals close, it will have 6 million subscribers
and will remain the fifth-largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gannett's systems are already upgraded and considered a
good mesh with Cox's systems. But Gannett, which bought the cable
systems five years ago from the Multimedia Corp. for $2.3 billion,
has never been a major player in the industry, which has
consolidated dramatically. This has enabled the larger companies to
benefit from economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications was initially part of Cox Enterprises, the
privately held media giant that owns The Atlanta Constitution and
18 other daily newspapers, as well as TV and radio stations and an
auto auction business. In 1993, James Kennedy, the grandson of
Cox's founder and chairman of Cox Enterprises, decided that Cox
either had to grow in cable or sell out. The company then took its
own cable operations public and used that stock to acquire Times
Mirror's cable operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
