<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COTEAU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENIS DE COTEAU, SAN FRANCISCO BALLET'S MUSIC DIRECTOR, DIES AT
70  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denis de Coteau, a conductor of wide experience who was the San
Francisco Ballet's longtime music director, died on Friday in San
Francisco. He was 70 and lived in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, the ballet company said.
</P>
<P>
   De Coteau joined the San Francisco Ballet as assistant conductor
in 1968 and served as the troupe's music director and conductor
from 1974 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he became music director emeritus in recognition of
his leadership of the ballet orchestra, considered one of the
finest in the country. Since his last performance in August, he had
continued to act as adviser on the music repertory to the company's
artistic director, Helgi Tomasson.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently invited to conduct symphony orchestras in the United
States and abroad, de Coteau was also known for his work with youth
orchestras. He conducted the Oakland Youth Symphony from 1970 to
1979, when the group became the first American youth orchestra to
win bronze and silver medals at the Herbert von Karajan Competition
in Berlin. de Coteau also conducted youth orchestras in Germany,
Australia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, de Coteau earned a bachelor's and a master's
degree in music from New York University and a doctorate from
Stanford University. Among his awards were the Pierre Monteux
Conducting Prize (1969), the Ascap Award for Adventuresome
Programming (1976) and commendations from the California
Legislature and the San Francisco City Council.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 de Coteau stepped in for the ailing Edo de Waart to
conduct the San Francisco Symphony and subsequently conducted the
symphony in a series of concerts that year. He served as associate
conductor on its national tour in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   De Coteau was conductor emeritus and a faculty member at the San
Francisco Conservatory of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Among the orchestras with which he appeared as guest conductor
were the BBC Scottish Symphony, the Tokyo City Philharmonic
Orchestra, the St. Louis Symphony, the Seattle Symphony and several
ballet orchestras. He was music director of the Flagstaff Festival
of the Arts in Arizona from 1977 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Lee Ming; three daughters, Michele,
Nadine and Nicole, all of the Bay Area; his twin brother, Norbert,
of New York; a stepson, Kevin Chou of La Jolla, Calif., and a
stepdaughter, Yueh Chou of Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990727.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6142 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-OUTBREAK-TEX     07-27 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-OUTBREAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE BIN THOUGHT TO BE SOURCE OF E. COLI OUTBREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN BROOKS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few youngsters infected with E. coli may have contaminated a
dormitory ice bin with their hands, leading to the spread of the
bacteria to more than 50 others at a Denton drill team camp, state
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears campers infected with the bacteria used their hands
to scoop out the ice and contaminated it,'' state epidemiologist
David Bergmire-Sweat said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, based on a Texas Department of Health
investigation that began after the June 9-11 camp, means state
health officials believe that they have pinpointed how at least 41
of the 58 participants who were infected came down with severe
gastrointestinal illnesses. But it does not explain how the camper
or campers who spread the bacteria had contracted it.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, who are doing their own investigation, were
cautious about the state's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the ice may be implicated, but we're keeping an open
mind,'' said Tom Skinner, spokesman for the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta. ``If you think about how many
people were involved, just now we're really starting to go through
the data with a fine-tooth comb. The ice is one of several things
that's being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say what the other theories are.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, the investigation is ongoing, and a
source has not been identified,'' Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials acknowledged that the investigation is not
complete and that there are plenty of unknowns. It is not known how
about 30 percent of the affected participants became ill _ whether
from an outside source or through direct exposure to someone who
was sick, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not a conclusion, it's at least a progress report in
terms of the investigation and what has been learned,'' said Doug
McBride, a spokesman for the state health department.
</P>
<P>
   The most seriously ill of the students is a Colleyville Heritage
High School drill team member who returned to the intensive care
unit at Baylor Medical Center at Dallas on Tuesday. Catherine
Harvey, 16, is fighting increasingly serious symptoms after the
original illness which caused her kidneys to shut down traveled to
her brain two weeks ago, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Harvey said this week that although her daughter's kidneys
have recovered after several weeks of dialysis, she has other
complications.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Harvey and an instructor are the only reported cases
of kidney failure linked to the outbreak. No information on the
instructor has been available. No illnesses have been reported at
subsequent camps, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time that the rare E. coli O111:H8 bacteria
has been linked to a large outbreak in the United States, although
several have been reported in Australia and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria, a relative of the more common E. coli O157:H7,
causes dizziness, vomiting, nausea, bloody diarrhea, cramping,
fever, and more rarely, kidney failure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rarity of the bacteria piqued the interest of the CDC, which
has interviewed more than 80 percent of the 750-plus students who
attended the June camp, Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigators collected information to aid state and
local officials and to add to their own limited research on the
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the state had announced a vehicle for the spread of
the bacteria when the CDC isn't ready to, Skinner said: ``You'll
have to ask Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria can be spread by infected people who don't wash
their hands and contaminate ice, water or food, said Bob Jones, an
epidemiologist at the Fort Worth Public Health Department, which
participated in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The illness also can be spread from person to person, which adds
to the questions that investigators acknowledged they may never
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of background noise,'' Jones said. ``There are
some secondary infections, some problems with recall accuracy.
Someone who was infected from the ice may have contaminated
something else, and someone could have become infected from that.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials came to suspect the ice after statistical
analysis of interviews with hundreds of camp participants who came
from schools throughout Texas as well as from Oklahoma and Kansas,
McBride said. The ice was not tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got 70 percent of them connected to that, the ice
is a strong indicator,'' he said. ``We'll continue to look at data
and information that we've accumulated and keep trying on a primary
source of infection, but there's obviously no guarantee we'll find
one.''
</P>
<P>
   University of North Texas officials, who also conducted an
investigation, said they saw students putting their hands in the
ice, and officials promptly stopped putting it out in large
containers. Youngsters were directed instead to get it from ice
machines in the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
