<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL: CUP BOYCOTT IS POSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON AND SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ The best players in the world will be on hand
for the Ryder Cup Sept. 24-26 at The Country Club in Brookline,
Mass., but in an interview in the forthcoming September issue of
Gold Digest, David Duval, the Cup point leader and the
second-ranked player in the world, intimated that might not happen
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Duval raised the possibility of a boycott of this year's event
because of player unrest over compensation, and if not this year,
than in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has been a little overcooked and will probably
stay that way until players choose not to play,'' Duval said in the
interview, which was obtained Tuesday by the Globe. ``What are we
going to receive for the Ryder Cup? A stipend of $5,000 each? I
just might take that money and retire. And we're not used?
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought of a boycott could cripple what has become
golf's fifth major, but Duval is unsure of the timing. ``Probably
not this time,'' he added. ``Although it could. It could happen
this September. More than likely, though, next time in 2001.
Certainly within two more. It's imminent. This is just from talking
to the guys. Some of them are fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval is on hand for the Canon Greater Hartford Open, which
begins Thursday, and when approached on the practice range, stood
by his comments to the magazine but offered no elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who recognizes the great disparity between what the PGA
of America and TCC will receive in revenue and what the players are
paid, acknowledged he hadn't read the article, but as he looked at
an advance copy, the leading money winner on the Tour added, ``I
really don't want to get into it. It's all right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he see a boycott of the matches Sept. 24-26? ``Like I
said, I don't really want to get into it. I think it's all very
well explained what I said. It was written out verbatim.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Tuttle, spokesman for The Country Club, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``As the host club we believe this is between the players and
the PGA of America. We hope everybody comes on Sept. 21 and we have
a great week of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to contact PGA of America CEO Jim Awtrey were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman is also in the field for the 48th GHO, and he was
asked Tuesday whether a boycott will become more of a reality.
``Oh, I think it will be something that will be talked about and
resolved in the offseason, so to speak,'' he said. ``I don't feel
that strongly about it where I would ever think about boycotting.
If I was a member of the team, I would play regardless. I think
David Duval is probably the same way. A lot of guys are venting
frustrations and they say things that they don't totally mean, but
there is truth to what they say. David's a great guy and I really
respect him because he usually says it the way it is and he's got a
good point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup has changed a lot over the years. ``It's evolved
from just being a match between golf organizations where there was
no money involved at all, to now becoming a multi, multi,
multimillion dollar revenue generator for the golf unions, while
the players are still where they were 40 to 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club sold out the corporate tents for $15.2 million
more than 2 1/2 years prior to the event. This price only included
the tents and location. They've since sold tents at adjoining
Putterham Meadows, and the first $3 million goes to the town of
Brookline. Golf Digest estimates a total income of $63 million and
a net profit of $17.5 milion for the PGA of America and $6 million
for TCC.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger has watched the Ryder Cup go from a nondescript
event to one of the sporting world's biggest international
spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup in the early 80's was not even on the map,'' he
said. ``I mean, I was on the Tour and didn't know what it was. So
here we are now, 16 years later, and the Ryder Cup from 1983 to
1999 has just exploded in popularity, and its ability to generate
revenue is astronomical.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the money being generated by the Ryder Cup was
just now coming into the place it's at now. It was becoming
astronomical. Then, the issues were brought up, kind of behind the
scenes, by players about being paid to play. In some ways, I think
(Duval's) got a point. In other ways, it's like to represent your
country, maybe you shouldn't be paid. I don't know. I'm on the
fence about that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little question the Ryder Cup has become big business.
Hotels are sold out. Houses are rented out at sky-rocketing prices.
Corporations have rented nearby clubs. BankBoston has bought at
tent for $500,000 and rented Charles River CC from Tuesday to
Saturday for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Mark O'Meara, who is also on hand, have voiced
concerns that it is getting out of hand. Duval's vented to Golf
Digest. O'Meara has been on record for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are professionals,'' said Duval in the Q &AMP; A. ``And if the
figures are correct _ they're supposedly going to gross anywhere
from $20 million to $30 million _ well, where is it all going?''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who will leave here to participate in a two-man
match-play event in California with Tiger Woods next Monday and
Tuesday, said this goes beyond just the game's two most celebrated
players of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a lot of players,'' he said in the interview. ``Four or
five. Six or eight. It's not my place or my mission to seek guys
out to find out what they're thinking. But it's out there. If you
have players on a Ryder Cup saying, `We need to talk,' what are the
alternatives? Does the PGA of America go to the next 12 guys on the
list and ask them to play?''
</P>
<P>
   There have been suggestions by O'Meara and Phil Mickelson that
maybe $1 million should be sent to a player's charity out of the
coffer. ``Bingo,'' responded Duval. ``That's exactly right. Without
the players, they're not going to have a Ryder Cup. But all these
other people who go to the Ryder Cup to work or whatever, aren't
they still drawing their salaries that week. Mark O'Meara got
blasted for bringing up the compensation issue during the last
Ryder Cup, and he was absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman echoed Duval's sentiments regarding distribution of the
funds. ``I think everybody would be very happy with (giving to a
charity),'' he said. ``The fact of the matter is that the PGA of
America does give _ I think it's important that the average person
knows this. The PGA of America does give to the PGA Tour a
percentage of the rights fees from the TV, which I think amounts to
about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been my opinion that the PGA of America has shared
a significant amount of money with the PGA Tour. Now what the PGA
Tour does with it should be the issue. If the PGA of America is
giving 20 percent of the rights fee to the Tour, then maybe it's
the Tour's responsibility to pass it on down to the players. PGA of
America, as far as I'm concerned, has done their duty. They've
passed some back to the players' organization and maybe that's the
way to do it. Let the Tour handle that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert thinks a lot of the players' concerns are
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think players will go to the point where they'll
boycott, but I think the players have some concerns,'' he said
after a GHO practice round. ``I think the players get frustrated
because everyone just kind of puts a deaf ear to their comments.
Maybe the time is right to sit down with the players and get some
ideas. I think the biggest thing the players get frustrated with is
the fact that they say the tournament's got the tradition. It's
60-70 years old and we've never paid the players. Well, 60-70 years
ago they didn't make tens of millions of dollars on the event,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara was in form at the British Open in Carnoustie. Scotland.
``The majority of players don't want to speak about it because
they're going to get crucified in the press,'' he said. ``I've
played on four Ryder Cup teams. I think the Ryder Cup is a very
special event. I've never denied that. Playing for your country is
a honor, but I think more or less playing as a team is what the
honor is all about. As long as the PGA of America and the European
PGA Tour feel the money is going back to further the game or is
going back to good charities, I have no problem not being paid.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a precedent for professional athletes to be paid for
international exhibitions. The United States Tennis Association
compensates players when they participate in the Davis and
Federation cups. Men playing in the Davis Cup are paid as much as
$50,000 for the weekend's appearance plus expenses.
</P>
<P>
   However, most American Olympians get money only for winning a
medal, either from their federations, the US Olympic Committee, or
sponsors, but they do not get paid merely for making an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert is optimistic something will be worked out. ``I think
the general feeling is the players are happy with the event,'' he
said. ``It's a lot of fun. But sometimes the media will build
things up a little bit bigger than they are. I'm looking forward to
it, if I'm on the team. I'm looking forward to playing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Powers and Joe Sullivan of the Globe staff contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
