<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLE IN MEXICO A LONG SHOT FOR US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ So, are the Yanks going to hit the
perfecta again? Are goalkeeper Kasey Keller's arms going to be 8
feet long again, with a dozen fingers on each hand? Is the US men's
soccer team going to beat Brazil the way it did at the CONCACAF
Gold Cup last year, when Keller was touched by magic and his mates
knocked off the Samba Kings for the first time?
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was a different game under different conditions,''
says coach Bruce Arena. ``We don't look back on it at all. That
game could just as easily have been 6-0 for Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1-0 for the Americans only because Keller stopped the
fabled Romario five times. ``It just happened to be one of those
special nights,'' says Keller, who will be between the posts again
at Jalisco Stadium when the US plays its second match at the FIFA
Confederations Cup. ``I'm not expecting to have the same
performance again. It would be very, very unrealistic. If Brazil
has the same chances that they had then, we're probably going to
lose by a few goals.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Germans lost here to the Brazilians, 4-0 _
their worst defeat in 45 years _ in a match that was scoreless
after 60 minutes. And Brazil was playing without top stars Ronaldo,
Rivaldo, and Roberto Carlos, who went back to their clubs after
helping their squad retain the Copa America two weekends ago.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. The Brazilians still had Serginho and Ronaldinho and
Ze Roberto and Alex, the last of whom came off the bench to score
two goals in two minutes. ``They can bring anyone in, and they play
the same way,'' muses Arena. ``That's amazing. And the scary
thought is, they probably have another 50 players just like these
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians have reloaded after last year's shocking 3-0 loss
to France in the World Cup final, and they're odds-on favorites to
bop the US and go on to beat the Mexicans for the title in Mexico
City's mammoth (as in 115,000 seats) Azteca Stadium a week from
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're very large underdogs,'' concedes Arena, whose
squad looked only so-so while beating New Zealand, 2-1, in its
opener. ``We know it's a great challenge, playing the best team in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are 1-7 lifetime against Brazil and have scored
one goal (Preki Radosavljevic's 1998 winner) since 1930. So the
Samba Kings aren't exactly quaking in their boots. ``Brazil and the
US have played a lot of times,'' observes Marcos, their backup
keeper. ``The US won once, and they were lucky to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Brazilians have rarely had it easy against Uncle
Sam _ four of their last five victories have been by 1-0 scores.
``The match is going to be difficult,'' says Serginho, ``because
they are a rival that by nature has complicated things for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans know enough not to get into a track meet with the
fleet Brazilians. So they'll mark them closely, try to keep them
wide, hope Keller can swat aside whatever bullets get through, and
attack with enough conviction to earn their rivals' respect. ``Do
we have a special plan?'' says Arena. ``We're going to try to win.
That's our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans can try to win knowing they have nothing to lose.
They got a free invitation here because the Mexicans, the
confederation champs, were already in as hosts. If they lose, they
can still advance to the semifinals by beating the Germans here
Friday night. They can even advance with a draw Friday if they keep
it close and the Germans don't run amok on the New Zealanders.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yanks will put Keller on the line again, buy a win
ticket, and take another shot at the perfecta. Nothing to lose,
after all. ``There are three teams in this tournament with three
points, and we're one of them,'' figures Arena. ``So we can't be in
that bad shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
