<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-McGARITY-     07-27 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-McGARITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys rookie McGarity wants recognition
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Wane McGarity had one of the most recognizable
looks on the University of Texas football team last year. The only
problem was, he was often recognized as the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting dreadlocks, the Longhorns receiver was constantly
confused with teammate and good friend Ricky Williams, the beefy
Heisman Trophy-winning running back who became the No. 1 and only
draft pick of the New Orleans Saints this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened a lot,'' said McGarity, who measures only 5-8
and tops the scales at 191 pounds. ``It was a common mistake. It
would make you chuckle, because I'm not close to 240 pounds. That's
him.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity's braids were chopped before the draft, when scouts and
other football insiders began looking at Williams' hair and
questioning his decision-making. McGarity, no sure thing in the
draft after a pair of knee injuries suffered in college, knew he
couldn't afford to have any critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just something I had to do,'' McGarity said. ``You
start hearing things. It all started back at the draft. I didn't
want it to be one of those things where you (question) my character
and things. Most of the people who know me know I'm a pretty good
guy. But you can see it's growing back out. It will be back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   One month from now when NFL rosters are finalized, McGarity
hopes Dallas fans will find him recognizable. He was the first of
two fourth-round picks by the Cowboys, and with the ability to
catch the long ball, along with the hands and speed needed on
special teams, McGarity stands a good chance of making the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel I can make this team,'' he said. ``They play a
lot of receivers. There's a lot of spots available on special
teams. I feel I can do all that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity almost didn't get a chance to dress out on Tuesday.
Though his contract was settled on Monday, it wasn't actually
placed in front of him for a signature until 8:40 a.m. Tuesday.
Practice began at 8:45.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be out of the way,'' he said. ``It
was one more thing I didn't want to worry about, but it's over now.
When I came out here, I was real nervous, didn't know what to
expect. But once I caught my first pass, got out there on special
teams a little bit, I calmed down.''
</P>
<P>
   He made several catches and worked a bit as a punt returner
Tuesday as the Cowboys had their first workouts. Rookies and
selected veterans are in camp now, with the remaining players due
to report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty good,'' McGarity said. ``I accomplished pretty
much everything I wanted to. I wanted to come out here and perform
my best, which I did. But there are still some areas that I have to
work on.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his rookie ``Bible,'' a playbook that's more than a
little overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about two telephone books it looks like to me,'' McGarity
said. ``Austin telephone books _ Dallas' are probably too big.''
</P>
<P>
   He also got his jersey. His number _ 18 _ is also a bit too big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really prefer a single digit; it would make me look my
size,'' he said. ``When I wear big numbers, it makes me look
really, really little.''
</P>
<P>
   His college number _ 8 _ is already taken, and it's unlikely
quarterback Troy Aikman plans to part with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I hear, that guy's the boss,'' McGarity said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, it was doubtful McGarity would ever stand on
a practice field catching passes from Aikman or any other NFL
quarterback. In the third game of his junior season, McGarity tore
the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, an injury that
takes nearly a year to heal, even longer to fully recover from.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't have been devastating except that it was the second
time he'd gotten such news. He had redshirted in 1994 after tearing
the same ligament in the other knee on the first day of preseason
drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been through it all,'' McGarity said. ``Just to
come back from all those surgeries that I had and come out here and
still be a player, I think that speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   So did McGarity's numbers in his season season last year.
Embarrassing his doubters, he set UT records with 58 catches for
1,087 yards (18.7 per catch). His nine receiving touchdowns were
the second-highest total in school history.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity also boasts the longest reception in Longhorns history,
a 97-yarder against Oklahoma last year. He scored eight TDs
covering 30 or more yards in his UT career; five were 50 yards or
longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' passing game accounted for only 17 touchdowns last
season. Only 10 of those (four by Ernie Mills) were scored by the
wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm out here for _ my ability to run after the
catch, my ability to go out there and be a playmaker,'' McGarity
said. ``That's why I'm here. That's what I'm going to go out to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   A good showing on special teams would boost McGarity's chances
of making the roster, and on Tuesday he worked as a punt returner.
He had 11 kickoff returns scattered over three college seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I was concerned, they all looked like they were
spastic to me today,'' Cowboys special teams coach Joe Avezzano
said. ``Some guys were less spastic than others. He (McGarity) is
probably a little less spastic because he's one of those cute
little receiver-type guys floating around out there looking kind of
pretty. I look forward to seeing him do more things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
