u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLEANAIR-NYT &LR;      07-27 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEANAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SMART SHIFT IN CLEAN AIR TACTICS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   Government policy makers, like most people, are usually
reluctant to admit error. But Carol Browner, administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, says that Congress and two
administrations failed to foresee the dangers of a gasoline
additive that has helped to make the air cleaner but, as it turns
out, now threatens the nation's water supply. She has therefore
ordered a prompt rollback in the use of the chemical and asked
Congress to rewrite the legislation that led to its original
application.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 Congress required that gasoline sold in areas with
severe air pollution _ including New York and New Jersey _ contain
a higher amount of oxygen so that it would burn more cleanly and
thus produce less carbon monoxide and other pollutants. Oil
companies responded by using MTBE, or methyl tertiary butyl ether,
a widely available derivative of methanol.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE did what it was supposed to do _ reduce carbon monoxide
emissions. But a scientific panel set up by Ms. Browner last year
says that ``trace levels'' of MTBE can now be found in 5 to 10
percent of the drinking water supplies in areas where reformulated
gasoline is required by law, mainly from leaks from underground
storage tanks. Although MTBE is known to cause cancer in animals,
and makes water smell so bad that it is almost undrinkable, it is
not regarded as an immediate threat to public health. However, Ms.
Browner wisely decided that its potential risks outweighed the
known benefits.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a major blow to the country's clean air strategy.
The biggest problem _ smog _ is being addressed by other means,
including tighter controls on power plants and cars, as well as
cleaner gasoline produced by improved refining processes. Even so,
Congress must now revise the law mandating oxygenated fuels,
perhaps by setting general air quality standards for gasoline and
giving oil companies the flexibility to meet them with more benign
additives or other technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Browner has promised to tighten enforcement of
rules governing underground gasoline storage tanks. The panel
estimates that about one-fifth of these systems need prompt repair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
