A6154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-CONGRESS-     07-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE RENEWS CHINA'S TRADING BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Tuesday renewed trading privileges
with China for another year, separating U.S. commercial interests
from a long list of grievances that Washington has with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 260 to 170 to reject a measure that would have
ended the trade benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was widely expected, even though relations with
China have nose-dived after allegations that China stole American
nuclear secrets, the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, a
soaring trade deficit with Beijing, and China's crackdown on a
spiritual movement, Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual alliance of liberal Democrats and conservative
Republicans tried to capitalize on the strained relations to
buttress their contention that granting trade privileges to China
would reward a government that abuses the rights of its own people,
persecutes its citizens for their religious beliefs and menaces
neighboring Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics never gained much traction, buffeted by an
intensive lobbying campaign of business groups like the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce and corporations with interests in China like
General Motors, Boeing and Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, opponents picked up just four more votes than they
did last year to end what is now called ``normal trade relations''
with China.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote last year was 264 to 166.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of extending trade privileges, including the House
Republican leadership and moderate Democrats, argued that engaging
China through trade rather than isolating it would give Washington
more influence to improving human rights and religious tolerance
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a constructive, purposeful engagement with China
or we can have a new Cold War with a new evil empire,'' said Rep.
Tim Roemer, D-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America applauded the vote and expressed confidence
that it would rekindle momentum for a deal to gain entry for China
into the World Trade Organization this year. Such a bargain would
require Congress to drop the annual debate and grant China a
permanent version of what was once called ``most favored nation
status.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China's accession to the World Trade Organization is the next
key step, and one we hope Congress will take promptly, once a final
market-opening trade agreement is reached,'' Dana G. Mead, chairman
of Tenneco and of the Business Roundtable, an association of chief
executives, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In April, President Clinton and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of
China fell short of striking a major trade deal to present to
Congress when Clinton pulled back at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on May 7 cut off
negotiations altogether.
</P>
<P>
   House opponents to making the trade benefits permanent have
pledged a fierce battle. Administration officials are pinning their
diminishing hopes for a deal on a meeting between Clinton and
President Jiang Zemin of China in September in New Zealand at an
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain determined to pursue an agreement for China to join
the WTO on viable commercial terms,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Annual votes on trade with China are required under a 1974 law
that was intended to pressure Communist governments to relax
emigration policies. The votes were routine until the killings of
pro-democracy protesters at Tiananmen Square in 1989. Congress has
never revoked the trade privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has not yet considered the matter this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a test vote this month, senators indicated that they would
extend benefits, mostly lower taxes on Chinese goods shipped to the
United States, for an additional year.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the outcome preordained, a spirited debate seized the
House floor Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most emotional speeches came from Rep. David Wu, a
freshman Democrat from Oregon who is the first Taiwanese-American
elected to the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business of America must be more than just business, and
engagement must be through more than just the cash register,'' Wu
said in opposing renewed trade relations. ``Real engagement sees
the Chinese people as real people, people like us, people with
aspirations, with hopes, people who aspire to walk the path of
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Philip M. Crane, R-Ill., said cutting off benefits
would be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation of 1.2 billion people is more likely to imitate our
powerful example,'' Crane said, ``than it is to bend as a result of
our threats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
