</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLACEMENT-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SAYS ADVANCED-PLACEMENT CLASSES SHOW BIAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ College admissions officers have long used
advanced-placement courses as an important tool for measuring
applicants and the high schools they attend. But Tuesday, in a
lawsuit filed in a state court here, the American Civil Liberties
Union of Southern California said that yardstick was just another
way of discriminating against students and schools in low-income
and minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, against the State of California, says these schools
offer far fewer advanced courses than those in other communities.
Beverly Hills High, for example, a mostly white school, offers 14
advanced placement courses, the suit says, while Inglewood High in
South Los Angeles, mainly black and Hispanic, has only 3.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU says the lawsuit, based on files from the state's own
Department of Education, is the first in the nation to focus on the
effects of limited access to advanced courses. It says these
courses are more important than ever now that California's public
universities are barred from using race and sex as criteria for
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   At the top campuses, the average grade-point average for
entering freshmen exceeds 4.0, with the help of weighted grades for
advanced placement. The average at the University of California at
Los Angeles last fall, for example, was 4.16.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is flunking out when it comes to educating these
students, denying them the intellectually challenging courses
designed to prepare them for college and holding them back by
squelching their competitive chances of acceptance,'' Mark
Rosenbaum, the civil liberties union's local legal director, said
at a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the State Board of Education said officials
there would not comment on the suit until they had been served with
a copy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
