<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DEEP-COX     07-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DEEP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharks bring biting roles to forefront
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in ``Deep Blue Sea,'' somebody comments that sharks don't
eat people, they just bite people. Sharks, the expert said, don't
like the taste of human flesh and don't go back for more after the
first nibble.
</P>
<P>
   If that had held true, ``Deep Blue Sea'' would have been over in
about 15 minutes. But the sharks in the summer's second
get-out-of-the-water-you-danged-fool flick develop an absolute
passion for man meat, so it lasts the usual hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the goofy ``Lake Placid,'' which premiered earlier this
month, though, ``Deep Blue Sea'' will keep your heart racing for
the duration. The plot has gaping holes, the dialogue is often
laughable, the acting is spotty, but the fish truly rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Blue Sea'' opens in classic monster-movie fashion with
four scantily clad, isolated teens making out on a sailboat in the
middle of nowhere. Soon there's something banging the bottom of the
boat, and the teens end up flailing around in the water with the
dark, submerged shape closing in.
</P>
<P>
   Before they're too badly chewed, though, Carter Blake (Thomas
Jane) shows up with a steely glint in his eye, a two-day growth of
manly beard, a wetsuit covering his tight buns and a harpoon gun.
</P>
<P>
   Carter works for Aquatica, a research facility based in a former
submarine fueling station. The station has a communications tower
topside but most of the laboratories and crew quarters are built
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, led by Dr. Susan McAlester (Saffron Burrows),
have installed titanium fences in the water around the station to
contain specially bred mako sharks they are using in research on a
drug to cure Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   When their financial backer, Russell Franklin (Samuel L.
Jackson), compliments them on making such dramatic progress in
their experiments without violating the Harvard accords on genetic
manipulation, the scientists start exchanging meaningful glances.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out they have violated restrictions against genetic
manipulation to make their mako sharks bigger, stronger, faster and
much, much smarter. Mako sharks already are among the fastest,
nastiest predators in the sea, and these scientists have pumped
them up to the size of great white sharks, as featured in the
``Jaws'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin is pushing the scientists to show positive results, so
they decide to conduct their biggest experiment yet in the middle
of a tropical storm on the weekend when most of the research staff
is off partying on the mainland. That way when things go awry, only
a handful of characters are left as shark bait.
</P>
<P>
   Director Renny Harlin, who also directed and produced Cutthroat
Island and ``The Long Kiss Goodnight,'' apparently comes from the
big orange fireball school of directing, and he fills ``Deep Blue
Sea'' with exaggerated explosions.
</P>
<P>
   You might think''Deep Blue Sea'' would follow the ``Jaws
formula,'' but it owes a lot more to ``Alien.'' A scene where
survivors try to climb up a wide shaft while the water with the
sharks in it rises below and burning debris falls from above is
reminiscent of Ripley's escape through venting steam, flashing
strobes and emergency sirens.
</P>
<P>
   Harlin's breakneck pacing is perfect for a story that doesn't
stand up to scrutiny if you actually stop to think about what's
going on. For instance, how much do these people think sharks eat?
After eating several times their own weight in other sharks and
research assistants, these sharks are still chasing everything
moving.
</P>
<P>
   The only question in ``Deep Blue Sea'' is who will get eaten and
who will get away. Potential victims include rapper-turned-actor
L.L. Cool J, Stellan Skarsgard (''Good Will Hunting'') and
Australian actress Jacqueline McKenzie, who reads her lines like
she's the narrator of a corporate promotional video.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint: He who spouts the stupidest lines gets eaten.
</P>
<P>
   For example, somebody says, ``Nature can be lethal but it
doesn't hold a candle to man.'' You're almost grateful when the
shark breaks up that speech.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: jamescummings(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
