<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AT&AMP;T KNOWS WHAT'S IN A NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 4th graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Mercedes-Benz brand name can be affixed to a
sport-utility vehicle, if the Heinz brand name can appear on
mustard and if the Fritos brand name can be attached to chili, then
why not use the AT&AMP;T brand name for cable television service?
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. is doing just that, having announced Tuesday an
ambitious ``rebranding'' program to change the name of all products
and services offered by Tele-Communications Inc., which AT&AMP;T
acquired in March for $59.4 billion. Beginning next Tuesday, the
TCI Cable name will disappear, to be replaced by the moniker AT&AMP;T
Cable Services, part of a unit known as AT&AMP;T Broadband and Internet
Services, as well as the AT&AMP;T blue-globe logo.
</P>
<P>
   The change, which will take about six months to complete, has a
budget of $30 million just for the tangible elements, including $8
million for new signs, $6 million for new employee uniforms and $6
million to repaint 15,500 service trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The renaming will be extended beyond TCI Cable to include TCI
Digital Cable, now AT&AMP;T Digital Cable, which provides features like
an interactive on-screen guide and pay-per-view channels, and
TCI(AT)Home, now AT&AMP;T(AT)Home, the high-speed Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, part of the $150 million that TCI Cable has spent
annually on marketing will be devoted to pitches informing more
than 10 million customers of more than 600 local cable systems that
whatever was once TCI will henceforth be rebranded with the
familiar AT&AMP;T name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest brand transition in our company's history,''
Leo Hindery, president and chief executive of the broadband unit in
Englewood, Colo., said in a conference call news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The brand switcheroo is emblematic of efforts by AT&AMP;T to remake
itself into a provider of myriad communications services in
addition to its mainstay long-distance telephone operations. The
goal is for AT&AMP;T to keep pace with the regional Bell operating
companies like Bell Atlantic Corp. and SBC Communications Inc.,
which may offer long-distance services in a year.
</P>
<P>
   With the takeover of TCI, and the pending purchase of Mediaone
Group Inc. for $62.5 billion, AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest
long-distance provider, will also become the largest cable TV
company. AT&AMP;T is betting that the venerable AT&AMP;T brand name,
freshened when the words ``American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph'' were
eliminated in favor of the initials, will prove more appealing to
consumers than the TCI or Mediaone brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is obviously very well-known to consumers for the
long-distance business,'' said Doug Seserman, senior vice president
for marketing at AT&AMP;T Broadband and Internet Services. ``And prior
to the spinoff of Lucent Technologies, AT&AMP;T was branded on other
products like telephones and computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Research among consumers found that ``AT&AMP;T stands for trust,
reliability, quality of service and good price value,'' he added.
``And AT&AMP;T is also seen as the best brand to bring bundled services
to homes, whether long distance, cable or Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   While the puissance of the AT&AMP;T name may benefit the TCI
operations, the rebranding is risky, too, because it has the
potential to tarnish the luster of the AT&AMP;T image.
</P>
<P>
   ``TCI is a typical cable company brand with a typical cable
company image _ quite negative,'' said Clive Chajet, chairman of
Chajet Consultancy LLC in New York, a brand- and corporate-identity
consulting firm. ``Those brands have never gained for themselves
good reputations.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chajet said he thought the rebranding was a shrewd move.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is a classic example of a great brand name _ as good as
it gets,'' he said. ``That certainly would benefit any
communication service with the convergence of components like
television, telephones and high-speed access to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for any dilution of the AT&AMP;T image by extending it beyond
telephony, Chajet said that ``years ago I was hired by AT&AMP;T to work
on the AT&AMP;T Universal credit card, and when we asked consumers if
the AT&AMP;T name would work on a credit card, they said absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are old enough to remember, the AT&AMP;T nickname was Ma
Bell,'' he added, chuckling. ``And who is more trusted than
mother?''
</P>
<P>
   The initial advertising to promulgate word of the rebranding is
being created by two agencies that had worked for TCI, Seserman
said: Jordan McGrath Case &AMP; Partners/Euro RSCG in New York, part of
the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising, and Thomas &AMP;
Perkins in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working with our colleagues in Basking Ridge as to
long-term plans for marketing communications,'' Seserman added,
referring to the New Jersey village where AT&AMP;T has its
headquarters. The two principal AT&AMP;T agencies _ Foote, Cone &AMP;
Belding Worldwide in New York, part of True North Communications,
and Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York _ are also working on
assignments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mediaone name, Hindery said that ``we're fully
intending'' to rebrand it as AT&AMP;T Cable Services as soon as the
deal closes, which he anticipated for sometime in the first quarter
of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
