<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATWAVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, FURNACE OF LATE JULY COOLS, BUT IT WON'T LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ohio, Ill., N.C., S.C., Ark., N.Y., Fla., Texas, Kan.,
Okla.)  (lh) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ The heat wave hitting the middle and eastern
United States let up in some parts Tuesday, but only after claiming
more than 30 lives. And forecasters say the relief is only
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Urban areas are bearing the brunt of the death toll. Seven
heat-related deaths have been reported in Missouri, all in St.
Louis, since the heat wave began last week. Officials reported 10
heat-related deaths in Cincinnati, 12 in Chicago, at least three in
other parts of Illinois and two in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Artusa, a meteorologist with the National Weather
Service's climate prediction center in Camp Springs, Md., said hot
and humid air from the Equator was traveling farther north this
summer, so parts of the country not used to such prolonged heat are
getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A larger part of the country is seeing this hot and humid
weather,'' Artusa said, ``and it is preventing a number of cold
fronts and cooler air from moving down into the United States from
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Warner, a meteorologist at Penn State University, said
there was some slight cooling in parts of the Midwest Tuesday, and
temperatures were only in the 80s Tuesday afternoon across the
northern Plains and much of the Ohio Valley. But some of the day's
hottest temperatures, in the upper 90s and over 100, were being
reported in northern Texas and in Oklahoma and Kansas, he said. On
the East Coast, temperatures rose into the 90s again; New York City
recorded its fifth consecutive day of temperatures over 90.
</P>
<P>
   But the number that indicates what people are really feeling is
the heat index, which factors the heat and the humidity. In many
parts of the Midwest and the South, that number has been above 105
degrees for more than a week. Warner predicted a return this week
of the unusually hot weather in areas that got a respite Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In East St. Louis, Ill., across the river from St. Louis, at
least two deaths have been attributed to the heat. George Foster,
an emergency services coordinator for the city, said a shower
produced a break in the weather Tuesday; temperatures reached 90,
down from the high of 102 on Monday. Still, Foster said he spent
part of his day visiting elderly people to make sure they are aware
of the heat danger.
</P>
<P>
   Foster told of one woman who was sitting in her steamy apartment
with the air-conditioner turned off. He persuaded her to turn it
on, and stayed with her until the room cooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of seniors are on a fixed income and don't want to pay
the electric bill that goes up when you use your air-conditioner,''
he said. ``I tell them worry about the bill later, and worry about
staying alive right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The lower temperatures gave a break to utility companies
struggling to keep up with the demand of 24-hour air-conditioners
and fans, but several companies were still asking customers to
conserve electricity where they could.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued excessive heat warnings for
six states from Arkansas to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, a hot weather health warning issued by the state
last Tuesday remained in effect. That warning is issued after two
days of heat indexes above 105 degrees, and if that pattern is
predicted to continue for at least two more days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there is not going to be a real break for us
until sometime next week,'' said Diane Rackers, a spokeswoman for
the Missouri Emergency Management Agency. ``This is definitely the
worst heat we have had all summer, and probably the worst we have
seen in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, where steamy, sweltering days and nights are a
fact of life in mid-July, some areas are also experiencing
abnormally high temperatures. The Georgia Emergency Management
Agency issued a heat advisory for central and southern parts of the
state for Tuesday and Wednesday. That means heat indexes are
expected to be above 105. A spokeswoman for the agency said heat
indexes of 105 to 115 were predicted, with temperatures reaching
100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, New York state registered its 12th day in the 90s
this year, The Associated Press reported. That is typically the
number of 90-plus readings for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a ``Bermuda high'' sitting over the East, with its
clockwise rotation pumping hot, humid air north, this July could be
one of the hottest on record for the city, the news agency reported
Bob Stalker of the National Weather Service as saying. The average
temperature for the month is 77, but the average this July is close
to 81.
</P>
<P>
   In the coastal areas of South Carolina, where the heat is
usually tempered by ocean breezes, temperatures typically reach the
high 80s and low 90s this time of year. But Tuesday the
temperatures in Hilton Head, S.C., climbed close to 100, with a
heat index of about 110.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hilton Head national golf course, the 7:45 a.m. tee time
is always the easiest to get. But in the past few days of boiling
weather, it has become the most sought-after starting time for
golfers who want to get their games in before the heat of the
midday.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Squat and Gobble restaurant in Bluffton, near Hilton
Head Island, the head waitress, Brenda Wirthlin, finally had to
tell lunch patrons that the restaurant had run out of iced tea. On
a normal day, she said, customers drink about 7 gallons of iced
tea, but Tuesday she sold 21 gallons at lunch alone.
</P>
<P>
   Christie Johnson, of the South Carolina Emergency Management
Agency, summed up the weather this way: ``We are used to heat in
this part of the country, but this is too hot, even for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
