<SLUG> BC-TEN-WHEELCHAIR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES FIRST, INSPIRATION SECOND ON THIS TENNIS TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has biceps big enough to house newborns and an upper body as
impenetrable as concrete. When Stephen Welch is on the tennis
court, he plays with soul and a desire that often has him crashing
into the fence to track down potential winners.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is Welch's 27th birthday, and his girlfriend, Amy
Riley, obtained tickets to ``Late Show With David Letterman.'' But
they have to cancel because he has a match.
</P>
<P>
   Welch, the No. 2 wheelchair tennis player in the world, will
lead the top-seeded U.S. team against Poland in the quarterfinal
round of the World Team Cup, which is being played at the National
Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   When this week is over, Welch will head to Europe to play more
tennis. He is in the middle of nine straight weeks on the road. So
goes the life of a professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in a wheelchair has been a big blessing in my life,''
Welch said. ``At first I was aware of all the things I couldn't do.
Now, I'm looking at all the things I have done. Being in a
wheelchair helped me realize my dream: being a professional
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch developed a love for sports at age 4, when he took up
boxing. Then came baseball and soccer and track and swimming. But
when he was 8, doctors discovered that Welch had a degenerative
bone disease in his hip. He would not be able to walk long
distances without pain. He would need a wheelchair to get around,
and, certainly, he could not play sports the way able-bodied
children did.
</P>
<P>
   The other day Welch was telling Amy how good a baseball player
he once was. He told her he hit five home runs, including three
grand slams, in what would be his final year in Little League.
</P>
<P>
   When he first heard of his condition, Welch grew angry. He was
already aspiring to be a pro. But then he started playing
wheelchair basketball a few months later. He realized that he could
still be an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Now Welch is playing in one of the most storied tennis complexes
in the world. More than 270 world-class wheelchair tennis players,
representing 32 countries, are competing in the World Team Cup,
which is the wheelchair tennis equivalent to the Davis Cup. It is
the first time Flushing Meadows has played host to the event, and
it is the first time in more than a decade that the event has been
played in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has teams competing in all three divisions:
the top-seeded men, the women (seeded No. 2) and the quadriplegic
(seeded No. 1). The World Team Cup is a two-of-three series. The
quadriplegic final is Friday; the women's is on Saturday and the
men's on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To the average fan, their stories are inspirational. But all the
athletes here want to be more than human interest stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys joke around about the `I' word,'' said the U.S. men's
coach, Dan James, who is not disabled, referring to inspirational.
``They want to be recognized because of their skill. This group is
perfectly willing to kid about themselves, their disability, what
they have to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch is one of the stars of wheelchair tennis, which has
blossomed during its 15 years with the International Tennis
Federation. Fifteen years ago, wheelchair tennis was a fun
exhibition that served as a breather between matches during
tournaments. Now, the players have a full summer schedule that
carries them overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the tour in 1992, Welch has been a mainstay in the
top five. He has never won more than $6,750 in any tournament, but
his travel costs are paid for by his sponsors, Invacare, a company
that makes wheelchairs, Powerbar and Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Welch, who lives in Ft. Worth, Tex., is known for his speed on
the court and for his deadly topspin backhand. Most players use
their shoulder to make that shot, but he has to use his triceps.
It's a tough shot for wheelchair players to handle because the ball
bounces high. Welch developed muscular arms by pushing around his
18-pound wheelchair, which is made of titanium and aircraft
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, Welch plays basketball in an international
league. His team won the championship last season, and Welch was
named most valuable player for the second year in a row. He
averaged 25 points a game for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My disability is something I don't choose to focus on,'' Welch
said. ``I'm here, we're all here, for an athletic event.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch can walk short distances and do things like go to the
kitchen or to the shower in the hotel. Other than that, he uses his
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a great athlete,'' Riley said. ``People have to
realize that it takes a whole lot of ability to do what these guys
are doing. When I first met Steve, I remember him being so in love
with life. He thanks God everyday that he can walk, but that he is
also in a wheelchair because of what it has brought to his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
