<SLUG> BC-ARK-OTHER-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO LITTLE ROCK'S MAYOR, THAT OTHER MAYOR IS JUST ANOTHER MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With BC-NY-GIULIANI-ARK-NYT) (lh) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ There were two mayors roaming around this
soggy city Tuesday, but while the out-of-town Republican one with
the funny accent _ Rudolph Giuliani _ was flanked by bodyguards and
television cameras, the Democratic one, who has quietly presided
over the city for the last six years, was ducking out the back door
of City Hall, all by himself, for a quick drive.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man in a straw hat waved from the sidewalk, but no
one else seemed to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit less of a security apparatus around me than
around Giuliani, wouldn't you say?'' said the other mayor, Jim
Dailey, grinning as he slipped off his jacket and slipped into the
front of his Jeep Cherokee. Like Giuliani's familiar mayoral Chevy
Suburban, Dailey's Jeep is a blinding good-guy white, but that's
where the similarities end. It does not come with a chauffeur. It
does not contain any high-tech communications gear, except for a
cell phone. It is not filled with a team of zealously devoted
staffers, though Dailey's assistant did give him a typed-out
afternoon agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And when this mayor's agenda did not quite work out, as it did
not Tuesday, that is where the similarities between the two men _
both conservatives, both Roman Catholics, both in their 50s, both
with heads growing bereft of hair _ also end.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey had dashed out of City Hall Tuesday to try to greet
Giuliani officially _ mayor to mayor, politics aside _ at the
Rebsamen Golf Course along the Arkansas River, where Giuliani and
the state's lieutenant governor, Winthrop Paul Rockefeller, went to
hit a few balls. But Dailey arrived just a few minutes after the
Giuliani convoy had pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad-gum-it,'' said Dailey, scanning the links. Then he quickly
added in his whispery drawl, ``Oh, well, it's not the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Which gives you a good indication of why the Little Rock mayor
somehow did not seem to mind at all that the New York mayor had
come barnstorming into his city like a pudgy rock star in a tan
cotton suit. And that the New York mayor had come barnstorming
essentially to stick his finger in the eye of his potential
opponent for a New York Senate seat, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who
happens to be a good friend of the Little Rock mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to divorce myself from the political point he's
making,'' Dailey had said earlier in his office, where Giuliani
called him Tuesday morning as a courtesy. ``To me he's another
mayor, and be he Republican or Democrat or independent, I am
honored to have him in our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more graciously, Dailey added, ``As I indicated to him on
the phone, I certainly support Hillary, and yet I wish them both
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But later, on his way back from the golf course with the ``Big
on Little Rock'' T-shirt he had hoped to give to Giuliani, he
acknowledged that maybe he should try to act a little more
partisan. ``There's a criticism I get a lot from some of my
business friends _ that they don't think I'm tough enough, I don't
have enough of an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   And how does he think this might make him different from the
other mayor in town? He smiled. ``Well, I'd say my style is a much
more facilitating, `let's try to keep everybody at the table, let's
try to have a win-win' style.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, lest all of this be perceived as a criticism of Giuliani,
he added: ``There are a lot of different management styles that are
out there. I don't know that one is better than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say that Dalton James Dailey Jr., who turns 57 on
Saturday, was born to this kind of conciliation. From almost the
time he was old enough to talk, he dealt with a constituency,
though it was one of customers, not voters. He helped out, and then
helped run, his family's office-products business, where he learned
from his father the importance of keeping the customers happy. And
throughout his political life, the salesman in him has often
overshadowed the politician.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he even left city government and decided not to run for
Congress when he had a chance to become the president of the
National Office Products Association, making him, he proudly points
out, the first and only Arkansan to hold that job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that to tout myself, but just merely to give
you information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But city government attracted him back, and after being
appointed mayor by the City Council in 1992 under a different city
system, he became the first popularly elected mayor in more than
three decades in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The job has not made him rich. (His salary is $36,000 a year;
Giuliani's was recently raised to $195,000.) But in a city of
175,000, it is also not quite as busy a job as Giuliani's, in a
city of 7.3 million. There were, for example, 629 murders reported
last year in New York, a number bigger than the size of Little
Rock's whole police force. But on his own scale, Dailey says he
thinks he has accomplished a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Poor neighborhoods are rebuilding. As in New York, crime has
fallen greatly _ in a city that once had one of the highest per
capita murder rates in the country. But more importantly, in
another accomplishment he would share with the mayor of that other
city, Dailey says he believes he is quietly changing Little Rock's
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people now see,'' he said, ``that we are not some
hillbilly place, where people go around barefoot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
