u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-DEATH-APPEAL-NYT     07-27 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEATH-APPEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY COURT DENIES APPEAL FOR DEATH ROW INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
 (yn) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In a move that could clear the way for New
Jersey's first execution in more than 35 years, the State Supreme
Court on Tuesday denied an appeal filed by the public defender's
office on behalf of a condemned prisoner who has asked to die.
</P>
<P>
   John Martini Sr. was sentenced to death in 1990 for the 1989
kidnapping and murder of a Bergen County businessman. The justices
ruled 6-1 Tuesday that the state public defender's office did not
prove that the defendant's original trial lawyers were incompetent.
The justices also rejected an argument that new evidence discovered
about Martini's troubled past might have persuaded jurors to spare
him a death sentence and instead opt for a life prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the majority opinion, Chief Justice Deborah Poritz
argued that the mitigating evidence, which has never been publicly
revealed, might also have harmed Martini's standing in the eyes of
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence, if used, would have opened the door to damaging
rebuttal evidence by the state,'' Poritz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the ruling, Judge Bruce A. Gaeta of New Jersey
Superior Court set an execution date for Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Friedman, the assistant public defender who argued the
appeal on Martini's behalf, said he was disappointed by Tuesday's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The lone justice to dissent from the majority opinion was Alan
B. Handler, who has consistently opposed the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Martini was scheduled to meet Tuesday with Alan Zegas, the
court-appointed lawyer pursuing the request for a speedy execution.
Zegas said Martini was relieved that his wait for execution
appeared to be moving toward its end. He said he asked Martini if
he still wanted to forgo any appeals. ``He told me: `Absolutely.
How would you feel having to wake up every day in a bed with
roaches all around?'''
</P>
<P>
   Zegas said Martini also complained that he had been suffering
from medical problems. Lawyers from the public defender's office
are to meet with Martini on Wednesday and urge him to appeal his
case in Federal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Before Martini asked for a speedy execution, the State Supreme
Court had twice upheld his sentence. Some of Martini's
acquaintances say he has recently expressed reservations about his
request. When he asked to let the execution go ahead in 1995, he
was being held in a Philadelphia prison which, he said, had such
deplorable conditions that death would be a relief. Martini, 68, is
now housed in the more hospitable confines of the New Jersey State
Prison's capital sentencing unit in Trenton and is reconsidering
his decision, a confidant said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Martini continues his opposition to further appeals,
other challenges to the state's death penalty law, and the
logistics of carrying out capital punishment for the first time in
more than 30 years, will most likely stall any execution for
months, legal experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
