<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SET TO COME OUT AS SARATOGA OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ An undefeated 2-year-old filly will
lead the parade of star horses onto the Saratoga Race Course when
it opens Wednesday for New York's 131st season of racing in the
Adirondacks. And ready to follow them into the spotlight before the
week closes are the early favorite for next year's Kentucky Derby
and several candidates for this year's Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The meet opens with a steeplechase race at 1 o'clock, and runs
for six weeks through Labor Day, Sept. 6, with stakes races almost
every day and top trainers sending their top horses onto the stage
in a state-fair atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The season reaches a peak Aug. 28 when many of the best
3-year-olds in the country meet in ``the summertime Kentucky
Derby,'' the $1 million Travers.
</P>
<P>
   The grand old track on Union Avenue was getting its final
touches Tuesday from crews of workmen watering the
mile-and-one-eighth oval track in scorching heat, combing the
flower beds, raking the picnic areas and adding some flourishes for
the fans: a new sound system, a new grandstand roof and new
television monitors from the paddock to the seats at the head of
the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meet is two days old, one dozen promising 2-year-old
horses will have raced in the $100,000 Schuylerville for fillies on
Wednesday and the $100,000 Sanford for colts on Thursday. Both will
be run at six furlongs, and both will feature undefeated juveniles:
Magicalmysterycat, the stakes-winning filly from the West Coast,
and More Than Ready, the stakes-winning colt who set a track record
when he won the Tremont at Belmont Park on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Magicalmysterycat has raced three times and won three times, all
at Hollywood Park under the trainer D. Wayne Lukas. She is a
daughter of Storm Cat, who has sired 73 stakes winners. But she
will have to outrun Ogden Phipps' Finder's Fee, another daughter of
Storm Cat, who has won two of her three starts, including the
Astoria at Belmont Park on July 2. And both will have to outrun
Michael Tabor's Circle of Life, who made her debut at Belmont on
July 8 and won by more than eight lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we took a base on balls running her against New
York-breds the first time out,'' Todd Pletcher, who trains Circle
of Life, said. ``We were looking for a race that would help give
her confidence, and not be too stressful. We got just that. Now, we
are stepping up into a different category, and I think this is
typical of a 2-year-old stakes race at Saratoga. What you have are
the most accomplished horses in the division at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher, the leading trainer at Belmont Park in its recent
summertime meet and the leading trainer at Saratoga last year, is
also the trainer of More Than Ready, Thursday's star. The colt
faces a tight field of only four rivals in the Sanford, which wrote
a footnote to history 80 years ago as the only race that the great
Man o' War lost. More Than Ready has won all four of his starts,
and Pletcher envisions a future of great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it,'' he said, ``we have a horse that is 4-for-4
and who broke a track record in the Tremont that had existed for 26
years. The way he has done everything to this point, I think,
clearly established him as one of the most impressive 2-year-old
colts we've seen in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The rush of events continues on Friday with the first stakes
race on the turf, the Bernard Baruch. It will be followed on the
weekend by a pair of headliners: the 74th running of the Test
Stakes for fillies on Saturday and the 72nd running of the Whitney
Handicap on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney is expected to be a blockbuster, with a cast headed
by Behrens, one of the foremost candidates for Horse of the Year,
and Victory Gallop, the winner of last year's Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   They will face a strong field that includes Sir Bear, Catienus
and Connecting Terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
