<HEADLINE>
SNOWBIRDS FLYING SOUTH WEST FOR WIN TER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on the continued urbanization of the Southeast Valley,
construction workers competing for scarce RV spaces or the extended
slide of the Canadian dollar, but metropolitan Phoenix seems to be
falling out of favor as a winter visitor destination.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of steady increases, the number of snowbirds
wintering in the Phoenix area has declined for the second year in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University's annual Winter Visitor Survey found
that 3,700, or about 3 percent, fewer two-person households set up
winter residency in the Valley during the winter of 1998-99 than in
the season before. A similar decline was observed for the winter of
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The declines could be costly. Surveys indicate that more than
100,000 snowbird households take up residency in the Phoenix area
each winter and they spend an average $1,600 per month.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Visitor Survey is conducted by the College of
Business Center for Business Research and counts only households
living in RV or mobile home parks for more than 30 days from
October through May.
</P>
<P>
   Because Canadians typically make up as many as 15 to 20 percent
of the state's winter visitors, the drop can be partially
attributed to the weak Canadian dollar. But the research center's
manager, Tom Rex, believes there could be other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exchange rate for the Canadian dollar has dropped
to about $1.50 from $1.20 a few years back, Rex noted that the
large declines were felt in the mid-1990s and that the rates have
been relatively stable the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think the impact would have been felt a couple of
years ago if the exchange rate was the only factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rex also said that the drop in winter residents is being felt
only in the urban areas of the state, namely metropolitan Phoenix
and Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   More rural areas such as Yuma County, Parker and Lake Havasu
City saw their winter visitor counts increase last winter by more
than 1,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside the metropolitan areas, the number of winter visitors
seems to be increasing,'' Rex said.
</P>
<P>
   He was unable to explain the phenomenon, but thought the
increased urbanization of traditionally rural areas around Mesa and
Apache Junction could be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These typically are not urban folks,'' Rex said of the
Valley's winter visitors. ``Many of these people are coming from
farms and rural areas in Canada and the upper Midwest, and the
increased urbanization of the Valley may not sit well with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Newton at Val Vista Village in Mesa acknowledged that an
unusually high number of long-time, winter residents have recently
been leaving the park.
</P>
<P>
   At Apache Junction's Golden Vista RV Resort, Manager Glenn
Eubank said business was off last winter as much as 50 percent
during some weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't see the turnout last winter that we're used
to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rex, the Valley's booming economy also could be
gobbling up snowbirds' favorite RV spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger households coming into the area in response to the
state's strong market may be moving into some parks and displacing
the seasonal residents,'' Rex said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have been doing better attracting the higher-paying
jobs, many still offer relatively low pay and workers might have
trouble fitting into any other type of housing.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to better explain the slide, Rex said new questions
will be added to next year's Winter Visitors Survey to gain a
better understanding of what may be causing the snowbird exodus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
