<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-INJURIES-C     07-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-INJURIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves seek deadline-deals to fill lineup holes
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The question is no longer if. Now, the question is
who. And when and for how much in return.
</P>
<P>
   Some trading deadlines have rushed by John Schuerholz so
furiously that the Braves general manager was surprised he ever
thought he could make a deal. When midnight Saturday arrives, ``It
would surprise if we don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the bigger wonder is, given the loss of four regulars
through sickness or injury, that the Braves haven't done much yet.
Atlanta has slipped into offensive mediocrity, entering Tuesday
play ranked seventh in NL RBIs (493) and 11th in average (.266).
After a robust April (.274, 6.2 runs per game), production has
steadily declined in the ensuing three months (.263, 4.8 runs per
game).
</P>
<P>
   The loss of catcher Javy Lopez, whose knee surgery is scheduled
for Monday, combined with the New York Mets' post-All-Star break
surge, make a roster adjustment virtually mandatory. To date, the
only acquisitions have been pitchers Justin Speier (since demoted)
and John Hudek (since designated for assignment) and catcher Greg
Myers, a career .256 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter the hue, no matter the cry, we've done the same
thing for nine years,'' Schuerholz said. ``We try to make decisions
that are right for the organization. This year (is) a little more
challenging because of the injuries we've had to key people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be that as it may, we'll still do what we can to make
ourselves stronger by degrees. That will be a function of what kind
of deals are available for us to make.''
</P>
<P>
   As the club collects itself from a tumultuous Monday _ both
Lopez and left-hander Odalis Perez were declared out for the season
_ the nature of those deals is still evolving. The club is
investigating the availablity of veteran first basemen, inquiring
specifically about Will Clark in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has been seeking offers for Eric Karros, who is the
midst of a solid 23-homer, 65-RBI season. The Chicago Cubs, stuck
in last place with little hope for contention, could also move Mark
Grace, a 10-year veteran who can veto a trade who might be willing
to leave Chicago for the right circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be one of those guys you rent for two months
and then have to be looking for work at the end of the season,''
said Grace, whose contract expires at the end of the year. ``I'd
probably want a guarantee from the team I go to that they'll retain
me for the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But another trade strategy involves not replacing Lopez's bat in
the middle of the order but finding one to add to the top. Braves
Nos. 1 and 2 hitters are batting a combined .237, 38 points below
the league average. Braves lead-off hitters have a .309 on-base
percentage. The league norm is .351.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz has long touted Kansas City outfielder Johnny Damon,
a veteran lead-off hitter who is aribtration eligible for the
cash-strapped Royals. Montreal has been talking with the New York
Yankees about outfielder Rondell White, the Gray, Ga., product, who
would be an interesting fixture as a No. 2 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Adding an outfielder would necessitate returning Ryan Klesko to
first base, which he is willing to do. But the Expos are not keen
on dealing White. They asked the Yankees for shortstop Alfonso
Soriano, the pride prospect in the New York system.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects are not the Braves' long suit at the moment. Of the
top 10 prospects listed by Baseball American when the season
started, three are already in Atlanta (Bruce Chen, Kevin McGlinchy
and Micah Bowie) and three others are either injured or
recuperating (Odalis Perez, George Lombard and Wes Helms).
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk all we want but it's hard to do deals,'' manager
Bobby Cox said. ``It's easier said than done. But we're looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Schuerholz has maneuvered at mid-season with deals that
made a difference into October the Fred McGriff trade in 1993 and
the Mike Devereaux deal in 1995. None of the players Atlanta gave
up in those deals are currently in the majors. This month shouldn't
come so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for what ultimately makes is the strongest
possible team fo the next two months,'' Schuerholz said. ``Well,
hopefully for the next three months.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
