<HEADLINE>
DRIVING TO PREVENT CHILD ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new driving force in child abuse prevention: a
specialized state license plate.
</P>
<P>
   The plate, unveiled today, has a pale blue background smudged
with children's handprints and the slogan, ''It shouldn't hurt to
be a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in January, the plates will sell for $25, $17 of which
will go to prevention programs statewide, such as home visits to
new parents, public awareness campaigns, parenting classes and
support groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' plans to match that money 60 cents on
the dollar _ or a total of $27.10 for every plate purchased _ as
part of its charitable efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The plate will be shown today at the Child Crisis Center, a
non-profit shelter and group home in Mesa. Director Chris Fickas,
who has pushed for the plate for the past nine months, already has
one on her car.
</P>
<P>
   And she has one for Gov. Jane Hull _ it says ``KIDSGUV'' _ and
another for Sen. Tom Freestone, R-Mesa, who sponsored the
legislation needed to produce the plates. His says ``SEN TOM.''
</P>
<P>
   Since late October, child advocates from across the state have
lobbied lawmakers for the plate. They made phone calls, went to
meetings, called on lawmakers' offices and gave media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   There was some resistance, especially in the House, where two
lawmakers voted against the plate. They would have preferred,
Freestone said, that the plate carry an insignia in the corner
instead of the full illustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `We have put this problem in the corner too
long,' '' the senator said. ``The key is prevention. We are tired
of victims. We want to stop child abuse before it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, more than 8,000 motorists have purchased ``I Care
About Kids'' license plates, raising $74,784 since 1998 for child
abuse prevention programs. A similar license plate in Indiana
raises $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Fickas guesses that the Arizona plate could raise as much as
that, if not more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't have time to volunteer, if they can't afford
to give a bunch of money, they can still do something for
children,'' Fickas said. ``They have to have a license plate on
their car and, for a few extra dollars, they can impact a family's
life in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a regular license plate is covered by an owner's
yearly registration fee. The cost of the specialty plates is on top
of that fee.
</P>
<P>
   These new plates join 25 others designating classic cars,
prisoners of war, vehicles that run on alternative fuel and
supporters of the state's universities.
</P>
<P>
   If the child abuse prevention plates approach the success of the
environmental plates, introduced in 1992, it could mean big money.
In 1997, the sale of 40,926 environmental plates raised $1.23
million.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the environmental plates is used for education
programs statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ault, an administrator with the state Department of
Economic Security, which oversees Child Protective Services, plans
to get one of the new plates for her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good reminder driving down the freeway to be conscious
of the way we treat our children,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
