<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-HIRING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SCORES HIGH IN HIRING MINORITY GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the annual report card issued by Northeastern University's
Center for the Study of Sport in Society, the National Basketball
Association received an overall A-minus for the hiring of members
of minority groups and B for its gender hiring, while the National
Football League had the lowest grade for gender with a D-plus. The
NFL did get a B-plus for hiring members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The professional and college sports were graded on their hiring
practices of members of minority groups and women, on and off the
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league baseball received a B for race, but was not graded
on gender because not enough information was available. College
sports were significantly behind the pros with C's for race and
gender diversity in hiring. Last year's report looked at race only
and the NBA received an A-minus, the NFL a B-minus and baseball was
given a conditional C. It was the 10th study conducted by the
center whose mission is to increase awareness of sport and its
relation to society. Richard Lapchick, the center's director, said:
``While the hiring practices in sport have gotten better for people
of color and women, there is clearly significant room for progress
in all sports. Nonetheless, pro sport is measurably ahead of
society in these matters.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, the report looked at the National
Hockey League, the Women's National Basketball Association and
Major League Soccer. Although the three were not graded, the report
noted that soccer had the best record for minority group diversity
and the NHL the best for opportunities for women. The WNBA had good
records regarding both minority group and gender diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In both the pro and the college ranks, improvement is needed in
moving members of minority groups and women into front-office
positions, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2251EDT &QL; 
