<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BREWERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No shortage of Braves power
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So the Braves have spent the past 88 games suppressing
their problems by pointing to their name at the top of the National
League East standings. Make that 89.
</P>
<P>
   While the second-place Mets paused for a night in their hot
pursuit, the Braves hitters, who may have taken exception to recent
talk about how injuries have weakened their lineup, stood up
Tuesday night and cried, ``What about us?''
</P>
<P>
   Using four home runs, what's left of the Braves' lineup reeled
in a third consecutive win, 10-2 over the Milwaukee Brewers. Kevin
Millwood handled the rest to pick up his first win since the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets lost for the first time in seven games,
allowing the Braves to ``stretch'' their lead back to 1 1/2 games.
The Mets had won 10 of 12 since the All-Star break before falling
to the Pirates 5-1 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night, Hideo Nomo had never allowed more than
three runs in eight previous starts against Atlanta. But he was
unable to handle a Braves lineup without Javy Lopez, who's gone for
the season, and Brian Jordan, who'll be out another few days.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves trailing 2-1, Ryan Klesko golfed a double to
deep right field in the fourth inning to raise his average over the
past two weeks to .435. Andruw Jones followed with a two-run homer
to left to give the Braves a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone smoked a 1-0 Nomo pitch to left field an inning later
for his 13th home run of the season, his second in the past five
days, and a 4-2 lead. Randall Simon added a two-run shot off Nomo
in the sixth, and Gerald Williams led off a four-run seventh with a
home run off Eric Plunk.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for Millwood, who pitched seven innings on three
days' rest. Four of the five hits off Millwood went for extra
bases, but he held his own with runners on base. He stranded Sean
Berry at third in the fifth inning on a pair of fly-ball outs to
right field, and Alex Ochoa at second in the sixth inning on a fly
to center.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
