<SLUG> BC-TIMES-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES IN A JOINT INTERNET NEWS OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times said Tuesday that it was
establishing a joint news operation with TheStreet.com, an online
financial news service, as part of the Times' effort to expand and
enhance its presence on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said that the goal of the alliance was to help The
Times provide regularly updated business news and analysis on its
Web site, and that the initiative was one of several aimed at
differentiating the Times' Internet offerings from those of its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not presuming that the stories are going to appear in
our paper; their prime purpose is to serve the Web audience,''
Joseph Lelyveld, executive editor of The Times, said in a
statement. ``That said, we expect that many of the readers drawn to
The Times by the upgraded spot business coverage on our Web site
will gravitate to the newspaper itself for greater depth and
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper said that Jack Lynch, an assistant business editor
with The Times, would help hire and oversee six reporters for
TheStreet.com and would report to Lelyveld and Dave Kansas,
TheStreet.com's editor in chief.
</P>
<P>
   In February, New York Times Co. agreed to invest $15 million in
cash and services for a minority stake in TheStreet.com, which made
its initial public stock offering in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
