<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WOODSTOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: OH, TO BE YOUNG AND AT THE WRONG WOODSTOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Woodstock '99 has ended in a nasty and embarrassing
riot, young people are no doubt dying to hear more about how nice
the original was in 1969, when there were no ripoff vendors selling
$4 bottles of water and we all shared food and lived in peace and
yada yada yada yada yada.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago I went to a concert with about 500,000
acquaintances and wound up stranded for several days in Bethel,
N.Y., in inclement weather with not much in the way of food and
even less security. We managed to get along and enjoy ourselves
while creating a landmark in American cultural history in our spare
time. Obviously, the lesson is that we were nicer than kids today
and that everybody under 30 made a terrible mistake by failing to
be born right after World War II, when all the truly cool people
were coming into the world.
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, I've always believed that the secret of the original
Woodstock's success, the thing that turned chaos into gold, was
pure terror. Circumstances that nobody anticipated had left us in
the middle of nowhere, the roads clogged and impassable in every
direction, with no way for us to get out or anybody else to get in.
We were on our own, and if we behaved well, it was probably because
we knew there was nobody to protect us from ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The guards who had been hired to provide security for the
concert _ many of whom seemed to be off-duty New York City police _
were as isolated as the rest of us, cut off from their hotels and
their supervisors by the impassable roads. I remember feeding a
couple of them, who huddled miserably by our campfire in the chilly
damp night. Police were not particularly popular with the Woodstock
set, but the idea that the forces of law and order were either
going to flee on foot or starve to death was nevertheless
unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people at the concert, of course, did not give the
slightest thought to the possible consequences _ I am thinking of
the ones who thought it was a good plan to take pills from perfect
strangers and pop them in their mouths. But when the music ended at
night and you found yourself walking through the dark, packed in
the middle of several hundred thousand adolescents, it was hard to
avoid contemplating what would happen if somebody suddenly yelled
``Fire!'' and started pushing.
</P>
<P>
   The great irony of Woodstock '99 was not that it was held at an
abandoned Air Force base, near the place where they used to keep
the nuclear weapons. It was that the very amenities the producers
provided eliminated that sense of repressed wariness that pervaded
the original as much as mud and the smell of marijuana. Having
learned the lesson of the gate-crashers at Woodstock '69 and '94,
the organizers created a sort of monster fortress in Rome, N.Y.,
for this summer's concert, and filled it with souvenir stands and
fast-food outlets and videogame parlors and cash machines. The
overpriced soda and pizza might have made the kids feel ripped off,
but the very availability of so much bounty was proof that they
were still in civilization, under the protection of unseen but
efficient corporate authority figures.
</P>
<P>
   One of my strongest memories of the original Woodstock was of an
argument between a state trooper and a desperate farmer who was
trying to drive against traffic down a one-lane road that was lined
on both sides with abandoned vehicles. ``I gotta get home and milk
my cows,'' the farmer said, as the stream of pilgrims continued to
march, ride, walk, skip and otherwise make their way toward the
distant mecca where music was actually alleged to be happening.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper shook his head sadly and pointed the farmer in the
other direction. His cows could not have been more unreachable if
they had been parked on a floe in the middle of the Arctic Ocean. I
imagined them exploding, unsung victims of the Woodstock
phenomenon. It was another worry to add to stampedes, pneumonia and
midnight assault by drug-deluded maniacs.
</P>
<P>
   Along with music and good intentions, Woodstock '69 was created
by the consciousness of terrible possibilities. You can't recreate
it at five-year intervals. Trying is an awful idea, as bad as a
Beatles reunion or the ``Avengers'' movie. Bury the concept and let
this generation find its own disasters to avert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
