<SLUG> BC-BROWN-OUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC COALITION CALLS FOR TV BOYCOTT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A national coalition of Latino groups is asking all
Hispanics to boycott the four major TV networks in September to
protest the ``brownout'' of Latino characters on prime-time
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``If network executives have created a brownout of Latinos on
television, then Latinos will brownout television in response,''
said Felix Sanchez, president of the National Hispanic Foundation
for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation and nine other groups called for the one-week
boycott beginning Sept. 12 following an emergency summit during the
National Council of La Raza annual conference meeting in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 12 coincides with National Hispanic Heritage Week.
</P>
<P>
   The conference of more than 240 affiliate Latino organizations
concludes Wednesday at the George R. Brown Convention Center. Vice
President Al Gore is scheduled to deliver a luncheon speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Latino boycott comes on the heels of an announcement two
weeks ago by the NAACP that it also is considering boycotts and
legal action unless networks diversify their programming.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Nogales, spokesman for the National Hispanic Media
Coalition, said Latinos were ``mad as hell'' when they learned that
of the 26 new shows on the fall lineup, only one includes a
minority in a primary or secondary role. Actor Martin Sheen (born
Ramon Estevez) will star on NBC-TV's ``West Wing,'' beginning in
the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's par for the course,'' said Nogales. ``We're all tired
of talking to the networks about the same thing and having the same
promises given to us to achieve absolutely nothing at the end of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change has to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Latino groups plan a meeting in Washington the week of Sept.
12 to formally launch the boycott and take additional action they
say could include legal and regulatory remedies, appeals to
advertisers and purchasing network stock to influence stockholder
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the initial part of a broader fight,'' said La
Raza President Raul Yzaguirre, citing the collective $380 billion
annual purchasing power of the nation's 31 million Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this to be a protracted battle and we expect to
announce a series of other initiatives in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanics make up 11 percent of the American population,
they are less than 2 percent of the characters on prime-time
television shows and are portrayed more negatively and
stereotypically than other groups, coalition members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Cosby said `The Bill Cosby Show' did more for civil
rights than any piece of civil rights legislation because we had an
experience with black America. We understood black America to be no
different than who we were as regular Americans,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to say Latinos are regular Americans and we have yet
to have that simple statement reflected on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC said in a statement that including minorities is a top
priority. ``Although we are very proud of the minority
representation in many of NBC's dramas, including ''ER,`` ''Law &AMP;
Order,`` the upcoming ''Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit`` and
''Third Watch,`` we realize that there is still work to be done.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A CBS spokesman Tuesday referred to comments made earlier in
the week by CBS President Leslie Moonves in which he admitted that
``a lot more needs to be done about Latino inclusion.'' Moonves
said CBS had just added a Latino character to ``Family Law,'' a new
fall series, as well as specials featuring cross-over singers
Gloria Estefan and Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But while Moonves agreed television should reflect the racial
composition of America, he added, ``We do not think it fair that
the network of Bill Cosby (''Cosby,`` ''Kids Say the Darndest
Things``), Della Reese (Touched by an Angel), Cheech Marin (Nash
Bridges) and Arsenio Hall and Sammo Hung (Martial Law) should be
accused of not recognizing the minority audience.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said he wants to meet with La Raza, the NAACP and any
other groups protesting the lack of diversity in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dandridge, ABC vice president of communications, pointed out
that ABC airs the annual ALMA awards show, a La Raza-produced
counterpart to the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy a close relationship with them and we are willing to
meet with them or any organization that has constructive ideas on
how to address this very serious issue,'' Dandridge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize we need to do more; we are doing more. Judge us
by what we do in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Coalition members, which also include the League of United Latin
American Citizens and the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund, said they would seek a meeting with the NAACP to
pursue a joint effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only asking that people reflect the truth of where we
are,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at all those shows set in New York and you have
this incredible mosaic of people living in that city and you only
reflect all-white people on a show like `Friends,' the issue is,
are there no amigos in New York?''
</P>
<P>
   On the week of the boycott, coalition leaders are urging Latinos
and sympathetic Americans of all backgrounds to rent videos
featuring Latino themes or read Latino literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live in a fenced-in community, you see Latinos as your
gardener, as your maid, as your nanny, as the busboy and the
waiter, and we're there, there's no question, they're honest
jobs,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are more than that and that is what people fail to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
