<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES_NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS FIGHT FOR THE CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A learning opportunity presents itself this week
for those who envision themselves taking a major leap in the
rankings. They might want to watch Australians Lleyton Hewitt and
Andrew Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   They made the greatest leaps last year. The 18-year-old Hewitt,
seeded seventh, jumped 609 spots to 113 and has since climbed to
33. Ilie ended 1997 ranked 473 and finished 1998 at 59, a leap of
414 positions. He's currently 61st.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being Aussies (Ilie is naturalized; he was born in
Romania), the pair share other traits. They're both aggressive
baseliners who hit solid ground strokes and return serves well.
</P>
<P>
   They also never give up, which served Ilie well in his match
Tuesday against Byron Black. Ilie won in straight sets but served
for the match leading 6-4, 5-3 and lost. Black fought back to force
a tiebreaker, and Ilie missed on two other match points before
finally winning 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighters out there. We really want it,'' Ilie said. ``I
enjoy a good fight. I come back all the time. I value the important
points out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar face: Hewitt must have felt a sense of deja vu when he
looked across the court and saw Alex O'Brien as his first-round
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   It was nine days ago in Boston that Hewitt defeated O'Brien in a
Davis Cup reverse singles match.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt was disappointed he didn't get to face Pete Sampras, but
Australia's coach, John Newcombe, told him to pay attention anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat me down and said, `You could face him later on the
tour,''' Hewitt said. ``You could have a psychological advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   So here they were again, and there was Hewitt winning again,
this time 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   It's safer: Hewitt used to play Australian-rules football until
age 13, when he decided he could make more money and not get as
badly hurt by playing tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries did come into it,'' he said, ``but I was a little bit
better at tennis at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pull the monkey out of the bag: That's the saying Ilie's coach,
Nels Van Patten, has for Ilie when he's struggling and needs to
work some on-court magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a new motto,'' Ilie said. ``It's like pulling a
rabbit out of the hat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
