<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA CREW LANDS AT NIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ The Columbia astronauts swooped to a
rare night landing late Tuesday in Florida, concluding a successful
five-day mission to deploy the Chandra X-ray Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters had monitored storms in the area earlier in the day
before mission control cleared the shuttle's return to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Under a moonlit sky, astronaut Eileen Collins, the first female
spacecraft commander, steered the 220,000-pound spacecraft onto the
brightly lit shuttle runway at NASA's Kennedy Space Center at 11:20
p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really enjoyed this mission,'' said Collins, a
42-year-old Air Force colonel and test pilot, as her crew prepared
for re-entry. ``It's been absolutely super.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the 12th time a shuttle has landed in darkness in 95
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, pilot Jeff Ashby, flight engineer Steve Hawley, mission
specialist Catherine ``Cady'' Coleman and French astronaut Michel
Tognini were to undergo medical evaluations, meet with family
members and rest.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew planned to fly back to Houston on Wednesday at
the Johnson Space Center workers planned a brief public welcoming
ceremony at Ellington Field.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia blasted off Thursday night. Early the next morning,
Coleman led efforts to successfully deploy NASA's $1.55 billion
Chandra X-ray Observatory, the shuttle's primary payload. The
40-foot-long telescope was designed to assist astronomers in their
studies of the evolution of the universe. Specifically, it is
intended to help explain the role of black holes, quasars,
exploding stars and galactic collisions.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Columbia's launch was especially dramatic for
Collins and her crew. Within seconds, there was a momentary
electrical short that knocked out the primary controllers on two of
Columbia's three main rocket engines. Midway through the flight,
shuttle engineers released photographic evidence of a small leak of
explosive hydrogen fuel from the exhaust nozzle of the right
engine.
</P>
<P>
   Either problem could have caused the shuttle's rockets to shut
down prematurely during the eight-and-a-half-minute ascent, forcing
Collins and Ashby to attempt an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space program is a risky business,'' Coleman said,
reflecting on the risks the astronauts encountered. ``I do think
it's worth every single thing it took us to get up here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The telescope is so beautiful, and the information it will
send back is so fascinating,'' Coleman said. ``I think it will
answer questions we don't even know we have.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kennedy, ground crews prepared a hangar for Columbia where
engineers were to begin inspections of the narrow, stainless-steel
cooling tubes of the right rocket engine nozzle for potential
cracks or corrosive penetrations that could have been the source of
the fuel leak. Supercold liquid hydrogen from the shuttle's fuel
tanks circulates through the tubing on its way to the engine's
combustion chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers also will pour over the center engine and its
controller, the suspected source of the electrical short.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot more analysis that has to be done before we
know exactly what happened,'' Collins told a pre-landing news
conference from orbit. ``I know the shuttle program will be taking
action in the future to assure this won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Chandra's ground-control center in Cambridge,
Mass., engineers said Tuesday they have begun to activate the
scientific instruments and prepare for the third in a series of
maneuvers to place the telescope beyond the Earth's Van Allen
radiation belt.
</P>
<P>
   Within several days, the observatory should be circling the
Earth in an elliptical orbit with low and high points just over
6,200 miles and just under 87,000 miles. The first images should be
transmitted to Earth between mid-and late August.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra was designed for at least five years of operation.
</P>
<P>
   After its return, Columbia, the oldest of NASA's shuttles, is to
undergo a yearlong refurbishing at the Boeing Co. facilities in
California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
