<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-27 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-DEATHS-2NDLD     07-27 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-DEATHS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOSEMITE SUSPECT TELLS REPORTER HE WILL PLEAD GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs 13th graf for insert concerning other investigations;
adds new last graf concerning statement by Stayner family.) (lh) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He said he had dreamed of killing women for 30
years before he found his moment this February, when a middle-aged
woman and two teen-agers on a sightseeing trip to Yosemite National
Park happened to take a room at the motel where he worked as a
janitor.
</P>
<P>
   He killed all three women, Cary Stayner told a television
reporter on Monday night. Then he laid low, escaping suspicion of
the FBI when he was interviewed later in February by its agents,
who then focused on a group of ex-convicts as suspects.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, he said, he could no longer resist the temptation
to kill again, and he decapitated a 26-year-old Yosemite
naturalist, Joie Ruth Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   In a 25-minute jailhouse interview in Sacramento only hours
after he was charged in federal court there with the murder of Ms.
Armstrong, Stayner told the reporter, Ted Rowlands of KBWB-TV in
San Francisco, that he had fantasized since childhood about
murdering women and had killed these four ``because they were at
the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview was conducted off-camera and reported Monday on
the late news. In it, Rowlands reported that Stayner said he
planned to plead guilty to the Armstrong killing when he is
arraigned in Fresno on Aug. 6 and that he also wanted to plead
guilty to the other killings, with which he has not yet been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Rowlands said Stayner, a 37-year-old janitor at the Cedar Lodge
in El Portal, on Yosemite's western edge, had given a detailed
account of how he had killed Carole Sund, 42, her daughter Juli
Sund, 15, and their friend Silvina Pelosso, 16. Their disappearance
from the Cedar Lodge on Feb. 15 generated a vast investigation and
national headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, whose only prior arrest was for marijuana possession,
told Rowlands that he had tricked the three women into letting him
into their room and had then held them at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had strangled Carole Sund and Ms. Pelosso there, put
their bodies into the trunk of their rental car and then made Juli
Sund drive with him as he searched for a place to kill her and dump
the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, he said, he killed Juli Sund, by slashing her
throat so fiercely that he nearly severed her head, and dumped her
body near a creek. He then left the rental car, with two bodies
still in the trunk, at the remote community of Long Barn, a
two-and-a-half-hour drive east of El Portal, and took a taxi and a
bus back home.
</P>
<P>
   He did not sexually abuse any of his victims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he said, he returned _ not only to burn the car
but also to retrieve Mrs. Sund's wallet, which he used to throw the
FBI off his track by dumping it off a highway in Modesto, about
midway between El Portal and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic worked. When Mrs. Sund's wallet was found in Modesto,
both the FBI and local law-enforcement officials set up command
centers at a local hotel and began focusing on suspects in the
Modesto area. Several men with long criminal records have been held
in connection with the case for months, and a federal grand jury
has been hearing testimony since April from associates of those in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, when it announced that Stayner had been arrested
in the decapitation of Ms. Armstrong and was now ``the prime
suspect'' in the February slayings, the FBI had maintained that all
the people involved in those earlier killings were in custody,
albeit on unrelated charges. Now, in light of his confession,
several police departments in counties he has frequented say they
are re-examining some of their unsolved murders.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the television interview, two previously reported
FBI affidavits say that Stayner has confessed in detail to all four
killings, describing facts about the crimes that only someone
involved could have known.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Stayner also told of involvement of a
different kind. At the time Juli Sund's body was found, six days
after the discovery of the two other victims, the authorities said
only that they had been led to the body by a tip. Stayner said on
Monday night that the tip had come from him, in a letter he had
written the FBI telling agents where to look for the body. He had
someone else, unaware of his spree of killing, lick the envelope
for him so that his DNA could not be traced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, an FBI spokesman, Nick Rossi, declined to comment on
the affidavits and refused to confirm or deny any statements
Stayner ``may have made.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner's arrest, and confession, has brought new scrutiny to
the investigation of the case. James M. Maddock, who is in charge
of the FBI's Sacramento office, said that the agency will be
examining what, if anything, might have been done differently.
</P>
<P>
   In his confessions, both as described in the affidavits and by
the television station, Stayner said he took pains to throw
officials off by wetting towels in the women's room in the Cedar
Lodge to make it seem as if they had been there the day after he
had killed them.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner's family, was the victim of a terrible crime when he was
11. Stayner's younger brother, Steven, was kidnapped in their
hometown of Merced, and was held for seven years by a sexual
molester. When his abductor showed up one day with a new victim,
Steven and the younger boy escaped. Eight years later, in 1989, at
age 24, Steven was killed in a motorcycle crash.
</P>
<P>
   Reports by local news organizations have been filled with
speculation that Steven's ordeal may somehow have led his brother
to perpetrate violence against women. But in the interview, Stayner
said that he had fantasized about killing women since he was 7,
years before his brother was kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Stayner's father, Delbert Stayner, said that he
still could not believe that his son had committed the murders.
``Maybe someone threatened him into confessing,'' he said in a
brief telephone interview, his voice breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Later the Stayners issued a statement thanking the public for
the support they received when Steven was kidnapped and asking for
privacy now.
</P>
<P>
   y
</P>
</TEXT>
