A6328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-CLARK-NYT &LR;      07-27 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-CLARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GENERAL WHO LED NATO TROOPS TO RETIRE IN APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gen. Wesley K. Clark, who led NATO forces in the
war in Yugoslavia, will step down as commander of the alliance and
be replaced by a high-ranking Air Force officer, White House and
Pentagon officials said on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Clark would leave his post next April and
retire to civilian life. His replacement will be Gen. Joseph W.
Ralston, who was in line to become chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff two years ago but had to step aside from the Pentagon's most
senior military post because of a blemish in his personal life, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Clark was reported in Wednesday's Washington
Post, which characterized the move as arising from disagreements
that Clark had with the Pentagon over the conduct of the war in
Yugoslavia. Clark was known to favor a tougher stance against
President Slobodan Milosevic's aggression in Kosovo well before the
decision to go to war in late March.
</P>
<P>
   During the 11-week air campaign, Clark also urged the Pentagon
to let him plan for a ground invasion if the bombing did not repel
Serbian forces from Kosovo and end their cruelty toward Albanians
in that province. And during the aerial bombardments, he repeatedly
advocated use of more aircraft and more extensive strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House and Pentagon officials who confirmed Clark's
impending retirement and his replacement by Ralston characterized
the change as a way to encourage Ralston to postpone retirement and
stay in uniform, rather than a maneuver to banish Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clark did a great job,'' the White House official said. ``He
won the war, for God's sake!''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon official offered a similar assessment. ``If this
was in any way dissatisfaction with Clark, he'd be moved out long
before,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Both officials, who said they are familiar with the events that
began to unfold on Tuesday, spoke on condition they not be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   They described the replacement of Clark with Ralston as part of
a series of moves involving high-ranking military officers that
will be announced in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, interviewed by The Washington Post from Brussels,
declined to comment on what he might do next. ``There is a long
time yet to do this job, and I've got to keep my attention on it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House official said Defense Secretary William S. Cohen
wanted to do something ``to keep Joe Ralston in uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   The general, a much-decorated combat pilot who flew more than
100 combat missions in the Vietnam War and has been in the Air
Force for 34 years, seemed about to become chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But it was disclosed that he had had an adulterous affair in the
mid-1980s. While the affair was hardly scandalous by the standards
of sexual escapades that have embarrassed the military in recent
years, it was enough to keep him in the post of vice chairman of
the Joint Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston's term as vice chairman is up in February and, by law,
he would have to land a new military job within 60 days or revert
to a lower rank and retire, the officials explained on Tuesday
night. Therefore, they said, the position that Clark now holds was
the logical step for Ralston, especially since Clark's term has
already been extended.
</P>
</TEXT>
