<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-PANAM-ARCHDEACON-     07-27 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-PANAM-ARCHDEACON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gymnastics captain pulls out under cloud of suspicion
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Canada _ There's been another defection from the Pan
American Games.
</P>
<P>
   This time it's an American athlete.
</P>
<P>
   And while it's not about politics, it sure seems to have a lot
to do with pout.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati gymnast Jennie Thompson isn't leaving her country,
but she sure did leave the Pan Am Games Women's Gymnastics Event
Finals Tuesday night at Winnipeg Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The team captain of the U.S. women _ and the one girl here who
seemed to be a certain replacement for the Magnificent Seven who
won team gold and a nation's heart at the Atlanta Olympics in 1996
_ was mysteriously scratched from competition Tuesday after a
last-place finish in the night's opening vault event.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who will be 18 on Thursday, was visibly upset after
that event. She had claimed to be hampered by a bum ankle in recent
days and had it wrapped Tuesday night, but there seemed to be more
to her trouble than that.
</P>
<P>
   As the gymnasts readied for the night's second event _ the
uneven parallel bars on which Thompson was to compete _ Mary Lee
Tracy, the American head coach from Cincinnati, hurried over to
other team personnel and with a shake of the head said: ``I'm
pulling her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy then walked back to Thompson, who was at the edge of the
Arena floor. An animated conversation followed, cut short when the
team captain then wheeled around and disappeared down the athlete's
tunnel. A woman from the stands came down to the floor, talked
briefly with the coach, and with a shrug, Tracy then returned to
matters at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her ankles been bothering her and she had a bad landing,'' a
visibly disappointed Tracy said later. ``She didn't want to risk it
with all the things we have ahead of us in the coming months. She
left. She wanted to get it looked at _ now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was unavailable for comment. At first Courtney Caress,
the press officer for the U.S. national team, said Thompson would
talk about what happened in a few minutes. That promise was amended
to after the competition. Finally, Caress said Thompson had to
leave the arena:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more serious than they thought, so she's being
transported back to the athlete's village to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Told the explanation sounded fishy, Caress was adamant: ``She
didn't pull out of the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to her teammates, who struggled to a lone bronze medal
on the uneven parallel bars by Morgan White, the waif-like 16-year
old who also trains at Tracy's Cincinnati Gymnastics academy.
Meanwhile Canada cleaned up with six medals, including three gold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Americans got no Kerri Strug performance, here.
</P>
<P>
   Granted the stakes were not nearly as high as when the gimpy
Strug landed her vault in Atlanta and later was carried to the gold
medal presentation by coach Bela Karolyi. Then again, you've got
different personalities as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Thompson's been known as a temperamental sort with
a ``snapping turtle personality,'' as some put it. She's also been
known to get terribly down on herself.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened, she pulled out of two events Tuesday night.
That's after a subpar outing Saturday night in which the U.S. women
were edged for gold by the Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is still the top gymnastic prospect for the United
States Olympic effort at Sydney in 2000. Then again nothing ever
seems to go quite right for her.
</P>
<P>
   She was ``discovered'' by former Olympic gold medalist Bart
Connor when she was just seven. By age 10, she had become the
youngest U.S. event champion in history, winning the floor exercise
at the 1992 Junior Nationals. A year later she was the Junior
Nationals champion.
</P>
<P>
   But the sport can be grueling for young girls and it was on her.
Over the next few years she bounced back and forth between two of
the nations top coaches, Karolyi and Steve Nunno. Each move meant a
relocation, so from Wichita Falls, Texas, she moved to Houston,
Oklahoma City, back to Houston, back to Oklahoma and finally, two
years ago ended up in Cincinnati with Tracy,
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there were two surgeries that cost her all of
1995. An inflammation of the growth plate on her right heel
required sn operation and two screws to hold the heel to the foot.
Then bone chips had to be removed from her elbow.
</P>
<P>
   More frightening were the brief mental meltdowns. Once in
Houston her dad found her huddled in her bed, refusing to go to
Karolyi's gym. She wanted to leave his autocratic rule and return
to Nunno.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, she squeezed herself under the steering column of
her mom's car, grabbed the steering wheel and refused to budge. She
didn't want to go into the gym. A psychologist had to be called to
the parking lot to convince her to relent.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear stories like this you understand how some people
portray gymnastics as a form of institutionalized child abuse. That
might be a stretch, but the top kids do work 35 to 40 hours a week
in the gym. It's enough, according to 1972 Olympian Nancy Theis
Marshall _ who holds seminars on treatment of young athletes _ to
claim gymnasts receive an average of 1 minutes a sunshine a day. In
an attempt to stunt menstruation and puberty, girls often end up
with eating disorders. In fact, they are 10 times more likely than
the general populace to suffer from anorexia or bulimia. Then there
are the injuries, the pressure and the fact that girls are
considered all but washed up by 17 or 18.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, Thompson still endured and was a favorite
to make the 1996 Olympic team. She faltered at the Trials and
missed out. Still, when the Golden Girls went on a post Olympics
five months tour of the nation, Thompson was the only non-Olympian
invited.
</P>
<P>
   She struck up a friendship with two of the girls _ Jaycie Phelps
and Amanda Borden _ both of whom trained at Tracy's gym. The
Cincinnati coach _ once a Cincinnati Bengals cheerleader _ has
become one of the gymnastic gurus of the nation. She's also said to
be a comforting soul.
</P>
<P>
   That was supposed to spell rebirth for Thompson and the Pan Am
Games were to be her first step back.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, her first step was out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
