<HEADER>
A6334 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANG-INVESTIGATION-LA     07-27 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-INVESTIGATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE TO LAUNCH ANTI-GANG PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 and LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Targeting gang violence that took the life of a
16-year-old suburban North Hills boy, police pledged to send more
officers onto the streets, while county officials passed a law that
holds parents responsible for gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley's top police officer, Deputy Chief
Michael Bostic, said Tuesday the LAPD is launching an anti-gang
program next week to add officers and resources to Devonshire
Division, one of two Valley divisions hit by an upswing in
gang-related crimes while overall crime has plunged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the gang-detail officers, Metropolitan Division,
undercover narcotics division there. We've got almost every
resource there every day,'' Bostic said. ``We've just got to keep
doing everything we can.''
</P>
<P>
   But even strong police presence cannot guarantee an end to
crime, like the fatal shooting of Giovanni Avelar as he walked home
from Los Angeles-area Monroe High School last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't control the total disregard for the rights of someone
else,'' Bostic said. ``Eventually, the community has to decide that
they've had enough. The parents have to take responsibility for
those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the community is fed up and is willing to work with us,
we can't do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Los Angeles County supervisors adopted an ordinance
that could send parents to jail for up to six months and fine them
$500 if their minor children commit gang-related crimes and parents
didn't exercise enough control over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a dramatic and stunning resumption of gang
violence in the San Fernando Valley,'' said Supervisor Zev
Yaroslavsky, whose son attends Monroe High. ``The minute you walk
outside the boundaries of the school you're literally taking your
life into your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors also said they will consider opening an
investigation into the breakdown of a long-standing gang truce, and
they debated an anti-loitering ordinance targeted at gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Although the county's action affects only unincorporated areas
of Los Angeles County, board members said the plague of gang
violence must be stemmed at all corners.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors formally charged Luis Acosta, 18, with Avelar's
death on Tuesday. He was being held in lieu of $1.5 million bail.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they believe that among the reasons for the collapse
of a long-standing gang truce and rise in violence in the Valley is
that young gang members are starting new rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta has been with the notorious Langdon Street Gang since he
was 10 or 11 and became one of the top leaders, Devonshire
Detective Brad Cochran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his age and the other young gang members, they are
just as dangerous or more dangerous than their older
counterparts,'' Cochran said. ``We've got most of the older Langdon
Street guys in jail, but the serious narcotics activity keeps
things alive out there.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 21, Avelar was walking home from school when he was
confronted by two teen-agers who asked if he was affiliated with a
gang. One of those youths is believed to be Acosta.
</P>
<P>
   Avelar said he wasn't a gang member, and one of them began
punching him, police said.
</P>
<P>
   During the fight Acosta allegedly pulled out a handgun and shot
Avelar several times in the upper body.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplice remained at large at press time.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Avelar, a model student from El Salvador who hoped to
help support his family, is the ``epitome'' case of an innocent
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, the entire incident was just about turf,''
Cochran said. ``There was no other reason except they didn't think
he belonged there. It's just tragic, but everything is driven by
narcotics.''
</P>
<P>
   His death comes as a gang truce in place since 1993 has
crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich said he will introduce a motion
next week calling for an investigation into the unravelling of the
gang truce brokered in 1993 by a county agency.
</P>
<P>
   Antonovich's proposal was prompted by a Los Angeles Daily News
report Sunday that gang-related crime has risen in the Valley as
the truce has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Daily News analysis of police statistics, crime
attributed to gangs was up 3.65 percent in the Valley for the first
six months of 1999, compared to the same period in 1998. At the
same time, serious crime _ including gang-related offenses _ was
down 10 percent overall in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the troubling statistics, the LAPD planned to implement
the Community Law Enforcement and Recovery, CLEAR, program in the
Devonshire Division.
</P>
<P>
   The program, conceived in 1995 in the wake of the slaying of
3-year-old Stephanie Kuehn in the Cypress Park area of Los Angeles,
gives officers quick access to records and suspends the probable
cause requirement for searches of homes of probation violation
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   And, once in place, CLEAR will add more officers to the area,
which already is receiving extra attention, Bostic said.
</P>
<P>
   Enraged about the rise in violence in North Hills, members of
the group Familias Unidas plan to hold a news conference to call
for a return to peace and for more youth programs that can serve as
alternatives to gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good people in this community who care
about youth and are determined to promote peace in the face of
adversity,'' said Doris Casteneda, a North Hills parent and
Familias Unidas organizer. ``We know that violence is preventable
and that peace cannot be created through law enforcement efforts
alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
