<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-DISSENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES NOW MUST DEAL WITH RESENTMENT IN THE UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-UMPIRES) 
(mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The umpires' strategy to induce Major League Baseball to come to
the bargaining table began to unravel as soon as some of the
umpires returned home from the union meeting two weeks ago and
began talking to their wives and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we drank the Kool-Aid and had ether shot into the
room,'' one umpire said Tuesday, discussing the July 14 meeting in
Philadelphia. ``I got home that night and told my wife what we had
done and she said, `Don't you think you should have a cooling off
period and talk it over with your family?' So simplistic and so
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpire, who spoke on the condition he not be identified,
said his wife's reaction had punctured the high on which he was
still operating after returning home from the charged meeting,
where more than 50 umpires signed letters of resignation, effective
Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I came out out of the ether, I sat on the edge of the
bed and said, `What the heck have I just done?''' the umpire
recounted in a telephone interview. ``After giving it some thought,
I was one of the first guys to rescind. Not that I fear anything,
but I started looking at what happens if they accept the
resignations. There's not a lot I could do to make this kind of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Other umpires said they had consulted their lawyers after
returning home, and the lawyers reacted even more severely than the
umpire's wife did, telling them they had left themselves open to
the loss of their jobs. If they were going out on strike, which
their labor contract prohibits them from doing, they would
eventually reach a settlement with Major League Baseball and return
to work. Once the umpires submitted their resignations, however,
the leagues were free to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen umpires who had signed letters of resignation
subsequently rescinded their action, joining eight who had never
signed.
</P>
<P>
   That left 42 umpires _ nine in the American League, 33 in the
National _ who withdrew their resignations Tuesday after their
union leader and lawyer, Richard Phillips, failed to win the first
round of the union's lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires who held to their resignations until Tuesday
resented those who abandoned the strategy. The refusal of those
umpires to go along with the strategy was basically a repudiation
of Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me if I like Richie Phillips as a person
or not,'' Jerry Meals, a third-year member of the NL staff, said in
a telephone interview Tuesday. ``We as a union voted to retain
Richie Phillips for our counsel for the next five years back in
February. That is how we voted as a union and that is how the union
should stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Marsh, an 18-year NL umpire, said at Shea Stadium Tuesday
night that he believed baseball officials would have ``paid more
attention to us'' if the umpires had held together.
</P>
<P>
   The division in the union has created hardships for the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Froemming, a member of the union's board of directors,
heads a crew that has Mark Hirschbeck, the only NL umpire who did
not resign, and Wally Bell and Jeff Nelson, the two who withdrew
their resignations. ``I think it's difficult for everybody,''
Froemming said by telephone from Atlanta. ``It's a big hurt because
I've treated two of these guys like my best friends and almost like
my son and I feel they've turned their backs on me. Jeff just came
on, but I've known Wally and Mark for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The other three, Froemming said, had told him that they thought
he was making a mistake, ``that I will be unemployed and they'll be
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy has become routine in the locker room, the veteran
umpire added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not an open group anymore,'' he said. ``They have
complicated it. This is about individuals thinking they can do
better for themselves. They're not thinking as a group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
