<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTBE28-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD ARIZONA DROP FUEL REQUIRE MENTS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL AND THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona should drop its requirement that summertime fuel in the
metro area contain the controversial additive MTBE, a top state
air-quality official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That echoes the findings of a national panel, which is backing
away from the air-quality benefits of the additive because it's
been found to pollute water supplies and may cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona groundwater has been tainted by MTBE, but the
drinking-water supply is safe, say officials at the Arizona
Department of Environmental Quality and various municipal water
departments.
</P>
<P>
   DEQ has not received reports of tainted drinking water, agency
officials said Tuesday. MTBE has a distinct odor and taste that
likely would compel people to report it, something that has not
happened, said DEQ spokeswoman Amy Rezzonico.
</P>
<P>
   And representatives of various Valley water departments said
their routine tests for contaminants have not detected MTBE in
drinking-water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale found trace amount of MTBE at one well, but the
levels were well below health standards, said Barbara Olivieri, the
city's water quality director.
</P>
<P>
   Although drinking water is turning up clean, DEQ already has
documented cases of MTBE contamination in the groundwater around
underground gas-storage tanks in both urban and rural Arizona. In
random samples at 13 underground sites that it monitors, DEQ found
several cases where MTBE concentrations were hundreds of times
higher than the health-based guidance level it uses for drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   DEQ does not routinely check for MTBE contamination in Arizona
water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But because of concerns raised in California and other parts of
the U.S., Arizona has been re-examining its dependence on MTBE, or
methyl tertiary butyl ether.
</P>
<P>
   The state won't have a specific course of action until the DEQ
completes a draft `action plan'' on the fuel additive next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull is also waiting on the report, due Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see what they come up with,'' said Hull's
spokeswoman, Francie Noyes. ``We need to have our facts straight
before we decide to go in one direction or another. But this is
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Noyes said the governor wants to maintain the air-quality gains
that the metro area has made with cleaner-burning fuels, but must
be attentive to unintended problems, such as water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Domsky said it's likely that the state could parallel the
recommendations of the federal blue-ribbon panel. That group on
Tuesday recommended to the Environmental Protection Agency that the
use of MTBE be ``reduced substantially'' because, while it cleans
the air by making gasoline burn more cleanly, it can leak into
water supplies and pollute the water.
</P>
<P>
   California in March took the first step, vowing to phase out
MTBE by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could move in tandem with the rest of the
country,'' Domsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than requiring a specific oxygenate to make gasoline burn
cleaner, perhaps Arizona should simply set a performance standard,
Domsky said. It would be up to the oil companies to produce a fuel
that would meet that standard.
</P>
<P>
   At least one fuel company, Tosco, has already produced a
clean-burning gasoline that does not rely upon MTBE. In testimony
to the DEQ last March, Tosco said Arizona can get a clean-burning
gasoline without MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has been using MTBE in its gasoline since 1989, when it
was introduced to cut emissions during the winter. However, ethanol
has replaced MTBE as the wintertime oxygenate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, then-Gov. Fife Symington signed Maricopa County up for
the federal program that the blue-ribbon panel has scrutinized. He
said the clean-air benefits of MTBE would help Arizona aggressively
tackle ozone pollution, which plagues the Valley in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   A draft DEQ report in March detailed 13 locations where MTBE was
found in groundwater, and concluded that ``MTBE may well occur in
groundwater located near fuel-release sites throughout Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   DEQ drew samples from four sites in Mesa, although DEQ could not
determine their exact locations Tuesday. In all four cases, MTBE
concentrations were far in excess of the 35 parts per billion that
DEQ considers it health-based guidance level. The EPA recommends 20
to 40 ppb as a drinking-water standard, to ensure water has a
generally acceptable taste and odor.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rusty Bowers, R-Mesa, said he doesn't see MTBE as an
``imminent threat'' and said the state should balance clean air and
clean water concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally would just as soon get rid of it, now,'' Bowers
said.
</P>
<P>
   That offers little solace to people such as Bob Jacobs, a Valley
real-estate appraiser who has warned against MTBE's health effects
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, he said, turned a deaf ear to his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing could have been stopped,'' he said. Now, he
predicts, Valley motorists will have to pay higher prices at the
pump as oil companies try to recoup their investment in idled MTBE
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see people really outraged,'' he said,
envisioning prices upward of $1.50 a gallon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
